<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-SUIT-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT AGAINST GENENTECH ABOUT PATENT ENDS WITH JURY DEADLOCKED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A federal jury deadlocked Wednesday in a lawsuit
contending that Genentech Inc. had infringed a University of
California patent in developing its first big product, human growth
hormone.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock represented a narrow escape for Genentech, since
the panel vote was 8-1 in favor of the university, according to the
jury's foreman. The university will ask for a new trial, its lead
attorney, Gerald P. Dodson, said.
</P>
<P>
   The six-week-long trial, in U.S. District Court in San
Francisco, attracted widespread attention because of sensational
testimony in which a former Genentech researcher told of visiting a
laboratory at the university near midnight on a New Year's Eve and
clandestinely taking vital samples of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Such accusations raised new questions about past practices of
Genentech, one of the nation's oldest and most successful
biotechnology companies. In April, the company agreed to pay $50
million to settle federal criminal charges that it had marketed
human growth hormone for unapproved uses from 1985 to 1994,
pleading guilty to one criminal violation.
</P>
<P>
   The university had been seeking $400 million in damages, an
amount that could have been tripled if the jury had decided that
the infringement was willful. Genentech has had $2 billion in sales
of Protropin, as it calls its drug, since its approval in 1985. The
drug is used to treat children who are abnormally short because
their bodies do not make enough of the hormone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regard the deadlock on the infringement issue as a victory
because UC didn't prove its case to the satisfaction of the jury,''
Joseph Ferraro, a lawyer representing Genentech, said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodson, the university's lawyer, said, ``I don't see how
they can take great comfort in convincing one renegade juror out of
nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Charles A. Legge has set a hearing for June 22 to discuss
what happens next. It is likely that he will hear contentions by
Genentech that the university misled the Patent Office in obtaining
its patent.
</P>
<P>
   If Genentech prevails, the patent would be invalidated. If not,
a retrial could be held on the patent infringement claims with a
new jury.
</P>
<P>
   The jury, which deliberated six days, did rule in the
university's favor Wednesday on an attempt by Genentech to
invalidate the university's patent on different grounds. That
question will thus not be considered in any retrial.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The events at issue took place in the early days of the
biotechnology revolution in the late 1970s. The adversaries in this
trial had worked closely together to make the revolution happen.
One of Genentech's two founders was Herbert Boyer, a scientist at
the University of California at San Francisco who was a
co-developer of the basic technique of gene splicing.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensational testimony, about the so-called midnight
raid, came from Peter Seeburg, a former Genentech researcher. In
his previous job at the university, Seeburg and some colleagues had
cloned the gene for the production of human growth hormone. But the
rights to that invention remained with the university when he left.
</P>
<P>
   Seeburg, who now works at the Max Planck Institute for Medical
Research in Heidelberg, Germany, testified that he and a Genentech
colleague returned to his old laboratory at the university around
11 p.m. on Dec. 31, 1978, and made off with some samples of growth
hormone DNA, which Genentech then used to help develop its own
product.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he and David V. Goeddel, a then colleague at
Genentech who is one of the biotechnology industry's star
scientists, made a secret agreement to conceal this fact and that
Genentech researchers published a paper about their work in the
journal Nature that contained deliberate misstatements.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech has not disputed the taking of the university samples
_ it paid the university $2 million in 1980 to settle that matter _
but the company has maintained that it did not use the material to
develop the drug, for which it has received its own patents.
</P>
<P>
   Goeddel, who is now chief executive of Tularik Inc., a privately
held biotechnology company he founded, denied any agreement to
conceal the use of university DNA. He and several other authors of
the 1979 Nature paper have written letters to both Nature and
Science, another journal, saying that the accusations ``have
falsely impugned our reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Genentech has placed relevant pages of Goeddel's laboratory
notebook from the time on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Seeburg's testimony contradicted statements he had made under
oath in earlier depositions, and he admitted on the stand that
during the period in question he had alcohol and drug problems and
barely worked. Genentech also pointed out that Seeburg, as one of
the inventors listed on the university patent, stood to get nearly
10 percent of any payments the university won from Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald K. Losch, the jury foreman, said in an interview that the
jurors ``by and large'' believed that Genentech had used the
university samples in developing its product.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the jury disregarded much of Seeburg's
testimony. ``The facts could have been established almost entirely
without figuring out whether he was lying then or now,'' Losch, who
is himself a lawyer, said.
</P>
<P>
   Meirav Chovav, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney, said
Genentech, which has $1.7 billion in cash, would not have been hurt
financially even if it had lost the case because the damages
probably would not have been anywhere near as much as the
university wanted.
</P>
<P>
   She also described the trial outcome as an
``irrelevant-positive'' for Genentech's stock. The key issue for
the stock is that Roche Holding AG, the Swiss drug company that
owns two thirds of Genentech, must decide before the end of this
month whether to exercise its right to buy the rest of the company
for $82.50 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
