<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROYALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS EXTEND WINNING STREAK TO NINE GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The luxury of using Rafael Palmeiro as
designated hitter will be missed by the Texas Rangers starting
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro reminded those at The Ballpark in Arlington of that
possibility during the Rangers' 7-4 victory against the Kansas City
Royals on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, a first baseman reduced to the role of designated
hitter by an injured right knee, drove in three runs. He had a
one-out, two-run double during the Rangers' decisive six-run fifth
inning and later hit his team-high 15th home run in the seventh
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's offensive production and a strong, seven-inning
performance by right-hander Aaron Sele (5-4) propelled the Rangers
to their ninth consecutive victory. That is the longest this season
in the major leagues and the second-best in club history to a
14-game streak in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, begin interleague play Friday with a
three-game series scheduled at Arizona's Bank One Ballpark and Los
Angeles' Dodger Stadium, and that means National League rules will
prohibit manager Johnny Oates from using the designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   No designated hitter could mean no Palmeiro in the lineup until
the Rangers' return to The Ballpark on June 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it looks right now,'' Oates said. ``I don't see
him playing first base.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who emerged as the Rangers' Player of the Month for
May by hitting .404 with nine home runs and 26 runs batted in
during 27 games, plans to challenge that assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get a week off,'' said Palmeiro, whose
fifth-inning double off Kansas City's Kevin Appier (6-3) gave the
Rangers an insurmountable 3-2. ``I'm going to play first base in
some of those games. I feel good enough where I can play in a few
of those games. I'll give it a test Friday and see what happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I don't want to mess up what we've got going. But if I
feel I can do the job and not hurt the team, I'll try to play. If
I'm not ready, I'm not going to do it. We'll figure it out and do
it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates, though, remains unsure of Palmeiro's return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a slow process,'' Oates said. ``There's not a whole
lot of difference than there was two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The play of Lee Stevens prevents the Rangers and Palmeiro from
rushing his return to first base. Stevens will enter Friday's game
hitting .320 with 10 home runs and 31 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to keep playing, but I know I have to do a good
job,'' said Palmeiro, whose 2-for-2 performance Wednesday improved
his batting average to a team-high .360 with 43 RBI. ``I just can't
stand there. I have to do as good a job as Lee Stevens.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who won his second consecutive decision, made the most of
the Rangers' six-run fifth inning by surrendering only two runs on
seven hits and one walk during his 114-pitch appearance. The
seven-inning outing matched Sele's best of the season, an April 6
game against the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we scored, my job is to hold them,'' Sele said. ``This
team scores runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's presence supports that cause, yet he could be limited
to the role of a pinch hitter for the next six games should his
right knee not allow him to play first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not against that,'' Palmeiro said. ``I've thought about
coming off the bench with the game on the line and hitting a
game-winning home run. I've thought about it, but I'd rather be in
the game from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would prefer it, too. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
