<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PLACE MIKE MORGAN ON 15-DAY DISABLED LIST
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Right-hander Mike Morgan's availability for
his scheduled start Tuesday against Los Angeles at Dodger Stadium
remains in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers on Wednesday placed Morgan (inflammation, right leg)
on the 15-day disabled list. However, the Rangers made the move
retroactive to May 24, and that means Morgan could be reinstated
from the disabled list before Tuesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander John Burkett will replace Morgan in the rotation
for the start should Morgan not be available, manager Johnny Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready,'' said Morgan, who Wednesday threw in the
bullpen. ``My arm is not hurting. My leg just needs to get the
blood and swelling out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers recalled right-hander Danny Kolb, 24, from Triple-A
Oklahoma to replace Morgan on the roster. Kolb, who will be in
uniform for tomorrow's game at Arizona, went 3-0 with a 3.86
earned-run average during three starts at Oklahoma since his
promotion from Double-A Tulsa in May. Kolb will join the Rangers'
bullpen, Oates said. CLOSE LOOK AT APPIER
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Kevin Appier started Wednesday for the Kansas City
Royals, and that gave the Rangers a first-hand look at a pitcher
the organization has been scouting since spring training.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals have made no secret about their willingness to trade
Appier, but Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said there was no
special importance in watching him Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking at him,'' Melvin said. ``This is a chance
to see him for ourselves, but our scouts have seen him and
evaluated him.''
</P>
<P>
   Major-league officials say the Royals seek two premium prospects
for Appier in return, something the Rangers aren't willing to do
right now. CLAYTON READY TO PLAY
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton avoided a second stint on the 15-day
disabled list by informing Oates of his availability for tomorrow's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, who Saturday sustained a soft-tissue strain in the area
of his trapezius muscle in his right shoulder, missed his fourth
consecutive game Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good chance of me playing Friday,'' Clayton said.
``We'll see how it feels today and tomorrow. It's truly a
day-to-day thing, but I would think Friday could be the day.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rangers sent catcher John Marzano to Charlotte of the
Florida State League to begin a medical rehabilitation assignment.
Marzano, whom the Rangers invited to camp this spring as a
non-roster player, suffered a fracture to his left hand March 17
and has not played this season. Marzano served as a coach for
Triple-A Oklahoma while on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   _ Left-hander Andy Pratt, right-hander Travis Hughes and first
baseman Travis Hafner of Class-A Savannah have been selected to
play in the South Atlantic League All-Star Game on June 22. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
