<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EWING OUT AND KNICKS LOSE A CENTER OF GRAVITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ After months of hearing he was a barrier to the
Knicks' grand ambition, Patrick Ewing painfully stepped off the
court on Wednesday. He left an opening for his younger, quicker
teammates to run the floor without waiting for a limping 7-footer
to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   But has Ewing also left an opening for the Indiana Pacers? How
do the Knicks replace a franchise center, even the shop-worn and
limping figure who howled at the Market Square Arena rafters after
his last game on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you lose a great player,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy
said on Wednesday after learning that Ewing will miss the remainder
of the post-season with a partial tear in his left Achilles'
tendon. ``It doesn't help you. He was the one guy on our team who
had the respect of the officials, where he'll get a call when
bumped. But there's a lot of things he does for us, rebounding,
defense, low-post presence. We're just going to have to find some
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Life Without Patrick, a regular saga the past two seasons,
begins anew for the Knicks in Game 3 of the Eastern Conference
finals Saturday at Madison Square Garden. The Knicks are Allan
Houston's team now. And Latrell Sprewell's. And Larry Johnson's.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Pacers, the most brutish, experienced and talented
team in the East, the Knicks are down to an eight-man rotation of
role players, streak shooters and foul-prone big men. For all of
Ewing's defensive liabilities against Rik Smits, his ability to
create his own shot in the final minutes or draw the foul will be
sorely missed.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will attempt to fill the void by pushing the ball
upcourt feverishly, letting Sprewell gamble and basket-hang on
defense and Johnson to do his best to keep exploiting his mismatch
with Chris Mullin inside.
</P>
<P>
   But they will need more to advance to their first finals in five
years; Chris Dudley, Ewing's replacement, will need to conserve his
fouls to stay in the game; and Kurt Thomas, as combustible as John
Starks, needs to keep his poise.
</P>
<P>
   Before he knew of Ewing's season-ending injury on Wednesday,
Antonio Davis called Thomas, the scowling Knicks power forward,
``dirty,'' offering up Thomas' Game 2 high-bridge to the face of
Reggie Miller as proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kurt Thomas has really taken it upon himself to just
be dirty, and if that's the way you want to play, that's fine,''
Davis said, standing in the parking garage of Market Square Arena.
``Either the referee has to step in and take care of it or we'll
take care of it. One or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want anybody to be fighting for no reason,'' Davis
added. ``We don't want anybody to get kicked out because that's not
professional. But if that's what we have to do, then we're going to
have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional ante keeps rising in this series, a cauldron of
forearms and elbows that could easily goad the Knicks into falling
victim to their own passion. They lose their composure and toss
aside grand opportunities so often, it's as much a part of their
legacy as their resolve over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, one of the most physical players in the league, saw that
in Thomas' game on Tuesday night, that he had become the worst kind
of Knick; a nonthinking aggressor instead of a determined
basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the man, and he wasn't like that,'' Davis said. ``I
played against him when he was in Miami, and before he wasn't like
that. But he got a crazy look in his eye, and he's got this mean
streak going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is, but whoever told him that told him
the wrong thing. I think it's kind of taking him out of his game. I
think he's a better player than that, but he's so worried about
playing dirty that he's not playing the type of basketball that
he's played in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will run more isolation plays for Sprewell and
Houston, hoping they can kick-start the offense early in Ewing's
absence. Their hybrid team _ a mix of young athletes and bruising,
veteran big men put together by Ernie Grunfeld and Dave Checketts _
have the perfect opportunity in which to prove they can win
important games without an aging warrior, a proud player who will
ultimately be phased out the next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks future is suddenly now, though Van Gundy
understandably did not want to address that topic on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, to me, it's not about what we do in the future,'' he
said. ``I just wish there was a way to honor a guy who did so much
for us this year, who really was the consummate team guy in doing
what he could to help us win.''
</P>
<P>
   For his patient teammates who often deferred to him, there is a
way to honor Ewing. Govern their passions, take over his team and
remake it in their own image.
</P>
<P>
   It's what management wanted all along, and what the stubborn Big
Fella may understand what is best for the team today. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
