<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-2000(2     06-03 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-2000(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FIRST LEDE-WRITETHRU) PILOT MADE TWO LANDING ATTEMPTS, OFFICIAL
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 LITTLE ROCK, Ark.: the plane landed. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Airlines' chief pilot said he would not have tried to
land the plane if wind speeds exceeded 57.5 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone informed me that there were 50-knot gusts of wind
at the airport I was preparing to land at, I would leave town,''
said Cecil Ewell, who oversees all American Airlines pilots.
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service meteorologist George Wilken said radar
images showed the storm arriving in Little Rock about the same time
as the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scenario that the storm approached one end of the runway
as the plane approached from the other probably is correct,''
Wilken said.
</P>
<P>
   Weather data show that conditions were relatively calm 27
minutes before the accident, Black said. At that time, the wind at
the airport was out of the south at about 10 mph and visibility was
seven miles with lightly scattered clouds.
</P>
<P>
   But two minutes after the crash, the wind was out of the west
with gusts to nearly 30 mph, Black said. The gusts of more than 80
mph were recorded five minutes after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers said Buschmann alerted them about 30 minutes before
the crash that storms were looming around Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``A half-hour before the crash, he said there were strong
\Rstorm\S cells,'' Barrett Baber said. ``He said we were going to
try to go around them _ that was the last I heard'' from Buschman.
</P>
<P>
   The plane landed on Runway 04, which points almost north, and
then veered off the left side of the 7,200-foot runway before its
end, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger Richard Klamm said he was certain he was about to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time the pilot made his first bumpy touchdown until
the plane came to a stop was about 20 to 25 seconds,'' said Klamm,
49, of Pine Bluff, Ark. ``While you are swerving back and forth,
you don't have time to see your life flash before your eyes. I was
just thinking, `Get this plane under control.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When the plane touched down, it bounced, came back down and
bounced again, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell the pilot did not have control of the craft,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As it slid past the end of the runway, the plane turned right
into the large steel stanchion supporting the runway alignment
lights.
</P>
<P>
   The front of the fuselage was split just behind the cockpit, the
left side of the plane was ripped open by the steel light supports
and the left wing was torn off and crumpled.
</P>
<P>
   The tail of the plane separated from the rest of the fuselage.
Fire rolled through part of the plane, and some of the injured
apparently were seriously burned, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighting and rescue vehicles reached the scene within six to
seven minutes, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the survivors exited through cracks in the fuselage
because they could not get emergency exits open, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Black called the plane ``a clean aircraft, with no maintenance
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   It was delivered to American in August 1983. As of April 30, the
plane had logged nearly 49,000 hours of service and had been
through nearly 27,000 takeoff/landing ``cycles.'' Each pair, a
takeoff and a landing, is one cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look at the brakes, the runway surface, drainage of
the runway and the runway's skid resistance in determining why the
aircraft was not able to stop,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we don't know how far down the runway the plane
touched down, and whether the pilot tried to get it back into the
air when he saw that he could not stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known Wednesday whether wind shear _ a rapid change
in wind direction and speed that can bring an airliner crashing
down _ was a factor in the accident, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The Little Rock airport has a low-level wind-shear detection
system, but it does not have the newer Terminal Doppler Weather
Radar that was developed for the FAA after the wind-shear crash of
Delta Air Lines Flight 191 at D/FW Airport in 1985, safety board
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Little Rock Mayor Jim Dailey said he hopes the investigation
shows that the city's emergency response to the accident was
``helpful in saving lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first commercial aviation accident at our airport,
and, at the least, we will use this as an opportunity to be more
prepared in the future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who was en route to a speaking engagement in
Colorado, called Dailey from Air Force One to express his concern
for the crash victims and to offer his support in the
investigation, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also was asking about two friends of his who were on the
plane, Nancy and Craig Wood,'' the mayor said. ``I was able to tell
him that they both survived the crash and were OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Wood served in Clinton's administration while he was
governor of Arkansas, and Craig Wood is a member of the city's
water board, Dailey said.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Dan Reed, Betsy Blaney and Jim Fuquay contributed
to this report, which contains material from The Associated Press.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com.) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
