r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-2000(2     06-03 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-2000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FIRST LEDE-WRITETHRU) PILOT MADE TWO LANDING ATTEMPTS, OFFICIAL
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ The pilot who crashed his American Airlines
jetliner in a severe thunderstorm had aborted one landing and was
trying a second when the plane slid off the runway, broke apart and
burned, killing at least nine people, a federal investigator said
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the pilot circled the airport, then
apparently landed too far down the runway after weather conditions
deteriorated significantly in the minutes after the aborted
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 of the 145 people on board the McDonnell Douglas
Super 80 were injured, some critically, as hysterical passengers
scrambled off Flight 1420 from Dallas/Fort Worth Airport when it
crashed at 11:51 p.m. Tuesday. The left side of the fuselage was
peeled away as it slammed into a large steel structure that
supports runway alignment indicator lights.
</P>
<P>
   All but one passenger had been accounted for by Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors told harrowing tales of escaping from the thick smoke
and roaring flames as a violent downpour, hail and wind gusts of 75
mph enveloped the wreckage at Little Rock National Airport, just
yards from the Arkansas River.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I thought was that I was going to die,'' passenger Bonnie
Montgomery said. ``Everyone was pushing and pulling to get out of
that plane. We were on our hands and knees, and the smoke was so
thick we couldn't breathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even I pushed a few people, because your natural instinct to
survive just kicks in.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the National Transportation Safety Board
recovered the flight data boxes from the cockpit with hopes that
they would yield information about what the pilots knew of the
weather conditions when flight controllers cleared them to land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have recovered recorders and the tower transmissions. From
here we will go into understanding what the pilots were trying to
do,'' said George Black, an NTSB spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ultimately a pilot's decision to land or not, but they
have to base that on the information they have.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Richard Buschmann, 48, one of six members of the
flight crew, was killed in the crash. His co-pilot survived with
broken legs and other serious injuries and was ``interviewed
briefly,'' Black said, declining to say what the co-pilot told
investigators about the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The four flight attendants, all based at D/FW, also survived,
although two were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Baker, American's executive vice president for
operations, said that ``all of us'' at American ``are terribly
sorry that this accident has occurred. ... It is clearly a terrible
day for all of us at American Airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said airline officials ``will be doing everything we can,
together with the team of investigators, to determine exactly how
and why this accident happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Delayed for two hours by turbulent weather in North Texas, the
cockpit crew was on the last leg of a journey that originated in
Chicago, with stops in Salt Lake City and D/FW before Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   As it approached Little Rock, the plane ``started to rock pretty
good,'' said Kevin Mergel, 21, who was on the flight with other
members of the Ouichita Baptist University choir.
</P>
<P>
   After it touched down, ``I knew something was wrong when we
started to swerve,'' Mergel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping to God he could straighten out,'' Mergel said,
referring to the pilot. ``He was trying to reverse it and correct
things before making a mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Passenger Jamie Goss, a Georgetown University student, said the
plane was out of control immediately as the pilot struggled to slow
it down and keep it on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't,'' she told The Washington Post. ``I thought we
were never going to stop. Every time he would try to brake, we
would go to the left. I realized we were going farther and farther
to the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking out the window at the ground, and the third time
he tried to slow down, I saw the grass rushing by and knew we were
in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the NTSB was not ready to declare weather a factor in
the crash, conditions at the Little Rock airport deteriorated
rapidly as the aircraft approached the runway for landing.
</P>
<P>
   The plane's flight data recorder and cockpit voice recorder, as
well as tapes of the conversations between the pilots and air
traffic controllers, will be reviewed ``to determine what the
pilots knew or were told about the weather before they landed, and
what they might have attempted to do once they got into trouble,''
Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Steady winds of 50 mph with gusts up to 75 mph were reported in
the Little Rock area just before the plane landed. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
