<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GOVERNOR BUSH FINALLY EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 3:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who became the favorite for the
Republican presidential nomination without ever leaving Austin, has
begun to emerge from his self-imposed seclusion. The people of
Texas are probably grateful that Bush refused to campaign until
their Legislature had finished its business. But meanwhile the
expectations that have grown up around him have gotten so high that
he may find them impossible to meet. His first foray to Iowa and
New Hampshire later this month will be a kind of political
Groundhog Day, with spectators waiting to see whether Bush becomes
unnerved by the reality that greets him when he pops out of his
burrow.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has actually been filling two different roles in the
presidential race so far. He is the front-runner in a field of
Republican candidates by virtue of his family name and his
popularity as governor of a very large state. But he has also been
this season's Ross Perot or Colin Powell _ a famous but actually
little-known figure whom each voter can fashion into the ideal
candidate of his or her dreams. By actually venturing out to
campaign, Bush will have to fill in the blanks. He will inevitably
lose his status as a one-size-fits-all politician, just as Perot
did, and as Powell would have too, if he had chosen to run.
</P>
<P>
   The American people have a tendency to turn new faces into
mythic candidates, building them up into imaginary people who will
disdain compromise but nevertheless get a great deal done, cut
taxes while increasing services and defend the helpless overseas
while keeping the peace. Some of Bush's early fans will certainly
lose their enthusiasm for him when they discover he is mortal, and
others may realize his positions on issues are not nearly as close
to their own as they had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   While he stayed in Texas, Bush and his surrogates were piling up
contributions and endorsements, creating a campaign engine that
seems almost unstoppable. But we have seen inevitable candidates
fade before, and Bush is still a relatively untried campaigner. He
has actually only run in one hard-fought race _ against Gov. Ann
Richards in 1994. That was a big victory, but it cannot be compared
to the stress and demands of a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The field of Republican candidates hoping to become the Bush
Alternate is crowded, but there is no consensus fallback if the
front-runner stumbles. The primary season begins and ends very
early in 2000 _ a couple of states are even talking about voting in
December 1999. If this year turns out to be something other than
the triumphal march Bush's fans are expecting, the Republicans may
find themselves scrambling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
