<HEADER>
A0997 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RESPONSE-TEX     06-03 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RESPONSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH RESPONSE TEAMS ANTICIPATE CATASTROPHE
</HEADLINE>
 
(First Lede-Writethru) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAN REED and SEAN WOOD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ In a demonstration of the grim realities of the
airline business, American Airlines launched a huge response to the
crash of Flight 1420 late Tuesday night in Little Rock within
hours.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 a.m. Wednesday, every key executive in the company's
crisis response management team was in place at the American System
Operations Control Center near Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, at
company headquarters a half-mile away, or tied into the crisis
response team by phone.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 a.m., two jets filled with members of the airline's
Customer Assistance Relief Efforts, or CARE Team, and the technical
experts who make up its emergency response ``Go Team'' were
airborne, headed for Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:30 the cafeteria At American headquarters had been turned
into a fully equipped news media conference center.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock, American was criticized by families of some of
the crash victims, who were awaiting the flight at the airport and
were initially confused about what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   American executives acknowledged that it took several hours
after the crash for most of the CARE team members to get settled in
Little Rock, but they pointed out that Little Rock is a smaller
airport and not one of American's major hubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You simply do not have the same resources in a city the size
of Little rock that you have in a major metropolitan area from the
airline's perspective,'' said Robert Baker, American's executive
vice president for operations. ``I think our folks, collectively
the folks in Arkansas, did pretty darn well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our personnel were out at the crash site immediately helping
our passengers and helping to recover the injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the crash about 11:50 p.m. Tuesday, Art
Pappas, managing director of American's Systems Operations Control
Center, was notified of the crash. Pappas called American spokesman
Al Baker.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 a.m. Wednesday, the two men were in position at the head
of huge, U-shaped conference table in the ``bridge'' room
overlooking the main control room at the SOC, a room the size of
two football fields that looks much like NASA's Mission Control,
only about 10 times larger. Gathered around them were senior
representatives of nearly every effected department: flight
operations, ground operations, safety, scheduling, cabin service,
meteorology, reservations, corporate communications, legal and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission, Becker said, was to ``immediately regain control
of the situation to whatever degree we can and to begin responding
in the most effective, and most humane way we can to the tragedy
that had just occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   That response includes subtle efforts to protect the airline's
image. American made sure its news media briefing room had no
American signs or insignia visible. Two speakers' lecterns with
American Airlines logos used for
</P>
<P>
   happier events, sat in the corner of an adjacent room, while
American executives stood behind a plain brown lectern.
</P>
<P>
   But Becker downplayed the company's efforts at image damage
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of protecting the image flows from how well you
perform under great adversity,'' he said. ``And it evolves into how
you take care of the passengers and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first steps in activating American's plan was to call
in some of its 1,200 CARE team members _ American employees
systemwide who have volunteered to respond to an accident to aid
survivors and victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, American had activated 213 CARE Team members,
most of them based in North Texas. Of those, 121 were either in
Little Rock or en route there.
</P>
<P>
   While the airline has long had a practice of assigning employees
to the families of passengers involved in a crash, six years ago it
instituted a formal and thorough training process for its CARE Team
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are authorized to do whatever is necessary to make sure
that families are comfortable,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   CARE Team members are given carte blanche to pay for funerals,
hotel accommodations, meals, transportation and whatever else
victims or their families need.
</P>
<P>
   Most survivors, for example, needed new clothes because the ones
they were wearing when they escaped the crash were ruined by jet
fuel, mud and rain. Whatever remains of their luggage was still on
board the stricken plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our responsibility,'' said American Airlines spokesman
Mark Slitt.
</P>
<P>
   That sense of responsibility has been a relatively recent
development for the industry, said David Stempler, president of the
Airline Travelers Association in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone full circle from the less-than-caring, barely
responsible agencies and airlines to those who find this policy to
be more effective,'' Stempler said. ``It's a good business
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also federal law. In 1996, President Clinton signed the
Aviation Disaster Family Assistance Act, which gives survivors and
relatives someone to turn to for information after an aviation
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was written after the 1996 crashes of TWA Flight
800 off Long Island and a ValuJet plane in the Everglades. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0998 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-EWING-OUT-HNS &LR;      06-03 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-EWING-OUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ When Patrick Ewing missed a wide-open 15-foot jumper off
the heel of the rim at the end of the Knicks' 88-86 loss to Indiana
in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference finals, little did he know that
would be his last shot of the 1999 NBA playoffs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ewing, who has been plagued all season by a strained left
Achilles' tendon, said he felt something tear in the tendon during
warm-ups before Tuesday's game at Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, who played anyway, finishing with 10 points and three
rebounds in 25 minutes, underwent an MRI Wednesday morning at Beth
Israel Hospital Singer Division, which confirmed the tear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to work so hard and be so close to something
I've dreamed about for so many years,'' Ewing said. ``To not be
able to be on the floor to help my teammates is very frustrating
and disappointing. But if my Achilles' ruptures completely, it
would end my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, team doctors ended his season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a distinct tear, in contrast to his previous MRI,
which showed no tear,'' said Knicks team physician Dr. Norman
Scott. ``It's a partial tear. The treatment is that the choices
were out of his hands and he had to stop playing the rest of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following (Tuesday's) game, Patrick showed signs of swelling
in his Achilles' that we have not previously seen. This morning,
Patrick underwent an MRI which showed a partial tear of his left
Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a career-threatening injury, and we expect Patrick
to make a complete recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was stunned when Scott delivered the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You're kidding.' He didn't believe me,'' the doctor
said. ``He was really depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Achilles' will be immobilized in an air cast for six weeks.
Ewing will wear the removable cast over the majority of each day,
and after six weeks his Achilles' tendon will be re-examined.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing averaged 17.3 points and 9.9 rebounds during 38
regular-season games this year, missing 12 games because of
soreness in the Achilles' tendon. During the playoffs, a five-game
first-round victory over Miami and a sweep of Atlanta in the
conference semifinals, Ewing averaged 13.1 points and 8.7 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being hobbled by tenderness in the tendon, Ewing led the
Knicks to a victory in Game 1 against Indiana, scoring 16 points
and hauling in 10 rebounds in a game-high 40 minutes. Ewing scored
six points in the last minute, including four straight free throws
in the final 51.3 seconds to nail down the 93-90 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But with the series set to resume Saturday with Game 3 at
Madison Square Garden, there will be no more heroics from Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick wants to play, but the injury prevents that from being
a possibility,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``After all that he has
been through this year, playing injured and doing what he could do
to help his team achieve the goal of competing for a championship,
I feel very badly for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year veteran has been slowed by a string of injuries this
season _ but the biggest concerns at the start of the year were his
chronically sore knees and his surgically repaired right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Many thought that the broken wrist, which caused Ewing to miss
the final 56 games of last season, would end his career. But after
a strenuous rehabilitation regimen, Ewing returned in time for the
playoffs, playing in the final four games of the Knicks' five-game
loss to the Pacers in the Eastern Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The Achilles' tendon was not a concern until Ewing left in the
opening minute of a March 9 game against the Milwaukee Bucks. An
MRI showed no tissue damage, but Ewing sat out the next six games
as a precautionary measure.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing missed five more regular-season games before being placed
on the injured list May 5, forcing him to miss the season finale
vs. Miami. It was thought that that late-season rest would keep
Ewing healthy for the Knicks' playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Knicks' entering the playoffs as the No. 8 seed,
Ewing led them to the conference finals, the first time a team
seeded last has advanced that far. Ewing had been seeking his
second trip to the NBA Finals, having lost to the Rockets in the
1994 Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick has been on this journey,'' Van Gundy said. ``The
reason he plays today is to win a championship. It is the reason he
fought through a lot of pain to try and help. I feel bad for him.
It's as if he's been cheated out of another opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel badly for Patrick Ewing. I've been with him for 10
years, so I know what he stands for. I know how much he's put into
it. I'm disappointed for him, that all these sacrifices this year,
playing through pain, how hard he worked to come back from his
wrist injury, how much he was willing to do extra just to get
himself on the floor and give us a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed for him.''
</P>
<P>
   As are the Indiana Pacers, who watched Ewing limp off the floor
Tuesday after missing his game-ending shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see he was hurting,'' said Mark Jackson, once Ewing's
teammate. ``I'm proud of him. He's a warrior. A lot of guys
wouldn't have even suited up.''
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller, who has made a career out of toasting the Knicks
in the playoffs, took time out Wednesday to offer a toast to his
rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a shame, because Patrick is such a great competitor
and has been such a huge part of this great rivalry and the great
games that the two teams have played,'' Miller said. ``The Knicks
are still going to be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't make our job any easier. It probably makes it
tougher because they (the Knicks) will step it up even more.''
</P>
<P>
   They're going to have to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
