<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SAFRICA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CHALLENGE FOR SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 3:
</P>
<P>
   The slums in South Africa are as bleak as any in the world _
miles of single-room hovels, each holding a huge family or two,
with no electricity or water and only a bucket for waste. Apartheid
forced millions of blacks into these slums, and many have not been
able to leave. The most important task facing Thabo Mbeki, who will
become president following the African National Congress's apparent
election victory yesterday, is to improve life for these poor.
</P>
<P>
   When Nelson Mandela and Mbeki took over South Africa's
government in 1994, they wanted to focus on helping poor blacks.
But Mbeki, who is deputy president and ran economic policy,
apparently decided that simple redistribution would be rejected by
world markets and would not help enough of the poor. Instead he
chose a pro-business strategy, lowering taxes and seeking economic
growth by attracting foreign investment and preventing the flight
of white citizens or their capital.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa has reduced deficits and inflation. But
unemployment remains at a shocking 38 percent and income has not
increased. Apartheid left the country with one of the world's
worst-educated work forces. It also has inflexible labor rules that
inhibit job creation, a bloated government, inefficient state-run
industries and uncompetitive private industries. Reform is
necessary for growth, but is opposed by influential unionists and
Communists inside the ANC.
</P>
<P>
   To help the poor directly, the government cut the defense budget
and spent the money building more than 600,000 new houses and
providing water, phones or electricity to several million homes.
The millions helped, however, are only a small slice of South
Africa's poor. In addition, some programs have been badly run and
not directed at the worst poverty, which is rural. Many of the
water lines have cracked. Teacher spending is high, but education
is terrible, in part because little money is left for books and
many teachers are incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki promises to improve these programs. He is a strong
administrator, but making government efficient is difficult,
especially in a poor nation. More progress will come if he can
privatize state industries and remove obstacles to local job
creation. This will take courage, as Mbeki is not trusted by the
ANC's left wing. But his responsibility is to South Africa's poor,
who have waited for decades, and are waiting still. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
