<HEADLINE>
WOMAN SUES OLOWOKANDI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The attorney representing a Sacramento woman is
demanding a multimillion-dollar payment from Clippers center
Michael Olowokandi in a civil action filed Tuesday in Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement released Wednesday by Olowokandi's
representatives at Bill Duffy and Associates Sports Management, the
woman _ who, like Olowokandi, was a University of Pacific student
at the time _ is alleging her 1998 relationship with Olowokandi
that produced a child included one sexual encounter that was not
consensual.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no criminal charges have been filed. The woman has not
petitioned for custody of the child or financial remuneration for
its welfare. As of Wednesday night, Olowokandi's attorney had not
been served with the civil papers.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy would not provide names of those involved, or more
specific information about the situation, in order to protect the
interests of the four-month-old boy, who was given up for adoption
by his mother immediately after birth. According to BDA's
statement, Olowokandi was consulted by the woman before the
adoption process began and handled the attendant financial
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   But about a year after the alleged incident and four months
after signing a three-year, $10 million contract as the first
overall pick in the 1998 NBA Draft, Olowokandi _ who, according to
the BDA statement, passed a polygraph test concerning the issue of
consent _ is facing civil action.
</P>
<P>
   The statement indicated the accusations against Olowokandi
``will not be taken lightly,'' and that ``the NBA and the Clippers
support and respect his right to defend himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
