<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON'S WRIST HEALING PROPERLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Right fielder Tim Salmon had the cast removed from his
sprained left wrist Wednesday and the news was good _ the wrist
ligaments are healing properly and if the progress continues he
could return before the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took the cast off and didn't put it back on,'' Salmon
said. ``That's a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon was examined by hand specialist Dr. Normal Zemel and team
medical director Dr. Lewis Yocum but did not have an MRI performed.
As long as the wrist continues to get better, there's no reason for
an MRI, though Salmon was fitted with a removable splint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pain was reduced and the range of motion was better,'' he
said. ``It's healing.''
</P>
<P>
   If there had not been signs of improvement, season-ending
surgery would have been a consideration. Instead, Salmon will
undergo therapy to regain flexibility and strength in his wrist and
hand.
</P>
<P>
   When he'll be able to return to the field is not easy to say,
Salmon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a broken bone where you can say it'll be healed
in six weeks or a certain time frame,'' Salmon said. ``Only God
knows how quickly it's going to heal. I don't want to get locked
into a date.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two weeks is the window. I'll do that and see where
we're at. After that, either I'm making progress and can start
swinging the bat or not, and we'll go from there. . . . It could be
two to three weeks, it could be four to five weeks. There could be
surgery down the road. I'll just do what I have to do to get
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very good news,'' manager Terry Collins said. ``You take
the guy's cast off and start getting him ready to play. That's good
news. It's what we've been waiting to hear, certainly.''
</P>
<P>
   Draft status: The Angels did not have a first-round pick in the
free agent draft that began Wednesday, but they did have picks in
rounds 2-22. The draft concludes today.
</P>
<P>
   With their second-round pick (the 68th selection overall), the
Angels took right-handed pitcher John Lackey (6-foot-6, 200 pounds)
from Grayson County Junior College in Denison, Texas. Lackey went
10-3 with a 4.23 ERA in 16 games (15 starts) this season. He also
played first base and hit .428 with 15 homers and 81 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real excited to hear I was drafted by the Angels,''
Lackey said. ``It's an opportunity that every little kid wants when
growing up and I was really excited when I heard I went in the
second round.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' first seven picks were pitchers. Of their 21 picks
Wednesday, 10 were pitchers, 13 were collegiate players, four were
JC players and four were high school players.
</P>
<P>
   Slump over?: Troy Glaus went into Wednesday's game with five
hits in his previous 12 at-bats, including two homers. It appears
Glaus has emerged from a slump that lasted all of May, but Collins
said Glaus' work with hitting coach Rod Carew must not change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the process is, keep doing it,'' Collins said. ``Tony
Gwynn always said when you're hot, take extra batting practice. He
didn't want to lose what you're trying to do, maintain it because
it's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus hit .130 in May (12 for 92), but Collins was happy with
the way Glaus, 22, handled the slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he did fine,'' Collins said. ``I'm sure he was
frustrated at times, but I think he handled it great.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are off today and will begin a three-game series
against the Dodgers at Dodger Stadium on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
