<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-PITCHING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTING PITCHERS ADDING STRENGTH TO STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Aaron Sele turned in a workmanlike
performance against the Kansas City Royals on Wednesday. The Texas
Rangers' right-hander pitched seven innings, allowing seven hits
and two runs in a 7-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wider scope of the Rangers' nine-game winning streak,
Sele's performance paints a brighter picture for the team. During
those nine games, the Rangers' starting pitchers have combined for
a 4.07 earned-run average, dropping the combined ERA from 7.00 to
6.41 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all starts with our starting pitchers,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``They give us a chance, and we're going to win
a lot of ballgames. Unfortunately, it also falls on their
shoulders. But to put together a nice winning streak you've got to
have good starting pitching and a quality bullpen to finish it
off.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been the case in the six-game home sweep of Minnesota
and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Rick Helling, Jeff Zimmerman and John Wetteland
combined to hold the Royals to one run, the fewest runs allowed
since May 15. Sele (5-4) followed that showing with good work in
the first three innings, allowing only two hits. He faltered a
little in the fourth, allowing two runs and three hits, but
regained his composure in his last three innings _ after the
Rangers rallied for a 6-2 lead _ to keep the Royals to two hits and
no runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to make some pitches, other than in the fourth
inning where they got a couple of breaking balls up in the zone
where they hurt me,'' Sele said. ``But really my job after we
scored six is to come out and shut them down, and that what's I've
got to do. That's what my whole focus was on.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday, the Rangers' bullpen accounted for four
consecutive victories, which overshadowed some solid work from the
starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been big,'' left-fielder Rusty Greer said of the starting
rotation. ``That's the way you win ballgames, with good pitching
and defense. The offense is the last thing to come around.
Hopefully we can keep swinging the bats and give them some
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Support for the starting rotation was lacking at the beginning
of the season, when some ERAs soared into double digits. That was
cause for some concern, but the numbers were bound to drop as the
staff developed consistency, pitching coach Dick Bosman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of repetition and a lot of work,'' he said.
``Sometimes it takes a little bit longer to get into really good
pitching shape mentally and physically. We've stayed the course,
and I really don't believe we've changed the game plan or anything
like that. We just kept doing what we were doing in the past that
brought us success.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
