<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'98 RUNNER-UP RETURNING TO U.S. OPEN AS PRO
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ Jenny Chuasiriporn, runner-up to Se Ri Pak
while competing as an amateur in last year's U.S. Women's Open,
said she is confident about making a memorable professional debut
this week at Old Waverly Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn, 21, will compete as a professional for the first
time in Thursday's opening round of an event where she has won low
amateur honors the past two years. Pak needed 20 holes in last
year's playoff to keep Chuasiriporn from arriving at Old Waverly
with a ``defending champion'' title as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My track record for Opens is pretty good, so I feel
confident,'' said Chuasiriporn, who has finished 56th and second at
the past two Opens. ``I realize there are a lot of expectations on
me. But it doesn't really feel any different to me. I'm excited. I
feel like I am ready for the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn, a member of Duke's 1999 NCAA championship team,
seeks to make enough money by the end of the season to earn her
LPGA Tour card for next year without going through qualifying
school. Chuasiriporn said she has accepted sponsor's exemptions to
three upcoming LPGA events: the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic (July
1-4), the Michelob Light Classic (July 8-11) and the Big Apple
Classic (July 15-18). RAINS DAMPEN COURSE
</P>
<P>
   Forget about firm and fast course conditions during Thursday's
opening round. Play was suspended for 21/2 hours Wednesday morning
because of showers. The final practice round was cut short at 2:45
p.m., when a second wave of storms dumped more than an inch of rain
on the course.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deluge, Dallas resident Kelli Kuehne described the
greens as ``very quick ... They are big, so target golf is very
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the targets have become more tempting because of soft
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to winning an Open is keeping your composure when you
bogey from the middle of the fairway with a 9-iron in your hand,''
said Karrie Webb, the LPGA Tour's leading money winner. ``That's
what knocks you off your game. With a wet course, that's not as
likely to happen.'' KUEHNE ANSWERS SELF-DOUBTS
</P>
<P>
   Kelli Kuehne, a two-time U.S. Amateur champion who played at the
University of Texas, said the best part of Sunday's victory at the
Corning Classic was coming back from a final-round deficit to
secure her first career victory on the LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know I still have the same instinct that I had
during my amateur days, because that's been missing for a while,''
said Kuehne, 22, who closed with a round of 2-under 70 and won by
one stroke. ``I've struggled as a pro, so getting that first win
meant a lot. It was pretty neat for a couple of girls to come up to
me and say, `You've got yours. Now, I'm waiting to get mine.' That
was great to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne, who joined the LPGA Tour in 1997, did not crack the top
10 at any of her first 33 tournaments as a professional. But she
has placed seventh and first the past two weeks, the best finishes
of her career. As for the likelihood of continuing her roll at the
Open, Kuehne said: ``I'm very comfortable playing in USGA events
because I love the courses they pick. You have to hit it straight
and putt well and that fits my game. I definitely think that's to
my advantage.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeanne Cho, a 17-year-old foreign exchange student, is
skipping her high school graduation in Bradenton, Fla., to compete
in the Women's Open. Cho's permanent residence is Boulogne, France,
and she is a member of the 1999 French National Junior Team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among Thursday's starters are nine players who list Texas
residences, including former TCU golfers Marci Bozarth (Houston)
and Jenny Lidback (Houston). nn
</P>
</TEXT>
