<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN OFFERS PLAN FOR SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUN CITY, Ariz. _ Warning that a ``pervasive public cynicism''
threatens to undermine American democracy, Sen. John McCain
outlined a plan Wednesday to save one the nation's most vital
institutions _ the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential can didate wants to allow recipients
to invest some of their benefits in the stock market. He also would
protect Social Security from congressional raids and remove earning
limits that penalize seniors for working.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants a commitment from the next president to use 60
percent of the federal budget surplus to keep the Social Security
system solvent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is more about your children and grandchildren,'' he
told about 100 retirees in Sun City, ``but that doesn't diminish
the urgency of the cause. It makes it greater.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said such reforms will re-establish the public trust,
which has been squandered by elected officials who rely on
poll-driven policies, phony posturing, partisan politics and
``damage control we substitute for progress.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain was critical of a proposal by President Clinton to allow
the government to invest up to $700 bil lion in Social Security
funds in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really want the federal government to be the major stock
holder in General Motors or Micro soft?'' McCain asked. ``Do we
want Washington bureaucrats picking winners and losers in the
economy? Of course not.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Dougherty, an 82-year-old retired credit manager, said he
likes McCain's ideas about Social Secu rity, but thinks McCain
lacks pizazz as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to get more charisma,'' Dougherty said, adding that
he respects McCain. ``I like him. I think he's honest, and I admire
his service record (as a Navy pilot and POW in Vietnam).''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Neumeister, an 80-year-old retired engineer, said McCain
doesn't seem as self-interested as other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he wants to do what's best for the country,''
Neumeister said.
</P>
<P>
   Retiree Roland Smith, 81, said he was concerned about the
potential for looting in the Social Security investment plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we guard against people who would take advantage of the
new system?'' Smith asked. ``How do we protect ourselves against
the Charles Keatings of the world?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said under his plan, people would be able to invest 2
percent or 3 percent in Social Security payroll taxes, selecting
investment options _ such as conservative mutual funds _ from a
menu created by an independent panel of experts.
</P>
<P>
   He said such a move could increase Social Security benefits from
an annual $24,000 to more than $60,000 for a family earning $35,000
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Social Security reve nue can only be invested by the
government in government securi ties.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said two Democrats _ Sen. Pat Moynihan of New York and
Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska _ have also endorsed the private
investment concept ``because they know it is the only way Social
Security can be saved without raising taxes or cutting benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also called for Social Security Trust Funds to be
separated from the rest of the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   McCain noted that as the popula tion ages, fewer and fewer
workers will be paying for a growing number of Social Security
recipi ents. The result, he said, would be a rise in Social
Security taxes from 12.4 percent to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as it would be unconscion able to break a sacred trust
with you by confiscating your promised re tirement benefits,''
McCain said, ``it would be morally bankrupt to im pose such an
onerous burden on our progeny.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain criticized recent Social Security legislation in the
House of Representatives, saying the ``lock box'' law has a fatal
loophole that allows the money to be tapped for emergency spending
measures.
</P>
<P>
   McCain noted that a few days before the House passed the lock
box bill, Congress sent an emer gency spending bill to the
president that included millions of dollars in pork barrel spending
for such dire ``emergencies'' as subsidized rein deer ranches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently,'' McCain quipped, ``even Santa Claus has hired a
Washington lobbyist.'' &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at 444-8178 or at bill.muller &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. Republic writer Ruben Navarrette contributed to this
article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
