<SLUG> BC-WACKY-WEATHER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA NINA SPRINGS FAST ONE ON SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN, DONNA HUFFAKER AND MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Turn up the heat, get out the woolens, the
weatherman says it's going to snow tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to June in Los Angeles in the year of La Nina. Record
rainfall Wednesday, snow tonight on Mt. Wilson in the Angeles
National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very, very unusual for June,'' said National Weather Service
meteorologist Gary Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday set a record for the most rain on a June 2 in Los
Angeles -- 0.58 of an inch downtown, 0.91 in Glendale, 0.71 at the
Getty Center. Most of the Valley and its northern and western
suburbs got less than 0.25 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the third-heaviest rain this century recorded in the
month of June (in Los Angeles County),'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a 40 percent chance of showers in the lower elevations
today and into early Friday, and in the mountains it is expected to
snow above 6,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight lows in the suburban San Fernando Valley northwest of
downtown and surrounding areas are expected to be in the upper 40s
and 50s, with highs today and Friday in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Weather Service officials could not recall the last time it
snowed around Los Angeles in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' said Kenar Yegyayan, 24, of Glendale, as she
walked down Brand Boulevard bundled up in a leather coat. ``My
sacrificial rain dance must be working. L.A. is just too sunny.''
</P>
<P>
   Her companion disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Miami. I like my weather warm, like my women,'' said
Al Zequeira, 40, of Glendale. ``This weather is like Seattle. It's
too depressing,'' he said. But then he saw the bright side of his
predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be gloomy in L.A. than gloomy in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Treto, 35, of Glendale, a valet at Valet Unified Parking
in downtown Glendale, wore an extra layer of company uniform with a
vest and jacket over his usual white shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rain, it should be over,'' Treto said. ``The body doesn't
like it to be this cold.''
</P>
<P>
   The wacky weather surprised even the forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intensity . . . Caught us off guard,'' Ryan admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest rainfall was in La Crescenta, which received more
than an inch and a half. Burbank received nearly six-tenths of an
inch while Northridge absorbed a tad more than one-tenth of an
inch.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor restaurants kept their tabletop umbrellas tied down
Wednesday to allow patrons to catch whatever sun they could as it
played hide-and-seek behind the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Valley are expected to be in the low to
mid-60s today, climbing to the mid-60s to low 70s on Friday,
forecasters said. Wednesday's high was 65 in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   An unusually strong upper level low-pressure system is allowing
the cool, moist air as it creeps down the California coast from up
north, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the crazy weather on La Nina, said Bill Patzert, a
satellite oceanographer at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   The global weather phenomenon has chilled coastal waters as much
as 4 degrees below normal from the Gulf of Alaska to Baja
California, which in turn gives rise to the marine layer and
overcast skies, he said. The ocean temperatures are expected to
climb exceedingly slowly, meaning the gloomy weather could extend
into July and August this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The somber skies Wednesday didn't faze Rafael Farias and Jose
Sanchez as they used a cherry picker to hang banners along Grand
Avenue announcing ticket sales for the women's 1999 World Cup of
Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   They ducked under some trees for a few minutes during a morning
shower but after that, nothing bothered them, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how Aztec blood is,'' said Farias. ``It's warm
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The rain caught Julie Bachman without an umbrella, forcing her
to run back to her car Tuesday night after seeing Elvis Costello
perform at the Wiltern Theatre. So, to be safe, on Wednesday she
took her small, black umbrella to work at the criminal courts
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sat all day in my supervisor's office,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With little regard for the wintry weather, Tony Martinez went
about his business as a bicycle messenger Wednesday -- wearing
short sleeves and short pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's California, man,'' he said, shrugging outside the civil
courthouse on Hill Street downtown. ``To me this weather is kind of
tropical -- it's humid.''
</P>
<P>
   When he wakes up Friday morning and looks at the mountains,
though, Martinez might not feel the climate is so Caribbean
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The cool weather was also a hot conversation topic at barber
shops around the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying it's screwball weather, the rain, the cold,
the dragging in the June gloom,'' said barber Joe Nozzi, who owns
Captain's Hair and Galley in Canoga Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all talking about it. The rain surprised a lot of
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   County officials warn that the rain could boost the mosquito
population, and they urged residents to get rid of any collected
rainwater or landscape water and to maintain ponds and pools with
adequate filtration and chemical additives.
</P>
<P>
   Infected female mosquitoes can transmit St. Louis encephalitis
virus, a potential cause of inflammation of the brain and spinal
cord. Humans can contract the disease only through the bite of an
infected mosquito. Los Angeles County had 25 reported human cases
of the virus between 1984 and 1992, including one death.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
