<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE DISAPPOINTS JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The middle of the Dodgers lineup features Gary
Sheffield, Raul Mondesi, Todd Hundley and Eric Karros. For most of
the season Eric Young led off, replaced by Devon White a week ago.
The shortstop, Mark Grudzielanek, once had 54 doubles in a season.
</P>
<P>
   All of which means nada when talking about the 1999 Dodgers'
dismal offense.
</P>
<P>
   In the 16-team National League, the Dodgers rank 11th in runs
scored (245) and 13th in batting average (.261). They've also
grounded into 46 double plays, fourth most in the league. None of
which sits particularly well with manager Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know, offensively, we're more talented,'' Johnson said. ``I
know we can score more runs than we've been scoring. We hit into
too many double plays. We hit the pitch that's sometimes designed
for us to hit into double plays. We don't situationally hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers don't hit behind runners, aren't adept bunters,
don't deliver sacrifice flies and don't score like they should. In
their last six games (four losses), they're 5 for 51 with runners
in scoring position. During the just-concluded nine-game road trip,
the Dodgers scored four runs or less seven times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we jelled offensively? No,'' Johnson said. ``Have we
jelled pitching-wise? I think we're getting closer. What's
frustrating is that first game here. We could have broken that game
open. We just haven't put it all together. That's the frustrating
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Vero Beach update: Dodgers officials met briefly with
representatives from Vero Beach, Fla., and Indian River County in
Florida to discuss the ramifications of Gov. Jeb Bush vetoing $7.5
million in funding and came away with very little.
</P>
<P>
   Indian River County administrator Jim Chandler said the meeting
lasted approximately one hour. Dodgers general counsel Sam
Fernandez and director of business development Fred Coons asked the
city and county to exhaust every option in trying to find more
funding than the $13 million available. ``We agreed that everybody
(should be) creative to see if there's a way we can make things
work out,'' Coons said.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler said there wasn't any additional funding that could be
secured. If the Dodgers wanted to remain at Dodgertown, the
organization would have to drastically change its demands to have
the land purchased and the site renovated. No other face-to-face
meetings are planned, though the sides will continue to talk via
telephone. Coons said the team expects to meet soon with
representatives from the Fort McDowell Indian Community, near
Phoenix, about their proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Draft Dodgers: The Dodgers' first three picks of the amateur
draft were shortstops, which held with the club's philosophy of
drafting pure talent and tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're tool guys, have high ceilings,'' Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone said. ``We're trying to get more athleticism,
more speed-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' first choice, 37th overall, was ``sandwich pick''
Jason Repko of Hanford High in West Richland, Wash. Repko, a
5-foot-11, 175-pounder, batted .581 with 18 homers and 47 RBI. He
was rated 54th on Baseball America's Top 100 prospects list.
</P>
<P>
   Repko, who will be represented by his dad, Ed, and his family
will be at Dodger Stadium this weekend to begin contract
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pumped about it. I'm in awe,'' Repko, 18, said. ``It just
gives me the opportunity to do something I've worked for all my
life. I've always had a goal of being a major-league baseball
player. This is the next step. It's what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' next two picks were shortstops Brennan King of
Oakland High in Morfreesboro, Tenn. (69th overall) and Drew Meyer
of Bishop England High in Charleston, S.C. (83rd).
</P>
<P>
   Extra bases: Johnson said a likely scenario has the Dodgers
placing Todd Hollandsworth on the disabled list Friday and
activating utility infielder Jose Vizcaino, despite Johnson's talk
of needing a fifth outfielder to rest White. ``There really isn't
another left-handed (batting) outfielder (in the system),'' Johnson
said. ``The good thing is we have a few days off coming up. That'll
help Devo. He's been dragging the past few days.'' . . . White and
Grudzielanek were given the day off and replaced in the lineup by
Trenidad Hubbard and Tripp Cromer.
</P>
</TEXT>
