<SLUG> BC-MCVIDEO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN VIDEO SELLS PERSONAL STORY, NOT POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain on Wednesday unveiled his
presidential campaign video, a feel-good biography that aims to
yank at America's heartstrings by employing dramatic
black-and-white footage of McCain twice eluding death during the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign immediately sent 50,000 copies of the video
to likely Republican voters in New Hampshire, which is hosting a
February 2000 primary considered crucial to the Arizona
Republican's chances.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-minute video is long on personality themes and
comparatively short on issues.
</P>
<P>
   While other candidates highlight their positions _ Steve Forbes,
for example, emphasizes his tax-simplification plan _ McCain's
campaign handlers believe his personal story is his most powerful
selling point.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the video features grainy footage of McCain, a Navy pilot,
scrambling out of a plane in 1967 after it was hit by a rocket that
misfired on the deck of the USS Forrestal. The subsequent fire and
explosions killed 134 men.
</P>
<P>
   There are clips of McCain, filmed by a French film crew, lying
on his back in a Hanoi prison camp after his plane was shot out of
the sky. He was held by his captors from October 1967 until March
1973.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping it personal, a present-day McCain is seen reminiscing
about the impact his absence had on his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter, Sidney, was 6 months old when I left to go to
Vietnam, and 6 years old when I returned,'' McCain says on the
tape. He said Sidney grew more accustomed to having pets than a
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when my (first) wife, Carol, was telling her, `Your daddy
is coming gome,' she said, `Oh yeah, where will he sleep and what
do we feed him?' ''
</P>
<P>
   What the video does not say is almost as important as what it
does.
</P>
<P>
   For example, President Clinton is never mentioned. But the video
displays a lingering image of the White House with this voiceover:
``At a time when some leaders let us down, John McCain is a man we
can believe, and believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the video make reference to Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
the GOP front-runner in the polls. But the video chronicles the
McCain family's extensive military background and says McCain is
``more tested and better prepared'' to lead than others seeking the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``A son of the Navy, John Sidney McCain was born into a family
where duty, honor and country are articles of faith,'' the narrator
says. ``His father and grandfather were admirals, and, at the age
of 17, young John McCain followed in their footsteps to the U.S.
Naval Academy.''
</P>
<P>
   The video does not say that the young McCain, who seemed to have
a rebellious streak, finished near the bottom of his class.
</P>
<P>
   The video was produced by Stevens Reed Curcio, McCain's
Virginia-based polling firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``His story is remarkable enough if you just recite the words,''
said Paul Curcio, a partner in the firm. ``But to have the actual
film of some of those events taking place _ whether on the
Forrestal or in the Hanoi Hilton _ it just gives it that much more
power and poignancy.''
</P>
<P>
   Little, if any, of the footage in the video is simulated.
However, neither Curcio nor campaign spokesman Howard Opinsky said
they knew the origin of a fleeting shot of McCain parachuting from
the sky over Hanoi after he was shot down. Opinsky said he could
not rule out the possibility that the clip was a re-creation.
</P>
<P>
   The video makes reference to McCain's divorce to his first wife,
saying it is typical for POWs to struggle with their family lives
upon their return. McCain's second wife, the former Cindy Hensley,
appears on camera and describes her husband as ``a loving, kind,
strong father. He understands the importance of being there and
being relied upon.''
</P>
<P>
   The video was previewed by McCain campaign staff members for the
press at a downtown Washington restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign videos have become increasingly important since the
emergence of video capabilities on the Internet. In 1992, Clinton
made effective use of a video detailing his humble origins. It was
shown at the Democratic National Convention to help warm up the
crowd before Clinton accepted the nomination. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
