<HEADER>
A1015 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-U.S.OPEN-COURSE-T     06-03 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S. </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS EXPECT OLD WAVERLY COURSE TO POSE FORMIDABLE OPEN
CHALLENGE
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-COURSE-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year, rising star Se Ri Pak won the U.S. Women's Open golf
championship with the highest over-par score in the tournament in
15 years. While the then-20-year-old Korean-born pro commanded
center stage at the LPGA's greatest show, she had to share some of
the spotlight with the golf course on which she won.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwolf Run in Kohler, Wis., was the real winner, some golf
analysts observed, bringing the field to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Open, which begins Thursday, is being played at Old
Waverly Golf Club, a universally acclaimed layout in West Point,
Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a phenom such as Pak will again emerge as the surprise
champion is not known. What is certain is that like Blackwolf Run,
Old Waverly will try the souls and talents of the best women's
players in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Said Meg Mallon, the 1991 U.S. Women's Open champion, ``It's a
fabulous course. I'm excited to see what kind of shape the (United
States Golf Association) has it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's going to be a bear, but a fair test of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in 1998 it was Blackwolf. In 1999, it's The Bear.
</P>
<P>
   Opened 11 years ago, Old Waverly will play to 6,433 yards for
the Open and a par of 72.
</P>
<P>
   There are hazards aplenty, including 40-acre Lake Waverly, which
comes into play at five holes on the back nine, including No. 17
and No. 18, a finishing hole that offers the potential for a
dramatic conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Old Waverly was modified after being awarded the
Open four years ago, and those modifications won't make scoring any
easier. For example, bunkers were added, bringing the total of
traps to 101. In addition, 11 tees were redone and two greens were
rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the USGA's handling of the rough that could make for
difficult shots and high scores, as the women pros know all too
well. While the USGA likes deep rough for its championships, the
rough for the U.S. Women's Open will be held to two inches.
</P>
<P>
   That might seem like a less-than-severe test, but golfers point
out that the Old Waverly rough, a hybrid Bermuda grass, is tough
even at a shorter depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Bermuda, it's like a nest when the ball settles in
there,'' said Austin resident and former University of Texas golfer
Cindy Figg-Currier, an LPGA Tour competitor. ``It can be really
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Figg-Currier said golfers accustomed to attempting challenging
recovery shots from the rough on other courses might be
well-advised to play it safe from Old Waverly's rough by pitching
back into the fairway and all but conceding bogey.
</P>
<P>
   The greens won't be any bargain, either, being bent grass and
tuned to warp speed, per USGA standards.
</P>
<P>
   If the course, designed by Bob Cupp and Jerry Pate, doesn't get
to the pros, the weather might. Even golfers accustomed to
performing in warm weather could be affected by the potential heat
and humidity of small-town central Mississippi in June.
</P>
<P>
   Figg-Currier said she was happy to play in Austin recently at
the Philips International Honoring Harvey Penick because it allowed
her a test under Texas' hot and humid conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Favorites to survive Old Waverly start with the tour's top
players. Among them: Karrie Webb, Julie Inkster and Mallon _ each
of whom has won multiple events this season, as has Rachel
Hetherington. Superstar Annika Sorenstam, who has yet to win this
year, is another possible contender along with Pak, who also has
failed to repeat her successes of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mallon and Inkster said they are pointing for this Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the majors,'' Mallon said. ``They're usually
our best-conditioned courses and our toughest tests of golf. I
really get psyched up for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, who has won three major championships among her 19 LPGA
victories, has never won the Open, although she finished second in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about the Open,'' Inkster said, ``is that you have
to be on a course you like, that suits your game.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Open rotates among venues, she added, ``That happens
maybe twice in five years.'' In addition, she said, a player has to
be at the top of her game to contend.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of one of her best seasons, the veteran hopes this
is the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the U.S. Open would the capper (to my career),''
Inkster said. ``It would be the icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, she must get past The Bear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
