r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRIVING-WHILE-BLACK-K     06-03 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVING-WHILE-BLACK-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Racial profiling is simply unfair, minorities say  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It is a hot August evening, and Katherine
Carrell is chatting with her two sons on the lawn outside the
family's Blue Springs, Mo., townhouse.
</P>
<P>
   As she talks, Carrell is eying a police car, creeping up and
down the street. The police car goes by three times during their
brief conversation, turning around at the end of the cul-de-sac.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip, 21, and Quintin, 19, get into their car and drive off,
headed for the movies. The cruiser, parked about 50 feet up the
street, pulls out too.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed, Carrell waves her arms, flagging down both the squad
car and her sons. She demands to know why the officer has taken so
much interest in her sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't look like they fit in this neighborhood,'' the
officer says.
</P>
<P>
   Carrell is furious. She is half Japanese and half
African-American. Her sons' father is African-American. The officer
is white.
</P>
<P>
   This is Carrell's version of events; Blue Springs police tell a
different story. In their version, the officer's suspicions were
based on the young men's actions, not their skin color.
</P>
<P>
   That incident, like many involving minorities and police, boils
down to perceptions: what officers see as suspicious behavior,
viewed from one angle, and what minorities see as racial
harassment, viewed from another.
</P>
<P>
   For generations, African-Americans, Hispanics and other ethnic
groups have argued that they are routinely stopped by police and
questioned simply because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, that has been an unproven allegation. But that
may be changing. Proposed federal legislation, court-ordered
remedies and pressure from civil-rights groups are fueling studies
to determine whether minorities are targeted unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union, in a report released
Wednesday, said the number of highway traffic stops based on race
has increased significantly because of the war on drugs. The ACLU
has filed lawsuits in Maryland, Illinois, New Jersey and Oklahoma
challenging the police practice known as racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, Katherine Carrell isn't the only one
with a firsthand account. Others, including several business
executives, say they believe they have been stopped because of
their skin color.
</P>
<P>
   Racial stereotypes that link minorities to criminal behavior are
viewed as the catalyst for the stops. In the view of many
minorities, their ``suspicious behavior'' amounts to nothing more
than ``Driving While Black.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Stopped many times
</P>
<P>
   The Carrells have lived in their Blue Springs home for nearly
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, Quintin Carrell estimates he has been stopped
more than a dozen times. He has been followed by police, frisked
and told that he was stopped because of reports of a prowler.
</P>
<P>
   But he has never been ticketed for a traffic offense. A noise
violation for his car stereo was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they apply their stereotypes on me, `a black man
driving in a predominately white town,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Carrell is afraid for her sons _ especially Phillip,
who she knows may be short-tempered with police because he is fed
up with what he views as unfair treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just scary,'' Carrell said. ``I'm afraid for the phone
call from the police saying, `We are sorry. We stopped your son and
we thought he had a gun. He was shot and killed.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After the encounter in front of her home, she filed a complaint
with the Blue Springs Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Written reports compiled during the investigation of the
complaint tell the police version of the evening's events. Blue
Springs police allowed The Kansas City Star to read the complete
file of reports.
</P>
<P>
   The officer wrote he had received ``hard, furtive glances'' from
her sons when he had driven by them minutes earlier, before their
car stopped at the home.
</P>
<P>
   The car was unfamiliar to the officer. The young men pulled up
on the curb, instead of pulling into the driveway. They bounded up
the lawn, leaving one car door open. Another young man, also
African-American, was left sitting in the front passenger seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, based on my training and experience as a police
officer, I believed the occupants of the vehicle may have been
involved in some type of criminal activity,'' the officer wrote in
a report later.
</P>
<P>
   The officer asserts he did not intend to stop Carrell's sons.
His suspicions were alleviated when he saw the boys talking with
their mother.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Springs Police Chief H.L. Brown supports his officer's
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the exact same set of circumstances and turn them white,
the officer would have done the exact same thing,'' Brown said.
``They were suspicious.''  &LR; brk:Chiefs consider matter
</P>
<P>
   In early April, 20 police chiefs from some of the nation's
largest cities gathered to discuss the perception of racially
biased traffic stops. The Washington meeting was called by the
Police Executive Research Forum, which represents 40 percent of
America's police forces.
</P>
<P>
   Local departments also recognize that there is a widely held
belief that race plays a role in traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   Overland Park Chief of Police John Douglass accepts that police
officers are influenced by the racial stereotypes inherent in
American society. Some officers initially might want to act when
they see a black or Hispanic who doesn't seem to ``fit'' in an
area, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those myths have to be trained out,'' Douglass said. ``It has
to be taught away.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the Blue Springs chief, argues that, at times, police are
correct to note the person who seems ``out of place.'' But good
policing means not acting on that suspicion until it is supported
by other factors, Brown and others said.
</P>
<P>
   ``An officer should be able to tell you why he stopped you,''
said Atkins Warren, a former police chief and now the regional
director of the U.S. Justice Department's Community Relations
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have led police to this point.
</P>
<P>
   The courts, over a number of years, have given more authority to
police in car stops. A 1996 Supreme Court decision said police may
use traffic stops as a pretext to uncover other types of criminal
activity.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, zero-tolerance policies on drugs have fueled
an increase in police actions. One result is a nationwide drop in
crime, but more contacts with police for some people.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Wexler, the forum's executive director, recalls the
comment of one chief: ``It seems like the better the job we do in
driving crime down, the more the trust factor in the community is
being diminished,'' the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Diminished trust undermines community policing, a philosophy
practiced in Kansas City and many other cities. Community policing
asks citizens to link with police in fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we drive crime way down, but it comes at the expense of the
community's respect, it is not worth it,'' Wexler said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials argue that race is often wrongly blamed when
minorities don't understand what may have aroused their suspicions.
That assertion _ that minorities too often claim race as the reason
for their stop _ is a factor in the Carrell case.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Fain, director of the Kansas City Police Department's
Office of Citizen Complaints, said racial bias is a common
complaint, even though police unions and associations say officers
often can't determine the race of a driver when they stop a car.
</P>
<P>
   Fain, an African-American, says she hears the race issue raised
from every perspective: whites complaining a black officer was
racist to give them a ticket, and blacks saying they were stopped
solely because of their race by a white officer.
</P>
<P>
   With each case, she does what she terms ``reality testing,''
probing for more information. ``What else might have singled you
out?'' she will ask a black person who was stopped by a white
officer.  &LR; brk:Statistics needed
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation, efforts are under way to push for valid
statistics to attach to this question of perception.
</P>
<P>
   A few court-ordered studies of traffic stop patterns are proving
that minorities in some areas are subjected to a disproportionate
number of traffic stops. The New Jersey Turnpike is the
most-often-cited example.
</P>
<P>
   There, a study found African-Americans made up 13.5 percent of
the traffic and 15 percent of the speeders, but were subject to 46
percent of the traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed federal legislation would order law enforcement
agencies to collect data to track any possible racial patterns in
police activity. At least 12 state legislatures are also
considering legislation that would require such studies.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri legislature, in its last session, passed such a
measure. But it has no teeth because it did not order the Highway
Patrol to collect the data, but simply suggested it ``may'' keep
the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Police Organizations, which
represents police unions, argues that the public needs to
understand it might come in contact with police as they fight
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a society, sometimes law-abiding citizens will be
inconvenienced when police aggressively enforce the laws and
investigate crimes,'' wrote Robert Scully, executive director of
the 220,000 member National Association.
</P>
<P>
   Overland Park Chief Douglass is a member of another group
opposed to the proposed legislation _ the International Association
of Chiefs of Police. Douglass is a member of the chiefs group's
ethics and image committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the consensus is we would all be naive to believe
that there are no police officers who don't tend to stop people
based on race,'' Douglass said. ``But we don't feel it is as
widespread as some people believe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
