<SLUG> BC-FUEL-SUMMIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIONS FOR ENSURING AREA'S AIR QUALITY DEBATED AT FUEL SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ You've heard of designer suits and jewelry,
but can you imagine designer gasoline?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one way for Kansas City to bring its air quality into
compliance with federal guidelines may involve what oil industry
representatives refer to as a ``designer'' or ``boutique'' fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel is so named because it's a special blend _ in this
case, a Kansas City blend _ that is intended to help a community
meet its specific air-quality needs.
</P>
<P>
   This designer fuel was suggested Wednesday at a daylong ``fuel
summit'' as one of the three or four main options for cleaning the
metro area's air.
</P>
<P>
   Although not their preference, oil industry representatives
indicated that even a regional blend would be better than
reformulated gas, which is designed to reduce emissions of
chemicals that create ozone. Use of reformulated gasoline is the
key element in the metro area's strategy for meeting federal
air-quality guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``RFG is just not an option for us,'' said Gary Schooveld, who
represented Phillips 66.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting assembled regulators, local officials, oil refiners,
petroleum marketers and advocates of different alternative fuel
blends at the Jack Reardon Civic Center in Kansas City, Kan. The
meeting concludes today and is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   During the meeting, the oil refiners raised numerous questions
and criticized the push to bring reformulated gas to Kansas City
area pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Ric Telthorst of the Missouri Oil Council said the main
opposition is centered on an oil industry lawsuit in Washington
that claims it is illegal for Kansas City, as well as some other
cities, to have such fuel. The federal Clean Air Act, he explained,
has set limits on how the fuel could be introduced into a
community. Kansas City, he said, doesn't meet the requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The oil refiners oppose making it available to more cities
because it would increase their costs of production. Some refiners
in the Missouri Oil Council don't yet make the new fuel, while
others have only a limited capacity to produce it.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Jack Smith, a professional facilitator who led a similar
session in St. Louis last year, the meeting today will address the
area's more immediate clean-air problem: making its transportation
plans conform to federal requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In May, federal transportation officials ruled, unexpectedly,
that the area's transportation plan fails to conform with its
clean-air plans. As a result, those transportation plans have
lapsed and new highway improvement projects that expand a highway's
capacity must be placed on hold.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest way out of that fix would be for the governors of
Missouri and Kansas to request that the metro area be allowed to
bring reformulated gas to area service stations in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If the governors don't act in about a month, millions of dollars
in highway expansions, including some $30 million in construction
on the new Chouteau Bridge, may be placed on hold, state and
federal official say.
</P>
<P>
   The governors have promised to make a decision after the fuel
summit.
</P>
<P>
   The need to move quickly on the transportation plan issue may be
the toughest hurdle in the path toward a regional ``designer''
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Randolph, chief air pollution regulator for the Missouri
Department of Natural Resources, told the oil refiners Wednesday
that designing a special state blend would take months to work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't leave today saying we want to investigate a new state
fuel for x-number of months,'' Randolph said. ``That's a
non-answer. We can't go that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
