<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1023 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KC-SCHOOLS-KAN &LR;      06-03 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-SCHOOLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL BOARD'S ACTION ON ADMINISTRATOR LEAVES MANY QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANIKA WHITE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ By asking the Kansas City Board of Education
for a vote of confidence Tuesday night, Phyllis Chase hoped to
better determine her chances of becoming the permanent district
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Some district observers, however, say Chase's request was an
exercise in futility.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her best efforts, they say, the interim chief
administrator for curriculum and instruction will not be the next
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my understanding that the DMC (Desegregation Monitoring
Committee) is not in favor of her being superintendent. They don't
think she's qualified,'' said Arthur A. Benson II, lawyer for the
plaintiff schoolchildren in the federal desegregation case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard that she was spending a lot of time campaigning
for the superintendency. But I think she should concentrate her
energies on more productive goals like helping educate the kids in
the Kansas City School District while she's looking for another
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the monitoring committee would not comment publicly
about whether Chase was still under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent search committee _ which consists of all
three DMC members and school board member Helen Ragsdale _
interviewed Chase in early May.
</P>
<P>
   The committee later rejected the initial round of candidates and
asked a search firm to find others.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said Wednesday that she thought she still was in the
running, because the search committee had not specifically told her
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly I'm a candidate,'' Chase said. ``And I've been doing
the job for the last six months, and I still desire to be up for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to look at my future options, and I think it's
critical that I know where the board of directors is in terms of my
candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting Tuesday four board members gave Chase a vote of
confidence, three members voted no, and Sandy Mayer abstained.
Connie Clark was absent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the board's position was just as muddled.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer said she should have voted against the motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in favor of her taking that (superintendent's)
position,'' Mayer said. ``I think we need a superintendent who is
going to challenge the board based on what's best for the children.
She has had the authority. She has had her hands free to make tough
decisions, and I haven't seen that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Riley said he wished he could change his no vote to an
abstention.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a vote saying I don't support Phyllis Chase,''
Riley said. ``It's just there are more important things at hand,
and I support people by actions, not by symbols.''
</P>
<P>
   Ragsdale said her no vote was against the motion, not against
Chase. But she said she was disappointed that Chase put the board
in such a position.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should have realized that we supported her when we went to
court and asked them to reconsider and let her apply for that job.
So that was a show of support,'' Ragsdale said. ``And she applied
for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said it was difficult for board members to push the
candidacy of any one person because the selection committee chooses
the candidates who will be presented to the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know where we stand in our power to select a
superintendent,'' Riley said. ``I feel like we're in between a rock
and a hard spot, because the DMC has so much power.''
</P>
<P>
   Board member Patricia Kurtz said that despite the monitoring
committee's heavy involvement and the questions about Chase's
candidacy, community and board support could be enough to win Chase
the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if you count votes, she's got the (board) votes
to be the superintendent. I don't understand why they (the DMC)
don't see this as I do, that we have the best of all possible
worlds here,'' Kurtz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very willing to embrace someone within the organization
who has proven herself under the most difficult circumstances. I
think she has the potential to flourish into a very fine leader of
the district.''
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring committee member Charles McClain said the selection
committee expected to present more candidates to the board in the
next two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
