<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-DEPARTURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTI MANUEL IS LEAVING SPRINT FOR TELOCITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Patti Manuel, formerly president of Sprint's
long-distance division and the company's top-ranking woman
executive, has signed on as president of Telocity Inc., a
telecommunications start-up in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Telocity, started in 1997, is a provider of digital subscriber
line service. DSL is a technology that allows telephone companies
to provide high-speed Internet service over standard copper phone
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Telocity is developing a technology that will let consumers
install DSL service in their homes without an expensive and
time-consuming visit by an installer. The company is testing the
resulting product, a box, and hopes to introduce it in partnership
with phone companies by the end of summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make DSL more of a plug-and-play product, to
eliminate the truck roll by the phone company,'' Manuel said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel, 42, worked at Westwood-based Sprint Corp. for 13 years.
She was head of the long-distance division for slightly more than a
year. Manuel quit in late March, citing personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   She said the move to Telocity involved a substantial cut from
the $876,910 she earned in salary and bonus at Sprint in 1998. She
will, however, have a substantial equity position in Telocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risk,'' she said, ``but an educated risk on a market
that is growing very rapidly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
