<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1026 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANGSTERS-KAN &LR;      06-03 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANGSTERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR WILL TAKE YOU BACK TO A TIME OF TOMMY GUNS AND `PRETTY BOY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Zoot-suited gangsters and billy club-wielding
cops take center stage this summer when Gray Line begins offering
guided bus tours of Kansas City's seamy past.
</P>
<P>
   The Gangsters of Kansas City Tour will join Gray Line's other
motor coach trips that focus on the city's pioneer history, jazz,
fountains and Harry S. Truman, said Bill George, president of
Metropolitan Transportation Services Inc., which operates Gray
Line.
</P>
<P>
   The famous bullet holes in Union Station _ long believed put
there June 17, 1933, by Charles ``Pretty Boy'' Floyd and others in
a shootout with authorities _ are to be one of the tour's
highlights.
</P>
<P>
   Union Station also will serve as the starting point for what
promises to be part guided tour and part Disneyesque production
complete with costumed characters and what some say is an
inappropriate script.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been determined how specific the narration will be
regarding more recent events, including the mob wars of the 1970s
that spelled an end to the city's River Quay district _ reborn a
decade later as the River Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sensitive subject,'' George acknowledged. ``The tour
has a gangster theme, but everything's going to have a positive
spin. The rebirth of the River Market, for example, is a great
story.''
</P>
<P>
   George announced the plans at a luncheon Wednesday attended by
members of the Hotel and Motel Association of Greater Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The tour _ which sounds similar to a gangster-themed tour in
Chicago _ is raising a few eyebrows in the Jackson County
prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Present-day violence and crime is what we're fighting,'' said
Phil Levota, an assistant prosecutor who specializes in inner-city
gang cases. ``Any time you glorify violence, it is just not a good
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan employee Gary Conroy agrees the city's crime
history is a touchy topic for many. Conroy, 52, said Wednesday he
grew up in the Northeast area where elements of Kansas City's
organized crime family have long had a foothold.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the characters we're not going to name in the
narration, I grew up with,'' Conroy said.
</P>
<P>
   Conroy is leaving his desk job at Metropolitan to perform as
fictional Johnny ``KC'' Holiday in a running gangster skit that
accompanies each tour. It culminates in a shootout with police.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday survives. The officer, named O'Henry, doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City does have colorful history, and gangsters are
certainly a part of it,'' Levota said. But the shootout crosses the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``A policeman getting shot would be something this office would
not find entertaining,'' Levota said.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute to two-hour tour will cost between $19 and $24 per
person, depending on the price of an embossed souvenir tin cup
that, George says, serves as a symbol of the bathtub-gin and
speakeasy era.
</P>
<P>
   Tour riders also will get a taste of Kansas City from before
World War II through the 1950s, as video monitors flash pictures of
historic but long-gone buildings, the Country Club Plaza under
construction and other scenes as the coach passes by those spots.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part now, said George, is finishing the research,
producing the video and pacing it to match the tour. The company
hired a local historian who is compiling information.
</P>
<P>
   Not much is final at this point, George said. But tales of
Kansas City political boss Tom Pendergast certainly will be
included.
</P>
<P>
   George said the tour should have plenty of appeal for both
tourists and Kansas Citians. ``We want people to be tourists in
their own town...to discover what's in their own back yard,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gangster Tour bus will be hard to miss on the city's
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan paid $100,000 for a custom-built 16-passenger coach
that mimics a 1930s panel truck _ typically used to transport
illicit alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   It will be chased by a restored 1940s Chevrolet Fleetline,
painted as a black-and-white police cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the city's very colorful past,'' George said,
``but just as well as how far we've come. The tour is really going
to showcase midtown and downtown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
