<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DRAFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS USE TOP PICKS ON TWO YOUNG PITCHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Texas Rangers selected two pitchers with
their two ``sandwich'' picks in Wednesday's first-year player
draft.
</P>
<P>
   If they are as talented as they are enthusiastic about who
drafted them, then the Rangers' pitching problems are over.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers used the 38th overall pick to take right-hander
Colby Lewis from Bakersfield (Calif.) College and the 47th overall
pick to select right-hander David Mead from Soddy Daisy High School
in Sale Creek, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Both pitchers are hard throwers, although Lewis underwent elbow
ligament transplant surgery three years ago. But Rangers scouting
director Chuck McMichael said Lewis' elbow is no longer a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewis is a physically strong guy,'' McMichael said. ``He's a
fastball, curveball guy who is learning a changeup. This is a guy
you give to your player-development people and say, `OK baby.' ...
The ball leaves his hand and explodes at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mead is a real lean, real lanky guy with a high leg kick and
what we call a very whippy arm. He has a chance to throw extremely
hard some day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers must first sign them, but that doesn't appear to be
a major obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who was 4-5 with a 2.86 earned-run average and 108
strikeouts in 88 innings, has signed a letter of intent to play for
Long Beach State but said he doesn't expect to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highly unlikely,'' Lewis said. ``I'm pretty much 100
percent set on the Rangers. I'm not worried about getting enough
money. To be a club's first pick is outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Mead, who was 2-3 with a 3.56 ERA and 61 strikeouts in 41
innings for Soddy Daisy, has a scholarship to Santa Fe Community
College in Gainesville, Fla., but said he also expects to turn
professional instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lifelong dream,'' Mead said. ``I'm still in shock.
... As long as the negotiations go well, I will sign with the
Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Through 22 rounds, the Rangers made 25 picks, including former
Irving High School standout Ernie Villegas in the 14th round and
Martin High School outfielder Kevin Marshall in the 20th round.
</P>
<P>
   Villegas, an outfielder from Northeast Texas Community College
in Mount Pleasant, was picked by the New York Yankees in the 12th
round in 1997. Marshall hit .385 with eight triples, 28 runs scored
and 23 runs batted in this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took 13 pitchers among those 25 picks, seven
outfielders, three catchers, a shortstop and a first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, the Rangers selected right-hander Nick
Regilio, a sinker/slider pitcher with an above-average changeup who
was 7-2 with a 4.58 ERA for Jacksonville University in Florida. In
the third round, the Rangers took Hank Blalock, a shortstop from
Rancho Bernardo (Calif.) High School who hit .515 with 11 homers
and 40 RBI this year. The Rangers will likely move him to third
base.
</P>
<P>
   There was one painful note for the Rangers. The Oakland
Athletics took Southern California pitcher Barry Zito with the
ninth overall pick. The Rangers drafted him in the third round last
year out of junior college but couldn't sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't acrimonious negotiations,'' McMichael said.
``They were confusing negotiations. I think the kid wanted to sign.
Whatever advice he was getting... I don't know.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
