<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVITZ GETS COOL RECEPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Given the month of June by the NFL to present his
plans for a remodeled Coliseum to the area's multitude of agencies,
Michael Ovitz opened his rush salesmanship Wednesday with the
Coliseum Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Many on the commission have been working with the rival Eli
Broad-Ed Roski Jr. group competing with Ovitz for the ownership of
the NFL's 32nd franchise, and Ovitz hardly found an audience eager
to embrace his belated Coliseum plans.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Mike Roos, while calling Ovitz's elaborate plans
``bold and daring,'' clearly was miffed he had put together his
Coliseum renovation scheme on state property without first
consulting with the commission or other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm struck by, isn't there a high potential that you have
developed a wonderful illusion that's a house of cards?'' Roos
asked. ``If you take one card out, the whole thing collapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the (Los Angeles) conservancy people say, `Your concept may
well be to emulate and model on the Coliseum in Rome, but that's
not what our purpose is.' If in fact they pull that card out, what
happens to all the reliant parts that you have built this model
upon?''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz originally wanted to build a new stadium in Carson, and
after the NFL announced the Coliseum as the Los Angeles expansion
site, had less than six weeks to design new plans for the
historical monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very much like a Chinese jigsaw puzzle,'' Ovitz said.
``A bit of a Catch 22. The question is, do you go to all of the
committees first and get everyone's point of view and then design,
which we did not have the time to do? Or do you design something
that is going to catch (the NFL's) attention and get them to take
Los Angeles very seriously, when there is a deal sitting in Houston
that is actually incredibly acceptable right now? What we attempted
to do, was meet their needs first.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz first presented his ``vision'' for the Coliseum to NFL
owners last week in Atlanta. Broad also presented an update of his
plan to the owners, stressing his group had met with the proper
agencies for input, his plan was not ``pie in the sky'' and was one
that could get done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due diligence'' became a sudden catch phrase for NFL
commissioner Paul Tagliabue and he talked of using this month to
exercise earnest application of the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Broad-Roski plans are all but complete, and there is
little left for their group to accomplish this month. But for
Ovitz, it is another opportunity to catch up at the Coliseum, and
it enhances the suspicion among many he is the favored prospective
owner of Tagliabue and the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, you have a person (Ovitz) willing to go
anywhere, willing to do a design on the back of an envelope,'' Roos
said. ``Yet, tell me if I'm not hearing this right, but they seem
to be calling him. They seem to be saying, `Here is the criteria,
you solve the problem.'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ovitz said after the commission meeting he has been in
close contact with Tagliabue since the NFL meetings in Atlanta
ended last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just talked to (Tagliabue) on my way over here, actually,
and briefed him on what was going on,'' Ovitz said. ``He's going to
call me tonight because he wants to know what went on here and said
in the month of June he wants us to present this plan to all of the
local constituencies, and this is what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the discussion with the Coliseum Commission focused on
parking. The Ovitz plan calls for five garages that could hold
27,000 parking spaces and cost an estimated $250 million, money he
said would have to come from outside his ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz said Wednesday, however, the NFL asked for 25,000 spaces,
so he provided a method for building them around the Coliseum. He
said the garages were modular in design and fewer spaces could be
built.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan on looking for advice, we are looking for feedback at
this point and we are not suggesting that we build these plans as
they stand,'' Ovitz said. ``This is what we were asked to do in
order to bring football back to Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Lisa Specht and Roos also quizzed Ovitz about
possibly teaming up with Broad. Roos said if Ovitz was so open to
new ideas, what about the plans Broad-Roski had already put
together with input from the area agencies?
</P>
<P>
   ``Great, that idea was presented and I assume if they (NFL
owners) wanted that idea, they would have chosen that plan and
voted on it, and that would have been that,'' Ovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz has been invited by Broad to join his group, and Ovitz
said he expects to talk to Broad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're wide open to it,'' Ovitz said. ``I like Eli a lot. We've
known each other a long time. I think he has to look at what we're
doing, and we have to look at what he's doing and see if there's
some common ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the projects are compatible, but surely our
desire here downtown are.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad-Roski announced they were giving up their exclusive
agreement with the Coliseum at the owners meetings, and the
Coliseum Commission officially severed the agreement
Wednesday. &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
