<HEADER>
A1033 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     06-03 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MILWAUKEE _ If County Stadium can withstand the explosives the
Astros set off Wednesday night, it may take a few well-placed
missiles when the time comes to demolish the outgoing ballpark at
the end of the season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Astros' offense, a powder keg of frustration in recent
games, smoked the Milwaukee Brewers 9-1 in what they hope was a
breakout game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were due for one of those,'' said Astros third baseman Bill
Spiers, who drove in his first two runs since May 18.
</P>
<P>
   And Jose Lima was due for a win. After all, he was riding a
one-game losing streak, which constitutes a drought considering the
way he has pitched this season.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who had an eight-game winning streak snapped in his
previous outing, bounced back stronger than ever, holding the
Brewers to four hits in his second complete game of the season. It
was the fewest hits Lima has allowed in a nine-inning outing in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to brag on myself,'' Lima said. ``But I had great
stuff. I kept my slider and my changeup down, and my sinker was
working. I only made one mistake all night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers scored on Dave Nilsson's homer in the fifth. Two of
their other three hits were infield singles. Lima struck out eight
batters and needed only 98 pitches to get through the 2-hour,
26-minute game.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored four runs in the first and five in the fourth
in an offensive display reminiscent of their quick-strike scoring
ability of the first six weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   How welcome was Wednesday's outburst? The Astros had scored
seven runs in their previous three games combined, and their nine
hits equaled their total for the previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that sooner or later we were going to bust out,''
Spiers said. ``When you struggle for as long as we've struggled,
you usually break out in a big way.''
</P>
<P>
   As many long nights as the Astros have endured at the expense of
opposing pitchers, it was about time they made short work of
someone. Cal Eldred, where have you been the past two weeks?
</P>
<P>
   Eldred, who has given up two touchdowns and a field goal in his
last two outings, may have been just what the Astros needed to get
their misguided offense back on track. The Astros scored nine runs
in 3 innings against Eldred in their most explosive offensive
showing since they beat the Dodgers 11-3 on May 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been scuffling for a while, and when you've got as many
talented hitters as we have, it's only a matter of time before you
turn it around,'' first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``It doesn't
matter who's pitching against us; sooner or later we're going to
get some hits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had the bases loaded when Tuesday's rain-shortened
game ended, and Wednesday they picked up where they left off,
blasting Eldred for four runs on three hits in the first inning.
Bagwell and Richard Hidalgo accounted for the scoring with a pair
of two-run homers.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hidalgo's second homer in four at-bats _ dating to Sunday
in Pittsburgh _ and his ninth of the season. Bagwell leads the
Astros with 15 home runs and 47 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros put together an even bigger inning in the fourth when
they scored five runs on three hits. Derek Bell drove in a run with
a sacrifice fly, and Carl Everett and Spiers each delivered two-run
singles.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson's blast over the right-center-field wall put the Brewers
on the scoreboard in the fifth inning. Nilsson's homer traveled 436
feet, the second-longest home run at County Stadium this season.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all the Brewers had to brag about as Lima retired 27
of the 31 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I get nervous when we score a lot of runs early in
the game,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``I worry because I
think the pitcher might get too relaxed. But Lima didn't. He
pitched one heck of a game. When he's on like he was tonight, he
doesn't give the other team anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Righthander Jim Pittsley relieved Eldred in the fourth inning
and pitched 4 scoreless innings. The Astros got only one hit over
the final five innings, but Lima made sure that was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lot of fun to play behind,'' Bagwell said. ``He pitches
fast, and he wins. That's a good combination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
