<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVAR FAMILY RELIEVED TO REACH LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUDIO CITY, Calif. -- A little more than a week ago, Kosovo
Liberation Army soldier Shukri Rexha was in the war-torn Balkans
fighting for his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   With much prodding by his cousin, West Hills resident Hajrush
Vlashi, he flew with his family and sister Wednesday to Los Angeles
International Airport and to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy to be here,'' said 33-year-old Rexha, who until a
little more than a week ago was fighting the Serbs. ``I still can't
believe I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rexha and his wife, Nadire, 21; their son, 23-month-old Andi;
and his sister, Nazmije, 14, were picked up at the airport at 2:30
p.m. by Vlashi's wife, Renee. On her way home, she dropped Rexha
off at her husband's work, the Out Take Cafe in suburban Studio
City, where he works as a waiter.
</P>
<P>
   When Rexha came walking in through the back of the restaurant,
Vlashi and five of his relatives from Kosovo, who flew to Los
Angeles only days ago, were waiting at a table. Ibrahim and Meside
Vlashi and their three children rose to their feet and greeted
Rexha with smiles and hugs. He kissed their children on their
cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rexha updated them about what was happening in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   From the restaurant's eclectic fare, Vlashi served him a Coke
and a lamb shank dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether it was his first Coke, Rexha said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we have that there,'' Vlashi said. ``We have a Coke
factory over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vlashi requested that Rexha's family come over a month ago and a
week ago Rexha decided to bring his family to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be with his family,'' Vlashi said. ``If it was
his choice, he'd go back tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rexha does return to Kosovo, Vlashi said, he'd like to keep
his family in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 32 members of the Vlashi family have now come to the
United States. The Vlashi family came from the small village of
Hani-Elezit, where a concrete factory was the major industry. Some
were truck drivers, security guards or supervisors. Others were
skilled craftsmen and professional musicians. The women were
housewives. Before all the wars started in Yugoslavia, Rexha served
his required year in the Yugoslav Army, where he was in the
military police. He's also a professional musician who plays
accordion and the keyboards. He spent several months in Switzerland
playing in a band in Albanian restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Since their arrival about two weeks ago, they have met with
vocational counselors, searched for houses and have began the
process of getting adjusted to life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After eating at the restaurant Wednesday, Vlashi and Rexha drove
to Vlashi's home in West Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very, very glad to be here,'' said Renee Vlashi. ``In
the car, (Rexha) was going, `I'm here in Los Angeles,' pointing to
things. I think he's planning on staying here with his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Renee said Rexha brought his family to the United States for the
same reason many other refugees have come here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is very bad over there,'' she said. ``We have
relatives calling almost every day wanting to come over.''
</P>
<P>
   She estimates her husband has about 200 more relatives either in
Kosovo or Macedonia. About 15 more hope to come to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really, really need money,'' Renee Vlashi said. ``(The
donations) have been slow.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
