</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS OUTLAST YANKEES, 10-7 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One pitcher was afraid to hit anybody, the other
pitcher seemed scared to throw the ball over the plate, and the
plate umpire was philosophically opposed to calling strikes. What
resulted at Yankee Stadium on Wednesday night merits a place in
posterity only because it serves as a stiff reminder that truly bad
baseball is possible at all levels.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Cleveland Indians combined for 147 pitches, 16
runs, 15 hits, 3 errors and 5 visits to the mound in 92 minutes.
And then they started the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Once Cleveland Manager Mike Hargrove yanked his starting
pitcher, Jaret Wright, the reliever Steve Karsay restored some
order and the Indians survived the Yankees, 10-7, to take the third
and decisive game in the three-game series. The Yankees will be off
on Thursdayy, before beginning a three-game series with the Mets on
Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees hope that the leadoff hitter Chuck Knoblauch will be
able to play. Knoblauch left Wednesday night's game in the fifth
inning, after Wright hit him in the ribs with a 94-mile-an-hour
fastball. Knoblauch said afterward that he expected to play. But
the Yankees aren't so sure about the reliever Jeff Nelson, who has
a stiff elbow and who may be headed to the disabled list again.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Indians are the American League's superpowers,
probably destined to play meaningful games sometime in the fall,
and for the first time, there is some uneasiness between the two
clubs. Three batters got hit Tuesday, Knoblauch was nailed on
Wednesday night, leaving Knoblauch and his teammates to wonder
whether Wright had hit him on purpose. ``You never know what some
people are thinking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wright and Andy Pettitte, the Yankees' starting pitcher,
threw so badly that it would be hard to imagine they could control
anything, let alone a beanball, in a game that disintegrated
quickly. With runners at first and third and one out in the top of
the first inning, Manny Ramirez hit a line drive to right, where
Paul O'Neill charged in, reached down with his glove, set his body
to throw home _ and flat missed the ball in the evening shadows. As
it rolled to the wall in right field, O'Neill in ragged pursuit,
both runners scored and Ramirez rambled into third base.
</P>
<P>
   The error came at the worst time, for Pettitte again was a
reluctant combatant; to Yankees Manager Joe Torre, Pettitte
appeared as if he were throwing stiffly, trying to guide the ball
over the plate. ``He kept getting behind in the count,'' Torre
said. ``And when you get behind, it's suicide against this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte said: ``I felt mechanical _ I started trying to do too
much out there. I was scuffling. I just stunk tonight. There's no
excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   After O'Neill's three-base error, Pettitte walked Jim Thome and
then Travis Fryman dumped a run-scoring double into right-center.
Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, walked slowly to the
mound and Pettitte's Adam's apple bobbed deeply. Pettitte walked
the No. 8 batter Einar Diaz before finally extricating himself from
the inning, having allowed four runs on 28 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Wright, however, Pettitte had all the presence of a
general. Eleven days ago, Wright plugged Detroit's Tony Clark in
the helmet with a fastball, prompting American League President
Gene Budig to schedule a face-to-face meeting with Wright. Probably
unsure whether he might be suspended, given detention or forced to
write ``I will not bean anybody'' 100 times, Wright surrendered
eight runs against Boston last Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wright met with Budig Tuesday and, according to Hargrove,
exchanged some good ideas. Budig apparently had little to offer in
the way of pitching advice, however, because Wright was a mess
against the Yanks. After throwing a fastball high and tight to
Knoblauch in the first, the 36,955 fans at Yankee Stadium booed
him. Young and stubborn, Wright brushed off the effects of the
jeering later, but the fact remains that after the fans noisily
reminded him that he was on unspoken, double-secret probation for
hitting too many batters, he fell apart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter singled. O'Neill doubled. Bernie Williams doubled.
Tino Martinez walked. With one out, Scott Brosius singled, and just
like that, the Yankees led, 5-4. O'Neill slammed a two-run home run
in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte was hardly in the frame of mind to protect a lead.
He got away with two walks in the second inning. (Neither Pettitte
nor Wright was helped by the fact that the home-plate umpire, Tim
Tschida, called a consistently miniature strike zone.) But Pettitte
allowed a two-run double to Omar Vizquel and a run-scoring single
to Alomar and the score was tied. The screams for Torre to take
action grew louder, and when Torre went to the mound to make a
change, Pettitte was booed, as if his name were Irabu or something.
Little more than half of his 72 pitches were thrown for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But even after Ramiro Mendoza took over, the Indians went on to
add two more runs in that inning, one scoring after an error by
Martinez, who may have been lulled into a daze by the incredibly
slow pace.
</P>
<P>
   Wright continued to get in trouble and Karsay took over in the
fourth, giving up just one hit in three and two-thirds innings and
adding some sanity to the otherwise brutal game. When it was over,
the Yankees' designated hitter, Chili Davis _ who had struck out to
end the contest _ showed pictures to reporters documenting how
Tschida had blown a strike call in the final at-bat, a strange end
to a strange game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't pretty from either side,'' Hargrove said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
