<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG 12 LOOKS FOR SOLUTION TO KANSAS STATE BOWL PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 12 MEETINGS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. _ There is no simple solution for the
``Kansas State Problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 Conference's spring meetings Wednesday focused on how
to avoid a repeat of last season's bowl problem. When Kansas State
lost in the Big 12 championship game, the Wildcats went from
playing for the national championship to free-falling to the Alamo
Bowl, fourth on the league's bowl pecking order.
</P>
<P>
   The conundrum: Conference championship games aren't played until
the first Saturday in December. Waiting until those games are
played to make bowl picks allows little time for travel plans and
selling tickets. Making deals ahead of the championship games
creates problems illustrated by the Kansas State situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a personal opinion, but I'd like to see some way that
we protect the runner-up or the loser of the championship game,''
Big 12 commissioner Kevin Weiberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tradeoff involved,'' said Nebraska's Bill Byrne,
chairman of the Big 12 athletic directors. ``We want to be flexible
for the bowls to allow them to sell tickets, but we need to and
want to honor the results of the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``And several athletic directors are concerned about going to a
bowl game where you're obligated to sell tickets but it's a game
your fans are not excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 hopes to come up with some potential solutions to
present to their bowl partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in their hands now,'' said Rick Baker, executive director
of the Cotton Bowl, which matches the first Big 12 team not
selected by the Bowl Championship Series against a Southeastern
Conference team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kicked around a lot of things, but it's back in their court
now,'' said John Reid, executive director of the Holiday Bowl. The
Holiday gets the third choice of Big 12 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Baker requested that if the Big 12 has any suggestions or
solutions, to put them in writing. The Cotton Bowl's officers are
meeting July 1 and Baker would like to be able to consider any Big
12 proposals then.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is for the Cotton Bowl to select its Big 12 team
based on the Bowl Championship Series ranking. Another is to add a
won-loss differential. For example, the Cotton Bowl couldn't select
an 8-3 team over a team with just won loss.
</P>
<P>
   However, either proposal would require changing the contract
between the Cotton and the Big 12. FOOTBALL SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 released conference football schedules for the 2000
through 2003 seasons. The schedules are subject to changes dictated
by television.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State professor Tim VanVoorhis wrote a computer program to
come up with the schedules. He was given parameters such as
Texas-Oklahoma in early October, Colorado-Nebraska and Texas-Texas
A&AMP;M at the end of the season, teams end seasons with one home and
one road game and teams play no more than two consecutive road
games.
</P>
<P>
   VanVoorhis came up with 400 possible schedules; assistant
commissioner Tim Allen narrowed those down to four for the athletic
directors to examine.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Oklahoma and Oklahoma State have been given permission to
move their annual ``Bedlam Game'' to Thanksgiving weekend. This
year, the Sooners and the Cowboys are scheduled to play Nov. 27. TV
GAMES
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 announced eight football games this year have been
selected for telecasts. The schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 4 _ Stanford at Texas and Nebraska at Iowa, 11 a.m. ABC
regional telecast; Alabama-Birmingham at Missouri, 2:30 p.m., Fox
Syndication; Colorado State-Colorado, time to be determined, Fox
Sports; Sept. 11 _ California at Nebraska, 2:30 p.m., ABC regional;
Tulsa at Oklahoma State, 11:30 a.m., Fox Syndication; Iowa at Iowa
State, 6 p.m., Fox Sports; Sept. 18 _ Kansas at Colorado, 2:30
p.m., ABC regional.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor at Oklahoma game Sept. 18 could be announced Thursday
as a Fox Syndication telecast. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
