<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS NIP METS, 8-7 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Franco knew he was not going to go the whole
season without blowing a save. It was the timing of his first one
on Wednesday night that shook both he and the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   One out away from a desperately needed victory, the Mets
suffered their most devastating defeat of the season on Wednesday
night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Franco came on in the ninth inning to protect a 7-6 lead but he
blew his first save in 15 chances when Mike Cameron hit
bases-loaded single to give the Cincinnati Reds a come-from-behind
8-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who have lost a season-high six consecutive games, now
travel to the Bronx on Friday to open a weekend series with the
Yankees after going oh-for their homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later it was going to happen,'' said a disconsolate
Franco, whose critics have long lambasted him for the critically
bad timing of his blown saves. ``I wish it would have been later
than today.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco was not the only one. He was one pitch away from a
victory that would have sent the Mets to Yankee Stadium, Friday
night, on a rare good note. But the 38-year-old left hander did not
record the third out of the ninth until it was way too late.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Mets, who dropped to 27-26, have lost 17 of 27 games
since running off a season-high six straight wins. With Wednesday
night's loss, the Mets dropped into third place in the National
League East, percentage points behind the Philadelphia Phillies.
The last time they were only one game over .500 was April 9.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Mets lost six consecutive games was early last
season. The last time they dropped six straight games at Shea
Stadium was 1994. The last time they were swept in two consecutive
three-game series was 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Most astonishing of all: The last _ and only _ time the Mets
were swept in two consecutive three-game series at home, as they
were over the last six days? Try Aug., 1962, at the Polo Grounds,
in the first season of the franchise's existence. Shea had not even
been built. The Mets lost 120 games that year.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, these Mets need a victory badly. As Manager Bobby
Valentine said when asked how much longer his team could wait
before they win again, ``I'd have liked it to happen yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Mets are staring at three games against the
defending World Champions after what Valentine described as a
much-needed day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it will kick start us a little bit,'' Franco said of
this weekend's series with the Yankees, in which the Mets will
decidedly be the underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there's going to be a jolt there and hopefully it
does us some good,'' said Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Both Franco and Ventura, along with Mike Piazza and Dennis Cook,
had spoken during a players' only team meeting after Tuesday's
loss.
</P>
<P>
   And, as if to do something to take his mind off the Mets'
current struggles, Franco had grabbed a garden shovel and a few
packets of vegetable seeds from his locker stall on Wednesday
afternoon and headed for the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing else to do out there lately,'' the erstwhile
gardener _ and full-time closer _ said, referring to the slide the
Mets took into Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Franco had his hands full at Shea Stadium a
few hours later, but not of earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had rallied from three runs down in the bottom of the
seventh for a 7-6 lead. And Franco was soon one out away from his
15th save.
</P>
<P>
   But he walked Greg Vaughn on a 3-1 pitch with two out and Barry
Larkin followed with a crucial infield single to move Vaughn to
second. The ball might have been an easy grounder for Ventura at
third had he not been playing on the line to prevent extra bases
with the tying run at first. Instead, Luis Lopez, the shortstop,
had to dive at the ball just to keep it from going into left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just made a lousy decision,'' Valentine said, attempting to
take some of the blame. After Franco fell behind Dmitri Young, 3-0,
the runners executed a double steal on a 3-1 pitch. Young the
walked on a full count to load the bases. And then, after falling
behind 0-2, Cameron _ who had entered the game 0 for his last 24 _
worked the count to 2-2 before lining a fastball that Franco left
over the plate up the middle for the game-winning single.
</P>
<P>
   As Larkin came around with the go-ahead run, a softball whizzed
by Franco, who was busy watching the two runs score. On a night
that the Mets had somehow bailed out Jason Isringhausen before
losing in stunning fashion, one unruly fan was apparently letting
the Mets know just how he felt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
