<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REST IN RUN TO GLORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ If it's Wednesday, this must be Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a hectic cycle of racing and travel that began even
before his Kentucky Derby and Preakness victories, Charismatic
stepped off a horse van at trainer outside D. Wayne Lukas' Belmont
Park barn late on a muggy morning.
</P>
<P>
   The van ride followed a flight delayed more than an hour by a
lightning storm in Louisville, Ky., the first thing that's slowed
him down all spring.
</P>
<P>
   As he arrived, 11 other 3-year-olds were being entered in
Saturday's Belmont Stakes, the large field a tangible sign that
Charismatic is not held in the awe of the 11 Triple Crown winners,
the group he's trying to join.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, Charismatic might not be a great thoroughbred, a
Citation or a Secretariat or an Affirmed. But in one important
respect, he is a horse the old-timers should appreciate, a
throwback to the sport's gilded age.
</P>
<P>
   In the 43 days that began with the April 3 Santa Anita Derby, he
has raced four times, taking no longer than 15 days between races.
To him the 21 days between the Preakness and Belmont must feel like
a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   For the six races from the March 6 El Camino Real Derby at Bay
Meadows in the San Francisco Bay Area to the Belmont, he will have
visited six racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   He has already raced nine times in 1999 _ more than the average
'90s Kentucky Derby winner raced in his entire 3-year-old season.
And whereas most modern racehorses would wilt, Charismatic has
appeared to thrive, improving from a Santa Anita Derby also-ran to
a potential immortal since his campaign heated up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what gives Charismatic a chance to complete the Triple
Crown that his overall ability wouldn't otherwise suggest,'' said
Steve Davidowitz, author of the handicapping textbook ``Betting
Thoroughbreds.''
</P>
<P>
   In decades past, horses routinely raced this often. Citation,
the 1948 Triple Crown winner, won the Jersey Stakes !ital!in
between!off! the Preakness and Belmont, which completed a string of
seven races in 52 days.
</P>
<P>
   But racing was different in those days: Tracks were powdery.
Competition was less evenly matched. Thoroughbreds were a hardier
lot, the breed not yet dragged down by widespread use of Lasix and
other medications, and by breeders' recent obsession with speed.
</P>
<P>
   And these days, stakes purses are high enough that top horses
don't have to race more than once a month to pay the owners' bills.
</P>
<P>
   But after late-blooming Charismatic ran fourth in the Santa
Anita Derby, he had to win the Lexington Stakes at Keeneland two
weeks later to earn a place in the Churchill Downs starting gate.
So began the every-two-weeks schedule, with hard workouts between
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's working, why back off?'' said Richard Mandella, one of
California's leading trainers.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic can stand it because he's a big, muscular horse. In
fact, without a heavy schedule, as Lukas found out, the colt plain
gets fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as wide as he is tall,'' said Elliott Walden (he was
exaggerating), who trains Belmont challenger Menifee. ``A
lighter-framed horse couldn't do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who has never been accused of babying his horses, said
the heavy seasoning and ``bounce-back ability'' is an advantage for
Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to win the Derby, at some point you have to test
them, hold their feet to the fire,'' Lukas said.
</P>
<P>
   But could Charismatic's strength prove his weakness Saturday?
What if the workload catches up with him during the 1{-mile
Belmont?
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point it's got to catch up with him. Whether that'll
be Saturday or not, I'm not prepared to say,'' Walden said.
``(These) horses are dealing with a lot of stress. We're all hoping
our horse has got one more good one in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Can a handicapper know before the race?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw him in the post parade for the Preakness, he looked
like an absolute bull,'' Davidowitz said. ``Unfortunately for those
who have to make predictions the day before the Belmont,
(Charismatic's physical condition) will probably be most apparent
in the post parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's got some bounce in his step, an arch in his neck,
beautiful color and rippling muscles, then he feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   And all that work might pay off in a Triple Crown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
