<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU SPRINT RELAY MISSES FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIPS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho _ A season of hope and disappointment ended because
of a hole in the ground.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's 4x100-meter relay team, which began the outdoor season
dreaming of setting records and fought through a series of injuries
to get to the NCAA Outdoor Track and Field Championships, was
stopped Wednesday by Jarmiene Holloway's sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, who ran the second leg for the Horned Frogs, severely
twisted his ankle just before the race, stepping in a divot in
Bronco Stadium's hammer-throw area, which is being used as a warmup
area during the NCAA meet. He ran in the 4x100 preliminary heat
anyway, but was noticeably slower, which also threw off the timing
of the Frogs' baton exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a shockingly slow time of 40.19 seconds, far off
TCU's season best of 38.64 and last among the nine teams that
finished the event's two heats. The top eight teams of the 12
entered qualified for Friday's final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went wrong,'' said a distraught Ricardo ``Flash''
Williams, who ran the anchor leg. ``Everything. I don't know what
to say. By the time I got the baton, I was too far back. I ran OK,
but I was just too far behind.''
</P>
<P>
   For Holloway, a senior, the injury not only cost him a chance to
defend the Frogs' 1998 national relay title _ he was a member of
the team that ran a collegiate record 38.04 at last year's NCAA
meet _ it may also cost him a shot at the 100-meter crown. TCU
coach Monte Stratton said Holloway, last year's NCAA runner-up in
that event, is doubtful for tonight's 100 meter preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad day,'' Holloway said. ``I'm going to get treatment
and rest and hope I can be ready for the 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway wasn't the only one who had a bad day in the relay.
Texas' Eric Frempong and Nathanael Esprit botched the final handoff
and wound up disqualified for running out of the exchange zone.
North Texas dropped the baton and was also disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' women, on the other hand, were their usual overpowering
selves in the 4x100, posting the day's fastest qualifying time of
42.90. In addition, the Longhorns got a huge break when archrival
Louisiana State, expected to challenge Texas for the women's team
title, was knocked out of the running by a dropped baton as leadoff
runner Joyce Bates tried to hand off to Chenelle Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it, but it just brushed past my hand,'' Marshall said.
``This really hurts, and we can't get it back, but we've got to
realize that we can still win this meet.''
</P>
<P>
   That thought was not lost on the Longhorns, who were not about
to break into backflips over LSU's misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't help them, but they've got a lot more people here
to score points for them,'' Texas' Nanceen Perry said. ``This
doesn't take them out of nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but Perry did her part for the Longhorns'
championship effort with a strong relay leg and a blazing 200
meters. The senior ran a school-record 22.55 to lead three Texas
runners into Friday's semifinals. Texas also qualified Tanya
Jarrett and Angel Patterson for the 400-meter hurdles final and Liz
Diaz for the 800 final.
</P>
<P>
   As Texas prepared for its usual assault in the running events,
SMU's women grabbed a share of the first-day lead with Florence
Ezeh's victory in the hammer throw. Her best mark of 207 feet, 2
inches in the early afternoon rain outdistanced the 206-5 of South
Carolina's Michelle Fournier. The 10 points tied SMU with Kansas
State and Pittsburgh for first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I wanted to be good, rather than just saying maybe I
can be good,'' said Ezeh, a sophomore who failed to make the final
at last year's NCAA meet. ``Now I say I want to be good, and that
has made me change.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford took the men's lead with a 1-2-3 finish in the 10,000
meters for 24 points ahead of Auburn with 13 and SMU with 10,
thanks mostly to Janus Robberts' second-place finish in the discus.
</P>
<P>
   With the relay team out and Holloway hobbling, TCU's hopes for a
high team finish are gone. The only healthy Frogs sprinter left
running is Bryan Howard, who moved on to the 200 semifinals on a
day in which temperatures in the 40s slowed the times considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Howard's 20.77 was second in his heat to local favorite Corey
Nelson of Boise State but beat that of his nemesis, defending NCAA
100 champion Leonard Myles-Mills of Brigham Young. Myles-Mills was
third in 20.93.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked over and said, `Man, not him again,' '' said Howard,
who was second to Myles-Mills in the 100 and 200 at the Western
Athletic Conference meet. ``It was nice to beat him, but he'll be
ready to roll when it counts.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
