<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY HURT AS DODGERS LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Losing the series to the Pittsburgh Pirates was bad
enough, but the Dodgers added an exclamation point by getting swept
in a three-game series for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   They lost 8-4 in lethargic fashion Wednesday at Three Rivers
Stadium to fall to 26-26 and end their one-time promising road trip
at 4-5. And they stagger into today's off-day trailing the Arizona
Diamondbacks by five games.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and it gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Todd Hundley will have his left wrist X-rayed today
after he injured it in a third-inning collision at home plate with
Ed Sprague. The initial diagnosis is a sprain that will keep
Hundley out of the lineup at least for the Anaheim series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it (broken the wrist) twice, and I'll know when I
wake up (today) what's going on,'' said Hundley, who left the game
after grounding out in the sixth. ``I didn't feel it pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was examined after the game by Pittsburgh Steelers team
physician Dr. Jim Bradley, who diagnosed it as a bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Still, excuse Hundley for his extreme concern. The pain is at
the base of his left thumb, on the outside of his hand. He said
it's the same place he broke it in 1992 and again in 1995 when he
and Dodgers second baseman Eric Young, then a member of the
Colorado Rockies, collided.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor said the symptoms are more of a bone bruise than a
broken bone, and I'm hopin' and prayin' he's right,'' Hundley said.
``When I grabbed the bat, I was sick. That's why I wanted to keep
in the game. This could be my last game of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hundley had trouble throwing out runners, and
despite hitting .228 and going 2 for 26 on the road trip, a
long-term injury would be jolting to the Dodgers. It means L.A.
will have rookie Angel Pena catching and Paul LoDuca, who's at
Triple-A Albuquerque, as the backup unless they search the trade
waters.
</P>
<P>
   In the best-case scenario, manager Davey Johnson said Hundley
would likely miss the Angels series and possibly the three games
against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While Hundley hasn't provided the production the Dodgers hoped
for, the switch-hitter has provided protection and a necessary
break in a righty-dominated lineup. And with Todd Hollandsworth
slated for the disabled list Friday, it leaves switch-hitting
center fielder Devon White as the only possible lefty bat among the
starters.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries bring to light just how barren the minor-league
system is, and how little it can help during these crucial times.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things (needed) is depth, and you knew that was
lacking going in,'' Johnson said. ``When a couple of guys go down,
it kind of exposes you. It's tough when you have guys on the bench
and it's a right-handed (hitter) against a right-handed (pitcher).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you rest somebody, you try to create matchups off the
bench. I'm not sure an all right-handed lineup can consistently
beat a right-handed pitcher. We got it, but Holly's hurt, (Jose)
Vizcaino's been hurt. Those are things we need to perk up a lineup.
Not a big thing, but we have to tighten it up until the guys get
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Hundley overshadowed the hurt the Pirates put on
the Dodgers. Darren Dreifort (5-4) yielded seven runs on nine hits
(two homers) while Pittsburgh's Todd Ritchie (5-3) allowed four
runs in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The three-game losing streak matches the Dodgers' longest of the
season. They haven't won three straight since winning five in a row
April 27 through May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time it looks like we're going to get over the hump, we
stumble,'' Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw said. ``You have to win three,
four, five in a row so when you stumble it doesn't look bad. It
will come. You have to trust that it will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
