<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     06-03 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PARIS _ Today, the circle is unbroken. Ten years after their first
meeting in a French Open semifinal, the two fading _ but fighting
still _ divas of women's tennis reprise a historic match that
should have launched an epic rivalry, perhaps even one the equal of
Navratilova vs. Evert.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi Graf, already ensconced at No. 1 after her Golden Slam
year of 1988, needed three sets to rid herself of the gawky,
grunting 15-year-old who had won her first professional title
barely a month earlier in Houston. Steffi was way ahead of Monica
Seles in terms of experience and sophistication, but you could see
Monica's potential straightaway. Those explosive, brutally
efficient, if stylishly deficient, two-fisted groundstrokes of hers
would not be denied for long by anybody, Graf included.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi saw it coming. She knew she had met, in Seles, an all too
worthy adversary.
</P>
<P>
   They would play nine more times through the 1993 Australian
Open, where Seles won in three sets to claim the title. Eight of
the matches would be finals, including two French Open wars that
went Seles' way _ the latter 10-8 in the third _ plus a Wimbledon
rout by Graf. Only on grass had Steffi kept Monica's number.
Overall, their head-to-head stood Graf 6, Seles 4. But Monica was
the new No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   And then she was stabbed, an insane and tragic event that
changed, and ruined, everything.
</P>
<P>
   A German maniac who worshipped Graf stuck a knife in Seles' back
in April '93, and Monica hasn't won much of anything that mattered
since. Hiding from the demons, she was totally off the tour for
almost 2{ years in the prime of her career, while Graf cleaned up.
Since Seles' return at the '95 U.S. Open, she has beaten Graf just
once in four tries, in the Australian Open quarters last January.
</P>
<P>
   Of Steffi's 21 Grand Slam titles, six were claimed during
Monica's exile, as was a significant chunk of her record $21
million in earnings. Seles' corresponding numbers are nine majors
won and $11.2 million banked. Overall, the series stands Graf 9,
Seles 5. By comparison, Evert and Navratilova faced off on more
than 70 mostly memorable occasions.
</P>
<P>
   And consider this oddity: Today's pairing is the first to pit
Steffi and Monica in any semi since that first one here.
</P>
<P>
   Had the normal course of events not been criminally altered,
however, the parity between the two women's records might be
striking. Who can say? It's a pity, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   A greater shame might be how, unlike Chrissie and Martina, Graf
and Seles have never bonded despite the many ties that should bind
them. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hard one for me to answer, just too hard,'' Monica
has said. ``Steffi and I shared one emotional moment when she came
to the hospital to see me after I was stabbed, but that's been it.
There has been no communication between the two of us. We have no
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   For that, Graf probably deserves most of the blame. She has
always been a loner. Just as she snubs the next generation's
phenoms now, she paid little heed to Evert, Navratilova and Billie
Jean King before her. They believe Graf's aloofness, fostered by an
overbearing father who taught Steffi to see the whole world as an
adversary, actually did damage to the game during her decade-long
reign.
</P>
<P>
   Seles, although a tad ditzy, was a charming woman-child before
the stabbing, as gregarious with fans and sponsors as Graf was
remote. Monica would have been the superior leading-light
ambassador by far.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps, in a final accounting, the better player. We'll
never know, because the likely few matches of import left between
them won't answer any questions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Graf, at 29, is as strong and healthy as she has been
since recovering from the reconstructive surgery on her knee that
cost her a year of competition, she's hardly the Steamroller Steffi
we remember. She doesn't have a tournament title yet in '99 and
admits to succumbing to a bad case of the shakes in the defeat by
Seles in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely lost concentration,'' she said. ``I was extremely
nervous, and I didn't have an explanation for it. Rarely has
anything like that happened to me.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Seles, despite a current 11-match winning streak, she has
surrendered much of her bite as well. Their day is about done.
Either would be a decided underdog against No. 1-ranked Martina
Hingis, assuming she beats Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, in the Saturday
final.
</P>
<P>
   While this French hurrah may not be their last, it's close. The
resurgent teen terror Hingis has already eclipsed both Graf and
Seles, while the other kids, led by the Williams sisters, are
closing fast.
</P>
<P>
   Observes Hingis, speaking with the intemperance of youth but
truthfully nonetheless: ``Steffi has had some results in the past,
but it's a faster, more athletic game now than when she was (on
top). Her time has passed.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica's time, regrettably, never fully came. It should have,
but it didn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
