<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN MAKES THE TWINS PAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ It was either the ultimate show of respect for Garret
Anderson or just plain stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the decision by Minnesota Twins pitcher Brad Radke
to pitch to Mo Vaughn with first base open and the potential
winning run on third base in the eighth inning was the difference
as the Angels beat the Twins 2-1 on Wednesday night in front of
17,766 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Radke and Angels starter Chuck Finley had been locked in a 1-1
game going into the eighth, and it was Radke who gave in. Darin
Erstad doubled to lead off the eighth, then went to third on Randy
Velarde's sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Vaughn, who was 0 for 3 against Radke in the
game but entered the contest with a .414 lifetime average against
him. Instead of walking Vaughn intentionally and pitching to
Anderson, who had homered earlier in the game, Radke went after
Vaughn and paid for it. He singled past a diving second baseman
Brent Gates, who was playing in on the infield grass, scoring
Erstad for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Finley gave way to closer Troy Percival to start the ninth, and
Percival earned his 15th save. Finley (4-5) gave up one run and
five hits in eight innings. He struck out five, giving him 2,016 in
his career to move into 49th place on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Finley began the game by retiring the first eight batters he
faced. Doug Mientkiewicz broke the string with a two-out single in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, it wasn't unlike Finley's previous start last
Friday, when he struck out seven consecutive Royals during one
stretch only to see the game blow up in his face. Finley was out of
that game in the fifth after giving up eight runs and seven hits in
four-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to say (why that happened),'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``You go back and watch the film and say `Gosh, all
of a sudden...' Normally, Chuck is one of those guys that when he
has trouble he has the knack to get out of it. Well, not a knack.
He !ital!knows &UR; !off! &LR;  how to get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, though, didn't fall apart Wednesday. He didn't allow a
Twins baserunner to get into scoring position until there were two
out in the fifth. That's when Chad Allen singled, then scored on a
double by Mientkiewicz for a 1-0 Twins lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Radke (4-5) was tough on Angels hitters, which is
nothing new. He went into the game with a record of 7-1 and a 1.57
ERA against Anaheim in his career. He was 3-0 with a 1.65 ERA last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The only Angel to get a hit off Radke in the first 32/3 innings
was Erstad, who had two _ a ground-ball single to right in the
first and a line-drive single to left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Decker, starting at first base for the fourth time this
season, singled to right with two out in the fourth, then went to
third on a double to right by Troy Glaus. Decker and Glaus were
stranded when Matt Walbeck grounded to second to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels finally got on the scoreboard in the sixth on
Anderson's homer, his 12th of the season, on a 3-1 pitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
