<HEADLINE>
U.S., CANADA REACH AGREEMENT ON FAR-REACHING SALMON TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A sweeping U.S.-Canadian agreement for management and
conservation of West Coast salmon runs will be unveiled Thursday,
sources in both countries confirmed Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress votes the money to support it, the accord would end
a prolonged and at times confrontational dispute over fish that
return from the north Pacific to spawn in rivers of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year agreement is to be announced in Vancouver by
Canadian Fisheries Minister David Anderson and in Seattle by Gov.
Gary Locke. Locke reportedly will be accompanied by former White
House Counsel Lloyd Cutler, named last month by President Clinton
to oversee negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really good news for the salmon,'' Sen. Patty Murray,
D-Wash., said late Wednesday. ``It will be a very long-term
agreement, which is great since we won't have to go back through
all this again.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord is particularly good news for imperiled Puget Sound
and Columbia River salmon runs. The accord reportedly requires
further deep cutbacks in Canadians' catch of U.S.-bound chinook
salmon off the west coast of Vancouver Island and in the Strait of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators, including Locke, were still working on final
details Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and the White House have put substantial political
capital on the line to solve the prolonged cross-border salmon war.
Locke, who keeps count, has been involved in 31 salmon meetings
since last November.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared clear, from details available Wednesday night, that
Congress will have to appropriate a large amount of money to make
the accord work.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government would need to spend upwards of $25
million to buy out commercial licenses of non-Indian U.S.
fishermen. About $2 million of state money also would be required.
Canada's contribution is to be announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would establish two $75 million salmon enhancement
funds, one in the north and one in the south, reportedly under
U.S.-Canadian administration.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be available to help fish runs in such places as
the Skeena River of northern British Columbia _ where Canadians
have blamed fishing in Alaska waters for declining salmon
populations _ as well as restoring depleted fish stocks of rivers
in the Puget Sound-Georgia Strait region.
</P>
<P>
   While lasting a decade for most of the coast, the accord will
reportedly be in effect for 12 years on the Fraser River. The
Canadian river, which flows into the Strait of Georgia just north
of the U.S.-Canada border, is a crucial resource to Washington and
British Columbia fishermen as well as native fisheries in both
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The undammed Fraser River is the world's greatest sockeye salmon
stream. Allocation of the river's sockeye runs has been a point of
contention for years. Although bound for a Canadian stream, Fraser
River sockeye swim through U.S. waters in Alaska at the start of
their southward migration, and the Strait of Juan de Fuca and San
Juan Islands before entering the river.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reportedly contains a formula for allocating the
abundant Fraser River sockeye, along with the promise of resources
to restore other salmon species in the river that have experienced
severe declines.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, the salmon dispute has rocked the
world's longest peaceful border. Canadians have resorted to
unaccustomed militancy in pressing their claim that the United
States takes too many fish bound for British Columbia rivers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Canada's then-fisheries minister Brian Tobin slapped a
$1,100 ``licensing fee'' on U.S. fishing boats using Canadian
waters of the Inside Passage en route to Alaska. The Canadian coast
guard detained several boats that refused to pay.
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia Premier Glen Clark proposed in 1996 that U.S.
Navy vessels be barred from using an important torpedo testing
range on Vancouver Island. The Canadian federal government _ far
more conciliatory to the United States _ eventually moved to
expropriate the bay from provincial ownership.
</P>
<P>
   A major confrontation came in 1997. Angry at the catching of
Canada-bound chinook and sockeye salmon off Noyes Island in Alaska,
fishing boats prevented the Alaska ferry ``Malaspina'' from leaving
Prince Rupert, B.C., for four days.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon war took a turn toward peace last summer, however,
even as formal talks between the two countries were at an impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed at the decline of coho salmon runs in its own rivers,
Canada moved unilaterally to curtail the sport and commercial catch
of millions of coho salmon off Vancouver Island and the Queen
Charlotte Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian curtailments had major benefits south of the
border, increasing the numbers of coho and chinook salmon reaching
such Puget Sound streams as the Nooksack, Skagit and Stiliguamish
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Locke returned the favor. State officials cut back Americans'
catch of coho salmon bound for the Thompson River in British
Columbia, as well as the early sockeye salmon run beginning its
900-mile migration up the Fraser River to remote Stuart Lake in
central British Columbia. It turned out that the Fraser River was
experiencing record water temperatures and high salmon mortality.
The U.S. action was vital to the survival of the so-called early
Stuart run.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Locke formed a mutual admiration society as a
result of last year's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confrontation made everybody poorer. Our constituencies are
tired of arguments over who would kill the last fish,'' the
Canadian fisheries minister told a recent Seattle luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Locke, faced with a listings of salmon under the Endangered
Species Act, has looked for Canadians' help in assuring that
Washington-bound fish are not caught while in the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long-term U.S.-Canada agreement would focus on recovery of
salmon in all of our rivers,'' Locke told the same luncheon. ``We
have a shared regional identity.''
</P>
<P>
   While cross-border relations improved, Canadians have fought
furiously among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The British Columbia government has accused its federal
government of making far too many concessions to the United States,
and not trying hard enough to halt interceptions of Canada-bound
salmon in Alaska waters.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Anderson has cut Premier Clark out of Canada-U.S.
negotiations and decried the premier's outspoken nationalism as an
impediment to a salmon accord.
</P>
<P>
   More than 13,000 people have left the B.C. fishing industry in
recent years. With canneries closing along B.C.'s north coast, the
province has begun studying once-unthinkable alternatives like
drilling for oil in Hecate Strait between the Queen Charlotte
Islands and the B.C. coast.
</P>
