<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DRAMATICS AS TIGERS STOP RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TIGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It has come down to a matter of perception. Some people
will look at one game and see things that should have been done,
could have been done, and brood about it.
</P>
<P>
   Others will look at a bigger picture. Twenty wins in the last 26
games, a five-game winning streak that included good pitching,
timely hitting, late-inning rallies, all of the things needed to
put a team in first place.
</P>
<P>
   They will, as Red Sox first baseman Mike Stanley and several of
his teammates did Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, see a season broken down into a
series of three- and four-game challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the series and we move on,'' said Stanley, who had
three hits Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, not dismissing a 4-2 loss to the
Tigers at Fenway Park as meaningless, but not placing too much
importance on his team's first defeat in a week. ``You try and win
series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox did that, beating the Tigers the first two games of
the three-game set before lefthander Justin Thompson, who has
beaten the Sox twice this season, fired his assortment of darts and
heat over eight-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who beat the Red Sox in Detroit in April, needed his
best stuff to outpitch Tim Wakefield, who turned in one of his
stronger efforts of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got beat,'' said Wakefield, who is 3-5 but has had two
strong efforts in his last three starts. ``It was a matter of
getting to him early. And we couldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike much of the last month, when the Red Sox went on a
remarkable 20-5 burst, and the last week, when they swept the
Indians in Cleveland and came from behind in wins over the Tigers
on Monday and Tuesday, the Red Sox had no magic formula
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, much to the disappointment of the Fenway faithful
of 27,280.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson limited the Red Sox to four hits through the first
eight innings before a Nomar Garciaparra infield hit and a 409-foot
blast by Stanley (his sixth home run of the season) over the screen
above the left-field wall brought about thoughts of another Red Sox
rally.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the previous two games, when Detroit manager Larry
Parrish's call to the bullpen brought only hits, home runs, and
defeat, Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night a Tiger reliever responded.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Jones came in to finish things without any more damage and
the Red Sox had to be content to win two of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're doing is playing the schedule,'' said Williams,
whose team will play an exhibition game in Pawtucket Thursday night
before entertaining the Atlanta Braves in a three-game set
beginning Friday night with a Pedro Martinez-Tom Glavine matchup
that will have people talking about baseball in October. ``We won a
series against a tough club.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that tough, but tough enough. The Tigers built their lead
against Wakefield slowly.
</P>
<P>
   They managed a run in the third on a pair of singles, one going
just past the pitcher's mound. Detroit added two more in the fourth
and that was all Thompson needed to get his fifth win in 11
decisions and end a personal four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Red Sox, it also wasted a pretty good
effort by Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw some good pitches out there tonight,'' said Williams.
``He had a good knuckleball. He was on the plate, getting a lot of
hitters out.''
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a semi-day of rest, then another of those ``series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the series and that makes it a little easier,'' said
Wakefield. ``Things didn't work out tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The other side of the picture is that first place still is
theirs and they are still one of the hottest teams in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good baseball,'' said Garciaparra, making it
sound so simple.
</P>
<P>
   So they are. Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night just wasn't quite good enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
