<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-TIGERS-THOMPSON-B     06-03 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TIGERS-THOMPSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON'S WIN JUST IN TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He beat them last year. He has already beaten them
twice this year. Ask who is the toughest pitcher in the American
League and the Red Sox might very well mention Tigers lefthander
Justin Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that Thompson was in the middle of a horrible stretch
going into the third and final game of Detroit's series at Fenway
Park Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that in his last five starts, he had four losses, a
no-decision, and had allowed 20 earned runs in 25 innings.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to facing the Red Sox, Thompson looks like
Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's effort was the latest evidence. In working
eight-plus innings and allowing six hits in a 4-2 win, Thompson
needed only 87 pitches. The only Sox hitter to solve Thompson was
Mike Stanley, who had three hits, including a two-run homer in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is 2-0 against Boston this season, with an earned run
average of 1.13. For his career, he is 4-1 with a 2.75 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps you off balance,'' said Stanley. ``He's got a great
changeup. He hides his pitches well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good fastball, big changeup to righthanded batters, not afraid
to throw the breaking ball to righthanded batters either,'' said
third baseman John Valentin. ``The kid's got talent.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost a month, not many people on the Tigers saw it. After
opening the season with a pair of losses and horrible efforts
against the Rangers and Yankees, Thompson came back to pitch seven
strong innings in a win over the Yankees April 16.
</P>
<P>
   Then came eight shutout innings against the Sox in a 1-0 win
April 22, and two more wins.
</P>
<P>
   But just like that, it all went south on Thompson. He had five
starts, no wins, four losses, one no-decision, and a whole lot of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night may have turned things back the other way for
Thompson, who was looking for his first career shutout and the
first complete game by the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   But then Nomar Garciaparra had a sharp infield single to start
the ninth and Stanley hit a pitch over the screen above the
left-field wall, and Thompson was done for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully for the Tigers, Todd Jones finished off the
proceedings, making Thompson a winner and leaving the Red Sox to
wonder what they needed to do to beat him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
