SLEEPWALK _ Three weeks before he fatally stabbed his wife, Scott
Falater was heard discussing a similar case in which a Canadian man
who also claimed to be sleepwalking was acquitted of killing his
mother-in-law, the prosecutor said Wednesday. S tory will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-AZR &LR;      06-03 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALKING DEFENDANT REPORTEDLY DISCUSSED SIMILAR CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three weeks before he fatally stabbed his wife, Scott Falater
was heard discussing a similar case in which a Canadian man who
also claimed to be sleepwalking was acquitted of killing his
mother-in-law, the prosecutor said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in open court after the jury was excused for the day,
prosecutor Juan Martinez outlined that new lead and two others to
support his charge that Falater deliberately stabbed Yarmila
Falater 44 times and held her head underwater in the family's pool.
</P>
<P>
   One lead, Martinez said, is a new witness prepared to testify
that she told Yarmila that her husband had been unfaithful.
</P>
<P>
   In another lead, Martinez said that Randy Keadle _ who testified
last week for the defense that Falater ``was a very peaceful man''
_ has since reported that Falater ``may have dragged his daughter
upstairs by the hair'' after a minor infraction of household rules.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said Keadle also provided information about a Motorola
employee who heard Falater, a Motorola engineer at the time of the
1997 attack, discuss the Canadian sleepwalking case.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion took place a few weeks before Falater killed his
wife with a hunting knife and stored the weapon and his
blood-spattered clothing in the back of his car. He says he was
sleepwalking at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The potentially explosive new information prompted a protest
from defense attorney Michael Kimerer, who said the claims had
arrived ``a little late in the game'' and too abruptly for him to
evaluate their significance.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Martinez would be allowed to present the
new information. Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Ronald S.
Reinstein ordered attorneys to meet Wednesday night to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   In another surprising announcement, Martinez said a new witness
has reported that a few months before her death, Yarmila Falater
talked about developing a venereal disease in 1990. The witness, a
nurse practitioner and former neighbor, will testify that she told
Yarmila that her husband had been ``messing around,'' Martinez
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the information supports his motion that Reinstein
reverse a pre-trial decision that information from 1990 about the
disease was too old to be relevant to a trial on a 1997 killing.
</P>
<P>
   If presented to the jury, the information could damage the
defense claim that the Falater home was a model of domestic
tranquility, that the couple never quarreled and were still deeply
in love after 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past week, the defense has called more than a dozen
witnesses who have testified glowingly about Falater's personal
life as a family man and local leader of the Mormon Church.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most important defense witnesses were the two teenage
Falater children, who last week described their father as an
unfailingly kind man whose temper never got out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The key defense witness Wednesday was Falater's mother, Lois
Wilcek, who described several instances when her son had walked in
his sleep as a boy and young man.
</P>
<P>
   That testimony is key, Kimerer says, because sleepwalking adults
almost always have a childhood history of sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   Wilcek also contradicted the testimony of a key prosecution
witness, who had watched from his yard as Falater dragged his wife
to the pool after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The witness, Greg Koons, had denied telling Kimerer and Wilcek
shortly afterward that Falater's movements had been ``robotic.''
Wilcek remembered the conversation differently.
</P>
<P>
   Koons had said that Falater ``was very deliberate, had no
expression on his face at all, and his movements were not rushed;
they were slow and mechanical,'' Wilcek said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody said, `You mean like a robot?' And he said, `Yes,
like a robot.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, two of Falater's former colleagues at
Motorola cried as they spoke glowingly of the engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was _ is _ one of the best people I know,''
Gordon Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Ingram said she had been stunned to learn in 1997 that
Falater had been charged in his wife's death. ``It was totally
inconsistent with his character and with him as a person, with him
as a priesthood-holding member of the Mormon Church,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But another former Motorola colleague surprised the courtroom
with his recollection that Falater had called his wife ``either
dumpy or overweight.'' But Chester Gordon quickly agreed with
defense attorney Lori Voepel who suggested that Falater had made
the remark ``in a loving way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
