<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1091 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     06-03 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ It was either the ultimate show of respect for Garret
Anderson or just plain stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the decision by Minnesota Twins pitcher Brad Radke
to pitch to Mo Vaughn with first base open and the potential
winning run on third base in the eighth inning was the difference
as the Angels beat the Twins 2-1 on Wednesday night in front of
17,766 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Radke and Angels starter Chuck Finley had been locked in a 1-1
game going into the eighth, and it was Radke who gave in. Darin
Erstad doubled to lead off the inning, then went to third on Randy
Velarde's sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Vaughn, who at that point was 0 for 3 against
Radke in the game but entered the contest with a .414 lifetime
average against him. Instead of walking Vaughn intentionally and
pitching to Anderson, who had homered earlier in the game, Radke
went after Vaughn and paid for it. Vaughn singled past a diving
second baseman Brent Gates, who was playing in on the infield
grass, scoring Erstad for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know T.K. (Twins manager Tom Kelly) and we've faced each
other before in that situation,'' Vaughn said. ``He kind of lets me
play the game. I told their first baseman I appreciate that,
because a lot of guys wouldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins wouldn't say whether or not he
would have pitched to Vaughn. He said he won't second-guess an
opposing manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad we had (Vaughn) up there and he came through,''
Collins said. ``The key was Erstad. He's swinging great now and he
got on.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad appeared to have hit a home run to lead off the eighth,
but second-base umpire Gary Cederstrom correctly ruled that a fan
reached below the top of the fence to catch the ball. Erstad had to
stay at second with a ground-rule double.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a triple,'' Collins said. ``Darin's running hard all
the way. They (fans) don't understand. I'll give them a dozen
baseballs if they'd leave that one alone.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out it didn't matter. Erstad scored the winning run
anyway and made a winner out of Finley (4-5). Finley gave way to
closer Troy Percival to start the ninth, and Percival earned his
15th save.
</P>
<P>
   Finley (4-5) gave up one run and five hits in eight innings. He
struck out five, giving him 2,016 in his career and moving him into
49th place on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those pitching performances that didn't go to
waste,'' Collins said. ``We just don't seem to score him a lot of
runs. But Chuck Finley's style is to pitch and pitch well.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley said he's used to pitching in low-scoring games. Often he
faces the other team's ace, and Radke was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake and gave them a run, and he made a mistake
and gave us a run,'' Finley said. ``I was just hoping he had one
more in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I take the mound, I expect to be pitching in a 2-1 game,
a 3-2 game, a 1-0 game. That's just the way I approach it. I don't
start crying if the offense doesn't get me three or four runs in
the first couple of innings. If you go out there trying not to get
hit because the offense isn't scoring, you're going to get
whacked.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins scored their only run of the game in the fifth on an
RBI double by Doug Mientkiewicz, and the Angels got the run back on
Anderson's solo homer in the sixth, his 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad had a big game with three hits, his first three-hit game
since April 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
