<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 03:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1107 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUNAR-PROSPECTOR-SFCH     06-03 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUNAR-PROSPECTOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUNAR PROSPECTOR ON SUICIDE MISSION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  The bargain-basement spacecraft that found tantalizing signs of
water on the moon will die in a final effort to confirm the
discovery, NASA scientists announced Wednesday.
<P>
   The odds are 10 to 1 against success for its death plunge into
the sunless depths of a lunar crater, but because the Lunar
Prospector's mission is over anyway, the scientists have decided to
make the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, the 354-pound spacecraft caused a worldwide
sensation when its on-board sensor signalled back to Earth that it
was detecting large amounts of hydrogen in the deepest, darkest
bottoms of steep-walled craters in the terrain around both lunar
poles.
</P>
<P>
   The hydrogen was a strong indication that frozen water lies in
the permanently shadowed craters, according to Alan Binder, the
mission's chief scientist. And when the spacecraft was commanded to
descend from an orbit of 65 miles to six miles above the moon's
surface, the sensor gathered even more intriguing hints of water.
Scientists estimated that the darkest craters at both poles might
contain a total of at least 800 billion gallons of water.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement about the possibility of ice arose because of the
likelihood that water might eventually provide both rocket fuel and
oxygen to support human scientific colonies on the lunar surface.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Guenter Riegler of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration's Office of Space Science said that on July 31,
ground controllers will try commanding the spacecraft to end its
18-month orbital flight and dive directly into a crater named
Mawson, located at the moon's south pole.
</P>
<P>
   The crater's steep, high rim means its base has remained in
permanent shadow ever since a wandering meteorite gouged it out
billions of years ago. Because Mawson is only 31 to 38 miles
across, it will be a highly difficult target to hit, Riegler said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the spacecraft does reach the target, its impact energy
will be the equivalent of crashing a two-ton car at more than 1,000
mph, according to a NASA announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists hope that the impact will churn some 40 pounds of
water vapor up from the lunar surface _ an extremely thin cloud
that might be detectable by instruments on Earth or aboard other
spacecraft. Astronomers at the University of Texas in Austin have
been allocated time to use the Hubble Space Telescope in an effort
to observe the impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the probability of success for such a bold undertaking
is low, the potential science payoff is tremendous,'' Riegler said.
``It seems fitting to give Lunar Prospector the chance to provide
scientific data right up to the very end of its highly successful
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Launched on January 6 last year, the spacecraft was one of the
new series of ``faster, better, cheaper'' missions ordered by NASA
administrator Daniel Golin; where other spacecraft have cost in the
billions, Lunar Prospector cost only $63 million _ one of the
cheapest space ventures on record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 03:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIANANMEN-ANNIVERSARY     06-03 2331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIANANMEN-ANNIVERSARY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROTEST THAT TRANSFORMED CHINA'S IDENTITY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By APRIL LYNCH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  BEIJING _ Friday, the 10th anniversary of the Tiananmen
crackdown will probably pass without much public fanfare in this
city that saw so much heartfelt protest, political upheaval and,
ultimately, brutal bloodshed in the spring of 1989.
<P>
   Tiananmen Square itself has been walled off with metal
construction fences, ostensibly in the name of renovation. Police
have rounded up dissidents in an attempt to thwart any public
commemorations. Many Chinese people, still appalled by the NATO
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, are suddenly loath to
criticize their government in front of outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   But public silence should not be mistaken for acquiescence, or
despair. The legacy of Tiananmen and June 4 has fundamentally
changed contemporary China and resonates throughout the country
even during an anniversary marked by enforced quiet. Tomorrow,
according to many Beijing residents, millions of private memories
will pay tribute to a movement that continues to shape the People's
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell those June 4 exiles living overseas that we remember what
they did,'' said a student surnamed Xu, a 24-year-old business
major at one of Beijing's most prestigious universities. ``They
made some mistakes, and we may not agree with everything they
wanted. But many of the reforms they struggled for, we now breathe
in every day, like air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Liu Si'' (June 4) lives on as a catalyst for change in China,
even within the government that tried to squelch it. The 1989
protests forced rapid reforms in the country's economy and its
systems of social control. The one major demand rejected by the
Communist Party _ greater political pluralism _ is slowly evolving
despite the party's recent harsh efforts to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The protests also changed the thinking of many ordinary
citizens. Police and social observers have tallied frequent
demonstrations around China in recent years, often centered around
economic inequality or government indifference. The Tiananmen-era
realization that people could form powerful groups outside official
channels has led to the widespread growth of associations that,
even if they are mostly apolitical, subtly loosen the party's grip
on society.
</P>
<P>
   Such quiet, incremental signs of success stands &LR;  in contrast to
the days that immediately followed June 4, when Beijing felt like
an occupied city. Almost two months of largely peaceful student and
popular protests calling for widespread reforms in Chinese politics
and society were crushed by tanks and troops acting on government
orders to stop the demonstrations at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   The weeks before the crackdown had a heady, carnival-like feel
in the normally serious capital, and the protests that began on
April 15 eventually spread to more than 75 cities across China. On
some days, more than a million people took to the streets in
Beijing. Contingents from doctrinaire government agencies joined in
the marches, waving banners calling for change. Students camping in
Tiananmen Square put up the now-famous ``Goddess of Democracy''
statue, its rickety, white plaster effigy staring down the giant
portrait of Chairman Mao that hangs over the gate to the Forbidden
City.
</P>
<P>
   When the crackdown began over the night of June 3 and the
following morning, many workers and other residents who tried to
stop the troops in the streets leading to Tiananmen Square paid
with their lives. A few soldiers died as well. The government puts
the official death toll at about 230, while dissident groups put
the number in the thousands. Afterwards &LR; , thousands of organizers
and participants were arrested, and key leaders of the protests
were forced into exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world needs to know what happened here, how they have
treated us like animals,'' a middle-aged man in a torn white work
shirt and plastic sandals gasped to this reporter as he stopped for
breath near a pile of crushed bicycles after running from army
gunfire the morning of June 4. ``Everything is finished.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't. On the government side, the same Communist Party
that declared martial law and turned the People's Liberation Army
on the people quickly realized that the deep discontent reflected
in the protests could not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps this bad thing will enable us to go ahead with reform
and the open policy at a steadier and better _ even a faster _
pace,'' former party boss Deng Xiaoping said in a speech five days
after the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the turmoil of that time, Deng's words were dismissed by many
as cynical platitudes.
</P>
<P>
   But the party put them into action. The government began
launched &LR; a campaign of economic, legal, social and educational
reforms that _ with the notable exception of greater democracy and
political pluralism _ directly reflected many of the demands that
echoed through the streets of Beijing in the spring of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Economic reforms have fattened the wallets and brightened the
financial prospects of many urban students, professionals and
workers, although many in China's remote rural areas have yet to
share in the wave of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The government also decided to loosen up on people's personal
lives, letting recent graduates choose their own jobs, giving
people more say in choosing their own housing and eliminating the
need to get government approval before marriage. More than 10,000
villages, at the party's urging, have experimented with electing
their own officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tiananmen generation had less to hope for,'' said Hu Yang,
a 26-year-old computer science major at Beijing University. ``We
have a lot of choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Other reforms that sprang from the streets in 1989 _ stamping
out official corruption and creating a fair, independent legal
system _ have been slower to kick in, despite party efforts to push
them through. The government has put thousands of officials _
including Beijing's mayor _ on trial for corruption in the 1990s,
sentencing some to death. But many in Beijing still complain that
personal connections, favors and bribery remain the most effective
way to get anything done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before 1989, it was the people with the good party connections
who got their way,'' said a 31-year-old software engineer surnamed
Jiang, who complains of being thwarted by bureaucrats in his
attempts to get the permits to start his own company. ``Now, it is
the people with a big stock portfolio. That may be change, but it's
not the kind we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is often true of the legal system, where an independent
judiciary and the rule of law are still far off.
</P>
<P>
   Many judges are still political appointees, often chosen more
for their ability to follow orders than to interpret legal codes.
Party whims often override the law books, and corruption is
prevalent. In Beijing's legal circles, it remains a bleak joke that
one of the most useful courses that law schools could offer would
be titled ``How to Invite the Judge Out to Dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Party officials also stepped up nationalist propaganda and
rhetoric after Tiananmen, drumming achievements from Chinese
history and stories of party glory into the heads of the young.
Earlier in the '80s, the government under Deng had emphasized
reform over doctrine. Such ``lapses in theoretical work,'' Deng
said in his June 9, 1989, speech, were the party's ``worst omission
of the past 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a decade of increased political indoctrination,
students in Beijing are more critical of the West than their
predecessors were in 1989. At the same time, however, they are even
more Westernized, eager to join foreign companies, study overseas
or swap their proletariat ``Flying Pigeon'' bicycles for a mountain
bike or a Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   That split personality was reflected in the recent attacks on
U.S. diplomatic posts that followed the embassy bombing in
Belgrade, as young crowds dressed in knock-off Nike gear blasted
embassy and consular buildings with rocks and paint bombs. Some
sincerely echoed the party line that the bombing was a deliberate
act of aggression. Others were more questioning of official views,
but that did not dampen their rage over perceived U.S. carelessness
and callousness about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many in Beijing said, such skepticism of the West should
not be confused with a return to the days of Mao's Red Guards.
Today's young people, hungry for their own information, turn to
mobile phones, satellite TV, radio talk shows, pagers and the
Internet. Like their older brothers and sisters from the Tiananmen
generation, they often find ways around party censorship of the
media.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Cultural Synthesis
</P>
<P>
   And, like young people everywhere, they often struggle to find
coherent meaning in the growing flood of information. As a result,
many are most comfortable with influences that blend China and the
West. Pop culture trends from consumer-happy Hong Kong and
politically democratic Taiwan once considered subversive are
quickly embraced _ and often have more resonance than their Western
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``American music is pretty cool, but Taiwan music is really
cool,'' said an 18-year-old guitar player who goes by his English
name of Jimmy, chosen in honor of Jimi Hendrix. ``Taiwan music is
in Chinese, and it is so moody, all about yourself and your hopes
and what you want. Those are new thoughts for a lot of kids as they
grow up, and they really like it.''
</P>
<P>
   That growing obsession with self is just one reflection of
Tiananmen's other major impact _ a gradual change in the way people
think.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 protests reflected and coalesced what had been a
growing dissatisfaction with forced collective thought in China.
Even after the crackdown, and despite some periods of heavy-handed
repression, the party has been unable to stamp out people's desire
to think for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   At a popular level, at least in Beijing and other big Chinese
cities, the Tiananmen mass movement brought home the power of an
individual decision of conscience. While the effect in China's vast
countryside is harder to gauge, many urban residents who joined the
protests learned that they could get the government's attention,
form groups outside party-sanctioned channels _ and quickly get in
trouble if they didn't keep things well-organized and low-key.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been an upsurge in public groups of all kinds,
from spiritual orders such as Falun Gong to the small but
well-organized China Democracy Party, which is quietly pushing for
official acceptance. While many of the nonpolitical groups have no
intention of directly challenging the Communists, their very
existence and large memberships subtly weaken the party's grip on
society.
</P>
<P>
   Most such groups, whether political or not, have also learned to
bolster their emotional appeal with strong organization and a
quiet, orderly way of challenging the party. The powerful
sentiments and hopes of the Tiananmen protests, some said, will
never be realized until there are foundations built under them.
</P>
<P>
   These groups are trying to avoid the fate that continues to
befall outspoken dissidents in China. Leaders of the China
Democracy Party were recently given jail terms of up to 13 years,
and Tiananmen activists have either been rounded up or put under
house arrest in advance of the anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   When government officials made moves to clamp down on Falun Gong
and its millions of followers this spring, the group sent more than
10,000 members _ mostly middle-aged women _ to sit quietly around
Communist Party headquarters in protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very smart,'' said one Beijing woman who is not a
Falun Gong follower but lives in a neighborhood where the group is
popular. ``They gave the government a big headache. How do you stop
a bunch of quiet women who look like everyone's mother?''
</P>
<P>
   The China Democracy Party, rather than marching through the
streets, has also taken a path of quiet resistance that has proved
hard for the government to quash. Although the authorities rebuffed
the party's attempts to become officially registered and jailed its
top leaders, the party continues to hold low-profile networking
meetings and develop its already strong organizational base.
</P>
<P>
   Many thoughtful Chinese see this more systematic kind of dissent
as a sign that post-Mao China is growing up.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Tiananmen protesters were fundamentally more
interested in reform than revolution. Now, they focus on building
the social awareness and structures needed for real reform _ often
one person, work unit or neighborhood at a time. In such a vast
country, that will take time.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of the chaos that could erupt if the party suddenly
collapsed, many have chosen to be grudgingly patient with the
gradual pace of change. Most said they pin their hopes on
reform-minded Premier Zhu cq &LR; Rongji, who is grappling with the
social effects of rapid economic change _ tens of millions of
unemployed people, millions of migrant workers, farmers locked in
land and water disputes, and peasants fighting high taxes.
</P>
<P>
   At Beijing's prestigious Qinghua University, one small group of
students is remembering Tiananmen in a way that reflects China 10
years later. Using news photos from Western magazines or downloaded
off the Internet, the students have made a small, photocopied
collage of the 1989 protests and are sharing it with friends. One
23-year-old woman, surnamed Gao, smiled as she looked at one image
of a cheering crowd running through the streets with a bright
banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very young then, but these pictures are very
beautiful,'' she said. ``People look so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Does she mind that she can't hang the collage up on campus, or
that many other students won't do anything to commemorate the
anniversary at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too much,'' she said. ``I do what I like, and they can do
what they like. I think that is what people at Tiananmen wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 0347EDT &QL; 
