<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 03:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1124 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-DISSIDENTS-SFCH     06-03 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIANANMEN DISSIDENTS REMEMBER MOVEMENT _ AND THOSE WHO DIED FOR 
 IT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BENJAMIN PIMENTEL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ For Jing Chang of Daly City, Calif.,
remembering Tiananmen Square triggers a range of emotions.
<P>
   After escaping China shortly after the June 4 crackdown, the
former Beijing University student leader fled to the United States,
where he began a new life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very lucky,'' said the 31-year-old entrepreneur, who
has just started his own Internet company. ``I was able come to the
States and live here and make some kind of achievement in my
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still have a very strong sense of guilt because of what
happened. I was a student leader _ and I bear responsibility for
the lives and well-being of my fellow students.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after escaping to the United States, many Bay Area
Chinese exiles have moved on, starting families and settling into
new careers. But like Chang, they still think of their homeland and
what they tried to achieve 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Chang's colleagues and friends were killed when Chinese
soldiers opened fire on the demonstrators in the Beijing square, he
said. After the bloody incident, he helped fellow students escape,
finding them places to hide and giving them pocket money. Chang
himself was later smuggled out of the country by sympathizers from
Hong Kong. He had to hide in the water tank of a container ship.
``I thought I was in hell,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Chang arrived in San Francisco in late 1989, then moved east,
earning an MBA at Columbia University. He worked for a Hong Kong
consulting firm before returning this year to the Bay Area to start
his own company.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Weiguo, 42, was a Beijing journalist when the bloodbath
happened. He was later imprisoned twice for his dissident views and
writings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the government fired on the students, it was as if I
myself was hit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police harassed him to the point that whenever he heard sirens,
he got very nervous. When Chinese authorities gave him permission
to leave the country, he grabbed the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was living in horror,'' he said. ``By being here, I am away
from that horror.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhang arrived in San Francisco in 1993. He lives in El Cerrito,
Calif., and is a visiting scholar at the University of California's
Graduate School of Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   He still writes about China and spends much time learning about
the Internet and the New Media which he hopes will one day make it
easier to distribute news and information in China.
</P>
<P>
   Another journalist, Zhou Sha, 34, was an editor for a
Canton-based business weekly newspaper during the upheaval. He
helped pass on information to supporters and the media in other
countries after the massacre. He later had to be smuggled out of
the country via Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty bad,'' Zhou said. ``I felt that the country
didn't have any hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhou came to the United States in late 1989. Two years later, he
joined the U.S. Navy and served on the Seventh Fleet's humanitarian
mission to Bosnia. He is now an independent computer engineering
consultant living in Daly City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other dissidents went to school. I got to know other
Americans,'' he said of his military experience. ``It made me feel
like a normal American.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang has also acquired U.S. citizenship. Zhang has applied for
a green card, but said he hopes to remain a Chinese citizen.
</P>
<P>
   It's a special week for the three exiles.
</P>
<P>
   Chang has been helping organize a daylong commemoration of
Tiananmen. Zhang is writing articles on the 1989 protests for
Chinese-language newspapers in the Bay Area and Hong Kong. He also
plans to attend the planned demonstration and vigil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably will see some friends and exchange some of our
ideas,'' Zhou said of his plans.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back to the decade after Tiananmen hasn't been easy.
Many attitudes have changed, toward China and toward the dissidents
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   China has undergone rapid economic growth which, even the
dissidents admit, has meant a better life for many Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed feelings about the 10th anniversary,'' Zhang
said. ``I feel happy that China has made a lot of progress
economically. ... At the same time, I feel sad because,
politically, China is reversing the cause of freedom and
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the pro-democracy movement in exile has also faced
criticism for being fractious and for putting the spotlight on the
negative side of China.
</P>
<P>
   Mountain View business consultant George Koo even belittles the
significance of the Tiananmen Square anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 10th anniversary of Tiananmen is a much bigger deal
outside China than inside,'' said Koo, who has worked with American
companies doing business in Asia. ``There are certain people who
are very interested in keeping that thing on the front pages of the
papers ... the very anti-China elements in this country.''Some are
dissidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese exiles scoff at such views, accusing some U.S.
business and political leaders of downplaying the repression for
their economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never sacrifice the Chinese people's well-being and
human rights for your business connections,'' Chang said. ``I think
that's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Chinese Americans want to do business (with China); they
depend on China to make a living,'' Zhou said. ``People like me,
who don't depend on China, can have a more objective view of what's
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics, like San Francisco attorney Ed Liu, say it's also
time to take a deeper look at Tiananmen.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Beijing government clearly used excessive force,
Liu said some of the student leaders' tactics were also
confrontational and should be reexamined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years is a long time,'' he said. ``We are now developing a
much more sobering perspective. There are some thoughts that it
could have turned out differently if some of the leaders had acted
more responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang still reflects on his own leadership _ and the death of
his fellow students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, because of my inexperience and limitations of
my capabilities, I couldn't protect them,'' he said. ``We didn't
really achieve what we wanted. I feel very sad.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
