<P>
   1. JOAN CHEN'S 'XIU XIU' MARKS BRAVE DEBUT Joan Chen was a
teenage star of Chinese films before heading West for a career in
Europe and Hollywood. In America, she is best known for captivating
performances in ``The Last Emperor,'' and ``David Lynch's ``Twin
Peaks'' television series. Now the actress has become a director,
with ``Xiu-Xiu, The Sent Down Girl.'' This controversial film,
which Chen also co-wrote and produced, is set during China's
Cultural Revolution. It has already been banned by the Chinese
government. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 800 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
HEADING TO BROADWAY IN SEARCH OF REASONS TO BELIEVE At the
beginning of his one-man play about the Middle East, ``Via
Dolorosa,'' David Hare declares that he recently realized, ``almost
without noticing, that for some time my subject as a playwright has
been faith. My subject is belief.'' He envies the Arabs and
Israelis their fervour, while being too aware of its
destructiveness to adapt any such passions himself. Conversely, all
around him in England he sees the rigor mortis of a life without
that passion. That's the horrible irony of Western civilization at
the millennium, as he tells the audience. By Ed Siegal. Boston
Globe. 1,800 words + photo.
