<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-CHANCELLOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UC BERKELEY CHANCELLOR RAPS 4% ADMISSIONS POLICY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ California's new policy of admitting the top 4
percent of California high school students to the University of
California will have ``no truly significant impact'' on the
percentages of black and Hispanic students at the Berkeley campus,
Berkeley Chancellor Robert Berdahl said Wednesday.
<P>
   The new policy, recently approved by Governor Gray Davis and the
UC Board of Regents, is the state's latest effort to maintain
minority enrollments in the wake of Proposition 209, which banned
race-based affirmative action in public education, employment and
state contracting.
</P>
<P>
   The intention of the new policy is to give students from
poor-performing high schools in the state an equal chance of
gaining admission to the university.
</P>
<P>
   Berdahl, speaking to the National Press Club, noted that the 4
percent admission standard does not guarantee admission to the
prestigious Berkeley or Los Angeles campuses.
</P>
<P>
   But, Berdahl said, the policy will benefit disadvantaged
students by sending a signal that ``if you work hard and do
extremely well and graduate from high school (in the top 4
percent), you will be eligible for admission. ... You will not feel
you are already barred because you had the bad luck to have
attended a weak high school.''
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that Berkeley is focusing, instead, on other
approaches to increase minority admissions. Berdahl said those
initiatives include ``a massive refocusing of investment to correct
inequalities in the K-12 public school system, with higher
education engaging the problems of public schools and investing
more in outreach and remediation; and second, a deep re-evaluation
of the standards by which we judge merit, with public universities
leading a transition toward judging students as individuals rather
than as the sum of their grade-point average and test scores.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, UC Berkeley started an outreach program to improve 50
poor-performing public schools in San Francisco, Oakland, Berkeley
and West Contra Costa County. Called the Berkeley Pledge School
Partnerships, its intention is to improve the academic performance
of minority applicants to Berkeley. The program uses such methods
as after-school and in-school tutoring, teacher training and
Internet-based curriculum enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   Berdahl also said that the Berkeley admissions process has been
altered to ``evaluate students on the basis of the hand they have
been dealt and how they have played that hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Berdahl insisted that ``academic standards still remain the
basic premise'' for student admissions, ``but they are evaluated
not simply in terms of test scores or grade-point averages.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``context of the school'' is also considered, he said, and
students are evaluated ``in terms of the kind of curriculum with
which they challenge themselves. If a student attends a high school
that has a significant number of advanced placement classes but
refuses to take those classes, that student has not challenged
himself or pushed herself as hard as she ought to,'' Berdahl said.
``If, on the contrary, that student has attended a school which has
far fewer advanced placement classes, one that we might consider to
be a disadvantaged environment, but that student has taken all of
the advanced placement classes ... that student, it seems to me,
should be given credit for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Berdahl took over as Berkeley chancellor in July 1997, after
serving as president of the University of Texas, another school
where race-based affirmative action was banned after the Supreme
Court ruled against the practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
