<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NATO'S RIFT IS SLOBBO'S GIFT &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ On the banner of Serbia, it is written: ``Only Unity
Saves the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic will be quick to take
advantage of the disunity of the outside world as his visitors
present him with a peace plan whose authors were denying some of
its contents the moment the envoys set off for Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The disunity was as preposterous as it was potentially
tragic... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (650 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-SENILE-PEACE-PLAN-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIVILIANS IN BELGRADE HAVE A BONE TO PICK WITH NATO &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ I didn't take a shower Tuesday morning. The power
cuts have severed the water supply again. My taps roar at me like a
sick lion and the red plastic bucket on my balcony collects an inch
of grey rainwater from Belgrade's polluted skies; definitely not
for brushing my teeth, maybe _ just maybe _ enough to flush the
toilet.
</P>
<P>
   No power, no water, no cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels and London and Paris, you might be forgiven for
believing that NATO's wishful thinking represents reality; that
Serbia is on its knees, that its people are on the verge of
insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   But returning to Belgrade after a month away is a weird
experience. The mood is harder, more cynical, more resigned... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (975 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-LIFE-INSIDE-BELGRADE-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FACE OF `COLLATERAL DAMAGE' &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SURDULICA, CENTRAL SERBIA _ Not far from Milena Malobabic's
young body, we found the notebook of love poems she wrote for her
boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's jets had killed her and at least 18 other patients in the
tuberculosis sanatorium just a few hours earlier and Milena's body
lay in the shade of a pine tree, her long black hair drifting over
her face in the breeze, a silver earring still sparkling in her
left ear.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombs destroyed a hospital Monday and they called it _
heaven spare us again _ ``collateral damage.'' But Milena's death
alone constitutes a unique tragedy of war... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (1,000 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CASUALTIES-OF-NATO-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
