<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREASMVILLE: Diamond in the rough
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Hartsfield
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s and early 1960s Atlanta was a much smaller
town, especially in the southwestern part of the city in the little
community known as Oakland City.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer we often played baseball on a large field next
to ``Miss Georgia,'' an ice cream shop where you could get a scoop
of ice cream for a nickel. A ``spinning wheel,'' what they called a
milkshake, was 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   A briar patch was out in right field, the infield sloped as you
ran toward first base, and the back of a tire company was not too
deep in left field.
</P>
<P>
   When Mack came to bat, the left fielder had to play with his
back to the wall of the tire company, because Mack could hit it
over the building and out onto Lee Street with most swings.
</P>
<P>
   He was the slugger of our neighborhood. But every day we played,
somebody got a big hit, made a great play or slid home with the
winning run, as we chased fly balls into the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   One day as we played, a chauffeur-driven Cadillac pulled into
the parking lot of the ice cream shop.
</P>
<P>
   The curiosity was overwhelming for 10- and 12-year-old boys, so
we went over to see who was inside.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Mickey Mantle, we wondered, or Whitey Ford or Ted
Williams?
</P>
<P>
   But that couldn't be, because this was baseball season. So it
was probably just some rich person.
</P>
<P>
   As we approached, the window came down and we could see a
beautiful woman with flaming red hair inside the car.
</P>
<P>
   It was Susan Hayward, the glamorous Hollywood actress!
</P>
<P>
   She waved to us as the car pulled away. She was probably
returning to her home in Carrollton, not far down the road from
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly our game continued, with more home runs, great catches
in the outfield and balls rolling into the briar patch, which were
ground-rule doubles, unless the ball was touched by an errant
fielder, and then you could run forever.
</P>
<P>
   These were our glory days!
</P>
<P>
   When the game was finally called on account of darkness, we made
our way to Spratlin's Grocery up on Lee Street and bought penny
bubblegum baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   I usually got some good ones. That particular day I traded a
Nellie Fox for an Al Kaline. What a steal! I had two Nellie Foxes
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   There is an apartment building on the field now. I bet that
under the cement parking lot or building foundation there are the
remnants of an old baseball that was forever lost in the briars.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Hartsfield makes his home in Marietta, Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas,
75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your article is used,
you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville articles, visit
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
