A1233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-CO     06-03 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Man vs. woman: a new snag
 &HT;    For release June 6, 1999.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since women rose up and demanded their rightful place in
society, I have been in step. As females moved out into the
workplace, I bonded with their cause _ quite forcefully supported
ERA. It only seemed right.
</P>
<P>
   I often do the dishes, also the grocery shopping; my married
sons go off to Indian Princess camp with their daughters, there's
no ordering around of the female members of the family and, I can
boast, we're 50-50 in my clan.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I've ever measured it.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes disturbing news from Germany where the Greens
party, a radically minded ecologist group with growing power in
Bonn, is insisting on a legal requirement that men do an equal
share of housework.
</P>
<P>
   This would include, the Greens say, cooking, doing the dishes
and cleaning up the house. ``If both partners are working, the
50-50 principle also has to hold true over the housework,'' a
spokesperson for the Greens said.
</P>
<P>
   Unclear to me is what the rules should be regarding households
where the female doesn't work. Since everything is aimed at working
partners, am I to assume that women who do not work do not qualify
for the 50-50 rule?
</P>
<P>
   I have no problem with men doing their fare share. As I said
above, we're about 50-50 in my family. But this proposed measure by
the Greens is demanding the 50-50 ratio and, in order to keep it,
someone's got to maintain records.
</P>
<P>
   This is the issue upon which I pounce.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to keep score?
</P>
<P>
   The Greens are contending that no matter the new relationship
between men and women these days, working mothers still do three
hours a month more household work than their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   So someone in Germany was keeping score, which does not surprise
me, knowing the efficiency of the German mind.
</P>
<P>
   If it passes, charts will have to be placed _ say on
refrigerators _ marking the minutes and hours worked by each
partner in performing the tedious chores of the household.
</P>
<P>
   I see a need for stopwatches.
</P>
<P>
   Looming are never-before-thought-of confrontations between
husband and wife, or partners, as the expression now goes. Did I do
the dishes in 12 minutes or 17 minutes? Did she spend one hour at
the washing machine, or one hour and 10 minutes and, besides, she
was reading a book all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Things like that. Venus and Mars stuff.
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking about something like that a couple of weeks ago
when we were going through a life boat drill on a cruise ship
leaving Lisbon. As the passengers stood on deck, their life jackets
firmly tied to their bodies, the ship's officer announced that in
case of emergency, and despite the sufficient capacities of the
life boats, loading would be women and children first.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, that ain't 50-50! Neither is the fact that guys have to
sign up for Selective Service and gals don't.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't allow those male-icous thoughts to alter my
devotion to a 50-50 partnership with my wife. Nevertheless, with
the Greens coming up with their proposal and the likelihood that
some equally radical group on this side of the Atlantic might seize
upon it, I raise the question:
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to keep score and how? None of this he-said,
she-said stuff.
</P>
<P>
   After 45 years of marriage, my wife and I still can't work out
the difference of time. When she says she'll be ready to leave the
house in five minutes, it always takes 10. When I tell her there's
only two minutes left in the basketball game, it always takes 15
minutes to play it.
</P>
<P>
   We don't operate on the same clock; never did, never will.
</P>
<P>
   And now someone is suggesting a law that requires we keep a
clock on housework? Yeah, well how about one that keeps track of
who spends how much time in control of the bathroom?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
