<HEADER>
A1253 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV06-C     06-03 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE POLITICS OF FAITH VS. THE EVILS OF HOLLYWOOD
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's easy enough to dismiss the coming $1 million
federal probe into whether the entertainment industry markets
violence to children as yet another bit of fluffy Washington show
business.
</P>
<P>
   After all, we already know ``our children are being fed a
dependable daily dose of violence,'' as President Clinton put it
from his Rose Garden lectern in ordering the review. ``This stuff
sells,'' Clinton said, without waiting for the results to come in.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the nanny-in-chief was doing his thing: Washington is
about politics, just like Hollywood is about illusion. Only these
days, lots of the stuff being peddled out of this town is
illusionary, while the big campaign bucks being milked out of
Hollywood are quite real.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the Democratic president acted out of a political
desire to pre-empt the Republican-led Congress, which was moving to
approve a comparable investigation out of a political desire to
deflect pressure for more gun controls following the Littleton
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   That said, some of the changes occurring on both coasts do bear
a closer look. For one thing, in gearing up for the 2000 elections,
Democrats have found religion. For another, Hollywood has lost its
moral gears.
</P>
<P>
   In his first term, Clinton ate the Republicans' lunch by
balancing the budget and cutting welfare rolls. In trying to win
his first term, Al Gore cites the Bible to explain what drove two
teenagers to commit mayhem in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives have long held a lock on the Holy Scripture as a
guide to policy choices. No longer. The politics of faith that
drove the president to the crack down on Hollywood violence also
drove the vice president to summon seven religion reporters to a
White House schmooze about theology.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, the conservative crowd takes a somewhat cynical
view. Says Gary Bauer, a second-tier Republican White House
hopeful: ``I welcome converts, but I suspect it has something to do
with the political calendar and polls showing that a majority of
Americans now think our problems are spiritual rather than
economic.''
</P>
<P>
   Then too, Washington experts would have less to study if
Hollywood hadn't become so cynical in its bloody marketing
campaigns. Any honest inquiry would reveal that there's been plenty
of violence in movies, going back to the Depression and World War
II. Nobody kept us from paying our quarters to sit in the
children's section.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that all of us knew then whom to root for. The
bad guys wore black hats and invariably got what they deserved.
Even before the MGM lion roared, we already knew that the good guys
would win the war, even though they would have to suffer brutality
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Justice Department will probe why Hollywood no
longer makes a moral choices between good and evil. Perhaps Buffy
the Vampire Slayer will be caught selling nuclear secrets to the
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
