<HEADER>
A1259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-GOODING-PROFILE-     06-03 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GOODING-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUBA GOODING JR.: SHOW ME THE ROLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Jerry Maguire,'' Cuba Gooding Jr. made the kind of
impression every actor dreams of. The impression was made with the
words: ``Show me the money.''
</P>
<P>
   His character's famous catch phrase became so familiar that
complete strangers shout it at him on the street. Even his agent,
the actor says, has been known to greet him that way. (Well, at
least he has an honest agent.)
</P>
<P>
   But if the phrase implies someone interested in money over all
else, Gooding has not lived up to it. Some actors use their new
star recognition to move into higher-paying action movies, all but
deserting the character-driven roles they were originally praised
for. (Nicolas Cage, please come home.)
</P>
<P>
   Gooding said he has been offered big-studio money to do
action-movie lead roles, but he doesn't think those are right for
him. So he has chosen to stay in character roles, even though it
has kept him a supporting actor. It's not that he doesn't want to
do leads _ he certainly does. But he wants to do roles that
interest him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every actor has choices to make, and the way the choices are
made will affect his career forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time that Gooding, 31, has made acting
choices with his long-range career in mind. After his first big
success in movies, a featured role in the surprise low-budget hit
``Boyz in the Hood,'' Gooding was offered similar urban films and
bad-guy roles. But he said no to avoid being typecast. Being picky
has cost him a lot of films, but now he's identified with quality
character parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm on the track, sometimes in a positive direction,
sometimes in a negative. But on the whole I think I'm sticking to
my plan.''
</P>
<P>
   And it seems to be paying off. After strong supporting roles in
``Jerry Maguire,'' ``As Good As It Gets'' and ``What Dreams May
Come,'' Gooding finally has his first real lead in a major studio
film with ``Instinct,'' opening Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the studio (Disney) is promoting it more as an Anthony
Hopkins film, Gooding's character has the larger part and carries
the most dramatic weight.
</P>
<P>
   So is it a breakthrough role in his career?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Gooding.
</P>
<P>
   When he called recently, Gooding was in a limousine heading for
the Denver airport. He was sharing the ride with his ``Instinct''
director, Jon Turteltaub (``Phenomenon''), as they stumped the
country to promote the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Instinct'' role is especially sweet for Gooding because he
was not the first choice for the role. Gooding has said that both
Tom Hanks and Mel Gibson were early candidates, but the deals never
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always looking to get the opportunities that aren't handed
to me,'' said Gooding. ``When `Jerry Maguire' came around, I was
like the third choice for this read-through (audition). Director
Cameron Crowe said, `I've got to be honest: I never really thought
of you for this, but after seeing this read-through, I think that
you're a contender for the role.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I ate, drank, slept the character until my next audition,''
Gooding said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the actor got the part, and eventually a
best-supporting-actor Academy Award for his performance.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding may be staying with character parts for now, but he
makes no bones about wanting them to be in lead, not support roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to make the transition from support actor to lead
actor. This was the first role I saw an opportunity (to do that).
My strife is showing the studio they can green-light a movie with
me, with a character that carries the burden of telling the story
through his eyes. That was my first goal. That was always my first
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to fight to show that I could be a lead. This script was
one of the best I had read in a while, and it really made me want
it for that reason.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Instinct,'' Gooding plays Caulder, a young psychiatrist
given the opportunity to work on a high-profile case, that of a
famous anthropologist (Hopkins) who seems to have gone homicidally
mad.
</P>
<P>
   The anthropologist, named Powell, had disappeared in Africa,
actually going to live with the gorilla band he was studying. When
park rangers began killing the gorillas, Powell killed two rangers
to protect the rest of the animals. Since his capture he has
refused to speak or communicate.
</P>
<P>
   In Powell, Caulder sees either a great opportunity to help
someone or a big career break. Maybe both. Part of the complexity
of Gooding's performance is that we must decide for ourselves where
Caulder's heart lies.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins has the film's flashier role, the eccentric mute who
represents nature being destroyed by man's callousness. But it's
Gooding who has the tougher part.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so tricky about the role Cuba played is that you don't
get the juicy acting moments a more flamboyant character would
have,'' said Turteltaub. ``It is far more difficult for an actor to
play a common man and make simple emotions believable. That's much
tougher than it is to bounce off the walls and play someone with
one leg or no tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are pitfalls in the other stuff _ overacting _ and
that's where Anthony Hopkins is so brilliant. But in the case of
Caulder, Cuba has to make an average man feel believable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where that is tough is we have so much to compare him to. If
you're playing a man who lives with gorillas, nobody knows what
that's like, so you're going to take Anthony Hopkins' word for it.
Cuba had to present a character who is very mainstream. That
requires a lot of subtlety.''
</P>
<P>
   With a large percentage of the movie taking place in dialogue
between the two Oscar-winning actors, Turteltaub knew he'd have to
find ways to keep the interaction dramatic. One approach he took
was to shoot the actors very tightly _ a technique hardly likely to
win critical praise, although he believes it works.
</P>
<P>
   Another was to emphasize the different ways the two adversaries
approach dealing with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cat-mouse game between them,'' said Turteltaub.
``There is an unpredictability to their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the script does _ and I tried to do _ is always allow
Cuba to be asking the kind of questions that will throw Anthony
Hopkins' character off guard. Anthony Hopkins would always be
taking physical postures that would be throwing Cuba's character
off guard. Therefore, the audience is always thrown off guard by
both.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooding, as anyone who saw his enthusiastic acceptance of the
Oscar might guess, has a reputation for high energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a nut,'' Turteltaub said. ``What you see publicly from
Cuba is just the tip of the iceberg. If you find him in a limo
listening to Busta Rhymes, you're in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   (At this point, the limo's radio cranks up to full volume.
Turteltaub starts laughing and yells at Gooding, ``Behave yourself,
I have an interview to do.'')
</P>
<P>
   Gooding knew going into the film that he couldn't use too much
of his famous energy in the role, at least not overtly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The character being a psychiatrist and just sitting in a room
for most of the movie talking with a patient ... I knew this
couldn't be flamboyant and boisterous and energetic,'' Gooding
said. ``I had to kind of sit there and hold my poise. I thought
that might be a nice challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the majority of ``Instinct'' consists of Gooding and
Hopkins going one-on-one in a small room, talking, arguing and
playing mind games, you might wonder if their styles clashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was because of the relationship of the
characters in our movie, but we were sort of stand-offish,''
Gooding said. ``Everybody calls Anthony Hopkins `Tony.' I never
stopped calling him Anthony. He never corrected me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that it was a stiff relationship, because I love the guy.
We are looking for something to do together again. Maybe it was
that we are personal in our approaches to acting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gooding said the different styles did not cause them
difficulty on camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Completely the opposite. We didn't do one day of rehearsal on
this movie. We didn't talk about the scenes. We didn't talk about
what the dialogue meant. When we went to dinner, we never talked
about the day's work. The only exchange of comments would be, `That
felt good.' That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
