<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS04-COX     06-03 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can Sean Elliott stay hot for two weeks?
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ When Sean Elliott walks into Portland's Rose
Garden today, certain dimensions might seem out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rims are going to look like the Grand Canyon to him,''
said Steve Kerr, Elliott's teammate with the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   That's the view from a hero's perch, where Elliott now stands
after hitting the game-winning three-point shot from 24 feet
against Portland on Monday, giving the Spurs a 2-0 lead in the NBA
Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The shot _ Elliott's sixth three-pointer of the game _ was
off-balance, rushed and perhaps ill-conceived, considering that
Elliott had nine seconds to find a better one and that
7-foot-1-inch teammate David Robinson was waiting near the basket.
But it went in, and 20 minutes later Elliott said, ``I could do it
again now. I'm still feeling it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why teammates Kerr and Mario Elie, who have won playoff
games for other teams with critical shots, think Elliott should be
able to ride this feeling for at least a few more games.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr made a name for himself by hitting a 17-foot jump shot with
five seconds left in game six of the 1997 NBA Finals to secure the
championship for Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, you feel like anything you throw up is going to go
in,'' Kerr said. ``When Sean goes out Friday, he's going to feel
relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's six-for-seven accuracy on three-pointers Monday will
boost him more than if he had just made the one that everyone will
remember, Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you shoot like that, you gain confidence,'' Kerr
said. ``But when you do it in the playoffs, it even increases that
confidence more. Smart players, when they are playing, think about
situations where they've come through in the clutch.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie, playing for Houston, made a three-point shot in game seven
of the 1995 Western Conference semifinals to lift the Rockets past
Phoenix, giving his team momentum it carried all the way to a
second straight NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I hit my three-pointer in Phoenix, I felt like every
shot was going in,'' Elie said.
</P>
<P>
   Elie has since been regarded as a dangerous clutch shooter, a
reputation he enhanced by hitting a last-second three-pointer to
beat the Rockets on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of sustained momentum, Elie notes the continued
success of Allan Houston, the New York guard whose running shot
eliminated Miami from the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, an inconsistent three-point shooter most of his career
_ he hit 32.8 percent this season _ said his confidence has
recently been building. He hit four of 10 three-pointers against
the Lakers in the Western Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just feels like a regular shot now,'' Elliott said.
``Instead of a long-distance shot, it feels like a 12-footer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr wishes he could say the same. Kerr is the most accurate
three-point shooter in NBA history _ 46.3 percent _ albeit as a
part-time player. But right now, the rim probably looks more like a
golf hole than the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr received his first serious playing time in the postseason
Monday, 11 minutes. Left open by the Blazers, he missed all five of
his shots, three from behind the arc. His body language after each
miss suggested agony and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Given sporadic playing time this season by coach Gregg Popovich,
primarily because of his liabilities on defense, Kerr never found a
groove, never shot consistently. He hit only 31.3 percent of his
three-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has moved back into the rotation behind Avery Johnson at
point guard. Popovich told Kerr that he would receive more playing
time because Portland double-teams Tim Duncan and David Robinson so
well near the basket that the Spurs might need to rely more than
usual on outside shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pop's always apologizing to me for a lack of playing time, and
I'm always apologizing for a lack of production,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Elliott, Kerr said that at some point the new hero
probably will have a game when he loses his shooting touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, the law of averages takes over,'' Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   Having moved back into the spotlight himself, Kerr can only hope
so.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
