A1265 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MILNER04-COX     06-03 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MILNER04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Berger's `Return of Little Big Man' worth your time
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Way back in the 1960s, when Thomas Berger's wonderfully original
take on the Wild American West, ``Little Big Man'' came out, first
as a book then as a movie starring Dustin Hoffman in the title
role, many people agreed with me that both versions were about as
good as books and movies come.
</P>
<P>
   Now, all these years later, when it was least expected, Berger
has produced a sequel, ``The Return of Little Big Man'' (Little,
Brown and Company) and, although it lacks the scintillating
surprise of the first one, this sequel is definitely worth your
time.
</P>
<P>
   And the good news _ the other good news, I should say _ is that
Berger has set himself up for yet a second sequel. The ancient
Little Big Man, after 432 pages of one tall tale after another,
declares, ``Right now, though, I got to take a nap. If I ever wake
up, you sure will hear the rest of my story.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Little Big Man book, as many of you may recall, found
Jack Crabb, the only survivor of Custer's Last Stand at Little Big
Horn, in a nursing home at age 100-and something, telling his life
story, how he was raised by Cheyenne Indians after they raided his
family's westward bound wagon, killing his parents and making off
with his older sister and him. His Indian name becomes Little Big
Man and he learns Cheyenne ways and becomes a rookie Cheyenne
warrior before being captured by white soldiers and returned to
``civilization'' where, among other things, he tangles with Wyatt
Earp and Wild Bill Hickok.
</P>
<P>
   Jack goes back and forth several times, from the white world to
the Indian world, as he is on the losing side in every battle
between the two. He is able to straighten out several Wild West
myths by relating what really happened because he was there.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of ``Little Big Man'', Jack's supposed death cuts
short his tale. However, a newly discovered manuscript reveals that
Jack faked his death to get out of his publishing contract, and, in
this sequel, picks up the amazing story of his life, giving
eyewitness accounts of the assassination of Wild Bill Hickok and
what really happend at the O.K. Corral. He also hangs out with Bat
Masterson and Annie Oakley and travels to Europe with Buffalo Bill
Cody.
</P>
<P>
   Jack falls in love, at last, near the end of this volume but
decides to wait to tell ``what became of me and her during the rest
of my life, what happened with her book, what kind of work I done
next and where, while technically speaking a middle-aged man, I had
lived not quite half my life at that point, so there's lots left to
relate to what still for some time was my competent years, with
quite a bit happening ...as the nineteenth century turned into the
twentieth, for example Tom Edison begun to make moving pictures to
be shown in theaters rather than just peep machines, gold was
discovered in the Klondike and Colonel Teddy Roosevelt's Rough
Riders fought at the battle of Santiago de Cuba, not on horseback
as you might think, but on foot and took a hill by the name of
Kettle and not San Juan....''
</P>
<P>
   So, we've got a lot to look forward to, if Jack doesn't drop
dead before he gets it told.
</P>
<P>
   And we will hope Berger continues to produce his Mark Twain-like
stories for a long time to come. As the London Times has declared,
``He is one of the century's most important writers.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
