A1266 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN04-COX     06-03 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A letter to my daughter upon her graduation
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Dear Meredith:
</P>
<P>
   I guess this means I'll have to stop calling you Goose, now that
you're a high-school graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Nah.
</P>
<P>
   Jeez. Where did the time go? In my mind you're still the little
brown-eyed girl in the photo in my office, wearing one of my
T-shirts as a dress, posed with your sister and her pet lamb. You
were 5, and everybody could tell you were my daughter because you
walk like me _ toes pointed out, bouncing up and down on the balls
of your feet.
</P>
<P>
   I nicknamed you Goose a few weeks after your birth. You just
pecked around, bright eyes following everything, and it seemed to
fit. You were a happy baby, always smiling and giggling.
</P>
<P>
   As you grew up, it was obvious you had a gift for the written
word. I remember when you had a poem published in a teen magazine
because your older sister fibbed and told them you were 13, even
though you were only 11. I still have the 20-page short story you
wrote at about age 9, called ``The Best Christmas Ever.'' I have a
file drawer half-filled with your stories, scripts for plays,
drawings and such.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my greatest pleasure these days comes from talking to
you about books we've both read. I wish I had your memory for
characters, dialogue and such. The older I get, the harder it is to
remember much about what I read two weeks after I've finished.
</P>
<P>
   You are the undisputed world champion of the Six Degrees of
Kevin Bacon parlor game, where someone names a movie and the other
person has to somehow connect it to Bacon through common actors in
six or fewer steps. Of course, you could have been bamboozling me
when I named some obscure film and you ripped through and connected
it to him in a matter of seconds. I know the names of about 10
actors, and the faces of a few more, and that's it. You, on the
other hand, are the queen of movies.
</P>
<P>
   You have lived half your life with me as a weekend dad living in
another house down the road a few miles. I know that's been hard,
but I hope you realize I tried to be the best father I could under
the circumstances. You did great, despite all the changes in your
life caused by us adults, especially me. I am so proud of what
you've accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's off to college, to join your sister at the University
of Texas. I know you're going to love it, and I know you'll do
well. I am thrilled that you plan to major in journalism, but if
you change your mind in a few semesters that's fine, too. Do what
makes you the happiest, what fulfills you the most. I'd be just as
proud of you if you decided to be an accountant. And you'd make
more money.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some unsolicited advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't be intimidated by the university. Sure, it's big, but
your world there will be relatively small. Just ignore the rest.
That worked great for me.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Avoid driving in Austin at all costs. Both driving and finding
your way around a big city are not your strong suits. Have you ever
heard the expression, ``Lost as a goose?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you do get lost, don't panic. Everybody has to be
somewhere. You're just not where you're supposed to be. You'll find
your way back.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't marry too young. I think 30 is about right. And when you
do get hitched, marry your best friend. It helps if your best
friend has lots of money, but it's not a requirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make new friends. Keep your old ones, of course, but that's
one of the joys of college _ meeting new people from other places.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't be too trusting of strangers. You will be living in a
city of a million people, some of whom are scumbags. The percentage
is probably no higher than in our little town, but the numbers are
greater. Be cautious. Lock your doors. This is your father
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Remember to call your mom and me regularly, not just when you
need money. And don't forget about your grandparents. I know you'll
be busy, but you should check in once in a while. And before you
call, remember we're all old and likely asleep after 10 p.m., hard
as that is to believe.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep reading and writing, no matter what you end up doing for
a living. God doesn't give out many natural gifts, and you should
take advantage of the ones you're given.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most important, keep your sense of humor. Life is funny, and
yours will take many unexpected twists. That's the way it goes.
Just don't take it all too seriously, and you'll live a happier and
likely longer life.
</P>
<P>
   Congrats, Goose. I'm proud of you.
</P>
<P>
   Love,
</P>
<P>
   Dad
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
