<HEADER>
A1271 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN04-COX     06-03 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is it over yet? The reasons this session was a snoozer
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's potential presidential
candidacy dominated the 1999 session of the Texas Legislature. And
it was one of the most boring sessions in memory _ which is
probably exactly what Bush wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's political ambitions were not the only thing that made
it a lackluster session. Other factors included:
</P>
<P>
   _ The absence of all-controlling former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock as
presiding officer of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   _ A $6.4 billion budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   _ The absence of any major crises, either from court suits or
lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's run for the White House didn't color everything, but it
colored a lot. It was a distraction because the news media paid a
lot of attention to it, casting _ rightly or wrongly _ many of
Bush's actions or inactions in the context of presidential
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although the governor's staff tries to paint it otherwise, Bush
paid less hands-on attention to Texas legislators than in previous
sessions. He was busy being briefed on national and international
issues, and receiving politicians and other supplicants from
elsewhere in the country to endorse his candidacy or kiss his ring.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, lobbyists said the governor's office seemed
much more interested in the fine print of many pieces of
legislation than in previous sessions. The speculation was he
wanted to be sure that most controversial measures were either
worked out well before they reached his desk, or, like the
hate-crimes bill, sidetracked so he wouldn't be forced to choose
whether to veto or sign the controversial measure.
</P>
<P>
   The fact Bullock no longer was the Senate's wagonmaster made
that body looser and less focused, as power was decentralized more
than it ever had been under Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   The budget surplus put the Legislature and Gov. Bush in the
comfortable position of dividing up extra money between various
state functions such as a teacher pay hike and tax cuts. There
would have been considerably more pressure had the legislators been
levying new taxes, as they had done more than once in the 1980s
after the oil bust, and as recently as 1991, when Democrat Ann
Richards was the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of major crises was in stark contrast to, for instance,
Richards' first term. In 1991, she was trying to pass a
constitutional amendment to allow a lottery; raising more than $8
billion in taxes; setting up the so-called Robin Hood school plan
to achieve equity in spending between school districts; and dealing
with legislative and congressional redistricting. By contrast, all
the 1999 Legislature had to pass was the appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some observers were amazed toward the end of last week
when Bush seemed to have put himself in the awkward position of
favoring an additional quarter-billion-dollar tax cut over spending
the money on early education.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the issue that might have precipitated a
special session. The Senate, with a 16-15 Republican majority,
eventually capitulated, for the most part, apparently taking its
lead from Bush. The realization must have sunk in about the public
relations damage possible to Bush's popularity _ particularly since
he claims education is his No. 1 issue.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to be the issue in the closing days that could have
forced Bush to call a special session _ particularly if he
continued to insist on additional tax cuts that would come out of
education money. But creative budgeteers found an extra $100
million at the end, and enough was spread around to let the Senate
and Bush save face.
</P>
<P>
   One lobbyist who is a former legislator said one wrinkle on the
absence of Bullock, who was usually into everything, was the frosty
relationship between Bullock's successor, Republican Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry, and Democratic House Speaker Pete Laney.
</P>
<P>
   While Bullock and Laney maintained constant communication and
were centrists who worked together on many issues, the more
ideological and less engaged Perry paid much less attention to the
House and its leadership.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Perry seemed ready to do anything he could to
make Bush look better. Small wonder; Perry's iron grip on Bush's
coattails was what allowed Perry to be lieutenant governor in the
first place. Making Bush look good enough that Americans put him in
the White House would also put Perry in the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the American-Statesman.
You may contact him at dmcneely(at)statesman.com or (512) 445-3644.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
