<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VACUUM04-COX     06-03 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACUUM04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tips to keep picking a vacuum from becoming a chore
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If your house or apartment has floors, you need a
vacuum cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   Regular vacuuming is critical to the lives of rugs and carpets,
and even hardwood, tile and stone floors benefit from having
abrasive dust and grit removed.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, just knowing you need a vacuum is not enough;
you have to figure out which of the hundreds of available models is
best for you.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Scott, owner of First Class Cleaning Service, said your
choice in a vacuum should be based on how you're going to use it.
How much carpeting do you have? How often do you plan to vacuum? Do
you also have many hard-surface floors? Will you be vacuuming to
clean furniture or draperies? Will you need to carry the vacuum up
and down stairs?
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't pick a vacuum because it's the No. 1 model in the
country,'' Scott said. ``You don't just get the one your neighbor
has. You don't get the one with the best commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the tool that does the job you need it to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Christy Hawley, director of housekeeping at Homewood
Suite Hotel, said the vacuums their cleaning staff uses are
powerful commercial models designed for constant, heavy-duty use.
</P>
<P>
   But their commercial machines are designed mostly for floors
only, and Scott and Hawley both use ordinary residential vacuums at
home. Scott said he has a Sanyo vacuum at home while Hawley owns a
Dirt Devil.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy an upright vacuum cleaner for less than $100, or you
can easily spend more than $1,000. The construction, motor size,
filtration systems, advertising budget and extra features affect
how much you will pay.
</P>
<P>
   Below are explanations of some of the features you are likely to
find as you compare the upright vacuum cleaners on the market today
and questions you should ask before making a purchase:
</P>
<P>
   Bodies and attachments
</P>
<P>
   Most residential upright vacuum cleaners sold today have hard,
plastic bodies with attachments such as crevice tools stored in
slots or compartments on the plastic shell.
</P>
<P>
   The business end of the vacuum holds a rotating brush inside a
suction chamber. A hose leads from the suction chamber up over the
handle of the vacuum and into filtering and storage chamber that
captures dust and dirt and expels clean air.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the plastic in the body is an important
consideration. Thin, brittle plastics will break, while thick,
pliable plastics and metals will stand up to abuse, lengthening the
life of the appliance.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be impressed by the machine with the most attached
gadgets; look instead for attachments you're actually likely to
use. Are attachments conveniently located or are they likely to
fall off?
</P>
<P>
   Pay close attention to the length of the hose and any tubes or
wands used with the attachments. Are they easy to use and long
enough to reach the housing of your ceiling fans, for example?
</P>
<P>
   Hoses on modern vacuums can become clogged. Can the hose be
easily cleared of debris? Some machines have see-through hoses that
make spotting obstructions easy.
</P>
<P>
   Some vacuums come without attachments and are just designed to
sweep floors. You may find such machines, which can offer better
suction at lower prices, are all you need.
</P>
<P>
   Does the machine use bags or does it have a dirt chamber?
Replacing bags can be a hassle and add expense to the operation of
your machine, but dirt chambers can be messy to empty and clean.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult is it to remove accumulated dirt from the machine
you are considering?
</P>
<P>
   Are the belts that turn the beater/sweeper bar easily
accessible? How sturdy are the belts and how often must they be
replaced?
</P>
<P>
   How easy is the machine to maneuver? Is the handle in a
comfortable position when you're sweeping?
</P>
<P>
   Filtration
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fussnecker of Fussnecker Sweeper Sales and Service said one
feature that consumers are demanding more than ever is air
filtration.
</P>
<P>
   But microfiltration systems that sift allergens and even smells
from the air add complications and expense to vacuuming.
Manufacturers sometimes make confusing claims to try to convince
customers their vacuums release the cleanest air.
</P>
<P>
   The most widely heard term in air filtration is HEPA, which
stands for High-Efficiency Particulate Arrestor or High-Efficiency
Particle Air, depending on who you talk to. To carry the
designation HEPA, a filter must meet specific criteria on the size
of the particles it blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Many vacuums come with designations such as ``HEPA-like'' or
``high-efficiency'' or ``allergy-safe.'' To compare the filtration
claims of one manufacturer against another, look for percentages
and microns.
</P>
<P>
   A micron is a microscopic distance equal to 1/1000th of a
millimeter. A filter that removes 99 percent of the particles that
are 0.3 microns is more effective than a filter that removes 95
percent at 0.5 microns and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Superior filtration reduces the allergens the vacuum sprays into
the air and can reduce odors. Poor filtering can allow dust to blow
out of the vacuum and settle back in your house.
</P>
<P>
   To be really effective, the air that travels through the vacuum
must be contained in an airtight stream until it passes through all
the machine's filters. Does the vacuum you are considering have
efficient filters to block dust from its motor as well as from the
air?
</P>
<P>
   Remember that most microfilters come with cartridges, typically
costing $5 to $25, that must be replaced periodically. Find out how
often cartridges must be replaced and figure the replacement costs
of cartridges when figuring the cost of running your machine.
</P>
<P>
   Motors and suction
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the more powerful the motor, the greater the suction.
The greater the suction, the better the vacuum draws deep dirt out
of carpets and other things you're cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of motor power is the amp rating of the vacuum
cleaner. A 10-amp vacuum is more powerful than a 7-amp, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   Fussnecker said vacuum manufacturers have been in an arms race
the past few years to offer machines with bigger motors. He said
most have settled on 10 amps and aren't likely to go much higher.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is many household electrical systems have 15-amp
circuits, and vacuums with larger motors are more likely to
overload circuits.
</P>
<P>
   Another area of competition between companies is in hyping their
air-moving systems. You'll run into wind tunnels, vortexes,
whirlwinds, cyclones and other descriptions of how vacuums create
suction.
</P>
<P>
   All these systems of directing air don't mean much unless the
vacuum picks up dirt.
</P>
<P>
   To compare one machine with another, you'll have to find a
retailer that will let you spread dirt on a test carpet and clean
it up with several models.
</P>
<P>
   Other options
</P>
<P>
   _ Height adjustment: Shag rugs are coming back into fashion, so
your vacuum should adjust quickly and easily to varying heights,
otherwise the brush can bite too deeply into the pile. Some vacuums
adjust automatically to changing carpet heights, but most use a
knob or sliding switch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brush cut-off: If you plan to use your vacuum on tile or
hardwood floors, you should look for this often-neglected feature.
The switch disengages the sweeper brush so you can sweep hard
floors without the brush spreading dirt around.
</P>
<P>
   _ Self-propelled: If you have trouble moving a vacuum cleaner
around, some come with internal motors that move the machine back
and forth with a slight push or pull on a control handle. This
feature may be useful for a few physically challenged users, but it
adds cost to the machine, and most modern vacuums are very easy to
maneuver without being self-propelled.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dirt sensors: This may be just a fad, but a growing number of
vacuums come with sensors that use light beams or sound to sense
dirt as it enters the suction chamber. When no more dirt is
detected, the machine flashes a green light indicating your carpet
is clean.
</P>
<P>
   _ Suction control: Extremely powerful machines can actually
produce too much suction for some applications. For example, they
could pull a set of light kitchen curtains right off the rod. Area
rugs on hard-surface floors sometimes require less suction as well.
Suction adjustments that slow down the motor or open vents on
attachments make some jobs easier.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
