<HEADER>
A1275 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX     06-03 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gather ye at the dunking pond for Rep. Barr's edict
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Recruits, assume the position. Congressman Bob
Barr (the one with the penlight in his teeth) has arrived to
examine you.
</P>
<P>
   You say you want to join the Army? We want you. First, you'll
submit to this inspection of your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Christian? OK. Jew? Pass. Muslim? Approved. Wiccan? You are
hereby restrained.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least that's the way Barr wants the U.S. Army to do
things. In fact, he's demanding it. After finding out that a group
of Wiccans was practicing the religion at Fort Hood under
permission from the U.S. government, Barr went into the hissiest of
fits. It turned out Fort Hood was just the first of several
military bases condoning the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, the U.S. government condoning all varieties of
spiritual beliefs. It's un-American. It must be stopped. And Barr
is the man to do it.
</P>
<P>
   It was Barr, recall, who led the without-sin brigade that
railroaded Bill Clinton into impeachment proceedings. We were asked
to disregard information about the Georgia Republican's own
indiscretions, pulsating on Larry Flynt's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Now the righteous congressman wants us to get exercised over the
way Wiccans _ they do not shrink from ``witch'' _ exercise their
religion on military bases. Nip this in the bud, he tells the
Pentagon. Base commanders are ignoring Barr at this point, which
pretty much puts them in line with most rank-and-file civilians in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Wicca is a neo-pagan, nature-based sect, tax-exempt as a
religion in the eyes of the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Barr isn't interested in ousting Wiccans, just in
prohibiting their rituals. This would be a trick. Consider for the
moment what it would entail if the military were to ban, say,
Christian rituals. Would a clasping of hands before the face
violate the code of conduct? Would a heavenward nod?
</P>
<P>
   Barr said that allowing Wiccan rituals on-base undermines
military readiness, ``to say nothing of detrimental effects on our
society'' and the military's upholding the ``spirit of 'God and
country,''' failing to properly attribute late, beloved holy man
Ayatollah Khomeini for the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of being denounced as giving aid and comfort to
infidels, Congressman Chet Edwards, whose district includes Fort
Hood, had a measured response: ``It would be terrible policy to
require each installation commander to define what is a religion
and decide which religions can be practiced by American citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrible policy for military commanders, right. But it can be
good politics for self-righteous hand-wringers who truly appear to
think that government can and should authorize religious beliefs _
and that it's the majority's duty to impose its beliefs on the
minority in matters of state (and, of course, school). These people
really need to find a hobby. Totem carving, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   It should amaze all to think that people could go to Washington
and not find better ways to spend their time than finding ways for
government to control free thoughts and expression.
</P>
<P>
   The perennial push for an anti-flag desecration amendment suits
these folks fine. They want the law to delineate how one can
comport oneself around a symbol, disregarding the fact that a
symbol can take countless forms, on fabric, on paper, on
undershorts. You can skywrite a symbol. You can paint it on your
belly for the hockey game. You can print it on Silly Putty and
stretch it and compress it and bounce it off the wall.
</P>
<P>
   A law defining illegal acts involving a symbol seemingly would
be as long as the New York phone book. The same goes for a code of
prohibited religious rituals on military bases.
</P>
<P>
   When lawmakers have nothing better to do, government really has
become the problem.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
