   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUS-MESSAGES (San Francisco) _ Muni, the San Francisco bus
system, is testing electronic message boards that post approximate
arrival times of buses for riders used to waiting it out. The
boards rely on a satellite global positioning system that transmits
bus locations. By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-POLL (San Francisco) _ Long before the attack ads,
televised debates and campaign rallies, California voters lean
toward the anointed front-running Republican candidates for the
2000 presidential nomination _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former
Cabinet member Elizabeth Dole _ as their choice over Democratic
Vice President Al Gore, a San Francisco Examiner poll shows. By
ANDREW POLLACK.
</P>
<P>
   ATHEIST-MISSING (San Antonio) _ Gary Karr, one of three men
accused of kidnapping and murdering atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair
and her two adult children, swears he had no part in the crimes.
``He absolutely denies he had anything to do with the murders,''
said Thomas Mills, a Dallas lawyer who met with Karr earlier this
week in a Michigan jail. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   AMUSEMENT-RIDES (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Amusement parks in
California would be subject to government inspection and tougher
fines under a measure overwhelmingly approved by the state Assembly
_ two years to the day after a Napa High School student plunged to
her death at WaterWorld USA in Concord, Calif. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California's hate crime law
would get beefed up for murderers of gays, lesbians and the
disabled under a measure approved by the Assembly with strong
Republican support. The law now requires a sentence of life in
prison without parole or the death penalty for anyone who
deliberately sets out to kill someone because of their race, color,
religion or nationality. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
