   JOB-STABILITY (San Francisco) _ Some employees define loyalty as
working hard for a company today, not staying there for decades.
They want pay based on performance, not longevity. And they don't
see anything wrong with job hopping. It's a new generation of
workers, but it's not necessarily Generation X. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-GLITCHES (San Francisco) _ When does a software bug
cross over from annoying glitch to class-action lawsuit? A New
Jersey class-action recently challenged a longtime software
industry practice of issuing imperfect titles, in this case forcing
a software publisher to release a free fix. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-BANKS (San Francisco) _ The Federal Reserve's top gun in the
West reassured the public that the dreaded Year 2000 bug won't
ravage the nation's financial system when the new century rolls
around. Robert T. Parry predicted that the country's financial
infrastructure will run smoothly, despite nightmarish forecasts
that the banking system will crash and burn. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
