<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSTINCT-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INSTINCT' IMITATES TRUE DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Watching the earnest ridiculousness of
``Instinct,'' alternative titles flood the mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Lecter Goes Ape'' is an obvious one for this tale of a
brilliant primatologist played by Anthony Hopkins who turns
homicidal after spending too much time in the company of African
mountain gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams Goes to Prison'' _ hey, like the ring of that one
_ is another. Cuba Gooding Jr., as the psychiatrist trying to get
to the bottom of the researcher's mania, decides to uplift the
spirits of all the criminally insane inmates on his patient's cell
block, thus bringing oppressed-little-guy-vs.-heartless-institution
demagogy to surreal new heights.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about ``I'm OK, You're OK, but I Really Prefer Animals to
People''? This film is basically about two lonely, emotionally
distant professionals who reach out and touch one another under
extraordinary circumstances. One of them unapologetically murdered
a bunch of Rwandans, but by gosh, he had his reasons.
</P>
<P>
   When Hopkins' wild-haired, pre-verbally grunting Ethan Powell is
repatriated from Africa to an overcrowded Florida prison, hotshot
university shrink Theo Caulder (Gooding) figures to make his career
_ and a sweet book deal _ by bringing the scientist back to
conversational mode. Relatively fearless _ Caulder gets close to
Powell in ways correctional authorities and anyone who's seen
``Silence of the Lambs'' wouldn't dare to _ the young analyst soon
has the old apeman chattering away.
</P>
<P>
   They bond. Powell's resentful daughter Lyn (``NewsRadio's''
Maura Tierney) can't believe it; dad always kept his distance from
her, even before his simian regression.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Powell eventually tells Caulder what really happened in
that mountainous jungle. Hopkins describes the events with
mesmerizing aplomb, but his vocal dexterity can't save the story
from painful predictability, both narrative-wise and in its
unexamined, nature's nicer than mankind morality. Nevertheless,
Caulder is deeply moved and risks his career on rescuing, rather
than just explaining, his new friend.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, anyone with any sense can see that Powell should
not be rescued. However brilliant he is and emotionally
understandable the circumstances of his crime may have been, he is
still dangerously violent. We may come to understand, feel for,
perhaps even admire Powell, but Hopkins is too good at giving the
man a feral edge for us to ever feel safe about him running around
loose.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jon Turteltaub, however, marshals every trick in the
Hollywood manipulation manual to try to make us feel good about the
prospect. Turteltaub does easily digestible warm glow movies such
as ``Phenomenon'' and ``While You Were Sleeping,'' and he seems to
believe that the same kind of fake sensitivity those movies thrived
on can be as profitably applied to the deeper, much darker subject
matter ``Instinct'' explores.
</P>
<P>
   It can't, despite mighty efforts on Hopkins' and, to a lesser
extent, Gooding's part to take the material as seriously as it
demands. In the final analysis, though, ``Instinct'' only apes real
drama. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1345 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIMBO-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      06-03 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMBO-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT IN A STATE OF `LIMBO' 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Most movies have endings. Some of them aren't
satisfying; many stretch the limits of plausibility. A few films
finish on an ambiguous note, leaving the audience to wonder what
might happen immediately after the final dissolve. But most of the
time, filmmakers throw us a bone and try to tie things up in a way
that sends us shuffling off to the lobby with the feeling that
we've seen a story _ good, bad or mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo'' doesn't have an ending. And it doesn't have much of a
story, either. The advertisements for this dreary disappointment
define the word ``limbo'' as a condition of unknowable outcome.
Hence, filmmaker John Sayles gives us an open-ended finale that is
intended to be haunting and profound, but comes off instead as
precious and somewhat frustrating. (For satisfying ambiguity, check
out ``Besieged.'')
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick would be even more vexing to viewers if they cared
about the story. (Interest begins to wane a good 30 minutes before
the, um, ``conclusion.'') Still, Sayles' failure to resolve the
plot prompted much derision from the audience. A few stayed in
their seats, resolutely believing that the projectionist must have
dropped a reel or that the film would pick up again after the
credits concluded. Wrong and wrong. (A mixed blessing.)
</P>
<P>
   Like other Sayles films such as ``Matewan,'' ``Lone Star'' and
``Passion Fish,'' ``Limbo'' looks at a specific place and the
diverse groups of people who call it home. Here, it's Alaska,
America's last frontier and a significantly under-used setting for
movies. Sadly, Sayles, who filmed mostly around Juneau, doesn't
manage to capture much of the state's character.
</P>
<P>
   The film's first hour mixes character introductions with some
rather heavy-handed sociopolitical commentary. We encounter the
film's three main individuals: Fortysomething singer Donna De
Angelo (Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio) and her beleaguered teen-age
daughter Noelle (Vanessa Martinez) and a sad-sack former fisherman,
Joe Gastineau (Sayles veteran David Strathairn).
</P>
<P>
   They meet at an outdoor wedding. Donna is the singer with the
reception band. It's her last gig with the group; she kisses off
her boyfriend/bandleader with a funny song called ``Better Off
Without You.'' (The formally trained Mastrantonio has a lovely
voice, reminiscent of a shopworn Emmylou Harris.) She gets Joe to
help her move her belongings and, during this initial encounter,
indicates she thinks he's an OK guy. Soon, Joe is showing up at her
lounge shows.
</P>
<P>
   They've all been through the wringer. Sayles makes the point
rather obvious by having a tour guide often describe Alaska as a
place for ``desperate men and desperate times.'' (The sign of a
desperate filmmaker?)
</P>
<P>
   Donna has horrifically poor taste in men, and her relationship
with her daughter has suffered for it. Noelle, a gifted
storyteller, has taken to self-mutilation. Joe gave up fishing 25
years ago after an accident with his boat took two passengers'
lives. His idea of a fun first date? He takes Donna to the mouth of
a river where migrating salmon die.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of peripheral subplots involving slimy
developers looking to turn Alaska into a theme park and yokel
tourists appreciating a synthesized frontier instead of the real
thing. There are spats between old-timers and newcomers and much
talk of second chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo's'' leisurely tone takes a sudden shift in its second
hour when Joe's shady brother (Casey Siemaszko) returns to town
with a dangerous plan. At this point, Sayles leaves his treatises
behind for sheer suspense. Unfortunately, he's out of his element
here, and the movie slogs to its eventual state of limbo rather
uneventfully.
</P>
<P>
   It's all pretty cheerless, the cinematic equivalent of a long
winter's night in Alaska. Certainly it's Sayles' darkest hour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1349 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIMBO-REVIEW-LADN     06-03 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMBO-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by SLANG partners)  The film: ``Limbo'' (R; language). 
The stars: Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, David Strathairn, Vanessa
Martinez. 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by John Sayles. Released by
Screen Gems. 
Running time: Two hours, six minutes. 
Playing: Landmark's Westside Pavilion in West Los Angeles;
Laemmle's Sunset 5 in West Hollywood. 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars 
 
 
By Glenn Whipp, Daily News Film Critic 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most movies have endings. Some of them aren't satisfying; many
stretch the limits of plausibility. A few films finish on an
ambiguous note, leaving the audience to wonder what might happen
immediately after the final dissolve. But most of the time,
filmmakers throw us a bone and try to tie things up in a way that
sends us shuffling off to the lobby with the feeling that we've
seen a story _ good, bad or mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo'' doesn't have an ending. And it doesn't have much of a
story, either. The advertisements for this dreary disappointment
define the word ``limbo'' as a condition of unknowable outcome.
Hence, filmmaker John Sayles gives us an open-ended finale that is
intended to be haunting and profound, but comes off instead as
precious and somewhat frustrating. (For satisfying ambiguity, check
out ``Besieged.'')
</P>
<P>
   The gimmick would be even more vexing to viewers if they cared
about the story. (Interest begins to wane a good 30 minutes before
the, um, ``conclusion.'') Still, Sayles' failure to resolve the
plot prompted much derision from the audience. A few stayed in
their seats, resolutely believing that the projectionist must have
dropped a reel or that the film would pick up again after the
credits concluded. Wrong and wrong. (A mixed blessing.)
</P>
<P>
   Like other Sayles films such as ``Matewan,'' ``Lone Star'' and
``Passion Fish,'' ``Limbo'' looks at a specific place and the
diverse groups of people who call it home. Here, it's Alaska,
America's last frontier and a significantly under-used setting for
movies. Sadly, Sayles, who filmed mostly around Juneau, doesn't
manage to capture much of the state's character.
</P>
<P>
   The film's first hour mixes character introductions with some
rather heavy-handed sociopolitical commentary. We encounter the
film's three main individuals: Fortysomething singer Donna De
Angelo (Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio) and her beleaguered teen-age
daughter Noelle (Vanessa Martinez) and a sad-sack former fisherman,
Joe Gastineau (Sayles veteran David Strathairn).
</P>
<P>
   They meet at an outdoor wedding. Donna is the singer with the
reception band. It's her last gig with the group; she kisses off
her boyfriend/bandleader with a funny song called ``Better Off
Without You.'' (The formally trained Mastrantonio has a lovely
voice, reminiscent of a shopworn Emmylou Harris.) She gets Joe to
help her move her belongings and, during this initial encounter,
indicates she thinks he's an OK guy. Soon, Joe is showing up at her
lounge shows.
</P>
<P>
   They've all been through the wringer. Sayles makes the point
rather obvious by having a tour guide often describe Alaska as a
place for ``desperate men and desperate times.'' (The sign of a
desperate filmmaker?)
</P>
<P>
   Donna has horrifically poor taste in men, and her relationship
with her daughter has suffered for it. Noelle, a gifted
storyteller, has taken to self-mutilation. Joe gave up fishing 25
years ago after an accident with his boat took two passengers'
lives. His idea of a fun first date? He takes Donna to the mouth of
a river where migrating salmon die.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of peripheral subplots involving slimy
developers looking to turn Alaska into a theme park and yokel
tourists appreciating a synthesized frontier instead of the real
thing. There are spats between old-timers and newcomers and much
talk of second chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo's'' leisurely tone takes a sudden shift in its second
hour when Joe's shady brother (Casey Siemaszko) returns to town
with a dangerous plan. At this point, Sayles leaves his treatises
behind for sheer suspense. Unfortunately, he's out of his element
here, and the movie slogs to its eventual state of limbo rather
uneventfully.
</P>
<P>
   It's all pretty cheerless, the cinematic equivalent of a long
winter's night in Alaska. Certainly it's Sayles' darkest hour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
