<HEADER>
A1358 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUENA-VISTA-REVIEW-LA     06-03 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUENA-VISTA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDING SESSION LEADS TO DYNAMIC DOCUMENTARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``The Buena Vista Social Club'' documents one of
life's happy bits of justice. A group of elderly Cuban musicians,
largely forgotten in their home country, band together, record an
album and become an international sensation. Director Wim Winders
follows these masters into the recording studio and concert hall,
recording their stories along with the transforming beauty of music
that may be on the verge of disappearing altogether.
</P>
<P>
   This splendid documentary also captures the faded beauty of a
crumbling Havana, which is filmed by Wenders in a hypersaturated
color that accentuates the island's sultry sensuality. Politics are
never specifically discussed here, but then, it's understood that
the Cuban revolution brushed these men aside in favor of younger
musicians who played different styles. That neglect gives the film
an understated melancholia, a sense of time and talent wasted for
too many years.
</P>
<P>
   American guitar great Ry Cooder originally went to Havana three
years ago to record a traditional album of sones and boleros with
musicians from Cuba and Mali. The Africans didn't make it; they
were hung up with visa problems. So Cooder searched out the
old-timers, discovering that many of them had abandoned their music
because nobody wanted to listen. The album they made, also titled
``The Buena Vista Social Club,'' sold 1.5 million copies, won a
Grammy and turned its musicians into international stars.
</P>
<P>
   The movie shows the group in the recording studio a year later,
preparing an album featuring 71-year-old singer Ibrahim Ferrer.
Wenders also mixes in footage of two concerts, one in Amsterdam,
the other last July at Carnegie Hall along with intimate portraits
of the musicians themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Wenders couldn't have asked for better documentary subjects. The
sweet, shy Ferrer lives in a run-down apartment where he keeps an
altar to St. Lazarus. Ferrer keeps the shrine stocked with rum,
honey and perfume. ``I suppose I like it _ he does, too,'' he says,
adding he knew that some day his fortunes would change because of
this faith.
</P>
<P>
   Pianist Ruben Gonzalez, 80, had not played for years, and many
thought him to be dead or incapacitated by arthritis. Not true _ he
just couldn't afford a piano. Cooder calls Gonzalez ``the greatest
piano soloist'' he has ever heard, and Wenders beautifully reveals
the graceful music from this extraordinary man.
</P>
<P>
   There's also 91-year-old composer and singer Compay Segundo, who
has five children and jokes that he's trying for a sixth; stand-up
bass player Orlando Lopez Vergara (``Cachaito''), nephew of
legendary bassist Israel ``Cachao'' Lopez; and Cooder and his son,
percussionist Joachim, reveling in the kind of collaboration that
comes along maybe once in a musician's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Wenders mostly lets the musicians and their songs speak for
themselves. The movie slowly builds toward its shining climax _ the
Carnegie Hall concert and scenes of the wide-eyed musicians roaming
the streets of New York, amazed at the enormity and wealth of their
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   One moment alone _ the tears in Ferrer's eyes as the standing
ovation from an appreciative Carnegie Hall audience washes over him
_ makes this movie a gem. But Wenders shows us many such scenes of
aching radiance. This movie, like the music these virtuosos made,
is a testament to the power and beauty of art created from passion.
Savor it now and pass it along to someone you love. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
