<HEADLINE>
A ROAR AGAINST TEEN APATHY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Whenever I speak to groups of high school kids, I
always deliver the same message:
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure, politics is boring, and I know you don't care about
it. That's because, for all its warts, the system generally works
pretty well these days. You don't care about politics because life
is good. If you don't pay close attention to the people who hold
down public office, though, they can make life Hell for you.
</P>
<P>
   How do I know that? Because I lived through a particularly
outrageous blunder called the Vietnam War that cost 58,000 American
lives. Trust me, I always tell the kids, you ignore the political
process at your personal peril.
</P>
<P>
   Few of them listen. That's why I was so pleased recently when I
saw a school paper written by an 18-year-old Shenendehowa High
School senior named Amanda Bird. That's a big, regional high school
in the comfortable Albany suburb of Clifton Park. On May 18, school
districts across New York state held school board and budget votes.
Bird went to the polling place at Gowana Junior High School, on the
sprawling Shenendehowa campus, to cast her first ballot ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I had stepped foot into Gowana,'' she wrote, ``I
was lanky with glasses and braces ... Now was my time to shine! I
was about to vote, and people had to listen to my opinion whether
they liked it or not ...
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents directed me to a table where a very sweet senior
citizen talked with me and explained what I had to do. My mother
was allowed to come into the booth with me to `show me the ropes.'
At first, I just stood and stared at the maze of switches in
wonder. Then I focused and snapped down my decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled back the lever, stepped out of the booth and smiled.
My very first voting experience. I had no idea if my votes would
make any difference, but I had done my job. I had done everything
in my personal power to give my opinion ...
</P>
<P>
   ``On the ride home, I pondered the results of the night. I
really had no comprehension what a good turnout was. I noticed that
there were people at every booth and a variety of ages had turned
up to vote. I am not sure what I expected from this experience.
Would it be a life-changing event? In a way, yes, it had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no turning back. Now, I am an adult. I am able to
vote on the presidencies now. (There certainly won't be another
Bill Clinton if I have anything to do about it.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may find it scary to think of me, Amanda Bird as an
adult. They will just have to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am woman, hear me roar.''
</P>
<P>
   You know what? I just love it when they roar like that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0100 </DOCNO>
