<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAWBERRIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'TIS THE SEASON FOR BERRY GOOD EATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As kitchen disasters go, having too many
strawberries isn't one. And after a day in the pick-your-own
fields, just about everyone has too many berries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we find people get more stuff than they want, no matter
what (crop) it is,'' said Dave Bowman, owner of Bowman Orchards in
Malta, N.Y. ``Especially if they bring kids with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Children seem to like berries best just picked, unwashed, in the
field. ``We can tell because they come out with red stains all
around their mouths,'' Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep strawberries fresher longer, cover the unwashed berries
with plastic wrap and place them in the refrigerator as soon as
possible after picking, Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortcakes and pies are favorite uses for strawberries, but here
are a few more ideas:
</P>
<P>
   _ Strawberry-stuffed French toast. Combine 1/2 cup sliced
strawberries, 1 tablespoon sugar and an 8-ounce package of softened
cream cheese in a bowl. Spread the mixture on six slices of French
or Italian bread. Top with six more slices of bread. Combine three
eggs, 1/4 cup milk, 1 teaspoon vanilla and a 1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
in a pie plate. Dip the ``sandwiches'' in egg mixture and fry in
melted butter until golden brown. Serve topped with confectioners'
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strawberry-chocolate milk shakes. This recipe serves two and
was adapted from ``The Ghirardelli Chocolate Cookbook'': Dump 1 cup
sliced strawberries, 1 cup vanilla ice cream, 2 tablespoons
Ghirardelli sweet ground chocolate and cocoa, and 3/4 cup milk into
a blender and hit the puree button until mixture is smooth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Strawberry salad: Combine 1/4 cup oil, 3/4 cup red-wine
vinegar, 2 teaspoons brown sugar, 1 teaspoon garlic salt and 1/2
teaspoon sesame seeds in a jar. Shake well. Place cleaned salad
greens in a bowl. Top with grated carrots and strawberries. Drizzle
with dressing.
</P>
<P>
   FRUIT SOUP
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 6 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the fat-laden, cream-based soups more commonly made from
fruit, this refreshing concoction combines fruit in a clear, spiced
broth. Pair with muffins or popovers for a light lunch. From
``Splendid Soups,'' by James Peterson (Bantam, 1993).
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, cut in half lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4-inch-thick piece fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 star anise, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 (2-inch) cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 quart water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 mango, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 papaya, peeled, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   2 kiwis, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberries, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pineapple, peeled, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   Combine the vanilla bean, ginger, anise, cinnamon, sugar, water
and orange juice in a 4-quart pot with a tight-fitting lid. Bring
mixture to a slow simmer. Cover and cook for 5 minutes. Remove from
heat and let cool. Strain broth through a strainer, discarding
spices.
</P>
<P>
   Combine fruit and syrup in a mixing bowl and chill for an hour.
Serve in chilled bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Note: You can make the broth ahead and chill but for best
results, dice and mix the fruit at the last minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
