<HEADER>
A1381 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PIGEONFORGE-TO     06-03 1627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PIGEONFORGE-TOUR1STTAKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    48 hours in Pigeon Forge: Whirlwind visit to the land of
Dollywood finds that kitsch plus creativity equals fun
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, June6.
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIGEON FORGE, Tenn. _ Twenty five years ago, this strip of U.S.
441 was mostly cow pastures, a place you drove through on the way
to look at the quilt of fall leaves in the Smokies or to watch
candy makers pop out nutty pralines in Gatlinburg. But that tourist
town was geographically limited, walled in on all four sides by the
permanent boundaries of the great Smoky Mountains National Park. As
more people spilled into the area with money in their pockets, tiny
Pigeon Forge, just five miles away, got moving.
</P>
<P>
   A few souvenir stands popped up, such as the wonderfully tacky
Hill-Billy Village, enticing visitors to ``See Moonshine Stills
Free!!'' Then came an amusement park known by many names _ Rebel
Railroad, Gold Rush Junction, Silver Dollar City _ before it was
taken over by country queen (and hometown girl) Dolly Parton.
Dollywood became one of the mountains' most popular attractions,
and soon it begat more motels, which begat outlet malls, which
begat other amusements, which begat more motels. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 11 million tourists spend $615 million here
each year. The greatest number of visitors zoom in from Atlanta,
just four hours beyond the Perimeter up I-75.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekend, I decided to see what it's like to take a
quickie vacation in this fast-growing mountain mecca. Although
there are overwhelming choices in what to see and do, I opted to go
for a mix of as many attractions and food spots as possible (which
often made me feel like I was racing through a supermarket on a
game show shopping spree).
</P>
<P>
   To help you plan your trip, I've assigned grades, but keep this
in mind _ any experience here is as subjective as your favorite
color of neon.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting around: The first thing I notice as I turn onto the
Parkway, the main drag, is the wall of traffic. There are so many
cars inching their way through town it's like watching a mouse
being digested down the belly of a python. There's only one main
road, and merchants have fought plans for a bypass. Most of the
folks sitting in all these cars know what they're getting into: 78
percent are repeat visitors, according to Pigeon Forge Department
of Tourism surveys.
</P>
<P>
   It's immediately clear that a huge part of my weekend is going
to be spent sitting in traffic. I'll have to add at least 30
minutes onto any drive, as it could very well take 45 minutes to an
hour to get from one end of the five-mile Parkway to the other. I
tune in to WDLY-FM, kick back and listen to George Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D- (F if not for WDLY)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging: Thank God I have reservations, because there are few
vacancy signs on the more than five dozen motels that line the
road. I picked the Quality Inn, a five-story motel on the edge of
the great Smoky Mountains National Park, mainly because the chain
always has in-room coffeemakers and cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   If you're expecting valet parking, a bellboy, room service or a
little piece of chocolate on your pillow at night, Pigeon Forge
isn't for you. The fanciest amenity is an in-room Jacuzzi, which
every motel _ even ones that look like they might not have indoor
plumbing _ seems to offer. No doubt that's because 2,500 couples
get married here each year in Vegas-like chapels that dot the
valley.
</P>
<P>
   My room _ with a Jacuzzi that sits in the middle of the floor
like an altar, across from a gas-burning fireplace _ is pricey
compared with most in Pigeon Forge. It's $95 a night, dropping to
$65 on weekdays. But its proximity to the park offers a decent view
of the gateway to the mountains on the tiny balcony. There are
dozens of other motels whose rooms go for as little as $55 on
weekends ($35 Monday through Thursday), allowing parents a fairly
inexpensive family getaway.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dianna Harris from Sugar Hill is here with 32
family members to celebrate her parents' 50th wedding anniversary.
The clan has rented a downstairs meeting room to ``play cards and
get together.'' They spill out into the parking lot as darkness
falls, laughing and sipping soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lee Greenwood's Portrait of America: Greenwood's theater is
the first you spot driving in from the interstate, a hulking
monument in a motel/restaurant complex called River Bluff Landing.
</P>
<P>
   Country music fans will remember Greenwood as the former Vegas
lounge singer who became a Nashville hitmaker in the '80s. In the
'90s, however, the hits dried up. In 1996, he and investors sank
$10 million into this theater and launched a Vegas-style show based
loosely on Greenwood's most famous hit, ``God Bless the U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   The 8 p.m. show is about half full, peopled mostly by tour bus
groups welcomed by a cheery emcee: ``Chester County Seniors, say
hey!'' Then Greenwood, backed by a gaggle of buoyant young singers
and dancers, takes us on a ``red, white and blue tour of America.''
The 2 1/2 hours of song and dance is like fast-forwarding through
``American Bandstand'' and ``That's Entertainment'' simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   A Motown trio gyrates through ``Get Ready.'' Dancers do Agnes de
Mille in a quickie version of ``Oklahoma.'' A group dressed like
the Blues Brothers belts out ``Soul Man.'' Greenwood pops in and
out of the show for the really big numbers, usually as grandiose as
wind sweeping down the plain. At one point, he appears on a balcony
in mask and cape warbling ``Music of the Night'' from ``Phantom of
the Opera.'' Then Greenwood and cast compress ``West Side Story''
into a less-than-10-minute medley. Of course, the grand finale is
``God Bless the U.S.A.'' complete with giant flag and silhouette of
the Iwo Jima flag-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the show comes off as excessive and overproduced, kind
of like eating three hot fudge cakes from Shoney's.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of food, the Chicken Provencal, $14.95, next door at
LG's (Greenwood's restaurant) is surprisingly good, the best meal I
had all weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An unexpected lullaby: I'm back at the motel by 11 p.m. Out my
window somewhere in the night, a bluegrass gospel group is singing,
``When I get to heaven/ I'll put on a crown and walk around/ All
over the promised land.'' Compared to the razzle-dazzle of the
Greenwood show, this is beautiful, as if the spirits of the Smokies
are singing me to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Alan Jackson's Showcar Cafe: The biggest breakfast crowd by
far this morning overflows this round restaurant, which features
``authentic home-
</P>
<P>
   style recipes from Alan's Mama's kitchen.'' This cavernous
eating spot, a temple to the yee-haw country artist from Newnan,
lends new meaning to the term ``cult of personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's pinup face is everywhere _ on T-shirts, jewelry, door
posters, a giant video screen playing nonstop hits, childhood
snapshots in every booth, even golf balls. I almost expect to see
Jackson's blond mane materializing in the biscuits and gravy like
the Shroud of Turin.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Mahoney from Surgoinsville, Tenn., making her ``seventh
or eighth'' trip to Pigeon Forge this year, says she's here today
``to see the man with the perfect body. Ooooh, I love them legs!''
</P>
<P>
   Holy cow. Turns out Jackson is indeed due to make his first-ever
appearance at the restaurant. By the time he launches into a
20-minute concert in the parking lot, fans and traffic virtually
shut down the Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+ (but only if
</P>
<P>
   you're a Jackson fan)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Applewood Farmhouse Restaurant: Sorry, even Mama's pancakes
aren't worth the crowd at Jackson's place. Instead, I head over to
this quaint little white clapboard house that sits off the main
road overlooking the Little Pigeon River. The waitress (dressed in
gingham, natch) seats us immediately, then hauls out a chuckwagon
full of country ham, grits, biscuits, applesauce muffins, apple
fritters and apple butter for just $7.25. Even Granny would be
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Outlet shopping: Dollywood may get most of the publicity, but
Pigeon Forge tourism statistics show that most people come here to
shop at the town's six outlet malls, boasting more than 200 stores.
These complexes feature the usual suspects: Anne Klein, Eddie
Bauer, Coach, Geoffrey Beene, Nike, Samsonite, Corning/Revere, the
Gap. You can find most of this merchandise within a stone's throw
of Atlanta, but there's just something about being on vacation that
makes you want to fill your kitchen cabinets with every possible
piece of
</P>
<P>
   Pfaltzgraff.
</P>
<P>
   I stop into the one discount store I've never seen before: the
Cross Outlet, under the orange-roofed Z-Buda Outlet Mall, just a
couple of doors down from Mountain Man Military Supplies. Yes, you
can actually buy just about any kind of cross of Protestant design
or taste imaginable here _ puff, 3-D, the coveted white gold, ones
with little pink roses twirling up the sides, as well as cross
rings and earrings.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A (for the overall
</P>
<P>
   outlet experience)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hill-Billy Village: Along with Pigeon Forge Pottery, this is
the town's oldest tourist attraction, a yellow-and-red trinket
market straight out of Al Capp's Dogpatch, a kitschy shrine of
political incorrectness. You can buy stuffed Smoky Mountain black
bears, Indian tomahawks, Dixie flag wall hangings, ceramic praying
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Burl, a radiologist from Berea, Ky., tries on a black
felt hillbilly hat with a corncob pipe stuck in the brim. ``It's
what you have to buy when you come to the Smokies,'' she says and
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
