<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-03 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER ABSURDITY FROM A STUPID WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There are countless absurdities in the
undeclared war we are waging against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   They range from the incredible _ military maps with the Chinese
embassy's old address on them _ to the overlooked. For example,
this by David Rieff in the New Republic magazine:
</P>
<P>
   ``The stupidest thing about this stupid war is that, for all
their talk of primordial attachment to Kosovo, almost no Serb
actually wants to live there.''
</P>
<P>
   To the pile of absurdities, add a phrase that already has become
a cliche in the language of the Kosovo ``situation.'' It has been
uttered by everyone from President Clinton and British Prime
Minister Tony Blair to the red-hots who regularly call in to radio
talk shows. Most recently, Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif., said it
while discussing the deployment of NATO ground troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Like the bombing, Tauscher said, ground forces may be part of
what it takes to cause ``Mr. Milosevic to come to his senses.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the evil and black-hearted Slobodan Milosevic will abide
by the international peace agreement and end the conflict, as his
government pledged on Thursday to do.
</P>
<P>
   He will order the withdrawal of his soldiers from Kosovo. He'll
call a halt to the brutal and immoral miniholocaust that he has
waged to ``cleanse'' Kosovo of ethnic Albanians. And he'll do
nothing to stop the installation of gun-toting peacekeepers who can
oversee the safe return of Kosovo Albanians to their looted and
burned-out homes.
</P>
<P>
   Why will he do this? Perhaps one sortie too many of U.S.
aircraft will have taken out one too many Belgrade power station or
one too many of the summer homes of one too many of Milosevic's
closest pals.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Milosevic's toughest general will have looked him in the
eye and told him that the latest inventory shows that the Yugoslav
army hasn't enough ammo and facilities to defeat the Campfire Girls
in a sustained ground war.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that NATO's missiles and soldiers will not cause,
however, is ``Mr. Milosevic'' to ``come to his senses.''
</P>
<P>
   Cave in? Capitulate? Cry ``uncle''? Promise to be a good boy and
a model war crimes defendant _ all the while crossing his fingers
behind his back? He could do any of these.
</P>
<P>
   But come to his senses? How can anyone _ even a congresswoman _
say such a thing with a straight face?
</P>
<P>
   Every time I hear another somber pol repeat the phrase, the same
metaphoric image leaps to mind: Distinguished-looking men and women
stand around a dog house, beating and battering its roof and walls
with baseball bats. Ten feet away, a vicious pitbull with rabies
sits and watches them.
</P>
<P>
   When someone asks the people what they are doing, they point to
the dog and say, ``We're trying to make him come to his senses.''
</P>
<P>
   If people like Tauscher truly believe that this bloody,
often-backfiring NATO campaign can actually bring a mean,
calculating SOB like Milosevic to his senses, our government is in
worse shape than I ever dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't believe it but they keep using the phrase because
it sounds nicer and more civilized than something like ``quit,''
``knuckle under'' or ``surrender,'' they need to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade is in tatters; much of Eastern Europe already feels the
economic reversal that the NATO air raids have caused, and hundreds
of thousands of the very people we want to help are living in
abject misery in refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't ``the situation'' in Kosovo use one less absurdity?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1382 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PIGEONFORGE-TO     06-03 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PIGEONFORGE-TOUR2NDTAKE </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   PIGEON FORGE, Tenn.:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Carbo's Police Museum: The sign screams ``See Buford Pusser's
Death Car.'' I have to stop. And sure enough, the remains of the
famous Tennessee sheriff's Corvette Stingray are here, under glass,
burnt to a crisp. So are his whup-ass sticks, and his XL
navy-and-white polyester shirt. For the $5.88 admission you can
also see a colossal collection of police hats, badges, radar guns,
billy clubs, framed photos of George Wallace and ``confiscated
items'' such as an ice pick made out of a wooden Coke bottle
opener. The whole place is lit by eerie red lights. I watch
``Cops,'' but this is a little too creepy for even my quirky
tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Alabama Grill: Another celebrity theme restaurant, this
one a monument to the country group Alabama. Pictures of the boys
from Fort Payne are everywhere, including a massive mural in the
front lobby that looks like something painted by high school kids
on the gymnasium wall. There are lots of photos of other
celebrities and their memorabilia, such as a framed shot of Irlene
Mandrell on the cover of Gun World magazine. The food is mostly
burger fare. Somehow, this doesn't seem as much fun as Jackson's
joint, but maybe my home's not in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stages West Western Store: Want to get married but have
nothing to wear? This store with the Dodge City facade boasts an
entire wall of white, Western-wear wedding dresses with fringe for
$451. There's also a good collection of Western arts and crafts. I
found a pair of great pillow shams mimicking the old Roy Rogers
bedspreads from the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Comedy Barn: This huge, pink-and-yellow barn looks like
something off the set of ``Hee Haw,'' probably because it was the
home of the old cornfield comic himself, Archie Campbell, who used
to perform here during breaks from filming the TV show. It now
presents a comedy revue with skits so corny they could have been
written by Porter Wagoner bassist-comic ``Speck'' Rhodes (remember
the guy with the bolo hat and blacked-out teeth?). There's also
country music, a ventriloquist, fire jugglers, Arnold the
Mind-Reading Pig, a guy dressed up like Granny Clampett who plays
``Orange Blossom Special'' on the fiddle, and a puppet named Duffy
who hosts the whole shebang.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, this is cheesier than anything Kraft
packages, the equivalent of a clown trying desperately to make kids
pay attention at a Saturday morning birthday party. But halfway
into the show, I find myself laughing anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Even when comic Stephen Knowles yanks 60-year-old John Cory
onstage, straps a Julio Iglesias mask on his face and makes him
lip-sync to ``To All the Girls I've Loved Before.'' The Marietta
convenience store owner is so game, he buys the souvenir video of
this very show for $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tastebuds Cafe: On a tip, I head up Ware's Valley Road to what
has been touted as Pigeon Forge's only gourmet restaurant. But it
doesn't depart from the mood entirely _ Tastebuds is in a
double-wide trailer. This tiny eatery, owned and operated by chef
Giacomo ``Jock'' Lijoi, turns out to be an intimate, tasty and
entertaining departure from Pigeon Forge's usual.
</P>
<P>
   Waiter Donnie Rudder humors us with his Elvis impersonation _
``Thank you, thank you very much'' _ and cajoles the diners at the
dozen tables to shout ``hello'' to customers as they walk in the
door. And the food, continental cuisine with some regional fare
including grilled pork chops, is delicious. Plus, since Pigeon
Forge is dry, you can brown bag a bottle of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Louise Mandrell Theater: As the sun sets, it's time to head
back down the Parkway to Mandrell's ornate palace, where a huge
neon sign constantly flashes the claim: ``The Smokies Most
Spectacular Show!!'' They use a lot of exclamation points here in
Pigeon Forge, and Mandrell's three-hour fiesta is the biggest one
of all. It turns out to be one of the best halftime shows I've ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Mandrell saws on her fiddle until smoke comes pouring out
(literally). She does backflips while swing dancing. She dons a
camouflage military uniform and scales netting like she's heading
to Parris Island. The show-
</P>
<P>
   stopper is when Mandrell shimmies into a NASCAR uniform and
drives a race car onstage, where it is hoisted in the air only to _
blam! _ disappear in an explosion of lights and smoke. The
extravaganza ends, of course, with a patriotic tribute and huge
American flag.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I would've preferred fire twirling.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Robert F. Thomas Church in the Valley: Pigeon Forge is
unusually silent this morning, probably since so many of the people
who visit are religious. So I decide to go to church _ at, of all
places, Dollywood.
</P>
<P>
   If you could draw a picture of the Church in the Wildwood, this
would be it. The tiny wooden country chapel sits in the middle of
the sprawling amusement park like an anachronism, complete with
steeple and bell, wooden pews and a tinny upright piano. Full-time
chaplain Pete Owen hoists a girl on his shoulders to pull the long
rope that rings out the start of the service, a nondenominational,
30-minute worship program that makes me flash back to the days so
long ago when I would sit with my Granny in the amen corner of the
Bakerville (Tenn.) Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   We sing ``When the Roll Is Called Up Yonder,'' ``Just a Little
Talk With Jesus'' and ``Blessed Assurance.'' We pray for the sick _
Fran recovering from surgery, Richard having problems with his
heart _ then hear a short sermon. We close with ``God Be With You
'Til We Meet Again.'' After a day and a half of the gaudy and
glitzy, this is as refreshing as cold mountain water. The best show
in Pigeon Forge.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A+
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Country Tonite: This is one of the few musical productions
offering a Sunday matinee, so I drop in. It features no name acts,
doesn't advertise heavily, and no one makes a race car disappear.
Still, ``Country Tonite'' provides some of the weekend's best
entertainment. The young cast of singers and dancers serves up a
kind of country version of ``Your Hit Parade,'' where the songs are
the stars rather than the singers _ ``This Kiss,'' ``Honey, I'm
Home,'' ``I Hate Her'' and ``There's Your Trouble.'' If you're a
fan of contemporary country music, you'll enjoy it as much as
listening to a good country station on a long car trip.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Blackwood Quartet: My last stop is at Eddie's Heart &AMP; Soul
Cafe, where legendary gospel star Ron Blackwood is offering a
no-frills evening of Southern gospel music and dinner. In fact,
Blackwood and his fellow vocalists sing to a tape piping out of
what looks to be an industrial strength karaoke machine. While the
performance should rely less on contemporary tunes and stick to the
traditional, Eddie's turns out to have a souvenir shop rich with
gospel tapes, books and posters.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   As I pull out of town, I pass by a stark black-and-white sign
that asks: ``Do you know where you're going?'' Conveniently enough,
it provides an answer: ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I'm going home to the city. But my 48 hours in Pigeon
Forge turned out to be much more fun than I had anticipated, a
blend of the crass and the creative rolled up in the beauty of the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's Sunday, and I've been to church, I must be blessed. I
don't even hit traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
