<HEADER>
A1384 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PIGEONFORGE06-     06-03 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PIGEONFORGE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pigeon Forge, Tenn., is pure, mindless entertainment _ and
millions flock here every year
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIGEON FORGE, Tenn. _ As soon as I hit the city limits sign of
this tiny tourist town at the foothills of the Smoky Mountains,
it's apparent that I've forgotten something essential for a weekend
trip to Pigeon Forge: a folding lawn chair.
</P>
<P>
   It's dusk, and hundreds of people are pulling their cars out of
the bottleneck of traffic that runs up and down this valley,
popping the hatches on their sport-utility vehicles and setting up
webbed patio seats side by side facing the highway. It's a somewhat
bizarre ritual that seems to be as natural here as the blinking
arrival of the lightning bugs. This curious gantlet stretches the
length of the five-mile Parkway (as the main drag is called) as if
people are sitting waiting for a parade or a road race to begin.
</P>
<P>
   But no floats, no runners or even marching bands are headed this
way. It soon becomes clear that the show, the event, that everyone
is there to see is Pigeon Forge itself.
</P>
<P>
   The entire town is a carnival midway of neon signs, cheap
motels, in-room Jacuzzis, pancake houses, souvenir stands,
vaudeville-style shows (with acts such as Arnold the Mind-Reading
Pig), loud go-carts, outlet malls, Elvis impersonators, stores that
sell Christmas decorations in the middle of summer, and flashing
arcade games. Hanging over it all are cranes from which people drop
toward earth at the end of a bungee cord. They dangle over this
canyon of neon and concrete like a nightcrawler stuck on a hook at
the end of a fishing line.
</P>
<P>
   The people who come here and enjoy it _ including those folks in
folding chairs by the side of the road _ are unapologetic in their
pursuit of populist pleasure. Purist Tourists. They love this Bible
Belt Las Vegas, a city of spontaneous generation that plopped out
of the Smokies three decades ago like Darwin's fish sprouting legs.
A working man's Magic Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   As a tourist destination, it provokes sharply polarized
feelings; just mention the place in a crowd and see how many eyes
roll. Although the community sits smack in the middle of one of the
South's most profoundly spiritual sights _ the Smoky Mountains
rising through the mist like silent humpback whales _ there's
virtually nothing natural within the Pigeon Forge city limits. No
museums to distract you (unless you count the one where you can
gawk at Sheriff Buford Pusser's burned-up death car), no historic
sights or self-guided walking tours. I didn't spot one gourmet
coffee stand, and everything pretty much shuts down by 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But let's set aside the elitist viewpoint for a few minutes and
reconsider why 11 million people visit Pigeon Forge every year.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the car at the intersection of the Parkway and
Dollywood Lane at Traffic Light 8 (there are 10 in all, and people
navigate around town by referring to the numbers), I flash back to
when I was a kid let loose at the fair each fall in rural Middle
Tennessee. The grown-ups would stick change in our hands and,
inevitably, my cousin Bilbo would head straight to an arcade game
called the Steam Shovel, into which he would feed nickels,
trancelike. The trick was to lower a set of metal jaws onto a pile
of trinkets _ beads, plastic rings, whistles _ and try to haul out
as many as possible. The diversion from our rather humdrum lives
was so intense that Bilbo would spend all his money within an hour,
then cry the rest of the afternoon because the experience was over.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Pigeon Forge is: seductively mindless
entertainment. If you can accept these terms and conditions, take
the town for exactly what it is and nothing more, and let your hair
down (or stuff it up under a University of Tennessee Big Orange
cap), a summer trip here can be a heck of a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
