<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TENNEVENTS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upcoming events around Tennesee
 &HT;    EDs: Embaroed for Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  JUNE
</P>
<P>
   Friday-Saturday: 23rd annual Dulcimer &AMP; Harp Festival, Folk
Center of the Smokies, Cosby. Come to jam, learn to play or just
listen to the music. Also homemade food, crafts and nightly
concerts. 423-625-9675.
</P>
<P>
   Friday-June 19: Riverbend Festival, Ross' Landing and downtown,
Chattanooga. More than 100 musical acts play on five stages along
the restored riverfront district. Also, sporting events, family
activities, fine arts exhibits, food and fireworks. 423-265-4112 or
423-756-2212.
</P>
<P>
   June 14-19: International Country Music Fan Fair, Nashville.
Country music fans mix and mingle with their favorite stars. Also,
35 hours of live shows, exhibits, autograph sessions, concerts,
celebrity games, photo sessions and the Grand Masters Fiddling
Championship. 615-889-7503
</P>
<P>
   June 19-20: 53rd annual Rhododendron Festival, Roan Mountain
State Park. Native arts and crafts, music, food and wildlife tours
at the 600-acre rhododendron garden. 423-772-3303.
</P>
<P>
   June 23-27: Chet Atkins' Musicians Days, Nashville. Musicians
from around the world gather to demonstrate their craft at a
variety of indoor and outdoor venues. 615-256-9596.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JULY
</P>
<P>
   July 2-3: Official State and National Championship Smithville
Fiddlers' Jamboree and Crafts Festival, Smithville. Old-time
Appalachian music and dance competitions and juried craft show.
615-597-8500.
</P>
<P>
   July 3: Patriot Festival, Pigeon Forge. Entertainment, speakers
and fireworks. 1-800-251-9100.
</P>
<P>
   July 3-5: Historic Jonesborough Days, Jonesborough. Crafters,
arts and crafts exhibits, parade, fireworks, Southern cooking,
entertainment and clogging in the state's oldest town. 423-753-5281
</P>
<P>
   July 4: July Fourth Celebration and Anvil Shoot, Museum of
Appalachia, Norris. ``Shooting'' of the anvil, music, crafters and
demonstrations of old-time activities such as sassafras tea
brewing, sheep herding and rail splitting. 423-494-7680 or
423-494-0514.
</P>
<P>
   July 8-10: Lauderdale County Tomato Festival, Ripley. Arts and
crafts, food vendors, barbecue contest, tomato tasting, live bands
and lots of local tomatoes and vegetables. 901-635-9541.
</P>
<P>
   July 9-11: Uncle Dave Macon Days, Cannonsburgh Village,
Murfreesboro. Old-time music competitions, juried arts and crafts
show, historic photo exhibit, heritage activities for children,
shaped-note singing and impromptu jam and singing sessions.
615-893-2371 or 1-800-716-7560
</P>
<P>
   July 23-25: Folk Medicine Festival, Red Boiling Springs. Folk
heritage demonstrations, music, children's entertainment, arts and
crafts. 615-699-2180.
</P>
<P>
   July 23-Aug. 1: Annual Gatlinburg Craftsmen Fairs, Gatlinburg. A
gathering of more than 125 crafters from across the country. Also,
country and bluegrass music shows daily. (Also, Sept. 3-6, Oct.
6-24.) 423-436-7479.
</P>
<P>
   July 30-31: St. Patrick's Irish Picnic, McEwen. Barbecue with
entertainment, crafts, games and more at the St. Patrick's Picnic
Grounds. 931-582-3417 or 931-582-3986.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 7-8: Cherokee Days of Recognition, Red Clay State Historic
Park, Cleveland. Food, song and dance of the Cherokees.
423-478-0339.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 7-8: Franklin Jazz Festival, Franklin. Continuous jazz,
Dixieland, big band and headliner acts on the restored square of
this 19th-century downtown area. 615-790-5541.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 20-21: Mountain Heritage Days Rodeo, Mountain City. Under
the lights in Ralph Stout Park. 423-727-5800.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 21: Goody's Headache Powder 500, Bristol Motor Speedway,
Bristol. NASCAR Winston Cup Series race. 423-764-1161.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 26-Sept. 4: Tennessee Walking Horse National Celebration,
Shelbyville. More than 2,000 Tennessee walking horses ride for
prizes and awards. 931-684-5915.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 27-28: 17th annual Smoky Mountain Fiddlers Convention,
Loudon. Bluegrass bands, fiddle, banjo, guitar, clogging and buck
dancing competition. Also, arts and crafts and Memories on Mulberry
Antique &AMP; Quilt Show. 423-458-5956.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 28-29: Air Show '99, Arnold Field, Halls. Veterans are
special guests at this two-day show featuring warbirds from the B17
to the T-6, modern aerobatics, pyrotechnics with strafing and bomb
runs, helicopters, vendors and massive WWII military vehicle
exhibits. 901-365-9541.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 3-6: Italian Street Fair, Nashville. An extravaganza
featuring Italian food, marketplace, carnival rides, entertainment,
arts and crafts and games. 615-255-5600.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 10-19: Tennessee State Fair, Nashville. Exhibits, midway
rides, animal and variety shows, live stage presentations,
livestock, agricultural and craft competitions, game booths and
food. 615-862-8980.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 11-12: Germantown Festival, Germantown. An arts and crafts
fair with rides, games, food, entertainment and car displays.
901-757-9212.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 16-Nov. 1: Smoky Mountain Harvest Festival, Gatlinburg,
Pigeon Forge and Sevierville. Harvest decorations, special events
and craft shows. 1-800-267-7088.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
