<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1418 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUPERT-EVERETT-ON-GAY     06-03 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUPERT-EVERETT-ON-GAY-LABEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT'S PEAK  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE B&AMP;W PHTO is available ELECTRONICALLY by E-MAIL. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By MERLE GINSBERG 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Rupert Everett can just see the headline now. Hollywood's most
prominent openly gay actor playing a royal sprite in a glam film
version of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream''? What else but ``King of
the Fairies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then at least I'll have graduated from 'Queen of the
Fairies,''' the British actor quips dryly during breakfast at
Hugo's in Los Angeles. ``I'm moving up the fairy ladder, don't you
think? It's a laugh. And by the by, I did play Titania in the
school play.''
</P>
<P>
   In a roller-coaster screen career spanning over 15 years,
Everett has learned to deal with the vagaries of fame with sharp
wit, droll insouciance and the supreme confidence that comes from
his lanky good looks. So it's easy to understand how he landed the
role of Oberon in Michael Hoffman's all-star ``Dream,'' as well as
that of the idly rich Lord Goring in a new film version of Oscar
Wilde's ``An Ideal Husband'' _ a character Wilde seems to have
based on himself. Miramax will release that film, costarring Cate
Blanchett, Jeremy Northam, Minnie Driver and Julianne Moore, in
late June.
</P>
<P>
   And in early July, the 40-year-old actor will play the
swashbuckling villain of a Disney kid-oriented extravaganza called
``Inspector Gadget.'' He doesn't do much to dispel the notion that
that's most likely his money gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``But life's a money gig, don't you think?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's last major outing, ``My Best Friend's Wedding,'' was
certainly his biggest grosser ever _ it made about $300 million
worldwide _ and it turned him into a bankable Hollywood star after
years of toiling in lukewarm films with intermittent stabs at pop
music (a dismal failure) and novel writing (``Hello, Darling, Are
You Working?'' and ``The Hairdresser of St. Tropez'').
</P>
<P>
   Everett bounded to fame in the mid-'80s in ``Another Country''
and ``Dance With a Stranger.'' But except for a brief,
well-received turn in ``The Madness of King George,'' it was
downhill from there _ until he walked away with his few scenes in
``My Best Friend's Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I wasn't nominated for an Oscar, I was vaguely
disappointed,'' he says of that experience. ``After all that hype,
my expectations had been high. But right around then, all these
movies that are coming out fell into place. And I did that bit in
`Shakespeare in Love''' _ an unbilled stint as Christopher Marlowe,
Shakespeare's playwrighting competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I saw Glenda Jackson do it in Ken Russell's `The
Boyfriend,' I thought it was very glamorous to go unbilled,'' he
says. ``I'd really wanted to play Shakespeare, but they'd cast Joe
(Fiennes).''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's cell phone rings now and then, each time with the same
woman _ whom he drippingly calls ``darling'' and whom he'd be
squiring to dinner that evening _ on the other end. \
</P>
<P>
   He won't identify her, but it's apparently his new best friend,
Madonna, whom he met way back through Sean Penn. The two start
shooting ``The Next Best Thing'' in late May in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy here in L.A. at the moment,'' he says, ``and so
is my dog (Mo, a black lab). I was very unhappy when I lived here
until a few years ago. I was always a big failure. It's not a town
to be a failure in. You have a really victimy, horrible existence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a career windfall a little bit later in life, you
really appreciate it,'' he continues. ``I know these moments don't
last forever. I'll probably be caught with my pants down at the
George Michael memorial toilet in Beverly Hills one of these
days!''
</P>
<P>
   Everett might claim to love Los Angeles, but he maintains
residences in Miami and New York's West Village, and he still jets
back to his former home cities of Paris and London now and then.
</P>
<P>
   But his devotion to Mo prevents him from moving back to England,
with its stringent canine quarantine, and he has little good to say
about Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most boring, backward, Third World country and city
you can possibly imagine,'' he laments. ``Who cares about the
architecture? You can see that in a book. It was fun and sexy in
the '70s, then ruined when that hideous, horrible Mitterrand got
into power. He ruined France, made it this awful, bourgeois Third
World country. They don't know what's going on outside their own
stupid country _ they are so insular and proud.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the jet-set existence and contrary to his reputation
(he was expelled from London's Central School of Speech and Drama
for ``insubordination''), Everett says he's never really been too
wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a very middle-class background _ it's saved me
from autodestruction at many times in my life,'' he says. ``When I
lived in Paris, I went to the same place every night. In L.A., I
stay home all the time and I work out every day. I travel all the
time, but when I get to a new town, I never go anywhere new. I know
that's kind of narrow-minded, but I've always been a bit like that.
I fear it's creeping middle age.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he is relentlessly cast as a debauched aristocrat.
Everett doesn't see his plummy upper-class delivery as having
served him all that well, however _ particularly in his
shortest-lived career: that of singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pop star thing didn't work, probably because I didn't have
the originality necessary for it,'' he says. ``I was too tied to an
image of upper-class English carelessness. If I had thought about
it more carefully, I might have done `hoo-ray rap': upper-class
rap. But I find this upper-class thing very boring.''
</P>
<P>
   As Oberon, Everett is an aristocrat once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of laughs doing it; I was terribly amused,'' he
says, but adds, ``One problem was, the whole movie, I'm in a
loincloth _ which I didn't love. Showing the whole of your body's
always a lot harder than showing off a little of it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hollywood still dishes about Everett as the first openly
gay movie star, that once-incendiary issue now causes him to erupt
in a dramatic yawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such old news,'' he says. ``It hasn't shown up in any of
my recent parts. I haven't played gay since `My Best Friend's
Wedding.' The gay scripts I get are often filled with bad
characters and are tragically bad,'' he complains. ``The one I'm
doing now is a script I rewrote myself _ a very good story, but
again, the gay character was totally stereotypical in a very dull
way.''
</P>
<P>
   He's referring to ``The Next Best Thing,'' the story of two old
friends, played by him and Madonna, who get smashed one day and
find themselves having sex. When she becomes pregnant, they bring
up baby together _ for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a great admirer of Madonna's,'' Everett says.
``I totally believe in her as an actress and as this character in
the film. She's been disparaged as an actress because we're all so
conscious of her image. The thing with acting is, you're a good
actor in the public eye one day, and the next day, you're a bad
one.''
</P>
<P>
   While he's refreshingly up-front on most topics, there's still
one thing Everett remains uncharacteristically tight-lipped about:
his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   He may have shouted from the rooftops that he's gay, but he's
never so much as whispered the name of someone he's involved with.
Nor is he ever photographed with a significant other _ save his
dog, who often flies on the Concorde with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A personal life's still a personal life, isn't it?'' he says.
``Well, I promise you, I don't have one. I'm one of those tragic
people who just climbs into a refrigerator when they go home at
night. I don't want to be a leaflet or a manual. I want to keep it
to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses for a moment before adding, ``Or I just don't have
enough of a life for anyone to care.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have no sympathy for anyone trying to `out' people,'' he
continues. ``I hate the whole outing thing. I saw Boy George on
television talking about George Michael _ disgusting! Who wants to
see that big blob on the telly? Too bad there's not a closet big
enough for him that hide in.''
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Merle Ginsberg is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
