<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT YOU STUDY IN COLLEGE MAY BE MORE IMPORTANT THAN WHERE YOU GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's some good economic news for college graduates _ and
their parents _ who recently received their sheepskin: Your
earnings should be at least 62 percent higher than that of your
peers who have only a high school education.
</P>
<P>
   College grads earning advanced degrees face even better news.
The average annual salary of a bachelor's degree holder is around
$48,300 a year, but those with a master's degree earn $54,300
annually, and doctoral degree holders have mean annual salaries of
$67,500. Lawyers and doctors do even better, of course, earning
more than $90,000 on average.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the many facts gleaned from the U.S. census
and other studies in the new book ``The College Majors Handbook:
The Actual Jobs, Earnings, and Trends for Graduates of 60 College
Majors'' (Jist Works, Indianapolis, 619 pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Though numerous books rate colleges and universities, this book
focuses on perhaps an even more important decision than where to go
to school: what to study once you get there.
</P>
<P>
   As the authors write: ``Clearly the choice of undergraduate
major has a powerful impact on the earnings and, ultimately, the
living standards of college graduates. ... The skills and abilities
they acquire in college have lasting and even lifetime influences
on their labor market outcomes, their status in the community,
their happiness on the job, and their standard of living.''
</P>
<P>
   The three authors are all professors at Northwestern University.
Neeta Fogg and Paul Harrington are economists at Northwestern's
Center for Labor Market Studies. Thomas Harrington is a counseling
psychologist who teaches vocation psychology and career counseling.
</P>
<P>
   They have pooled their research and studies to take specific
looks at 60 of the most sought-after college degrees, from
aerospace engineering to visual arts.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the information provided is from the National Survey of
College Graduates, which sampled more than 148,000 college
graduates to gather data on education, employment and earnings
experience. The survey is the largest and most comprehensive study
of college graduates ever conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The information provided for each major includes salaries,
occupations, on-the-job training and employment outlook in a
detailed discussion. Behind the numbers, the authors point out
interesting patterns about just what happens to people after
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, those who choose dramatic arts, a popular major,
may find themselves on unforeseen career paths after graduation,
the authors write. According to the studies in the book, less than
20 percent of dramatic arts graduates work in jobs closely related
to their field of study. An additional 20 percent actually work in
jobs that do not require a college degree. Salaries of dramatic
arts majors also run more than $10,000 less than those of the
average college graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The employment outlook for this group looks equally grim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dramatic arts majors will likely continue to have difficulty
in the labor market in the future and will more likely work in
part-time positions, be unemployed, and work in a job that does not
require a college degree,'' the authors write.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, those receiving a bachelor's degree in chemistry
are much more likely to be chemists, with more than 70 percent
working in jobs related to their major. Their average annual salary
of $55,000 is about 14 percent more than that of the average
bachelor's degree holder. Also, a whopping 56 percent of all
chemistry majors go on to obtain advanced degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The book says that, although the overall demand for college
graduates is expected to increase nearly 25 percent between 1996
and 2006, the demand for chemists is expected to grow about 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers certainly don't mean everything when making the weighty
decision of what to do with your life, but this book can bring a
heavy dose of reality to what happens after you receive that
diploma. The book should be required reading for anyone entering
college.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   ``Generations: Planning Your Legacy''
</P>
<P>
   By Robert A. Esperti and Renno L. Peterson
</P>
<P>
   Esperti Peterson Institute, $49.95
</P>
<P>
   If you need a thorough read on how to set up your estate for
your heirs, this 608-page book by attorneys Robert Esperti and
Renno Peterson covers the waterfront, offering descriptions of the
latest trends in this area. Wills and probate are no longer the
most important aspects of estate planning. The book includes
chapters on revocable living trusts, asset protection and
charitable planning.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Patent Searching Made Easy: How to Do Patent Searches on the
Internet and in the Library''
</P>
<P>
   By David Hitchcock
</P>
<P>
   Nolo Press, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   You don't necessarily need a lawyer or professional patent
searcher to find out if your new idea or product has already been
done before. This book provides a step-by-step process for checking
out product patents using the World Wide Web for those listings
after 1971, and the Patent and Trademark Depository Libraries for
those listings before 1971. Author David Hitchcock is also a
physicist, engineer and patent searching expert. Nolo is the
pre-eminent publisher of self-help legal guides.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven Steps to Fearless Speaking''
</P>
<P>
   By Lilyan Wilder
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   As a consultant to broadcast journalists at NBC, CBS, ABC and
CNN, as well as a host of other public speakers in politics,
business and entertainment, Lilyan Wilder has earned a strong
reputation in speech coaching. Rather than focus on performance
techniques such as your vocal pitch or eye contact, Wilder instead
discusses the more human aspect of conveying a message in this
book.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
