<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKATING-CHAMPIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMPIONS ON ICE INTRODUCES PROMISING NEW TALENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By BETTY KWONG 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It all started with ``Twinkle, Twinkle Little
Star.''
</P>
<P>
   A tiny speck of a girl at age 6, Naomi Nari Nam swizzled her way
across the ice and jumped in place to the tune of the kiddies'
ditty.
</P>
<P>
   The audience applauded, and the judges declared it a winning
performance.
</P>
<P>
   And so began Nam's figure skating career, one that's taken her
from that first competition at an Orange County ice rink to the
1999 U.S. National Championships, where she earned a silver medal,
skating fans' adoration and the chance to tour with the world's
best.
</P>
<P>
   When the spotlight goes on at the Los Angeles Sports Arena on
Saturday afternoon, you'll see the 13-year-old Irvine, Calif.,
sprite performing along with world-famous skating stars like
Michelle Kwan, Oksana Baiul, Todd Eldredge and Alexei Yagudin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big tour, and it's my first time. I'm so excited,''
said Nam, who's scheduled to perform in 13 shows on the West Coast
leg of the 45-city tour. ``I want to make a good impression so I
can come back next year.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll skate to an aptly named tune, ``Getting to Know You.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from `The King and I' _ the cartoon!'' she says,
giggling. ``It's a very cheery song.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the cast of this summer's John Hancock Champions on Ice
Tour showcases a lot of new names that spectators are just
beginning to get to know.
</P>
<P>
   There's new energy emerging out of this post-Olympic season,
with talents like Nam and West Los Angeles' Trifun Zivanovic, the
1999 national men's silver medalist, stealing some of the thunder
from the established stars of the amateur skating world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to attend the shows as a young kid with my parents and
just be in awe of all the performers. And now I get to be in it
myself, so it's pretty cool,'' said Zivanovic, 23, who trains in
Culver City and teaches skating in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   Zivanovic, who's scheduled to perform on the tour's three
Southern California stops, plans to skate to Queen's ``Crazy Little
Thing Called Love,'' a program he learned only four weeks ago. ``I
just want to go out there and have fun and entertain people.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than just an opportunity to entertain, the show also
becomes an unexpected training ground for many young skaters, said
Tom Collins, owner, producer and the man at the show's helm for 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always say they learn as an amateur so much on a tour,
because they skate at least five shows a week in front of a large
audience,'' Collins said. ``They can try some new footwork ... see
if the audience likes it, and if it's not right, they can correct
it. They can try their new jumps _ their triples and their quads.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right, quadruple-rotation jumps. Exhibition skating shows
used to be anticlimatic follow-ups to exciting competition
performances. Instead of programs packed with difficult maneuvers
designed to leave judges drooling, skaters opted for simpler and
safer program elements.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore, Collins said. Skating-savvy audiences are demanding
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could fool them 10 years ago. Now you can't fool them,''
he said. ``On the tour, a lot of times they used to do numbers that
didn't have triples and quads in them. Now (skaters) understand you
can't get by without them. You have to skate almost like it's a
competition every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Quadruples _ even in competition _ are still a rarity, but
triples are a given expectation among male competitors these days,
Zivanovic said. ``The skill level on these tours is getting higher
and higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Those rising expectations are enough to send most teen-agers
into hiding. But not the 4-foot-10-inch, 83-pound Nam, who still
trains at the same Orange County rink that made her a 6-year-old
champion.
</P>
<P>
   She's working on upping the consistency of her triple lutz.
She's working on triple-triple jump combinations. She's working on
developing her own style.
</P>
<P>
   Three to four hours a day, six days a week, this is her training
regimen _ squeezed in between homework and hanging out with family
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show the whole skating world that I'm mature enough
_ even if I'm only 13 _ to be in the senior ladies' group,'' Nam
said.
</P>
<P>
   Touring with world-class skaters in the Champions on Ice tour
sounds like a pretty good start. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
