<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILL FRISELL/``GOOD DOG, HAPPY MAN'' (Nonesuch)!off!
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the warmly refined, rootsy sound fashioned on his
previous two albums, guitarist Frisell joins drummer Jim Keltner,
organist Wayne Horvitz and multi-instrumentalist Greg Leisz for
excursions into country, blues, bluegrass and rock that maintain a
melancholic mood throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Ry Cooder drops by for a shimmering reading of the traditional
folk tune ``Shenandoah,'' dedicated to jazz guitarist Johnny Smith,
and its well-known melody is perfectly in tune with the rest of
this classy collection of beautifully played and arranged pieces. 3
1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DUKE ELLINGTON/``ELLINGTON AT NEWPORT 1956'' (Columbia Legacy)!off!
</P>
<P>
   Paul Gonsalves. ``Diminuendo and Crescendo in Blue.''
Twenty-seven choruses. It's one of the most famous jazz solos in
history and the defining performance of Ellington's electrifying
Newport ``comeback'' concert. This two-CD reissue finally delivers
the actual concert in its entirety and in stereo. (Columbia asked
Ellington to re-record the set in the studio the following day;
those performances are also included here.)
</P>
<P>
   Boasting 100 minutes of previously unissued prime Ellington,
this set is a priceless release, made all the better by extensive,
illustrated liner notes that beautifully put the concert into its
historical context. ``Ellington at Newport 1956'' is the perfect
album to introduce listeners to the composer's greatness on the
centennial of his birth. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEAUSOLEIL/``CAJUNIZATION'' (Rhino)
</P>
<P>
   The much-loved Louisiana band led by Michael Doucet cranks out
another fine effort, mixing the classic Cajun forms with some of
that regional music's antecedents, including a lovely waltz in
``Chanson Pour Tommy,'' a slinky half-blues, half-Lalo Schifrin
``L'Amour Poisonne'' and more. Their last album won a Grammy; this
one has a chance, too. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ David Bloom &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
COUNT BASIE BUNCH/``TOO MARVELOUS FOR WORDS'' (Vanguard) &QL; 
MEL POWELL/``THE BEST THINGS IN LIFE'' (Vanguard)!off!
</P>
<P>
   The first two issues from John Hammond's 1950s Vanguard Jazz
Showcase series, these two samplers offer solid tracks culled from
a variety of recordings. The Basie album (3 stars) features the
Count's sidemen (and, on four songs, the Count himself) doing what
they did best _ the blues. The best cuts come from a trio featuring
drummer Jo Jones, bassist Tommy Bryant and pianist Ray Bryant.
(Jones positively wails on ``Old Man River.'') The Powell album (3
stars) also comes from four sources and includes four big-band cuts
featuring vocalist Joan Wilie. Throughout, Powell demonstrates
versatile, lyrical playing that is always interesting. The two
reissues are the first of a 10-CD series devoted to
Hammond-produced recordings. We look forward to the rest.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
