<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Thursday, June 3, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Friday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ANALYSIS (Washington) _ The U.S.-led western alliance
wins promises from Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to stop
the ``ethnic cleansing'' of Kosovar Albanians and allow displaced
refugees to return to their province. But in a compromise peace
plan, President Clinton and NATO yield on some of their key
demands. They agree to allow a greater role for the United Nations
and a prominent role for Russian troops in Serbian-held areas. BY
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-CONLEY (Washington) _ Sean Conley, 13, who is home-schooled
in Newark, Calif., loses in the sixth round of the 72nd National
Spelling Bee here after failing to spell ``coreopsis,'' which
refers to a genus of flowering herbs. Earlier he was correct on
``opacate,'' which means to darken or dim, and ``machicolation,'' a
opening in a castle wall. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-DeMAIORIBUS (Washington) _ Natalie DeMaiorbus, 13, who has
completed the seventh grade at Holy Spirit School in San Antonio,
fell one letter short of moving into the fifth round of the
National Spelling Bee. She dropped an ``n'' trying to spell
``tinnitus,'' which means a loud noise. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-MOORE (Washington) _ Stacey Moore, 14, of Midland, Texas, is
knocked out of the National Spelling Bee in the fifth round after
failing to spell the word ``excursus,'' which is a digression from
the main topic of discussion. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (London) _ Great Britain is all atwitter over
genetically altered food and plants. People are torn between
hysterical fears that monarch butterflies may be killed and claims
that the new science will be a commercial boon and help fight
hunger in poor countries. In America, however, we are pressing
ahead with crop biotechnology despite its uncertainties. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
