<HEADER>
A1463 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRIS-ROCK-LADN     06-03 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRIS-ROCK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMEDIAN A BUSY, BUSY GUY THESE DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ He's loud, rude, funny and very, very smart. Or
is that smart and very, very funny?
</P>
<P>
   OK, OK, how about very, very smart; very, very funny; and not
least of all, comedian Chris Rock is very, very, very busy.
</P>
<P>
   He's rolling into Los Angeles on Saturday in the latest stop of
a 28-city tour, building up to a taping later this month for his
latest hourlong comedy special on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   He has a weekly talk show on HBO; executive production duties on
ABC's ``The Hughleys;'' appearances in two films; a book, record
and TV commercials; and he's developing a comedy magazine.
</P>
<P>
   All of which begs a simple question, as he's about to board the
tour bus from Milwaukee to another appearance outside Chicago: Hey,
Chris, when do you have time to breathe?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like to work,'' Rock said. ``It's the only thing I do
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Any time for a good time?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much,'' Rock said. ``I just work, man, trying to get some
work done. I've been hot and cold before, so this time I'm doing
everything I can while I can. I think I promised myself if I ever
got hot again, I wouldn't take it for granted. `Cause if you're not
working, you're nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock grew up in one of Brooklyn's toughest neighborhoods,
Bedford-Stuyvesant, where getting his butt kicked was a regular
occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they act like we used to hang out,'' Rock said of his
childhood tormentors. ``They act like them beating me up was us
hanging out.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as a young child, being a comedian sounded like a great
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much always wanted to be a comedian,'' Rock said.
``It seemed like a fun job. You got paid to talk, to make people
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining the cast of ``Saturday Night Live'' in 1989 was a big
break, building his name and close friendships with cast members
such as Adam Sandler.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a dry spell for four years, before the momentum started
moving forward again, but even in his slow stretches there was
always stand-up comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stand-up, the thing about stand-up, I don't have to listen to
anybody,'' Rock said. ``It's a control freak's dream. And it's easy
to count the money. There's no creative accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a man alone on a stage, trying to make a roomful of people
laugh, has other advantages as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to experiment creatively, to joke about things
you might have a hard time doing in another format: abortion, gun
control,'' Rock said.
</P>
<P>
   He resists defining his comedy as political, though it is _
deeply so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's life, I wouldn't say it's politics,'' Rock said. ``It's
political in a barbershop sense. It's guys in a barbershop
talking.''
</P>
<P>
   But it comes from a radically different angle than the full-on
bore of the Washington punditocracy, certainly, or even from most
other comedians.
</P>
<P>
   It's like being black and from Bed-Stuy and clever allows Rock
to look at topics in a number of different lights, giving him his
own unique take on things.
</P>
<P>
   It's what makes Rock interesting, not just funny.
</P>
<P>
   That view means topics such as how Harlem coped with the death
of Princess Diana. More recently, it's abortion, high school
slaughters and the related topic of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun control is a double-edged sword,'' Rock says. ``On the one
hand, we definitely need gun control. On the other hand, my people
are very oppressed. They got their asses kicked, legally, forever.
Something tells me if we could never buy a gun again, my people
would be the first ones in line getting their asses kicked again.''
</P>
<P>
   His answer: ``I think there should be bullet control. A bullet
should cost $5,000. If a bullet costs $5,000, there would be no
innocent bystanders.''
</P>
<P>
   Racism is another evergreen, even if it doesn't sound like the
most promising comedy source.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audiences always want to hear about it,'' Rock said. ``You
listen to the radio, you want to hear a love song. You listen to a
young, black comedian, you want to hear him talk about racism.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, dubious police shootings of blacks from Riverside to
New York give him lots to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never goes away,'' Rock said. ``White police, white people
in general, still haven't learned how to differentiate. (CBS ``60
Minutes'' correspondent) Ed Bradley and (gangsta rapper) Ol' Dirty
Bastard pretty much get treated the same. Even though you try to
treat people the same in general, when you respect them, you treat
those people differently. There's a difference between how you
treat Jeffrey Katzenberg vs. Pauly Shore, for instance. That
doesn't happen to black people.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Rock is honing his material in appearances such as
Saturday's before stepping onto one of the most fearsome stages in
America, the Apollo Theater.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the Harlem Renaissance in the 1920s, the Apollo
remains one of the shrines of American black culture. Its audience
_ discriminating tastes honed by decades of seeing the cream of
black culture _ is known as one of the nation's most demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of the Apollo is you've got a real honest
audience,'' said Rock. ``In the first HBO special, a guy (in an
opening act) is getting booed off the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Rock is unlikely to suffer the same fate, it has happened
``a few times, far too numerous actually.''
</P>
<P>
   But he shrugs it off as the price of audacity: ``You're trying
out stuff. If you're not going to be conventional, there's always
the chance they'll turn on you. But being on the stage is the only
place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Rock's many projects, what he really wants to do is,
yes, direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not crazy for a comedian to say that,'' Rock said. ``When
you're a comedian, you've got your act, there's producing, there's
writing, there's performing. If you're a comedian, your job is to
make things better than they are on paper. That's what a director's
job is, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He's already learned from such directors as ``Lethal Weapon's''
Richard Donner, Kevin Smith and Neil Labute.
</P>
<P>
   Of the latter two, whose films he will appear in this summer, he
says, ``They're both really intense, meticulous, dark guys, the
first really A-list guys I've worked with, other than Dick Donner.
There's a big difference between an A director and a B director.''
</P>
<P>
   And the difference is?
</P>
<P>
   ``An A director is like a great corner man in a fight, who
really knows what they're doing, really knows how to tell you how
to slip the punch,'' Rock said. ``B directors tend to get scared:
`Oh, no, he's hitting you pretty hard.' The secret is preparation.
It's all preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock laces his conversation with sports metaphors, evidence of
his love of athletics. So, was he so sports-minded growing up? &QL; 
``I played everything, and I sucked at everything,'' he says
freely. And now? ``I watch everything, go to everything, and I
still suck at everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Except work. That he does very, very, very well. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
