<HEADER>
A1464 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JARREAU-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      06-03 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JARREAU-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL JARREAU, 59, GETTING 2ND WIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUG CARROLL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Al Jarreau has been at this singing thing for a long
time now, and it has taken him places that his boyhood dream of
playing baseball never would have.
</P>
<P>
   He has won five Grammy Awards. His distinctive, soaring tenor,
reminiscent of Nat King Cole or Johnny Mathis, is fluent in pop,
R&AMP;B and jazz. He is respected in the music business as a consummate
professional, a class act.
</P>
<P>
   So, if he's that good, how come he's still such a well-kept
secret? It's a question that Jarreau burns to answer with the next
stage of his career. At age 59, he has a new record label
(PolyGram) and a new outlook to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of the second half,'' says Jarreau.
``I'm still looking for that brass ring of reaching the numbers I
know I can reach when my music gets heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm long overdue for a big hit album. . . . There are some
mediocre singers who sell 8 to 10 million records, and I think I
have the potential to do like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau has had steady but hardly spectacular sales during a
career that took root back in the mid-'60s when he was part of a
trio headed by George Duke, with whom he still collaborates.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, name a Jarreau tune besides ``We're in This Love
Together.'' Can't? That's what we're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've paid for my records with the record company and made a
few bucks,'' he says. ``But my income comes from going to Chicago
or Arizona or Bemidji, Minnesota, concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still striving to make it, in lots of ways, in my own
head. I think I haven't laid a glove on (listeners) yet. The
potential audience out there for music with something to say is
bigger than I've experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau admits his versatility may have worked against him. This
is a man who won Grammys for Best Male Pop Vocalist and Best Male
Jazz Vocalist (begin ital) in the same year (end ital) (1980). He
played Teen Angel in ``Grease'' on Broadway. He has big-band and
symphony projects he wants to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably carry the label of `jazz singer,' but that's not
really true,'' says Jarreau, a preacher's kid from Milwaukee who
grew up in a musical family. ``I'm not the jazz singer people
expect me to be, or like the ones who have been before. I couldn't
be pinned down as a jazz, R&AMP;B or pop singer. I have been blessed
with a love for different kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   His first album for PolyGram is due in January and will stay
true to the eclecticism that fans are accustomed to. It will
include ``God's Gift to the World,'' a duet with Vanessa Williams
that Jarreau says is ``a real anthemic, heart-and-soul song.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially refreshing is Jarreau's heart-and-soul passion for
what he does _ and the ease with which he expresses it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the joy of my life,'' he says of singing. ``It makes me
laugh and grin and smile. It's the fountain of youth. I'm so
blessed to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Jarreau thought he could make a living at
shortstop. He played baseball at Ripon College in Wisconsin and
entertained visions of a big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great and the dream was fun,'' he says. ``That's the
stuff of life, man, dreaming and seeing yourself in the future _
and having that inspire you.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, chords won out over curveballs. He has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distinctive sound of a singer or horn player is something
we strive for or hope to arrive at,'' Jarreau says. ``I'm glad to
hear that from people. They say, `A song came on the radio and I
knew it was you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Should be a fascinating second half. &QL; 
Doug Carroll can be reached atdoug.carroll(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
