   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-AGREEMENT (Seattle) _ The United States and Canada
announce a long-sought agreement to protect the threatened salmon
populations that have been depleted by Canadian fishermen as the
fish migrate along the coast. Canada has agreed to reduce catches
of some salmon runs by 40 percent and the U.S. will buy back
licenses of Canadian fishermen. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-POLICE-SHOOTING (Los Angeles) _ A homeless woman, a former
banker who became schizophrenic, waved a screwdriver at police and
they killed her, spawning protests over police brutality. But
without Al Sharpton, this protest has not become a national issue
like the Louima assault. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-COMMISSION (San Francisco) _ The national gambling
commission finishes its last meeting Thursday with recommendations
that political contributions from gambling companies be limited,
college betting be curtailed and states cut back on advertising for
lotteries in poor neighborhoods and consider moratoriums on further
gambling operations. The recommendations now go to Congress but
many feel they have not gone far or deep enough. By Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-VIOLENCE-ASSESS (Los Angeles) _ While Hollywood gets
worked up about a lot of issues, violence is not one of them. This
is because violence sells, particularly in the lucrative overseas
market. Also, the ratings system is geared toward knocking out sex,
not violence. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
