<SLUG> BC-BUS-MESSAGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUS SYSTEM TESTS ELECTRONIC ARRIVAL TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Muni, the San Francisco bus system, is testing
electronic message boards that post approximate arrival times of
buses for riders accustomed to waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the electronic message boards, which rely on a satellite
global positioning system to transmit bus locations, were activated
Wednesday along the 22-Filmore line. The boards are part of a pilot
project scheduled to run for 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   If it works, the system could change the wait-and-see nature of
riding public buses. Riders determine arrival times of buses by
using the electronic boards or they could log on to a Web site and
time their departure from office or home to the next arriving bus.
Eventually, the system's designers said, riders could even see how
many people are on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much needed,'' said Joan Dill, a frequent rider, watching
as Mayor Willie Brown and Muni chief Michael Burns touted the
system. ``Waiting for buses has always been a problem, and this
will give us an estimation of how long you'll be standing there.
Believe it or not, they used to have something called a schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said the system would improve the reliability of service
by telling both customers and Muni's command center where buses
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``This line was chosen because it was selected as the most
unreliable,'' Burns said. ``If it works here, it can work
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of NextBus Information Systems, the Emeryville,
Calif., company that designed the system, said the signs were 95
percent accurate based on testing.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Maresca, chief operating officer of NextBus, said accuracy
would rise to 99 percent if the system were installed on all lines.
The cost of installing the system at the 4,500 stops in San
Francisco would be about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the city would evaluate the performance of the system
before considering whether to buy the signs. Muni could be the
first large urban transit department to install the system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1420EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
