<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1467 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIOXIDANTS-HEALTH-A     06-03 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIOXIDANTS-HEALTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODY'S WAR ON DISEASE PITS ANTIOXIDANTS VS. FREE RADICALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Medical researchers tell of a war that never ends.
</P>
<P>
   It takes place every day of our lives at the cellular level
between harmful elements known as free radicals and beneficial ones
called antioxidants.
</P>
<P>
   Antioxidants have been known in medical circles for 50 years,
but they've only recently surfaced in mainstream health. They occur
naturally in our bodies as enzymes. They've also been discovered in
certain fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   The public is primarily aware of them as supplements added to
products that boldly tout an array of possible benefits _
everything from preventing heart disease and cancer to staving off
arthritis, eye cataracts and Alzheimer's. They're also said to slow
down the aging process.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a lot of confusion about antioxidants; even more
regarding their evil counterparts, the free radicals.
</P>
<P>
   A name reminiscent of '60s activists, free radicals are actually
volatile atoms or groups of atoms that can trigger chain reactions
capable of causing damage to biological targets, such as cells,
proteins and even DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the National Institutes of Health in Bethesda,
Md., have recently implicated free-radical mechanisms in the
pathology of many human diseases, including cancer, stroke,
malaria, arthritis and neuro-degenerative diseases, as well as in
aging and HIV infections.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers, including Dr. Yang C. Fann, science task manager
for Information Technology Support Service in Research Triangle
Park, N.C., believe that under normal conditions, the effects of
free radicals are neutralized by antioxidants our bodies produce
naturally. Problems occur when additional troops of free radicals
are introduced, primarily through environmental sources, which
throws off the natural internal balance. ITSS is under contract to
the National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Air pollution, smoking, alcohol, etc., contribute to oxidative
damage in our body,'' Fann said. ``Hence, these natural
(antioxidant) enzymes are not enough to defend against the
continuous onslaught of both natural and environmental free
radicals.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why many nutritionists and physicians believe that
eating foods rich in antioxidants helps to even the score.
Antioxidants are found primarily in flavonoids, a large and unique
group of nutrients found in certain vegetables and fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that certain dietary supplements, such as
vitamins A, C and E, and selenium, with their antioxidant effects,
also help in the fight against environmental free radicals.
However, less conclusive is research that synthetic forms of
antioxidants, such as vitamin supplements, are as valuable as those
found naturally in foods.
</P>
<P>
   The American Heart Association, for example, refuses to endorse
antioxidant supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Valley health professionals offer varying opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe antioxidants found in foods as well as dietary
supplements have an effect,'' said Marcia Francis, a staff
pharmacist for CIGNA HealthCare in Phoenix. ``I take the
supplements. I think they have a real benefit, especially since we
have so much exposure to pollutants and chemicals, and all these
things that are harmful to our bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Moss, a general practitioner in Fountain Hills,
recommends antioxidants in natural food form to his patients. He's
not as sold on supplements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you start isolating them, then you need to start looking
at them as a medicinal product and have to be careful,'' Moss said.
``A lot of people are making a lot of money on this not totally
defined product.''
</P>
<P>
   A general Internet search on the key word ``antioxidants'' turns
up page after page of entrepreneurs selling health products with
``environmental toxin fighting'' antioxidants. Most of these
products simply have antioxidant vitamins A, C or E added to them.
You can buy energy bars with antioxidants, honey with antioxidants,
sunscreen with antioxidants and much more.
</P>
<P>
   Juice bars have also jumped on the antioxidant bandwagon by
offering Smoothies and vegetable drinks with antioxidants. These
antioxidants, however, are usually the natural kind found in fresh
fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Karla Birkholz, a family practitioner with Your Family
Physician in Glendale, acknowledges that Americans spend ``huge
amounts of money on nothing'' in the health and nutrition fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do believe antioxidants should be part of the prevention
regimen,'' Birkholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Moss, she is not as convinced that synthetic antioxidants
have the same impact as natural ones, but she doesn't dismiss the
potential of antioxidant vitamins, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vitamins C and E have been shown to have value,'' Birkholz
said. ``Minerals like selenium and zinc also appear useful at
absorbing free radicals.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as a pharmacist, Francis said, she knows for certain
that the established medical community is writing prescriptions
featuring antioxidant vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of breast-cancer patients and Alzheimer's patients are
taking vitamin E,'' Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   New sources of antioxidants are still being discovered, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They now believe a very good source comes from grape seeds,''
Francis said. ``They've also discovered one of the most potent
antioxidants in a particular species of pine tree that grows in the
southern Mediterranean. This tree contains pycnogenol, a chemical
structure that specifically prevents sun damage to the skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Francis believes in synthetic antioxidants, she points
out that it's unwise to begin taking any dietary supplement without
first discussing it with one's physician and pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people should definitely not take antioxidants,'' Francis
said. ``Patients undergoing radiation or chemotherapy could do
damage to their treatments by taking antioxidants.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, in the discussion and analysis of antioxidants, it's
looking more and more like our mothers were right in pushing the
fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain healthy antioxidant levels, nutritionists recommend
two to three servings of fruit per day and three to five servings
of vegetables daily.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that supplements also help, it's generally believed
best to take a multivitamin, which offers a range of antioxidants
and nutrients.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
