<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALDEZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMOS TAKE NOTICE: BREAST FEEDING GOOD FOR BABIES, BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA VALDEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Imagine you were an anthropologist visiting from
another planet. It wouldn't take you long to assess the
significance of female breasts in our culture: They are for
marketing and men.
</P>
<P>
   It's a conclusion based on solid evidence: Nobody in America
goes broke overestimating the selling power of the breast. From``
Playboy'' to WonderBra to Hooters, fortunes have been built on the
swell and tilt of young, human mammary glands.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the evidence in popular culture, breasts are not
primarily tools for profit or pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   They are designed to feed babies.
</P>
<P>
   And they are so good at it that a pair of University of Arizona
researchers say HMOs could take the benefits to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anne L. Wright and Dr. Thomas M. Ball of the Department of
Pediatrics at the Arizona Health Sciences Center in Tucson found
that babies who aren't breast-fed rack up bigger medical bills. In
the first year of life, each formula-fed baby costs between $331
and $445 more than one who feeds on mother's milk.
</P>
<P>
   Their study was an effort to put a dollar value on the what
medical science has known for years about the wonders of human
milk. Mother's milk changes in composition as an infant's needs
change. It stimulates immunological responses, it promotes tissue
growth in the brain and lungs. It's even associated with higher IQs
in later childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Those are such amazing life-giving, health-giving benefits that
you'd think female breasts would enjoy a place or reverence in our
society. But instead of being treated with dignity as the Grande
Dames of Motherhood, they get glitzy billing as shallow starlets.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific knowledge didn't change that. Maybe cold cash can.
The study by Wright and Ball offers impressive numbers for the bean
counters who run health maintenance organizations. If it gets the
attention it deserves, attitudes toward breasts and breast-feeding
could change dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs have jumbo-size buying power to use for babies' well-being.
They can influence what hospitals do by sending patients only to
hospitals that facilitate, rather than undermine, breast-feeding.
They can make it standard practice to have lactation specialists
available to provide tips and guidance to new mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Business can also play a role _ and reap a benefit _ from
breast-feeding. The researchers found that ``If a parent misses two
hours of work for the excess illness attributable to
formula-feeding, more than 2,000 hours _ the equivalent of one year
of employment _ are lost per 1,000 never-breast-fed infants.''
</P>
<P>
   Just over half of mothers nationwide start breast-feeding, says
Wright, but many give up after a short period of time. Returning to
work is one big reason women quit giving their babies the best food
there is for them, Wright says.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses can help turn that around by offering support _ and
private rooms with electricity and refrigerators _ for women who
want to pump milk after they return from maternity leave.
</P>
<P>
   Other women stop breast-feeding _ or don't start _ because
doctors, hospitals, family and friends are indifferent to the value
of mother's milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have to have that support to buck what our society says
about breasts,'' says Wright.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation were photos of cleavage are far more common than
tableaus of mothers nursing infants, the ladies who lactate need
champions.
</P>
<P>
   It would be ironic if they get them because of a new
understanding of the monetary worth of breast milk.
</P>
<P>
   But considering that breasts have long been heralded more for
their performance on jiggle shows than for their value to infants,
the crassness of the motivation will be less important than the
satisfied burp of well-fed babies. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Linda Valdez can be reached at linda.valdez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
