<HEADLINE>
FED OFFICIAL REASSURES CONSUMERS ON MILLENNIUM GLITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The head of the Federal Reserve's Western
district sought to reassure the public Wednesday that the Year 2000
computer glitch wouldn't ravage the nation's financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an economist, I deal with probabilities all the time,''
said Robert T. Parry, president of the Fed's San Francisco
district, which covers nine Western states. ``I think the
probabilities are very high that on Jan. 1, 2000, nothing very
unusual is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Parry predicted that checks, automated teller machines, credit
and debit cards, and direct deposits would run smoothly, despite
forecasts that the banking system will crash and burn.
</P>
<P>
   Parry told the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco that there may
be short-term, isolated disruptions. A widespread financial crisis
is unlikely, though, because the government and banks have taken
many precautions over the past year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 98 percent of the computer systems in thousands of banks
that do business with the Fed are ready for the date change, Parry
said. The remaining 2 percent will meet federal regulations for
2000 readiness by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The concern arises from older computers and other electronic
devices that originally were programmed to recognize only the last
two digits of a year and may fail or malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators from the Fed and other government agencies have
examined banks over the past year to ensure they can handle the
date change.
</P>
<P>
   The banks and the Fed also have set up emergency plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if there's a huge cash demand? What if there are power
outages? What if there's a disruption in armored carrier service?''
said Carol Eckert, a Fed spokeswoman. ``We don't think that'll
happen, but these are part of the contingency plans.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure what may happen to the nation's financial system,
businesses, government agencies, and transportation and energy
networks. To play it safe, tens of billions of dollars have been
spent to upgrade technology.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who want more information on the millennium bug may
get a free copy of ``The Year 2000, Your Bank and You,'' from the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which oversees state-chartered
banks not covered by the Fed. The FDIC can be reached toll-free at
888-878-3256, on the Internet at www.fdic.gov or by writing to the
Consumer Information Center, Item 613-F, Pueblo, CO 81009.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1434EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
