<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BHUTAN-TV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION COMES TO BHUTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THIMPU, Bhutan _ They missed the first moonwalk, the O.J.
Simpson trial, the final episode of ``Seinfeld,'' and thousands of
hours of televised coverage of President Clinton and Monica
Lewinsky. In fact, most people here haven't heard of Neil
Armstrong, O.J. or Bill _ or, for that matter, television.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night, inhabitants of this remote kingdom tucked
in the Himalayas officially welcomed the talking box, taking a step
closer to a modern world kept at bay for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Crowded into homes and shops equipped with TV sets, some stared
and others cheered and whistled at the nation's inaugural broadcast
_ the 25th anniversary celebration of their king's coronation.
Masked dancers twirled on the screen before them, clad in colorful
skirts and pointed metal helmets that, to Western eyes, looked
straight out of the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   The day before, after orange-robed monks blessed fruits, rice,
and ornate silver jugs of salty, buttered tea _ and the country's
first Internet service provider _ one of the king's four wives
pressed a button that launched the nation into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Like Shangri-La, the fictional Himalayan paradise of the 1930s
classic novel ``Lost Horizon,'' where inhabitants of the secluded
valley never aged, so too the kingdom of Bhutan has managed to
shelter itself from the outside world and largely freeze its
culture in time.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of TV and the Internet to mark the anniversary
of King Jigme Singye Wangchuck's coronation is the latest move in a
gradual campaign to bring this poor nation out of isolation, but it
is also the most controversial. In a country that had only one
murder last year and where officials say only one person has died
of AIDS, some worry that throwing open a window to the outside
world could usher in a torrent of social ills unimagined by most
people here, and reshape the very fabric of Bhutanese life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go home and watch TV, it means you won't be talking to
your grandmom,'' said Karma Gallay, 27, who works for his family's
construction company in Thimpu. ``I'm afraid TV will glamorize
foreign culture. . . . Material possession is counted as such
success in the West, but here, you'll see a farmer saving every
chhetrum (penny) to build a monastery or a stupa for religion. I
don't want to lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are others such as Chencho Gyeltshen, 17, a
crimson-robed monk, who see a benefit to the changes: ``It's good
to have TV so we can know what other countries are doing. I know
India's below and China's above, but what happens there, I don't
know. On the other hand, I can see it as an evil, because someone
who never knew of stealing or murder could see it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Balancing the good and evil of the modern world is a familiar
challenge in Bhutan; its leaders have tried for three decades to
follow a path to progress with one foot planted firmly in the past.
King Jigme's oft-repeated motto is to promote ``gross national
happiness'' _ the notion that material wealth and development
should not supplant spiritual well-being, cultural traditions, and
environmental preservation. Bhutanese people say that as much as
they might have to learn from the modern world, the West could also
stand to learn from Bhutan's example.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutan is the only remaining independent Buddhist kingdom in the
Himalayas. Tibet, Sikkim, and Ladakh have all been annexed by
neighboring China or India, and perhaps that is why Bhutan has so
fiercely guarded its heritage and shied away from outside contact.
Tourism began only in 1974, and is limited by a $200 daily tourist
tax. Last year was the highest number ever _ a mere 6,000.
</P>
<P>
   This is a country of 700,000 people with 9,000 phone lines, not
a single traffic light, where the pace is so unhurried that dogs
sun themselves lazily in the road, and more people are killed by
bears than cars. It is a place with negligible crime, no lawyers,
and 5,000 underemployed soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   But the flip side of preserving heritage and nature has been,
until recently, a lack of modern advances to improve people's
standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, this country of spectacular, rugged topography had
no roads, and all travel was by horseback on winding mountain
passes. The country has no postal system or paper currency, not to
mention hospitals, running water, electricity or telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is a small airport and 2,100 miles of road traverse
the country, though many people still live several days' walk from
the nearest road. The government says a majority of villages have
access to a health center, a primary school, piped water, and
latrines. Nearly 32,000 households have electricity, though 70
percent of homes still do not. Since 1985, the infant mortality
rate has halved, literacy has doubled to 54 percent, and life
expectancy has jumped by 20 years to 66.
</P>
<P>
   Bhutan's per capita income of $645 is poor by Western standards,
but it is the highest in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the country is largely poor, hungry, and inadequately
educated. That is why many here think television and the Internet
could become powerful teaching tools.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, watching TV was illegal in Bhutan, though
hundreds of people had set up satellite dishes and were watching
foreign programs, from wrestling to Hindi movies. Officials
estimate that there are 5,000 computers in the country, most in
offices, and about 4,000 TV sets, most of which were being used to
watch imported videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an advantage'' to TV and the Internet. ``Bhutan is
landlocked and one of the world's least developed countries, and
we'd like to copy and learn from other countries' experiences,''
said Sherub Tenzin, 49, the governor of Paro district. ``The
challenge is for people themselves to choose good from bad. But we
are so deeply rooted in our culture and religion that I think what
is bad or good can easily be seen by any humble person.''
</P>
<P>
   Kencho Pem, 41, a farmer in Pangzhi, a village less than an
hour's drive from the capital, has never seen a television, but
likes the idea of a box that is like a radio with pictures. She
would be willing to save as much as $200 toward buying one, but
first has to wait for electrical lines.
</P>
<P>
   Pem understands that TV would bring puzzling information from
faraway places, but says ``it would be good to have this TV. People
should have a positive attitude to whatever they see. Forget what's
bad and just take the good. Even if someone doesn't know how to
steal and sees it on TV, that doesn't mean they will pick up that
habit.''
</P>
<P>
   Novice news anchor Tshewang Dendup, 29, has seen American news
and received two days of TV training last month. But he isn't
trying to emulate Tom Brokaw or Larry King. Like everything Bhutan
does, he said, ``We're trying to take the best from the West and
also the cream of Bhutan culture _ the middle path. It's a
tremendous challenge, especially in a society where half the
population is illiterate and what you project is going to be very
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Karma Ura, director of the Center for Bhutan Studies, worries
less about viewers aping bad habits from TV, and more about them
starting to question their own way of life. He has seen a few
moments of ``Baywatch,'' which he described as ``statuesque people
surfing in their underwear,'' and did not see the value of such a
show to the 85 percent of Bhutanese who are farmers.
</P>
<P>
   For villagers, ``TV will at first be a source of fascination and
excitement. People will see things they've never conceived of as
possible _ how tall others are, how rich they are.'' But he frets
that the next, perhaps inevitable, stage is to start to feel
inferior to an imaginary Hollywood life.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a carpet in front of his computer and an old-style,
unbound book of Buddhist writings, Ura reflected that ``Bhutan
balances tradition and modernity, environmentalism and development,
materialism and spirituality. It requires great courage not to
follow international trends . . . especially when your choice is so
divergent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
