<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-SLA-BOS &LR;      06-03 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-SLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASE SETS IN AS ISRAELI-BACKED MILITIA EXITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEZZINE, Lebanon _ From a stone tower above the army post, a
white statue of the Virgin Mary cast a merciful glance down upon
the Israeli-paid militiamen as they nervously watched their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's proxy forces, known as the South Lebanon Army, early
Thursday completed the first staged retreat of the last active
warfront in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, while pulling back from positions in the
surrounding villages, six soldiers stood guard around a rusted, old
tank at the entrance to this town. They trained automatic rifles at
cars approaching the checkpoint, occasionally firing warning shots.
</P>
<P>
   Inside one such car, a woman with children screamed: ``We are
going to the school!''
</P>
<P>
   The SLA is on edge these days, but with reason.
</P>
<P>
   To the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah guerrillas gaining ground in
their war of attrition against Israeli occupation of South Lebanon,
the SLA soldiers in this Christian enclave are collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   To the Lebanese government, which is officially in a state of
war with Israel, the SLA forces are traitors who face treason
charges in court that could carry the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   To the Israelis, they provide a foothold in places like this
strategic enclave just north of Israel's self-proclaimed ``security
zone.'' Israel pays the militiamen $550-a-month in US currency.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the SLA fighters claim they signed up to support their
families, or because they were coerced into joining by the
occupying Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are halfway through the withdrawal,'' said the regional SLA
commander, who asked that his name not be used because he feared
for his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are scared, very frightened. . . . The Lebanese
government is saying we are collaborators, but we are like any
Lebanese. We are the people,'' said the 40-year-old SLA major.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of this commander and the SLA forces who serve with him
hangs in the balance as this initial withdrawal could set the stage
for a larger withdrawal of Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak has vowed to bring home
2,000 Israeli troops within one year from the 6-to-10-mile-wide
swath of land it has occupied in south Lebanon since 1985 to
protect its northern border against incursions and rockets. The
withdrawal was a campaign promise that resonated with many voters
who see Lebanon as Israel's Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The SLA major recently inherited the job of regional commander
after two consecutive predecessors were killed in roadside bombs.
He will soon join his family which has retreated deeper inside the
security zone.
</P>
<P>
   A feeling has set in that the SLA forces are unraveling.
</P>
<P>
   One soldier at the checkpoint, who also asked his name not be
used, said, ``I will go to Israel. We will be safe with them.'' He
added, ``If I stay, they'll beat me to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those planning to turn themselves in, he added, ``They are
making a big mistake. They will end up in jail. Or they will end up
killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Another SLA soldier, younger, thinner, and chain smoking
Marlboro Lights as he spoke, said he was planning to stay in
Jezzine, where he was born, and take his chances despite the dire
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would camp out on the outskirts of town and see if
Lebanese army moves troops in. If Hezbollah forces take control of
the area, he said he would run for his life.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was worried that he would be tried by the
Lebanese as a collaborator, he said, ``If they put me in jail, they
would have to put all Jezzine in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Jezzine, the center of a rocky valley of hillside villages set
among terraced vineyards and citrus groves, is now nearly empty.
Its population was more than 20,000 in the mid-1980s and is now
less than 5,000. More families in this predominantly Christian town
fled in recent days. Many of them, especially those who sided with
the SLA, fear reprisals from the Hezbollah fighters and their
guiding clerics.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, which is roughly 75 percent Muslim and 25 percent
Christian, the specter of sectarian violence always lurks. But it
casts a more pronounced shadow these days over what many hope is
the beginning of the end of this war.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah press attache Ibrahim Musawi insisted Wednesday that
``the Christian fears are irrational'' and added, ``It is Israel
that is stirring these primitive instincts and fears of sectarian
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   A cliffside Maronite Christian monastery several miles from
Jezzine has opened its doors to take in a frightened population.
Rev. Paul Khawand, of the Maronite order, has also gathered the
names of 203 militiamen who have deserted the SLA and are willing
to surrender and face legal action. Khawand met with Hezbollah
leader Sayyed Hassan Nasrallah to help ensure the safety of the SLA
deserters and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting was very positive,'' said the Rev. Abdel Alam.
``It's a volatile situation, but people are working very hard to
stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Farid Khazen, a political scientist at American University of
Beirut, said the Lebanese government must exert influence
immediately after the SLA pullout and that it should adopt an
amnesty bill pending in the parliament for SLA soldiers who turn
themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is not handled properly by the Lebanese government, it
will polarize the people further along religious lines,'' Khazen
said. ``But if it is handled properly, it will help rebuild
national unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Muslim-Christian tension lurks beneath the surface, for
many families the key issue is security. Three generations of the
Nawfals were sitting on a patio in front of their home. They are
Christian, but said they get along fine with their Muslim
neighbors. What they want is an end to the violence and a chance to
build a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time it is bombs and explosions here,'' said Charbel
Nawfal, 40. As if on cue, the thunder of shelling rumbled in the
hills.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to a turn in the road, a blackened patch of earth 75
yards away, where just 10 days ago an SLA commander and his driver
were killed by a roadside bomb, the deadly signature of Hezbollah.
The blast blew out four windows in the home where he lives with his
wife and four children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are against the violence,'' he said, ``no matter where it
comes from.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
