<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-BACKBAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID TRENDY STRIP, A HAVEN FOR THE HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Newbury Street, the strip of trendy boutiques and brick
row houses with some of the nation's most upscale real estate, will
also be the home of some of the city's most destitute citizens when
a homeless shelter opens on the glitzy stretch next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the two extremes _ the opulent and those just
getting by,'' said Tom Philbin, spokesman for the Department of
Neighborhood Development, which helped fund the shelter in the
basement of Emmanuel Church.
</P>
<P>
   For the past decade, about 20 mentally ill women have been
sleeping in Back Bay alleys and on benches, in effect choosing the
cool cement of that affluent neighborhood over others, and
impressing their faces on the minds of wealthy shoppers and
residents who step over them.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence in the Back Bay neighborhood is truly a study of
the haves and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   Just across the street from the church where six of the women
sleep on any given night is Giorgio Armani, where a woman's
lavender jacket costs $2,300. A few doors down is the Ritz-Carlton
hotel, where a room for the night can cost $800.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the way the city should be,'' said Philip
Mangano, executive director of the Massachusetts Housing and
Shelter Alliance. ``The best cities welcome everybody. Any kind of
exclusivity makes the city soulless.''
</P>
<P>
   For several years, street outreach workers have developed
relationships with the women, who have refused to live anywhere but
the streets of Back Bay. Eventually, a half-dozen of the women
agreed to move into the shelter, said Laureen Sandler of the
Tri-City Mental Health and Retardation Center, the organization
that will manage the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on Newbury Street can tell you about these women.
They are women who would normally never use a homeless shelter,''
said Sandler.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the church on a recent weekday, Lauren
Wilson sat on the curb shaking a Starbucks cup toward passersby.
``Can you help a lady?'' she asked. ``I come to this corner every
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't always feel like anyone gives us a second chance _ so
we give up, commit suicide, or keep getting high. But this shelter
will help us,'' said Wilson, who is now off the streets and living
in an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   People can be generous on Newbury Street, she added. It's not
unusual to be given a $100 bill on a holiday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody has been so welcoming of having a shelter in
Back Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you are going to have some opposition. There is
always going to be some resistance,'' said Mangano. ``People are
concerned of any change; change is scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Luanne Pryor, a Back Bay resident, said that initially residents
were concerned that the church basement's back entrance _ in the
center of a busy and dangerous alley _ would be unsafe. But shelter
organizers, with the help of city and private funds, moved the
entrance to the front of the church, said Sandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going to affect anything in Back Bay,''
said Geoffrey Reynolds, a Newbury Street real estate broker. ``Back
Bay is the most expensive neighborhood in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Other real estate brokers say Back Bay is the second-most
expensive neighborhood and retail strip in the country, behind only
Fifth Avenue in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly rent on a 400-square-foot apartment is $1,500 to
$1,600, while office-space rental can cost up to $110 a square
foot, said Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is saying they want to help the homeless, to give
them a place to sleep, as long as it's not next to me,'' said
Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Mangano and others who work with the homeless say the shelter
will help curb fatalities. Within the past year, 140 homeless
people have died in Boston and 12 of them died on the streets, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the dead of winter, there are usually nearly 30 mentally
ill women roaming the streets, said Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino,
who spoke at a recent ceremony to celebrate the shelter's opening.
</P>
<P>
   With all its posh and high price tags, Newbury Street is no
stranger to the obviously needy. Panhandlers often sit on curbs,
some singing for spare change. Recently, a rumpled man lifted
himself up from a bench to ask for 45 cents to buy medicine for his
sniffles.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Cattan, who on a recent sunny day was sipping coffee and
taking a drag of a cigarette, said she sees them every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you say it?'' asked Cattan, a native of Cyprus,
struggling for the right word to explain how people on the streets
ignore the homeless. ``We tune them out. So I think it's good they
are building a shelter on Newbury Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in black Prada pants, white Armani shirt, and
spit-and-polish Gucci shoes, Steven Masters, a hairstylist at
Avanti Salon, is the symbol of Newbury's hipster scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is wonderful,'' he said of the shelter, as he
strolled down the street balancing an armload of coffee cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many shops and people have been so blessed with so much
around here, I think it's time to give back,'' he said. ``This is
such a beautiful street. I don't think it should just be for a
certain group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
