<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-03 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING THE ONES THAT GOT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of Boston's finest gardens survive only in the library of
the Society for the Preservation of New England Antiquities, which
houses 20,000 architectural plans and 400,000 historic photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost Gardens of New England,'' a display of 40 garden images
from 1790 through 1930 that opened last month in SPNEA's newly
rented office and gallery space in downtown Boston, mines this
trove. It features watercolors, historic photographs, plans, and
even an antique stereoscope for looking at 3-D stereo views of
19th-century landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The title is a bit of a misnomer, as some parts of some of the
gardens survive, though not in the full high-maintenance glory
depicted here. One completely lost garden in the exhibit is the
Kidder Estate, known as The Lilacs, which existed in Medford,
Mass., from 1810 to 1905. It had extensive, elaborate terraces
crowned with a lattice summer house and geometric vegetable and
cutting gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Another goner is the 1855 Rand Home in Cambridge, Mass., which
had a 2-acre Victorian garden with a wisteria-draped gazebo, an
orchard, and a well-designed period garden that survived in the
family for a century, until it was paved over to become a shopping
center in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The show reflects the new importance that SPNEA, like the rest
of the preservation community, is attaching to garden history since
hiring Betsy Igleheart as its first director of landscapes last
year. Good thing, too. With 35 house museums scattered through New
England, SPNEA is the region's largest owner of historic
landscapes. It is restoring several of these gardens, including
those at the Lyman Estate in Waltham and the Codman Estate in
Lincoln, with help from the Massachusetts Historical Commission.
</P>
<P>
   A sudden popular interest in historical gardens is reflected in
the success of the three-year-old Traditional Gardening magazine,
published in Southborough, and the certificate program in
landscape-design history that the Radcliffe Seminars in Cambridge
initiated six years ago. The nine-year-old New England Garden
History Society and the Garden Conservancy, founded in 1989 to help
preserve significant gardens, are also part of this trend.
</P>
<P>
   Like architecture, garden design has historic periods, and
``Lost Gardens'' delivers a brief primer on three New England
themes.
</P>
<P>
   One wall devoted to ``Gardens of the New Republic'' (1780-1830)
explores the heavily English-influenced gardens of the
post-Revolutionary era. These came in two styles: the ``ancient,''
or geometric, form and the naturalistic park-like approach
pioneered by English designer Lancelot ``Capability'' Brown. His
nickname came from his ``capability'' to do huge, sweeping feats of
landsculpting, and his style was employed on major country estates
such as Theodore Lyman's The Vale in Waltham. It impressed visitors
with its deer park, ``beautiful serpentine river,'' and ``elegant
swans swimming about.'' In 1822, landscape author J. C. Loudon
called it ``one of the most beautifully and artistically arranged
estates in the country.'' Visitors used to approach on an elegant
bridge over a pond, but the entry road was moved, presumably by the
owner, when the town of Waltham tried to tax the bridge.
Greenhouses that are still home to the Lymans' heirloom grapes and
camellias do survive, however.
</P>
<P>
   Symmetrical style
</P>
<P>
   High-style residents of New England's prosperous cities and port
towns like Portsmouth, N.H., and Newburyport also built elaborate
gardens during this early period. Working on relatively small urban
plots, they favored the more symmetrical style that fit the ordered
context of city life. Old photographs of the Brockway garden in
Newburyport, for example, show a complex design of geometric beds.
</P>
<P>
   SPNEA's 1807 Rundlet-May property in Portsmouth, N.H., is among
the minute fraction of town gardens that survive with their
original geometric layout from this early period. It's open to the
public. James Rundlet kept detailed expense records that show he
spent a total of $104 for many dozens of trees and roses.
</P>
<P>
   Artfully pruned food-producing vines and trees were often
highlighted instead of ornamentals in gardens like these. Why grow
flowering dogwoods when you could grow apples, peaches, cherries,
pears, and plums that flowered just as well, and yielded fruit too?
The Yankee ethic held that food-producing plants were more morally
uplifting and less materialistic than ornamentals. One of SPNEA's
current projects is to re-create an orchard of espaliered fruit
trees against the restored 425-foot-long brick ``peach wall'' on
the Lyman property. (The heat retained by the brick helped tender
fruits survive and ripen more quickly.)
</P>
<P>
   In the next historical period, between 1840 and 1910, the
American middle-class suburban ideal developed, inspired by the
writings of Andrew Jackson Downing. He promoted two major types of
landscapes: the ``beautiful'' style, with serpentine lines, lawns,
and groups of deciduous trees, and the ``picturesque,''
incorporating irregular lines, rocky outcroppings, and pointed
evergreens. The latter was used at the Bowen House in Woodstock,
Conn., which SPNEA is also restoring.
</P>
<P>
   Suburbs ``offered all the benefits of rural pleasures and many
of the benefits of park scenery without relinquishing the luxuries
of town life,'' wrote Downing's disciple, Frank J. Scott, in 1870.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man could have envisioned today's total triumph of the
featureless American lawn. Their idea of a suburb was Jamaica Plain
or Cambridge, both represented in the exhibit by old photos of
Victorian gardens awash in ornamental plantings, fruit trees, and
grape trellises, per Downing's recommendations. The exhibit has a
drawing of the picturesque garden of the 1856 Merriam House on
Chestnut Street in JP. That house still stands as a private
residence, but the garden was sacrificed to subdivisions,
reflecting the longstanding practice of preserving historic
buildings but not their landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Revival gardens
</P>
<P>
   Today, we are witnessing the second coming of the ``revival
garden'' phase, which began in the late 19th century. These
deliberately ``old-fashioned'' gardens often frame Colonial Revival
buildings but borrow from many historical periods and cultures. The
fenced-in front-yard garden of Colonial times has been only one
model. The 1899 sunken Italianate garden of the Codman Estate, The
Grange, is a revival garden inspired by classical Rome. The formal
gardens of French chateaux served as another style source. These
gardens boast of the owner's European travels and refinement. The
old ones often contained a terra-cotta Bacchus or ancient pot,
souvenirs from abroad that are now subject to theft, because the
revival style has become so popular again that everyone wants one.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious goal of the exhibit is to highlight SPNEA-owned
gardens. Another, says Lorna Condon, SPNEA curator of Library and
Archives, is ``to inspire new garden design to be compatible with
historic houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners no longer restore a historic home down to its
doorknobs, then purchase standard-issue landscaping. They want
gardens that are roughly in period with their house.
</P>
<P>
   Some lucky homeowners find the original garden plans for their
own old houses in the SPNEA archives, Condon says. ``We have
thousands of users who call us every year and say, `Do you have a
photo of our old house?' Almost every week someone comes in and
finds original photos or plans for their house or garden. They jump
for joy.''
</P>
<P>
   The SPNEA library, now closed for renovation, will reopen to the
public June 30 by appointment; call 617-227-3957, ext. 225. Hours
will be Wednesday through Friday, 9:30 a.m. to 4:45 p.m., and
there's a $5 fee for nonmembers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost Gardens of New England'' is the third show at the new
gallery at the corner of Cambridge and New Chardon streets. The
gallery stands between Government Center and SPNEA's headquarters
at the Harrison Gray Otis House, which houses the library. The show
will run through Sept. 17, Monday through Friday, 10 a.m. to 4
p.m., and is free to the public. (For gallery information, call
617-570-9105.)
</P>
<P>
   Like the Smithsonian Institution in Washington, SPNEA serves as
a grandmother's attic of cultural history, and only half its
objects are on display in the house museums. This gallery space
will allow some of those items a brief respite from storage. The
previous show, titled ``Walk Right In,'' featured 50 pairs of
shoes, the oldest from the 1600s and the newest a pair from
gastronome Julia Child.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1502EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
