<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1526 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      06-03 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION LEAK CALLS FOR ASPHALT CAULK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have 3 feet of paving on one side of the foundation. There
is a small gap of about 110-inch between paving and foundation. I
think some water is getting in there and wetting my basement. What
can I do?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BALBIR SINGH, Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. For a 110-inch gap, insert an asphalt caulk. It comes in a
caulking cartridge, and you should be able to squeeze quite a bit
in that joint. Make it as deep as practicable. Although such a
narrow gap seems too small for water to go through in sufficient
volume to wet the basement, water can do so many things as it seeks
its own level.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't get much caulk in the joint, widen it by chipping
out old paving so more caulk can be inserted. Make the gap an inch
deep.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have had a bucket of driveway black-top sealer stored away
for six years. It has never frozen. Is it still good to use?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
I.S., Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The proof is in the opening. Open the can, and if it looks
viable (can be stirred, and is not stiff as a board), then you can
use it. Remember, though, that driveway sealer is mostly cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Help! I'm in the middle of a project. I put a hole in the
wall for an outlet box. I saved the patch I cut out so I can fill a
nearby hole where I removed the outlet box. I have another, smaller
hole that also needs to be filled; it is quite a bit smaller than
the outlet box hole. How can I best fill those holes?
</P>
<P>
   ART KRUSINSKI, Sudbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. For the hole with the ready-made patch, butter liberally the
edges of the hole with joint compound (not spackling), and also
butter the edges of the patch. Place it in the opening, and let the
compound dry. Then smooth off the seams with more joint compound,
let dry, sand smooth, and do it twice more.
</P>
<P>
   For a smaller hole, butter the edges liberally, but don't try to
fill the hole. Let that dry. Butter the edges again, making the
hole even smaller. Repeat until the hole is filled, let dry, sand
smooth, and repaint the walls. You might get away with
spot-painting the patches; latex wall paint can often be
patch-painted without the patch showing.
</P>
<P>
   Lay the joint compound in thin layers to prevent cracking when
it dries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The white cedar shingles on my garage look terrible after the
garage roof was replaced. How can I clean them up?
</P>
<P>
   FRAN ARCAND, Scituate, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. How to treat the shingles depends on what caused them to look
terrible. First, when you say white cedar shingles, I assume they
are untreated, unpainted, and unstained, and left to weather
naturally. If they are scarred and marked from falling asphalt
shingles (sloppy roofers!), there is little you can do but scrape
off the asphalt marks, and maybe sand a little to get rid of the
gross marks.
</P>
<P>
   If they are excessively black, you can treat them with household
bleach and water in a 1-to-3 solution, then rinse the bleach off
and let them continue to weather. Or, apply one thin coat of a
bleaching oil, which will turn them light gray and hasten
weathering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a second-floor slider that opens on to a deck with a
rubber roof. After the roof was installed, water has continued to
leak in through the wall under the slider, particularly in a
driving rain. The floor swells up and is damp, and the paneled wall
puckers up in the room below. How can that be fixed?
</P>
<P>
   MARGO STARK, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. With great difficulty, especially if there is no step-down
from slider to roof. With the slider threshold just inches or less
from the roof, the space below the threshold is difficult to patch,
flash, or caulk. I suggest you caulk that space, immediately under
the threshold, with an asphalt roofing caulk or roofing cement. And
make sure the space where the roof meets the wall is caulked as
well. This is assuming that the slider itself is not leaking.
</P>
<P>
   If all this does not solve or improve the situation, I suggest
you bite the bullet and raise the slider so there is at least a
7-inch step-down. This will allow you to flash the space (install
lead or aluminum flashing) for much more security against leaks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had my floors sanded and finished. The finisher used
moisture-cured polyurethane, which is neither oil- nor water-based.
I had to be out of the house for two days during the installation,
but I am concerned about toxic fumes afterward. Are there any, and
what can be done about them?
</P>
<P>
   M.O., Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It is true that the fumes are highly toxic, but since the
homeowner must be out of the house for two days during installation
and curing time, it must be assumed that the fumes are toxic only
for those two days. Other than staying out of the house for another
week or so, I suggest you ventilate it thoroughly by opening all
windows and putting fans in some of the windows for exhausting the
air.
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOB-STABILITY-HNS &LR;      06-03 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOB-STABILITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY POINTS TO GROWING SHIFT TOWARD CAREER SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some employees define loyalty as working hard
for a company today, not staying there for decades. They want pay
based on performance, not longevity. They want mentoring, but don't
care as much about a clear career path. And they don't see anything
wrong with job hopping.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new generation of workers. But it's not Generation X.
</P>
<P>
   Generation Xers are no more likely to emphasize those qualities
than are people in their 50s, according to a survey by Interim
Services Inc. and Louis Harris and Associates. The national survey
of 1,001 adults says 22 percent of workers are ``emergent,'' people
with those types of attitudes, while 29 percent think more
traditionally, emphasizing job security and a clear career path.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 49 percent of respondents are described by Ray
Marcy, the president and chief executive of Interim, as
``migrating.'' These are people with some traditional values and
some emergent ones.
</P>
<P>
   He believes they are changing toward the emergent mind-set of
``career security'' rather than traditional job security because of
the waves of layoffs over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Several items on the survey particularly illustrated the
differences in attitudes:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``An employer is responsible for providing a clear career
development path for employees.'' Overall, 85 percent of
respondents agreed with that statement, and 93 percent of
traditional workers did. But only 64 percent of emergent employees
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``An employer has a moral obligation to keep long-term
employees as long as they meet the requirements in the job
description.'' Overall, 83 percent agreed; among traditional
workers, 95 percent agreed; among emergent workers, 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Loyalty is being willing to stay with an employer for the
long haul.'' Overall, 75 percent agreed; traditional, 94 percent;
emergent, 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My level of commitment to an employer depends on the
likelihood of long-term job security.'' Overall, 72 percent agreed;
traditional, 89 percent; emergent, 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Long-term career advancement depends on staying with an
employer for a long time.'' Overall, 56 percent agreed;
traditional, 85 percent; emergent, 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``An employer who expects all employees to follow the rules
and regulations, regardless of the circumstances.'' Overall, 60
percent of workers found that to be an attractive quality, and 76
percent of traditional employees did. But only 39 percent of
emergent workers were attracted.
</P>
<P>
   Although age and experience made little difference in the ratio
of emergent workers to traditional ones, a couple of demographic
factors did. Those with college degrees or annual salaries of more
than $50,000 were far more likely to be emergent employees than
traditional ones.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy said one aspect of the survey particularly surprised him:
He expected that traditional workers would be more comfortable in a
traditional environment, and emergent employees would prefer an
emergent one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The survey dispelled that, saying that a traditional worker
was comfortable in each environment,'' Marcy said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 50 percent of traditional workers in traditional
companies said there was a good to excellent likelihood of them
staying there for at least the next five years. For traditional
workers in emergent companies, though, the likelihood of staying
actually increased to 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When the same question was asked of emergent workers, only 31
percent said they were likely to stay for the five years in a
traditional company. In an emergent company, however, the
likelihood increased to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy said that traditional employers _ ones who avoid hiring
people who have changed jobs every few years, don't discipline or
fire poor performers and apply the same set of rules to all workers
_ will continually find themselves drawing from a smaller hiring
pool as more employees find more satisfaction at emergent
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not moving toward an emergent workplace,'' he said,
``you've really got to evaluate your chances of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of significant advantages of emergent workplaces that
are gaining in popularity are flexible work hours and opportunities
for mentoring. Of the three things that all the people surveyed
liked most about their jobs, the one mentioned most frequently was
``a work schedule that meets my needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcy said that although workers don't emphasize clear career
paths as much as they used to, they do expect the company to help
them grow. ``People were more than twice as likely to look for
another job if there weren't adequate mentoring opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   He said companies can also attract more emergent employees by
granting workers more independence, encouraging debate and limiting
the need for memos, especially those that workers and bosses use
for ``covering their tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's survey didn't consider which industries the workers
were in, but Marcy hopes to include that next year. Still, he knows
from experience that certain industries are more likely to stick to
the traditional mold than others are.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the high-tech industry, you're going to find
more of an emergent environment than in, say, a law firm.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His e-mail
address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
