<HEADLINE>
HOW THE DEATH OF A LOVED REUNITED ONE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Margaret Kennedy died this April at age 98, she left behind
two of her six children, 45 grandchildren, and 97
great-grandchildren who live all over the country, from Maine to
California and everywhere in between. Margaret had been the hub of
this great wheel of a family, the central point at which they all
connected. Now scattered, the different branches of this extended
family hardly ever came together, and the cousins knew very little
about one another's lives.
</P>
<P>
   It took Margaret's death to turn them into the Kennedy clan.
</P>
<P>
   As one of her grandchildren put it: ``During those 10 days, and
in the days and weeks following, cousins burst into life for each
other like desert flowers suddenly blooming after a spring rain.
This new landscape of relationships was Grandma's final gift to us.
It's a gift of love, which blossomed because of technology. It
happened through e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   The day she went into the hospital with a stroke, her grandson,
Paul, sent e-mail to everyone whose address he could get hold of:
``We are going to try to have someone with her at all times. I will
pass on more information when I get some. Please keep her in your
prayers, and I know this sounds wrong, but don't pray for a
recovery. Pray she will go to God after having lived a life that
touched so many people in so many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Margaret 10 days to die, days in which her descendants
shared their memories and celebrated her generous spirit, her
idiosyncracies, and her fun-loving nature. Their stories made their
way to Margaret's bedside and filled her last hours with
companionship, bringing her the comforting news that none of her
loving had been in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma just wrote and apologized for not coming and taking
care of her nursing duties as I just had surgery. You should have
seen her the last time. She arrived at the hospital at the age of
93, wearing a shower cap and her white jacket, and announced that
my private nurse from Boston had arrived. Let me tell you, I did
recover fast after that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Grandma came, there were card games every night! I know
heaven awaits her entry with open arms and a deck of cards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Grandma taking me to the 1964 World's Fair all by
myself, making me feel so special _ like I was her only
grandchild.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma always planned a bingo party for us. She always had a
gift for each and a poem or a story she made up to go with the
gifts. I remember going to the Salvation Army with her to purchase
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw on TV about a dish soap that could be whipped into a
creamy-looking frosting. When we finished, Krista asked Grandma if
she would like a taste. Unfortunately, Grandma took a big
finger-licking sample. It's the only time I really remember Grandma
getting mad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most painful memory to me is the time I spilled scalding
hot tea in her lap, but Grandma never made me feel one bit of
guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maggie came to visit me in Mexico. We went to a bullfight.
You-know-who decided she wanted the matador's autograph. We raced
to the entrance where she boldly approached him and gave him a kiss
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you dearly, Grandma. Lest I forget, I will always
remember when I cause trouble it is not my fault. It is in my
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma won an award for her work with senior citizens _ she
was a senior citizen herself! Her car broke down as she was
delivering Meals on Wheels. When the police came to her assistance,
she shamed them into driving her on her route to finish delivering
the meals!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Grandma's favorite grandchild and my children are her
favorite grandchildren. I know because of the way she treated us.
There's no way she could've done so much for the rest of you. (Or
could she?)''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you Grandma. When you finish your journey, tell my mom
that I finally got my degree and I think she would have been proud
of how I did. I'm sorry she couldn't be there, but I thank God that
you could. Save a seat at the table for us; we'll be along in due
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma, Mom reminded me that you always wanted to attend your
own wake. I think you are getting your wish. In laughing and crying
through all these memories, rest assured you're a classic. So, Dad,
give the lady a pint. I raise my glass to you, Grandma. You are one
in a million.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodbye, Grandma. Thank you and congratulations on a mission
well done. It's OK, you can rest now. We'll take it from here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This column is based on a manuscript, ``Memories of Grandma
Kennedy: An E-mail Chronology,'' compiled by a reader, Gail
Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
