<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FENCING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMENTING THE LOSS OF A GENTLEMEN'S ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE FENCING MASTER &QL; 
By Arturo Perez-Reverte (translated, from the Spanish, by Margaret
Jull Costa) &QL; 
Harcourt Brace, 245 pp., $24 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They eyed each other across the desk like fencers waiting to
strike,'' wrote Arturo Perez-Reverte of two antagonists,
archibishop and priest, in his last novel, ``The Seville
Communion,'' surely the most amusing and disturbing thriller of the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
   By another writer, a sentence like that could be dismissed as a
cliche, and a dated one at that. Who among writers today knows
anything about fencing? Perez-Reverte does, and his new novel,
``The Fencing Master,'' set in Madrid in 1868, is among other
things a lament for a skill, an art, that has lost its place in
society; gentlemen duelled with pistols then, and they don't duel
at all now.
</P>
<P>
   Don Jaime Astarloa, the fencing master, is the last of a
vanished breed, courtly, well-spoken, old-fashioned, 56 and aging,
down on his luck, devoted to honor, to his art, and to abstract
principles that are also a matter of life and death. He is writing
a treatise on fencing, and his secret is an unstoppable thrust that
he is determined to bring to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Many students have asked the fencing master for his secret, but
he will impart it only to those he deems worthy, and there haven't
been many of them. As ``The Fencing Master'' begins, Don Jaime is
approached by the most unusual applicant of his career, a woman,
Dona Adela de Otero _ dark-haired, violet-eyed, mysterious, a scar
at the right corner of her mouth ``which seemed to impress on the
mouth a permanent, enigmatic smile.'' Dona Adela marshals every
skill of persuasion, but Don Jaime is reluctant to teach her, even
when she raises the stakes. He learns what a skilled fencer she is
in conversation, and then, in a trial lesson, discovers she is an
athlete, an intellectual athlete of extraordinary training, skill,
discipline, cunning, and ruthlessness.
</P>
<P>
   He agrees to teach her; Dona Adela confirms his love of his art,
and awakens turbulent feelings in Don Jaime that he thought he had
put to sleep decades before. What Don Jaime does not know is that
his lessons with Dona Adela will draw him into a murky intrigue in
which nothing is quite what it seems to be _ politics intersect
with revolution; there is deception, revenge, compromising
documents, and murder; sex is a weapon as lethal as an unbuttoned
foil. The moves of the practice studio, the classical thrusts and
parries of fencing, parallel the events outside the studio, much as
chess moves permeate an earlier novel of Perez-Reverte's, ``The
Flanders Panel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fencing Master'' is Perez-Reverte's fourth novel, and his
methods are now familiar. His work, like that of Don Jaime, pays
homage to the 19th-century masters (specifically Dumas) while
extending it along nontraditional lines. He is a careful and
scrupulous researcher who takes considerable pains to get things
right; there is a lot of fencing lore in the new novel _ science,
mathematics, psychology, and mystique. Perez-Reverte has mastered
it so fully that he doesn't feel he needs to supply a primer, to
explain a lot of it, to show us how it looks, how it works. He just
gives us the technical language, like an old-school ballet critic,
or the kind of music critic who (according to George Bernard Shaw's
first editor) was always going on about Bach in B-minor.
</P>
<P>
   This may enthrall some readers as much as it irritates others.
What everyone can agree upon is that he has extraordinary feeling
for place and time, and 19th-century Madrid becomes as much a
presence, and indeed a character, in the novel as contemporary
Seville does in his ``Seville Communion.'' He knows all the
old-fashioned secrets about maintaining a proportion between action
and suspense that keeps the reader engrossed, and he is not averse
to melodrama, mistaken identities, washed-up corpses, a key paper
fallen out of sight, and secrets from the past only now coming to
light.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Perez-Reverte irresistible _ and one of the world's
best-selling writers, now coming into his own in America _ is the
thoroughly modern, intelligent, and sophisticated sensibility that
plays so subtly upon the unsubtle events that are his subject. A
synopsis of a Perez-Reverte plot would be exciting, but not nearly
as interesting as his books, each of which creates a psychological
climate that is the most compelling thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that ``The Fencing Master'' may prove of more
limited interest to readers than ``The Seville Communion'' _ it
lacks the Shakespearean clowning of that book, and all of
Perez-Reverte's considerable skill cannot make 19th-century Spanish
politics as fascinating as the perennial questions of faith and
works that engage and define the characters in the earlier book.
Some of the hinges of the plot creak and need oiling. But the crux
of the matter, as always, is disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Don Jaime is a 19th-century Don Quixote with a mind at once more
modern and more old-fashioned than those around him; he can make
his life meaningful only by making it meaningless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
