<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 3 PLAGUES OF PAINT: PEELING, BLEEDING, AND MOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memorial Day is the traditional day for planting in the garden
because it's the last day of possible frosts. And, it's nice and
warm to be grubbing in the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The merry day, last of the month, is also a good time to start
painting outdoors, although it has been safe to paint for more than
a month.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the rub. Your house looks terrible after just a few
years since the last paint job. It's full of mildew, and the
peeling is horrendous.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge: how to paint the house so all these obnoxious
things don't happen. After all, a professional paint job, can cost
$5,000 to $10,000, a not-so-pretty penny for something that won't
last five years.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways that paint fails, but there are also many
ways to make sure it does not fail in the future.
</P>
<P>
   One preventive measure is to use a top quality paint; bargain
paints just won't hack it. You have to pay for the quality, but in
the long run it is well worth even up to $30 a gallon for a paint
that will perform properly for up to eight years or more.
</P>
<P>
   And that is where John G. Stauffer comes into the picture. He is
director of the Rohm &AMP; Haas Quality Paint Institute of Spring
House, Pa., and is on a tour of the nation, beating the drums for
quality paint and how to solve all those paint problems so many of
us have.
</P>
<P>
   Stauffer uses his own house as a success story on how paint can
work for many years. His is a 1935 tudor with stucco walls and
half-timbering, all painted.
</P>
<P>
   He used an elastomeric paint on the stucco, the best, he said,
for masonry. Elastometric paint is a tough coating that goes on
thick and is elastic (hence the name), expanding and contracting
with the stucco affected by moisture content and temperature. Two
coats are needed.
</P>
<P>
   But for new masonry, Stauffer recommends a seal coat on masonry
less than 30 days old. Surface preparation and caulking of cracks
are also important, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The half-timbering, which was originally stained and varnished,
is now painted a dark brown with acrylic house paint, after the
requisite removal of some or all of the varnish and heavy sanding.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet the paint Stauffer used is of high quality, because
that is the linchpin of his institute, called QPI for short. The
institute, launched in 1989, manufactures raw materials for all
kinds of paints, stains, caulks, inks, sealers, and even roof
tiles. It also consults for paint manufacturers, and maintains
paint and stain testing facilities in different parts of the
nation, each with different climate and weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   And the emphasis is on acrylic (water- based) paints, which
Stauffer says provide good adhesion. They stick, he said. Water
evaporates qauickly, so acrylic paints are fast drying. And, being
resistant to alkalies, they're good for masonry.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us have problems with our painted or stained houses, but
the three most important ones, and most frustrating, are peeling
paint, cedar bleed, and mildew and its prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Peeling paint
</P>
<P>
   This plague has several causes.
</P>
<P>
   1. Old stain and paint will oxidize, said Stauffer, and new
paint over that will fail. Several coats already on the wall can
cause the newest coat to peel, he said. Paint will not stick to
weathered wood, either, or old paint that has exposed weathered
wood.
</P>
<P>
   To combat these problems, sand heavily to remove as much of the
old paint as posisble, and, if posisble, sand enough to reveal new
wood.
</P>
<P>
   Sanding old paint is also important, Stauffer said. It will
smooth out the little craters created by blistering and peeling.
While the sides of these craters are very small, they are enough to
allow primerand/or paint to bridge over them, making the paint coat
very thin on the edges, with resulting premature peeling and wear.
Feather those craters with sandpaper, Stauffer said, and this won't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the primer, said Stauffer. Relatively new but
taking up half the market are latex primers.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion and contraction, due to moisture and temperature
changes, will cause paint to peel. The solution is to sand heavily,
use a high quality paint, and apply it according to label
instructions. So, read the labels and follow the instuctions, said
Stuaffer. Follow the rules as to how thin or thick a coating should
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned more with too thin a coat,'' said Stauffer. If
you apply a paint to cover 500 square feet per gallon as opposed to
the recommended 300 square feet, you are applying it too thinly.
</P>
<P>
   How paint dries can affect its behavior. One that is allowed to
dry before its time will fail. This often happens, Stauffer said,
if the paint is applied on a very hot day, on a breezy day with low
humidity, on a too-cold day, and on a porous surface. So, again,
read the label and follow the instructions, said Stauffer.
</P>
<P>
   Water vapor migrating through the wall from inside the house is
still another factor, and may be a particular plague in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   What happens: Water vapor builds up in the house, makes its way
through the vapor barrier because the barrier has nail holes in it,
goes through insulation, and ends up against the back of the
sheathing boards, where it condenses on those cool boards, coming
through eventually, the claphboards or shingles, pushing the paint
clear off. The symptom of this is paint peeling down to the bare
wood.
</P>
<P>
   A possible cure is to place 1/2-inch Styrofoam insulation on the
outside of the sheathing, under shingles or clapboards. This
insulation will keep the sheathing warm, and water vapor will not
condense. This is normally done with new construction. On a
retrofit, the insulation is installed under new shingles or
clapboards.
</P>
<P>
   And, short of that rather elaborate arrangement, Stauffer said
the proper use of a primer on the clapboards or shingles can help
prevent the water vapor migration through the siding.
</P>
<P>
   The use of stains _ solid latex stains on old paint and bare
wood, and semitransparent stains on bare wood _ can help solve the
problem because the solid stains resist peeling and semitransparent
stains do not, indeed, peel.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar bleed
</P>
<P>
   Cedar bleed, the dreaded brown stains that appear on a painted
surface, are a New England plague because so much red cedar is used
for siding. The bleed is caused by water behind the cedar leaching
out the tannins in the cedar and depositing them _ as brown stains
_ on the surface. White cedar is not as much of a problem because
it contains fewer tannins.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar bleed can be washed off, but it becomes a constant,
paint-in-the-neck maintenance chore.
</P>
<P>
   The bleed is a bigger plague in the Northeast, said Stauffer,
because of the vast amount of red cedar used as siding.
</P>
<P>
   Latex paints are more vulnerable to tannin stains, said
Stauffer. To cure them, apply a primer; latex or oil is acceptable.
In fact, half the primers used today are latex, a far cry from just
a few years ago. Use a latex primer containing zinc oxide.
</P>
<P>
   Two coats of primer should block most tannins, Stauffer said. Do
not prime when it is damp. Read the labels and follow instructions,
he said. That goes for the rule against priming, painting, and
staining under 50 degrees, and for two days after if the
temperature threatens to drop under 50 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Mildew, another plague
</P>
<P>
   Mildew or mold? Look for it, identify it, and treat it, said
Stauffer. It's not hard to find; it appears as black smudges,
spots, stains, and little dots on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Treat it with a solution of one part household bleach and three
parts water. Leave it on for 20 mintues, then scrub with a scrub
brush. It is important to rinse it off for two reasons: Bleach is
incompatible with all finishes. And bleach left on will break down
the oils and fibers of all woods. Rinsing will reduce the damage to
the wood, Stauffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Glossy paints resist mildew better than flat ones, and latex
paints better than oil paints, because there are fewer nutrients in
latex paints for mildew to feed on.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Stauffer, quality paints contain a mildewcide that
will retard the growth of mildew; cheaper paints usually do not
contain mildewcides.
</P>
<P>
   Painting other siding
</P>
<P>
   There is a paint for everything, and that includes asbestos
siding, aluminum siding, and even vinyl siding.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there is no special paint for asbestos siding, said
Stauffer, but old asbestos siding is very absorbent, and needs a
sealer such as masonry sealer to stabilize the surface. Wait
overnight after seealing before painting with an acrylic house
paint.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you have to clean the old siding. With asbestos
siding, do not power-wash or scrub; that could release asbestos
fibers. Instead, wash with a detergent and water and use a sponge
or cloth, and rinse with a hose.
</P>
<P>
   As for aluminum siding, sand it and clean it with detergent and
water, and apply a top quality 100 percent acrylic latex paint,
which has excellent adhesion and good resistance to chalking and
fading.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while vinyl may be final, the colors sometimes can
fade, and vinyl too can be painted. The procedure is similar to
what you'd do with aluminum, but do not sand the vinyl because it
can cause permanent scratches. Use an acrylic latex paint for the
greater flexibility that allows it to expand and contract with the
siding when temperatures change.
</P>
<P>
   The only taboo: Paint vinyl a color that is no darker than the
original. Dark colors tend to absorb heat, which can cause panels
to warp and buckle irreversibly.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now you can enjoy the rest of the long weekend, if you can
stop thinking about those three plagues of paint.
</P>
<P>
   (Peter Hotton is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
