<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Dallas, Ga. _The Battle of Pickett's Mill 135th Annual Living
History Commemoration is Saturday and Sunday at the Pickett's Mill
Battlefield State Historic Site. Re-creations of camp life,
artillery demonstrations, military drills and brief skirmishes.
770-443-7850.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Braselton _ Chateau Elan's Swinging on the Grapevine Summer
Concert Series opens Saturday with the Jesters. Concerts continue
Saturday nights through Aug. 28 in the open-air pavilion next to
the winery. A new feature this year is ``Swing Night'' June 19 with
Zoot and the Swingin' Suits (free swing lessons before the
concert). All shows $25 per person. 770-932-0900 or 1-800-233-9463.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calhoun _ In honor of National Trails Day, New Echota
Historical Site will host Cherokee artist Tommy Wildcat from
Tahlequah, Okla., on Saturday. He will demonstrate river cane flute
music, singing and blowgun shooting. One-hour sessions at 10 a.m.,
1 and 4 p.m. 706-624-1321.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Florence, Ala. _ The 11th annual Frontier Day Celebration at
historic Pope's Tavern Museum is Saturday and Sunday. The outdoor
event celebrates the city's frontier heritage with old-time crafts
demonstrations by costumed interpreters, music by the Shoals
Dulcimer and Folk Music Association and homemade fried pies and
lemonade. 256-760-6439.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hendersonville, N.C. _ The fourth annual Hendersonville Film
Festival, Friday through Sunday, is ``A Celebration of North
Carolina Film &AMP; Filmmakers.'' All films will be shown in the Smoky
Mountain Theater at Lake Pointe Landing Center. 828-697-7310.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The Folk Art Center presents Clay Day on
Saturday, with potters from the Southern Highland Art Guild and the
Odyssey Center for Ceramic Art sharing their skills. 828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williamsburg, Va. _ The Yorktown Victory Center presents a
special exhibition, ``The Washingtons of Colonial Virginia,''
opening Friday. In observance of George Washington's death 200
years ago, the exhibition focuses on the first president's
ancestors in Virginia and their role in the history of the colony
and its government. Through February. 1-888-593-4682.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Roanoke, Va. _ The Roanoke Festival in the Park is Thursday
through Sunday. 540-342-2640 or www.rev.net/festival/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Norfolk, Va. _ The Norfolk Harborfest, through Sunday,
features tall ships, fresh seafood and more. 757-441-2345 or
www.festeventsva.org/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Plains, Va. _ The 18th annual Vintage Virginia Wine
Festival Saturday and Sunday in the Meadow is a presentation of 200
wines from 40 Virginia wineries, plus special rides for children
and live jazz, blues, reggae and rock. 1-800-277-2675.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richmond _ The Virginia Museum of Fine Arts presents the
exhibition ``The Splendors of Egypt,'' a panoramic view of one of
the world's oldest and most sophisticated civilizations, with more
than 200 masterpieces, some 5,000 years old. Through Nov. 28.
804-367-0878 or www.vmfa.state.va.us.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta _ The Container Store is hosting free ``Organized
Traveler'' workshops that include advice on packing and travel
checklists at these store locations: 120 Perimeter Center,
770-351-0065 (1 and 3 p.m. Saturday, 3 p.m. Sunday) and 3255
Peachtree Road N.E., 404-261-4776 (1 and 3 p.m. June 12, 3 p.m.
June 13).
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
