<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY TIES DISTRESS, ALTERNATIVE THERAPY;  
 DISCOURAGING NEWS ON AN AIDS VACCINE;  
 POOR NUTRITION HITS ELDERLY IN HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newly diagnosed breast cancer patients who turn to remedies like
massage, herbs, and relaxation in addition to standard cancer
therapy are more likely to be emotionally distressed than patients
who don't use such remedies, a Harvard study of 480 women shows.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to alternative or complementary medicine appears to be a
marker for anxiety and depression, say Drs. Harold J. Burstein,
Jane C. Weeks, and their colleagues from Harvard Medical School and
the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in this week's New England Journal
of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, all the women had similar mental health
characteristics, according to their recollections of how they felt
before diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   But three months after surgery, the use of alternative therapies
was greatest among those with more depression, fear of cancer
recurrence, and lower scores on questionnaires about mental health,
sexual functioning, and physical symptoms. The tendency for more
distressed women to seek complementary therapy was independent of
the type of standard cancer care they received and their prognoses.
(All had relatively early, stage I or II breast cancer.)
</P>
<P>
   There was no difference in distress indicated by the type of
complementary therapy sought, the researchers add. Women either
tended to use several complementary approaches, or none.
</P>
<P>
   By 12 months after diagnosis, most patients, whether they used
complementary remedies or not, were happier, although those who had
turned to nontraditional remedies still reported less sexual
satisfaction and more fear of recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   The findings contrast with the view that people who seek
alternative remedies are ``self-assertive, psychologically strong,
and well-adjusted,'' notes Dr. Jimmie Holland, a psychiatrist at
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York in an
accompanying editorial.
</P>
<P>
   These women ``were not psychologically strong. On the contrary,
they turned to alternative medicine to alleviate their distress,''
she writes. Doctors should recognize this, she says, and offer
counseling to people who use complementary medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraging news on an AIDS vaccine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Australian researchers studying people infected with a mild
strain of the AIDS virus that scientists had hoped to use as a
vaccine have found that some of those patients now show signs of
immune damage, discouraging news for AIDS vaccine developers.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the New England Journal of Medicine,
does not entirely dash hope that live, attenuated versions of the
mutant strain could be used as a vaccine, said Dr. John Sullivan, a
University of Massachusetts pediatrician and AIDS researcher,
though it does mean ``a single gene deletion does not attentuate
the virus enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But the study does provide ``another cautionary note with
respect to the use of live attenuated HIV strains as vaccines,''
says an editorial accompanying the report.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, 13 people in Australia got transfusions from
a donor infected with an AIDS virus missing a gene called ``nef.''
Eight became infected. The transfusions occurred before there were
tests to detect the virus in donated blood.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the eight have died: two from causes unrelated to AIDS
and one from possibly unrelated causes. The five others and the
donor have been symptom free for 14 years, evidence that the mutant
virus is slower to wreak havoc than the common forms.
</P>
<P>
   Three still have undetectable viral loads, but the other three
now have detectable virus and decreasing immune cells.
</P>
<P>
   Poor nutrition hits elderly in hospitals &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many hospitalized elderly patients get such poor nutrition that
they may be at increased risk of death, a study in this week's
Journal of the American Medical Association shows.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Little Rock, Ark., studied 497 patients age 65
or older who were hospitalized for at least four days. The patients
were equally sick and had similar blood levels of a protein called
albumin, often used to gauge nutritional status.
</P>
<P>
   But in the hospital, one in five got so little to eat, often
because their doctors ordered ``nothing by mouth'' and did not
offer alternatives such as feeding by intravenous or stomach tubes,
that they got less than half the calories they needed.
</P>
<P>
   The poorly nourished patients were eight times more likely to
die in the hospital than those who got adequate calories and three
times as likely to die in the 90 days after discharge.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear which comes first, poor nutrition or
worsening medical status, says Dr. Dennis H. Sullivan, director of
the geriatric research, education and clinical center at the
Central Arkansas Veterans Healthcare System. But he says doctors
should boost nutritional intake whenever possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
