<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGTRUCK-SALES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES DRIVING SALES OF BIG-CAB TRUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JIM THORPE, Pa. _ The big pickup truck rumbles along a high
ridge here in what used to be the heart of coal country. It
scampers over rocks, splashes through the big pools of water that
the locals call ``sips,'' and rolls easily through muck and gravel.
</P>
<P>
   As it breaks from the woods, the four-door, V8 engine,
six-passenger Toyota Tundra is shifted from 4- to 2-wheel-drive.
When it hits the pavement, it runs as smoothly and as quietly as
any family sedan. New this year, the Tundra will be the first
foreign challenge to absolute domestic dominance of the big truck
market in North America. It is a market that Sandy Allen
Lobenstein, a senior market planner for Toyota, calls ``the
largest, most competitive, most lucrative segment in the auto
industry today.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look in the rearview mirror now, but the next set of
lights looming high behind you may not be a trendy SUV. Instead, it
will probably be a big-cab, four-door pickup truck, carrying a
family of six on its way to a soccer game or a campsite. All the
major US truck manufacturers are rapidly expanding their capacity
to build them.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps even more significant is that even makers of luxury
cars are looking to satisfy the growing demand for big-cab pickups.
Lincoln will build one and call it the Blackwood, essentially its
Navigator SUV with a cargo bed, and industry reports say even
Cadillac will match it with a pickup/SUV of its own.
</P>
<P>
   These trucks, once the virtually sole domain of construction
crews, are becoming a family vehicle of choice across the country.
People saw the trucks and realized a big cab with four doors and
seating for six and a pickup bed on the back ``meets the demands of
the whole day,'' says Al Giombetti, the group truck brand manager
for Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   He says customers justify the purchase this way: ``It's got
versatility and utility: I can use it for work, to go to the
restaurant, to pick up my kids at soccer _ and I can also carry
sheets of plywood in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giombetti says the trend started with an industry innovation
aimed at a narrow niche, but mushroomed into a broad customer
expectation. And it is a wave within a wave. In 1998, Americans
bought more vans, pickup trucks, and SUVs than they did cars.
Pickups alone, in the first quarter of this year, accounted for
46.3 percent of General Motors sales; 60.6 percent of Ford sales;
and 70.3 percent of the Chrysler portion (which includes Dodge
trucks) of the newly merged Daimler-Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is the industry's largest seller of pickup trucks, and when
it offered a four-door option on its F-series of trucks for the
1996-97 model year, that option accounted for just 5 percent of
truck sales. By the 98 model year, it was up to 30 percent. By the
end of 1999, Ford predicts it will be 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At Dodge, 71 percent of the sales of its popular Ram pickup are
big-cab models, and 90 percent of those are four-door. By the end
of this year the company will add the four-door option to its
Dakota series of trucks.
</P>
<P>
   And Chevrolet, which in the past year saw its pickup sales go
from 486,000 to 686,000 _ even though its primary entry in the
big-cab market was a three-door _ will offer a four-door version of
its Silverado for 2000, complete with a full back seat and
headrests. In addition, the company, which acknowledges it
underestimated the pickup truck market last year, will offer a
Blazer model with a pickup bed, and a variation of the Suburban
that will also have a bed, Ron Zarella, president of GM North
America, told Automotive News this week.
</P>
<P>
   Four-door ``crew cab'' trucks, with full-size doors that open
toward the front like car doors, have been around for years, but
they tended to be loud, spartan, utilitarian brutes. The new,
better-riding, and quieter truck has large doors for front-seat
passengers, and smaller doors, which open toward the rear, for
back-seat riders. And some companies _ Ford among them with a 2001
SuperCrew _ are preparing elegant models of the old crew-cab style
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The shift, say industry analysts, is part of an evolution as
American car buyers moved from minivans to SUVs. They liked the
ability of minivans to cart kids around. They liked the ability of
SUVs to not only carry whole families and gear in comfort, but also
the safety their height and size offer and the performance of
four-wheel-drive in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   And then they noticed the big-cab, four-door pickups, which
offered all these things, plus a bed in back to haul lumber for
weekend building projects, manure for gardens, stones for walls,
bags and buckets for trips to the recycling center, and, with a cap
or tarp added, camping and other recreational gear _ all while the
entire family rides in sedan-like comfort. In addition, these
trucks, from the mid-teens to high $20,000 range, are often priced
$10,000 or lower than comparable wagon-like SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   The utility of the truck is precisely what lured Glenn Fiore of
Norwell, Mass., out of his two-door SUV and behind the wheel of a
Ford F-150 SuperCab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed more doors. I needed a pickup truck,'' says the
father of two, who works in building maintenance at Harvard
University and has projects going on around the house every
weekend. ``Plus, my son Michael always wanted a truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Quirk, the manager at Quirk Ford in Quincy, Mass., where
Fiore bought his truck, says he saw the shift in truck sales start
about three years ago, when big cabs had two doors, ``then they
went to three, and now they've gone to four _ and that's because of
the families that want them.''
</P>
<P>
   Toyota's entry, even its competitors acknowledge, is a sign that
it is a strong market. The Tundra, Toyota's first V8, is the size
of the base-level big trucks. The company will produce 100,000
vehicles at a plant in Indiana, thus avoiding high import fees, for
the 2000 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Hoyt, a Toyota spokesman, tells the story of how Toyota
came to produce a V8.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from Japan were meeting with American dealers and
talking about a new truck, Hoyt says, when one dealer rose and
said, ``If you don't have a V8, you might as well go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the strength of the big-engine, big-cab truck market in
this country, a vehicle ``unique to North America,'' says Toyota's
Lobenstein. He calls the market ``easy to identify, but difficult
to win over'' because of brand loyalty that is passed down through
the generations. If your father was a Chevy man, or Ford or Dodge,
then so were you.
</P>
<P>
   But trucks are not just for men anymore, and women are either
buying them _ many for a sense of safety or for convenience _ or
telling their husbands that if they want a truck, it's got to be a
truck the whole family can ride in.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that ``women in particular like sitting up
higher'' for reasons of safety, says Dan Hubbert, a spokesman for
Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   David Bostswick, the director of corporate market research for
Dodge, likens the switch from two-door, single-seat trucks to the
switch people _ mostly men _ had to make from two-passenger sports
cars to sedans and vans once they had families.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to be able to justify it, or else it was just a matter
of indulgence,'' he says of vehicles that, while fun, were not
practical for families. Many owners had to give up their sports car
fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Bostwick says that ruggedly individualistic pickup drivers
either found or were directed to another route: the big cab,
four-door, six-passenger truck. Gone are the days when dad can't
stop to pick up the kids from soccer on his way home from the
lumberyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you can be a rugged individual father,'' Bostwick says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
