<HEADLINE>
NASCAR BRINGS A LITTLE HOWYABEEN TO NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Welcome Race Fans.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sign you see in little towns and larger cities out on the
spokes that lead to the hub that is Loudon, N.H., home of New
Hampshire International Speedway, New England's largest sports
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the howdy, howyabeen, family atmosphere that
big-time NASCAR racing has brought to New England, and you'll find
the signs all the way up near the Canadian border, over near the
Maine coast, virtually everywhere New Hampshire touches another
border.
</P>
<P>
   Around 100,000 people pour into Loudon for each of the two
Winston Cup races held there each summer, forming a large,
informed, transitory and _ surprise to cynics of the sport _
wealthy city. The median family income at these races at the top of
the sport is around $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the wonderful world of wheels, there are many cliques: sports
car savants, muscle car mavens, antique car buffs. And all of these
break down into cliques of their own. Even in the world of
motorcycles, cliques can be snobbish little groups: Harley riders
don't like riders of Japanese bikes; BMW riders try to set
themselves aside; riders of old Harleys look down on riders of the
new Evo Harleys and complain of this new, richer breed of rider _
never mind that had this new breed not come along to buy the bikes,
there would likely be no Harley-Davidson company &UR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  I'm thinking about cliques because it has long disturbed me
that many of the more self-proclaimed ``classy'' breed of auto
enthusiasts have long looked down on stock car racing fans. In
concert with elitists who know nothing about cars or racing, they
see stock car fans as a bunch of toothless goobers with low IQs.
</P>
<P>
   Talk radio in Boston makes fun of them; coverage of the sport _
except when the Winston Cup races are held at Loudon _ can be
sporadic across the media spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wants to watch a bunch of cars go round and round?'' is
the common cynic's question.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the athleticism (that's right, athleticism) of
drivers who endure heat, fatigue, pounding, noise and pressures
that would challenge any athlete from any sport _ and probably
leave your average football lineman dehydrated and prostrate.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the wonderful teamwork that a crew must weave from
the moment it arrives at the track early on race week to the
split-second differences they can make in all-important pit stops.
</P>
<P>
   And never mind the sophisticated engineering and technology and
body sculpting that is fine-tuned day after day.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is as much to be written about tuning a Winston Cup
engine, setting up a suspension, adjusting tires, as there is to be
written about any expensive sports car or muscle car or antique or
exotic.
</P>
<P>
   And to tell you the truth, more Americans can relate to a
Winston Cup car, a Busch series car, even a converted Camaro racing
around a dirt track somewhere in Maine than they can to any of the
above.
</P>
<P>
   Industry and business knows this; even the auto magazines
favored by nonrace fans have come to the realization. Motor Trend
and Car and Driver have expanded race sections.
</P>
<P>
   AutoWeek, an industry trade journal, has a section at its back
devoted to racing. Last week's issue featured a story on the France
and Penske racing families merging their tracks, which include
Daytona, Talladega, Phoenix, Darlington, Watkins Glen, California,
Michigan and North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The ad on the back cover of the magazine showed Pontiac Racing's
Interstate Batteries race car with the proclamation, ``Wider is
Better.'' Beneath it was a Widetrack Pontiac Grand Prix, a consumer
vehicle. Under the skin, the cars have nothing in common, but from
the flared-nostril nose, up and over the roofline, they look much
the same. And that is testimony to the adage developed over the
last three decades of auto racing: ``Win on Sunday. Sell on
Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just the auto industry that has spotted the
economic potential of race fans _ 40 percent of whom are women, by
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Studies done for advertisters show that nearly three-quarters of
NASCAR fans say they buy the products they see advertised on their
favorite cars or racetrack walls. Basketball? It gets 38 percent
product fan support.
</P>
<P>
   And at nearly $500 million each year in sponsorship money,
NASCAR racing takes in more than professional baseball, football,
basketball and hockey combined.
</P>
<P>
   There has long been a national obsession with wheels and speed _
is Steve McQueen's car chase in the movie ``Bullitt'' a scene that
thrilled film afficianados, really so different from watching a
good race on a track?
</P>
<P>
   This is why, at hundreds of tracks around the country every
year, families gather on weekend nights for hours of racing. From
little spots like Spud Speedway up in Aroostook County, Maine, to
Unity Raceway in Unity, Maine, to other small tracks across New
England, and right up to the big one, Loudon, it happens here.
</P>
<P>
   It is exciting. It is family entertainment. And its fans are not
a bunch of toothless goobers.
</P>
<P>
   So let's occasionally bring some racing to this column on
Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   We won't talk race results or favorite drivers or point
standings.
</P>
<P>
   But let's meet some of the folks who run crews for drivers like
Jeff Gordon or Dale Earnhardt. Let's meet the guys who change the
tires and fill the tanks in those hotflash pitstops.
</P>
<P>
   Let's find out what's in a NASCAR engine, how you tune it, how
long it lasts. And what about aerodynamics, tire pressure, tire
wear, suspension setups? How do you build one of these cars from
the ground up?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, maybe we'll even take one out for a spin and share the ride
with you in this column.
</P>
<P>
   Because, in the world of Automobilia, there is a place for this;
there is a place because race cars have wheels and have engines and
have fans who want to know how one powers the other.
</P>
<P>
   So today, because there is a place for race fans, let's erect
another one of those signs that welcomes you under this big tent.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome Race Fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
