<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1554 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-CHUASIRIPORN-BOS &LR;      06-03 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CHUASIRIPORN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW PRO WITH AN OPEN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ As she made her way from the 16th green to
the 17th tee Tuesday at Old Waverly Golf Club, Jenny Chuasiriporn
stopped and signed dozens of autographs. Her playing partners
waited patiently on the tee, and when Chuasiriporn arrived, one of
them had some friendly advice: ``You should shorten your name.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn laughed and showed off the pleasant smile that had
made the golf world take notice a year ago. Her improbable run as
an amateur at the US Women's Open last July, punctuated by a 40- to
50-foot birdie putt on the 72d hole to force a playoff, is fresh on
everyone's mind as the 54th renewal of the most prestigious
championship in women's golf got under way here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed for this daughter of Thai immigrants. She is
now a professional and while the game is still golf, many of the
dynamics have changed. Refreshingly, it is a process she has not
jumped into.
</P>
<P>
   ``No logos on me,'' she said. ``No rush. There'll be time.''
</P>
<P>
   At 21, Chuasiriporn is still innocent enough to think tomorrow
is a long way away. Too many others know better, so they are
reaching for a piece of her now, while the image of her dramatic
play last year is a hot commodity. Last July, she stood on the 18th
hole at Blackwolf Run in Wisconsin, shocked, almost apologetic as
her putt rolled in. Though she lost to Se Ri Pak on the 20th
playoff hole, Chuasiriporn captivated our hearts and reminded us
that the soul of the game does not revolve around money.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, there are still those reminders. Like her
golf bag, which has not yet become a corporate billboard,
displaying only the Duke University logo on the side. And her
brother Joey, who will carry her bag again this week. And her clubs
are still Callaway because she has this idea that she has done OK
by them to this point. There is a small incentive deal with
Titleist, said Chuasiriporn, but for the most part she has tried to
push all this to the side while she concentrates on golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense of disappointment (that she lost the playoff
last year), but I am just a big believer in things happening for a
reason,'' she said. ``I could kind of go back and imagine had I
won, and it would have just been really hectic.''
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity did more than knock on her door last year; it kicked
the thing in. But Chuasiriporn wanted no part of the quick money
that surely would have been tossed at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing in me that wanted to turn pro at that
time,'' said Chuasiriporn, who returned to Duke for her senior year
and helped lead the Blue Devils to the national championship. It
accomplished a personal goal, though she concedes that her play was
not up to her high standards. ``I was kind of distracted a little
bit, with the golf side and the school side. I took a little break
in the winter, and it always takes me a couple of months to get
back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a concession to the pro life, Chuasiriporn spent a lot of
time deciding on a management company before settling on Pros,
Inc., run by Vinny Giles. People who know her say it was agonizing
for her because in a short period of time she had made lots of
friends. Saying no did not come easy to her.
</P>
<P>
   That decision made and her collegiate career completed, the
recipe for Chuasiriporn has been simple. ``Focus. Visualize. Forget
mechanics,'' said Ted Sheftic.
</P>
<P>
   A professional instructor in Hanover, Pa., Sheftic was
introduced to a 12-year-old Chuasiriporn and has been her only
teacher. He had two televisions set up in his home last July so he
wouldn't miss a minute of the playoff, but this year he's taken
time off to be at the Open in person.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Sheftic about Chuasiriporn and he doesn't talk about
one-piece takeaways or ball-striking or great rhythm. ``She has a
great smile, doesn't she?'' he said. ``She's such a great kid. No
regrets about last year. She told me she wasn't ready to win. She
said, `I'll win someday. I'm just happy for Se Ri.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The world of women's professional golf, it appears, is happy to
have Chuasiriporn, though there are warnings about what lies ahead.
``I'm sure she'll feel a lot of pressure,'' said Nancy Lopez, who
can relate to Chuasiriporn's situation. As an 18-year-old amateur,
Lopez finished second in the Women's Open. Two years later, she
made her pro debut at the 1977 Open and finished second again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first turn professional and you're out here, and
after having the Open that she had last year, she is probably going
to have more pressure than a lot of people. I think probably more
so from herself,'' said Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   This is not lost on Chuasiriporn. ``I realize there is a lot of
expectations. I ran into a little problem toward the end of my
college career because I did have a lot of expectations. But I
learned so much from that. You can't really golf with all those
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Learning curve
</P>
<P>
   To ease into the pro world, Chuasiriporn asked her brother to
carry her bag again. They are very close, and he has been with her
at both US Women's Opens in which she has made noteworthy splashes.
(At Pumpkin Ridge in 1997, Chuasiriporn was low amateur.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been busy, very busy for her,'' said Joey, a scratch
golfer who played at Penn State. ``But she's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared so Tuesday during her practice round at Old Waverly
when Chuasiriporn showed off the game that nearly made her just the
second amateur to win the Women's Open. Consistently she hit it
15-20 yards inside of her playing partners, veteran LPGA players
Cindy Figg-Currier and LaRee Sugg. She usually hits irons into the
par 4s, whereas many of her opponents must hit 5- and 7-woods.
</P>
<P>
   She also took note of her mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-4 sixth, a 348-yarder that doglegs right and leaves
you an approach from an elevated fairway, Chuasiriporn dropped her
second shot into a bunker. She dropped another ball and put that
shot into the rough. A third try. This one pin high, 8 feet left.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hit a half-wedge, then three-quarters,'' said Sheftic.
``Then a full wedge. Now she knows, it's a full wedge to get it to
the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuasiriporn also knows that while it's the Open, there is much
more ahead. Already, she has accepted sponsor's exemptions into
three consecutive events beginning July 1 _ Jamie Farr Kroger
Classic, Michelob Light Classic, and JAL Big Apple Classic. Barring
the long shot _ that she wins one of these events or earns enough
money to gain her card _ Chuasiriporn accepts the prospects of
playing on the Futures Tour and going to Tour School in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But that's getting too far ahead. She doesn't think last year's
performances should necessarily make her a favorite this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I really care about is I want to hit the ball well,'' said
Chuasiriporn. ``I am not really worried about finishing a certain
way again.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey has pro aspirations himself and Tuesday he will play in
Summit, N.J., in an effort to qualify for the men's US Open at
Pinehurst, N.C. It would be nice to prepare, he said, but his
loyalty to his sister comes first.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just wants to tee it up. I think she'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she'd be more comfortable when her parents _ Pornpimol
and Supoj _ come in from Baltimore with her 11-year-old brother
Jimmy. They flew in Wednesday, having closed the family restaurant,
The Bangkok Place, for just the second time ever. The first time,
naturally, was a result of the Blackwolf theatrics.
</P>
<P>
   This US Women's Open stuff may be good for her golf career, but
it's hurting the family business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
