<HEADER>
A1557 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-03 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING TO LIVE WITH CELLULITE IS A HARD PILL TO SWALLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's ``The One and Only Cellasene,'' a dietary supplement that
helps eliminate cellulite, or so its distributor, Rexall Sundown,
claims.
</P>
<P>
   I bought it even though I know that ridding the female body of
cellulite by taking a pill is almost certainly an impossible dream.
It was an impulse purchase. A sign in the drugstore announced:
``The product that caused riots in Australia.'' There was no
rioting at my local drug store, but there were only two packages of
the stuff left, and I decided I'd better grab some while I could.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian riots broke out when rumors of a Cellasene
shortage began circulating. What if the same thing were to happen
here? I didn't want to chance being trampled by a herd of
cellulite-crazed women.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, who will remain nameless if I value my life, has been
taking Cellasene for nearly three weeks. Has she noticed any
change? ``I think maybe yes,'' she says. ``But it could be all in
my head.''
</P>
<P>
   If only cellulite were all in our heads. Unfortunately, it's all
on our thighs and backsides. It's the bane of the female body, even
the slim female body. Women of every size and shape are plagued by
cellulite. The connective tissue that separates a woman's muscles
from her skin is shaped like a honeycomb. Fat gathers in these
little pockets and the result is cellulite. It has been described
as looking like orange peel, or cottage cheese, or sponge. It's not
pretty.
</P>
<P>
   Men don't get cellulite. Men's connective tissue doesn't dimple.
It just lies there, maddeningly smooth.
</P>
<P>
   In the package are 30 blood-red Cellasene softgels, each big
enough to choke a goat. The recommended dosage is three pills a
day, after meals. The 30 pills cost $37, about $1.23 each.
According to the instructions, ``benefits are best realized after 8
weeks of continuous use.'' Which adds up to $206.64, or $103.32 per
thigh. Then there's maintenance, one pill a day forever, or until
your cellulite totally disappears, which basically amounts to the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   How is Cellasene supposed to work? An explanation on the
distributor's Web site is somewhat vague, claiming that the product
increases blood flow and metabolic rate, thus ``freeing'' trapped
fat and eliminating cellulite. Cellasene is a dietary supplement,
not a drug. The ingredients include gingko biloba, borage, sweet
clover, fish and vegetable oils, and bladderwrack, which isn't the
potent diuretic its name implies but an iodine-rich sea vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   But does Cellasene work? Reports in the Washington Post and
elsewhere have quoted Cellasene's inventor, Italian chemist
Gianfranco Merizzi, claiming that his product doesn't just reduce
the appearance of cellulite, it ``cures'' the condition. But
Merizzi's critics in the medical community say that his unpublished
studies of the product are unreliable. The word ``fraud'' has been
bandied about in connection with the product. Obesity expert Dr.
Michael Rosenbaum, associate professor of clinical medicine at
Columbia University and coauthor of a recently published study on
cellulite, has been widely quoted as saying that Cellasene simply
doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever seems to go broke marketing cellulite-related
remedies and nostrums. Herbal wraps. Rubber undergarments.
Massagers. Firming creams and lotions. Now Cellasene. No wonder
there were riots in Australia when women feared the supply was
running out. If any cellulite eliminator really worked, could there
ever be enough to go around?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we should try to look at cellulite in a different light,
try to view it as a sign of beauty. Or perhaps not. We may have to
learn to live with our cellulite, but learning to love it is a lot
to ask.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; (Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
