<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
HEADS TURN, TRAFFIC STOPS IN HOMAGE TO HUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
 AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you emerge from the local store and spot a pair of legs
protruding from beneath your automobile, it means one of two
things: 1. You weren't paying enough attention when you drove in
and you will soon be discussing the mishap with the authorities, or
2. You drive a Hummer.
</P>
<P>
   There he was, feet sticking out beneath the driver's side door,
scrambling out when he heard the driver approach. Sorry, he said,
just had to see what it looked like underneath. Drive a Hummer and
trips take longer than most _ trips to the drug store, the
supermarket, a North Country campground. You need to build in time
to socialize with those who want to talk about your Hummer.
</P>
<P>
   It is a growling, crawling, eye-catching rig, and at more than
seven feet wide and distinctly military in its bearing, AM General
Corp.'s Hummer may be the most recognizeable vehicle on American
roads.
</P>
<P>
   And that is remarkable given that, ever since it went into
civilian production for the 1992 model year, only 6,500 of them
have been sold. Of course, appearances of the military version _
the High Mobility Multi-purpose Wheeled Vehicle (hence, HUMVEE) _
on American television screens during the Gulf War helped tenderize
us for the civilian model.
</P>
<P>
   So did the Hummer's appearance in such action films as
``Independence Day,'' ``Broken Arrow,'' and a half dozen others in
the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   The civilian Hummers share the same driveline, chassis, and
basic body construction with the 170,000 military beasts AM General
has built since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   We are fascinated, but most of us will never ride in one and far
fewer will ever drive or own one. So let's go for a spin.
</P>
<P>
   Settle into the driver's cockpit _ and with the wraparound dash,
comfortable leather seat, shift levers and myriad display gauges
and switches, it feels like you're in an airplane. There are round,
analog gauges for fuel supply, engine temperature, oil pressure, a
voltmeter, speedomoter, tachometer and a clock.
</P>
<P>
   A backlit ``status center'' lights up to report on a range of
features from coolant supply to lights to drive train operation.
There are no-nonsense push switches for wipers and lights and a
switch to change from main diesel fuel tank (25 gallons) to
auxiliary (17 gallons). There is even a switch, with gauges for
front and rear tires, to deflate the tires for running on soft sand
and reinflate them, using a built-in compressor, on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   While the driver has plenty of room, this four-passenger
hardtop, with small pickup bed, seats the passengers in tight
quarters. But packed in may be a good thing when the Hummer gets
offroad, and lowrange, first gear gives its four tires the feel of
creeping steel dozer tracks rather than rubber tires.
</P>
<P>
   To take the offroad pounding, the Hummer has four-wheel, fully
indepenent suspension and heavy duty springs. It has 16 inches of
clearance, a low-center of gravity, and massive shock absorbers.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension not only lets the cab bounce stiffly (yet
comfortably) up and down, but also back and forth, a sensation I
had not felt since riding in a big Diamond Reo hauling a gasoline
tanker from New Hampshire to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to its offroad bite are geared hubs at each wheel for a
gear reduction of almost 2:1. To picture this, think of your
bicycle, which shifts down to more teeth on the front sprocket, but
can then also shift to more teeth on the back for extra torque.
</P>
<P>
   Its TorqTrac 4 system senses wheel slippage and transfers torque
to the wheels with the most purchase.
</P>
<P>
   All of which asks the question: Where will it go?
</P>
<P>
   Almost anywhere. Put its front tires against a 22-inch vertical
step along the trail and the rear wheels will follow. It will run
through 30 inches of water (the doors have rubber seals and the air
intake sits above the hood), a foot-and-a-half of mud, three feet
of snow. It will climb 30-degree hills (and probably more, though
the builder does not promote this feature).
</P>
<P>
   It does it all with a snarly, sure dexterity, and in New
England, where the woods are thick, the biggest danger is that what
is inside and underneath this vehicle is capable of taking it
places that endanger the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Can you get it stuck? Yes, even a bulldozer can get stuck, so
stick the Hummer's wheels on one side in enough mud that the wheels
on the other don't have any purchase and you are stuck. Been there,
done that. But that is a hazard with any offroad driving and the
Hummer should not be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   To get offroad, you need to travel overroad, and since, I
suspect, many Hummers don't get all that far offroad, you need to
ask how it does on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   It's loud. Diesel engines and great, knobby tires do not lend to
a quiet ride. It gives off a steady hum at lower speeds and it gets
louder, even as it cruises smoothly at 70 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   It's not quick (0-60 in 18 seconds) and that can be problematic
in merging into traffic on highways as you come up the exit ramp.
Because of its size, drivers whizzing by tend to let it in; a
smaller car accelerating this slowly would spend a lot of time
waiting for the right opening.
</P>
<P>
   But once it gets moving, it is fine on the highway, though it
shouldn't linger in the passing lane on today's highways, where
speeds of 80 and higher are common.
</P>
<P>
   In about 10 days of driving, from commuting to Boston from New
Hampshire to some pretty heavy offroad testing, it averaged about
11.5 per gallon of diesel fuel. A gasoline engine would do far
worse and that may be why Hummer does not offer a gasoline model
any longer.
</P>
<P>
   At prices from $60,000 to more than $90,000, this is a pricey
toy (and I can't imagine having it as my sole transportation). It's
built for a niche, within a niche, within a niche. But for those
folks, it is truly an amazing piece of machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   _ Hummer should find a better use for the large, flat deck that
separates the two rear seats. Storage? A jump seat option?
</P>
<P>
   _ At prices approaching $100,000, the Hummer ought to have a
radio that has decent AM reception.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches:
</P>
<P>
   _ Overhead lights whose lenses are also the switches that turn
them on and off.
</P>
<P>
   _ The web straps connecting door to cab beside the hinges. Open
one of these broad doors in a stiff wind and it could be torn off.
The straps prevent that.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers
</P>
<P>
   Base price: $78,887
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $91,523
</P>
<P>
   Horsepower/Torque:195 hp/430 lbs.-ft.
</P>
<P>
   Wheelbase/Overall length:130 inches/184.5inches
</P>
<P>
   Width/Height:86.5 inches/75 inches
</P>
<P>
   Curb weight:6,760 lbs.
</P>
<P>
   Seating:4 passengers
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1523EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
