<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     06-03 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUCONY FINDS SHOE THAT FITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early spring of last year, when the world was still awash
in excess inventory of Nike sneakers, John Fisher placed his faith
in 1981 technology to get sales moving again at Saucony Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Peabody, Mass., company, which was still known as Hyde
Athletic Industries Inc. at that time, tried to make the tricky
leap from performance shoes to fashion statements and latched on to
a powerful ``retro'' trend that has propelled Saucony stock.
</P>
<P>
   Saucony shares have more than tripled since February to 16 1/2
and peaked last week at 18 3/4. The stock had been stuck in a
narrow price band of 4 to 6 per share for nearly five years before
the move. The catalyst: first quarter earnings that more than
tripled and a powerful sales growth trend still in full force.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about sneaker companies playing the fickle
and sometimes dangerous market for hot shoe fashions, but Saucony
seemed like the last company you would expect to give it a try.
</P>
<P>
   Saucony reintroduced its Jazz running shoes, which helped build
the company's reputation for high-performance products when they
first hit the market 18 years ago. The original Jazz can't compete
with today's running shoes on technology, but they are still
comfortable and fit well. Priced in the $40 to $60 range, they were
a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started to kick in over the last nine months, but it didn't
really become apparent before the last six months,'' said analyst
Jennifer Black of Black &AMP; Co., who initiated coverage of Saucony
with a ``buy'' rating in May.
</P>
<P>
   A company that was accustomed to placing ads in Runner's World
started to showcase its Jazz Originals in magazines like Spin, Vibe
and XXL.
</P>
<P>
   How different is this world from Saucony's traditional clinetele
of serious jocks? The line got perhaps its biggest boost when it
was featured as part of a fashion forecast in an issue of Teen
People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher, the chief executive at Saucony, won't say he's in
the fashion business. He's reluctant to even use the word. ``Style
driven is the term we use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a good reason for his reticence. Shoe fashions can
change on a dime. The retro trend favoring a return to oldies,
which Fisher ascribes to products from the Volkswagen Beetle to Gap
kakhis, may be in style today but surely not indefinitely.
Athletic-shoe companies lime Reebok International Ltd. that make a
fortune in fashion typically fall hard when they go out of style
and choke on inventories of footware no one wants to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to this type of selling is to be on board, not
overboard,'' said Fisher. ``If you trace some of the problems of
the top-tier (athletic-shoe) vendors, you'll find inventory glut
became a real stumbling block. We're not large enough to sustain
the kinds of hits inventory glut can cause and we want to learn
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Saucony assembles and manufactures most of its shoes at a
factory in Bangor, Maine, and is making Jazz Originals in volume
only to match orders. Fisher is making the shoes relatively scarce
to limit inventory and maintain the allure of the brand, which now
comes in many variations. ``We are taking essentially a zero
inventory position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saucony's other business lines, which include shoes for running
and walking, high-end bicycles and sportsware, are doing just fine.
But Fisher said 44 percent of all the company's year-to-year sales
growth and most of the company's backorders are for Jazz Originals.
</P>
<P>
   All that begs the question, what's in it for investors who buy
Saucony shares now? Even if the company completely escapes the
fashion inventory trap, the engine behind its growth can't last
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Among other problems: liquidity in Saucony stock is terrible.
The company only has 6.3 million shares outstanding and trades just
20,000 on a typical day. Fisher owns about 22 percent of the stock
and his brother-in-law, chief operating officer Charles Gottesman,
holds another 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher agrees liquidity of Saucony stock is an issue for
investors. As for sales growth, he insists there is plenty of
opportunity for more ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz Originals are still spreading across the country and
international sales are virtually untapped. More importantly, the
Jazz success has created visibility for Saucony that it never had
before.
</P>
<P>
   Saucony shoes, which had been in about 200 Foot Locker stores,
are sold in about 1400 stores today, according to Fisher. Its shoes
are available in 900 Lady Foot Lockers, up from 600 historically.
</P>
<P>
   Even if fashions change, the broader exposure to Saucony's brand
will boost sales well into the future, Fisher thinks. ``It will
raise the brand, in the worst case, far beyond what it was when we
started,'' he said. ``We think there's a lot of mileage in front of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
