<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS GORE TRAILING BUSH, DOLE IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Long before the attack ads, televised debates
and campaign rallies, California voters lean toward Republicans
George W. Bush and Elizabeth Dole as their choice over Democratic
Vice President Al Gore, according to a poll released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The survey shows Bush and Dole with solid support among female
voters in head-to-head matchups with Gore, providing the chance for
Republicans to overcome the so-called gender gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a window of opportunity ... to close the gender gap
and get women voters,'' said Del Ali of Research 2000 in Rockville,
Md., which conducted the poll for the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the governor of Texas, and Dole, the former president of
the American Red Cross, still face a formidable challenge in
balancing their moderate images to sustain the support of women
voters while at the same time satisfying conservatives who dominate
the party nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that if the election were held now, Bush would
lead Gore 49 percent to 44 percent, with 7 percent undecided. Dole,
pitted against Gore, was favored by 48 percent of those surveyed to
46 percent for the vice president _ a statistical dead heat _ with
6 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bush-Gore contest, women voters favored the vice
president 46 percent to 45 percent with 9 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   When Dole was matched against Gore, she was chosen by 51 percent
of the women to 43 percent for Gore with 6 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The poll comes more than nine months before the California
presidential primary and well before the general election, a point
Gore's spokesman was quick to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are like 17 months away from the general election,'' said
Roger Salazar, Gore's campaign spokesman. ``Many people have not
had an opportunity to focus on the candidates, what they stand for
and what they're all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very confident that as we get the vice president out
there to talk about his issues, and his ideas for the American
people and where he wants to take them, people will respond in a
very positive way,'' Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has visited California more than 50 times since he and
President Clinton won election to their first term in 1992, will
again visit the state as part of a national campaign swing after he
formally launches his candidacy for president on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 810 Californians who vote regularly in statewide
elections was conducted May 27 to 29. It has a margin of error of
plus or minus 3.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifty-two percent of those surveyed said Clinton was doing an
excellent or good job, the same number as an Examiner poll in
September 1998 at the height of the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifty-three percent opposed Clinton's handling of the war in
Kosovo, while 41 percent approved of his actions, and 6 percent
were not sure.
</P>
<P>
   The poll focused on the 2000 presidential campaign in which
California, for the first time in the modern era of presidential
primaries, will play a significant role in deciding the party's
nominees. Most of delegates will be won in March 2000 when big
states _ led March 7 by California, New York, Massachusetts and
Ohio _ have scheduled their primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Among 373 Democratic voters surveyed by Research 2000 about
their party's nominating campaign, Gore topped his chief Democratic
rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, 54 percent to 33
percent with 13 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Among 300 Republican voters asked their choice in the
11-candidate GOP field, Bush won 31 percent. Dole was next with 16
percent, and Sen. John McCain of Arizona tallied 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates received single-digit support with 11
percent of the Republican voters undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the popular two-term governor and son of former President
George Bush, is relatively unknown in California. He intends to
make his first full-blown campaign swing here at the end of the
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
