<HEADLINE>
GUIDE TO WHO'S A BOUNCIN' BABY BOOMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I was born in 1966, and a co-worker said that I'm a baby
boomer. What years are covered by the baby boom?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.K., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The dates vary in different news reports, but here's how they
often break down:
</P>
<P>
   The ``baby boom'' occurred from 1946 to 1964, adding 76.8
million children to the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   Generation X was born between 1965 and 1978. There were 52.4
million babies born during those years, which are sometimes called
the ``baby bust'' because of a declining birth rate.
</P>
<P>
   Generation Y arrived in 1979 and extends to the present. With
77.6 million children born as of last year, Gen Y-ers now outnumber
baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to Marvel Comics after it declared bankruptcy?
Is the company still in business?
</P>
<P>
   _ R.N., Denton, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The comic-book publisher was reorganized in 1998 as part of a
Chapter 11 bankruptcy case and is now a subsidiary of Marvel
Enterprises, formerly known as Toy Biz.
</P>
<P>
   The company filed for bankruptcy in December 1996 because of
losses and an inability to repay debt incurred by the acquisition
of the trading-card companies Fleer and SkyBox International.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which trades as MVL on the New York Stock Exchange,
had $232 million in sales in 1998 and 1,600 employees.
</P>
<P>
   More information is available from the company's Web site at
www.marvel.com/biz.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to George Lucas?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.C., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the filmmaker in care of Industrial Light and Magic,
Box 2459, San Rafael, CA 94912.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who turned 55 a few days before ``The Phantom Menace''
opened, is working on the script for the sequel, which has an
estimated budget of $100 million and a scheduled release date of
June 2002.
</P>
<P>
   After financing the $112 million ``Phantom Menace'' by himself,
Lucas could earn as much as $1 billion from the movie: $700 million
from the box office and $300 million from merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
