<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALAN COCHRUM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Can God Be Trusted?''
</P>
<P>
   By John G. Stackhouse Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford University Press, $25
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   You're almost afraid to ask, but ... almost five decades after
C.S. Lewis' ``Mere Christianity,'' has John G. Stackhouse Jr.
written this generation's successor to that classic work of
religious sensibility?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numbing effects of ``a never-ending stream of
tragedy, disaster, selfishness, and absurdity,'' the Canadian
scholar writes in ``Can God Be Trusted?,'' ``every once in a while
a story grips us, we sit up straight, and the old questions return:
`How could this happen? What kind of a world is this?' And we might
ask one of the oldest questions of all, `How could a good and
almighty God possibly allow such evil to occur?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Stackhouse does not have an unassailable answer to that
question, which is one of his central points. But after making some
valid suggestions, he goes on to argue that Christianity depicts a
God who can be trusted nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Stackhouse's work is marked by the same kind of commonsensical
yet penetrating arguments that made Lewis such a beloved figure.
Readers of ``Can God Be Trusted?'' may find that they have
discovered something wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
