<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASUALTIES-OF-NATO-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FACE OF `COLLATERAL DAMAGE'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This provocative 1,000-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SURDULICA, CENTRAL SERBIA _ Not far from Milena Malobabic's
young body, we found the notebook of love poems she wrote for her
boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's jets had killed her and at least 18 other patients in the
tuberculosis sanatorium just a few hours earlier and Milena's body
lay in the shade of a pine tree, her long black hair drifting over
her face in the breeze, a silver earring still sparkling in her
left ear.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy here to report that the deaths of Milena and
her mother and two brothers and the other 14 patients we found dead
_ not to mention the three elderly people whose shredded remains I
also discovered in the sandwiched concrete of the sanatorium _ is
an atrocity. And it would be true.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombs destroyed a hospital Monday and they called it _
heaven spare us again _ ``collateral damage.'' But Milena's death
alone constitutes a unique tragedy of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you only knew how much I suffer now,'' she had written in
her first poem in the notebook in childish Biro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's wrong, but I want to go back to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Milena still loves you, but I feel my wounds so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I can still kiss you.''
</P>
<P>
   The poem had been written at least two months ago and across the
side of one page, Milena had inscribed the words _ in capital
letters and in English _ ``I LOVE YOU DEJANE!''
</P>
<P>
   The Serb woman who translated Milena's poem to me broke down in
tears. No going back to Dejane now. The wounds are too many.
Suffering is best not spoken of.
</P>
<P>
   Beside Milena's body was her mother _ both feet torn off but
placed gently beside her severed legs _ and Milena's two brothers,
one of them with an arm bent over his face as if still cowering
from the bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-uniformed Yugoslav rescue teams covered all of them
with bloodstained sheets to protect them from the flies. They lay
only a few meters from a pile of concrete and torn clothes and old
papers. That's where we found Milena's notebook.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 patients at the Special Hospital for Lung and
Tuberculosis were also seriously wounded when the NATO bombs fell
on them just after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the two-story 75-year-old hospital simply caved in on
the men and women in their beds which is where most of them died _
although one old man whose body I saw was still dressed in a pair
of old blue trousers and a torn striped shirt.
</P>
<P>
   It was an elderly people's home as well as a tuberculosis
clinic. It was a hospital, set in a pine forest, marked on every
map.
</P>
<P>
   Branislav Ristic, the commander of the local civil defense unit,
had been among the first to reach the scene of horror. ``When I got
here,'' he said, ``there was fire and smoke in all the trees and
people screaming in the darkness and terribly wounded people trying
to crawl out of broken windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was screaming for help. But because this city is
bombed every six hours or so, we had a problem at first to get
enough people to help.''
</P>
<P>
   There was, he said, no military target in the area. So I took a
little walk up into the pine forest, joined hurriedly by none other
than Ristic. ``There is nothing, you see, no military target,
nothing,'' he said as we walked between towering stinging nettles,
the trees alive with bird song.
</P>
<P>
   But in a small glade perhaps half a kilometer from the hospital,
I found the remains of two camp fires _ the ash was still warm in
my hands _ and four ``foxholes'' - the kind of rectangular pits
that soldiers dig to protect themselves from bombs. Down another
track were another 12 ``foxholes,'' all newly dug.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital staff were worried about the bombs, Ristic said. They
probably built them. The unwounded patients had sat by the fires
after they were evacuated from the bombed building.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what is called a likely story. Had there been some
military vehicle here, a missile launcher perhaps? Not so, insisted
the Yugoslav authorities when I raised with them such a heretical
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   However there was, they said, a radio repeater station a
kilometer away, which was a regular NATO target. Perhaps defense
personnel for the station had been camped here, I was told. ``Maybe
engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   But it most certainly was not the barracks or munitions depot
which NATO claimed it was targeting Monday. There was no barracks
here.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the old problem of reporting civilian deaths in the
Yugoslav war.
</P>
<P>
   To find the slightest, most minimal reason why a hospital might
be bombed is to transfer the guilt of the slaughter to the
Yugoslavs and thus to say that Yugoslavia killed its own people
even when they are torn to pieces by NATO bombs. And any Yugoslav
who hears such a remark regards it, not unnaturally, as an
obscenity.
</P>
<P>
   Geneva Conventions _ so assiduously produced by NATO in the wake
of war crimes against Albanians in Kosovo _ state quite
specifically that civilians must be protected even if they are in
the vicinity of military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   But the patients at Surdulica were not given that protection.
Nor were the other 450 dead (more than half of them Albanian) in
NATO's other 16 ``mistakes'' during this Balkan war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partisans were treated here during the Second World War
and the Germans knew they were here but never touched them,''
Ristic said as we walked back beneath the pine stands, filtered
sunlight blessing the smashed concrete and glass and the patients''
clothes which had been blasted high into the branches of a silver
birch tree.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that they took the bodies of Milena and her family
off the grass and loaded them onto an orange-painted dump truck for
their journey to the local morgue. &QL; 
