 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIVILIANS IN BELGRADE HAVE A BONE TO PICK WITH NATO &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ROBERT FISK, The Independent of London &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ I didn't take a shower Tuesday morning. The power
cuts have severed the water supply again. My taps roar at me like a
sick lion and the red plastic bucket on my balcony collects an inch
of grey rainwater from Belgrade's polluted skies; definitely not
for brushing my teeth, maybe _ just maybe _ enough to flush the
toilet.
</P>
<P>
   No power, no water, no cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels and London and Paris, you might be forgiven for
believing that NATO's wishful thinking represents reality; that
Serbia is on its knees, that its people are on the verge of
insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   But returning to Belgrade after a month away is a weird
experience. The mood is harder, more cynical, more resigned... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (975 words) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
