<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1636 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPERTS-CASES06-COX     06-03 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPERTS-CASES06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENTISTS OFFER EXPERTS TO HELP COURTS DEAL WITH EXPERTS
 &HT;    With EXPERTS. For release Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three decisions by the Supreme Court in the 1990s have outlined
duties of federal judges in controlling the quality of evidence
presented to juries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daubert vs. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals Inc., 1993. Two
California youths, including 19-year-old Jason Daubert of San
Diego, claimed pre-natal use of Merrell Dow's morning sickness
drug, Bendectin, by their mother led to their birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court said that judges should act as ``gatekeepers''
and screen evidence to ensure that juries hear information that is
``not only relevant but reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   _ General Electric et. al. v. Joiner, 1995. Robert K. Joiner, a
longtime electrician for the Water and Light Department of
Thomasville, Ga., was diagnosed with lung cancer in 1991.
Contending that the chemicals known as PCBs inside electrical
transformers ``promoted'' his lung cancer, he sued General Electric
and Westinghouse Electric, manufacturers of the transformers, and
Monsanto Corp., maker of the PCBs.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. district court declared Joiner's expert unreliable and
would not permit his testimony. The case was then thrown out of
court. The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta reversed
the judge, saying he lacked authority to dismiss the case.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court ruled that when a judge makes a decision
under his new ``gatekeeper'' responsibilities, the decision cannot
be appealed except on grounds of abuse of discretion by the judge.
The ruling made it much more difficult to force a federal judge to
allow scientific or technical evidence to a go to a jury.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kumho Tire Co. v. Carmichael, 1999. Patrick Carmichael and his
family of eight were traveling to Alabama when a rear tire on their
Ford minivan blew out. The van rolled over, injuring most of the
passengers and killing the Carmichaels' 11-year-old
</P>
<P>
   daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The Carmichaels sued Ford, which paid a settlement, and Kumho
Tire Co., the South Korean maker of the steel-belted radial,
claiming a defect caused the blowout. The company said the tire was
old and worn and should have been replaced. A federal district
judge, citing the Daubert decision, barred the testimony of a tire
tester that the Kumho tire was faulty.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Carmichael got the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta to reverse the trial judge on the grounds that
his ``gatekeeper'' authority applied only to scientific testimony,
not to experts who rely on their experience and observation. The
Supreme Court reversed the Appeals Court, saying the ``gatekeeper''
responsibility applied to all expert witnesses, not merely
scientific witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1555EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1637 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPERTS06-COX     06-03 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPERTS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENTISTS OFFER EXPERTS TO HELP COURTS DEAL WITH EXPERTS
 &HT;    780&AMP;add. With EXPERTS-CASES. For release Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ University of Georgia law professor Ronald Carlson
calls them ``jukebox experts,'' court witnesses who sing the tunes
they're paid for.
</P>
<P>
   With more and more cases involving complicated scientific or
technical questions, the opinions of expert witnesses can sway
juries deciding issues involving millions of dollars in claims.
Weighing their conflicting testimony is becoming a problem for the
judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   Did experiments on animals place a pharmaceuticals manufacturer
on notice that a particular drug would cause birth defects in the
offspring of women who take it?
</P>
<P>
   Was the design and manufacture of a tire responsible for a fatal
car crash?
</P>
<P>
   Is the number of cases of a chronic disease among persons
exposed to a toxic chemical significantly higher than the number
occurring among persons who were not exposed?
</P>
<P>
   Expert opinion about such issues ranges from absolutely to
absolutely not. Opposing lawyers often show up with experts from
opposite extremes of scientific opinion.
</P>
<P>
   And while a case's winner looks around for the nearest bank or
shakes hands with the lawyers who just averted a hemorrhage of
cash, the loser cries ``junk science'' or ``bought science.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not that the witnesses are paid to testify.
Juries find out about that shortly after the cross-examination
begins.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that in an increasingly scientific and
technological world, finding where the truth may lie between
extremes of scientific opinion is imposing an increasingly serious
burden on the court system, critics say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much accelerated scientific development out there
that a poor judge can't be expected to keep up with these things,''
Carlson said. ``They need some way they can go to get prepped by an
expert who has no dog in a particular fight, no axe to grind.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson applauded a new project by the American Association for
the Advancement of Science to help federal judges find such
experts.
</P>
<P>
   Under a five-year demonstration project called Court Appointed
Scientific Experts, or ``CASE,'' the association, in cooperation
with the American Bar Association, will provide judges with lists
of respected and impartial scientists in specific fields.
</P>
<P>
   The project, funded by grants from the Open Society Institute
and the Leland Fikes Foundation of Dallas, will be overseen by a
committee of lawyers, federal judges and scientists. Beginning in
September, federal judges will be able to request assistance in a
particular field and receive from the CASE project a list of
experts who have been screened for conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   It would be up to the judge to decide whether to rely on the
selected expert for private advice about technical issues or to
testify before the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proper administration of justice depends on a
decision-making process that is fair and impartial and reasoned,''
said 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals Judge Pamela Ann Rymer, who
will chair the project advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judges often come from liberal arts educations and generalist
legal backgrounds,'' Judge Rymer added. ``The system has typically
depended on the adversary system to educate and inform the judge.
Many of us have felt increasing need for education that goes beyond
that, both for ourselves and ultimately, for juries.''
</P>
<P>
   Although federal judges have long had the authority to appoint
independent experts, without a neutral source for such experts this
has not been feasible in most cases, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the Supreme Court has issued a series of opinions
that place growing responsibility on federal judges to serve as
``gatekeepers'' of expert testimony. Judges must ``scrutinize''
such testimony to make sure it is valid regardless of the
scientist's qualifications, and the right to appeal the judge's
decisions in that regard are restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some lawyers think the courts already have gone too far in
screening scientific testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, we have developed into a system that has decided that
juries cannot be trusted,'' said Barry Nace, a Washington tort
lawyer. ``How this has happened is not a great mystery. The call
for tort reform and huge sums of money spent in a public relations
campaign convinced judges that they had to 'do something' to
protect the system.''
</P>
<P>
   This happened, he said, during a time when the judicial system
has fallen more and more under control of conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Nace said he was invited to participate in the ``CASE'' project
but declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the courts have been busy deciding such important issues
as how to eliminate evidence, real people have been trying to get
justice,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But Supreme Court Justice Stephen Breyer, speaking to the
science association's annual meeting last year, said that an ``age
of science'' had imposed new demands on the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   He listed some of the scientific issues that have come before
the Supreme Court in recent years, including the potential toxicity
of some chemicals; whether medical technology's ability to reduce
pain affects a person's ``right to die;'' the validity of DNA
sampling, voice prints or experts' predictions of the ``future
dangerousness'' of an individual; the reasonableness of a
government agency's conclusions about the safety of a drug; the
risk to wildlife of a proposed dam, and the risks associated with
nuclear waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Bryant of Trial Lawyers for Public Justice, a public
interest law firm in Washington, agrees with Nace that ``there has
been an enormous campaign by some corporate defendants'' to keep
scientific evidence away from juries.
</P>
<P>
   He said the CASE system, if federal judges use it properly,
``could end up aiding the adversary system, rather than hindering
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
