<HEADER>
A1648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-RELIGION-$ADV05-     06-03 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-RELIGION-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'FAITH IS THE CENTER OF MY LIFE,' GORE SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories for release
Saturday, June 5.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore is usually thought of as a
politician who understands science and technology, so it is
surprising to see a Bible-quoting Gore running for president by
talking about his ``personal faith tradition'' and enlisting
``faith-based organizations'' to help government tackle social
ills.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, a former divinity student, told a small group of
reporters at the White House last week (May 29) that his religious
ideals and government service have never been separate in his mind,
and that he frequently consults the Bible in order to better
understand current events.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have the Earth circle the sun and still believe in
God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is a holist. He believes that dividing the world into
different categories _ fact and value, science and religion, art
and morals _ misses the most important point, that the world is a
living, integrated whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scientific revolution has given us, as a civilization,
previously unimaginable power to dissect each little narrow slice
of the world, `` Gore said. ``But (it) took away an appreciation
for many of the gestalts and many of the most important meanings
that are found only in the whole and not in the sum of its parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, the breach between science and religion is on the
mend, he said, and science's ``contempt'' for a belief in God is
``giving way to a more tolerant blend and a more nuanced
intellectual view that, yes, maybe there is something to this idea
of faith and beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith is the center of my life,'' he said in response to a
question about his personal religious beliefs. ``I don't wear it on
my sleeve. But I'm happy to respond to your question by affirming
my faith.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I think the purpose of life is to glorify God. I
turn to my faith as the bedrock of my approach to any important
question in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   It is rare that presidential candidates speak so openly of their
personal faith, especially Democratic candidates. Jimmy Carter, a
self-described ``born-again'' Christian who won the White House in
1976, was the exception in a party that is largely agnostic in
terms of religious values _ one reason for its poor standing among
evangelical Christians.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's soulful speeches of late, as well as his new proposal
to provide government subsidies to religious groups doing social
work, have met hardly a peep of protest from Democratic activists
or political allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a change in the larger structure of philosophical
debate within which our civilization moves along that makes it
easier for people to make reference to faith-based principles that
are important to them,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason, Gore believes, is the profound affect the
deaths of 15 people at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.,
has had on the entire country.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the aftermath of the tragedy at Columbine, a lot of us did
a lot of soul searching,'' he said. ``And when you look hard enough
for answers to something that is really difficult, you kind of
naturally reach into your faith tradition. I do.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he added, ``I not infrequently will look for scriptural
reference to illuminate my thinking about current events.''
</P>
<P>
   He also frequently consults all manner of religious texts. Most
recently, he has been influenced by ``The Marriage of Sense and
Soul,'' by Ken Wilber, who lives in Boulder, Colo. Wilber's idea is
that modern civilization is a ``flatland'' lacking depth and
meaning because it exalts the rational and the material over the
spiritual and the emotional.
</P>
<P>
   Gore inherited the faith of his father, Southern Baptist. But
growing up, he and his family alternated attending services at his
father's church and at his mother's, the Church of Christ. Then,
too, there were the daily chapel services he attended while a
student at the Episcopal-run St. Albans school in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gore attended a year of divinity school at Vanderbilt University
in 1971 after returning from military duty in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to intensively explore those questions I had which
seemed then _ and seem now _ to be the most important questions
about life: What is the purpose of life? What's our relationship to
the Creator? What are our spiritual obligations to one another?''
he said. ``I didn't find all the answers I thought I might, but I
found better questions. And I found a process of living out better
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's faith was tested in 1989 when his young son was struck by
an automobile and nearly died. The introspection that resulted led
to his best-selling book, ``Earth in the Balance,'' which is as
much about Gore's search for an ``inner ecology'' of faith as it is
about environmental threats to the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's recent emphasis on religion has been viewed with some
cynicism by critics. GOP presidential candidate Gary Bauer
suggested it has more to do with ``the political calendar and
polls'' than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   But in his book, which was published in 1992 before Bill Clinton
selected him as his running mate, Gore sounded many of the
value-laden themes now common in presidential campaigns in both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote about the ``retreat into the seductive tools and
technologies of industrial civilization'' that has left people
feeling isolated and disconnected from their roots, about ``a
spiritual crisis in modern civilization that seems to be based on
an emptiness at its center and the absence of a larger spiritual
purpose, of the need for faith as ``the primary force that enables
us to choose meaning and direction and then hold to it despite all
the buffeting chaos in life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can often say the same thing in a secular framework,''
Gore said at the White House meeting. ``And I have often in the
past and still do try to say it both ways, because it's true that
some people are still uncomfortable with a faith-based
vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
