<HEADER>
A1670 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TARGET-EXPANDING-BOS &LR;      06-03 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TARGET-EXPANDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDWESTERN RETAILER AIMS FOR SHARE OF NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The store on the edge of New York City boasts wide aisles,
aircraft-hangar dimensions, and a mile-and-a-half of shelves loaded
with everything from clothing to designer tea kettles. In fact, the
store is so big that entrances are color-coded so shoppers can
remember where they came in.
</P>
<P>
   The store is Target, which seeks to offer the best of two retail
worlds: merchandise comparable in quality to that of a department
store, at a discounter's prices.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers seem to like the formula. In 1998, Target's sales
exceeded $23 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get good values,'' said Wayne Wexler of Queens, after
he and his wife spent $400 at a Target in New York last week.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of Caldor going out of business, Minneapolis-based
Target is preparing to invade New England. Over the next few
months, the highly successful chain plans to open its first eight
stores in the region, including stores in Danvers, Holyoke, North
Attleborough, and Taunton in late July.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, Target, a division of Dayton
Hudson Corp., could operate as many as two dozen stores in New
England within three years as it rapidly grows to 1,000 stores from
coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   Tough competition helped put Caldor out of business. Will
Target's arrival mean more retail casualties as the Midwestern
giant brings its high-volume, low-margin formula to New England?
</P>
<P>
   Target likes to bill itself as ``an upscale discounter,'' notes
retail consultant Walter F. Loeb of Loeb Associates.
</P>
<P>
   That means it can compete with both discount chains and
department stores. And given its flair for fashion, some of the
smaller offprice apparel retailers could feel the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Braintree-based Bradlees Inc. insists Target is not a major
threat. Both chains compete for customers with household incomes of
about $50,000. But with the high cost of living in New England,
$50,000 doesn't go as far here as it does in some Midwestern
markets where Target has thrived, Bradlees claims.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, New Englanders in the $50,000 income bracket are
far thriftier than their counterparts elsewhere, suggests Bradlees
chairman and chief executive Peter Thorner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers want jeans in the $12 to $16 category,'' he
says. ``They wouldn't buy a pair for $22.''
</P>
<P>
   In the roughly 20 locations where the two chains compete head to
head in New York and New Jersey, Bradlees's lower prices have
helped fend off the Target challenge, Thorner claims.
</P>
<P>
   According to Target, nearly half of its customers _ or
``guests'' as Target prefers to call them _ have incomes above
$50,000. About 80 percent are college educated. Target customers
tend to be younger than those who shop other discount chains.
</P>
<P>
   In the size of its big-box stores and its no-frills ambiance,
Target is somewhat similar to a Wal-Mart or a Kmart, its chief
rivals, but Target's merchandise has more of a fashion focus.
</P>
<P>
   Target will look for inspiration in a ``Pottery Barn or a Crate
&AMP; Barrel'' and then try to make something that's ``a little more
affordable,'' said Barrett LaMothe Ladd, a product manager at
Management Ventures Inc., a consulting firm in Cambridge that
follows the retail industry.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the chain recently got a lot of ink after hiring
celebrity architect Michael Graves to design an exclusive line of
home products for Target. If you want a tea kettle with swell
racing lines or a toaster that some might mistake for art, Graves
is your man.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same with clothing. As Target spokeswoman Carolyn
Brookter notes, what other discounter has its own New York fashion
show?
</P>
<P>
   Target's department-store heritage may account for some of its
fashion sense and sensitivity to trends, Ladd said. Target's
corporate parent also operates such Midwestern department store
chains as Dayton's, Hudson's, and Marshall Field's.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that fashion sense has persuaded some women to think of
Target as an alternative to department stores and offprice apparel
retailers when shopping for clothes.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the country, Target takes some business away
from such department store chains as J.C. Penney and Sears,
Roebuck, and that's likely to be the case in New England as well,
says Midwest Research analyst Jeff Stinson.
</P>
<P>
   To keep prices low and profits high, Target relies heavily on
its own private-label merchandise. With its huge size, Target has
plenty of buying power to leverage vendors and back up its
marketing slogan of ``Expect more. Pay less.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Target sell? It's almost easier to list what it
doesn't sell. Among the items that can't be found at most Targets
are personal computers, heavy appliances such as washing machines,
and big furniture pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But most Targets do stock milk, bread, clothing for the whole
family, TV sets, home furnishings, patio furniture, jewelry,
cameras, toys, bikes, sporting goods, prescription drugs, and
best-selling books, movies, and music. Some even sell eyeglasses.
And in places like Iowa, Nebraska, and Utah, the chain is testing a
SuperTarget, which combines a Target with a grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Even without groceries, all that merchandise means a Target
needs a huge amount of space. The first stores in New England are
expected to range in size from about 117,000 square feet to about
157,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   That means Target stores in the Northeast are more likely to be
found in the suburbs than in a big city's downtown shopping area,
where such big spaces are rare and costly.
</P>
<P>
   Target traces its roots to 1962 when its corporate parent
identified a need for a department store alternative. The idea was
to find a more convenient format than a department store, then fill
it with less expensive goods.
</P>
<P>
   Occupying a niche that seeks to combine the best of both the
department store and the discount worlds, Target has proved to be a
retail powerhouse in its native Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Now growing at the rate of 60 to 65 stores a year, the chain has
duplicated its success throughout most of the country, arriving in
the mid-Atlantic states within the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   With stores up and running in New York and New Jersey, Target is
now poised to enter New England. Analysts see no reason why Target
can't be as successful here as it has been in most other parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think New England's demographics and Target's customer
demographics match up very well,'' said Ladd of Management
Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   For its most recent quarter, Dayton Hudson said overall Target
revenues were up 14 percent and profits were up 23 percent _
impressive results even in a strong economy. At the end of the
quarter, Target operated 859 stores.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Target generated just under 75 percent of Dayton
Hudson's total revenue of $30.95 billion; Dayton Hudson's 1998
profits rose 24 percent to $935 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
