 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, June 4, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PEACE-PLAN (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ On the 72nd day of
NATO's air war against Yugoslavia, President Slobodan Milosevic on
Thursday accepted an international peace plan to end the Kosovo
conflict and allow nearly one million ethnic Albanian refugees to
return to what is left of their homes. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ News Analysis on
Milosevic and what he got out of _ or didn't get out of _ the peace
proposal. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ U.S. reaction to peace
developments in Yugoslavia: National Security Council says it looks
like ``the real thing.'' By John Broder and Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ June 4, 1989, remains China's
biggest taboo: the day troops moved into Beijing and dispersed the
massive pro-democracy protest with guns and tanks, killing hundreds
and injuring thousands. Painful memories now lay buried under the
loose gravel of a decade of prosperity and, with public
soul-searching strictly forbidden, the conflicts and trauma they
evoke have been left unresolved. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ It should be
clear by Thursday night if the African National Congress is getting
the two-thirds majority in parliament that would enable it to amend
Constitution. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-AGREEMENT (Seattle) _ Seeking to end a long-running
international dispute that has imperiled salmon stocks and once led
to an angry blockade by Canadian fishermen of an Alaskan ferry, the
United States and Canada on Thursday announced a comprehensive plan
to set quotas on salmon catches along thousands of miles of the
Pacific Ocean and establish a U.S.-paid conservation fund to
protect the fish. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-COMMISSION (San Francisco) _ After spending two years
studying the social and economic effect that the widespread growth
of the gambling industry has had on the country, The National
Gambling Impact Study Commission completed its work here Thursday,
and prepared to deliver a list of recommended changes for the
industry to President Clinton, Congress, state governors and tribal
leaders. By Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-II (Washington) _ Part Two of a two-part
series: The computer printout that came with 7-year-old Cory
Christen's medication contained a litany of side effects. But it
said nothing about the tremors he started to get, a possible
symptom of a widely known, dangerous side effect: irregular heart
beat. After several months on the drug, he collapsed and died.
Cory's death highlights what drug safety experts describe as a
dangerous flaw in the way consumers are informed of the risks of
prescription medicines. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1605EDT &QL; 
