<HEADER>
A1678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      06-03 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for Friday,
June 4.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ On Patrick Ewing, who is lost for
the rest of the playoffs but who certainly has earned his ring if
the Knicks do somehow go on to win the NBA title. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ For New York sports fans, Saturday is
something special: The Yankees and the Mets at Yankee Stadium at
1:30; the Belmont Stakes, with a Triple Crown on the line, at 5:30,
and the Knicks and Pacers in Game 3 of their playoff series at
6:30. It's a magical mystery tour, but don't try going to all three
events, unless you're ingenious. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS (Purchase, N.Y.) _ The Knicks begin life without
Patrick Ewing, holding an extra-long practice to prepare for Game 3
on Saturday against Indiana. Story is likely to focus on Chris
Dudley, who will now start at center with Ewing out and who will
have to battle his tendency to pick up quick fouls that put him
right back on the bench. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-COLUMN (New York) _ On Baseball column on the three-game
Yankees-Mets interleague series, which begins Friday night at
Yankee Stadium. If you want to see a Subway Series this season you
better attend the games this weekend for the second interleague
series later this season, at Shea. Because the Mets aren't good
enough to make it to the post-season. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-YANKS-METS (New York) _ A lede-all on this weekend's
Yankees-Mets battle. The Yankees have been struggling a bit, but
nowhere near as badly as the Mets, and this weekend's pitching
matchups clearly favor the world champions. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
