<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXTREME-FILM-REVIEW-N     06-03 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTREME-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EXTREME': DAREDEVILS AND DIRECTORS DEFY DEATH! 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As pretty as a gas-station calendar, as covered with sponsors'
names and insignia as a stock car, ``Extreme'' is the latest of the
Imax films that uses the couch potato's favorite medium, the
screen, to deify those who thrill to the challenges of the great
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Everest,'' the visible heroes of ``Extreme'' risk life
and limb to ski or snowboard from peaks of remote mountains, to
ride the roaring tunnels of towering waves, and to haul themselves
up the sheer faces of forbidding rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The all but invisible heroes, led by the film's director, Jon
Long, are recording these flirtations with death from helicopters
or suspended from cables, seen only in a few outtakes among the
final credits.
</P>
<P>
   What they have achieved is mesmerizing at its best, commercial
puffery at its very least, and more a tribute to the rapturous
essence of nature than to the dozen and a half professionals who
ski, snowboard, surf, windsurf, rock climb and ice climb their way
through the film's 44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The narration, with cliches about ``a place where time doesn't
exist'' and less than poetic comments from its subjects about fear
and freedom and self-reliance and pushing the self and harmony with
mountains and adrenaline, poses no threat to the oratory of
Demosthenes, Lincoln or Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   But the pristine snows and blue-green waves, the sunlight
filtered through sea, the orange sunsets, the rust-colored rock
chimneys, the enormous spread of icicles hanging from a
mountainside like the pipes of some heavenly organ provide
``Extreme'' with its true eloquence.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for vacation season, this celebration of the
adventurous and a vicarious journey to Alaska, Hawaii and Utah
provide a pleasurable excursion into escapism. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   EXTREME
</P>
<P>
   Directed and edited by Jon Long; director of photography, Bill
Reeve; music by Soulfood and DJ Free; produced by Neils de Jong
Franken; released by Imax Corp. Running time: 44 minutes. This film
is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Francine Moreillon, Brant Moles and Gordy Peifer (skiers);
Terje Haakonsen, Craig Kelly, Victoria Jealouse and Brandon Ruff
(snowboarders); Ross Clarke-Jones and Ken Bradshaw (surfers); Robby
Naish, Bjorn Dunkerbeck, Jason Polakow and Josh Stone
(windsurfers); Lynn Hill and Nancy Feagin (rock climbers), and
Barry Blanchard and Catherine Mulvihill (ice climbers). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESERT-FILM-REVIEW-NY     06-03 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESERT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DESERT BLUE': A LIFE-OR-DEATH PLOT, FOR DREAMS AND FOR
TEEN-AGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, a group of teen-agers growing up in a desert
town so far off the beaten track that television remains something
of a mystery might not seem like interesting company.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Desert Blue,'' the graceful literary and directorial
touch of Morgan J. Freeman turns these youngsters into individuals
rather than cinema's customary caricatures, and before long they
manage to command attention, engage emotions and generate curiosity
about what will become of them.
</P>
<P>
   In its low-key, sometimes quirky way and despite a foreseeable
conclusion, this modest film by Freeman _ not the actor but the
writer and director of ``Hurricane Streets,'' an award winner at
Sundance in 1997 _ is a life-or-death story.
</P>
<P>
   On one level it is a tale of the life or death of dreams and
ambition and of the life-or-death circumstances that envelop the
fictional desert town of Baxter, Calif., population 87, when a
tanker truck overturns while carrying the concentrated secret
formula for Empire Cola, manufactured in a forbidding plant on the
edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   Because the driver, splattered with the concentrate, soon dies,
Baxter is quarantined by the Environmental Protection Agency and
FBI. All the inhabitants, who seem mainly to be teen-agers, are
trapped there, as are a divorced professor of cultural studies
(John Heard) from San Francisco and his teen-age daughter from Los
Angeles, Skye (Kate Hudson), the star of a television show called
``Maggie's World.''
</P>
<P>
   They have come to town so the professor can see its claim to
roadside fame, a towering re-creation of an ice cream cone.
</P>
<P>
   Skye, at first standoffish and impatient to return to her milieu
of agents and auditions, eventually accepts the company of Baxter's
teen-agers, especially Blue (Brendan Sexton III), who is still
coming to terms with the death of his father six months earlier in
a mysterious fire that destroyed the town's motel.
</P>
<P>
   Blue's father, it seems, was the spirit behind the giant cone
and the dreamer who had hoped to put the old gold mining town back
on the map with a beach-and-ocean park in the desert until his
potential water supply was diverted to Empire Cola.
</P>
<P>
   So Blue still toils away in his father's sand pit of dreams,
painting canoes, while his friend Pete (Casey Affleck) dreams of
winning the coming all-terrain-vehicle race, Cale (Ethan Suplee)
dreams of becoming the sheriff's deputy, and the smoldering Ely
(Christina Ricci), the sheriff's daughter, dreams of blowing up the
whole place with her handy supply of know-how and explosives. That
is, of course, if they don't die first from the Empire Cola spill.
</P>
<P>
   In the night, around fires on the edge of town, hemmed in by the
government, these teen-agers drink, ponder their long-range future
and consider what they might do if there is to be no tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   To such big questions, Freeman brings a light touch but an
effective one. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Desert Blue'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes uninhibited language,
necking, bombings and a shooting. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DESERT BLUE
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Morgan J. Freeman; director of
photography, Enrique Chediak; edited by Sabine Hoffman; music by
Vytas Nagisetty; production designer, David Doernberg; produced by
Andrea Sperling, Nadia Leonelli and Michael Burns; released by
Samuel Goldwyn Films. Running time: 87 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Brendan Sexton III (Blue), Kate Hudson (Skye), John Heard
(Lance), Christina Ricci (Ely), Casey Affleck (Pete), Sara Gilbert
(Sandy), Ethan Suplee (Cale) and Lucinda Jenney (Caroline).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
