<SLUG> BC-INSTINCT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INSTINCT': PHILOSOPHICAL POPCORN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Big thespian guns are rolled out to lay down a barrage of
philosophical popcorn in the psychological mystery ``Instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   The big guns are the Academy Award winners Anthony Hopkins and
Cuba Gooding Jr. The philosophical popcorn runs along these lines:
Nature is good. Civilization is bad. Animals are pure. Man is evil.
Peace is preferable to war. Put love, particularly the love of
children and family, above ambition and career.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Instinct,'' the medium is more palatable than
the saccharine message because Hopkins and Gooding know how to put
on a show. As is known by those who have attended his Lecter in
``The Silence of the Lambs,'' Hopkins masters in portrayals of the
violently homicidal. Terrifying though he may be in these
depictions, Hopkins is, bar none, a moviegoer's ideal prison
inmate.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gooding (``Jerry Maguire''), his cherubic face and bright
spirit in the face of adversity make him pleasant, sympathetic
company even in the most blighted surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two of them, they keep ``Instinct'' afloat on its
sea of simplisms through a succession of climaxes until at last it
reaches its unavoidable ending.
</P>
<P>
   In this film, directed by Jon Turteltaub (``Phenomenon'' and
``Cool Runnings''), and written by Gerald DiPego (``Phenomenon''
and ``Message in a Bottle''), Hopkins plays Ethan Powell. For the
most part resembling Robinson Crusoe in manacles and leg irons,
this mute, shaggy creature is first seen in an African prison where
he has been held for murder and assault.
</P>
<P>
   But because he is an eminent anthropologist and primatologist,
Powell is being turned over to U.S. officials for repatriation.
Mysterious and volatile, he is placed in a truck with snarling
dogs, but by journey's end, he has reduced them, shades of
Crocodile Dundee, to docile Dobermans.
</P>
<P>
   Why has this scholarly man first vanished into the Rwandan
forest for two years, and why has he clubbed two park rangers to
death and injured three others? As the movie puts it, how does a
man become an animal?
</P>
<P>
   These are the questions that Gooding, in the role of Theo
Caulder, a most promising and very ambitious resident from the
University of Miami Department of Psychiatry, hopes to answer if
his mentor, Ben Hillard (Donald Sutherland, wise, cunning and
bearded) gives him the chance to evaluate the silent prisoner.
Success in this endeavor can propel Caulder on a meteoric ascent to
professional renown and perhaps even the top of the best-seller
list.
</P>
<P>
   Is Powell to remain imprisoned, or does the solution to the
mystery of the man hold some justification for freeing him after a
competency hearing?
</P>
<P>
   So, like Clarice Starling and Hannibal Lecter in ``The Silence
of the Lambs,'' Caulder and Powell match wits in the moldering
confines of the Harmony Bay Correctional Facility, where Powell has
been caged among the psychiatric prisoners after turning
explosively on his escorts at the Miami airport.
</P>
<P>
   The prison is one of those places characterized by neglect and
sadism, particularly in the person of Dacks (John Ashton), a brutal
guard, and Bluto (Paul Bates), a hulking inmate. Besides trying to
deal with the volatile Powell and other prisoners, young Caulder
must contend with the inhospitable warden and the defeatist prison
psychiatrist, John Murray (George Dzundza).
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of the facile shallowness of ``Instinct'' that
when Caulder at last manages to enlist the prisoners in defying the
unfair system that allots one of them a half-hour daily in a patch
of high-walled yard, Dr. Murray gazes at him as if he had just
witnessed the second coming of Freud.
</P>
<P>
   Caulder previously has wasted no time breaking through Powell's
silence, which is not to say that he has the upper hand in this
two-way struggle to achieve understanding, which takes him into the
life of Powell's rejected daughter, Lyn (Maura Tierney), and, in
flashbacks, among the great apes of the Rwandan forest.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Powell and Caulder emerge the wiser; moviegoers,
despite the efforts of the stars, somewhat the poorer.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Instinct'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes coarse language, homicide,
sudden and bloody violence and sadism.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jon Turteltaub; written by Gerald DiPego, suggested
by the novel ``Ishmael,'' by Daniel Quinn; director of photography,
Philippe Rousselot; edited by Richard Francis-Bruce; music by Danny
Elfman; production designer, Garreth Stover; special character
effects by Stan Winston; produced by Michael Taylor and Barbara
Boyle; released by Touchstone Pictures. Running time: 124 minutes.
This film is rated R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Anthony Hopkins (Ethan Powell), Cuba Gooding Jr. (Theo
Caulder), Donald Sutherland (Ben Hillard), Maura Tierney (Lyn
Powell), George Dzundza (Dr. John Murray), John Ashton (Dacks),
Paul Bates (Bluto) and John Aylward (Warden Keefer).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
