<SLUG> BC-CI3004-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia lawmakers aim to convince other states to buy C-130Js
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some members of Georgia's congressional delegation
hope they are as fortunate as former House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
whose ability to direct defense spending to Marietta, Ga., won him
a dubious honor.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich merited an entry in a government watchdog group's 1999
Congressional Pig Book when last-minute horse trading brought an
additional $112 million for two Lockheed Martin KC-130J tanker
planes.
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Against Government Waste called the funds for the
planes, a modified version of the company's transport plane, an
``expensive going-away present'' for Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   While the Georgians do not especially want to find themselves in
the Pig Book, they might live with the distinction if it means more
money for Lockheed Martin, which builds the planes and employs
9,200 people at its Marietta plant.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.) said last month that such funding
would not be wasteful: ``It is my view that the C-130J is not a
'pork' project.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell argued in a letter to Appropriations Committee member
Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.) last month that the program ``is not
only a military necessity but also carries significant import for
the state of Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   He is making the same argument to Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott (R-Miss.) and other colleagues, hoping that they will push for
money to buy several C-130Js for Air Force and Marine Corps bases
in their states.
</P>
<P>
   Keesler Air Force Base in Biloxi, Miss., is home to a squadron
of WC-130s that have been modified to track storms. Keesler's
Hurricane Hunters already fly two modified C-130Js.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell is trying to persuade Lott that the base needs two
more planes next year, Coverdell spokeswoman Burson Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell and Rep. Saxby Chambliss (R-Ga.) also are trying to
convince Pennsylvanians that their state's Air National Guard needs
a C-130J next year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Murtha (D-Pa.), the ranking Democrat on the defense
appropriations subcommittee, is a strong advocate for
Pennsylvania's military units and a longtime supporter of the C-130
program.
</P>
<P>
   The annual appropriations process will be in full swing in the
coming weeks, and members of Congress will be looking to protect
programs that benefit their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy the Georgians are employing is simple. And it
mirrors the practice of defense contractors, who have spread their
production facilities over various states to increase the number of
advocates in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgians are trying to enhance their clout, diminished by
Gingrich's exit, by convincing colleagues of the need for the
planes in their states.
</P>
<P>
   The task is complicated by the absence of any C-130Js in the
Pentagon's budget request for the 2000 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But the plane's backers in Congress have made some headway. The
House Armed Services Committee has authorized four planes, at a
cost of about $60 million each. The Georgians think they can get
support for as many as four more.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin told the Georgia delegation this year that the
U.S. government must buy 12 planes next year and in 2001 to keep
its production line running without laying off workers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that number is realistic or merely a negotiating
position is a matter of debate within the Georgia delegation.
</P>
<P>
   In a written plea for administration support, Coverdell told
Defense Secretary William Cohen that Lockheed Martin could accept a
buy of eight planes in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Lockheed Martin is saying little. ``The mark-up
process is kind of a long process. We'll see what's there when it's
over and done with,'' said Sam Grizzle, a spokesman in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockheed lobbyists in Washington are in close contact with
Georgia's representatives and senators, visiting their offices
regularly and even attending campaign fund-raising receptions. At
one recent event for Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.), Chambliss huddled
with Chuck Monroe, Lockheed's point man in Washington for the
C-130J.
</P>
<P>
   The concern appears to be short-term. Hundreds of earlier models
of the C-130 perform a variety of functions for both the Air Force
and Marine Corps, including moving people and cargo in the ongoing
war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Both armed services say they will replace their aging transport
and tanker fleets with C-130Js beginning in 2002 and 2005,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
