<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VIENNA (CIRCA 1900) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``To the Age, It's Art'' was the rallying cry of the Vienna
Secessionists in 1900, when the architect Josef Hoffmann and the
other founders of the Secession were proclaiming the need for a new
style for a new era.
</P>
<P>
   They had rejected the historicism of the late 1800s, when the
Emperor Franz Josef commissioned a Greek temple Parliament, a
Gothic City Hall and Baroque apartment houses on the Ringstrasse,
the wide boulevard that circles Vienna. The Ringstrasse became a
metaphor for everything antiquated and passe, and helped galvanize
a design revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Writers have long sought to explain the atmosphere of the turn
of the century; one was Robert Musil in ``The Man Without
Qualities.'' ``Out of the oil-smooth spirit of the two last decades
of the 19th century, suddenly, throughout Europe, there rose a
kindling fever,'' he wrote in 1930. ``People were standing up on
all sides to fight against the old way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The design revolution spread across Europe to Scotland and,
eventually, to the United States. It included architecture, design
and all the decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   As Kirk Varnedoe, a curator at the Museum of Modern Art, has
written, ``The challenge from the outset was to recover richness
from reduction, to rephrase simplicity with a reticent elegance
that would render superfluous the conventional luxuriance they were
eliminating.''
</P>
<P>
   The icons of this explosive age have been a 20-year passion for
Maurice and Margo Cohen, a Detroit couple who are selling their
collection of early-20th-century decorative arts at Christie's on
June 11.
</P>
<P>
   Many of their works were purchased through the New York dealer
Barry Friedman, who said he had tried unsuccessfully to buy the
collection back when the Cohens decided to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of museum-quality pieces there,'' Friedman
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is considered such a serious collection that Dr. Christian
Witt-Dorring, a curator at the Museum of Applied Arts in Vienna,
wrote the introduction to the catalog for the Cohen sale.
</P>
<P>
   In it he tells how the creations of designers like Christopher
Dresser in England, Charles Rennie Mackintosh in Scotland, Carlo
Bugatti in Italy, and Otto Wagner and Hoffmann in Vienna ``are
evidence of the enormous creative power released at the turn of the
century and directly resulting in bold manufacturing opportunities
and marketing innovations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cohens were truly cosmopolitan in their collecting,
concentrating on Austrian works but also including Scottish,
Italian, English and American pieces. From Vienna they bought some
of the earliest examples of bentwood furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner and Hoffmann produced designs for J.&AMP; J. Kohn, a company
that pioneered the use of bent wood. The sale is to include some
models that have been highly sought since 1986, when they were seen
in the Museum of Modern Art exhibition ``Vienna 1900: Art,
Architecture and Design.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several examples of the chair Hoffmann devised in 1904
for the dining room of the Purkersdorf Sanatorium, a modern spa he
designed on the outskirts of Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last Purkersdorf chair sold at auction went for about
$60,000 in May in London,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   The only design motif on the chair is the circle. The back splat
is pierced with 30 small round holes, lined up in pairs like
marching soldiers. The circle motif is echoed beneath the seat by
two wood spheres attached to each chair leg, a structural support
that is also decorative.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Cohen chairs are being sold individually, with an
estimate of $20,000 to $30,000 apiece. One lot is a set of eight of
the chairs, with an estimate of $160,000 to $240,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's great triumph in Vienna was the 1904 Postal Savings
Bank, planned as a total work of art for which he designed the
building, the fixtures and all the furniture, which was
manufactured by Kohn's rival, Thonet, in ebonized wood with
aluminum studs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cohens are selling the set of bookshelves from the
director's office at the bank (estimate: $50,000 to $80,000); a
sleek armchair with aluminum-capped feet from the board room
($40,000 to $60,000) and a desk with aluminum stringing and studs
($40,000 to $60,000).
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said a Hoffmann brass chalice, circa 1925, designed for
the Weiner Werstatte cooperative was among 300 made; in 1928 it
cost $18.75. Its estimate is $10,000 to $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   From Italy the Cohens bought a pair of ebonized slat-wood side
chairs designed around 1900 by Carlo Bugatti, an Italian architect
who was much influenced by Islamic furniture. The chairs are inlaid
with pewter, brass and copper. The estimate for the pair: $26,000
to $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s the market for great turn-of-the-century Viennese
antiques was overheated, then cooled down. Now, experts say, it is
strong &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William Doyle Galleries' sale of 20th-century art and design on
Monday includes several superb vessels by a Polish-born potter, Lea
H. Halpern (1899-1986), whose work has been forgotten in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Known in the Netherlands as the van Gogh of potters, Ms. Halpern
liked simple shapes and complex surfaces. She considered herself to
be an artist and never intended her pots to be used. She gave them
names like ``Rainy Day,'' ``Black-Eyed Daisy,'' ``Comet'' and
``Spider's Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Schooled in painting, modeling and ceramics in Vienna, she
worked in Gouda, the Netherlands, until World War II, experimenting
with glazes, special effects and innovative pigments. The quality
of her work was recognized early; both Queen Emma and Princess
Juliana bought work at her first show in 1931. The following year
the Stedelijk Museum in Amsterdam gave her a one-woman show and
bought some vases.
</P>
<P>
   Her work has great variety; while the shapes are classic (like
Shang bronzes), the textures vary from satin smooth to eggshell to
lava. The palette is often wild: turquoise with splashes of purple,
or orange with gold. Subtle shades like pale green celadon often
have the crackled surface of ancient Chinese ware. The pieces beg
to be touched.
</P>
<P>
   In 1939 Ms. Halpern was offered a show at Holland House in
Rockefeller Center, which she accepted. She was so concerned about
shipping her works that she sailed with the collection on the liner
Rotterdam. She planned to return home, but the outbreak of war made
it impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Halpern decided to remain in the United States permanently,
marrying and settling outside of Baltimore, where she continued to
work.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 the Frans Halsmuseum in Haarlem had a Halpern show; in
1976 the Baltimore Museum of Art had one. The British Museum, the
Victoria and Albert, the National Collection of Fine Arts in
Washington and the Metropolitan Museum of Art have collected her
pottery.
</P>
<P>
   R.L. Hobson, former curator of ceramics at the British Museum,
called her ``a rare flower in this mechanical age.''
</P>
<P>
   It is even rarer for so many of her pieces to come up for sale
at one time. The estimates range from $300 to $5,000 apiece.
</P>
</TEXT>
