<HEADER>
A1728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      06-03 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFAIRS OF THE HUMAN HEART, TANGLED IN A FOREST OF FAIRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Pfeiffer, Rupert Everett, Kevin Kline, Stanley Tucci,
Christian Bale, Calista Flockhart, Anna Friel, Dominic West, David
Strathairn, Bernard Hill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Michael Hoffman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 115 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's tale of tangled matchmaking jumps forward 250
years or so and moves to Tuscany, where ``the necklines are high,
parents are rigid and marriage is seldom a matter of love.'' As if
by illustration, Egeus (Hill) petitions Theseus (Strathairn), the
Duke of ``Monte Athena,'' to order Egeus' daughter, Hermia (Ms.
Friel), to cease her affections for Lysander (West) and marry
Demetrius (Bale).
</P>
<P>
   The law being the law, the duke can only direct Hermia to wed as
her father wishes. With all not well by the ``left pap where the
heart doth pump,'' Hermia and Lysander take off for the forest on
bicycles, pursued by Demetrius, who is stuck on Hermia, and Helena
(Ms. Flockhart), who is smitten with Demetrius.
</P>
<P>
   In the wood all of them fall prey to fairies who are of robust
libido themselves. Having problems with his wildly romantic queen,
Titania (Ms. Pfeiffer), the smoothly amorous fairy king, Oberon (
Everett), finds it in his interests to tamper with her affections
and those of the humans who have cycled into their midst.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he dispatches the horned sprite Puck (Tucci) with
instructions to squeeze mind-altering drops onto the eyelids of the
queen and the mortals as they sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Puck, though, gets his characters and potions confused. Titania
awakes to find herself in love with Bottom (Kline), a member of a
local acting troupe, who temporarily has the head of an ass. And
now Demetrius loves Helena, leaving the field clear for Hermia and
Lysander. But only the duke can assure that ``Jack will have Jill
and naught will be ill.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Lovers are discreetly unclothed in situations that are
obviously sexual but not graphically so. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY The talk turns bawdy at times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 Not suitable. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-12 As an introduction to Shakespeare, the movie might
make a useful exercise, though that's not exactly the strongest
enticement. The sex isn't that bothersome by most standards, nor is
the racy talk, but there is plenty of attentive listening to be
done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Teen-agers shouldn't expect ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' which, of course, is not by Shakespeare but about him and
thus has more leeway to entertain. ``A Midsummer Night's Dream''
will suffer by comparison. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NOTTING HILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts, Hugh Grant, Rhys Ifans, Hugh Bonneville, Emma
Chambers, James Dreyfus, Gina McKee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Roger Michell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 105 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The young woman browsing for books looks a lot like Julia
Roberts. Or is it Anna Scott, a major American movie star who's
trying to do a few things incognito in London without getting blown
away by hordes of paparazzi? As Scott, Ms. Roberts is virtually
playing herself when she wanders into the bookshop belonging to
William Thacker (Grant).
</P>
<P>
   With belief suspended for the rest of the movie (not that it
matters), Anna is free to find William charming enough to step
right up and give him a pretty good smooch. One encounter leads to
another. He's hooked, albeit cautiously, and she's leaning.
</P>
<P>
   William has a gently bumbling way about him, a self-deprecating
wit, an affable slob of a flat mate (Ifans), a sweet ditz of a
sister (Ms. Chambers) and several nicely eccentric friends.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing with the hoi polloi is a new experience for Anna, but she
tries hard and is as self-effacing as the next person. Now 29,
she's been on a diet since she was 19 and has had some cosmetic
surgery to correct a couple of wayward features. She also allows
that she's not that long in the talent department.
</P>
<P>
   When her schedule allows, she gets back to London and reconnects
with William. She's the instigator, but there comes a point when
her fame will separate them forever if he doesn't step up and carry
her off to relative oblivion. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Ms. Roberts and Grant don't generate sexual heat (one gets
the feeling they might break), but Anna and William make love
off-screen, reappearing in bed for a benign, photogenic look-see
after the fact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Swear words are heard and seen stenciled on a T-shirt,
though the mood is jokey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 They wouldn't suffer irreparable damage, but clearly
this isn't a film for young children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 Both stars will appeal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP One sees this movie to ogle Ms. Roberts and Grant
and be carried along by the fantasy. That will strike some
teen-agers as dumb, though not others. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE WINSLOW BOY
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Hawthorne, Jeremy Northam, Rebecca Pidgeon, Gemma Jones,
Guy Edwards &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Mamet &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 110 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Mamet's film, based on Terence Rattigan's play and a
real-life incident, Ronnie Winslow, 13, stands in the rain in his
naval academy uniform, clutching a letter from the British
admiralty. The boy, according to the letter, has been expelled for
stealing a five-shilling postal order.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Arthur (Hawthorne), a moderately well-to-do
Edwardian family patriarch until this business develops, tells
Ronnie that he won't blame him but that he should not lie because
it will be apparent if he does. Did he steal the postal order? No,
Ronnie answers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus begins a protracted defense that consumes Arthur and his
hard-headed daughter, Catherine (Ms. Pidgeon); drains the Winslow
coffers; threatens Catherine's marriage prospects, and drives the
press and British government to distraction.
</P>
<P>
   On the favorable side of the ledger, the Winslows secure the
services of Sir Robert Morton (Northam), a brilliant barrister and
a member of the House of Commons. Morton is a cold character, but
when Ronnie survives his private cross-examination, he takes the
case and ultimately pursues it with ardor even after Arthur wants
to drop the matter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 Just to prove it can be done, here's a serious
feature film without bloodshed, sex or foul language. Too bad small
children won't understand a word. Older viewers in this category
will get the general idea, but the going will be too slow and wordy
to retain interest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-12 If parents gave a push, the film could catch hold
with some viewers (admittedly not many). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Teen-agers choose their own movies. If they're
willing to try something different, they will be rewarded. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
