<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-03 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hum Is Audible Off Broadway
</P>
<P>
   Heard enough about the Tonys? Good. While the good people of
Broadway engage in their Tony festivities, the denizens of Off
Broadway and the world beyond are busy finalizing their schedules,
settling down in new homes and closing up shop.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news comes first, as a pair of long-running Off Broadway
shows reach the end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   At the Soho Playhouse, ``Killer Joe'' closes on Sunday. The
play, about a murder scheme hatched in a trailer park, had strong
reviews and even stronger box office figures after opening in
October. But sales began to drop after its original stars, Amanda
Plummer and Scott Glenn, left early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Several replacement casts have been tried out with mixed
results. Two weeks ago, Lori Petty, of ``Tank Girl'' fame, left
earlier than expected, said Darren Lee Cole, the producer. A call
to Ms. Petty's manager in Los Angeles was not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said that ``Killer Joe'' had earned back about 80 percent
of its initial $350,000 investment and that productions in San
Francisco, Boston and Toronto are likely. A film deal is also
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful Thing'' is also planning to close, on June 27. The
story of two male teen-agers in the blush of first love, the play
ran five months and will have recouped its $265,000 investment,
said Roy Gabay, one of the producers. A production in Los Angeles
looks likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go through July and August,'' Gabay said.
``And if I go out, I'd rather go out on top.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Atlantic Theater Company, ``The Cider House Rules,''
Peter Parnell's ambitious seven-hour adaptation of John Irving's
novel, may remain half seen in New York. The piece's first half,
which received mixed reviews, closes on Sunday. Neil Pepe, the
Atlantic's artistic director, said this week that the mixed reviews
had made financing the second half _ which would cost about
$300,000 _ difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for an angel,'' said Pepe, who added that
producers had about a third of the money needed for the second
part. ``It's been an extraordinary journey. It would be a shame to
leave it halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, new productions are being lined up. At the Variety
Arts, producers said this week that the musical ``A Good Swift
Kick'' will open on July 29.
</P>
<P>
   The show, by John Forster, is described in press materials as
``20-odd musicals in 90ish minutes,'' with songs on subjects
ranging from ``Thomas Jefferson's DNA, to cultural imperialism, to
the final thoughts of a deer crossing the turnpike.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   At the Manhattan Theater Club, ``Y2K'' by Arthur Kopit is
confirmed for the fall, with Bob Balaban directing. It joins three
other new plays, ``An Experiment with an Air Pump'' by Shelagh
Stephenson, ``Fuddy Meers'' by David Lindsay-Abaire and ``Proof''
by David Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   And the Signature Theater Company, which devotes each season to
the work of one playwright, has chosen the lineup for next year's
tribute to Maria Irene Fornes. Two short works, ``Mud'' and
``Drowning,'' both directed by David Esbjornson, will open on Sept.
26, followed by ``Enter the Night'' on Dec. 5, and then a world
premiere of an untitled new play in February 2000. The season will
also include cabaret performances of some of Ms. Fornes'
experimental musical work.
</P>
<P>
   A Script in Hand
</P>
<P>
   The last time F. Murray Abraham was on stage in New York was in
1997, in ``Triumph of Love,'' the short-lived musical at the
1,078-seat Royale Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Abraham (``Please call me Murray'') has been busy
acting in movies, where he made an indelible mark _ winning an
Oscar _ in the 1984 film ``Amadeus.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was during one of these job excursions last year that
Abraham found the script that brings him back to the stage. While
in Melbourne, Australia, Abraham said, he was approached by a young
woman with a script in hand. It is not an uncommon occurrence, he
said, but his reaction was.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one seemed so good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So starting next month, Abraham, along with Joyce Van Patten,
will appear in ``It's My Party and I'll Die If I Want To,'' by
Elizabeth Coleman, at the Arclight Theater, a 99-seat theater on
West 71st Street. It is, as the title suggests, a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   How does the jump from Broadway to the lands Off Off feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going back to the roots,'' said Abraham, with a laugh.
``It's like performing in a cave.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost Home
</P>
<P>
   For 13 years, Ellie Covan has been opening her home, a
second-floor loft on the Bowery, to the public, inviting complete
strangers to sit on her couches and watch play readings,
performance art and dance. The Blue Man Group started there as did
performers like John Leguizamo and Lisa Kron. The actors were paid
a little for their labors, and no show had tickets costing more
than $12. Ms. Covan called her homey performance space Dixon Place;
many artists simply called it home.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, Ms. Covan told the crowd at the Obie Awards that
she had lost her lease and would have to close.
</P>
<P>
   So people in the downtown theater scene heaved a collective sigh
of relief this week when the Vineyard Theater announced that it had
offered Ms. Covan its old theater on East 26th Street for the year
to continue her unique style of developmental work. The Vineyard
moved to a larger space on Union Square in 1989 and was using the
old theater for rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Covan said she was surprised and thrilled by the offer. She
said the new space will open, with ``a slightly different feel,''
just after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll bring some of our finer couches,'' she said,
adding that she won't be living there. ``That's the best part.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
