<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      06-03 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ideal Time For Wilde?
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Oliver Parker says that if there is one thing he has
learned in his career in theater and film as a writer, actor and
director, it's that Oscar Wilde is not a good candidate for screen
adaptations. Hollywood has been busy mining the canon of English
literature, from Austen to Shakespeare, but Wilde has been
conspicuously ignored. ``Too theatrical,'' Parker said he had
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   And so Parker is understandably in a reflective mood as he
prepares for the release of his adaptation of Wilde's play ``An
Ideal Husband'' on June 18. The movie, which Parker wrote and
directed, stars Rupert Everett, Jeremy Northam, Cate Blanchett,
Julianne Moore and Minnie Driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilde is a bit frightening, and the language is so dense and
rich,'' Parker said. ``But something niggled me.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``niggled'' was the obvious relevance of a story about a
noble-minded but flawed politician ( Northam), desperate to conceal
a secret about a past financial indiscretion and how that collides
with the high-minded principles of his wife (Ms. Blanchett). All
this takes place as the world's greatest power (Britain in this
instance) contemplates its role at the end of a century (the 19th).
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get it out this year, of course,'' said Parker, an
Englishman. ``You can see why. It was so rooted in pertinence.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker's only other major film was ``Othello,'' which starred
Laurence Fishburne, Irene Jacob and Kenneth Branagh, so he has
experience adapting material for a contemporary audience. He said
that although he had rejected an ``Ideal Husband'' adaptation out
of hand when it was first proposed, he was intrigued enough to play
with a script that simplified the plot and developed some of the
characters differently.
</P>
<P>
   The key, Parker said, was taking liberties with the play while
preserving Wilde's razor-sharp wit and dissection of social
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said he removed many of the farcical elements and made it
less of a sendup of a drawing room comedy. Instead he emphasized
the role of a woman, played by Ms. Moore (with an English accent),
who blackmails Northam's character. Parker had great fun giving
Everett free reign as London's most marriage-resistant and clever
bachelor, Lord Goring.
</P>
<P>
   Parker also invented a bet on which the future of every major
character turns, a device that makes the movie's conclusion both
unexpected and, well, highly theatrical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun thing about a period piece is it gives some
perspective on contemporary events without being embarrassing,''
Parker said. ``I had British political life in mind. It felt to me
like a seediness had become a regular part of the day. But I guess
you could see some pertinence to America.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilde has been so transformed in Parker's eyes, he said, that he
is now considering a new adaptation, of ``The Importance of Being
Earnest.''
</P>
<P>
   Throwing Strikes
</P>
<P>
   When young men dream of breaking into major league baseball,
they often dream of Cape Cod. No, not lying on the beaches there,
but playing in a summer league that, though little known beyond
baseball circles and the cape's clam-roll stands, has long been a
training ground for some of the best professional talent. Think of
players like Mo Vaughn and Jeff Bagwell. The Cape Cod League, to
which a select number of college players are invited each year,
represents the cusp of making it or not for many hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   And so Mike Tollin, who has built a career in part as a producer
of sports movies, has chosen ``Summer Catch,'' a script about a
young man in the Cape Cod League, for his debut as a feature
director. He expects to begin shooting this summer for a possible
release early next summer through Warner Brothers. The actors have
not been chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Tollin has had a distinguished career as a producer, most
recently of ``Varsity Blues.'' He and his partner, Brian Robbins,
also produce the HBO series ``Arliss,'' about a sports agent, and
they received an Oscar nomination for their 1995 documentary ``Hank
Aaron: Chasing the Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer Catch'' had first been accepted at Fox, with Matt Damon
set to star as an aspiring pitcher and Keri Russell of the
television show ``Felicity'' as his love interest. The deal fell
through, and Tollin said he jumped at the opportunity to do a
picture about the league and to focus on directing for a change. He
likened the experience being the pitcher in a ball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole other level of creative control to
directing,'' said Tollin, adding that he would seek the kind of
authenticity found in such films as ``Bull Durham.'' ``Being on the
mound, there's nothing that compares with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The film follows a pitcher named Ryan who grows up in the shadow
of the league's ramshackle ball park, cutting lawns for his
father's landscaping business. His arm propels him into the league,
suddenly making him a contender for the affections of a young woman
whose lawn he used to mow. It also sets him against his friends,
who are used to squaring off against the outsiders who show up each
summer to play ball and drink at a local bar before heading off to
grander things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about that last shot at the pros before the inevitable
encroachment of reality,'' said Tollin, who is from Philadelphia
and is a staunch Phillies fan.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he said, the film will be a celebration of a
pursuit he and most of the other people involved in the movie
adore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all baseball fanatics,'' he said. ``We all love the game
and have great respect for the game. That's what this really is
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Tea With Zeffirelli
</P>
<P>
   These days of war in Yugoslavia may not seem like the wisest
time to wager on the shared connections within Europe and between
Europe and the United States. But then Franco Zeffirelli has never
been conventional. So he has placed his bets more or less across
the board on unity rather than division.
</P>
<P>
   Zeffirelli's current movie, the autobiographical ``Tea With
Mussolini,'' searches for and finds these common cultural roots
amid the hostilities of World War II in Florence. The movie tells
of a group of eccentric British and American women who took him in
and raised him, and of how brutally they were treated by
Mussolini's government and the Germans. The film is ultimately a
love letter to these affectionate if naive esthetes for the
enduring values they imparted to an impressionable young man.
</P>
<P>
   Zeffirelli, 76, discussed these cultural ties from his home in
Florence, where he is campaigning for a seat in the European
Parliament. His platform is to focus and build upon the commonality
within Europe and between Europe and America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love America very much,'' Zeffirelli said. ``Your country
has given the world so much. I've only one virtue in my
personality, gratitude and loyalty. That is what has driven me in
the movie and in my political campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The film and the political campaign reflect an unmistakable
optimism that Zeffirelli said he has not always had. The killing
and brutish behavior he witnessed during World War II left deep
scars, he said, but in ``Tea With Mussolini,'' ``the scars have
disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It needed a long sedimentation period, the memories,'' he
said. ``They needed to become objective. If I had done this 30
years ago, it would have been much darker. But the story has been
well guided by destiny, I think. It's very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly Zeffirelli said he takes a hopeful attitude toward
cultural cooperation among European nations and especially between
Europe and the United States. One proposal he has championed, he
said, is the construction of a huge international performing arts
center in Florence on a 30-acre site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope this would be done with the help of America,'' he
said, a stand that is sure to meet some opposition from Europeans
who resent American cultural influence.
</P>
<P>
   Another plank in his platform, Zeffirelli said, is to encourage
greater cooperation between the United States and Europe in
filmmaking, an issue over which tempers have sometimes flared.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than resisting Hollywood's influence and its cultural
hegemony, as some Europeans have described it, Europe should
welcome American investment in European films and film companies,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be more open,'' Zeffirelli said.
</P>
<P>
   The European Parliament election takes place in mid-June, two
days before Zeffirelli flies to Hollywood, he said, to begin
negotiations on two new movie projects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
