<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tracing 30 Years Of Gay Life
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard of the word lesbian, but I knew enough to
hide,'' says a woman from North Carolina in ``Before Stonewall,''
the 1984 Emmy Award-winning film by John Scagliotti, Robert
Rosenberg and Greta Schiller. Like dozens of homosexuals reared in
the '20s and '30s who were interviewed for the documentary, she hid
her differences as best she could in the decades before June 27,
1969, when a police raid on the Stonewall Inn in New York City
touched off three nights of rioting and effectively launched the
gay movement.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, First Run Features will release ``Before Stonewall''
and, for the first time on video, ``After Stonewall,'' a second
chapter by Scagliotti, Janet Baus and Dan Hunt, which will have its
first television showing on PBS on June 23.
</P>
<P>
   Together the two films are a history of gay life. ``The first
one took much longer because material wasn't available then,''
Scagliotti said. ``Homosexuality wasn't even a topic in the
national archives.'' The second film, completed this year, was
easier, though by the late '90s sources wanted to be paid for their
information. ``There's been such a fundamental change in
recognition,'' he said. ``We could go all over the country. People
were more aware of what gay and lesbian lives are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Stonewall'' begins in the '20s, when homosexuality was
grounds to be committed to a hospital in some states but became a
call to the bohemian life from the Barbary Coast of San Francisco
to Greenwich Village and Harlem in New York. The film touches on
the writings pouring from the likes of Langston Hughes, Gertrude
Stein and Tennessee Williams, the so-called code of decency that in
1935 banned any reference to homosexuality in films, and other
repressive measures that took hold amid the economic and social
strains of the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   One of the better passages covers World War II, when gay people
of both sexes volunteered for the military in large numbers. Men
tell of joining the Marines to prove that homosexuals could
withstand tests of macho physicality (even though, as one man
reports, they ``threw like girls,'' which gave them trouble with
hand grenades). Working in the defense plants, women, including
lesbians, flooded urban areas and discovered themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948 the Kinsey report said that there were 20 million
homosexuals. That kind of number was excuse enough to link
homosexuality with communism. Gay people fought back. ``We began
asking, `Why are we being intimidated by a bunch of jerks who know
nothing about life?''' the poet Allen Ginsberg says in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Homosexuality is officially removed from the list of psychiatric
disturbances in 1974. Lesbians split from male homosexuals, finding
them sexist, and feminists distance themselves from lesbians.
Poetry soothes the hurts. ``Thank God for bad poetry,'' says a
lesbian. Harvey Milk is assassinated. Anita Bryant wants to save
our children. ``Rare Cancer Seen in 41 Homosexuals,'' reads a
headline in The New York Times. In the film, AIDS brings a loss of
all innocence. ``By '86 people started getting angry,'' Scagliotti
said.
</P>
<P>
   For information: (800) 488-6652.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gods and Monsters
</P>
<P>
   In a razor-sharp performance, Ian McKellen is the director James
Whale, who died mysteriously in 1957. Adapted from Christopher
Bram's hypothetical novel, Bill Condon's film catches Whale, a
marvelously urbane English homosexual, after a small stroke has
left him with painful thoughts of the past and particularly
receptive to an obsession with his young gardener (Brendan Fraser).
Taking off from Whale's complex nature, Condon, Janet Maslin wrote
in The New York Times, builds ``an immensely touching character
study that is heightened by well-chosen glimpses of Hollywood's
past.'' 1998. Universal. $99.91. 105 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: June 8.
</P>
<P>
   Psycho
</P>
<P>
   The room rate at the Bates Motel has jumped to $36.50, but
little else in Gus Van Sant's color imitation of Alfred Hitchcock's
film (1960) strays far from the master's blueprint. Anne Heche's
Marion bleeds orange in the shower scene, and she is more
headstrong and flirty than Janet Leigh was the first time. The one
major falloff is Vince Vaughn, whose beefy and rather obvious
Norman Bates is a far cry from Anthony Perkins' sneaky, birdlike
presence as the original Norman. If Van Sant is no Hitchcock,
neither does he botch an ``artful, good-looking remake (a modest
term, but it beats plagiarism)'' (Maslin). 1998. Universal.
$105.77. 109 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date: June 8. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Theory of Flight
</P>
<P>
   Dying of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (Lou Gehrig's disease),
the feisty Jane (Helena Bonham Carter) talks dirty and spends her
spare time watching hard-core pornography. Eager to lose her
virginity, she gets the help of Richard (Kenneth Branagh), a failed
painter who builds primitive flying machines. Richard is not to be
the lover, but he is to conduct the search, beginning with
employment agencies and finally leading to a suave professional
escort who will be paid for his services. To finance that, Richard
decides to rob a bank, but he's never more than an allegorical
construction in a film that ``might be described as a
disease-of-the-week movie with comic and mythic pretensions''
(Stephen Holden). 1998. New Line. $104.16. 99 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gabbeh
</P>
<P>
   In a film by the Iranian director Mohsen Makhmalbaf, the figures
in an old couple's gabbeh (a wool carpet woven to tell a story)
come to life and relate a tale of a wandering clan and requited
love. Gabbeh (Shaghayegh Djodat), a character in the rug, is
followed across the countryside by a horseman in black whom she
would like to run off with if responsibilities and social
conditions within the clan would ever permit, which they never seem
to. Grandly poetic and richly reportorial, ``Gabbeh'' is ``woven
with art'' (Lawrence Van Gelder). 1996. New Yorker. $89.99. 75
minutes. Farsi with English subtitles. No rating. Release date:
June 8. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; True to usual form, video best renters run to romance, comedy
and animated films, with a small number of dramas cracking the Top
40. Here are some examples.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YOU'VE GOT MAIL. &LR;  In Nora Ephron's film, currently the No. 1
best seller and best renter, Joe (Tom Hanks) and Kathleen (Meg
Ryan) take each other's measure on the Internet. 1998. Warner.
$22.96. 119 minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STEPMOM. &LR;  Trying to get cozy with the children of her lover (Ed
Harris), Isabel Kelly (Julia Roberts) runs into resistance from
their mother (Susan Sarandon) before illness takes a hand. 1998.
Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37. 124 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A BUG'S LIFE. &LR;  To help save thousands of his fellows from a
small but efficiently intimidating gang of grasshoppers, an ant
named Flik enlists a traveling band of circus bugs. 1998. $26.99.
96 minutes. Closed captioned. G.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELIZABETH. &LR;  With a nod to historical accuracy, Shekhar Kapur's
lavish costume drama stars Cate Blanchett as a monarch who carries
her responsibilities with the air of a glamorously stressed-out
modern woman. 1998. Polygram. $99.99. 121 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BULWORTH. &LR;  Senator Jay Bulworth (Warren Beatty) is so fed up
with his job and life that he hires a hit man to kill him for his
life insurance. Then it occurs to him that with nothing to lose he
can do the unthinkable for a politician: tell the truth. 1998. Fox.
$104.16. 106 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIX DAYS, SEVEN NIGHTS. &LR;  Released in December, Ivan Reitman's
film about a pilot (Harrison Ford) and a magazine editor (Anne
Heche) stuck on an island together has the current longevity title
for a best renter: almost six months. 1998. Touchstone. $104. 111
minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
