<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1755 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV0     06-03 1901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH CAMP CONDITIONS DETERIORATING, AID OFFICIALS AND KOSOVAR
REFUGEES WORRY AHEAD TO WINTER
 &HT;    EDs: Contains optional trims.
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With REFUGEES-CAMP-$ADV06; REFUGEES-BOX-$ADV06.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Lehze is northwest of
capital city of Tirana, on the Adriatic Sea coast.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEHZE, Albania _ It is early June, but the talk is of winter.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the afternoon, it is already stifling in this old
warehouse that was used in communist days to house tractors for
cooperative farms. The moist smell of perspiration is heavy in the
concrete block building that is now home to more than 560 refugees
from Kosovo. They have been here six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people on Earth must live this way?'' asks Nugret
Termkolli, a leader of the refugees who come from the tiny Kosovar
village of Bardhi I Madh(CQ). ``We are like animals in a barn only
worse,'' he says, walking down a row of cardboard boxes, blankets
and foam mattresses arranged into individual family living spaces.
``We have no toilets or suitable places to wash. The world has
forgotten us.''
</P>
<P>
   Families here sleep on makeshift beds laid on the hard concrete
floor. The women take turns at three propane-fueled stoves to cook
meals of beans and crude fried bread for their families. Food is
scarce, brought every week or so by an Englishman the refugees only
know as ``George.''
</P>
<P>
   Their water comes from a single outside hose. The children have
diarrhea. Two refugees have died. No one knows why. Doctors have
visited here twice.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of spending the winter here horrifies Termkolli.
``It's impossible,'' he says, with a tone of frustration changing
to panic. ``We have no way to keep warm and there will be an
epidemic of diseases. We would be better off taking our chances
with the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   With each passing day, it becomes more likely that winter will
come and go before the souls in this tractor warehouse see their
homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last week's acceptance of an international peace plan by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's government, refugees and
aid officials here alike consider it a foregone conclusion that the
nearly 450,000 Kosovar refugees in Albania will be away from home
months -- perhaps years.
</P>
<P>
   There are still the mines, they say. Many of the homes have been
burned to the ground. But most important, they just don't trust
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to believe Milosevic any more. But if NATO
goes into Kosovo, we will follow immediately,'' said Istref Veseli,
a 43-year-old from Vucitrn who had been imprisoned by Serbs for 21
days and arrived in Albania two weeks ago after being released.
</P>
<P>
   His family is still in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to sit in tents in Kosovo than tents in Albania,''
he said, referring to the fact that many homes back home had been
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from Kosovo have been through so much, but it is now
almost certain that they must endure much more. The next few weeks
will be grim. Balkan summers are hot, with many days bringing
temperatures above 100 degrees, while many refugee camps are built
on flat, treeless plains. Aid workers worry about dehydration and
disease among weakened refugees, particularly the old, infirm and
infants.
</P>
<P>
   And then they will confront the cold, wet winter with its
specters of exposure and even more disease.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many camps in Albania were thrown up on sites
that don't meet minimal standards for health and safety. But relief
groups, under the double pressure of sheltering the flood of
refugees and getting out of the military's way, say they have
little choice but to use what they know are unsuitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of land the government provides is not really usable,''
said Carsten Voelz, the manager of Camp Hope, a U.S. camp for
20,000 being constructed in southern Albania. ``But you do what you
can.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Land ownership in this country, which until 1990 forbade private
citizens from owning property, is a complex issue that renders most
sites useless. Aid groups have begun erecting shelters only to have
armed men interrupt their work to evict them. Consequently, many of
the sites made available by the Albanian government were so
undesirable that nobody was willing to fight over them.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Hope, Albania's largest camp, is on a broad, flat plain that
offers no cover from the sun in the summer or wind and rain in the
winter. The 200-acre site is below sea level, and drains poorly, a
situation made worse by the fact that local farmers for decades
have flooded the land as a way to irrigate it. It offers little
water -- the ultimate factor that limits capacity -- so camp
planners hope to pipe water from a well being dug about 10 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   At Spitalli, a German camp designed for 6,000 near the port city
of Durres, conditions are worse. The camp was placed across a
gravel road from a 20-foot wide channel that carries raw sewage
from Durres to a pool from which it is pumped untreated into the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   However, the aging pumps -- a best guess places them at about 30
years old -- often breakdown, creating a pool of smelly, putrid and
ultimately unhealthy soup to gather near the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the system of ditches dug between the rows of
tents was so poorly engineered in the haste to build the camp that
water doesn't drain away from the camp. It stands brown and frothy
behind the tents and has become a breeding ground for mosquitoes
and other sickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disaster,'' said Roland Amvhein, a C.A.R.E.
International engineer who has been frustrated in his struggle to
correct the problem. ``We try to help these people, and then we put
them in a place like this. Does this make any sense?''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Taillfer, Spitalli's manager, believes the camp must
be abandoned as soon as possible -- certainly before winter. ``It
was not a good site to begin with; in fact, it was a bad site,''
she said. ``The next step must be to move these people to hard
buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   The nagging, unresolved question is where.
</P>
<P>
   So far, aid workers are far from having an answer even as time
is running out to prepare shelter by September in the mountains and
October in the lowlands. The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees is
trying with rising urgency to find winter shelter for the refugees
and already is shipping in 15,000 winter tents. But its efforts
thus far have fallen well short of the projected need.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. refugee agency has identified more than 150 sites both
in buildings and parcels of land for shelter. Yet, only slightly
more than half have been opened to refugees. The maximum identified
capacity is less than 350,000 -- still more than 100,000 less than
the total of refugees now in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Few existing camps provide conditions for refugees to survive
the winter and will have to be radically modified or refugees will
have to be moved to vacant buildings adapted for them the choice
aid workers prefer.
</P>
<P>
   But, far too few buildings remain identified, and the general
condition of vacant buildings in Albania is exceedingly poor --
making it expensive to make them livable.
</P>
<P>
   In the Korca district, for example, city officials have
identified about 40 buildings that can be converted to housing for
about 50 refugees each, or about 2,000 refugees. Yet, one camp in
the district already has 2,700 refugees who will have to be
relocated to winter quarters, while the French army is finishing a
pair of summer camps that will house up to 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   As she awaits word on the proposed peace plan that would halt
the NATO bombing and allow the refugees back into Kosovo, Marci Van
Dyke, a Relief International worker who manages the Qatromi camp,
worries about the arithmetic. ``We also are hearing that we may see
another 60,000 refugees from Macedonia,'' she said over coffee in a
shaded canteen at the sun-baked camp. ``There's no way that would
work.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, pressures are mounting on Albania to accept
even more refugees, perhaps driving the total to 1 million.
Officials in Macedonia, where there are 250,000 refugees, are
demanding that they be relocated. And NATO officials are pressing
to move the 30,000 refugees near the Yugoslavian border with
Albania in Kukes, which has been the scene of increasing military
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a hurry to relocate them because something bad is
going to happen in Kukes,'' said Paul Giannone, an emergency
planner from C.A.R.E.'s Atlanta office. ``We have absolutely no
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, conditions in Albania already are fragile. The crisis thus
far has been contained because of the hospitality of Albanian
families, who are housing an estimated 250,000 refugees in their
homes. But officials worry that their generosity cannot last
forever and that the burden of housing and feeding the refugees
will severely strain the resources of so many families in Europe's
poorest nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian government is offering each host family a monthly
supplement of $10 per refugee with a maximum of $120, but officials
worry this is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Kujtim Dashi, a municipal official in the Lezhe prefecture in
northern Albania, said the strain on host families of having
usually more than 10 refugees in their homes is immense. ``In
Albania, we say that 'Our house belongs to God, and our guests,'
but this is very difficult for them,'' said Dashi, who said that
nearly 29,000 refugees have registered in his prefecture. ``Even
Albanians have their limits.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The strain already is proving too much. Aid workers report that
growing numbers of refugees are leaving host families to seek other
shelter. The British-built Qatromi camp in the mountains near
Macedonia already has received 1,000 refugees who had been with
host families.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the rising tension among Albanian families, there
is growing hostility among the refugees who are frustrated by the
harsh realities of life as a ward of relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the mounting pressure of the refugee crisis may be too
much for Albania to bear. Genc Ruli, the president of the Institute
of Contemporary Studies, worries that Albania is sitting on a
ticking refugee bomb. ``This relative stability we see now is
fragile and temporary,'' Ruli said. ``There is a real chance that
we could descend into chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Near the tiny village of Balldren, a mechanic's garage provides
shelter to 58 refugees. They have lived there seven weeks. Among
them are women as old as 90 and newborn babies.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few men, Shaban, Krasniqi, a 42-year-old welder,
speaks longingly of his two-story home near Pristina, Kosovo's
provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if my home is burned down, I would go back there,' he
says, considering the prospect of spending the next months living
in the garage. ``Even there, we could face the winter when it
comes, making the best of it with our families in our own places.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks at the white concrete block building and shakes his
head. ``But here,'' he says. ``NATO must not let the winter catch
us here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
