<HEADER>
A1767 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-ARTICHOKE-ART-HN     06-03 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ARTICHOKE-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL FOR THE SEDUCTIVE QUALITIES OF THE VERSATILE ARTICHOKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
(Eds.: Also see: Food-artichokes-recipes) 
 
By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you had been the first person to tackle an artichoke, do you
think we still would be eating them today? First you encounter
prickly stickers at the end of the leaves. Then you work your way
through the tough leaves to the fuzzy, inedible thistle. At last,
you reach the small heart.
</P>
<P>
   The miracle is that someone dared to persevere, to discover that
once artichokes are cooked and ``dissected,'' they are a delicious
treat, although only the soft part of the leaves, the heart and the
bottom are edible.
</P>
<P>
   Artichokes are one of the world's oldest known foods _ actually
they are flower buds _ and they are very versatile. They can be
marinated, sauteed, boiled, added to stir-frys, or simmered in
stews and pot roasts.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is more elegant as a first course than a steamed
artichoke with a dipping sauce. For a luncheon or light meal, stuff
artichokes with seasoned crumbs, seafood salad, cheese rarebit,
pasta salad or creamed chicken _ or even a favorite cooked frozen
entree.
</P>
<P>
   Baby artichokes are increasingly popular. They have no fuzz or
fibrous leaves in the center, so you can trim them for a completely
edible artichoke.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, artichokes are mature when picked, whether
baby or jumbo size. Artichokes of various sizes develop on the same
plant; the baby chokes grow at the bottom where they are protected
from the sun by the plant fronds.
</P>
<P>
   Most artichokes grown in the United States come from California.
They are available year-round, but the season peaks from March to
May. The fall crop usually peaks in October. This year's crop
matured later than usual, and we should have a good supply into
June. It won't set a record, but is the best recent crop. The past
three years' bad weather in California caused severe losses.
</P>
<P>
   To store, do not wash artichokes before refrigerating. They will
keep as long as two weeks if you drizzle a few drops of water on
each artichoke, then seal in an airtight plastic bag and
refrigerate at 32 to 34 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Basic preparation is the same for large or baby artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   For whole, medium or large artichokes, wash under cool running
water, pull off the lower outer petals, and cut stems to 1 inch or
less. Snip off the tips of petals if desired, and drop artichokes
into water acidulated with lemon juice to preserve the green color.
</P>
<P>
   For baby artichokes, bend back the lower, outer petals until
they snap off easily near the base. Cut off the top third or just
below the green tips of the petals with a sharp stainless-steel
knife. Pare remaining dark green areas from bases. Cut off stems.
Halve or quarter as desired. If center petals are purple or pink,
remove them and the fuzzy centers. If the interior of the baby
artichoke is white, the whole artichoke is edible. Dip it in lemon
juice, or rub all surfaces with lemon juice. Cook as directed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COOKING METHODS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ To boil: Stand artichokes in a large pan with 3 quarts
boiling, salted water. If desired, add olive or vegetable oil,
lemon juice and seasonings. Cover and boil gently 20 to 40 minutes
according to size or until a petal near the center pulls out
easily. Drain. For baby artichokes, cook 10 to 15 minutes. After 10
minutes, test with a toothpick stuck in the base where stem was
cut.
</P>
<P>
   _ To steam: Place artichokes on a rack above boiling water,
cover and steam 25 to 40 minutes depending on size or until petal
near center pulls out easily. (Baby artichokes require only about
10 minutes). Because of steam, remove lid carefully.
</P>
<P>
   _ To microwave: Rinse artichokes well in cool water. Pull off
the lowest petals and trim stem even with bottom of choke. There's
no need to snip the prickly, pointy tip from each leaf because the
tip softens during cooking. Do cut 1/2 inch off the top, however.
For 1 medium artichoke, place it upside down in a glass custard cup
or measuring cup. Cover with vented plastic wrap. Microwave on high
4 to 5 minutes. Let stand 5 minutes. If stuffing, spoon out the
fuzzy choke.
</P>
<P>
   To microwave several at a time, place them upside down in
custard cups or a single large casserole. For 2 artichokes,
microwave 7 minutes; 3 artichokes, 10 minutes; 4 artichokes, 12
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Artichokes are an important source of vitamin C, folic acid and
magnesium. They are virtually fat-free and are low in sodium. A
12-ounce artichoke provides 25 calories, 3 grams protein, 6 grams
carbohydrates, 185 milligrams potassium and 75 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid discoloration, cook artichokes in a nonreactive metal,
enamel or ceramic pan and cut with a stainless steel knife.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
