<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1756 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-LEAD-$ADV06-CO     06-03 1647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LEAD-$ADV06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GENERATIONS ABANDONED: Lead poisoning of Mexican children
detected years ago
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Torreon is 300 miles south
of the south-central Texas border. Penoles is spelled with a tilda
symbol over the ``n.''
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORREON, Mexico _ The first studies indicating that lead dust
was poisoning children in this northern Mexican industrial city go
back about 20 years, enough to produce two generations of victims.
</P>
<P>
   That was long before Julio Cesar Olage, 4, and his sister
Guadalupe, 1, were hospitalized in May with enough lead in their
blood to put them in a coma and cause permanent brain damage and
physical harm.
</P>
<P>
   The children's mother, Esperanza Olage, fears it may be too late
for her toddlers despite the treatment they are receiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my other children have been in special education,'' she
said, fighting grief and exhaustion. ``Just look at that one over
there, Maria Elena. She's 18 now, and she can't read or write.''
</P>
<P>
   Olage's youngest children, who have spent two weeks in the
hospital, are among the more than 2,800 children under 12 in
Torreon who have been identified in recent months as having
unacceptable, even extremely dangerous levels of lead in their
blood that could cause mental retardation.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, Torreon has fast become synonymous with neglect and
the tragic consequences of letting industries pollute the
environment, no matter how many jobs they provide.
</P>
<P>
   In one Torreon neighborhood, more than 90 percent of all the
children are contaminated with lead, many at levels so high they
should be under close medical supervision.
</P>
<P>
   That neighborhood, the working-class barrio of Luis Echeverria,
is just a fence away from Met-Mex Penoles, the world's
fourth-largest metal refinery.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Del Pilar family, whose house is next to the
fence, lead has poisoned two generations that has breathed and
ingested dust from the refinery.
</P>
<P>
   Julieta del Pilar was 3 in 1981 when she tested high for lead
during a survey of schoolchildren here conducted by Mexican
university researchers.
</P>
<P>
   She had 34 micrograms of lead for every deciliter of blood,
which at that time was considered abnormal in the United States and
now is considered enough to cause mental retardation if exposure is
not reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican environmental officials failed to react to the research.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Julieta -- who was never able to learn to read or
write -- gave birth to a son, Juan Alberto, 1. He recently tested
at an alarming 60 and Julieta, who was tested because she was
breastfeeding, was told her level was now 67.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta consider a lead
level over 10 unacceptable. Children with levels over 25 should be
in treatment and removed immediately from contaminated sites. Those
with levels over 70 are considered a medical emergency. Children
are particularly vulnerable to lead poisoning because their bodies
and brains are still developing.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 2,800 contaminated children of Torreon, 732 measured
at levels between 25 and 39. Another 604 registered levels between
40 and 69. The total of children over 70 is not known yet.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 20 children have been hospitalized so far, including
4-year-old Julio Cesar Olage, who was admitted at a potentially
devastating 96 and 1-year-old Guadalupe Olage, who measured 83.
</P>
<P>
   Torreon, a stark, desert city 300 miles south of the Texas
border, was forced to confront this epidemic earlier this year,
when the Coahuila state government here ordered the Penoles
refinery to conduct a massive clean-up.
</P>
<P>
   This includes installing new equipment to contain the lead dust
released from raw ore trucked into the refinery, and working with
health officials to hospitalize some children and make sure others
are treated with vitamin and mineral supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Using a $6.4 million fund it has established, the company must
also buy the families' property in Luis Echeverria so it can be
demolished and cleansed of heavy metals and the families relocated.
</P>
<P>
   Many families here are fighting with the company over offers for
their houses, which they say are too low. Meanwhile, the majority
of the affected children are still living in the neighborhood,
which Penoles sweeps and cleans every day with industrial vacuums
and ordinary brooms in an attempt to lower the lead count in
children remaining in the barrio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have children with long-term damage. I can't deny
that,'' said Edmundo Mesta, a doctor and occupational health
specialist who has worked for Penoles for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Mesta has been put in charge of registering children, cleaning
the barrio and trying to reverse Penoles' credibility gap with the
community.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 and 1995, Penoles was audited by environmental officials
and ordered to improve equipment to reduce dangers inside the plant
and threatening emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking inside the plant, at our workers and their
health,'' Mesta said. ``But no one took the time to stop and think
about what we have done to the community in our almost 100 years of
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesta and environmental officials say that lead dust wafting
over the fence from deliveries of raw minerals is the prime source
that's been poisoning the children. Neither emissions from
processing or a giant heap of slag that towers over the refinery's
property are culprits, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists say the full magnitude of Torreon's
environmental health disaster -- one of Mexico's worst to date --
hasn't yet been measured.
</P>
<P>
   Pediatricians and toxicologists say children should also be
tested for traces of other heavy metals, including cadmium and
arsenic. Both are carcinogenic and are so abundant around the
Torreon factory they too pose a major health risk, according to a
study by Dartmouth Medical School published in April.
</P>
<P>
   More children living in barrios beyond Luis Echeverria should
also be tested, said Jose Manuel Velasco, a Torreon pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could a minimum of 6,000 children affected,'' Velasco
said. ``The government's work is not over with.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Velasco found lead in alarming quantities in infants
and toddlers he was treating for other ailments. He reported to
state health officials, who did nothing, and then brought his
grievances to the state legislature, which ordered testing.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has been slow to adopt standards governing lead emissions
and other safety requirements that could have prevented the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   But some scientists argue that studies indicating that Torreon
was in trouble have long been dismissed because officials were
reluctant to crack down on powerful industries.
</P>
<P>
   Toxicologist Lilia Albert began surveys of lead in Torreon's
children in 1978 while she was affiliated with Mexico City's Center
for Investigation and Advanced Studies of the National
Polytechnical Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities ``tried to minimize our findings,'' Albert said. ``I
think the problem was that they didn't want to affect the economy
because the refinery employs so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penoles refinery, owned by Alberto Bailleres, one of
Mexico's wealthiest men, employs about 2,100 here.
</P>
<P>
   Torreon, a city of 500,000, is a company town, where Penoles
distributes coloring books to children about a happy miner and a
main street is called Metallurgical Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Although she can't recall exactly when, Albert reported her
initial findings of high lead levels at an academic conference not
long after she took hair samples from children in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   She also informed federal environmental officials.
</P>
<P>
   They told her the hair samples were too few and were
insufficient proof of a problem, Albert said.
</P>
<P>
   Albert's findings as well as the conclusions of other surveys
taken in 1981 were published in a document in 1986 she says was
also ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The company and federal environmental officials argue that the
studies were not corroborated or widely disseminated.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, a toxicologist at Mexico's University of Durango
-- working in cooperation with the refinery -- published a study
that also confirmed that children were contaminated by lead.
</P>
<P>
   That helped spotlight Torreon's epidemic, although some in the
community had already been demanding action for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a story of complicity between the company and the
government,'' said Francisco Valdez, a university science professor
in Torreon who said he called studies to officials' attention more
than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, parents keeping vigil at Torreon hospitals and those
with children still in the barrio are worried their children are
not receiving proper treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 children in hospitals are receiving succimer, a
drug that removes lead from the body in extreme cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's how many they're treating, that's nothing,'' said
Andres Lugo of the West Texas Regional Poison Center in El Paso,
Texas. He was asked to go to Torreon to give doctors training in
the treatment of heavy metal poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Lugo recommended that many more children be given the drug. But
the company says it has to evaluate each child first and make sure
he won't be returning to Luis Echeverria after treatment.
</P>
<P>
   After 11 days in a hospital, 3-year-old Alfredo Mendiola, for
example, was still undergoing a battery of tests to determine the
extent of his poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   In April Alfredo tested at 71 and was admitted to the hospital
at 61.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the company is a killer. It is killing our children,''
said his mother, Eva. ``What will happen to them in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
