<SLUG> BC-TREK-IAN-MCDIARMID-IN-STAR-WARS-ART-ADV14-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV14 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI
</HEADLINE>
  THE EMPEROR'S NEW CLOTHES: IAN McDIARMID RETURNS TO `STAR WARS'  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., JUNE 14, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Ian
McDiarmid as Senator Palpatine in ``Star Wars: The Phantom
Menace.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Ever since the words ``The Phantom Menace'' first leaked out of
Lucasfilm headquarters, ``Star Wars'' aficionados were tortured by
the mystery: Never mind what is the matrix _ who or what was the
phantom menace?
 &HT;    The Internet offered various contradictory, unsubstantiated
ideas, none of them very convincing. The trailers didn't provide
any hints. The cast and production staff were uniformly unhelpful.
 &HT;    Nobody seemed to know, and everybody yearned to.
 &HT;    Well, everybody except for Ian McDiarmid, who wasn't yearning at
all. And no wonder, since he himself is the phantom menace.
 &HT;    As both Senator Palpatine and the evil Sith Lord Darth Sidious,
it's McDiarmid who wreaks all sorts of cosmic havoc on Qui-Gon Jinn
(Liam Neeson), Obi-Wan Kenobi (Ewan McGregor) and Queen Amidala
(Natalie Portman) in ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace.''
 &HT;    It shouldn't have been so great a surprise _ after all, we'd
already seen McDiarmid back in 1984 as the merciless but aged
Emperor Palpatine in ``Return of the Jedi,'' and it was clear that
the Emperor knew more than a little about the Dark Side.
 &HT;    As for McDiarmid, he had a ball.
 &HT;    ``It was an incredibly unique opportunity,'' the gentlemanly
McDiarmid says during a conversation in the bar at the Almeida
Theatre, headquarters of the London company which he serves as
co-artistic director. ``I was under four hours of Nick Dudman's
very expert makeup for `Return of the Jedi,' and in `The Phantom
Menace' I am basically myself _ though I got about 10 years' help
from a hairpiece.
 &HT;    ``For all intents and purposes, Palpatine looks like me,'' he
said. ``That's sort of fascinating. In my career as an actor I've
often played older than myself, but you don't often go backwards in
time _ when you're really 15 years older _ to play a character
younger than yourself, and far younger than the same character
you've already played.''
 &HT;    McDiarmid spends much of ``The Phantom Menace'' wearing a
bemused, knowing smirk, and he never raises his voice. In one of
the film's tastiest scenes, Palpatine cryptically informs Anakin
Skywalker (Jake Lloyd) _ who we know will emerge as the Emperor's
deadly henchman, Darth Vader _ that he plans to watch the boy's
career very closely.
 &HT;    ``We actually shot that scene about a month before the film came
out,'' McDiarmid says. ``Anyway, it's true what they say about
playing kings and rulers, whether it's in Shakespeare or in `Star
Wars' _ it's not so much what you do, it's what everyone else
around you does.
 &HT;    ``The actor playing the king or ruler must relax and be the
center of it all. That's what I attempted to do throughout the
film.''
 &HT;    The Scottish-born McDiarmid knows from epics _ his credits
include 1981's ``Dragonslayer'' and 1995's ``Restoration,'' as well
as such stage shows as ``Volpone,'' in which he co-starred with his
``great friend'' Denis Lawson.
 &HT;    That makes a third ``Star Wars'' connection for Lawson, who not
only played Wedge, the X-Wing Red Leader in all three of the first
trilogy, but also happens to be Ewan McGregor's uncle.
 &HT;    The whole firestorm of publicity over ``The Phantom Menace'' has
been rather amusing to the 50-something actor, who had never been
associated with an event movie previously. He hadn't paid a lot of
attention to the gathering ``Star Wars'' hype over the last couple
of years, he reports.
 &HT;    In fact, until ``Star Wars'' honcho George Lucas called out of
the blue to invite McDiarmid out for a drink to discuss ``The
Phantom Menace,'' the two men hadn't seen each other in 15 years.
 &HT;    But McDiarmid was delighted to work with Lucas again, especially
since this time he would actually be directed by Lucas, who had
served only as producer on ``Return of the Jedi.''
 &HT;    ``George is, literally, physically and in every other way, in
charge,'' McDiarmid says. ``There are no suits, there's no studio
pressure, there's just George _ and that allowed us to concentrate
on the essence of the film.
 &HT;    ``I am thrilled that George seems determined to be at the helm
in every sense again for `Episode II' and perhaps even for `Episode
III,''' McDiarmid says. ``That's great for everybody, for the cast
and crew and for the fans of `Star Wars.'
 &HT;    ``I think `Star Wars' is as important to George as `The Ring'
cycle was to Wagner. It's absolutely in his blood.''
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    Director Barry Sonnenfeld takes an advance look at ``The Wild,
Wild West.'' 
 SIDEBAR: CONVENTION CALENDAR  
 June 26-27: Trek Expo 99 at the Exposition Center in Tulsa, Okla.,
featuring John de Lancie, Leonard Nimoy and Nicole deBoer. For
information, call (918) 834-9636. 
