<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KUKES-$ADV05-C     06-03 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KUKES-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KUKES: A POOR ALBANIAN CITY HOSTS EVEN POORER REFUGEES
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., June 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ In the cool springtime mornings here, acrid
smoke hangs close to the ground from the burning garbage in a dump
at the edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   The water supply, now rationed to two-hours per day, is low and
only the lucky few who rise before the sun will have showers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everywhere is the rank odor of open sewage and sweat as
the sun inches higher in the sky, and the temperature rises with
it.
</P>
<P>
   So begins the day for 25,000 locals in Kukes and four times as
many refugees living in and around the ramshackle town now
distinguished as the home to Kosovo's dispossessed ethnic
Albanians. Roughly 400,000 refugees have passed through Kukes, and
100,000 have remained in dusty tent camps and crowded private
homes, making it the epicenter of Europe's biggest humanitarian
crisis since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of fame we could have done without,''
concedes Mayor Safet Sula, 37, a democratic reformer and former
university professor. ``It goes without saying that we have big
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a tide of impoverished refugees descending on a similar
small town in the United States. Now, imagine this town was already
dirt poor, falling apart and rife with unemployment before the
influx of newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of Kukes, a town blessed with beautiful
mountains and cursed by fate. Situated in remote northern Albania
and, like the rest of the country, severed politically for much of
this century from the rest of the world, Kukes is a town that
history largely passed by.
</P>
<P>
   The current town, with its deteriorating block apartments and
potholed streets, was built between 1962 and 1978 after the
construction of a huge hydro-electric dam, whose reservoir flooded
the valley and the historic village of Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The roots of the people residing among the Alp-like Vikut
Mountains here stretch back to the Illyrian tribes, identified by
the Greeks when they settled the coastal areas of what is now
Albania in the 7th century B.C. Next came the Romans, whose
spreading empire incorporated the area as part of the province of
Macedonia in 146 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Turks followed to encompass the remote area as
part of the Ottoman Empire. But frigid in the winter and broiling
in the summer, Kukes never showed much promise for settlement or
commercial development.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18th century, historian Edward Gibbon wrote of Albania
that ``within sight of Italy is (a land) less known than the
interior of America.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   No one can seem to agree on why the place is called Kukes (which
Albanians alternatively pronounce ``kook-ESS,'' ``KOOK-see,'' or
simply ``KOOKS''). One legend says Kukes derives its name from the
cuckoo bird. Others believe two more plausible theories: that the
name either comes from the Illyrian word for ``forest,'' or that
Kukes took its name from a 17th century Turkish military leader who
commanded a garrison nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its roots, it was never a large place. A 1938 estimate
put the population at only 1,800. Electricity did not arrive until
1946, when engineers plundered a German tank left behind after the
war and used its diesel engine as a generator.
</P>
<P>
   Italian engineers carved the roads across the rough mountains in
the 1920s and little has been done to improve them since. Until
1991, private ownership of cars was restricted by the communist
regime, so few automobiles plowed the paths now being chewed up by
heavy trucks delivering supplies and moving refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In the region's knotty history, schoolchildren learn of
legendary battles fought in the Kukes valley between Albanian
militias outnumbered by powerful armies -- the Turks in 1909 and
the Serbs in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   In Communist times, under the rule of Albanian dictator Ever
Hoxha, Kukes was eyed as a potential tourist spot, as it sits
astride the man-made lake and scenic mountains. But mining of
copper and chromium, once the town's major job-producer, dumped its
by-products directly into the lake.
</P>
<P>
   When Communism fell, the mines went out of business, leaving
people in Kukes without jobs and with a lake tainted by heavy
metals.
</P>
<P>
   Its newest public building, the whitewashed Mosque of Salim Ben
Mahfuz, was opened in 1995, financed by an Egyptian religious
foundation. But almost no one attends it. While Albania is a mostly
Muslim country, its legacy of Communism means there are few devout.
</P>
<P>
   The annual per capita income of Albania, a country of 3.4
million, is $830, the lowest in Europe. Officially, unemployment in
Kukes was 40 percent before the onset of the refugee crisis.
Unofficially, the figure is put at 80 percent. gap???
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the refugees live in private homes, not the
camps, stretching the resources of Kukes to their breaking point.
The city has asked international relief agencies for help to expand
its aging water system. The mountains of garbage being generated by
the population boom are simply being piled at the northern end of
town and torched.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very poor place. There are no jobs for the Albanians
who live here, much less for the refugees,'' said Imri Gashi, 38,
who worked as a construction foreman in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The main occupation is trading, much of it illegal. Since
Communist rule collapsed in Albania in 1991, the government has
been unable to control its borders. Bandits rule in much of the
northeast, emblematic of the nationwide lawlessness following a
coup in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the world will never really know us -- ever,''
laments Nasif Dukle, a local teacher and the town's historian.
``I'm afraid it will be a strong and lasting memory of war and of
refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   But the crisis has been a boom to local hotels and restaurants
in the town. English-speaking Albanians are earning as much as $100
a day working for aid agencies and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like it was sent from heaven. It is raining money, and
maybe it will last only another month. But everyone is making as
much as they can now,'' says Jonas, a local translator.
</P>
<P>
   One tangible gift of the refugee crisis is a new dirt and gravel
airfield, built by engineers from the United Arab Emirates and
replacing an unusable runway built in 1937 by the Italians.
</P>
<P>
   The town's mayor wants more. He puts faith in NATO that the
Balkans can be put straight, and Kukes will for the first time in
its history have a chance to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that things will change in a good way,'' Sula, the
mayor, says. ``If the problems of Kosovo are solved and the border
is open, we can have new markets for our goods and new friendships.
This could be an important crossroads for that.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
