<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRAH-THEATER-REVIEW     06-03 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRAH-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HURRAH AT LAST': MAKING MINCEMEAT OF BOOMER VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It comes as only a small surprise that a character in
``Hurrah at Last'' suddenly breaks into an Italian aria, since the
scale of Richard Greenberg's eccentric new comedy, which opened
Thursday night at the Gramercy Theater, is nothing if not operatic.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about this offbeat piece, full of what can only be
described as good-natured bile, is BIG, from the ego of the hero,
played by a wondrously stewing and sputtering Peter Frechette, to
the kitchen cabinets, towering pine behemoths out of a shelter
magazine for circus freaks.
</P>
<P>
   Even the ``vast dog,'' in Greenberg's memorable phrasing, that
runs amok in the Act I loft party looks like a midsize Oldsmobile.
He's a 200-pound English mastiff named Thunder.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, whose urbane yuppie dramas, like ``Eastern Standard''
and ``Three Days of Rain,'' have earned him renown as a boomer
balladeer, is aiming here for something big: big laughs, that is,
at the expense of the generation he has so assiduously chronicled
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hurrah at Last'' he takes his sharply observed points and
plunges them in the backs of these selfish and insecure people.
Many of the sacred boomer concerns _ infertility, disposable
income, tortured parental relationships, obsessions with status and
creature comforts _ are ground up and re-served as souped-up
satire.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the potshots he takes are exceedingly funny, like when
Frechette, playing a broke and miserable gay writer named Laurie,
sneezes wetly into the face of the friend's baby he's been
compelled to swaddle.
</P>
<P>
   Or when he calls his terminally disgusted Jewish mother (the
droll Dori Brenner) on the carpet for putting up with a dry
marriage not unlike ``a Saturday morning cartoon written by August
Strindberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurrah at Last,'' presented at the Gramercy as part of the
Roundabout Theater Company season, ultimately doesn't hold together
particularly well, despite the brisk production by David Warren and
some spicy banter from Frechette, Ms. Brenner, Larry Keith and
Judith Blazer.
</P>
<P>
   Target practice is mostly what Greenberg is engaged in; the
scenes, imagined and real (and punctuated by John Gromada's music
for winds and percussion, which sounds a lot like the incidental
music in ``Art''), are mere excuses for Laurie to confront the
people in his life and the demons in his head, and to get some
things off his chest. The proceedings seem to flail along with him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no matter how scattered, it's not an unpleasant purging;
Greenberg's epigrams are often delivered in juicy sound bites. ``It
doesn't buy happiness,'' says Laurie's friend Oliver (Paul Michael
Valley), speaking of money. Yes, the broke Laurie replies, ``but it
upgrades despair.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie _ ``I'm the only boy who was named after a character in
`Little Women''' _ is indeed in desperate straits. He's a starving
novelist, sick and embittered, surrounded by wealthy relatives and
friends whose success only infuriates him further.
</P>
<P>
   They gather at a Christmas party thrown by his sister Thea
(Ileen Getz), who has been having no luck in her efforts to
conceive a child with her husband, Eamon (Kevin O'Rourke), an Irish
multimillionaire. Along with their mother and father (Ms. Brenner
and Keith) Thea invites Oliver, a vapid playwright with a big hit
under his belt; his shockingly fertile wife, Gia (Ms. Blazer), and
the leviathan Thunder (played, according to the credits, by
Dreyfus).
</P>
<P>
   Frechette is at his most engaging when he is foaming at the
mouth. Jealous of Oliver, resentful of his mother, contemptuous of
his sister, Laurie is an impossible brat who exists chiefly to
carp, and what he is most upset about is money. Much of the first
act is consumed with Laurie's complaint that the only intimate
details people guard zealously are about their finances.
</P>
<P>
   This is the setup for a scene in which Oliver strips naked for
Laurie but refuses to reveal how much he is being paid to adapt
Laurie's novel for the movies.
</P>
<P>
   That's about as close to profound as ``Hurrah at Last'' gets. It
has been packaged attractively; they could start taking orders
today for the interiors by the set designer Neil Patel, especially
Thea's killer kitchen. The play, too, is all surface. Like Thunder,
it throws its weight around, in a harmlessly playful sort of way. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HURRAH AT LAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Greenberg; directed by David Warren; sets by Neil
Patel; costumes by Candice Donnelly; lighting by Peter Maradudin;
original music and sound by John Gromada; production stage manager,
Jay Adler; associate artistic director, Scott Ellis. Presented by
the Roundabout Theater Company, Todd Haimes, artistic director;
Ellen Richard, managing director; Julia C. Levy, executive
director, external affairs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Peter Frechette (Laurie), Ileen Getz (Thea), Kevin
O'Rourke (Eamon), Paul Michael Valley (Oliver), Judith Blazer
(Gia), Larry Keith (Sumner) and Dori Brenner (Reva). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-SCHOOL04-COX     06-03 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SCHOOL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOME SCHOOLERS AT BEES BEAT THE ODDS
 &HT;    560&AMP;add. Optional material is usable as a separate box.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The fast-spreading home schooling movement got
another boost from this year's national spelling and geography
bees.
</P>
<P>
   For the third year in a row, at least 5 percent of the
participants in the National Spelling Bee were being educated by
their parents at home, rather than in a public or private school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess cream rises to the top,'' joked Bry(cq) Conley of
Newark, Calif., as she discussed the strong showing by her son Sean
and the dozen other home schoolers among the 249 students in the
spelling bee.
</P>
<P>
   In the televised climax Thursday, two of the eight finalists
were home-schooled. They were Ann Foley, 13, of Marion, Ohio, who
tied for sixth, and George Thampy, 11, of Maryland Heights, Mo.,
who tied for third.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, five of the 55 contestants in the National Geography
Bee were home schoolers, and David Beihl of Saluda, S.C., became
the first home schooler to win the geography bee. In the spelling
bee, the first and only home schooler to win so far was Rebecca
Sealfon of Brooklyn, N.Y., two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spelling and geography bees offer confirmation that home
schooling can work very well indeed,'' said Michael Farris,
president of the Home School Legal Defense Association in
Purcellville, Va., which helped topple many legal barriers to home
schooling. ``I think the movement's coming of age.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong showing by home schoolers really beats the odds. U.S.
Department of Education studies indicate that their numbers have
more than doubled in this decade, and now probably exceed 1
million. But that is still less than 2 percent of all children of
school age.
</P>
<P>
   Home schooling ``is excellent for a very few parents, with very
strong motivation,'' said K. George Thampy, shortly before his
son's third-place finish Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thampy works as a biochemist and physician, and his wife Bina
teaches young George, his two brothers and three sisters at their
home near St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision to home-school our children was scripturally
based,'' Thampy said. ``We wanted their education to stress
character development and godly values which are not promoted in
local schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Conley, on the other hand, said she and her husband, Mike, a
software engineer, were primarily interested in creating
``customized educations'' for Sean, 11, and his two younger
brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's cool about home schooling is that you can pick up
whatever method, subjects or approaches work for your family and
for your kid,'' said Conley. She said her sons will sometimes
concentrate on one to three subjects for two to three months in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents who try to reproduce the factory-school system _ you
sit at the kitchen table and study the same courses as regular
schools from 9 to 3 _ burn out after two or three years,'' Conley
said. ``But that's what's great about home schooling: If you don't
agree with me, you can do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More than half of all home schooling parents are motivated by
religion, usually Christian,'' said policy analyst Kevin Welner of
the graduate school of education at the University of Denver,
Boulder. ``But there is great diversity within that group, and
among the rest of the home schoolers, both in pedagogical theory
and in (ideological) orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, some wouldn't want their children to
compete in bees.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here; Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   For recent research on home schooling, see dueling articles by
Lawrence Rudner and by Kariane and Kevin Welner at Education Policy
Analysis Archives (http://epaa.asu.edu/epaa).
</P>
<P>
   Home schoolers' web pages include the Christian-oriented Home
School Legal Defense Association (http://www.hslda.org), the
secular National Home School Association
(http://www.n-h-a.org/nha.htm), the Jewish Orthodox Bnos Henya
Project (http://bnoshenya.org/), the Muslim home school magazine
(http://islam.org/MHSNR/list1.html), and the Pagan Homeschool Page
(http://hometown.aol.com/barbooch/index.htm).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
