<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1879 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMSBURG-HISTORY-     06-03 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMSBURG-HISTORY-2Takes-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPPING INTO COLONIAL HISTORY WITH CHILDREN IN TOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson was taking questions from the audience, all
reverential, about the Louisiana Purchase, his interest in wine
making and the men who shaped his mind. (Sir Isaac Newton, Sir
Francis Bacon and John Locke, he replied.) Skittish about breaking
the weird decorousness of the event at Colonial Williamsburg, which
was a supposed conversation with the retired third president, I
nonetheless asked if Jefferson had changed his opinion about the
newspapers of his day after they printed the ``scurrilous rumors''
about Sally Hemings, the slave with whom he is thought by many
modern historians, on the basis of DNA evidence, to have fathered a
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that still continuing?'' replied the smiling Jefferson, the
actor Bill Barker, as the audience laughed. Playing to type and
historical accuracy, Jefferson then said, ``I never made answer on
it publicly, and I will not do so today.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, in a soft Virginia drawl, that he was happier since
giving up newspapers in his retirement _ during Jefferson's
presidency, the papers went big with the Hemings scandal _ but then
said, paraphrasing Jefferson's most famous defense of freedom of
the press, that he would rather have ``a nation with newspapers and
no government than a nation with government and no newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience broke into enthusiastic applause, as if a president
himself had spoken.
</P>
<P>
   For three days this spring, my husband and I and our two
children, ages 9 and 5, wandered around Colonial Williamsburg, the
Virginia ``living history'' museum built by John D. Rockefeller
Jr.. I had anticipated another Disneyland. Instead, I found it
genuinely historically interesting, if sometimes hokey, with a new
emphasis on the slaves who made up more than half the town's
population in the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Like the study of American history itself, the 18th-century
capital of the Virginia colony has changed in its 65 years of
restoration from a sanitized celebration of the white planter elite
_ even in 1981 the historian Mike Wallace wrote that ``it embodies
a vision of total social order'' _ to a more real, and not always
politically correct, evocation of the nastier past. A 1994
re-enactment of a slave auction, for example, caused outrage among
some blacks.
</P>
<P>
   This year's theme at Williamsburg, ``Enslaving Virginia,''
offers the most extensive programming yet on the town residents
whose stories were largely unknown to tourists until the 1970s,
when a new generation of Williamsburg historians began insisting on
their inclusion. Since 1998, Williamsburg has organized its
programs around four rotating ``Days in History.'' If you are there
on the day that is supposed to be Nov. 17, 1775, when Lord Dunmore,
the colony's governor, offered freedom to any slave who sided with
the British crown, it is possible to spend almost all of your time,
from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m., in history walks, talks and re-enactments
focused on slavery.
</P>
<P>
   In between, you can stumble into conversations with some of
Williamsburg's 100 or so ``character interpreters,'' actors who
engaged us in interactive, impromptu and slightly embarrassing
theater often meant to teach the unsavory reality of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible news about town today, you have probably heard,'' one
actor playing a Colonial Williamsburg resident announced when we
approached him and a cluster of patriots on Duke of Gloucester
Street, the main street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negroes with arms _ can you believe it?'' another asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wise move, to free the servants and slaves of your enemy,''
the first said, referring to Lord Dunmore.
</P>
<P>
   I asked how people who spoke of freedom could own slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``God himself has put them here to be slaves,'' a third actor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, making sure we got the point, the first said, ``You cannot
free such valuable property.''
</P>
<P>
   But earlier we had been to the Courthouse for the re-enactment
of several trials and an unpleasant moment when Williamsburg's
desire to be honest about its history with blacks collided with
1999 sensitivities. An audience of tourists filled the spectators'
benches as actors playing a bailiff, an obnoxious defendant and a
judge argued over a case.
</P>
<P>
   At one point the judge asked for three volunteers from the
courtroom to inspect some land in dispute. The tourists all
volunteered eagerly. The bailiff selected three, two of them young
black men. But the judge rejected the two, because they were black.
``Free Negroes can't serve!'' barked the defendant, underscoring
the point, as the two 20th-century blacks sat down, looking
embarrassed. When I asked Williamsburg about the incident after I
got back, Stephen Elliott, the vice president for education,
winced, saying that the scene had been cut from the trial last year
and that it shouldn't have happened.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   We arrived in town, a seven-hour drive from New York City,
halfway through another of Williamsburg's ``days in history,'' May
15, 1776, when the colonists declared their independence. We were
unaware of this until we were efficiently educated by a
Williamsburg Inn concierge, who presented us with the Visitor's
Companion, a newspaper for tourists, which listed a daunting buffet
of events for the week. Looking at it was like trying to decide
what courses to take in college, but our concierge quickly circled
what she thought was best for us and the children.
</P>
<P>
   We weren't staying at the inn proper, the behemoth
white-columned institution of choice for visiting heads of state
(Williamsburg was the site of an economic summit conference for the
world's industrial powers in 1983) but at its lower-priced and
modern Providence Hall Wing, which is recommended for families.
There, the rooms are bigger and decorated with the usual wing
chairs, but they are not antiques. We had a balcony that looked
over a duck pond, and were just a short walk from the inn, where we
ate breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning we walked the five minutes to the historic
district for an orientation tour, led by a guide, Jerry Hedgepeth,
who pointed out attractions like the Wyeth House, where Jefferson
went to law school.
</P>
<P>
   He also gave a brief history lesson: In 1699 the Virginia
capital moved from Jamestown to Williamsburg, a planned city built
around a town common, Market Square, and anchored by the Capitol
building at one end and the College of William and Mary at the
other. Although Virginia's capital moved to Richmond in 1780,
Williamsburg was still intact in 1926, when Rockefeller began the
restoration that would eventually cost $68 million. Today there are
more than 500 restored or reconstructed buildings and 90 acres of
gardens and greens.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things I noticed was that Williamsburg, though
bucolic, was not pristine; paint was peeling off many of the white
clapboard houses, some of the grass was scruffy and sandy dirt
covered the main streets. Yet earlier criticism of the town by
historians focused on its absurd perfectness. When I got back home,
I called Cary Carson, Williamsburg's vice president for research,
who told me that Williamsburg has worked recently to make the town
less precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to paint all of the buildings at the same time,'' he
said. ``But nobody now and nobody then painted their property from
end to end.'' He added that sand is now brought in to cover up the
20th-century blacktop of Duke of Gloucester Street and that some of
the lawn-mowing is done by grazing sheep.
</P>
<P>
   After the tour, we went to some of the trades shops, popular
with the children, like that of the printer and the wig maker, who
told us that the hairpieces favored by 18th-century gentlemen were
``beastly uncomfortable, but they were fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon I went on ``Enslaving Virginia,'' a one-hour
history walk with a guide, Harvey Bakari, who ran through a quick
general history of slavery, then described how slaves did the
invisible work, lost to history, that made Williamsburg possible.
He concluded that ``the system of slavery would cause the colony to
live with a contradiction, the contradiction of liberty and
bondage.''
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was that there were few remnants on the walk to
illustrate his points; the slaves lived in Williamsburg's
outbuildings behind the big houses and left behind no furniture and
almost no belongings. Although slaves may well have spent as much
time as anyone else laboring behind the scenes in the town's grand
buildings, their identities were invisible in the Governor's Palace
or the Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   We ate most of our meals in Williamsburg's not-cheap
restaurants, where the waitresses wore period garb and the
Colonial-style food was mediocre, although no doubt better than
what people really ate in the 18th century. The best was Christiana
Campbell's Tavern, a reconstruction, where George Washington dined.
</P>
<P>
   I had scallop and oyster pot pie and was startled when an
actress playing Mrs. Campbell materialized, asking how we liked our
dinner. The real Mrs. Campbell was described not very pleasantly by
an 18th-century traveler as ``a little old Woman, about four feet
high; &AMP; equally thick, a little turn up Pug nose, a mouth screw'd
up to one side.'' The actress was younger and taller, but her odd
little dinner performance proved how fluid, and alive, history is.
</P>
<P>
   Today the contradictions of Jefferson on slavery are as riveting
as they were in his time. Just as we imagined the real Christiana
Campbell in her tavern, we could imagine the real Jefferson arguing
in the House of Burgesses, a part of the reconstructed Capitol that
nonetheless was compelling to see. History by definition is an act
of the imagination, especially for children. Williamsburg helps it
take flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
