<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      06-03 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIONSHIPS ARE HARD (BUT EASY TO TALK ABOUT) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mafia boss, sex columnist and sports agent are not likely to
turn up on anyone's list of most admired professions. But these
careers have been very good to HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Even before ``The Sopranos,'' with its mobbed-up family values,
emerged as last season's best and most talked about show (weekly
repeats begin on Wednesday), HBO had built two first-rate series
around characters whose jobs are full of satiric possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The comedies ``Sex and the City'' and ``Arliss,'' beginning new
seasons on Sunday, would never appear on a broadcast network in
anything like the same form, and it's more than rough language that
sets them apart. Their unheroic heroes, sophisticated social
assumptions and high level of cynicism are essential to their wit
and success.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sex and the City,'' Sarah Jessica Parker plays Carrie
Bradshaw, a newspaper columnist who charts the sexual customs of
New York City with all the devotion of an anthropologist and far
more personal involvement. As the second season begins, she has
broken up with her rich, powerful, commitment-phobic lover, known
as Big (Chris Noth), and imagines she sees him everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But as always the plot is less crucial than the observations of
Carrie and her relationship-obsessed friends, who in Sunday's
episode muse about the rules of breakups, and in the next week's
about how much or how little people like to talk during sex.
</P>
<P>
   Though its Manhattan locations are conspicuous and believable,
in other ways ``Sex and the City'' is loosely tethered to reality.
Carrie's friends are all upscale and urbane; they offer the kind of
convenient mix of attitudes that only occurs in fiction, and they
have one-track minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like seventh grade with bank accounts,'' says Miranda
(Cynthia Nixon), a lawyer who rarely has a man in her life,
stomping out of a restaurant in exasperation because the other
women will talk only about men.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha (Kim Cattrall), a public relations executive, is a
sleep-around. Charlotte (Kristin Davis), an art dealer, is a
perfectionist and control freak. They have a lot to talk about,
often in blunt terms.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's episode, when the friends take Carrie to a Yankees
game to cheer her up, baseball offers too many opportunities for
dialogue built on bad puns and double-entendres.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its sometimes clotted dialogue, there are solid reasons
why this series is a hit. It is often slyly funny and astute.
Charlotte says, ``It takes half the time you went out with someone
to get over him''; no scientific study is likely to pin the time
frame down better.
</P>
<P>
   And the humor can unexpectedly give way to real emotion. When
Carrie spots Big in a bar, it doesn't matter that she is on a
glamorous date with a Yankee. Her face registers both her pain and
her attempt to hide it, with Ms. Parker bringing deftness and
sympathy to a role that doesn't conspicuously lend itself to those
qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Under their cynical facades, these women are endless optimists
about ideal relationships, even as they settle for fleeting,
imperfect ones. That hopefulness may be the series' secret weapon. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ARLISS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Sunday night at 9:30 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no mushiness at the center of ``Arliss,'' which returns
for its fourth season as snappy and cynical as ever. Robert Wuhl,
who created the series and plays Arliss Michaels, a greedy sports
agent to the stars, makes the character likable because he so
blithely, openly enjoys making money.
</P>
<P>
   In this weekend's episode, Arliss has a health scare and
undergoes a colonoscopy. That leads to uncharacteristic flatulence
jokes that seem imported from ``South Park''; this series is too
sophisticated to need them.
</P>
<P>
   As Arliss waits for a call from the doctor, two of his
assistants, Rita (Sandra Oh) and Kirby (Jim Turner) squabble over
which of them will cheat a little old lady out of some valuable
baseball cards. A third, Stanley (Michael Boatman from ``Spin
City''), plans for a more lucrative life after Arliss.
</P>
<P>
   But while the series is cynical, it is never mean-spirited, and
it has a satisfying way of finding story endings that are humane
without being forced.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's show ends with a priceless scene in which Arliss sits
in front of a mausoleum. Wuhl's facial reaction demonstrates why
the series has maintained both its satiric edge and its appealing
humor. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX AND THE CITY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO, Sunday night at 9 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Created by Darren Star. Star and Michael Patrick King, executive
producers; John Melfi and Jenny Bicks, supervising producers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Sarah Jessica Parker (Carrie), Kim Cattrall (Samantha),
Kristin Davis (Charlotte), Cynthia Nixon (Miranda) and Chris Noth (
Big). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONY-AWARDS-3TAKES-NY     06-03 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-AWARDS-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY HOLDS ITS BREATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Forget the stock market. Never mind the Belmont. If
you have a farm, bet it.
</P>
<P>
   The surest wager in the world, say Broadway's pundits and
politicos, is that come 9:45 on Sunday night Dame Judi Dench will
rise to the stage of the Gershwin Theater and be presented with a
Tony award, her first, for her leading role in the drama ``Amy's
View.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Broadway is famously unpredictable, and its seers not
always reliable. But what is certain is that awards in 21
categories will be handed out on Sunday, when the best and
brightest of the theater world will gather to celebrate the end of
a season that many say wasn't exactly better or brighter than many
in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Though attendance and box office receipts are at an all-time
high, many theater professionals still grumble that the season has
been heavy on the blah.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the competition among musicals was dominated by ``The
Lion King'' and ``Ragtime,'' two audience pleasers that battled
till the end of Tony night, when ``Lion King'' won the Tony for
best musical. This year the musical field is weak, with three
bookless shows and ``Parade,'' already closed and considered a long
shot.
</P>
<P>
   But where musicals have faltered, plays have flourished, and it
is in the dramatic categories, many theater professionals say, that
the true drama of this year's Tonys will be found. For example, in
the race for best actor, Kevin Spacey, star of the revival of ``The
Iceman Cometh,'' will face off with Brian Dennehy, star of the
revival of ``Death of a Salesman,'' for the title of big man on
Broadway. Those two shows are also neck and neck for best revival.
And for best play the race may be even closer.
</P>
<P>
   With ballots due today, 11th-hour lobbying was in full stride
this week. Nominated actors made time for interviews and public
appearances, press representatives hounded tardy voters to see
shows, and producers worked the telephones to get out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The awards, administered by the League of American Theaters and
Producers and the American Theater Wing, are voted on by 812
theater professionals, including representatives of those two
organizations, designated members of the theatrical unions and some
theater journalists.
</P>
<P>
   An informal poll of two dozen theater experts _ producers, press
agents, talent agents and other know-it-alls, most of them Tony
voters and all of whom spoke only on the condition of anonymity _
suggested that there will be more than a few fierce races. In at
least three categories _ best play, best actor in a play and best
revival of a play _ the contests seem too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of an overwhelming blockbuster has added to the sense
that it's anybody's game to win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody concedes this is not a banner year,'' said one
agent. ``But on the other hand things are so wide open, everybody
thinks they're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some locks, to be sure, they say. (See Dame Judi.) The
three other women's acting categories _ best supporting actress in
a play and lead and supporting actress in a musical _ also have
clear front-runners. There is also a strong consensus about the
category of best musical and several smaller awards.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that the crystal ball gets murky, with many
categories having at least two strong contenders and sometimes
more. The Tony broadcast begins on PBS at 8, with awards for
design, direction, choreography and orchestration.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 the broadcast is handed off to CBS. Then the major acting
and production awards are delivered and, perhaps most important for
producers, the big production numbers will be shown in what amounts
to free advertising. The Tonys have become an important promotional
tool for Broadway, the one time each year that theater gets into
living rooms west of the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   A lively number by the cast of ``Smokey Joe's Cafe'' in 1995 was
credited with boosting that show's sales; this week it became the
longest running musical revue in Broadway history.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Tony show will open with the traditional Big
Production Number, featuring all the star presenters in a splashy
rendition of ``There's No Business Like Show Business.'' Numbers
from the nominees for best musical (``The Civil War,'' ``Parade,''
``Fosse'' and ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'') will follow, as
well as songs from the nominees for best musical revival (``Annie
Get Your Gun,'' ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown,'' ``Little Me''
and ``Peter Pan'').
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The job of making sure all this runs smoothly falls to Walter C.
Miller, executive producer of the awards, a man driven to
encapsulate the majesty, dignity and historical sweep of The
Theater, all in exactly one hour, 59 minutes and 54 seconds allowed
in the CBS broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Automatically we hate every winner,'' Miller said. ``You get
someone up there that starts thanking the doorman and their sister
Sadie, and you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to having to counter the impression of a lackluster
season, Miller's task has been complicated by the announcement in
late January by Rosie O'Donnell, who had been the show's host for
the last two years, that she would not be able to preside this
year. Ms. O'Donnell, credited with increasing the Tony broadcast's
ratings, blamed scheduling difficulties. (She has, it should be
noted, found time to grace the show's opening number.)
</P>
<P>
   The Tonys were also forced to move from Radio City Music Hall,
its home during the O'Donnell administration, to the Gershwin
Theater because Radio City is being renovated. But the Gershwin has
roughly 4,000 fewer seats as well as a current musical, ``Peter
Pan.''
</P>
<P>
   This means that the swarm of behind-the-scenes technicians who
run the Tonys have had to rehearse and set up their equipment in
the limited time before and after performances.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of one host the show will have a dozen sets of
presenters, matched for reasons sentimental, theatrical and
otherwise. Jason Robards and Spacey, past and present Hickeys in
``Iceman,'' will appear together, as will Scott Wolf and Christian
Slater, who have both portrayed the narrator in ``Side Man'' and
have the added connection of being cute and under 30.
</P>
<P>
   With the likes of Calista Flockhart, Matthew Broderick and
Laurence Fishburne on hand, there is little question that the Tonys
will have a decent celebrity quotient. And with Arthur Miller, who
is to receive a lifetime achievement award, and a lineup of elegant
leading ladies like Angela Lansbury, Carol Burnett, Chita Rivera
and Julie Andrews, the show will definitely have appropriate
theatrical weight.
</P>
<P>
   Whether all that will translate to strong television ratings is
an open question.
</P>
<P>
   While the most interesting races are likely to unfold in the
second part of the evening, the first hour, on PBS, may offer a few
clues and ``ooohs.''
</P>
<P>
   The award for best director of a play is a terrific lineup of
talent: Robert Falls (``Salesman''), Howard Davies (``Iceman''),
Garry Hynes (``The Lonesome West'') and Trevor Nunn (``Not About
Nightingales'').
</P>
<P>
   Most of the voters who were asked seemed to like Nunn, who is
credited with resurrecting ``Nightingales,'' a lost play by a young
Tennessee Williams. But a few said that Falls might take the award,
and that if he did, it could be the beginning of a lovely evening
for ``Salesman.''
</P>
<P>
   The early portion should also offer some moral victories for
advocates of traditional musicals, as the theater professionals
predicted that the awards for best book and original score would
go, respectively, to Alfred Uhry and Jason Robert Brown, both for
``Parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Another curiosity is the scenic design category: Bob Crowley was
nominated for both ``Twelfth Night'' and ``Iceman'' and will
compete against Richard Hoover (``Nightingales'') and Riccardo
Hernandez (``Parade''). Several Tony watchers said votes for
Crowley might be split between the two plays, allowing Hoover's
evocative, shadowy design for the Williams play to win.
</P>
<P>
   The real horse races come after CBS takes up the signal.
</P>
<P>
   The first award presented is for featured actor in a play. Here
the front-runner is Kevin Anderson of ``Salesman,'' who is up
against his cast mate Howard Witt as well as Finbar Lynch
(``Nightingales'') and Frank Wood (``Side Man''). But a few voters
felt that Anderson's youth and Witt's long service in the
theatrical trenches might conspire to lend Witt the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Another early award, featured actor in a musical, has
significantly less intrigue, with most voters believing Snoopy, as
portrayed by actor Roger Bart, will have his supper time, in part
because Scott Wise and Desmond Richardson, two nominees from
``Fosse,'' will split the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the award for best actor in a musical seems to be
a showdown between Tom Wopat (``Annie Get Your Gun'') and Martin
Short (``Little Me''). More is at stake for Wopat, who has never
been nominated and whose show is still open, so many
prognosticators said his producers, Fran and Barry Weissler, would
lobby hard enough for him to win.
</P>
<P>
   But Short's performance was loved by the press and the public,
and his name value may carry the day. Brent Carver of ``Parade''
was also mentioned by a few of those polled; his victory would be a
major upset.
</P>
<P>
   The actress categories are generally easier to call, the
professionals say. Zoe Wannamaker's performance in ``Electra,''
which earned her a nomination as best actress in a play, was widely
hailed as a revelatory portrait of Sophocles' tortured heroine.
</P>
<P>
   But the show closed in March, eons ago in Broadway time. The
other nominees are Stockard Channing, a past Tony winner, who
critics found to be about the only good thing in the revival of
``The Lion in Winter,'' and Marion Seldes, who won in 1967 and gave
a brief, admired turn in ``Ring Round the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   But _ and it's a monstrous but, the voters insist _
(italics)nobody(end italics) is going to ignore Dame Judi, who won
the Academy Award in March for ``Shakespeare in Love'' and then
promptly took up residence on Broadway, lending the season a hefty
dose of glamour and class.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Franz, playing Linda Loman in ``Salesman,'' is highly
favored to win as best featured actress in a play, although several
voters noted cattily that Ms. Franz's producers should also get an
award for somehow inveigling the Tony committee to consider her as
a featured actress, not a leading lady, thereby eliminating a
possible collision with the Dench express.
</P>
<P>
   On the musical side Bernadette Peters is strongly favored to win
best actress, although a few voters saw Carolee Carmello
(``Parade'') as a dark horse.
</P>
<P>
   The category of featured actress in a musical has seemingly been
a foregone conclusion for months; an early consensus formed around
the star-in-the-making Kristin Chenoweth (``You're a Good Man,
Charlie Brown'') and has stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   The major musical awards, for new work and revival, both have
favorites and long shots. For best musical ``Fosse'' is still
considered the winner by most of those polled, but small camps
seemed to be forming around ``Parade,'' which won a majority of the
pre-Tony awards, and even ``The Civil War,'' which had poor
reviews. Still, when pressed, the vast majority said ``Fosse''
would win.
</P>
<P>
   In the musical revival category, ``Annie Get Your Gun'' is the
leading candidate, but several said that ``Charlie Brown'' had put
a scare in the sharpshooter by winning several earlier awards.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the big three races.
</P>
<P>
   Many say the easiest to call may be the best actor contest, in
which Spacey and Dennehy are joined by Corin Redgrave, who
portrayed a brutal prison warden in ``Not About Nightingales,'' and
the Irish actor Brian F. O'Byrne, a brawler in ``The Lonesome
West.''
</P>
<P>
   The category is clearly viewed as Dennehy vs. Spacey. Both
actors have tried to play down the competition, appearing at the
Outer Critics Circle Awards and Drama Desk Awards to hand out
awards to each other.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of those asked said Dennehy would win.
</P>
<P>
   The reason seems to be partly sentimental. Dennehy, playing the
loser Willy Loman, touched a deep nerve in many who had seen the
play before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a completely new Willy,'' one producer said. ``He made
it his own.''
</P>
<P>
   While Spacey had strong reviews, some say the memory of previous
Hickeys, particularly Robards' 1956 version, may stand in his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sizable group of older people who remember Jason's
performance and still love it,'' one producer said. He added that
Dennehy would not have the same problem. ``I doubt there's anybody
running around saying Lee J. Cobb was so much better,'' the
producer said, referring to the actor who originated the role of
Willy Loman.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some noted that Spacey is also a Broadway veteran, having
won a Tony in 1991 for ``Lost in Yonkers.'' He has the added cachet
of being a Hollywood star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ultimately better for Broadway if Kevin wins,'' another
producer said. ``They'll reward him.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the best actor award may also reflect the voting
on best revival. Several Tony voters said they had split their
ballots between Dennehy for best actor and ``Iceman'' for best
revival. The logic, said one, was that the scope of the
four-and-a-half-hour ``Iceman'' was more impressive, while
productions of ``Death of a Salesman'' were more common. Also, the
voter said, it spread the Tony wealth around.
</P>
<P>
   In a year in which British imports ruled Broadway, the closest
race is the one with the most patriotic overtones. The competition
for best play seems to be an almost dead heat between ``Closer,''
Patrick Marber's dissection of modern British relationships, and
``Side Man,'' Warren Leight's bittersweet paean to jazz musicians.
Smaller camps support ``Nightingales'' and ``The Lonesome West.''
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom is that ``Side Man'' may have a small
edge because it was written by an American, and with slow sales, it
needs the award more than ``Closer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would really help `Side Man,''' said one press agent not
connected to the play. ``Plus, it would be nice to have an American
play on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Another press agent summed up the race this way: ```Closer' is
contemporary, fresh and out there and doesn't pander to the
traditional Broadway audience. Those are also the negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   A sweep by any production, except perhaps ``Salesman,'' seems a
long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an uninspired year, there's not going to be any big
winners and losers,'' one veteran press agent said. ``But as far as
the industry is concerned, that's just fine. It will spread the joy
around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
