<HEADER>
A1891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOREAU-RETROSPECTIVE-     06-03 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOREAU-RETROSPECTIVE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: GUSTAVE MOREAU _ STRANGE IN HIS DAY AND NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps as part of some larger millennial celebration
conspiracy, the Metropolitan Museum of Art has mounted its second
summer retrospective of a neglected if not disdained fin de siecle
European painter. Last year it was Sir Edward Burne-Jones, the
English Pre-Raphaelite. Now comes Gustave Moreau, the French
painter who ignored the art of his own time and, firing his
imagination with story lines and stylistic tips from past cultures,
created an art for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Organized on the centennial of Moreau's death in 1898, this is
his first American retrospective in 35 years. In many ways it feels
right on schedule. His highly finished paintings, with their
opulent detail and hothouse emotionality, called ``a little
sickish'' in his own time, look as intensely strange and decadent
as ever. Their fin de siecle aroma has withstood the test of time.
Their strangeness is only partly modified by hindsight, which
includes Moreau's influence on the Symbolists, the Fauves and the
Surrealists and his nearly abstract watercolors, which were once
cited as precursors of Abstract Expressionism and now suggest
Anselm Kiefer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Moreau was a loner, not a joiner. Although a
frequent presence in salons, he was the odd man out in 19th-century
French painting. His disturbing style was not Romantic, Realist or
Neo-Classical and had little to do with Impressionism, which he
considered bland and unadventurous. His independence and ability to
create a complete, self-sustaining esthetic universe is
particularly pertinent today, when the dearth of clear-cut art
movements makes many artists feel like loners.
</P>
<P>
   Moreau's backward- and forward-looking art is frequently
described in terms of opposites, as both regressive and
revolutionary; withheld, even hermetic, yet psychologically
intense; overly refined and finicky yet physically bold.
</P>
<P>
   He had a literary bent and an infallible faith in the human
imagination, which was one of his great subjects. And he had all
the markings of a painter's painter. Like Albert Pinkham Ryder, for
example, he worked and reworked his paintings over long periods of
time, avoided selling them when possible, and gained a reputation
for being reclusive, at least until the last six years of his life,
when he started teaching at the Ecole des Beaux-Arts and influenced
students like Matisse and Rouault.
</P>
<P>
   But Moreau was also serenely sure of of his achievement.
Well-to-do, he created an environment in which his paintings could
stay together in perpetuity: He added two stories to his house on
Rue de Rochefoucauld, where he lived and worked most of his life,
and bequeathed it to France along with its contents and 14,000
works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the works in this exhibition of 30 paintings and more
than 200 works on paper and oil sketches were lent by the Musee
Gustave Moreau, which remains the best place to experience Moreau's
art at full strength. But this exhibition does a more than adequate
job. It is consistently informative and intermittently affecting.
While it is hard to imagine loving everything Moreau put his
versatile hand to _ his art covers an immense range of style and
feeling _ it is equally hard to imagine loving none of it.
</P>
<P>
   The show contains several of the artist's greatest hits.
``Oedipus and the Sphinx,'' in the Met's collection, shows her
locked on his chest like a particularly elegant raptor, staring
into his face as if in shock from the realization that the jig is
finally up. Exhibited in the Salon of 1864, the painting earned
Moreau his first fame, was bought by Napoleon III and inspired
copies in the press, some of which are included here.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Salome (Salome Dancing Before Herod),'' the seductress,
ashimmer with silver, floats on the tips of her toes through the
burnished atmosphere of a palace that seems extrapolated from the
Hagia Sophia. And ``Hercules and the Lernaean Hydra'' shows an
exquisite youth confronting a veritable umbrella stand of swaying,
battle-ready snake heads dominated by a giant caped cobra in a
landscape strewn with victims. Both works were shown at the Salon
of 1876, again with much notice.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at these works, one can understand the case against
Moreau. It's all too much. John Rewald, the great chronicler of
Impressionism and Post-Impressionism, found his style overwrought,
flawed by ``a futile application to detail'' and categorized it as
``merely elaborate invention,'' greatly preferring Odilon Redon's
imaginary images for being partly inspired by nature. Gauguin, who
admired the artist, nonetheless complained that ``every human being
he makes is a piece of jewelry covered with jewelry'' and called
him ``an excellent chaser,'' referring no doubt to the ornamental
metalwork that is ubiquitous in the paintings. Other craft-oriented
epithets would have done just as well: engraver, gilder,
embroiderer, weaver, ceramicist, carver.
</P>
<P>
   Delicately roiling patterns and forms in every imaginable medium
cover nearly every surface in many of these paintings. We may be
lucky that Moreau never completed some of the obsessive detail in
some paintings; they may be the better for it.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Apparition'' of 1874-76, which shows Salome dancing
once again but with a vision of St. John the Baptist's severed head
floating before her, the entire architectural setting was simply
scratched into expanses of still-wet areas of milk chocolate paint,
making the surrounding palace less tangible than the Baptist's
head. In ``The Unicorn'' they are simply drawn in equally fine
lines of black paint on nearly bare surfaces, implying luxurious
garments, headdresses, chalices and textiles covered with fine
filigree.
</P>
<P>
   Moreau was born in Paris in 1826 to parents who encouraged his
artistic talents from the start. He began copying in the Louvre at
18, studied with the Neo-Classical painter Francois Edouard Picot
and for three years at the Ecole des Beaux-Arts, beginning in 1846.
</P>
<P>
   The first galleries of the exhibition are dominated by works
from the 1850s, including copies from Sodoma and Raphael (an
assertive, sweet-faced putto) that he made during two years of
study in Rome, where he sometimes painted alongside Edgar Degas.
Here he wavers between Neo-Classicism and Romanticism and even
Realism. His gigantic ``Song of Solomon'' is dominated by contorted
figures reminiscent of Delacroix and Chasseriau. His drawings of
friends, including one of Degas at the Uffizi, have some of Degas'
careful observation and austerity. Take a good look: these sheets
are the last you'll see of 19th-century France until the
exhibition's final work, a small self-portrait in ink on canvas.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hereafter imagination, history and a wild esthetic eclecticism
hold sway. Moreau seemed to believe in magic, centaurs, griffins,
Christian saints and Greek gods. He looked at Renaissance, Gothic,
Byzantine, Indian and Japanese art and seems to have been adept at
blending their conventions. The background landscape of ``The
Unicorn,'' for example, is a gloss on Renaissance compositions so
loosely worked that it looks both modern and somewhat Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Moreau's interest in the past could have resulted in mere
academicism had he not pursued his passion for exoticism, stylistic
eclecticism and physical experimentation to the extent he did. His
paintings give ancient myths a psychological heat not unlike that
of Henry Fuseli and William Blake, but the temperature is increased
by his feeling for the material things depicted in his paintings
and for the materials of art.
</P>
<P>
   This passion is manifested in this show in a direct and riveting
manner, in the many drawings, studies and preparatory sketches,
especially those clustered about several of the most important
canvases. It is visible as well in the constant shifts and changes
in Moreau's painting methods, which become more numerous and
contradictory as he proceeds. Up close, the later paintings in
particular can seem almost cacophonous in their contrasting
techniques. Again ``The Unicorn'' is a telling example, full of
frequent shifts between precise rendering, loose scumblings that
are alternately thickly impastoed or watery thin and the sketchy
yet refined linear filigrees of pattern. And a second look at the
rocky dwelling of the Lernaean Hydra reveals it to be brushed in
lightly and loosely, like a bit of particularly heavy mist.
</P>
<P>
   The arduous working process revealed by the drawings and
watercolors often creates the sensation that one is looking over
the artist's shoulder. Executed in ink, graphite, watercolor and
chalk, these vary tremendously in size and degree of finish with
some of the best being small, rough ink studies. From the 18
drawings that contributed to the making of ``Oedipus and the
Sphinx,'' for example, we see how many different, far more
conventional poses Moreau considered before he fixed on the potent
arm's-length embrace of the final image. Among those surrounding
``Hercules and the Lernaean Hydra'' are several studies of
different snakes heads made from reproductions and possibly after
visits to a natural history museum, reflecting an attentiveness to
natural detail that argues against Rewald's charge of ``merely
elaborate invention.''
</P>
<P>
   At their best Moreau's paintings are like children's-book
illustrations for adults, full of peculiar intensities and sexual
innuendos and physical detail that give familiar tales an
unaccustomed vividness. But their enveloping vision is not really
literary; in his best images Moreau pares the story down to a
dramatic moment whose spell transcends a particular narrative. He
achieved this spell through a combination of poetic license and
artistic discipline that give this exhibition a special
fascination. That Moreau's liberated imagination seems to have
gradually loosened his hand adds to its resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gustave Moreau: Between Epic and Dream'' is at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, Fifth Avenue at 82nd Street, (212)
879-5500, through Aug. 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
