<HEADER>
A1894 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-LIFE04-COX     06-03 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A tough cut: Taking pruners to an old friend
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLATNA _ Some might call it unthinkable, lopping off the top of
a large Japanese maple, and I acknowledge that it was the hardest
cut I've made in a long time; it was my first-bought. But it had to
be done. It was for the good of the tree, not just for me. And for
the garden.
</P>
<P>
   The average red threadleaf represents the height of elegance as
it dips and swoops and weeps, showing off its red foliage each
spring, then again in the fall. But this tree didn't dip much, or
swoop, and it wept barely at all. Instead, it grew mostly
horizontally, after its trunk reached a mere 18 inches in height.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen inches tall and somewhere around 20 years old. That'd
be respectable for a bonsai, but this was a garden maple, and its
growing habit had grown unseemly: Two long limbs reached out in
opposite directions at the top of the trunk. Oh, they had a bit of
a curve in them, but that didn't prevent the tree from looking like
a very short, very wide alien in my garden.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way; when I bought the maple in suburban
Washington back in the mid-1980s, it was pretty, and I was proud.
My first maple. I grew it in a container on Capitol Hill and
marveled that it was putting on so much more width than height.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I'd look at it and recall the words to a B.B. King
blues song about a ``sweet li'l angel. I love the way-y-y she
spreads her wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Atlanta in 1989, I made her the centerpiece of a
section of my back garden. She continued to spread, growing wider
by the year. Then, alas, as too often happens, the unusual became
the unwanted. By the mid-'90s I was looking at the widespread maple
and wanting her to flap her wings, so she would put on some height.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't. She kept on spreading, with each wing eventually
reaching some 5 feet. Still the trunk was 18 inches high.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes context is everything. In a space containing nothing
else, this tree with the 10-foot wingspan might still be beautiful,
the effect of one wing hovering over the fishpond a serendipitous
stroke of fine design. But in my very crowded space, it was lost, a
misfit, its novel wings unnoticed, unappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   I could have taken out the weeping juniper to give the maple
more room for its left wing. Or removed the black bamboo, opening
up space for the right wing. Instead, I brought out the pruners.
</P>
<P>
   First I cut one wing, then the other. It hurt. So many years, so
many springs and autumns, gone. Just like that. What was left was
the trunk, with the two fat, curved wing stubs at the top. I didn't
want to leave those reminders of the old horizontal tree; I wanted
a fresh start. So I decided to cut off the top of the trunk,
bringing it down to just over a foot tall.
</P>
<P>
   It was somehow fitting that this would be a rough cut to make. I
had left my pruning saw in McCaysville, so I had to either wait for
another day or do what I did: attack the 3-inch-diameter trunk with
pruners and a butcher knife, squeezing and hacking until I was able
to break off the top with a final push.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp crack signaled that it was done. I gathered the severed
wings, the broken top and wondered if I had done the right thing,
knowing I could never undo it.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking a way to preserve something of those garden-fresh days
when Japanese maples and I first met, I kept about 3 feet of one
wing, placing it on the fireplace mantel in the parlor. Vertical at
last, the wing looks good there, so much better than it did in the
garden. So much more prominent and, yes, elegant even. How much it
reminds me of a bronzed baby shoe that holds so many memories and
that never looked so stately on a child's stubby, unsteady foot.
</P>
<P>
   And what now of what is left in the garden? Will life be worth
living for a trunk without wings? If it does live (and Japanese
maples, as delicate as they appear, are some of the toughest little
trees I've ever grown), what form will it take?
</P>
<P>
   I want it to grow up, of course. And I want it to weep, to swoop
and dip.
</P>
<P>
   That'd take some time, I know. Still, each day, I look closely
for growth, for little branches that might do what the big branches
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not impatient, mind you. We two have a history. Fifteen
years I've raised this tree, lived with this tree. If she hasn't
given up on me, I won't give up on her. We can stay together, be
the way we were _ when I loved the way she spread her wings.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   (at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
