<HEADER>
A1896 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-03 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART WORLD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Circus Parade Hid Another
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When conservators at the Phillips Collection in
Washington began cleaning and restoring Gifford Beal's ``Parade of
Elephants,'' they made an astonishing discovery: beneath the 1924
painting was another canvas on the same stretcher, where it had
been hidden for 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Steele, the Phillips' chief conservator, and Gillian
Cook, an intern in the conservation department, had begun work on
``Parade of Elephants'' to prepare for ``Renoir to Rothko: The Eye
of Duncan Phillips,'' an exhibition that opens at the Phillips on
Sept. 25 and explores the collection of the museum's founder.
</P>
<P>
   It was when the conservators unframed ``Parade of Elephants''
and began studying it with a microscope and ultraviolet light that
they discovered two canvases, each with its own set of tacks. The
painting underneath, signed by the artist and dated 1918, depicts a
woman and her two children in front of a house looking down a steep
hillside toward a parade of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's director, curators and conservators have developed
theories about why the painting was covered up in the first place.
``It's fair to speculate that Beal had more canvases than
stretchers,'' said Jay Gates, director of the Phillips. Gates
suggested that Beal simply borrowed the stretcher for a newer work
and then forgot that a painting was underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you keep a painting covered up for 75 years, only six
years after it was painted, it's in pristine condition,'' Gates
added. ``All the colors are still vivid.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliza Rathbone, the chief curator, has given the new painting a
title: ``On the Hudson at Newburgh,'' where the Beal family owned a
home and where the artist frequently painted during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson River Valley landscape adds a new dimension to the
Beal holdings at the Phillips. Many of the works show scenes of the
circus, the theater or men at work. But the subject of this
painting represents Beal's earlier themes.
</P>
<P>
   While conservators working on Old Master paintings have
discovered concealed paintings beneath a canvas, finding a hidden
painting of an American artist is particularly unusual. Also
unusual is that the artist has a special relationship to the
Phillips. Beal was the uncle of Marjorie Phillips, the wife of
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   The two paintings are on view in the newly renovated
second-floor gallery, through Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Lichtenstein Collection
</P>
<P>
   When Roy Lichtenstein died two years ago, he left one painting
each to the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, the Museum of Modern Art
and the National Gallery of Art in Washington _ works he knew they
wanted. But that still left his estate with a substantial
collection of his drawings, prints, sculptures and paintings, which
the artist had kept for his own study.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, many of these works will become part of the Roy
Lichtenstein Foundation, a nonprofit institution established in
accordance with the artist's wishes. Its president is Dorothy
Lichtenstein, the artist's widow, and its director is Jack Cowart,
who is leaving his post as deputy director and chief curator at the
Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's offices will be in the artist's Greenwich
Village studio. ``We want to be a facilitator for anyone who is
studying Roy's work,'' Cowart said. ``This would mean building a
database of his work and being able to authenticate
Lichtensteins.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation hopes to initiate and direct the publication of a
series of catalogs raisonnes, establish and maintain a library and
archive of the artist's work, and lend works for exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't like the Warhol Foundation, who went into
grant-giving mode relatively quickly,'' Cowart said. ``We are not
intending to be a large grant giver.'' Nor did Cowart say there
will be a reason to put a bulk of Lichtenstein's works on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Art in Summer Whites
</P>
<P>
   She's using only men and yes, they will have their clothes on.
That is what will distinguish Vanessa Beecroft's new performance
piece from her previous, more risque work.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at 4:30 p.m., when the 30-year-old Italian artist
stages ``Vanessa Beecroft U.S. Navy,'' at the Museum of
Contemporary Art in San Diego, 25 Navy Seals wearing their summer
whites will stand in ceremonial formation in the museum's Farris
Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   The Seals, a special operations unit of the Navy with a base in
San Diego, conduct a variety of high-risk missions. Their role at
the museum, however, will be a lot tamer than their everyday work.
They are being presented as a portrait of the U.S. Navy's core
values _ honor, courage and commitment _ as well as of their sense
of mission and team spirit: they will stand in a formation that
will create a white square inside a museum gallery that is itself a
white square. The piece is supposed to represent military rules and
esthetics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a large Navy base here, but the military is a
constituency that museums have ignored, which is why I like the
idea of engaging them in a positive way,'' Hugh Davies, director of
the museum, said. ``It certainly is an unlikely alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Move to Sotheby's
</P>
<P>
   Laura Paulson, who for 10 years worked in the contemporary art
department at Christie's and more recently was part of Christie's
20th-century art department, resigned from the auction house this
week to become head of Sotheby's department of contemporary art in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura was my biggest competition,'' said Tobias Meyer, head of
Sotheby's contemporary art department worldwide. Ms. Paulson said
she welcomed the opportunity to head a department and added that
the large space Sotheby's plans to devote to contemporary art after
its York Avenue headquarters is renovated was another incentive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
