<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIMBO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     06-03 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIMBO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAMAGED, AND STRANDED, ON AN ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant in ``Notting Hill'' may be the
year's most adorable screen couple. But in evoking a burgeoning,
thorny grown-up relationship laden with heavy baggage, Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio and David Strathairn run rings around them
in John Sayles' powerful, boldly discursive film ``Limbo.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing Donna De Angelo, a well-traveled folk-rock performer
eking out a living as a lounge singer in Juneau, Alaska, Ms.
Mastrantonio digs into the sharpest crags of the role: a talented
second-tier performer who grits her teeth while counting her losses
but refuses to quit a troubadour life that still provides moments
of artistic transcendence.
</P>
<P>
   The wised-up veteran of a fading musical culture, Donna has
enough perspective to be able to joke that despite her miserable
track record with men, she was never foolish enough to get involved
with a drummer. She may be damaged, but she is not broken down, at
least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Donna's heaviest item of baggage is her resentful, frizzy-haired
teen-age daughter Noelle (Vanessa Martinez) from a former marriage,
who trails around after her. Noelle, who has inherited her mother's
tough facade, is an enormously promising writer who harbors a
bottled-up anger that comes out in impulsive acts of
self-mutilation.
</P>
<P>
   The film's early scenes find Donna abandoning her latest
disaster of a boyfriend and his band and hitching up with Joe
Gastineau (Strathairn), a lean, weatherbeaten former fisherman and
jack-of-all-trades. Strathairn's blend of intense, guarded
intelligence and compressed machismo are ideal for the role of a
veteran outdoorsman haunted by his responsibility for two drownings
in a freak sailing accident 25 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   If this oddly structured film feels like two short stories stuck
together, there is enough solid glue joining them that they
resonate off one another deeply.
</P>
<P>
   The first story is a satirically edged portrait of contemporary
Alaska in the throes of what might called development hell, which
has begun to threaten the livelihood of the region's old guard
residents. The second is a spare, gripping survivalist drama that
demystifies any dreamy notions we might have of living an Outward
Bound-type experience in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   The movie opens at a fund-raising event that introduces the
major characters as they mingle with beady-eyed developers spouting
grandiose plans to transform America's largest state into a
wilderness theme park.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Disney-worthy illusions, we hear about islands
stripped of timber except for a fringe of trees maintained to keep
up an appearance of virgin forest for passing tourist boats. At the
same time we watch the closing of a fish- processing plant and hear
ominous accounts of the area's diminishing fish stock.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes of tourists herded around by guides reeling off
mechanical spiels about the rugged old days offer a depressing
preview of what's to come: a kind of virtual Alaskan frontier
experience with minimal physical risk and discomfort to boatloads
of affluent retired people.
</P>
<P>
   Joe's description of the freedom and exhilaration he has
experienced living close to the bone as a fisherman, and Donna's
talk about the joy of ``hooking into'' the essence of a song on a
good night, establish them as kindred spirits: brave, hard-bitten
romantics who are getting on in years but who remain unwilling to
settle for a more comfortable but ``inauthentic'' life.
</P>
<P>
   But how authentic do they, or any of us really want life to be?
That's the big question that ``Limbo'' explores in its second half
when it finds Donna, Joe and Noelle suddenly stranded on a deserted
island without provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how they came to this fix is a not altogether
believable tale of corrupt high adventure, drug dealing and murder
involving Joe's half-brother Bobby (Casey Siemaszko).
</P>
<P>
   Shivering in their wet clothes and fearful of being shot to
death, the castaways are faced with meeting their most basic needs:
food, water, shelter and warmth. And the movie does a fine job of
capturing their initial shock and desperation and their coming to
terms with the prospect that they may never be rescued. (It also
doesn't have the wilderness cliche scene of a menacing bear.)
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they set up house in a rickety abandoned cabin that
was once inhabited by a fox farmer and his family. Here, Noelle
discovers the abandoned diary of a girl about her age who
accompanied her parents to the island. Noelle's nightly readings
describe a pioneer idyll that quickly deteriorates into a hell of
boredom, drudgery, failure and a despair verging on madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo,'' like all of Sayles' films, is unabashedly schematic,
and its screenplay veers back and forth between moments that feel
wonderfully spontaneous and awkwardly expository.
</P>
<P>
   Once the main characters are castaways, the movie develops in a
strand of mystical fatalism (in the diary and Noelle's relationship
to it) that cuts glaringly against the naturalism. It's a risky,
literary choice that some will find irritating.
</P>
<P>
   But if the film's bones are too prominent and its abrupt ending
highly problematic, the questions it raises and its characters'
humanity make `Limbo'' a compelling experience. A stately Bruce
Springsteen song, ``Lift Me Up,'' that rises over the final credits
ends the movie on a note of tragic supplication. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Limbo'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It has sexual situations. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIMBO
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and edited by John Sayles; director of
photography, Haskell Wexler; music by Mason Daring; production
designer, Gemma Jackson; produced by Maggie Renzi; released by
Screen Gems. Running time: 126 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio (Donna De Angelo), David
Strathairn (Joe Gastineau), Vanessa Martinez (Noelle De Angelo),
Kris Kristofferson (Smilin' Jack), Casey Siemaszko (Bobby
Gastineau), Kathryn Grody (Frankie), Rita Taggart (Lou), Leo
Burmester (Harmon King) and Michael Laskin (Albright).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
