<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1901 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS06-COX     06-03 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What became of Einstein's brain, other `Life Stories'
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, June 6.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Booknotes: Life Stories. By Brian Lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Times Books. $27.50. 471 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, nobody could say for sure where the brain was. This
most remarkable of brains, one that changed the world and changed
our understanding of the world, one that had to be wired
differently _ somebody borrows it and the damned thing gets lost.
</P>
<P>
   It was just what Albert Einstein was afraid would happen.
</P>
<P>
   When Denis Brian, one of Einstein's biographers, learned of this
macabre story, he set about writing a chapter entirely on the
brain. Three years ago, he was telling the story to C-SPAN's Brian
Lamb on ``Booknotes'' because it had come to him as ``such shocking
news.'' The great physicist had told family and friends he wanted
no memorials after he died, and he especially wanted no part of him
to remain. He wanted to be cremated, brain and all.
</P>
<P>
   But the dead are at a disadvantage, and no one knew it better
than the man doing the autopsy. Overcome with curiosity, the
pathologist evidently persuaded Einstein's son to leave this one
organ with him for research. Sons betray fathers in unaccountable
ways, and the only condition Hans Albert Einstein set was that
there be no publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Word was out, of course, almost immediately. In The New York
Times. Einstein's brain, available for dissection. But more of this
later.
</P>
<P>
   Questions no one else would ask
</P>
<P>
   Brian's anecdote is one of many in ``Booknotes: Life Stories,''
excerpts from 77 interviews Lamb has conducted with authors over
the show's 10-year history. It's a sequel, of sorts, to the
well-received ``Booknotes: America's Finest Authors on Reading,
Writing and the Power of Ideas,'' published in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Among loyal viewers, the TV show's format has become an
essential part of the experience. For an hour on Sunday evening,
Lamb (who will sign copies of the new book at 7:30 p.m. Wednesday
at Borders Books &AMP; Music on Peachtree Road) sits across a plain
coffee table from his guest, asking questions no one else would
ask. If sometimes they are questions you wouldn't think needed
asking, Lamb can laugh at himself. ``Admittedly,'' he writes, ``my
question, `Who was Abraham Lincoln?' did elicit raised eyebrows
from a Lincoln historian.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's by asking such questions that Lamb gets authors to tell
stories a viewer wouldn't expect to hear. One of the most unlikely
was told by Ron Chernow, who wrote a biography of a man _ John D.
Rockefeller _ in whom he hadn't the slightest interest: ``I told my
editor at Random House, Ann Godoff, that I thought Rocke-
</P>
<P>
   feller was the worst subject imaginable _ that he just seemed to
me cold, wooden, mechanical, ruthless, a man without any interior
life that I could see.''
</P>
<P>
   But he took the old tycoon on, and what he found was the person
William James had called ``the most strongly bad, and strongly
good, human being he had ever met.'' And one of the strangest. ``He
became something of a New Age health fanatic,'' Chernow told Lamb.
``He had all sorts of theories (about) how he could prolong his
life. This was the bane of his luncheon companions, but he used to
chew food 10 times before swallowing. Guests who observed him
closely said that even when he had liquid in his mouth he would
swirl it 10 times before swallowing.''
</P>
<P>
   A smorgasbord of characters
</P>
<P>
   As the above might suggest, the charm of Lamb's book is what it
reveals about the oddity of human character. But there is something
odd about the book, too. It is organized by centuries, with birth
dates determining whether a subject is pigeonholed in the 1700s,
the 1800s or the 1900s. You're not surprised to find George
Washington in the 1700s, Lincoln in the 1800s or Bill Clinton _ no
comparisons implied here _ in the 1900s. But lives often straddle
two centuries, and we associate a name by something more
significant than date of birth. Thus, Franklin D. Roosevelt, the
president whose term spanned the Great Depression and most of World
War II, and Harry Truman, the president who made the decision to
drop the atomic bomb, seem misplaced in the company of Ralph Waldo
Emerson and Thomas Edison.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a quibble. The more important feature of
``Booknotes: Life Stories'' is its smorgasbord appeal. You can pick
a subject at random, read half a dozen or so pages and come away
with a sense of who that person was, whatever his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two of these subjects happen to be American presidents, a
reflection of C-SPAN's focus and, as Lamb writes, ``our belief that
the lives of the 41 men who have held this office mirror the
broader landscape of American history and values.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. And yet it is the wholly unexpected story that is
always arresting. I said I'd tell you what happened to Einstein's
brain. It sat in a jar in the pathologist's basement and got left
behind when he and his wife divorced. The wife got tired of seeing
it around, and said, ``I wish they'd get this damn thing out of
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-four years after Einstein's death, it's been sliced up
like sushi. A Japanese scientist has some of it, a doctor in
Philadelphia other parts. For a man of 76, it was in excellent
condition, but otherwise just a brain. Clues to genius have yet to
turn up.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1730EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
