<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRISH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-03 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHO'S IRISH': FREE AND CONFUSED BY INFINITE POSSIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gish Jen's characters, Chinese immigrants and their
American-born children, find themselves commuting between two
cultures, between familial expectations and their own yearnings for
self-definition, between remembered traditions and shiny, new
dreams. As perennial outsiders, they are acutely aware of the
strange, sometimes baffling workings of the world around them and
the odd, unforeseen ways in which race and prejudice and family
history can complicate their sense of who they are.
</P>
<P>
   Like her characters, Ms. Jen _ who grew up in Scarsdale, N.Y.,
the daughter of immigrant parents _ has a keen eye for the
incongruities of contemporary life, and in this beautifully
articulated new collection of stories, she gives us a gently
satiric look at the American Dream and its fallout on those who
pursue it. She captures the absurdities and self-indulgences of a
country where adjectives like creative are attached to everything
from guitar playing to the selection of clothes, but she also
captures the wonderful sense of freedom it can confer on
individuals who are new to its shores.
</P>
<P>
   In two novels, ``Typical American'' (1991) and ``Mona in the
Promised Land'' (1996), Ms. Jen chronicled the lives of two
generations of a Chinese-American family: Ralph and Helen Chang,
who move to the States and achieve the good life in the suburbs by
opening a pancake house, and their daughters, Mona and Callie, who
struggle to map out independent lives of their own.
</P>
<P>
   In this collection of stories, she gives us some further takes
on the immigrant experience. Two of the stories, ``The Water Faucet
Vision'' and ``In the American Society,'' appear to be studies for
those earlier novels and stand somewhat shakily on their own; the
remaining tales introduce us to new characters who prove to be as
appealing and as ambivalently Americanized as the Changs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these people seem to be tottering on the edge of that
very American phenomenon, the identity crisis. As newcomers to
America, they take this country's promise of infinite possibility
seriously, a prospect that brings both liberating freedom and
dizzying dislocation. Members of the second generation in
particular find themselves pulled between the urge to fit in _ what
one character calls the ``fear of the weird'' _ and the suspicion
that their parents' pursuit of bourgeois respectability is somehow
empty.
</P>
<P>
   Addie, who is expecting a baby, has abandoned her quest to
``achieve immortality as a sculptress,'' having given up art to try
hospice work and garden design (``Just Wait''). Art Woo, who works
in a dying sector of the computer business, finds himself reviewing
the collapse of his marriage and dreaming of a new start on the
West Coast (``Birthmates''). And Duncan Hsu, who has dropped out of
military school, law school and computer programming school, moves
to China, where he finds himself hailed as a ``foreign expert'' in
``Duncan in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, like so many of Ms. Jen's characters, has had to contend
with the pressure of parental expectations: his mother calls every
day ``lest he imagine he had become the sort of son about whom she
could boast.'' She is always comparing him with his successful
brother Arnie, who runs a lucrative import-export business, while
Duncan worries that he has become ``a free man who believed nothing
in particular, who did nothing in particular,'' a ``free man who
had not even embraced his freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Pammie, the heroine of ``House, House, Home,'' the longest and
most ambitious story in the volume, has grown up as the dutiful
fifth daughter of struggling immigrants, and she has had to learn
from her American husband, Sven, that life can be fun, or ``at
least that there was no point in not having fun. That as often as
not, one's actions had no consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a shock to discover for Pammie,'' Ms. Jen writes.
``She had grown up considering the optimum use of every dollar and
every hour. Every action brightened or dimmed the great drive-in
screen of the future.'' While Pammie conscientiously remembers the
birthdays of all her relatives and carefully plans what to get
them, Sven, her former art history professor, chides her for
spending her life ``trying to remember and please.'' She will never
be a successful artist, he asserts: ``There is no such thing as a
nice artist. And there is no one nicer than the daughter of an
immigrant.''
</P>
<P>
   As their marriage unravels, it becomes clear that race and the
sense of otherness that often accompanies race have heightened
tensions between them. When Pammie's relatives question him as a
representative member of that American genus, the white college
professor (``Do art professors eat lunch? Do art professors eat
breakfast?''), he objects that he is ``not a specimen.'' And when
Sven takes up the study of Chinese art and begins encouraging
Pammie to wear Chinese dresses, she wonders, as a friend later puts
it, whether this was proof that ``Sven had seen her as other, as
not-self, as object to his subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the stories _ most notably ``Chin,'' a
simplistic study in prejudice _ are weaker than others, they all
evince Ms. Jen's wonderful ear for the idiosyncrasies of American
speech (and Chinese-American pidgin) and her ability to portray her
characters' lives with both bemusement and genuine affection. She
limns the inner lives of her heroes and heroines with authority and
aplomb while introducing a vivid supporting cast, from a crotchety
Chinese professor who has ``a loop-de-loop manner of talking with
his hands'' to a first-grade girl ``best known for having dressed
up as Madeline four Halloweens in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   She shows with this sparkling volume that she is as at ease with
the short story form as she is with the long-distance form of the
novel.
</P>
<P>
   Publication notes:
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S IRISH
</P>
<P>
   Stories
</P>
<P>
   By Gish Jen
</P>
<P>
   208 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $22.00.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURPRISE-PAINTING-NYT     06-03 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURPRISE-PAINTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAINTING PACKS A MILLION-DOLLAR SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ind., Fla., Mass.)   (bl)  
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts in Houston has paid $1.25 million for a
still life painting that for years covered a hole in the wall in an
Indiana home, its value unknown to the owner and its existence
unknown to art experts.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, ``Magnolias on Gold Velvet Cloth'' by the
19th-century American painter Martin Johnson Heade, was sold by a
man in his 30s who works at a tool-and-die company. He started to
realize the value of the work in January when he played
Masterpiece, a board game about art that includes an image of a
similar Heade.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, he turned to the Internet, found that Kennedy
Galleries in Manhattan handled Heade's work and sent an e-mail
asking if his painting might be by that artist. He then sent
digital images of it to Kennedy, which had the painting
authenticated and made the match with the Houston museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important rediscovery, and the painting is a
magnificent example of Heade's work at its best,'' said Theodore E.
Stebbins Jr., author of the 1975 catalog raisonne of Heade's works.
For the newly updated edition Stebbins, the American paintings
curator at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston, quickly added the
Houston Heade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolias on Gold Velvet Cloth,'' painted around 1890, is the
third important Heade flower painting to turn up in recent years.
Last month at Christie's ``Two Magnolias on Blue Plush'' sold for
$882,500; the seller, a man from Wisconsin, had paid $29 for it at
a rummage sale a decade ago. And in 1996 Christie's sold ``Magnolia
Blossoms on Blue Velvet'' for $937,500; it had been bought along
with a smaller Heade of cherokee roses at an estate sale in Arizona
for $100.
</P>
<P>
   Heade, a meticulous painter born in 1819 in Pennsylvania, is
known for his luminous landscapes and nature works as well as his
floral still lifes, which he painted largely after settling in St.
Augustine, Fla., in 1883. It makes sense that these works are now
being rediscovered, said Paul Provost, the American paintings
expert at Christie's, because many people purchased them while on
vacation in Florida then took them to their homes around the
country. ``They were passed down in the family, whose members
didn't always know what they had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The seller of ``Magnolias on Gold Velvet Cloth,'' who wants to
remain anonymous, bought it along with some furniture years ago for
``next to nothing,'' said Martha J. Fleischman, the president of
Kennedy Galleries. ``He was ignorant of the value, but he loved
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Heade's magnolia still lifes, which capture the blossoms at
close range and in various stages, number fewer than 20 and are
indeed popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are evocative, elegaic paintings, with soft, tender
light, unique in American still-life painting,'' Provost said. The
Boston museum, the National Gallery in Washington and the Art
Institute of Chicago are among the museums that own examples.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sets this apart from his other magnolia paintings,'' Ms.
Fleischman said, ``is that there's a little bit of leaf mold on one
of the leaves, like a beauty mark.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Ms. Fleischman saw ``Magnolias on Gold Velvet Cloth''
coming up on her computer screen, ``I got very excited,'' she said.
``I knew it was real, and I felt it was a museum-quality picture.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the people at the Houston museum, once they learned of
the discovery in March. In her excitement Ms. Fleischman had
confided to a decorative-arts curator there that she ``had made the
find of my life,'' but could not yet disclose what it was. Emily
Ballew Neff, the museum's curator of American art, was soon on the
phone to her, asking to know of the discovery as soon as Ms.
Fleischman could tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called her every week or every other week to let her know
we'd be interested,'' Ms. Neff said. ``The second she told me what
it was, I knew we had to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting was sent to Houston for inspection in late March.
It was, as Ms. Fleischman had already discovered, still in its
original frame and in near-perfect condition, protected from wear
by the original glass. ``I was 99 percent certain that this
painting would never leave Houston,'' Ms. Neff said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter C. Marzio, the museum's director, called an emergency
meeting of its trustees, who approved the purchase in less than an
hour and a half. One trustee, who chose to remain anonymous,
provided most of the cash, and two foundations provided the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Magnolias on Gold Velvet Cloth,'' the museum's first work by
Heade, went on view in Houston on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
