<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1911 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMAGE-THEATER-REVIEW-     06-03 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMAGE-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE IMAGE MAKERS': BLINK OF THE EYE, TREMOR OF THE SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The audience, for the moment, is the mirror for the
exasperatingly pretty young woman who is standing in the center of
the stage. She gazes into the darkness where we sit, rearranging
her waist-length hair with fascinated preoccupation, intensely
focused, it would seem, on the vision of her own face and body. She
is a study in rapturous self-communion that somehow goes way beyond
vanity.
</P>
<P>
   For there is wondering detachment in that gaze, a sense that
what she is looking at is not just herself but herself as seen by
others. She speaks with quiet, blissful gravity of the idea of
being a disembodied image, and for that one uncanny instant those
of us watching this actress portraying an actress seem to share
exactly her vision; her eyes are ours. As conjured by the stunning
young Swedish theater star Elin Klinga, it's a giddy, slightly
discomforting feeling, both abstract and alarmingly intimate.
</P>
<P>
   You have probably experienced this sensation before if you are
familiar with the films of Ingmar Bergman, who throughout his
half-century as a director has consistently and unnervingly found
the spirit in the flesh of his actors, the metaphysical in the
physical.
</P>
<P>
   The great joy in watching the Royal Dramatic Theater of Sweden's
production of ``The Image Makers,'' a play by Per Olov Enquist that
can be seen at the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Majestic Theater
only through Sunday, is in observing how Bergman translates that
same sensibility through deceptively simple-looking stagecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Enquist's endlessly reflective drama, a tale of artists both
literary and cinematic in the early days of silent pictures, is by
no means on a level with Bergman's screenplays for films like
``Persona'' and ``Cries and Whispers.'' Though it considers such
quintessentially Bergmanesque themes as the relations between
autobiography and art, between guilt and redemption, ``The Image
Makers'' works overtime in explaining itself, in tying up its
conundrums into neat packages of metaphors and psychological
answers to the mysteries of artistic creation. Suffice it to say
that how oysters make pearls figures prominently in the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But any play directed by 80-year-old Bergman is not be missed.
This one may not summon the illuminating shadows of his ``Long
Day's Journey Into Night'' or ``Madame de Sade,'' but it is filled
with precisely rendered gestures that have an awakening physical
immediacy, the surprise of a sudden slap on the face. Indeed,
non-Swedish speakers may find themselves wanting to discard their
headsets, through which simultaneous translation is provided, and
simply luxuriate in the body language of the work's four actors.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to understand why Bergman would have been drawn to
``The Image Makers,'' a dramatic rumination on a real-life
encounter between Swedish novelist Selma Lagerlof and filmmaker
Victor Sjostrom. Sjostrom was a mentor of the young Bergman and
appeared as an actor, to heartbreaking effect, in Bergman's 1957
masterpiece, ``Wild Strawberries.'' What's more, ``The Image
Makers'' is centered on Sjostrom's film ``The Phantom Carriage,''
which was adapted from a novel by Lagerlof and, in its depiction of
death as an animate and industrious presence, anticipated Bergman's
own ``Seventh Seal.''
</P>
<P>
   Enquist has written that ``The Image Makers'' is an
extrapolation on what is historically known about the meeting of
Lagerlof and Sjostrom in 1920, when the director visited the
novelist to read aloud to her the script he had made from her
novel. There was a long silence when Sjostrom finished reading,
after which Lagerlof asked her visitor if he wanted a drink;
nothing more. ``The Image Makers,'' as Enquist writes in his
preface to the work, is his speculative answer to a question he
posed to himself about that enigmatic silence: ``What did it
contain?''
</P>
<P>
   Silence, of course, as Bergman himself has made piercingly clear
throughout his work, can sound depths that words cannot. And while
Enquist presents a coherent and consistent argument, notable for
its tautly woven patterns of symbols, his play is often exceedingly
talky and didactic, with no ambiguity left unverbalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Image Makers,'' which resets the meeting between two
ostensibly different artistic minds in Sjostrom's film lab in
Stockholm, painstakingly identifies the roots of creative
inspiration. It does so in ways that start to smack of latter-day
group encounter sessions in which one person keeps hammering away
at another with merciless questions, stripping away illusions that
conceal a hard, quantifiable kernel of truth.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that this question-and-answer process is
largely carried out by two astonishingly vivid performers, Anita
Bjork as Lagerlof and Ms. Klinga as Tora Teje, the brash, brilliant
actress with whom Sjostrom (portrayed with self-effacing restraint
by Lennart Hjulstrom) is having an affair. The play's quartet is
completed by Julius Jaenzon, Sjostrom's cinematographer, who, as
embodied by Carl-Magnus Dellow, is crippled by clownish lust for
the tantalizing Tora.
</P>
<P>
   It is Tora, not Sjostrom, who is the real catalyst in the play,
the product of a poor, unhappy family and scant education who feels
like an outsider and who wants, more than anything, to be let in on
the secrets of how art is made. But as is so often the case in the
world of Bergman, it is the men who are the real outsiders here, as
the women merge into a fierce, ambivalent complicity in which each
discovers herself in the other.
</P>
<P>
   As written, Tora is an irritating part, that of the harsh,
volatile truth seeker who speaks what no one else dares. Ms.
Klinga, however, wears both her beauty and her character's
self-dramatizing temperament with a touchingly defensive flair. She
has the long-limbed, graceful awkwardness of a newborn colt, and
this Tora can't help being elegant even at her most defiantly
vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bjork's Selma is Tora's physical opposite, gravity cast in
granite. Yet from the moment she makes her entrance, as if a
battleship sailing majestically into a harbor, you know that this
woman's poise is the hard-won product of a relentless will. As Tora
chips away at the woman's stoniness, needling and supplicating, Ms.
Bjork relents by beautifully calibrated degrees. Her facial
expressions appear fractional, yet they are so articulate you often
have the feeling you are watching her face in close-up.
</P>
<P>
   The resonant physicality of these two women winds up eclipsing
everything else in the production. That includes Goran Wassberg's
simple, eminently functional set, Mago's handsome period costumes
and even the projected clips from Sjostrom's dark fantasia of a
film (which is being shown in its entirety as part of a related
film festival at the Academy). These cinematic images have a grimly
ethereal quality that you can't quite connect, except in bald
thematic terms, to the very solid living figures on the stage.
</P>
<P>
   But, oh, what Bergman and his actresses can do with the solid
human form. Watch for the scene in which Ms. Bjork, in a shocking
contradiction of her posture through the rest of the evening, falls
fluidly to the floor; it's a strangely quiet moment, but it
registers like a fist in the stomach. And there is the absolutely
delectable vision of what Ms. Klinga cunningly achieves with her
bare feet when Tora takes off her shoes in the second act. Under
Bergman's direction, even toes can speak louder than words.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE IMAGE MAKERS'
</P>
<P>
   By Per Olov Enquist; directed by Ingmar Bergman; sets by Goran
Wassberg; costumes by Mago; wigs and masks by Leif Qvistrom;
lighting by Pierre Leveau; producer, Sofi Lerstrom. The Royal
Dramatic Theater of Sweden, Ingrid Dahlberg, artistic and managing
director. Presented by the Brooklyn Academy of Music, Bruce C.
Ratner, chairman of the board; Harvey Lichtenstein, president and
executive producer. At the Majestic Theater, 651 Fulton St., Fort
Greene, Brooklyn.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Anita Bjork (Selma Lagerlof), Elin Klinga (Tora Teje),
Lennart Hjulstrom (Viktor Sjostrom) and Carl-Magnus Dellow (Julius
Jaenzon).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
