<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-COSTS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A LIGHTNING STRIKE, A $3.6 MILLION FOREST FIRE GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Colo., Okl., Fla., Ga.)  
(dw) 
 By KAREN VOYLES The Gainesville Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLUSTEE, Fla. _ The Friendly Fire near the Florida-Georgia
border could be renamed Expensive or Expansive. It has already cost
the federal government an estimated $3.6 million to fight, and by
Thursday flames had consumed 64,000 acres of wilderness and
swampland.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the money not spent on helicopters and water-dropping
air tankers will make its way to small-town shops, motels and
restaurants. But ultimately, the fire may cost the area economy,
one business leader said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was named for the hunting camp in the Osceola National
Forest near where a lightning strike sparked it two weeks ago.
Within days, the fire had spread to the Okefenokee National
Wildlife Refuge in southern Georgia and onto private timber lands
on both side of the state line.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no serious injuries and no homes were threatened
by the blaze. Officials credit a quick decision by local U.S.
Division of Forestry workers who saw how fast the fire was
spreading and called for help.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 firefighters, 12 helicopters, three air tankers,
70 fire engines and 70 bulldozers are assigned to the area and paid
for by the federal government. Firefighting efforts continued in
shifts around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our estimated costs for this fire are $3,611,736, and about
half of that is for the aerial equipment,'' said Steve Parsons, a
forest service employee from western Virginia who is serving as
operations spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government also is paying dozens of on-call,
temporary firefighters from around the country who are willing to
take assignments anywhere in the nation on almost no notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also give the firefighters a per diem of $6 for breakfast,
$16 for dinner and we pay their hotel rooms,'' said James Meredith,
a forest service employee from Mississippi now serving as finance
chief for the Friendly Fire. Firefighters carry lunches provided
for them to their work sites at the beginning of their shifts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to handling meal money, motel bills and payroll
paperwork, Meredith has been struggling with concerns such as
finding places for firefighters to rent the more than 100
four-wheel-drive trucks and sport-utility vehicles they needed as
soon as they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   His staff is also dealing with purchasing problems, like where
to buy bottled water by the pallet and how to get huge quantities
of fuel for helicopters to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons said his agency tries to buy locally to avoid shipping
costs. That could be a boon to places like Lake City, which is near
the Osceola National Forest, but Jim Poole, executive director of
the Lake City-Columbia County Chamber of Commerce, said expansive
fires last year caused the area to lose money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long range, the losses to timber sales were more than
the gains made during the fire,'' Poole said.
</P>
<P>
   Poole said fires in north Florida last year resulted in a glut
of fire-damaged timber being rushed to sawmills. The glut pushed
timber prices down from $1,500 and $2,000 an acre to $500 an acre,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Timber producers were also hurt because they were selling wood
from trees that they had intended to market a year or more later.
</P>
<P>
   Among those assigned to the Friendly Fire was Maria Hennessey of
the Pike Inter-Agency Hotshot Crew. She was flown to Florida from
Monument, Colo., to work on her first assignment with the 20-member
crew. She said little of what she was taught about firefighting in
the mountains applies to this fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tactics are really different here because out West we work
more on establishing a fire line and here those are already in
place,'' Hennessey said. ``Here, we are doing other things, like
looking for those hotspots, instead of working with the hand tools
and creating those firebreaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Another crew member, Erin Johnson, is in her fifth year as a
hotshot firefighter. But she saw something she would never run into
out West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my first alligator from about 5 feet away _ he was
probably 3 or 4 feet long. It wasn't really frightening, just
surprising,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   John Youngbull flew in from El Reno, Okla., to fight a Florida
wildfire for the second time in two years. He saw something he sees
regularly back home _ his brother, Randy. The Youngbulls work for
the U.S. Division of Forestry in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   While John Youngbull fights blazes from a fire engine, Randy
Youngbull is a part of a 20-member crew working on the ground with
hand tools. This is the first time they've worked together so far
from home. And they agree on two things _ the need for water and
the attitude of local residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell my crew that it is really hard to adjust to the
humidity here, so drink a lot of water or someone will stick a
needle in your arm and pump fluids into you,'' said Randy
Youngbull. He said he learned that lesson a year ago while fighting
the fires in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't say enough about how nice everyone, all these
local residents, have been,'' said John Youngbull. ``We go places
out West, like in Idaho, and you get a fire right up to a fence
line, and there are big signs saying `no trespassing' and `no
federal employees allowed to cross the fence.' Here, people are
happy to see you and really want you to feel welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun, in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
