<HEADER>
A1919 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-03 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `ANALYZE THIS,' starring Robert De Niro and Billy Crystal.
Directed by Harold Ramis (R, 110 minutes). The title, concept and
teaming of these co-stars are all funny before the lights go down,
so think of this comedy as an offer you can't refuse. Cast as a
mobster whose confidence is shaken, De Niro is hilarious simply by
playing his role halfway straight, in classic goodfella style. His
mobster finds just the right comic foil in Crystal as the
psychiatrist who utters the immortal, ``When I got into family
therapy, this wasn't the family I had in mind.'' There's a lot more
where that came from in this breezy comedic treat (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `BESIEGED,' starring Thandie Newton and David Thewlis. Directed
by Bernardo Bertolucci (R, 92 minutes). Like all Bertolucci films,
the love story of an expatriate African woman (Ms. Newton) fleeing
an oppressive military regime and the reclusive British pianist
(Thewlis) for whom she works as a housekeeper in Rome is a visual
jewel. Based on a short story by James Lasdun, ``Besieged'' is a
film of few words and powerful images. (Especially of a military
coup in a poor African country.) The love is sealed through an
extraordinary act of self-sacrifice and a deepening appreciation of
each other's tastes in music. If this elliptical movie leaves too
much unsaid, it has strong understated performances by its two
stars (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `ELECTION,' starring Matthew Broderick and Reese Witherspoon.
Directed by Alexander Payne (R, 105 minutes). From the acerbically
funny director of ``Citizen Ruth'' comes this caustic satire of the
American electoral process in a high school setting. Its leading
candidate, Tracy Flick, played tartly by Ms. Witherspoon, has a
mother who sought tactical advice for Tracy from Connie Chung and
Elizabeth Dole. Broderick plays the hapless good-guy teacher who
thinks this wicked little front-runner needs to be stopped. And the
hunky newcomer Chris Klein plays Tracy's reluctant opponent in a
style best described as early Keanu. With a lovely ear for
hypocritical conversation, the screenplay specializes in keeping
all the characters a few beats off what they actually mean
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ENTRAPMENT,' starring Sean Connery and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
Directed by Jon Amiel (PG-13, 105 minutes). This glossy caper
summons the days when being a thief was the profession of choice
among debonair movie heroes. And heroines: as the great-looking
insurance investigator who is supposedly investigating Connery's
glamorous super-burglar, Ms. Zeta-Jones makes a smashing gymnast
and heist expert in her own right. No need to believe the
outlandish details of the story; there's enough verve and charisma
to the stars to make the escapade easy on the eyes. The action
sequence, in which the stars hang off the side of the world's
largest skyscraper, is a vertiginous show stopper. And here's a
nice bonus: nobody gets killed (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ETERNITY AND A DAY,' starring Bruno Ganz. Directed by Theo
Angelopoulos (not rated, 132 minutes). Winner of the Palme d'Or at
last year's Cannes International Film Festival, this dreamy,
lulling film is the haunting poetic valedictory of a man spending
his last day on earth. As his memory leads him across the landscape
of his life, Ganz's soulful Greek writer (in a role originally
meant for Marcello Mastroianni) drifts through his past as he seeks
his life's meaning. The film's visual style is less magnificently
grandiose than the director's ``Ulysses' Gaze,'' but it roams from
mood to mood with a fluid, liberating assurance. It's a style
that's both trance-inducing and filled with unutterable emotion
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE LOSS OF SEXUAL INNOCENCE,' starring Julian Sands, Femi
Ogunbanjo and Hanne Klintoe. Written and directed by Mike Figgis,
(R, 101 minutes). Figgis' visually ravishing cinematic tone poem
retells the Adam and Eve story (Adam is black and Eve is white),
interspersing it with semiautobiographical reveries of the
director's early childhood in Kenya and his teen and adult years in
northern England. The strands are drawn together in a final scene
of violence and betrayal set at a film shoot in Tunisia and
reminiscent of Antonioni's film ``The Passenger.'' The film is
moody verging on melancholy, the storytelling elliptical, its view
of eroticism menacing rather than joyful. Though marred by
pretentious symbolism and an overall vagueness, this film has many
spellbinding moments (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE LOVE LETTER,' starring Kate Capshaw, Blythe Danner, Ellen
DeGeneres, Tom Everett Scott and Tom Selleck. Directed by Peter
No-sun Chan (R, 88 minutes). Cathleen Schine's whimsical romantic
novel about a summer affair between a divorced bookstore owner (Ms.
Capshaw) and a college student half her age (Scott) bleaches out
pungent ruminations on May-September love in favor of a bland
cuteness. The teeny-weeny story revolves around an unaddressed,
unsigned love letter that floats into people's lives and recharges
their romantic fantasies. The dialogue is flat, the level of the
acting grade-B sitcom (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE MATRIX,' starring Keanu Reeves, Laurence Fishburne and
Carrie-Anne Moss. Directed by Andy and Larry Wachowski (R, 120
minutes). The time-traveling story steeped in virtual reality will
be all but incomprehensible to anyone but techno freaks. And the
film borrows unapologetically from other sci-fi extravaganzas, with
a big debt to ``The X-Files'' in the paranoia department. But the
storytelling is intricately bizarre and the special effects are
indeed special, notably when it comes to midair martial arts with a
gravity-defying gusto. And Reeves shows that you can look like a
Prada model while behaving like an action hero. One of the main
stars here is Bill Pope, an inventive cinematographer. He and the
Wachowskis provide a couch-potato epiphany: while the characters
seem to be performing marvelous feats, they're often lying
stock-still in the grip of virtual reality (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1920 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-03 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: virtual reality (Maslin). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM,' starring Rupert Everett, Calista
Flockhart, Kevin Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer, Stanley Tucci and David
Strathairn. Directed by Michael Hoffman (PG-13, 115 minutes). This
is potluck Shakespeare, with a wildly uneven range of performances
and no clear style holding them together. Rather than wonder why
the actors are wrestling with bicycles in 19th-century Tuscany (a
setting used much less enchantingly than it might have been), it's
best to focus on the most comfortably Shakespearean performances
and not wonder what Ms. Flockhart is doing here. Kline makes a
perfect Bottom, Everett slinks seductively through Oberon's role
and Ms. Pfeiffer makes an appropriately gorgeous fairy queen. The
younger cast members are largely used as window dressing for the
Leo-Does-Romeo set (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE MUMMY,' starring Brendan Fraser, Rachel Weisz, Arnold
Vosloo and John Hannah. Directed by Stephen Sommers (PG-13, 134
minutes). More like a video game than a movie, this incoherent
spoof (very loosely based on the 1932 Boris Karloff horror
classic), overloaded with cheesy special effects, suggests an
unwieldy hybrid of ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' and ``Abbott and
Costello Meet the Mummy'' via ``Night of the Living Dead.'' The
intrepid adventurers who disturb an ancient Egyptian crypt that
carries a fearful curse are Fraser (playing a swashbuckling
American in the foreign legion), Ms. Weisz (as a plucky, wide-eyed
English librarian) and John Hannah (as her twitty older brother).
It's all played for laughs. The only scary moments involve swarming
scarabs who burrow under the skin and do awful ``Alien''-like
things (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `NOTTING HILL,' starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant. Directed
by Roger Michell (PG-13, 105 minutes). The most romantic notion
here may be that a Hollywood star as famous as Ms. Roberts might be
out, unassisted, browsing for a book. But it's enough to bring her
together with Grant's bashful bookseller and let two
extraordinarily charming actors play out an intelligent flirtation.
As written by Richard Curtis with frequent wit and welcome echoes
of his ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' this is a bright, winsome
romantic comedy that's as teasing as the characters themselves,
inviting the audience to ponder the movie star's burdens of being
world-famous and desperately attractive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE' (the Oscar winner for best film, best
original screenplay, best art direction, best costumes and best
comedy score). Starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth Paltrow (the
best-actress winner), Geoffrey Rush, Ben Affleck and Dame Judi
Dench (best supporting actress). Directed by John Madden (R, 113
minutes). A witty, sexy and merrily literate delight, with an
exhilaratingly clever premise that only gets better as the film
unfolds. The screenplay, originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm
and turned by Tom Stoppard into razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of
his ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine
whatever it likes about the link between Shakespeare's artistic
passions and his mad yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty.
Meanwhile, this tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an
Elizabethan theater fraught with the same backbiting and conniving
we enjoy today and has great fun presenting the creation of ``Romeo
and Juliet,'' glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a
fine, tempestuous duo, and she gives the first great, fully
realized starring performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,' starring Liam
Neeson, Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman and Jake Lloyd. Directed by
George Lucas (PG-13, 132 minutes). Stripped of hype and breathless
expectations, Lucas' first installment offers a happy surprise:
it's up to snuff. It sustains the gee-whiz spirit of the series and
offers a swashbuckling extra-galactic getaway, creating illusions
that are even more plausible than the kitchen-raiding raptors of
``Jurassic Park.'' While the human stars here are indeed reduced to
playing action figures, they are upstaged by amazing backdrops and
hordes of crazily lifelike space beings as the Lewis Carroll in
Lucas is given free rein. The ``Star Wars'' franchise was funnier
and scrappier when it was new. But it simply wasn't capable of this
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TEA WITH MUSSOLINI,' starring Cher, Dame Judi Dench, Joan
Plowright, Dame Maggie Smith and Lily Tomlin. Directed by Franco
Zeffirelli (PG, 117 minutes). The screen divas (especially Dame
Maggie) who give ``Tea With Mussolini'' a patina of class obviously
relish chewing the scenery in this sudsy historical drama (adapted
from a chapter of Zeffirelli's autobiography) about a circle of
English expatriate women living in Florence on the eve of World War
II. Dame Maggie, a quintessential British snob, is the leader of
the pack, nicknamed the Scorpioni, whose comfortable lives are
shattered when the Fascists rise to power and they find themselves
carted off to another city where they are held under house arrest.
Cher is her usual likable self as a free-spending, free-loving
wealthy American heiress and art collector who befriends the group
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WINSLOW BOY,' starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca Pidgeon and
Jeremy Northam. Written and directed by David Mamet (G, 110
minutes). Terence Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's trial
that created a furor in England has been artfully pared down to its
essentials in this stately and deliberate adaptation. Played with
unusually effective restraint by a fine, meticulous cast, it works
as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the family of a
cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the consequences of
that accusation. Benoit Delhomme's cinematography is beautifully
lucid and painterly. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch acting style sets
the film's tone and gives her suffragist character a sharp edge
(Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
