   MASSACHUSETTS-SPRINGFIELD-COPS. A new survey released by the
Justice Department highlight's Springfield, Mass., residents'
happiness with their cities police department. (350 words.) By
Tiffany Lynch
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA-FEDERAL-JUDGES. An Iowa senator could sink Nevada's
chances of receiving two more federal judgeships approved recently
by the Senate in its version of the crime bill. (500 words.) By
Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA-SAFE-NEEDLES. Hoping to reduce the number of accidents
caused by needles and other sharp medical instruments, Sen. Harry
Reid has introduced a legislative package that would beef up safety
measures at health care facilities. (300 words.) By Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-KOSOVO-PASCRELL. As Yugoslav leaders signaled
interest for a Western diplomatic solution in Kosovo, Rep. William
Pascrell, D-Paterson, said the final push for lasting peace should
come with international pressure to remove Serbian leader Slobodan
Milosevic. (400 words.) By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA-BEE. If Justin Balletta had opted for sushi
rather than pizza on Wednesday night, it may have saved him in the
fourth round of the Scripps Howard Spelling Bee on Thursday
morning. The Weddington sixth-grader misspelled ``sashimi,'' a
Japanese fish dish. The story will include information about two
other North Carolina spellers who made it to the final rounds of
the bee. (450 words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-BEE. North Olmsted teen Dan Joslyn couldn't muster the
right spelling of the word ``revictualment'' and was eliminated
from the national spelling bee Thursday. (10-12 inches.) By Sean
Gorman
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-KOSOVO-REACT. An attempt is being made to get reaction
from the Texas delegation to the possible peace in Kosovo. By Robin
Brown
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-BEE. Casper's Thomas Clayton made it to the second half
of the National Spelling Bee, but was eliminated when he misspelled
the word ``fugist.'' (300 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
