<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    Eds: Adds: CONTEMPT-JEWELL; Deletes: BARR-PORK;
 &HT;    UPDATES: KOSOVO-STRIKES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, June 4, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN AIRLINES CRASH
</P>
<P>
   CRASH _ LITTLE ROCK _ The pilot of the American Airlines jet
that crashed was getting a ``play by play'' about the deteriorating
weather in the minutes before the accident, a federal safety
official said today. NTSB investigators hoped to talk to the crew's
first officer, Michael Origel, today to see what he remembers about
the minutes before the crash. They were waiting for a doctor's
authorization. They're also looking at the runway's grooving and
drainage system, both of which could have preventing hydroplaning.
(Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The Serbian parliament on Thursday
voted overwhelmingly to accept a plan to end the conflict over
Kosovo, giving in on all of the conditions demanded by NATO. The
Serbs' capitulation does not mean an immediate end to NATO's
bombing. Under the plan, the attacks would stop only after Serb
troops withdraw from Kosovo. Serb withdrawal may start Sunday. NATO
generals expected to come to Belgrade within days. Bombing expected
to stop then if not earlier. The U.S. State Department said the
deal would require ``verifiable deeds, not seductive words.'' The
deal calls for an armed peacekeeping force with ``essential NATO
participation,'' a condition the Yugoslav government had vowed
never to accept. And it requires that 850,000 ethnic Albanian
refugees be allowed to return to return to their homes. But the
plan also says that Kosovo will remain part of Yugoslavia and that
the United Nations will play a role in enforcing the peace. It was
unclear what the deal would mean for Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, who has been indicted for war crimes and might be
subject to arrest. Opposition parties have begun demanding that he
resign. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in International/Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HOME-SCHOOL _ WASHINGTON _ For the third year in a row, at least
5 percent of the participants in the National Spelling Bee were
home-schooled. Coming on the heels of last week's victory by a home
schooler in the National Geography Bee, the strong performance has
been a boost for the fast-growing movement, whose parents range
from Southern Christians to Western pagans. (Mollison, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   w/SPELLING-BEE _ WASHINGTON _ How Cox-area spellers did on the
second day of the National Spelling Bee. May be led with a national
angle if newsworthy. (Hill, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ As the first week of rebuttal arguments
in the Microsoft antitrust trial ends Thursday, the body language
is unmistakable: the prosecution, the defense and even the judge
are conveying the strong impression that the government has the
case all but won, and what's being decided now is the nature of the
penalty. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   SPELLING-BEE _ WASHINGTON _ How Cox-area spellers did on the
second day of the National Spelling Bee. May be led with a national
angle if newsworthy. (Hill, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DOLE _ GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Elizabeth Dole hoped to raise $100,000
at a luncheon in Greensboro, N.C. Thursday, following a larger
event in Charlotte Tuesday. A look at how her campaign is doing in
Greensboro and the Tar Heel state. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLSHOOTINGS-FORUM _ Columbine, Colo., students at forum with
Heritage students. (Stafford, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPT-JEWELL _ATLANTA _Fulton County State Court Judge
Mathers ruled against the Atlanta Journal-Constitution Thursday,
finding the paper and two of its reporters in contempt for not
identifying sources used in reporting that Richard Jewell was a
target of the investigation into the Olympic Park bombings. The
ruling is immediately appealable, which the AJC is doing, so no one
is being hauled in. (Croft, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   JAIL-DEATH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The Travis County Sheriff's
Department will release its report today on a Mexican citizen who
died last month in the jail of a blow to the head. The detective
who investigated the case said he doesn't believe anyone struck
Campos _ who was kept isolated during his two-week stay due to
severe symptoms of alchohol withdrawal _ but he called
``questionable'' the four hours that Campos was left lying on the
floor of his cell before jailers called an ambulance. The Mexican
consulate is investigating at the request of Campos' family, who
mostly declined to comment. (Quinn, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   C130 _ WASHINGTON _ This is a tale of getting what you want. The
Pentagon asked for zero C-130J transport planes in its budget
request. Lockheed Martin, which makes the plane in Marietta, said,
``Are you sure?'' The Pentagon said, ``Yes, thank you, we're
sure.'' So now it looks as though the next budget will include
money for at least 4 and maybe as many as 7 of the $60 million
planes. That's what can happen when a powerful Democrat decides his
local National Guard unit absolutely needs one and the Senate
Majority Leader discovers a crying need for two in (guess where?)
Mississippi. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
