<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1964 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEE-MOORE-HNS &LR;      06-03 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEE-MOORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDLAND, TEXAS, STUDENT FALTERS IN 5TH ROUND OF SPELLING BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stacey Moore, 14, of Midland, Texas, was knocked
out of the National Spelling Bee in the fifth round Thursday after
failing to spell the word ``excursus,'' which is a digression from
the main topic of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day she had successfully spelled
``braunschweiger,'' a type of German sausage, to earn a place in
the competition's fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday she had clinched a spot in the final rounds of the
bee by spelling ``cricetid,'' which refers to a family of small
rodents; ``monetary,'' which has to do with a country's coinage or
currency, and ``interminable,'' which means endless.
</P>
<P>
   The 72nd National Spelling Bee began with 249 spellers, ranging
in age from 9 through 15. When the competition resumed Thursday 104
spellers, including Stacey, were still in the running.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the winner was Nupur Lala, a 14-year-old from Tampa,
Fla., who correctly spelled ``logorrhea,'' which means incoherent
talkativeness.
</P>
<P>
   Nupur, an eighth grader at Louis Benito Middle School in Tampa,
credited her success to studying for two hours a day and to
``divine intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   She will receive a $10,000 cash prize, plus encyclopedias, two
airline tickets and computer software. The contestants, most of
whom were sponsored by their local newspapers, all won regional
bees to qualify for the national bee.
</P>
<P>
   In round four Stacey found things getting harder. She said later
she never heard of ``braunschweiger.''
</P>
<P>
   But after she asked the so-called pronouncer, one of the contest
judges, to give her the word's meaning and origin, she was able to
spell it. She knew that some letter combinations in German are
different from those in English in words with the same sounds.
</P>
<P>
   So the first part of braunschweiger sounded something like
brown, and she knew that the letters a-u in German sound similar to
the letters o-w in English.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey was one of 47 students to survive the fourth round. But
in the fifth round she spelled ``excursus'' as ``excurssis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never heard it before in my life,'' she said after she
left the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other contestants, she did not appear upset after
she was eliminated. She grabbed a soft drink and met her family
outside of the ballroom where the competition was being held.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey, who completed the eighth grade last week at Alamo Junior
High School in Midland, plans to continue her spelling efforts next
year when, as a ninth grader, she will compete on the Robert E. Lee
High School varsity spelling team.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Midland Reporter-Telegram, Stacey will receive
$150 for her efforts and a commemorative watch. She and her family
will also spend the rest of the week touring the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey said she hopes to return to the National Spelling Bee
next year, but not as a contestant. she and her mother Pam and her
father Bruce hope to be rooting for Stacey's younger brother
Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, 11, who will be in the sixth grade at Crockett
Elementary School in Midland, said he someday hopes to represent
Midland in the National Spelling Bee, which is run by Scripps
Howard newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by
e-mail at jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
