<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 4, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A swarm of potent thunderstorms will erupt later Friday and
Friday night across the northern and central Plains as volatile
ingredients come together. Very humid air streaming northward from
Texas will act as fuel, while a compact jet stream disturbance from
the Rockies combines with an arriving cool front to act as a match
by lifting humid air rapidly skyward. A few of the explosive storms
will quickly become severe from western South Dakota to western
Nebraska, with large hail, damaging straight-line winds and
tornadoes possible. Storms will forge east at night. As with most
outbreaks of severe weather, only a small fraction of the area at
risk will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated severe thunderstorms will erupt over eastern New Mexico
and west Texas as a cold upper-level low-pressure system approaches
from the southern Rockies. Underneath the broad canopy of the cold
upper-level low, scattered showers and thunderstorms, some with
brief downpours and gusty winds, will develop from the southern
Sierra of California to the mountains and deserts of Arizona and
Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, widely separated thunderstorms, some heavy, will
develop across the eastern Gulf states, where very warm and humid
air near the ground bubbles skyward in the afternoon. Isolated
heavy thunderstorms will form in Florida in concert with the
leading edge of the sea breeze just inland from the Gulf and
Atlantic coasts.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Thursday's cool front, soothing breezes from the
northwest will complement low humidity across New England. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Elusive Butterfly &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weather is sometimes like an elusive butterfly. Indeed,
small-scale systems can literally fall through the cracks,
occurring between weather observing sites that might detect them.
In many cases, distances between weather sites are on the order of
a few hundred miles. But Oklahoma, a state noted for small-scale
systems of thunderstorms, has built a dense net to catch elusive
butterflies. In each county, there is at least one automated
observing site. The 114 sites create what is called a ``mesonet.''
On Wednesday, the net caught a very small-scale wind gust of 69 mph
near the town of Freedom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
