<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOLETO04-COX     06-03 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spoleto: Southern spin on arts
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ On a recent Sunday morning, the Rev. P.S.
Winton encouraged the capacity congregation of Grace Episcopal
Church to reach out to strangers. ``We want to help them become
Spoleticized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the secret to the success of the Spoleto Festival
USA, which every year turns warm-weather Charleston into a hot arts
destination for 17 days, starting Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is the time of festivals across the United States and the
world. Some are urban: New York's Fringe Festival, Seattle's
Bumbershoot. Some, like Aspen, take over a mountain for a week, a
month, a season. Charleston and Spoleto strike a nice balance
between the city and the small-town.
</P>
<P>
   In big cities, an arts festival tends to melt into the scenery.
Before it moved downtown and collapsed, the Arts Festival of
Atlanta managed to avoid anonymity by locating in Piedmont Park;
but a standard tourist junket to New York won't include the Fringe
Festival unless you know how and where to look for it.
</P>
<P>
   In Charleston, the city's Spoleto dreams flower in June and
reseed themselves for next year. You don't get the sense that the
stores and cafes set their Spoleto posters in the window just for
two weeks. Last year's poster doesn't come down until the new one
arrives. Bookstores and treasure shops display the sequence of
Spoleto art over the years. There's a Southern sense of continuity.
</P>
<P>
   Though shopkeepers are eager, as in every festival town, to
relieve tourists of their money, they make an effort to be gracious
about it, and to offer service as well as goods. ``Now, everyone
gather round,'' says Diana Smith, who runs Cafe Cafe on Meeting
Street and will mix up the filling for a pecan pie right before
your eyes, so you know it wasn't smuggled in from Stuckey's.
</P>
<P>
   The group she gathers is her early-morning servers, struggling
to cope with an overflow breakfast crowd on the festival's first
Saturday. ``I know things are busy and you're overwhelmed,'' she
says. ``But slow down a little. Take your time. Things aren't
getting done that should get done.'' She's referring to a slice of
coffeecake ordered but not delivered and other errata of that
nature. ``Remember we have a reputation to maintain.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the young woman from New York City who came down to
Charleston on the spur of the moment to join her parents from
Connecticut and her sister and brother-in-law from Charlotte, N.C.
Because they had arranged well in advance for tickets to
hard-to-get events, she couldn't be assured that she'd be able to
join them. But the festival staff ransacked the box office and
managed to find one more seat for ``Ricky Jay and His 52
Assistants,'' the master card trickster who's been packing 'em in
off-Broadway for years. Maybe she wasn't sitting with the rest of
her family, but she was right across the aisle and three rows up.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of can-do attitude that makes people like
Danielle Roshirt, an IBM executive from Detroit, return to Spoleto
on a trip arranged by her travel club. The club arranges tours to
Africa, the Far East, Europe _ but Roshirt wanted to come back to
Charleston, where she can listen to chamber music and jazz, buy a
few pieces of Charleston art, jog around the Battery in the
relative cool of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Spoleto moves on several tracks. For the tourists, it's a place
overflowing with chamber music and dance, opera and theater, jazz
and performance art, exhibits and lectures, all held against a
backdrop of elegant old houses on narrow shady streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charleston is a charming city _ worth visiting for itself,''
said Kathryn Costello, senior vice president for external affairs
at the University of Georgia, who has made four pilgrimages to
Spoleto. ``I think the attraction is the continuous availability of
performing and visual arts in such a beautiful place.''
</P>
<P>
   Costello's agenda is typical of festival-goers. She said of this
year's visit, which took place over the four-day Memorial Day
weekend: ``We filled them up. Of course, you have to have the
stamina for it!''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a place where art deals are struck, where presenters
and producers, agents and managers look after their current
proteges and check out exciting new acts to add to their stables.
</P>
<P>
   ``David often stops by,'' said Spoleto general director Nigel
Redden, asked whether David Gockney, his counterpart at Houston
Grand Opera, would be there to scope out Spoleto's operas. Like New
York, this is a place to hear singers and see how stage directors
work, but New York is full of hassles and distractions. Here you
can seal your bargain with a fabulous crabcake sandwich and a
bottomless pitcher of iced coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Spoleto takes place in Charleston's historic district beside the
waterfront. ``In a city like Atlanta, you have your choice of
performances, but they're scattered all over the place,'' said
Costello. ``This is a more compact city, where you have exposure to
so much in an area of a few blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   This and the weather guarantee a pleasant informality. After
performances, you may run into a cellist lugging her instrument
down the street. Listeners and musicians step across the invisible
line of demarcation, and the only topic of conversation _ for a few
minutes, anyway _ is music.
</P>
<P>
   In the warm humid climate, musicians don't bother with formal
concert attire; audiences wear anything from black tie to jeans,
tailored cocktail dresses to broomstick skirts, wing tips to
sandals. By evening, everyone wilts, and no one minds.
</P>
<P>
   Why step out of time and place for an arts festival when you can
see some of these same groups on the Atlanta concert circuit?
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to go away and concentrate on something,'' says
Costello. ``It's good to be removed from the clutter of what
occupies your day. Everyone's there with a common interest and
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
