A1968 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS &LR;      06-03 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER SAYS MAN LINKED TO MISSING ATHEIST IS INNOCENT OF MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A federal agent says Gary Karr played a role in
the apparent abduction and killing of famed atheist Madalyn Murray
O'Hair and her two adult children. But a lawyer who is prepared to
represent the ex-convict says Karr had no part in the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``He absolutely denies he had anything to do with the murders,''
said Thomas Mills, a Dallas lawyer who met with Karr earlier this
week in a Michigan jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt he talked to the law enforcement people in good faith
and maybe they've turned on him, and he doesn't know why,'' Mills
said.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit of an Internal Revenue Service investigator
implicates O'Hair's former office manager, David R. Waters, 52, of
Austin; Karr, 50; and a heavy-drinking man from Florida named Danny
Fry, who was killed shortly after the O'Hairs vanished from San
Antonio, of kidnapping and murdering the family in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said he traveled to Michigan Tuesday to talk with Karr,
who is being held near Detroit on a federal weapons charge. A
federal public defender is representing Karr in the weapons case,
which goes to trial July 6.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said he would defend Karr in Texas if and when he requires
representation there, and has already approached a judge in Dallas
about being appointed to that role. So far, Karr is charged in
Texas only with transporting stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   But Karr's admitted role in the O'Hair affair, that of a
helpful, uninformed bystander, contrasts sharply with the role
given him by the government in the affidavit filed in federal court
in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   While the document paints Waters as the mastermind, it puts Karr
in the middle of the action, renting vans and a San Antonio motel
room allegedly used in the kidnappings and killing of O'Hair, Jon
Garth Murray and Robin Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   The March 23 affidavit also says Waters and Karr later killed
Fry and dumped his headless, handless body by a river in Dallas
County.
</P>
<P>
   And according to an FBI agent who testified in federal court in
Detroit after Karr was arrested on March 25, Karr admitted
involvement in both crimes during 13 hours of interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   But Mills said the FBI exaggerated Karr's words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some belief that Mr. Waters was involved but no direct
evidence of it. He is willing to tell the truth about the whole
thing,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said Karr played only a marginal role in connection with
the O'Hairs, who abruptly left Austin in late August 1995, spent a
month in San Antonio and then vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Madalyn Murray O'Hair gained prominence in the 1960s for her
successful court battles to eliminate organized prayer in public
schools. She went on to lead a national atheist organization.
</P>
<P>
   She and her children are presumed dead even though their bodies
have not been found.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said Karr also denies any involvement in the Fry murder.
</P>
<P>
   Karr does admit knowing something about where the O'Hairs might
have been buried and has tried to steer federal agents to the site
near Camp Wood, a town northwest of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where he thinks Waters thinks they are buried but he
says he was not there when the bodies were buried,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Two FBI searches of the site have failed to turn up any remains.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said he decided to get involved in the case after
discussing it with Richard Helfrick, the public defender
representing Karr on the weapons charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything about the case grabs me. It looks like a case where
I can do some good for a person, and it looks like they have very
marginal evidence,'' Mills said of federal authorities. ``They are
trying to solve a mystery disappearance of well-known people by
making leaps of logic. It is all very fascinating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
