r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-INSTINCT-TEX     06-03 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INSTINCT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS `INSTINCT' IS WAY OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Instinct,'' it's as if Cuba Gooding Jr. had taken one of
the songs by his father's group, the Main Ingredient, a little too
seriously. Unfortunately, that song would be ``Everybody Plays the
Fool.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooding is a bright-eyed, ambitious teaching psychiatrist who is
handed the career opportunity of a lifetime by his mentor (Donald
Sutherland). The young shrink is asked to look into the case of an
eminent researcher, played by Anthony Hopkins. Hopkins has been
transported to the Gothic and gloomy mental-institution wing of a
Gothic and gloomy prison.
</P>
<P>
   It's whispered that Hopkins went crazy while in Africa and
became a murderer. Hopkins hasn't spoken since, and in this movie
that's all over the place, you wonder at first if it's because he's
rebelling against the nonsensical plot. Or perhaps he's beginning
to honor his vow to quit acting _ which he took and recanted a few
months ago _ before your very eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There is some small enjoyment to be had from ``Instinct,'' which
comes from the chemistry of Hopkins and Gooding. As an actor, one
of Gooding's strengths is that he's steeped in energy and common
sense. (He's smart enough that he should be a step ahead of the
tired old plot, since the audience will be.)
</P>
<P>
   Gooding is intelligent enough to stay away from ``Hey, I'm
playing a smart guy'' cliches, like toying with a pair of glasses
so we know he's graduated from college. And Hopkins' wariness,
which he can play for either a joke or teary empathy, promises
something in the early scenes, after Gooding breaks through
Hopkins' silence. (He'd have to, or there would be no picture; not
that there's much of one anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   This prodding relationship, and the chasm between their acting
styles, is entertaining. What we come out of the picture wanting is
for Gooding and Hopkins to exploit their intensity in a much better
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins summons a dry-as-parchment authority once he starts to
speak. I know you, Hopkins teases in Gooding's face, because I was
you. It turns out that while researching a tribe of apes, Hopkins
had a breakthrough. He got closer to them, physically and
spiritually, than anyone ever had. And he reverted to instinctive
behavior, freed from the cold, insensitive grasp of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the civilization that this movie asks him to return
to, who would blame him? Especially when it comes to the
representation of the African poachers who charge through the
jungle, ruthlessly dispatching the apes. (Hopkins is filled with
guilt because he inadvertently led the men to the apes. They
tracked him by his discarded equipment, as Hopkins shed the
civilized tools that keep him insulated from the natural world.)
</P>
<P>
   It was in the jungle that Hopkins killed. ``Yes, and I'd kill
again,'' he threatens, having gained the superhuman strength that
all men seem to get from being in the jungle too long. The cast,
including Maura Tierney as Hopkins' flinty daughter who wants her
dad back, must've been warned by their instincts to get out of this
movie. They should've listened to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instinct'' is rated R for violence and adult language.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
