<P>
   CHAPTER &AMP; VERSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ You're almost afraid to ask, but ... almost five
decades after C.S. Lewis' ``Mere Christianity,'' has John G.
Stackhouse Jr. written this generation's successor to that classic
work of religious sensibility? Despite the numbing effects of ``a
never-ending stream of tragedy, disaster, selfishness, and
absurdity,'' the Canadian scholar writes in ``Can God Be
Trusted?,'' ``every once in a while a story grips us, we sit up
straight, and the old questions return: `How could this happen?
What kind of a world is this?' And we might ask one of the oldest
questions of all, `How could a good and almighty God possibly allow
such evil to occur?''' By ALAN COCHRUM. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
