<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-WORKSHOP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAPS OF FAITH IN THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Russia)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The journey to the stage starts with a plie, one arm
resting on a ballet studio barre. Month by month, year by year,
ballet classes get harder and the stakes higher. At last come a
first few experiences in a theater as a tiny, nervous cog in the
huge machinery of a ballet production.
</P>
<P>
   Many students begin by dancing children's roles in ``The
Nutcracker.'' At the New York City Ballet there are coveted roles
in other works by George Balanchine, Jerome Robbins and Peter
Martins that give students a chance to perform among grown-up
dancers and even with a few stars.
</P>
<P>
   For young dancers at the School of American Ballet, affiliated
with City Ballet, there is another goal: the yearly workshop
performances at which the outside world takes its first measure of
a dancer's worth. Begun in 1965 under the aegis of Alexandra
Danilova, who had just joined the faculty, the workshop was
inspired by the annual graduation performances of the Imperial
Ballet Academy in St. Petersburg, Russia, where she and Balanchine
trained.
</P>
<P>
   Today the workshop draws not only family and friends but also
ballet company directors, choreographers and writers intent on
spotting the next generation's most promising dancers. This year'
performances, which begin Sunday, will include Balanchine's
``Tombeau de Couperin'' and ``Valse Fantaisie,'' Robbins'
``Fanfare'' and Christopher Wheeldon's new ``Scenes de Ballet.''
</P>
<P>
   Two surrogate fathers are also likely to be in the audience
appraising their charges. Peter Boal and Jock Soto, both City
Ballet principals, teach a variety of classes at the School of
American Ballet, specializing in training the male dancers. Ballet
lives on in the handing down of its physical and cultural
traditions. Leading dancers in companies around the world return to
teach the young. It was not so long ago that Boal and Soto were
among the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have attended the workshops over the decades cherish
the memory of their first sight of Boal, a small, frail,
well-combed blond child of notably serious demeanor, gliding onto
the stage in Jean-Pierre Bonnefous' ``Quadrille'' in 1978. He had
so inherent a sense of classical elegance that the audience gasped.
Three years later a fledgling star named Jock Soto emerged in
Martins' ``Magic Flute,'' well schooled by Martins in the art of
ballet mime and already showing signs of his gifts as a partner and
performer.
</P>
<P>
   Soto and Boal will be performing with City Ballet this weekend
across Lincoln Center at the New York State Theater. At the school
they have taught boys to jump high with feet pointed stylishly.
Girls learn to hold their upper torsos at just the right angle for
the boys to slip firm but delicate hands around their waists as
they dance together. The boys learn how to curve their arms
precisely above their heads to suggest, at least subliminally, a
crown's conferring royalty on ordinary mortals. All are trained to
absorb and remember long combinations of steps, working them out
with dancing hands as they watch their teachers. That is a
necessary skill for succeeding in the companies with which these
young dancers will soon be performing and from which they will one
day venture themselves, perhaps to teach.
</P>
<P>
   This year's workshop performances by students at the School of
American Ballet are Sunday at 2 and 8 p.m. (tickets are $25) and
Monday at 7 p.m. ($45) at the Juilliard Theater at Lincoln Center.
There is also a benefit supper on Monday, with tickets from $500 to
$1,000, including the performance. Reservations: (212) 769-6600.
</P>
</TEXT>
