<HEADER>
A1998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-FILM-FESTIVAL-NYT     06-03 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-FILM-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITE OF GLOOM: TIME TO BE GAILY GAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If asked to describe the mood of the 11th Annual New
York Lesbian and Gay Film Festival based only on its opening and
closing features, this year's events might be characterized as
Giddy Gay Lite.
</P>
<P>
   Both Rose Troche's ``Bedrooms and Hallways,'' which opened the
festival Thursday night, and Jim Fall's ``Trick,'' which closes the
series on June 13, partake of the same heady spirit that has
characterized recent semimainstream films like ``The Opposite of
Sex'' and ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss.'' In the world of Giddy
Gay Lite, gay liberation is almost a fait accompli, the AIDS
epidemic barely exists and rampant homophobia is somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Troche's film is a frothy post-Noel Coward romantic comedy,
a millennial, pansexual ``Design for Living'' set in contemporary
London. A single gay man in an otherwise heterosexual New Age men's
group confesses his attraction to another member who has recently
separated from his girlfriend of eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The two embark on an affair, and the gay man ends up sleeping
with the ex-girlfriend. Is anybody jealous or upset? Not really. No
dangerous emotions are allowed to undermine the cheery,
sophisticated banter.
</P>
<P>
   Fall's film, which will open commercially in the summer, is a
comic ``After Hours'' flavored survey of gay male life in
Manhattan. An aspiring musical-comedy composer with a straight male
roommate picks up a buffed-up go-go boy on the subway and brings
him home, but one interruption after another keeps preventing them
from having sex. They then roam the city in search of a rendezvous.
Tori Spelling gives a teeth-gnashing performance as a best friend
from hell.
</P>
<P>
   But between these bookends the festival has its share of serious
and cerebral work. One of the most original features, Scott King's
``Treasure Island,'' is a mock 1940s spy drama in which two
American code breakers construct a false identity and devise
military misinformation to be planted on a dead soldier's body. The
stylish black-and-white film turns into an eerie ghost story
exploring oppressive racial and sexual stereotypes in wartime
America with deadpan humor.
</P>
<P>
   In a totally different vein is Joseph Lovett's personal
documentary ``The Accident,'' in which the filmmaker re-enacts the
freak accident that killed his mother and interviews his siblings
to try to construct a psychological history of his troubled family.
Lovett's own homosexuality is only one of the many threads woven
together to create a subtle, ultimately enigmatic family portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian director Anne Wheeler's serious comedy ``Better Than
Chocolate'' is a cheery broadside for sexual diversity that follows
the evolving relationships of several couples including a feminist
lesbian and a woman who was once a man. Late in the film this
utopian fantasy takes a sudden, dark turn.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Winer's upbeat documentary ``Golden Threads'' profiles
Christine Burton, a 93-year-old woman who at the age of 80 founded
an international network for lesbians over 50.
</P>
<P>
   And from Germany, Kutlug Ataman's melodrama ``Lola and
Bildikid'' focuses on the identity crisis of a young gay Turk in
Germany and his violent, aggressively straight older brother. While
exploring Berlin's demimonde, the boy is befriended by Lola, a drag
queen whose macho lover wants her to have a sex-change operation.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the stronger features _ Lin Cheng-Sheng's ``Murmur of
Youth,'' from Japan, and Sebastien Lifshitz's ``Open Bodies'' and
Francois Ozon's ``Sitcom,'' both from France _ have previously been
shown in the New Directors/New Films Series. ``Murmur of Youth''
explores the painful romantic attachment of two teen-age girls.
``Open Bodies'' follows the gay and straight adventures of a
sexually curious French high school boy with a possessive older
male lover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitcom,'' which will open at the Quad Cinemas on June 18,
satirizes Gallic family values and the limitations of psychotherapy
in an erotic free-for-all whose many frantic couplings include
mother-son incest.
</P>
<P>
   The festival is also reviving two influential underground films,
James Bidgood's ``Pink Narcissus,'' a 1970 fantasia of gaudily
costumed gay male erotica, and Gregory Markopoulos' ``Twice a
Man,'' a 1963 retelling of the Greek drama of Phaedra and
Hippolytus set in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 200 films being shown in the festival include a
tribute to British independent filmmaker Pratibha Parmar, whose
newest work, ``Righteous Babes,'' is a documentary exploring the
convergence of feminism and rock in the music of women like Sinead
O'Connor, Tori Amos and Ani DiFranco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
