<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-03 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNAIL DARTER REDUX? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ To sacrifice the Monarch butterfly or to save it, that
is the question these days in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   This exaggerated dilemma reflects the latest pseudo-scientific
scare over the potential consequences of growing and eating
genetically altered food _ a rapidly spreading phenomenon driven by
new technological advances and the needs of commercial agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles and a band of other nervous nellies are demanding
a moratorium on such crops under the banner of protecting
butterflies and maybe humans too. Their concern for the environment
and our health is indeed a noble cause, but they are operating on
emotion rather than any reliable evidence of pending doom.
</P>
<P>
   The British have a history of this sort of thing where little
creatures are concerned. Not long ago conservationists demanded,
and got, an expensive tunnel dug under a major highway to save
small toads from being regularly squashed by cars.
</P>
<P>
   A similar crusade to protect the fox against all those cruel
hunters fond of riding to the hounds, however, failed. The fox
didn't have enough friends in high places. Prince Charles and his
aristocratic buddies were on those horses.
</P>
<P>
   The genetically modified (GM) food issue is a much more
hysterical topic in Great Britain than it is in America, where we
tend to trust the experts who assure us that plant biotechnology is
not only helpful but here to stay. The U.S. Department of
Agriculture is studying whether such crops should be labeled to
alert consumers concerned about food origins, but it is doing
nothing so radical as discouraging further research.
</P>
<P>
   If consumer panic spreads through Europe, however, it could have
devastating international consequences not only for commercial
agriculture but the fight against hunger in poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Both American and British scientists insist that GM soybeans,
tomatoes, corn and other foodstuffs are perfectly safe to eat. Yet
unreliable early studies have linked ``Frankenstein foods'' to
possible disease. One discredited alarmist report in England about
the danger of GM tomatoes so drove down sales of a perfectly good
GM tomato paste that the product has been taken off the market.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest impact, however, comes from a recent Cornell
University laboratory study that indicates Monarch caterpillars
confronted with the wind-borne pollen of GM corn either died or
produced smaller butterflies than usual. This was a bombshell in
Great Britain, where the British Butterfly Conservation Society is
a political force and tourist icons such as the restored Sudley
Castle eagerly plant wildflower fields to win the honor of being
designated a ``butterfly base''.
</P>
<P>
   The public fuss was fueled by Prince Charles' Internet website,
in which he crusades against GM foods and warns that ``mixing
genetic material from species that cannot breed naturally takes us
into areas that should be left to God.'' Perhaps waiting too long
to become king has impaired his ability to envision the scientific
future.
</P>
<P>
   The actual impact of GM corn on the survival of the Monarch
butterfly species is not clear. No one yet knows how many are being
killed or how to compare that with the damage to all insects from
the spraying of insecticides, which is unnecessary with some GM
crops.
</P>
<P>
   In America, we admire pretty butterflies and like to have them
around. But they are not yet our next snail darter, that miniature
fish whose rare habitat held up the construction of Tennessee's
massive Tellico Dam in the late 1970s and became a major
environmental issue.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court declared the darter was protected under
the Endangered Species Act; eventually a furious Congress invented
a legislative loophole that let the dam proceed anyway. Ironically,
biologists later discovered that the snail darter was alive and
well in other waters all along. The controversy had been for
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the butterfly bit will be the same.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits to mankind of GM foods seem obvious, producing
larger and more disease-resistant crops, reducing the amount of
chemicals currently used in intensive farming and expanding the
variety and location of plants. As the global population expands,
so must its reliable food supply.
</P>
<P>
   We do not have evidence that there will be a disastrous downside
from this. But as Ronald Reagan said in another context, it is wise
to trust but verify. We should continue to explore and develop the
technology, but carefully monitor and research it every step of the
way. It's a brave new world.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail,
at means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
