<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans four pages of stories on Kosovo for
Friday, June 4.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PEACE-PLAN (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ On the 72nd day of
NATO's air war against Yugoslavia, President Slobodan Milosevic on
Thursday accepted an international peace plan to end the Kosovo
conflict and allow nearly 1 million ethnic Albanian refugees to
return to what is left of their homes. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ News Analysis on
Milosevic and what he got out of _ or didn't get out of _ the
latest peace proposal. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PROBLEMS (Washington) _ While the agreement reportedly
reached with Slobodan Milosevic raised hopes that an end to the
bombardment might be near, it also made clear the enormity of the
tasks and questions that lay ahead. Looming largest were the
refugees - a million people without homes or crops, facing a
mountain winter. Many were likely to resist coming home to
destroyed homes, and even if they did return, they would have no
chance to lay in crops or set up sufficient housing for the winter.
By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ President Clinton said Thursday
that word of Yusoslav willingness to accept international peace
terms for Kosovo is encouraging and welcome, but insisted on seeing
``real results'' before there is an end to the NATO bombing of
Serbian targets. By John Broder and Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEE-REAX (Stenkovec I Camp, Macedonia) _ When the
camp loudspeakers broadcast the evening news Thursday with the
announcement of a potential peace agreement for Kosovo, Ahmet
Sharifi burst out laughing: ``Milosevic is lying again.'' The
reaction was the same on the sidelines of the men's round robin
volleyball game and in the long line of women filling their plastic
water jugs at an open spigot. No one here or in Cegrane, the
largest Kosovar camp, put any faith in the agreement by Milosevic
and the Serbian parliament to accept the NATO peace agreement. By
Elizabeth Becker and David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Cologne, Germany) _ European leaders cautiously
turned Thuesday to discussions about how and when to send in an
international security force to oversee Yugoslavia's acceptance of
NATO's terms _ withdrawal of all Yugoslav forces from Kosovo, and
the return of about a million refugees. ``We are talking days
rather than weeks,'' said Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, the
mediator who came here from Belgrade to report that Serbia had
agreed to the allies' terms. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The Russian role in the peace deal. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Residents of Belgrade
expressed relief at the news of a peace deal to end the war, but
their relief was tinged with bitterness that they had been put
through 10 weeks of bombing for little gain. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AHTISAARI (Undated) _ Profile of Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari: Geography, history and some stubborn Nordic patience
give Ahtisaari, 61, a reasoning power with Slobodan Milosevic and
his Russian advocates that no other European leader can match. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   E.U.-MILITARY (Cologne, Germany) _ The leaders of 15 European
countries decided Thursday to make the European Union a military
power for the first time in its 42-year history, with command
headquarters, staffs, and forces of its own for peacekeeping and
peacemaking missions in future crises like those in Kosovo or
Bosnia. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   At least three graphics are also in the works: highlights of the
peace plan; a comparison with the proposal drawn up in Rambouillet,
France, in February; and up-to-date numbers on refugees,
casualities, bombing runs, etc.
</P>
