<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-SHELTERS-ART-375-     06-03 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-SHELTERS-ART-375-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MOVE TO CURB ABUSIVE CORPORATE TAX SHELTERS IS DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first clue was an obscure reference in a
corporate financial statement to a sizable tax benefit, a possible
tipoff to a new form of tax shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after that tidbit came to the attention of Treasury
Department officials early last year, Jonathan Talisman, a deputy
assistant Treasury secretary for tax policy, got a phone call from
a tax professional describing a new and increasingly popular tax
avoidance strategy that matched what was hinted at in the corporate
document.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at Treasury and the IRS spent the next few months
figuring out the new shelter _ a complicated set of transactions
known as a ``liquidating REIT'' _ and determined that it was
becoming so popular among corporations that it would cost the
government billions of dollars in foregone revenues.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of the year, Treasury officials had convinced
Congress that the transactions abused the tax code and should be
shut down. A provision to do that was included in the tax bill
signed into law by President Clinton in October.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the episode was a case study in how the federal
government can root out attempts to game the tax system. But in its
dependence on a few lucky breaks, it also showed the haphazard
nature of efforts to control the proliferation of sophisticated
corporate tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about keeping ahead of the blizzard of tax-avoidance
strategies being developed and marketed by accountants and lawyers
to corporate clients, the Clinton administration has asked Congress
for broad new powers to discourage use of tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   If adopted, the administration's proposals would fundamentally
change the government's strategy for dealing with corporate tax
shelters. Instead of trying to find, understand and stop the
transactions after they have occurred, either through informal
intelligence gathering or audits or corporate returns, the
administration wants to make using a questionable shelter
sufficiently risky and costly that companies will choose not to use
them in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our proposals are designed to impose a regime that will cause
corporations not to engage in shelter transactions,'' Talisman
said, ``rather than having us chase them after the fact.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although Congress has acted a number of times in recent years to
curb specific types of tax shelters, and has some sympathy for the
goals behind the administration's current proposals, the Republican
majority has shown no indication that it will move to pass sweeping
legislation to deal with the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in pursuing its tax-shelter plan, the administration has
set off a sharp debate in Congress and among accountants and tax
lawyers over how big a problem there is and the degree to which
giving the IRS more power is the solution.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's approach, said Sen. William Roth, R-Del.,
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, ``may be overly broad and
may possibly subject legitimate business transactions to tax
shelter penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Weinberger, a principal in the lobbying firm of Washington
Counsel who is representing a number of large corporations, called
the administration's proposals ``unnecessary and certainly
premature, exceedingly vague and far reaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the House Ways and Means Committee, which last
year voted to rein in the powers of the IRS, Weinberger said the
administration's proposals ``appear to create an unprecedented
transfer of power to the executive branch and specifically IRS
revenue agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers have been looking for shelters for as long as there
have been taxes, and shelters have been used aggressively by
wealthy individuals as well as corporations.
</P>
<P>
   At issue here are not the tax breaks written into the law
deliberately by legislators to help constituents, interest groups
and campaign contributors, but those that arise from unforeseen
inconsistencies and unintended wrinkles in a tax code that takes on
new layers of complexity each year.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials say shelter abuse has become an increasing
problem as the tax code has grown more complex and as accounting
and law firms have become more aggressive in marketing
tax-minimizing strategies to their corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate tax executives routinely receive proposals from
accountants and lawyers on how they can shave their tax bills by
engaging in transactions that have no business purpose other than
to create tax breaks. Some law firms do a brisk business providing
legal opinions on the deals. Accounting firms sometimes take a cut
of the tax savings from the deals as their fee. The very names
attached to the transactions _ like stepped down preferred, or
lease-in lease-out _ hint at the complexity of the financial and
legal engineering behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Almost by definition, there are no reliable figures on the use
of these kinds of tax shelters. Developed in secrecy, and usually
buried cryptically deep in corporate tax filings and financial
statements, they often go undetected. Corporations and their tax
advisers certainly have no motivation to disclose them.
Administration officials cite estimates of revenue losses of more
than $10 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Tax lobbyists on the other side of the issue scoff at those
numbers, and point out that corporate tax revenues continue to grow
robustly, contributing to a big federal budget surplus. And they
say the Treasury Department and the IRS do not even use all the
powers currently available to them to fight tax avoidance,
including a 1997 law that expands requirements for companies to
register their use of shelters with the government.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to win over skeptics in Congress, the Treasury
Department plans to issue a refined proposal in the next month or
so, taking into account criticism that its approach is so
ill-defined that it would sweep many perfectly legitimate business
transactions into its net.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration is not expected to alter the basic thrust
of its approach, which it laid out earlier this year. Its plan
would allow the IRS to deny tax benefits generated by transactions
that it judges to be driven primarily by tax-avoidance
considerations. It would double, to 40 percent, the penalty imposed
on corporations found to have understated their tax bill by using
an improper tax shelter, and make it harder for companies to claim
they thought the shelter was allowable.
</P>
<P>
   It would deny deductions for the cost of tax advice that led to
use of a tax shelter. It would impose excise taxes on any fees
earned by accountants and lawyers in developing shelters for
corporate clients, and on the purchaser of a corporate tax shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, it would give the government
considerable leeway in determining what separates a creative but
permissible tax strategy from one that steps over the line _ a
divide that current tax law leaves maddeningly vague.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Treasury Department has lost all the battles. The
government has had some success cracking down on the use of
shelters in the last few years. In March, the Supreme Court let
stand a lower court decision invalidating a maneuver used by
Colgate-Palmolive Co. that would have created tax benefits for the
company through a deal with a Dutch bank in Bermuda. The lower
court had found the technique to be built on ``sham transactions''
with no purpose other than generating tax savings. The shelter had
been devised for Colgate and other clients by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   It has also caught wind of other types of deals relatively
early, including the liquidating REIT transactions shut down by
Congress last year. (In those deals banks and other companies
transferred mortgages into real estate investment trusts, which
were then liquidated in a way that created a tax break.) The
Treasury Department has also moved aggressively to limit use of
certain types of leasing deals that generate tax breaks by
transferring assets back and forth between American and foreign
owners.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's concern is shared by some tax lawyers,
accountants and corporate executives who feel pressured by the
competition to stretch the law in their efforts to keep tax bills
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constant promotion of these frequently artificial
transactions breeds significant disrespect for the tax system,
encouraging responsible corporate taxpayers to expect this type of
activity to be the norm and to follow the lead of other taxpayers
who have engaged in tax-advantaged transactions,'' Harold Handler,
a lawyer at Simpson Thacher &AMP; Bartlett who is chairman of the New
York State Bar Association's tax section, told the Senate Finance
Committee recently.
</P>
<P>
   But if it is to succeed in turning its proposals into law, the
administration will not only have to overcome the skepticism among
Republicans about handing more power to the IRS, but the concerted
opposition of some of the most influential lobbyists in Washington.
Among them is Kenneth Kies, a managing partner at
PricewaterhouseCoopers.
</P>
<P>
   A former staff director of the Joint Committee on Taxation,
which provides technical advice to Congress on tax issues, Kies
knows as much about the tax code as anyone in Washington. While
more closely aligned with the Republican majority, he is
sufficiently respected by Democrats to have acted as a go-between
in back-channel discussions earlier this year between Congress and
the White House over Social Security. And he is no shrinking
violet.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's tax shelter proposals, he said, are the
result of a ``good faith but misguided belief'' among senior
Treasury officials like Donald Lubick, the assistant Treasury
secretary for tax policy, and his deputy, Talisman, ``that the
system is in danger of collapsing in a heap.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing full well that Congress remains deeply suspicious of the
IRS, Kies said that the tax shelter problem is not big enough to
justify handing the tax service a whole new set of weapons,
especially since the service does not use all the powers it already
has to limit use of tax dodges.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the margin, there will always be people who are more
aggressive with the tax code than they should be,'' Kies said.
``The question is, what is the appropriate action to take relative
to that problem? Treasury has to meet a high burden to justify a
dramatic expansion of authority, and I don't think they're meeting
that burden.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
