<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2010 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOP10-MONSTERS-960(2T     06-03 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOP10-MONSTERS-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE THEY ARE, THE TOP TEN OF TERROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next Tuesday, Thomas Harris will unleash Hannibal Lecter on the
world for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hannibal,'' published by Dell, is the eagerly anticipated
sequel to ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' the bestseller that sent
chills through a nation of readers. Known for coolly devouring his
victims while enjoying a glass of fine wine, Hannibal the Cannibal
clearly ranks among the most evil characters in all of literature _
but he has plenty of company. Here is a list of the 10 scariest
literary monsters of all time. It is not for the squeamish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Dracula, in ``Dracula'' by Bram Stoker. Dracula is the king,
the epitome of the marrow-chilling villain. He wants your blood,
your body, your soul. Jonathan Harker found out the hard way:
</P>
<P>
   ``I raised the (coffin) lid ... and then I saw something which
filled my very soul with horror. There lay the Count, but looking
as if his youth had been half-renewed, for the white hair and
moustache were changed to dark iron-gray; the cheeks were fuller,
and the white skin seemed ruby-red underneath; the mouth was redder
than ever, for on the lips were gouts of fresh blood, which
trickled from the corners of the mouth and ran over the chin and
neck ... it seemed as if the whole awful creature were simply
gorged with blood. He lay like a filthy leech, exhausted with his
repletion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the being I was helping to transfer to London, where,
perhaps, for centuries to come he might, amongst its teeming
millions, satiate his lust for blood, and create a new and
ever-widening circle of semi-demons to batten on the helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Richard III, in ``Henry VI Part III'' and ``Richard III'' by
William Shakespeare. In both plays, Richard wanders the stage
proclaiming his basic rottenness and his scheme to kill anyone
standing between him and the English throne. Late in ``Henry VI''
(Part III, Act III, Scene II, to be exact) he makes his most
frightening admission:
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, I can smile, and murder while I smile ... and wet my
cheeks with artificial tears/and frame my face to all
occasions./I'll drown more sailors than the mermaid shall. ... Can
I do this, and cannot get a crown?''
</P>
<P>
   3. Blue Duck in ``Lonesome Dove'' by Larry McMurtry. This amoral
Comanchero kidnaps Lorena, Gus' prostitute friend, and takes her
off into the wilderness for the sexual pleasure of his bloodthirsty
band of followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue Duck hobbled the horses, then came and looked down at
her.
</P>
<P>
   ```I got a treatment for women that try to run away,' he said
casually. `I cut a little hole in their stomachs and pull out a gut
and wrap it around a limb. Then I drag them 30 or 40 feet and tie
them down. That way they can watch the coyotes come and eat their
guts.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Lorena doesnt try to run away. Soon afterward, she notices that
Blue Duck wears a necklace made of severed human fingers.
</P>
<P>
   4. Hannibal Lecter in ``Red Dragon'' and ``The Silence of the
Lambs'' by Thomas Harris.
</P>
<P>
   The frighteningly graphic descriptions of Lecter's attacks
almost pale in comparison with his shockingly casual comments. In
``The Silence of the Lambs,'' Hannibal explains to FBI agent
Clarice Starling why he served dinner guests grilled body parts of
someone he'd recently murdered:
</P>
<P>
   ``Haven't you ever had people coming over and no time to shop?
You have to make do with what's in the fridge, Clarice.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Napoleon the Pig in ``Animal Farm'' by George Orwell. Besides
its justified acclaim as political commentary, ``Animal Farm'' is a
masterpiece of caricature. It is Napoleon the Pig who emerges as a
despicable dictator every bit as bad as the deposed Farmer Jones.
We hear about Napoleon much more often than we meet him directly.
He is described early on as ``a large, rather fierce-looking
Berkshire boar ... with a reputation for getting his own way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book's final, horrifying chapter, Napoleon appears
equipped with the same implement that symbolized human cruelty. In
perhaps the most frightening, simply presented one-sentence
paragraph in modern literature, Orwell writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``He carried a whip in his trotter.''
</P>
<P>
   6. In ``A Tale of Two Cities,'' Charles Dickens presents us with
Madame Defarge, wife of a wine-shop owner and the bloody-minded
leader of the downtrodden Parisian masses. It would be easy to
sympathize with Madame D.'s cause, except for her delight in death
and her insatiable appetite for more victims. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing to her, that an innocent man was to die for the
sins of his forefathers; she saw, not him, but them. It was nothing
to her, that his wife was to be made a widow and his daughter an
orphan; that was insufficient punishment, because they were her
natural enemies and as such had no right to live. To appeal to her
was made hopeless by her having no sense of pity, even for
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   7. Eva Galli in ``Ghost Story'' by Peter Straub. The book
features a murderous shape-shifter who is the ghost of Eva Galli, a
young woman who died under shady circumstances involving a group of
young men who, as they aged, became respected members of their New
England community. Perhaps no passage is more chilling than the
moment a young writer discovers his new lover isn't quite, well,
``normal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been dozing more than sleeping for most of the night,
and I reached over lightly to touch Alma's bare rounded arm; I did
not want to wake her. But it was as if her arm gave my fingers a
shock: Not an electrical shock, but a shock of concentrated
feeling, a shock of revulsion _ as though I had touched a slug. I
snatched back my hand.... Sometime later I dreamed of her. I merely
saw her face; but it was not the face I knew, and the strangeness
of it made me moan with anxiety; and for the second time I came
wholly awake, not sure where I was or by whose side I lay.''
</P>
<P>
   8. The White Witch in ``The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe''
by C.S. Lewis. Now here is a glorious villain of childhood
bookshelves, ready to slaughter children or lions at whim. Hannibal
Lecter is, in a sense, her direct literary descendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last she drew near. She stood by Aslan's head. Her face was
working and twitching with passion. ... Then, just before she gave
the (knife) blow, she stooped down and said in a quivering voice,
`And now, who has won? Fool, did you think that by all this you
would save the human traitor? ... But when you are dead what will
prevent me from killing him as well? And who will take him out of
my hand then? Understand that you have given me Narnia forever, you
have lost your own life and you have not saved his. In that
knowledge, despair and die.'''
</P>
<P>
   9. Nurse Ratched (Big Nurse) in Ken Kesey's ``One Flew Over the
Cuckoo's Nest.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most horrifying characters in fiction kill with
regulations, not knives or teeth or claws. Enter, Nurse Ratched:
</P>
<P>
   ``What she dreams of ... is a world of precision, efficiency and
tidiness like a pocket watch with a glass back, a place where the
schedule is unbreakable and all the patients who aren't Outside,
obedient under her beam, are wheelchair Chronics with catheter
tubes run direct from every pantleg to the sewer under the floor
... she fixes these doctors (who disagree with her way of running
things) with dry-ice eyes day in, day out, until they retreat with
unnatural chills. `I tell you I don't know what it is,' they tell
the guy in charge of personnel. `Since I started on the ward with
that woman I feel like my veins are running ammonia. I shiver all
the time....'''
</P>
<P>
   10. The great white shark in ``Jaws'' by Peter Benchley.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century after the fact, too many people remember the
movie but have forgotten the book. Benchley's informed descriptions
of shark teeth, gills and digestive systems made his fictional
killer a literary nightmare with fins, especially when, in the
first few pages, the shark claims its initial victim.
</P>
<P>
   The shark ``smelled her now, and the vibrations _ erratic and
sharp _ signalled distress ... its dorsal fin broke water and its
tail, thrashing back and forth, cut the glassy surface with a hiss.
A series of tremors shook its body. The fish was about 40 feet from
the woman, off to the side, when it turned suddenly to the left,
dropped entirely below the surface, and, with two quick thrusts of
its tail, was upon her.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, the woman thought she had snagged her leg on a rock
or a piece of floating wood. There was no initial pain, only one
violent tug on her right leg. She reached down to touch her foot,
treading water with her left leg to keep her head up, feeling in
the blackness with her left hand. She could not find her foot ...''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TRAITS OF GREAT LITERARY VILLAINS
</P>
<P>
   The best fictional monsters are amoral, with no thought of right
or wrong. They do awful things because it is their nature _ and
they enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   They don't appear in the story too often. Psychologically, we
fear most what we don't quite see completely. Our imaginations fill
in some of the frightening details. What the monsters might do next
frightens us even more than whatever it is they've just done.
Hannibal, Dracula, the great white shark in ``Jaws'' _ they creep
around a lot but are out of the action more than they are in it.
Harris' challenge in the upcoming ``Hannibal'' is that Lecter
finally becomes the main character.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have to live to fight/bite another day. So far,
Hannibal Lecter has. Nurse Ratched did. Dracula didn't; neither did
Shakespeare's Richard III or Larry McMurtry's Blue Duck. But when
the best literary monsters die, they do it in character _
unrepentant and murderous to the last.
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
