NYT-06-03-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT04-COX     06-03 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: NEGATIVE SIGNS BUILDING FOR MICROSOFT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In resuming this week after a three-month break,
the focus of the Microsoft antitrust trial has subtly shifted from
the question whether Microsoft broke the law to what limits should
be placed on the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   In their private comments outside the courtroom, government
lawyers brim with confidence that they have already won the case,
voicing contempt for the defense. While Microsoft lawyers aren't
conceding defeat, the company in recent months has positioned
itself to live with an adverse verdict.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling is still months away, and it almost certainly will be
appealed. But in his comments from the bench, U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson, who is presiding over the case without a
jury, has repeatedly signaled that he accepts the government's
designation of Microsoft as a powerful monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions, Jackson has sought updated figures on the
browser wars, which are at the heart of the current defense
strategy. Microsoft contends that the $10 billion purchase of
browser maker Netscape Communications Corp. by America Online Inc.,
the nation's largest Internet provider, has breathed fresh life
into industry competition, at Microsoft's expense.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has branded internal pre-merger documents gleaned by
the defense that purportedly show a fresh cabal being brewed
against Microsoft ``either ambiguous or cryptic.''
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that Jackson is ready to impose heavy
sanctions against the company or to insist that its Windows
operating system be spun off as a separate business.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft looks like a loser in the courtroom, its prospects
in the business world appear to be largely unaffected. Signals
coming from Microsoft chairman Bill Gates suggest that the future
remains bright no matter what happens here.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in recent months Microsoft has cut a $5 billion deal with
AT&AMP;T to get a major foothold in the cable modem business. It is
also planning to roll out a new version of its Web TV venture that
will upgrade the set-top boxes into powerful home automation
devices.
</P>
<P>
   While his lawyers argue in court that the company faces stiff
competition from new technology devices, Gates contends in a
current Newsweek article that personal computers, which depend
almost exclusively on his company's Windows operating system, will
remain the industry standard.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that Microsoft faces stiff competition from a new
generation of technology devices is intended to persuade the judge
that the high-tech industry is sufficiently robust despite
complaints about Microsoft's purported illegal conduct toward its
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Institute of Technology professor Franklin Fisher
spent the week seeking to demolish that argument.
</P>
<P>
   In three full days on the witness stand, Fisher, the chief
economic witness for the government, made three key points:
</P>
<P>
   _ Within the foreseeable future, computer hardware makers do not
believe they have any viable commercial alternatives to loading
Windows on the machines they are shipping to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Since any substantial increase in the price of Windows will
not prompt Microsoft's customers to switch to another operating
system, Microsoft is not constrained in any real way by the cost or
availability of other systems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Microsoft's market share for personal computer operating
systems has been both very high and quite stable for several years.
There's every reason to believe that it will stay that way for some
time to come.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers sought to stem the impact of Fisher's testimony
by suggesting in court that Microsoft, which enjoys a market
capitalization of some $650 billion, was on the ropes and likely to
falter under pressure from Linux, an upstart operating system, or
the rapid spread of ``smart'' pagers and other hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, to trying to make their case, they offered a
``confidential'' E-mail message between two top Microsoft
executives, Jim Allchin and David Cole that suggested ``Linux is
beating Windows'' in the retail market place. Although the judge
openly suggested the memo, dated May 25, was cooked up to make an
impact in court, he reluctantly allowed it to become a trial
exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
