<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-TROPICAL04-     06-03 1640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-TROPICAL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gardeners embrace tropics to supply bold color, texture
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Graceful palm branches sway and giant elephant's-ears
bob in the breeze as orange canna lilies stretch their stalks
daringly toward an unforgiving sun. Broad-leafed banana trees
provide a shady respite from the sultry afternoon, allowing red
impatiens to form a small meadow as thick as carpet.
</P>
<P>
   An exotic resort in San Juan? Lush retreat in Palm Springs?
Romantic terrace in South Beach?
</P>
<P>
   Hold on to your papayas _ it's an intown back yard right here in
Hotlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make it look like a tropical oasis that could be
anywhere,'' Glenn Powell said of the garden he and Mark White
developed two years ago in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   They're not alone. Gardeners throughout metro Atlanta are
discovering what's become a hot trend as far north as Canada:
Tropical plants give gardens the kind of splashy color, giant form
and bold texture that make them as inviting as a Caribbean travel
brochure.
</P>
<P>
   They just don't like being left out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   But even tropicals not hardy enough to withstand Atlanta winters
can be used as summer annuals _ planted in the spring and disposed
of in the fall. Or they can be moved inside and treated as
houseplants, which is how most tropicals traditionally are used.
</P>
<P>
   Because demand has grown so much in recent years, prices, which
are across the board, have come down. That makes the idea of
temporary plants affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers are cheaper right now than wholesalers, which are
selling out of them,'' said Dottie Myers, an Atlanta landscape
architect. ``Yet the average homeowner is still a little skeptical.
It's hard for them to think of throwing away a tropical as you
would impatiens at the end of the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners successfully ``overwinter'' the plants by taking
them inside until the following spring. But area horticulturists
say those plants typically get off to a slow start the next year
when most gardeners are anxious to set out established plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes so much for them to come out of dormancy that by the
time they're able to produce flowers in large fashion, it's the end
of the season,'' said Tyne Worley, manager of Planters, a Atlanta
garden center.
</P>
<P>
   What's so hot about them?
</P>
<P>
   So how come such tough plants, with their gigantic leaves and
billowing blossoms, are such wimps when it comes to a little cold?
</P>
<P>
   Tropicals are trees, shrubs, vines, perennials and annuals that
flourish in the belt between the tropics of Cancer and Capricorn,
which includes cool upland environments as well as hot, steamy
lowlands, according to Richard Iversen ``We've been growing them
for 500 years since Columbus' trip to the Caribbean,'' Iversen
said.
</P>
<P>
   During Victorian times, homeowners in Europe and America became
drawn to the exotic plants and brought palms, banana trees and
other tropicals indoors and used them as lawn accents. But not
until recent years have consumers accepted the notion that it's OK
to move their houseplants outdoors in summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so common in the interior plant industry. You see
them in airports, in restaurants,'' said Iversen, a professor who
oversees the Tropical Garden at the State University of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the interior environment, tropical plants are restrained
and stunted, like tigers caged in a zoo, and they aren't always
pretty. Free tropical plants from the constriction of the indoor
environment by planting them outdoors for the summer months, and
they are transformed like Cinderella,'' he writes. ``Common
houseplants become avant-garde garden plants, tall, strong and good
looking. Rains wash away last winter's dust, and light levels close
to those of their native tropic environment stimulate growth.
Plants grow fast, and in a single season these exotics are at their
peak of perfection, as if they were on some Caribbean island.''
</P>
<P>
   Paradise found
</P>
<P>
   Powell and White, who own Agnes &AMP; Muriel's restaurant, were
seeking a certain atmosphere when they designed their tropical
garden two years ago. Powell wanted something less fussy than a
perennial garden, and White, who once lived in Florida, knew
tropicals well.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my old house in Grant Park, I had the traditional English
cottage garden with all the roses I was diligent about caring
for,'' Powell said. ``When we moved here, I wanted something
totally different and relaxed. Here, it's like you're not even in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Their courtyard garden is an extension of the Spanish style
house they bought six years ago. Surrounding its Mexican-tiled
patio and pathway are windmill palms, banana trees, fatsia,
bromeliads, ferns and ``Bengal Tiger'' canna lilies, with their
variegated leaves and orange blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   One reason tropicals have become popular is their colors,
texture and forms are easy to combine for an attractive design.
Tropicals offer so many contrasts _ tall, broad ginger leaves
paired with low frilly ferns, hot pink mandevilla against light
salmon caladiums, spiky dracena rising from ruffled coleus _ the
design process becomes fun.
</P>
<P>
   Another selling point is their heat tolerance. In late summer
and early fall, when most annuals and perennials gasp their final
breaths, tropicals are in full swing.
</P>
<P>
   As the first frost approaches, some area gardeners dig up
non-hardy tropicals, including some varieties of bananas,
elephant's ears, alocasia and begonias, and store them in a
basement or garage to shield them from frigid temperatures. But
other plants, such as cannas and gingers, can be treated as
perennials, left in the ground and covered with mulch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't make yourself ill worrying about them when cold comes,''
Myers said. ``Enjoy them while they're here.''
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FOR TROPICALS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Go for contrasts in form and texture when combining them in
the garden. Pair the broad coarse leaves of bananas and elephant's
ears with the fine, soft foliage of coleus, for example.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mix tropicals with traditional garden plants. Loose foliage
plants such as daylilies and ornamental grasses make attractive
companions for big-leafed exotic plants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tropicals like loamy soil rich in organic matter. Add compost
before planting.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most houseplants are tropicals and can be planted in the
garden or outdoor containers in spring. First acclimate them to the
increased exposure by placing them on a porch or partial shade for
several days.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For planting ideas, see the new tropical border at the
entrance to the Atlanta Botanical Garden. There, the staff is
experimenting with perennials hardy to Atlanta's zone 7 climate,
including agapanthus (Lily-of-the-Nile), hedychium (ginger lily),
hibiscus, erythrina (coral bean) and zephyranthes (rain lily).
They're combined with new cultivars of annuals, such as coleus,
salvia, plumbago, colocasia and alocasia (elephant's ears) and Musa
(red pygmy banana).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One negative about tropicals is they don't begin to grow until
temperatures get hot. To prevent gaps in beds and borders, plant
spring-blooming perennials in front of tropicals, said Mildred
Pinnell, horticulturist at the Atlanta Botanical Garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tall tropicals such as bananas or stiff ones such as agave or
yucca can be used to create focal points in a garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tropicals are heavy drinkers and feeders. Give them a liquid
fertilizer every week or so in summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Treat tropicals not hardy to this area as annuals. But if you
want to try your hand at ``overwintering,'' Cheri Fox,
horticulturist at the Atlanta Botanical Garden, suggested digging
up the plant in fall, cutting back its foliage to a minimum and
placing the roots in a black plastic container with a potting mix
that drains well. Water it lightly and store in a garage, basement
or storage building. Water about once a month or so throughout
winter before replanting in spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most banana trees survive winters 22 degrees and higher, Fox
said. For one of the hardiest types, try the Musa basjoo, a native
to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   TROPICALS WORTH A TRY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Black elephant's-ear (Colocasia `Jet Black Wonder'): Large,
deep charcoal gray leaves. Combine with chartreuse foliage, such as
coleus, cannas or Margarita sweet potato vine. Considered hardy for
Zone 7 (Atlanta). (The Atlanta Botanical Garden overwinters its as
water plants.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Canna `Bengal Tiger': Green and yellow zebra-striped leaves
with deep orange flowers. Combine with purple or maroon coleus.
Hardy to Zone 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Canna `Tropicana': Intense purple leaves with green, yellow,
pink and red stripes with orange flowers. Combine with yellow
lantana. Hardy to Zone 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bloodleaf banana (Musa zebrina): Deep green leaves splashed
with burgundy splotches. Smaller than most bananas, it grows 6 to 8
feet. Not hardy in Zone 7, but many Atlantans are successful at
overwintering indoors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ginger lily (Hedychium): Bold, straplike foliage with
orchidlike, fragrant blossoms in a range of colors, from raspberry
to white. At 6 feet tall, they make a dense background screen.
Hardy to Zone 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Angel's trumpet (Brugmansia): Bold, textured leaves with
large, fragrant trumpet-shaped flowers. Great container plant. Not
hardy in Zone 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Strobilanthes `Persian Shield': Shimmering lilac, blue and
maroon leaves. Combine with yellow petunias or Margarita sweet
potato vine. Not hardy in Zone 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mandevilla: A vine with dark green foliage and pink blooms in
a range of shades. Great mailbox climber. Not hardy in Zone 7.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   ``Go Tropical!'' _ a tropical plants class
</P>
<P>
   Where: Atlanta Botanical Garden
</P>
<P>
   When: 7-9 p.m. Aug. 9,16
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $40 (20 percent discount for ABG members)
</P>
<P>
   Information: 404-876-5859
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
