<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An impoverished boyhood and lots of `Endurance' bring runner to
Atlanta, a gold medal and a movie
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some, watching ``Endurance'' will be an endurance test.
Others may be mesmerized by this unusual docudrama, which stars
small, wind-swift Olympic gold medalist Haile Gebrselassie as
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Leslie Woodhead introduces us to the athlete as
he preps for the 10,000-meter run at the 1996 Olympics (the
straightforward Atlanta race footage was shot by longtime Games
documentarian Bud Greenspan). Then the movie shifts to the life of
young Haile (played by Yonas Zergaw), struggling to survive within
his large family in rural Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
   His athletic career started by necessity: He had to run six
miles each way to school, and every day he trekked three hours to
fetch fresh water for the family. The movie also drifts through a
mass baptism ceremony in a Coptic church and a daylong picnic by
villagers in the shade of an ancient tree. Given its dreamy,
wordless sequences and tracking shots of the Ethiopian countryside,
it makes sense that one of the film's three producers is the
visually driven director Terrence Malick.
</P>
<P>
   The movie can verge at times on poverty-chic, exploiting the
family's Third World ``otherness'' as the camera explores the
texture of their mud-walled home. But it maintains a respectful
distance. Woodhead's decision to cast non-actors in the film often
results in self-conscious stiffness, but it also lends a sense of
legitimacy to the story.
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``Endurance'' comes full circle to the Atlanta
Olympics, it's impossible not to be inspired by the power and grace
of Gebrselassie and his fellow runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Endurance''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Haile Gebrselassie. Rated G. At metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A peculiar but engaging blend of travelogue,
docudrama and sports film.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
