A2032 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-INSTINCT04-COX     06-03 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-INSTINCT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not fit for man or beasts
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Halfway through ``Instinct,'' it happens: the Triumphant Robin
Williams Moment.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I call the hackneyed scene in a movie when the
eccentric hero inspires his students/patients/soldiers to revolt
against an oppressive authority figure. At the height of this
rebellion, the camera hones in on the principal/doctor/
</P>
<P>
   commander who's trying to keep Williams down. The outfoxed guy
shakes his head with begrudging admiration and gasps, ``Son of a
(beep).''
</P>
<P>
   This was effective when Jack Nicholson faced down Louise
Fletcher in ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.'' Then Williams
started repeating the same trick over and over. Now it's a prime
Hollywood cliche used to stir up fake feeling.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Instinct,'' the Williams stand-in is Anthony Hopkins,
slumming. He plays Dr. Ethan Powell, an anthropologist locked up in
a psychiatric prison surrounded by ``colorful'' inmates (a la
``Cuckoo's Nest''). It seems that, after living for months in the
company of gorillas in the African wilds (a la ``Gorillas in the
Mist''), he went berserk and killed two natives. Why? It's up to
psychiatry student Theo Caulder (Cuba Gooding Jr.) to pick his mind
(a la Hopkins' own ``The Silence of the Lambs'').
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers' instinct behind ``Instinct'' seems to be this:
If you cobble together elements from other successful movies, maybe
the resulting mess will make money. There's even a tearful
monologue by Gooding; it's well played by the Oscar winner, but
seems designed to tug in the male-weepy, ``Good Will Hunting''
contingent.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is based very loosely on Daniel Quinn's ``Ishmael,''
about a talking ape who maunders on about man's ecological
responsibilities. For better or worse, this isn't that story,
though Gerald Di Pego's screenplay includes simplistic jabber about
``civilized'' vs. ``primitive'' societies, which the book might
have inspired.
</P>
<P>
   It also has howl-provoking ``deep'' exchanges. ``You're free to
go,'' Gooding tells Hopkins at the end of one interview. The
prisoner sagely replies, ``Am I? You? Are you free?''
</P>
<P>
   It's all shameful, shameless, and not even a guilty pleasure.
It's just a guess, but gut instincts say ``Instinct'' is the movie
that made Hopkins announce his retirement from acting. I hope he
changes his mind. But after sitting through this twaddle, I don't
blame him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instinct''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Anthony Hopkins and Cuba Gooding Jr. Rated R for
intense violent behavior.
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Resist your instinct to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
