A2033 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-MASK04-COX     06-03 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-MASK04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love, respect are uncovered in `Masks'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bian Lian Wang (Zhu Xu) has a problem. He's a street performer
whose specialty is a quick-change routine involving elaborate cloth
masks. How he does it is a secret, one that tradition mandates he
pass on only to a male heir.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, he has no heirs of either sex. When Master Liang
(Zhao Zhigang), a famous female impersonator at the local opera
troupe, warns Wang, ``Don't let your magic die,'' the old man takes
it to heart. He goes to a sad clearinghouse for orphans and buys a
7-year-old lad named Doggie (Zhou Ren-Ying).
</P>
<P>
   Now stop reading here if you're afraid of spoilers, because
there's no way to write about ``The King of Masks'' without giving
away one plot twist.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Doggie is actually a girl in disguise. In the China of
1930, being a female is hardly more respectable than being, well, a
doggy. The child's own father is willing to sell her to a stranger
because, in his eyes, a girl is little more than a mouth to feed
and a dowry to raise. From his personal experience as a man
disguised as a woman, the drag diva Liang explains, ``No one values
girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Wang discovers Doggie's deception, the movie becomes a
study of the respect and grudging love that grow between the two.
Wu Tianming's drama has the shape of an old folk tale, infused with
contemporary criticism of the society's dismissal of women. Though
it suffers some lapses of sentimentality and melodrama, it's held
together by its emotional core. The movie's secret weapon is Zhou,
who despite her young age is a mesmerizing, fearless little
actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The King of Masks''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Zhu Xu and Zhou Ren-Ying. Unrated. In Mandarin with
English subtitles. At Toco Hills. 1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A charming fable about the growing bond between a
street performer and his adopted child.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
