<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-NYMPHS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tangled `Twilight' dusky with oddities
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the lavishly demented mind of Canadian filmmaker Guy Maddin
(``Tales From the Gimli Hospital,'' ``Careful'') comes another
plush cinematic whatsit called ``Twilight of the Ice Nymphs.''
</P>
<P>
   A purveyor of cheerful artifice, Maddin (working with a
screenplay by George Toles) shoots his latest fractured fairy tale
on woodland sets made misty by a constant shower of ostrich
feathers. Unfolding in the world of Mandragora, the movie follows
the lovelorn adventures of hunky Peter, torn between a mysterious
woman named Juliana (Pascale Bussieres) and a married temptress
named Zephyr (Alice Krige), who has prayed to an ancient statue of
Venus for Peter's love. (For the record, Peter is played by a
British actor who chose to have his name removed from the
production; his voice was redubbed by cast mate Ross McMillan.)
</P>
<P>
   The film also includes Shelley Duvall as Peter's sister, Frank
Gorshin as her disgruntled handyman and R.H. Thomson as the doctor
she loves, a sinister one-legged fellow who holds Juliana in his
thrall. Maddin presents his melodrama with a warped glee, sending
his characters spinning through a world of wonderland oddities. The
sun never sets here (the scenes glow with filtered orange light),
and Peter wakes up to the boom of his own rifle, realizing, ``I've
been sleep-hunting again!'' A seductress dresses her targeted hunk
in her own purple negligee and they make love, oblivious to the
rising tide that enters the room and floods their bed. A human
skull bites the hand that picks it up.
</P>
<P>
   A little of Maddin's cuckoo approach goes a long way. But if
you're looking for a unique screen vision, ``Twilight'' is a good
place to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twilight
</P>
<P>
   of the Ice Nymphs''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Pascale Bussieres and Alice Krige. Unrated. Through
Thursday at Cinefest (Georgia State University). 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   31 minutes. 404-651-2463.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An overstuffed Freudian fable from Canadian auteur
Guy Maddin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
