<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CORRUPTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO DENOUNCES CORRUPTION REPORTS ON EVE OF SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Stung by reports that two prominent figures here
are involved with drug traffickers, Mexico's government hoped the
allegations would not hurt a scheduled meeting Friday with senior
U.S. officials on money laundering, immigration and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the arrival of Attorney General Janet Reno, White
House drug policy adviser Barry McCaffrey and other ranking
officials, Mexican Foreign Relations Secretary Rosario Green said
she was ``profoundly irritated'' by the timing of the reports,
published this week in the New York Times, the El Financiero of
Mexico City and the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a U.S. government report, the Post and El Financiero
charged that Carlos Hank Gonzalez and his sons posed a threat to
the United States because of their connection with major drug
organizations. Hank is one of Mexico's wealthiest men and a ranking
member of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times, meanwhile, on reported Wednesday on U.S.
doubts about the 1997 Mexican investigation into money laundering
allegations against President Ernesto Zedillo's private secretary,
Liebano Saenz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am bothered by (this) strange coincidence on the eve of an
important meeting where important agreements may be signed,'' Green
told reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She blamed the reports on ``anti-Mexican sectors in the United
States that don't want a better relationship with Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Green also challenged the U.S. government to present proof
against Hank and Saenz.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's office and Attorney General Jorge Madrazo strongly
denied the contents of the two reports.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and McCaffrey are scheduled to meet their Mexican
counterparts in what is an ongoing effort for better cooperation on
topics affecting both nations, primarily drug trafficking and
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright canceled her visit because
of developments in the peace efforts in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings are also part of accords signed earlier this year
between President Clinton and Zedillo that aimed to strengthen
cooperation between neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Zedillo and President Clinton gave us important
instructions ... to be able to advance in this relationship,''
Green said. ``So we hope that in this binational meeting, the
results are a useful, amicable and important dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Saenz released a response to the New York Times
report. He said he launched the investigation to quell an anonymous
allegation about drug corruption and that nothing illegal was
found.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's office, meanwhile, said it closed the
probe because ``there was no crime to pursue.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Times report ``reproachful,'' Zedillo's press office
said Saenz was ``an outstanding public official due to his respect
of the law, honesty and loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegations against Hank, who has been a congressman, Mexico
City mayor and governor to the state of Mexico, are not new, but
they have never led to any charges and he has adamantly denied
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2052 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-MILITARY-750(2TAKE     06-03 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-MILITARY-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN UNION ANNOUNCES PLAN TO FORM A MILITARY FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ The leaders of 15 European countries decided
Thursday to make the European Union a military power for the first
time in its 42-year history, with command headquarters, staffs and
forces of its own for peacekeeping and peacemaking missions in
future crises like those in Kosovo or Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Long an economic giant, the European Union today has a common
currency, the euro, in 11 countries. But when it comes to foreign
and defense policy, Europe does not even have a telephone number,
as Henry Kissinger sarcastically observed 25 years ago when he was
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   All that will change by the end of next year, the 15 leaders
vowed.
</P>
<P>
   By late 2000, according to the plan announced at the European
Union summit meeting here, Europe could carry a big stick, a
60,000-strong, five-nation Eurocorps based in Strasbourg, France,
and have a soft-spoken foreign and security policy czar to speak
for it.
</P>
<P>
   That could be Javier Solana of Spain, now secretary general of
NATO, whose candidacy for the job was on the leaders' agenda here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union must have the capacity for autonomous action, backed
up by credible military forces, the means to decide to use them,
and a readiness to do so, in order to respond to international
crises without prejudice to actions by NATO,'' the European leaders
declared.
</P>
<P>
   They echoed language first used by President Jacques Chirac of
France and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain six months ago
after two crises in the Balkans showed how far Europe still had to
go to be taken seriously as a military power, even on its own
continent. Neither in Bosnia nor in Kosovo were European countries,
whose total armed forces exceed those of the United States in size,
able to project military power convincingly enough to halt the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, all 15 leaders agreed to absorb the functions of
the 10-nation Western European Union, a long-dormant European
defense alliance founded a year before NATO in 1948, and put it at
the disposal of the new, more assertive Europe that is taking shape
under the European Union. ``In that event,'' they said, ``the WEU
as an organization would have completed its purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   All 10 members of the WEU _ Britain, Belgium, France, Italy,
Spain, Portugal, Luxembourg, The Netherlands, Germany and Greece _
already belong to both NATO and the European Union. Denmark does,
too, but has only observer status in the smaller European defense
organization, as do four other European Union members, Austria,
Ireland, Finland and Sweden, which are neutral or nonaligned and do
not belong to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   These countries would be able to join future European Union
peacekeeping or peacemaking operations, but only if they wanted to,
the leaders agreed, saying they would also welcome participation by
other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   With Germany's unification in 1990 acting as a spur to its
neighbors to closer unity among themselves, the Treaty of European
Union, negotiated at the end of 1991, committed the Europeans to a
common currency and a common foreign and security policy and
defense policy, building on the common market they created in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   They reaffirmed those aspirations in another treaty signed in
1997, and succeeded in launching the euro at the start of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the common foreign and security policy sputtered along
through successive crises in the Balkans in which the Europeans
showed little unity or common purpose until the Americans sent in
armed forces to help them in Bosnia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany, Chirac, Blair and
the others are determined that Europe should be taken more
seriously on the world stage. Part of what is driving them, their
advisers say, is concern that the United States, with only 100,000
troops in Europe now compared with three times that many at the end
of the Cold War, will not indefinitely be willing to pull the fat
out of the fire for Europeans who have long since been rich enough
to provide for their own defenses.
</P>
<P>
   American diplomats have welcomed Europe's newfound willingness
to do more for itself. But they remain skeptical about whether
Europeans will actually be willing to spend the billions of dollars
it would take to build the stronger European defense pillar that
American defense secretaries for decades have been saying they
wanted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's declaration by European Union leaders makes clear
that they still have a lot of work ahead of them to create the kind
of military decision making and planning ability that NATO has had
for many years.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac suggested that the Western European Union's general staff
and military committee, both based in a small headquarters in the
center of Brussels some distance from NATO's, should be transferred
to the European Union and presided over by its new foreign and
security policy coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   If that turns out to be Solana, one senior U.S. official said,
``We would be very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Guenter Verheugen, a German government official who has also
been suggested for that job, said of the plan to strengthen
European defense, ``It is not a replacement for the Atlantic
partnership, but a significant and necessary complement to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders themselves also noted, ``The alliance remains the
foundation of the collective defense of its member states.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders agreed at their summit meeting in Washington in
April on detailed arrangements to lend military headquarters
organizations, multinational staffs, and tanks, helicopters and
other equipment to the Europeans if they decided to undertake
operations the United States prefers to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   But as Gen. Klaus Naumann of Germany said when he retired last
month as NATO's senior military officer, such arrangements exist
only on paper so far.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, when the NATO allies decided to use air power to try
to force the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, to accept a
settlement in Kosovo, only the United States had the ability to
throw hundreds of airplanes into the battle. And though the
European allies all support the air war, their total contribution
of 277 planes is dwarfed by the United States, which has committed
as many as 815 to the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Only the United States had the intelligence satellites and
precision-guided weapons the allies needed to mount a campaign with
minimum casualties to their own pilots, and only the United States
has invested in a fleet of large-capacity transport aircraft big
enough to fly in the 50,000 or more peacekeepers planned for
Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2055 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSTINCT-GOODING-TEX     06-03 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSTINCT-GOODING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODING MOVES PAST DIFFICULT CHILDHOOD TO A SPOT ON HOLLYWOOD'S
A-LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a Cuba Gooding Jr., so it follows that there's a Cuba
Gooding Sr. What you might not know is that both are in show biz.
</P>
<P>
   You probably know Cuba Gooding Jr. by name _ from his
breakthrough role in 1991's ``Boyz in the Hood,'' from his
ubiquitous four-word catch phrase (which we won't repeat here) from
``Jerry Maguire,'' from his ebullient Oscar-night acceptance speech
for his ``Maguire'' role. You may even know that he's co-starring
with Anthony Hopkins in ``Instinct,'' a new psychological drama
that's opening Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you know Cuba Gooding Sr., you probably know him by voice _
and it helps to be a fan of early-'70s soul music. He was the lead
singer of the Main Ingredient, the sweet tenor behind such hits as
``Just Don't Want to Be Lonely'' and ``Everybody Plays the Fool.''
</P>
<P>
   And, like his son, he's an actor _ he was recently cast in two
movies. And that's caused some confusion, as Cuba Gooding Jr.
explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad calls me up, all upset,'' the younger Gooding says
during a Dallas visit. ``I go, `What's goin' on?' He goes, `I gotta
fax you over this form. You gotta sign it.' I said, `Yeah, yeah,
tell me, what's it for?' `Well, Screen Actors Guild says since I
got cast in these movies, I gotta have a credit release.' I said,
`What does that mean?' He says, `You gotta say I can use my own
name in this movie 'cause you're Cuba Gooding Jr. and I'm Cuba
Gooding, but it was my name first!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Cuba Gooding Jr. punctuates this story with a
loud, thigh-slapping laugh, one of several that he lets loose as he
and ``Instinct'' director Jon Turteltaub chat. At times during the
interview, Gooding seems subdued, even pensive, until he bursts out
laughing or slips into a rambunctious impersonation, including one
of Paul Newman that involves standing on a coffee table at The
Mansion on Turtle Creek.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Instinct,'' Gooding is much more restrained. He plays Theo
Caulder, a buttoned-down psychiatric resident who takes on the task
of tapping into the mind of primatologist Ethan Powell (Hopkins),
who apparently went mad and killed two people in Africa. Theo must
contend with Powell and the brutal snake-pit of a prison where
Powell is being held. Many scenes involve only Gooding and Hopkins,
in a game of psychological one-upmanship that at one point has
Hopkins' character slapping a piece of dirty duct tape over
Gooding's mouth and threatening to kill him. Gooding wore the duct
tape for most of the two days it took to film that scene.
</P>
<P>
   But that discomfort is minor compared with some of the
difficulties Gooding went through before becoming a star. In 1974,
the elder Gooding split from the family (Cuba Jr. was 6). The
family saw little of the money from the Main Ingredient hits, and
mother and children lived a nearly homeless existence, drifting
from motel to motel in the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding's mother kept the family close, reading the Bible to her
children every night. According to some reports, Gooding became a
born-again Christian at age 13, but Gooding says that happened
earlier, around the time he was in the fourth grade. He's not as
devout now, but he says God still plays a big role in his life and
in the raising of his sons, 4-year-old Spencer and 2-year-old
Mason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an ideal Christian by any means, but my kids go to
Sunday school,'' Gooding says. ``And I pray with them; we pray at
dinnertime and we pray before we go to bed every night. I just try
to keep a base in it, but maybe not as big a presence as maybe a
devout Christian would.''
</P>
<P>
   The constant moving gave Gooding a sense of rootlessness,
however; he attended a different school every year from eighth to
11th grade. By the time he was a junior at Kennedy High School in
the Northridge/Granada Hills area north of Los Angeles, he was
adamant that he wouldn't move to another school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom got a job, so we moved to another hotel in north
Hollywood, and I refused to stop going to that school,'' Gooding
says. ``And then that summer, I still kept taking the bus to a job
in Northridge. It was insane, and I finally just gave in and said,
`I'll graduate from North Hollywood,' and thank God I did. That's
where I met my agent. It was God's will.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooding had a small role in John Landis' 1988 comedy ``Coming to
America,'' but his breakthrough came in 1991's ``Boyz in the
Hood,'' in which he played a young man struggling to get out of his
troubled LA neighborhood. He then appeared in movies both
respectable (''A Few Good Men,'' ``Outbreak'') and
not-so-respectable (''Hitz,'' ``Gladiator''), but he hit the next
level when he played a brash but loyal pro football player in
``Jerry Maguire,'' for which he won the Best Supporting Actor
Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Maguire,'' he has become an A-list actor, appearing with
Jack Nicholson (''As Good as It Gets''), Robin Williams (''What
Dreams May Come''), and now Hopkins, as if he had joined some sort
of club for movies starring two Oscar-winners.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding's Oscar win was not only the last to date for an
African-American actor, it was the last time a black actor was
nominated for an Academy Award. Oscar's snubbing of
African-American actors has caused some controversy during recent
years, but few of Gooding's roles have called specifically for
someone black. Although he agrees that the choices for black actors
are limited, he believes that many of the problems come after a
black actor is cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely an opinion among filmmakers that, if a
black man is onscreen, it brings up a point if he has to kiss a
white woman ... it takes away from the story,'' Gooding says. ``And
that's probably reflective on today's society. To have a black man
carry your film, that raises different questions. So I'm always
looking to push that envelope as far as possible until pretty soon
it's not as much of an issue, at least when it comes to casting me.
Because I am a black actor.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Turteltaub resisted developing a love story involving
Gooding and Maura Tierney (''NewsRadio''), who plays Hopkins'
estranged daughter. But Turteltaub says that was less about the
black-and-white issue than it was about letting any romance creep
into the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Gooding was rumored to have been cast in a role that definitely
would have required a black actor: '60s soul singer Otis Redding,
in a Joe Eszterhas project called ``Blaze of Glory.'' But Gooding
says that the project never got out of the discussion stage. He
also says that budget problems derailed a Martin Luther King
project that he was working on with Oliver Stone.
</P>
<P>
   But although he's had professional disappointments, life
offscreen has become better for Gooding. His parents reconciled a
couple of years ago, and his father is singing again, doing well on
the nightclub and package-tour circuits. Even those years of living
in hotels resulted in some lasting connections for Gooding,
including his personal assistant, Shawn Shuttles, whom he met in
one of those hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said on the set of (the upcoming) `Chill Factor,' `Isn't it
funny, Shawn? All our life, we've been living in hotels, going,
`One day, we're gonna be rich and famous.' And here we are _ living
in hotels.'''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2058 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      06-03 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AND MILOSEVIC BOTH COMPROMISE TO REACH PEACE PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 A News Analysis  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S.-led western alliance won the agreement of
defiant Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic Thursday to halt the
ouster of ethnic Albanian Muslims from Kosovo, achieving the
central demand of NATO's 11-week bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of a compromise European-sponsored peace plan
approved by Milosevic and the Serbian parliament in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia also agreed to withdraw Yugoslav troops from Kosovo and
allow an estimated 1.4 million displaced Kosovo refugees to return
to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   To win those concessions from Milosevic, President Clinton and
the 19-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization gave in to
Yugoslav demands for the United Nations to supervise post-war
Kosovo, for the allies to reaffirm Yugoslav sovereignty over Kosovo
and for hundreds of Serbian troops to eventually return to Kosovo
at key border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   The concessions were designed to obtain Russia's cooperation and
Milosevic's approval of a plan to end a grinding bombing campaign
that has tested allied unity, eroded public support and raised the
specter that the allies would launch a grueling ground war. The
next step will be a cease fire by Yugoslav forces in Kosovo,
followed by a halt to NATO's bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The one-page peace plan _ consisting of 12 points _ was approved
by Milosevic and the Yugoslav parliament. It calls for Yugoslavia
to:
</P>
<P>
   _ End violence and repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Withdraw all military, police and paramilitary forces within
seven days of the agreement's implementation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Accept deployment of an international security force in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Permit the ``safe and free return of all refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-recalcitrant Yugloslav leader also accepted the demand
that he take part in a political process designed to provide
autonomy and self-government within Yugoslav territory to ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the peace deal leaves the Yugoslav dictator plenty of room
for face saving. The compromise:
</P>
<P>
   _ Responds to Milosevic's demand that the United Nations _ not
NATO _ take the lead in establishing peace in Kosovo, by calling
for deployment of an ``efficient international civilian and
security'' presence in Kosovo ``under U.N. auspices.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Fails to require Milosevic or his government to cooperate with
an international war crimes tribunal in the Hague, Netherlands,
that has indicted him for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Acknowledges Yugoslav territorial integrity and abandons a
proposal to have a referendum in Kosovo to fashion provincial
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Commits the allies to disarming both Albanian secessionists
and Serbian paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Permits hundreds of Serbian forces to return to Kosovo to
serve as liaisons with the international security force, identify
and potentially clear mine fields and maintain a presence ``at
places of Serb heritage'' and ``at key border crossings.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said that the European
plan reflected the key conditions laid down by the White House and
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The peace plan is ``something that NATO, the United States and
the (European Union) were comfortable with,'' Lockhart said. ``It's
something that was consistent with what NATO has articulated. It's
consistent with what our views are.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladislav Jovanovic, Yugoslavia's charge d'affairs at the United
Nations, said the 12-point blueprint crafted by Finnish President
Martti Ahtisaari and Viktor Chernomyrdin, the former prime minister
of Russia, was ``a compromise'' that responds to many of Belgrade's
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an agreement which addresses many needs and
accommodates many people,'' Jovanovic said. The allies ``have
accepted the United Nations as the sole international body
authorized to deal with peace and security.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing the United Nations into the mix gives Yugoslavia
greater opportunity to influence the tedious diplomatic and
on-the-ground military maneuvering that will accompany day-to-day
implementation of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has close ties to both Russia and China _ nations
that have veto power on the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Russia shares Slavic and Orthodox Christian ties with Yugoslavia
dating back centuries, as well as wariness about unilateral
military action by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The European plan also confronts the United States and Russia
with ticklish negotiations over the command structure on the ground
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has long stipulated that NATO troops serve
``at the core'' of the international security force, with a
``unified'' military command under NATO. That translates into
having Gen. Wesley Clark, the U.S. Army four-star general and NATO
military commander, ultimately commanding the operation.
</P>
<P>
   But the European plan only calls for ``an essential NATO
participation'' _ an ill-defined arrangement that sets the stage
for an independent role for Russian commanders and Russian troops
in Serbian-controlled sectors of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who worked with
European leaders to craft a European peace plan, said the United
States and Russia will continue efforts to agree on a command
structure for the Kosovo security force.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Milosevic's acceptance of the European peace plan
heralds the onset of a new phase of wrangling rather than the end
of disagreements that led to war.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Collins, a senior fellow in political-military studies at
the Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington,
D.C., said there remains plenty of room for tedious
misunderstandings that will fall short of galvanizing the NATO
alliance to resume the largest air campaign since the 1991 Persian
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said that ``significant details'' remain to be worked
out, including the composition of the peace enforcement force,
coordination of troop withdrawals and the relationship between NATO
and the United Nations on the supervision of the peacekeeping
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, a long-term peace enforcement operation will be a
mixed blessing for U.S. and NATO forces, which will have to face
land mines, hostile Serbs, aggrieved Kosovars, and a potentially
uncooperative Kosovo Liberation Army,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
