</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIO-POLLUTION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIO DE JANEIRO'S IMAGE TARNISHED AS BEACHES ARE SOILED WITH
SEWAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ To the 6.5 million people who live in
Rio, Copacabana and Ipanema are not merely beaches, but also the
soul and main calling card of this city.
</P>
<P>
   But along miles of shoreline where multitudes normally frolic,
the vista has been dominated in recent weeks by big red thumbs-down
emblems and signs warning that the water is ``inappropriate for
swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, part of a sewer line serving some of Rio's most
fashionable neighborhoods collapsed, forcing the government to dump
tons of raw sewage close to shore while repairs were done out at
sea.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been foul smells wafting in the air, beaches
closed because of pollution, general indignation _ and a body blow
to Rio's self-image as ``the marvelous city.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its fame as an international playground, Rio faces most
of the same problems as any other global metropolis: crime, noise,
overcrowding, inadequate transport. But Cariocas, as residents of
Rio are known, have traditionally regarded the city's beaches as
both a sanctuary from those difficulties and an eminently public
gathering place, the local equivalent of what the Agora was to
ancient Athens or Central Park is to Manhattanites.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Brazil, democracy begins on the beaches of Rio,'' said Joao
Fontes, president of the Leblon Residents' Association, a civic
group in the neighborhood adjoining Ipanema that has led protests
against the high levels of bacteria caused by the sewage dumping.
``The beach is the one place where a banker and a doorman can meet
on the same footing, where a maid may shine brighter than the rich
woman who employs her.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting culture of tolerance has been a magnet that
attracts not just foreign tourists, but also Brazilians of every
class from every corner of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the untreated waste being dumped close to shore, in
fact, was generated by a pair of large favelas, or hillside
squatter settlements, that overlook the chic Southern Zone
neighborhoods and have grown rapidly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absurd situation,'' said Afonso Rodrigues, an engineer
who is a member of a group that, until the onset of the sewage
crisis, met every Sunday to play volleyball on Ipanema beach.
``You've got people paying $200 a square foot to live in apartments
on the seafront, and they can't even use the beach because of this
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Rio Mayor Luiz Paulo Conde pointed out in an interview that the
sewage system is a responsibility not of the city but of the state
of Rio de Janeiro, which is immersed in a severe budget crisis. But
he acknowledged that ``when the city has a problem, the citizens
don't want to know if it's the city or the state that is in charge,
they just want a quick solution.''
</P>
<P>
   State authorities say that after a series of delays and mishaps,
the flow of waste has finally been brought under control, with no
permanent damage to the environment. Fontes and scientists
affiliated with his group contend, however, that sand on the
beaches remains contaminated and that offshore fishing continues to
be affected.
</P>
<P>
   But to others here, the sewage crisis and the debate
accompanying it are a reflection of a more fundamental civic
malaise. Having in recent years been deprived of the national
dominance it enjoyed throughout most of Brazilian history, Rio
today is a city in search of an identity suitable to its diminished
status.
</P>
<P>
   Political power in this nation of 165 million people has clearly
shifted to Brasilia, which formally replaced Rio as the nation's
capital nearly 40 years ago, controls the government purse strings
and is less sympathetic to Rio's needs than in the days when
legislators all had apartments here.
</P>
<P>
   On the business side, Sao Paulo, this city's traditional rival,
is now Brazil's undisputed economic powerhouse, brimming with the
confidence that come with that clout.
</P>
<P>
   So while Rio was suffering the indignity of being unable to use
its most famous beaches, an investment group in Sao Paulo announced
plans to build the world's tallest building there.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to another difference that rankles, Frederico Lacerda,
an engineer who is also part of the Ipanema volleyball group, said,
``Construction of our subway system is stalled because of budgetary
and political problems, while it seems that every month a new
station or line opens over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Conde did not dispute the shift in the balance of power, saying
``our vision is not one of competition'' with Sao Paulo, but also
said it did not mean Rio had lost any of the luster that made it a
great city. As he sees it, his city is becoming to Brazil what New
York City is to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the capital but it is the capital,'' he said.
``Brazil was civilized from Rio de Janeiro, and Rio will continue
to be a one-of-a-kind place where customs, food and music are
created, open to the world and symbolizing Brazil and its culture
in a way that Sao Paulo cannot.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in countless other ways large and small, Cariocas are
constantly being reminded that there may be something to the
traditional Paulista gibe that Rio is ``nothing more than a
decaying seaside resort.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's airlines, for instance, have made Sao Paulo, rather
than Rio, their hub for most regional and international flights,
which adds to travel time for people living here. Even television
programming has recently begun to take on a Sao Paulo flavor.
</P>
<P>
   In his column in Jornal do Brasil, Artur Xexeo complained in May
of what he called ``the fashion to kowtow to Sao Paulo.'' In the
past ``slang, style and everything else was exported from Rio by
television,'' he said, but national broadcasts now ``all of a
sudden have begun to use expressions that sound really peculiar to
the Carioca ear'' because they are typical of Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've won the war,'' Xexeo concluded, because Sao Paulo ``is
where the money is.'' But he took consolation in noting that the
most popular television soap operas continue to be made here,
proving that while ``Rio may not have money and may provoke the
disdain of the advertising market, it is still the most photogenic
city in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, there was much celebration locally when Hebe
Camargo, the hostess of a popular television talk show and a
dyed-in-the wool Paulista, announced at the height of the sewage
crisis that she was moving here.
</P>
<P>
   Sao Paulo, she said, has become too violent, crowded and badly
governed for a civilized person to enjoy, and besides, she had
belatedly discovered that ``I love Rio and I love Cariocas and the
affectionate way they treat visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Civic boosters here take such developments as a sign of Rio's
inherent moral superiority, despite the sewage problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sao Paulo has a mercantilistic view of life, but life is not
just made of material progress,'' said Artur da Tavola, author of
the book ``Rio: A Look of Love'' and a federal Senator who
represents the state of Rio de Janeiro. ``It also consists of
spiritual and esthetic progress, and Rio has an abundance of those
characteristics.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a table a few yards from the shore of Ipanema beach,
drinking from chilled coconuts and bottles of beer, Lacerda and his
friends agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Paulistas may make all their money over in Sao Paulo,'' he
said. ``But they still come here to spend it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
