<HEADLINE>
IN ROUND SIX, CALIFORNIA STUDENT HITS A BAD SPELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sean Conley of Newark, Calif., barreled his way
through five rounds of the 72nd National Spelling Bee here Thursday
before tripping up on the word ``coreopsis'' in round six.
</P>
<P>
   When the bee's pronouncer, who is one of the contest judges,
said the word, Sean, 11, who is home-schooled, stared straight
ahead and asked for the word's origin. The answer: Greek.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting a moment, he asked for all pronunciations of the word.
Then, still gazing into a mid-distance, he asked for the word's
definition. A coreopsis refers to any of a genus of flowering
herbs. Finally Sean repeated the word and spelled it
C-H-O-R-E-O-P-S-I-S.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``h'' was wrong, and a bell sounded, announcing the
error to the assemblage of contestants and their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Sean coolly walked off the stage to the so-called ``comfort
room,'' where some losing contestants struggle to regain their
composure. But he didn't seem to struggle at all, emerging quickly
and watching the few remaining contestants compete in a ballroom of
the Grand Hyatt Hotel here.
</P>
<P>
   Sean, who attends classes run by Tri-City Homeschoolers in
Newark, was quickly surrounded by his parents, Mike Conley, a
software engineer for Apple Computers Inc., and Bryanne Conley, a
teacher at Tri-City. His younger brothers, Devin, 9, and Alden, 4,
also greeted him.
</P>
<P>
   Sean said he never felt nervous on the ballroom stage. ``I
wasn't worried because I didn't think I was going to win,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he did tie for ninth place in the competition. Sponsored by
the San Francisco Examiner, Sean and his family received a free
trip to Washington, and he will take home a prize of $200 and a
commemorative watch.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't know what to spend the money on, but he
insisted: ``It's not going to be on study aids for spelling.'' He
also plays the piano, studies karate and competes in math contests
and chess tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   After the competition, Sean and his family met with their
congressman, Rep. Fortney ``Pete'' Stark, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The national bee's winner was Nupur Lala, 14, of Tampa, Fla.
Nupur, an eighth grader at Louis Benito Middle School there, won
after 11 rounds by correctly spelled ``nocicepter,'' which is
something that causes harm, and then an extra word, ``logorrhea,''
which means incoherent talkativeness, Lupur, who was eliminated in
the third round of last year's bee, jumped in the air and screamed
when she learned of her victory this year. She will receive the
$10,000 first-place prize, plus encyclopedias, two airline tickets
and computer software.
</P>
<P>
   Scripps Howard newspapers, based in Cincinnati, coordinates the
National Spelling Bee finals and produces the word lists and study
materials.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
