<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INSTINCT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INSTINCT' FAILS IN ATTEMPT TO MAKE A SOCIO-ENVIRONMENTAL
STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So few big-budget Hollywood movies even try to make an
environmental statement in the process of entertaining us that you
sort of hate to jump on one that does.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney's ``Instinct'' is basically a mess. It's well-acted
by a likable cast and is well-intended, but it misses: It doesn't
come off as the powerful socio-environmental statement it wants to
be.
</P>
<P>
   It is about a yuppie Miami psychiatrist (Cuba Gooding Jr.)
involved in the strange case of a renegade anthropologist (Sir
Anthony Hopkins) who went out of his mind in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   While in the midst of a long-term project studying the mountain
gorillas of Rwanda, it seems the good doctor suddenly and
inexplicably went berserk and killed several park rangers.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly what happened, and the man can't or won't
speak, but he's been convicted of murder and sent back to the
States to be incarcerated in the criminally insane ward of a
Florida state prison.
</P>
<P>
   The script follows the ambitious young shrink _ who thinks he
can get a best seller out of the case _ as he breaks down the
patient's resistance, gains his confidence and, in stages, learns
what happened (which we see in flashbacks).
</P>
<P>
   It's an ambitious movie that's part ``Spellbound'' psychiatric
detective story, part ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' snake-pit
drama, and part ``Gorillas in the Mist'' environmental parable _
but ultimately it fails to click as any of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins and Gooding give their usual earnest, strong
performances and develop a workable chemistry. But the script, and
Jon Turteltaub's unfocused direction, never allow their
performances to make a devastating emotional point.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the audience is way ahead of the hero in figuring out why
the gorilla-loving doctor killed those park rangers. So we wait the
entire movie for an inevitable environmental atrocity that we just
don't want to see.
</P>
<P>
   Instinct. Directed by Jon Turteltaub. Screenplay by Gerald
DiPego. Cast: Anthony Hopkins, Cuba Gooding Jr., Donald Sutherland,
Maura Tierney. Touchstone. 120 minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SAYLES-SPI &LR;      06-03 1649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SAYLES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN SAYLES AN INDEPENDENT FILMMAKER IN EVERY SENSE OF THE TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Steven Spielberg may be more financially successful
and Martin Scorsese may be more critically acclaimed, but no
director of the generation that has dominated American filmmaking
for the past 20 years is more universally admired than John Sayles.
</P>
<P>
   The even-dozen films he's made since 1980 have made his name
virtually synonymous with filmmaking integrity and independence,
and so many hundreds of young filmmakers have been inspired by his
example that he's truly the Godfather of the American Independent
Film Movement.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, his 12th film, ``Limbo,'' begins its national
theatrical run following its U.S. premiere in the 25th Seattle
International Film Festival, where his career was also honored with
a special in-person tribute, ``An Evening With John Sayles.''
</P>
<P>
   As I sat down to lunch with him earlier that day, I asked him if
it felt a little strange, receiving what amounts to a career
achievement award when he was still more than a year shy of his
50th birthday. Isn't it a bit like attending your own funeral?
</P>
<P>
   A tall, lanky man who _ except for some gray around his temples
_ looks almost exactly as he did the first time he came to Seattle
in 1980 hawking a little film called ``Return of the Secaucus
Seven,'' Sayles conceded there is something slightly ``unsettling''
about the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always that quality about a tribute, isn't there? It
assumes your best is behind you. I guess if I let myself think
about it very hard, or took it seriously, it might be intimidating.
But I just take it as a compliment, and let it go at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's been quite a career. In the '80s, he followed up
``Secaucus'' with a lesbian love story (``Lianna''), a college
romance (``Baby, It's You''), a sci-fi meditation on race relations
(``Brother From Another Planet''), an epic about the American labor
movement (``Matewan'') and a drama about the Black Sox baseball
scandal (``Eight Men Out'').
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s, he made an inner-city political drama (``City of
Hope''), a woman's buddy movie (``Passion Fish''), an Irish fairy
tale (``The Secret of Roan Inish''), a murder mystery set on the
Texas border (``Lone Star''), a Spanish-language political drama
(``Men With Guns'') and a Conradian survival story set in Alaska
(``Limbo'').
</P>
<P>
   Each has been a highly personal film with weighty themes done in
a different style with name actors and Hollywood-class production
values; each has been produced outside the studio system (even if
some were financed by studios); each has been, in some way, better
than the last. How has he managed such a feat?
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick to having a movie career is in not losing money. You
can almost always make another film if your last one made a little
money. So I make low-budget movies. `Limbo' was studio-financed
(Sony) but the budget was only $8 million. The studio probably
can't even remember the last time it released a movie that cost
them so little.''
</P>
<P>
   He also credits his creative longevity with the fact that _
unlike the normal, super-stressful, heart-attack-inducing Hollywood
filmmaking ordeal _ making a film is, for him, ``almost always a
good experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I not only work with people I respect, but with people that I
like. That seems to make a big difference,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles has, in fact, achieved a filmmaking stability that has
few precedents in the modern era. He displays none of the symbols
of movie success. He still lives in Hoboken, N.J., and on his farm
in Upstate New York. He works with the same actors and technicians
again and again. Both ``Secaucus'' (1980) and ``Limbo'' (1999) have
the same producer (longtime companion Maggie Renzi) and star (David
Strathairn).
</P>
<P>
   Another big factor in the Sayles success story _ and one about
which he is less forthcoming _ is that he has made himself the real
``star'' of his pictures. A bit of a ham, he frequently appears in
his own and in other directors' films, and a publicist who handled
one of the earlier films in the '90s told me, ``John never turns
down an interview _ no matter how small the publication.''
</P>
<P>
   When I asked him about this, he admitted that he did ``somewhere
between 200 and 300 interviews'' for every film he makes, ``and
often deal with a movie I made several years ago, which might just
be opening in Japan or somewhere.'' But he smarted at my suggestion
that he might do it out of some personal vanity. ``I really don't
have any choice,'' he said. ``It's something I have to do. My films
don't get national TV advertising. So I fight for every bit of
attention I can get.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be necessary for his survival, but this amazing
visibility has also helped make him almost as instantly
recognizable a figure to his movie-going generation as Hitchcock
was to an earlier one. And it's helped him create what is
undeniably his greatest asset as an independent filmmaker: his
covenant with his audience. ``John is a great salesman for his
films,'' actress Alfre Woodard once said. ``The honesty of his
films is also evident in his personality. People instinctively
trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   But if this makes Sayles sound like some shrewd movie huckster,
the truth is that he genuinely likes people, and enjoys the
exposure of interviews, festival appearances and public readings as
a relief from the hours, days and months he spends each year cut
off from people. ``I spend an awfully lot of my time just sitting
in front of my word-processor,'' he said. ``The collaborative part
is much more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if there is any one factor that distinguishes Sayles
from his filmmaking contemporaries, and has made his career unique
in his generation, it is the fact that he is, by nature, much more
of a literary than a film person. The author of numerous articles,
novels (including the National Book Award-nominated ``Union Dues'')
and short story collections, he approaches the filmmaking process,
he once said, ``as Dickens approaches the writing of a novel.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not an amateur film historian, he's never been a film nerd
in the sense of Spielberg or Scorsese, and he freely admits he
``doesn't see that many movies _ though I do tend to catch up at
the end of the year, when they send all those tapes to Academy
members for (Oscar) consideration.'' During a lull in our lunch
conversation, he looked at his watch and rather eagerly asked the
publicist, ``Say, where's a good bookstore in Seattle?''
</P>
<P>
   While his contemporaries are thinking in terms of daring camera
angles or showy sequences that wink at ``The Battleship Potemkin,''
Sayles is invariably struggling with how to tell a particular story
that has captured him. ``Usually an idea just comes to me out of
nowhere, and shapes itself into a story and just won't let me go,
and I think, `What is the best way for me to get rid of this
thing?'
</P>
<P>
   `Limbo' is a good example. It started with the concept of a
fisherman who was the sole survivor of a ship that went down _
which was a true story that someone told me. The idea of this
character feeling responsibility for what happened, and needing
redemption _ naturally got me thinking of (Joseph) Conrad, who I
love. For a while I thought of doing a Conrad story, but decided
that it's impossible to translate him to a modern setting _ at
least I've never seen it done ... His rhythm is somehow too tied to
his own era.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the idea kept working on me, and developed along the lines
of `how people take risks in their lives,' so that I finally had
the characters and story but no (setting). Gradually, I thought of
Alaska, where I'd attended a conference about 10 years ago and
which had seemed to me a place where people go to make a fresh
start. It's also a place in some cultural transition. So it finally
dawned on me that it was a good place to tell this particular story
and give it added depth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayles is also a writer who thinks of storytelling more in terms
of character than in plot and action. When I asked him about the
film's puzzling ending, his eyes glassed over and he seemed
disinterested. But when I asked him about the complex relationship
between the mother and daughter characters, he went into an excited
analysis _ clearly he had thought about it a great deal, and
enjoyed verbalizing it _ to the point that it took up a full 10
minutes on my tape.
</P>
<P>
   Critic Roger Ebert, a long-time Sayles fan, has said that, as
much as any filmmaker who has ever lived, Sayles has educated
himself about the ``business'' of film _ financing, production, the
media game _ and used it to customize a career that is a perfect
reflection of himself: his unique literary gifts, his maverick
temperament and a world-view that is, in its heart, both highly
practical and as idealistic as the '60s characters of his ``Return
of the Secaucus Seven.''
</P>
<P>
   Still and all, you have to wonder. Why, as he edges the
half-century mark, does he keep doing it? After the success of
``Lone Star'' in 1996, he could have cut a deal with any studio in
Hollywood on his own terms. He could be collecting $10 million fees
making $100 million epics.
</P>
<P>
   Why is he still beating himself to death doing one-hour
interviews with the Ballard (Wash.) Journal and scrapping together
financing for films that will never play the multiplexes of South
Carolina? Isn't he tired of the sheer grind of this process he's
developed for himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very tired. But I do what I do to make the kind of films I
need to make. As (grueling) as it is, it allows me to be as
independent as any filmmaker can reasonably expect to be, and still
have his films seen by a reasonably large number of people. If you
know a better way to reach that end, I'd sure be happy to hear
about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
