<HEADLINE>
`LIMBO' A TERRIFIC LITTLE GENRE THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Sayles' most endearing quality as a filmmaker may be his
sheer unpredictability. You just never know if the guy's going to
come up with a lesbian romance, an Irish children's story, a slice
of contemporary Texas life, or a Spanish-language drama filmed in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   His 12th and latest effort, ``Limbo,'' is yet another huge
geographic and thematic change-of-pace: a moody adventure story set
in Alaska that resonates with environmental undertones and is
filled with delicate character studies, but ends up being a
terrific little genre thriller.
</P>
<P>
   After an opening that establishes an ensemble of small-town
characters and the state of the State, Sayles gradually focuses on
the emerging love story between Donna (Mary Elizabeth
Mastrantonio), a touring saloon singer, and Joe (David Strathairn),
a native Alaskan handyman/ex-fisherman with a past.
</P>
<P>
   When the pair go out on a yacht with Donna's teenage daughter,
Noelle (Vanessa Martinez) and Joe's bad-boy half-brother (Casey
Siemaszko), they're attacked by pirates, and Joe, Donna and Noelle
swim through the icy waters to the safety of a deserted island.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the movie is a survival story as the makeshift
family is stranded (in limbo, hence the title), with little hope of
rescue, menaced by murderous drug runners, and living in a
dilapidated, abandoned homestead that seems to be haunted by the
spirits of its former occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Some moviegoers will find this film a little too structurally
jagged and open-ended for complete dramatic satisfaction, and
Sayles' legion of fans will probably find it not quite up to the
Olympian standard of ``Lone Star'' (the 1996 film that seems
destined to be regarded as Sayles' masterpiece).
</P>
<P>
   But it's still one of the director's more successful films: an
expert piece of movie craftsmanship that allows us to completely
identify with its characters, and works as a gripping psychological
drama, an eye-filling outdoor adventure and a nail-biting suspense
piece.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Sayles also makes the most of his cast: Mastrantonio
gives her career-best performance as the existential-minded
vocalist; Strathairn has never been more appealing or believable as
a Gary Cooper-ish man of the outdoors; and Martinez is the
embodiment of raging hormones and teenage neurosis.
</P>
<P>
   Working once again with legionary cameraman Haskell Wexler,
Sayles has also captured what may be the movies' eeriest evocation
of Alaska _ a land of economic opportunity, crass exploitation and
a natural environment that's as malevolent and threatening as
anything in a Joseph Conrad novel.
</P>
<P>
   Limbo. Directed, written and edited by John Sayles. Cast: Mary
Elizabeth Mastrantonio, David Strathairn, Vanessa Martinez, Kris
Kristofferson, Casey Siemaszko. Sony Pictures. 126 minutes. Rated R
for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
