<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WANT-YOU-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I WANT YOU' AS UNSETTLING, BLEAK AS OTHER WORKS BY MICHAEL
WINTERBOTTOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Winterbottom is one of Britain's best young moviemakers.
He ventures into the heart's darkest places and finds compassion
and grace in human frailty and errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Butterfly Kiss'' was a slap-in-the-face film full of extremes
that came to a touching conclusion with its violent means to an
end. ``Jude,'' based upon Thomas Hardy's depressing novel,
followed. And Winterbottom found a wider audience with ``Welcome to
Sarajevo.''
</P>
<P>
   We've not seen all of Winterbottom's films in America _ ``Go
Now'' did just that and he has a new film, ``Wonderland,'' that
received praise at the recent Cannes Film Festival. ``I Want You''
was made somewhere in between and has won a regular run here after
playing in the Emerging Masters series of this year's Seattle
International Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   It has much in common with Winterbottom's other films _ it's as
unsettling and bleak as the rest of his resume and contains some
breathtaking imagery and Super 35 shots that are innovative and
daring experiments.
</P>
<P>
   The film stars the stunning Rachel Weisz as Helen, a hairdresser
in the crumbling seaside town of Farhaven. When the story opens, a
body is dumped in the water. Cut to nine years later. A young man,
Martin (Alessandro Nivola), returns after nearly a decade in prison
for the murder. Helen has become an obsession for not only Martin,
with whom she shares a past _ and a secret _ but also for the local
DJ and a young boy named Honda, who won't speak since finding his
mother's dead body. The quartet tries desperately to connect, but
their differences, past ties and needs are insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   Winterbottom integrates the changing demographics of England _
Honda and his sister Smokey are immigrants living on the desolate
shore _ with the failing economy of a country that has long ceased
to be a formidable world power. The pall of better days spreads
over the director's grim view. As the stories merge and Helen's
past is revealed, we see that these are characters who are alone
and isolated in their desires and wants.
</P>
<P>
   As is true with all of Winterbottom's films, he has secured some
of the best acting talent around. He cast Saskia Reeves in
``Butterfly Kiss'' and Kate Winslet, Christopher Eccleston and
Rachel Griffiths in ``Jude.'' In ``I Want You,'' he's given Weisz a
terrific, complex and deceptive role.
</P>
<P>
   While Winterbottom isn't an easy director, his films are so
disturbing, true, imaginative and indelible that we willingly
invest time and suspend disbelief because his characters are never
far from our own lives.
</P>
<P>
   I Want You. Directed by Michael Winterbottom. Written by Eoin
McNamee. Cast: Rachel Weisz, Alessandro Nivola, Luka Petrosic, Ben
Daniels. Gramercy Pictures. 87 minutes. Rated R for nudity,
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
