<SLUG> BC-BORDER-JUSTICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PROBES DRUG-LINKED MONEY TRANSACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Texas Attorney General's Office is conducting
two dozen investigations into drug money allegedly being laundered
through banks at the rate of almost $7 million a month, a chief
investigator said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The probes were triggered by Texas bankers who alerted federal
officials about financial transactions by some of their customers,
Don Clemmer, chief of the financial crimes section of the office,
said in an interview here.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmer was in San Antonio to attend the 18th U.S.-Mexico Border
Attorneys General Conference at which money laundering,
cross-border fugitives and dead-beat parents were among the topics
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is part of a pilot program in which U.S. Treasury
Department reports filed by bankers are made available to state
investigators. The reports are filed by bankers who believe
customers may be attempting to skirt federal reporting laws or hide
illegal income.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmer would not say which banks were involved in the state
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Besides banks, investigators are looking at currency exchanges,
known as casas de cambio, and wire-transfer services often used by
immigrants to send money home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drug cartels have developed extensive money-laundering
operations within Texas,'' Clemmer told the attorneys general.
``Texas is like a funnel _ the drugs go out and the money comes
in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While the federal government deals with the international
aspects of money laundering, we deal with the local issues,'' he
said. ``We cannot do anything about money moving through Swiss bank
accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick is for cartels to avoid suspicion as they turn
street-corner profits into seemingly legitimate investments that
can be spent without being scrutinized by law-enforcement
officials, Clemmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The most important aspect of shutting down a cartel is proving
that the profits are gained illegally, Clemmer said.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came as the United States and Mexico again clashed
over allegations of drug money being laundered by some of Mexico's
elite.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. intelligence report released this week describes Mexican
billionaire Carlos Hank Gonzalez and his sons as ``a significant
criminal threat to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Madrazo Cuellar, the Mexican attorney general, challenged
the United States to share proof the family is involved in any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have any evidence, let us see it,'' Madrazo said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the $7 million in allegedly laundered money marks the
most extensive probe yet by the Texas attorney general's office,
but it is a small percentage of as much as $30 billion a year that
officials allege is laundered through Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Cartels have constantly tried to stay a step ahead of the
authorities by finding ways to stash profits.
</P>
<P>
   A recent cartel favorite has been hiding cash in cars and trucks
headed for Mexico. In the past, money has been hidden by disguising
it with wire transfers or as profits form money-exchange houses
which dot the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   Once the money is in Mexico, traffickers can place profits in
bank accounts or businesses, slipping it into legitimate financial
circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are crafty, like those mutant strains that develop as you
create medicines,'' said Shane Phelps, chief of the criminal
justice division for the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Clemmer praised Mexico's efforts at fighting drug trafficking
and money laundering: ``The Mexican government has implemented a
comprehensive drug strategy that includes an anti-money-laundering
initiative as well as attempts to increase public awareness of the
drug problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not blame Mexico for cross-border drug trafficking,
telling the meeting of attorneys general: ``If it were not for our
seemingly insatiable appetite for illegal drugs, the cartels would
have a far more difficult time marketing their products.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
