<SLUG> BC-GAMBLER-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBLER'S LUCK, THEN LIFE, RAN OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Retransmiting for clients)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RIC KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ For Dune Lop Moy, an inveterate gambler, 10,000 was an
unlucky number.
</P>
<P>
   That's how many dollars the 27-year-old restaurant worker from
Allston owed a bookie in Boston's Chinatown nicknamed ``Stinky
Mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Moy had gotten into his hole, and tried to dig out, by betting
on football games through local bookies, playing blackjack at
Foxwoods.
</P>
<P>
   But like other struggling workers in the Chinese community who
had become addicted to gambling, Moy was tapped out. Two months
ago, authorities found his beaten body folded and stuffed into a
large green suitcase that had been tossed in the weeds in Weymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the investigation continues, sources familar with the
Chinatown underworld believe that Moy was marked for murder by
Asian organized crime figures, or their mob associates, intent on
sending a chilling message to their customers: Pay your debts or
die.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a classical mobster hit,'' said one law
enforcement source. ``Old school.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chinatown, some community leaders say Moy's fate coincides
with a surge in gambling excesses, one they link to ethnic
targeting from the Connecticut casinos on top of the traditional
action at neighborhood underground gaming parlors.
</P>
<P>
   For them, Moy's death is a cautionary tale about compulsive
gamblers: Some have lost their life savings, others have lost their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   A recent article in the Chinese Progressive Association
newsletter warned: ``A growing number of people (mostly Asian) are
hooked on the Casino. Some even go there every week (if not every
day).''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daniel Chan of the Boston Chinese Evangelical Church
said he is counseling three married restaurant workers, chronic
players on the verge of losing their homes, who have busted their
family budgets at Foxwoods or Mohegan Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Like dominoes, Chan said, a compulsive gambler can strain the
finances of 10 other relatives or friends, borrowing money from one
to cover the debt of another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them to stop for the sake of the family,'' said Chan.
</P>
<P>
   Chan and others say the casinos are capitalizing on the affinity
of many Chinese for gambling, which is a part of a number of ethnic
festivities and celebrations. It ranges from youngsters playing
coin-toss games during Chinese New Year to women avidly playing
mah-jongg and men betting in bean-counting contests.
</P>
<P>
   Within a mystical culture that reveres nature, some gamblers may
try to please the spirits by playing certain numbers. Eight, for
example, sounds like the Chinese word for prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are targeting Asian clients because they know they are
willing to play the game,'' said Chan.
</P>
<P>
   One casino, Mohegan Sun, has an Asian marketing division.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Lowe, codirector of the progressive association, said
working people such as Dune Moy, who was a regular at the blackjack
tables, are particularly susceptible to come-ons from casinos.
Foxwoods ads beckon at Harrison Avenue and Beach Street. Casino
shuttle buses arrive each day at Kneeland Street. And Mohegan Sun
features Hong Kong entertainers and noodle bars that stay open into
the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   Lonely from laboring long hours in restaurants with little free
time, some men seek companionship with Chinese-speaking friends on
trips to the casinos, where the universal language is winning and
losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to make quick money to pay the bills,'' said Chan.
``When they lose, they lose deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Etess, senior vice president of marketing at Mohegan
Sun, said that while ``the Asian domestic market historically has
been a very fertile one for casinos,'' he denied that his business
was exploiting Asian gamblers. Foxwoods marketing officials could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Etess said gamblers who feel they have gone too far are reminded
by casino signs and brochures to call a counseling number. He said
that these messages soon will be translated into Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of our clientele, both of Asian descent and
otherwise, consume our product responsibly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Dune Moy, the odds were against him almost from the start.
</P>
<P>
   He had come to the United States from China and fell into a
dangerous life. Small and bespectacled, Moy drove fast cars and
lingered on the fringes of the underworld with a fast crowd that
included a heroin-sniffing tattooed gaming parlor enforcer, an
extortionist, and a crack dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Moy seemed to be a magnet for trouble, but time and again he
managed to extricate himself.
</P>
<P>
   Caught speeding, he lost his license, but eventually got it
back. When he was arrested for heroin possession in 1994, police
dropped the charges for insufficient evidence. When he was arrested
in a car with crack dealers that same year, prosecutors later let
him go when police could not find the five plastic bags of rock
they'd spotted beside him in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Moy had a major gambling habit. He owed money all over
Chinatown, including thousands to one bookie, said a source. When
he disappeared in late November, Moy's family hoped for the best.
</P>
<P>
   This time, with $10,000 hanging over his head, Dune Moy's luck
had run out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
