<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, June 4. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PEACE-PLAN (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ On the 72nd day of
NATO's air war against Yugoslavia, President Slobodan Milosevic on
Thursday accepted an international peace plan to end the Kosovo
conflict and allow nearly 1 million ethnic Albanian refugees to
return to what is left of their homes. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center: Photo refer:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEE-REAX (Stenkovec I Camp, Macedonia) _ When the
loudspeakers at this refugee camp broadcast the news of a potential
peace agreement for Kosovo, Ahmet Sharifi burst out laughing.
``Milosevic is lying again,'' he said. Such skepticism was echoed
on the sidelines of the men's round-robin volleyball game and in
the line of women filling their water jugs at an open spigot. By
Elizabeth Becker and David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   EU-MILITARY (Cologne, Germany) _ The leaders of 15 European
countries decided Thursday to make the European Union a military
power for the first time in its 42-year history, with command
headquarters, staffs and forces of its own for peacekeeping and
peacemaking missions in future crises like those in Kosovo or
Bosnia. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ News Analysis on
Milosevic and what he got out of _ or didn't get out of _ the peace
proposal. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S.-REAX (Washington) _ U.S. reaction to peace
developments in Yugoslavia: National Security Council says it looks
like ``the real thing.'' By John Broder and Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION (Midrand, South Africa) _ The African National
Congress won a second term today in a landslide victory that will
probably give South Africa's next President, Thabo Mbeki, control
of more than two-thirds of parliament. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRS.CLINTON (New York) _ Saying she was convinced that
Hillary Rodham Clinton was running for Senate, Rep. Nita Lowey
dropped out of the race for the Democratic nomination Thursday. By
Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-AGREEMENT (Seattle) _ Seeking to end a long-running
international dispute that has imperiled salmon stocks and once led
to an angry blockade by Canadian fishermen of an Alaskan ferry, the
United States and Canada on Thursday announced a comprehensive plan
to set quotas on salmon catches along thousands of miles of the
Pacific Ocean and establish a U.S.-paid conservation fund to
protect the fish. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-II (Washington) _ Part Two of a two-part
series: The computer printout that came with 7-year-old Cory
Christen's medication contained a litany of side effects. But it
said nothing about the tremors he started to get, a possible
symptom of a widely known, dangerous side effect: irregular heart
beat. After several months on the drug, he collapsed and died.
Cory's death highlights what drug safety experts describe as a
dangerous flaw in the way consumers are informed of the risks of
prescription medicines. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
