<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH BY PRESCRIPTION: AN OVERWHELMED SYSTEM CAN PRODUCE FATAL
ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs 2nd graf to insert name of lawyer, Michael S. Smith; subs 3rd
graf to switch attribution from Charles McLaughlin to Smith; subs
4th graf to note Montefiore is in New York and that ShopRite is
subsidiary of Wakefern; subs 9th graf to change `cases involved
mistakes like those that killed Helen McLaughlin' to just `cases
involved mistakes.'; subs 25th graf to change `outright mistakes,
as occurred with Mrs. McLaughlin and Miguel' to just `outright
mistakes, as occurred with Miguel'; subs 15th graf to give full
name of Leesburg Pharmacy and subs 35th graf to remove duplicated
mention of its location)  (Eds: a shorter version, a little under 2,000 words, has moved as
deadly-prescriptions-abridged) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic on rise
in prescriptions and decline in pharmacists is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Helen McLaughlin was 73 when she died from what her
relatives call a mixup in prescription drugs. In death, she joined
a group that is causing increasing anxiety among health care
experts and federal regulators: the tens of thousands of Americans
who are killed each year not by illness, but by medication intended
to treat it.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, Mrs. McLaughlin, a widow who lived with her two
daughters in Elizabeth, N.J., walked into the pharmacy department
of the local ShopRite supermarket to fill a prescription for
chlorpromazine, an anti-psychotic medication. She walked out,
according to her son Charles and Michael S. Smith, a lawyer who is
suing ShopRite on behalf of her family, with a drug that has a
nearly identical name, chlorpropamide, which is used by diabetics
to lower their blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
   It was a particularly serious mistake, the family said. Mrs.
McLaughlin suffered from diabetes, and was already taking
medication for it. She took the new drug in addition to her regular
pills for three weeks when she was admitted to Elizabeth General
Medical Center with dangerously low blood sugar. That, Smith said,
unleashed a cascade of health problems for his mother, including
stomach ulcers and a drug-resistant bacterial infection. She died
on May 20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the lawsuit, officials at ShopRite, a subsidiary of
Wakefern Food Corp, declined comment. But Charles McLaughlin, who
works as an ultrasound technician at Montefiore Medical Center in
New York, said he finds it difficult to comprehend that his mother
died from a medication she didn't need, or ask for. ``I work in a
hospital,'' he said. ``I know that errors occur. But on the other
hand there has to be some sort of failsafe system to prevent things
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is no failsafe system, a fact that is becoming
increasingly apparent to officials at the Food and Drug
Administration, as well as independent drug safety experts. They
say Helen McLaughlin's death highlights a pervasive and dangerous
problem: with more medications on pharmacy shelves than ever
before, and more prescriptions being written, the nation's health
care system is overwhelmed, creating a growing risk that patients
will be killed or hurt by adverse reactions or mistakes.
Regulators, even after approving a new drug, cannot always predict
all potential side effects, or toxic interactions. Many pharmacists
are overworked, and filling more prescriptions with less help. And
with as many as a dozen medications available for any one ailment,
doctors are having a hard time keeping abreast of FDA warnings
about possible risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just so many new drugs available. And keeping
current with the information that goes with each drug has become
almost impossible,'' said Dr. Kenneth Kizer, undersecretary for
health at the Department of Veterans' Affairs in Washington. ``The
system is just not designed to help the practitioner.''
</P>
<P>
   The true scope of the problem is unknown, in part because
hospitals and doctors are not required to report it.
</P>
<P>
   But recent studies lead scientists to think that prescription
drugs are killing and injuring far more people than previously
believed, and experts estimate two-thirds of the deaths and
injuries could be prevented. Last year, a study in the Journal of
the American Medical Association estimated that 106,000 hospital
patients die and 2.2 million are injured each year by adverse
reactions to prescription drugs, not including cases where errors
are involved. The estimate was the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   In another study, in 1995, Dr. Lucian Leape, a health policy
analyst at the Harvard School of Public Health, found that 6.5
percent of patients at two teaching hospitals in Boston had been
injured by their medicines, and one third of these cases involved
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials are convinced the danger is growing. In a recently
released 150-page report, they called for pharmacists, doctors,
hospitals and drug companies to work together to create ``a new
framework'' for cutting down on the risks from the drugs the agency
approves. On Tuesday, meanwhile, the FDA put a new rule into
effect: requiring the manufacturers of some especially risky drugs
to distribute explicit warning pamphlets to patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are being harmed and some of the harm is preventable,''
said Dr. Janet Woodcock, director of the FDA's Center for Drug
Evaluation and Research. ``All of these things are raising alarm
bells in people's minds that there is a potential for even more
serious problems. And the problem is pretty serious right now.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PRESSURES So Many Drugs, So Little Time
</P>
<P>
   That medications pose a public health threat is, in a sense,
testimony as much to medicine's success as its failure. As Leape
put it, ``Adverse drug events are a disease of medical progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical manufacturers are discovering new ways to treat
more diseases and conditions, from impotence to diabetes. The FDA,
long criticized as moving too slowly on drug applications, is now
approving products at a record-setting pace. And patients are
living longer with illnesses that could not be treated before.
</P>
<P>
   More prescriptions are being written, not only because there are
more drugs but because the population is aging; the elderly take
more than one third of all drugs that are prescribed. In 1992,
according to the National Association of Chain Drug Stores, 2.03
billion prescriptions were dispensed in retail pharmacies; by last
year, the figure was up to 2.78 billion. By the year 2005, the
association estimates, it will be 4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacies, pressed like other health care providers by the cost
controls of managed care, are struggling to fill the higher volume
of prescriptions in less time, and with less help. ``I worked
12-hour days, and if you get to the bathroom once a day, you're
fortunate,'' said Adle Joseph, a pharmacist at the Leesburg
Pharmacy in Leesburg, Va., who spent 35 years with the Rite Aid
chain before retiring last year to join a slower-paced, independent
store. ``The conditions are just not conducive to good safety.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
