<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIANANMEN-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER WON'T LET SON'S MEMORY DIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ding Zilin still cannot talk about June 4, 1989,
without crying. Her teenage son was one of hundreds of people slain
10 years ago Friday when Chinese troops used tanks and guns to
eject protesters from Tiananmen Square. But unlike most Chinese,
pressed or lulled into silence about the quashing of the democracy
movement, Ding has devoted her life to restoring the memory of that
day.
</P>
<P>
   Ding's son, Zhang Jielian, a high school senior, volunteered to
stand sentry that night outside the square to protect the college
students, who were leading the protests, from advancing troops. His
mother now lives by the words hand-printed on his signboard when he
was shot: ``If you are killed, we are still here.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, Ding has converted Zhang's room into a shrine, a
reminder of her loss and that of thousands of other families whose
relatives were killed or imprisoned during the extensive crackdown
on reform-minded students, and on the laborers, civil servants, and
others who crowded the streets to support and shield them.
</P>
<P>
   ``During these 10 years, more than 3,000 days, every day I am
missing my lost son. I think this torture will not stop till the
end of my life,'' Ding said, crying. ``He was only 17. He didn't
even live to get the right to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have tried to make sure that Friday's anniversary
will pass without disruption:They have rounded up at least 60
dissidents, boarded up Tiananmen Square for renovations, censored
news on the Internet and pager services, and blocked Cable News
Network and other foreign channels that are likely to air stories
commemorating the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   But Ding, 62, says repression cannot stop relatives of victims
from mourning and demanding that the Communist Party take
responsiblity for turning the People's Liberation Army against its
own citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see that Li Peng,'' the former Communist Party premier
who ordered martial law in 1989, ``can go to Western countries and
shake hands with leaders as if this never happened, I feel
terrible. . . . He should be held responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ding has tracked down 160 families who lost relatives and 70
people who were injured that night, but was stopped by authorities
from finishing her search. Like many witnesses, analysts, and
doctors who treated victims, Ding believes that the true number is
several hundred, possibly higher.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Ding and other victims' relatives filed suit against
the government, seeking reparations. Every year, she has marked the
anniversary with letters to authorities demanding an investigation
of the killings, a complete list of victims, compensation, and a
reversal of the official verdict on the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Her demands have gone unanswered. Instead, she was forced to
retire in 1995 as a professor of aesthetics at People's University
and has not been allowed to lecture or publish in China. She has
been under house arrest since March 3, presumably to keep her from
publicly commemorating the anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Ding is an unlikely thorn in the side of
authorities. She joined the Communist Party in 1960 and was a loyal
follower, even after she became a victim of its ideology. During
the Cultural Revolution of 1966-76, she was one of countless
intellectuals persecuted, yet even then, she said, ``I believed in
the propaganda. I never doubted the Communist Party.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for Ding to see her only child turn against the
party in which she had such faith. It was harder still for her to
imagine that the party would crush people favoring reasonable
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son was really worried when the military came to Beijing''
after martial law was declared May 20, 1989, ``but I told him that
high-ranking party officials said the military is not against the
civilians. I told him if they wanted to kill you, I wouldn't be a
member of the Communist Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son was killed as soldiers swept down the Avenue of
Everlasting Peace on their way to clear Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she said, she has come to realize that the bloody
crackdown ``was not an accident, but a result of the system of the
Communist Party.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, however, that party has managed to improve
most people's standard of living, and has persuaded a new
generation to replace dreams of democracy with blind nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jiang Qisheng, a June 4th student leader, believes the
hopes of 1989 remain in most people's hearts, even if the courage
to pursue them does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common people are cautious about speaking out or standing up
because of the nightmare of 10 years ago,'' said Jiang, who wrote a
petition urging a June 4th candlelight vigil before he was taken
away by police last month. ``But if they finally decide to stand
up, then big things will happen in China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
