<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta seeks new international image
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Convention and Visitors Bureau wants to
boost the city's image as an international destination.
</P>
<P>
   The ACVB will team with its counterparts in Cincinnati and New
York, and with Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines, to sponsor a trade
show targeting 120 of the largest European meeting and convention
planners.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first year for the trade show, Gateway Showcase,
which will be held Sept. 17-19 at the Atlanta Merchandise Mart.
Cincinnati and New York will host the event in subsequent years.
Those cities and Atlanta are Delta's three major gateways from
Europe _ with more than 250 trans-Atlantic flights weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Howard, vice president of public relations and tourism,
said groups that have not traditionally held meetings in the United
States and international conglomerates with a significant Georgia
or U.S. presence are being tapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of educating them to just how easy and
convenient Atlanta is as a meeting city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of international visitors has risen over the
years, Atlanta still pales by comparison to other major cities.
Howard estimates that 800,000 overseas visitors come to the metro
area annually. That compares to about 5 million in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``That says to us that we haven't scratched the surface,''
Howard said. ``Once you get past New York, San Francisco, Boston
and Washington, D.C., then market share really drops off
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Reis, executive vice president of New York-based Allied
Tours, said while Atlanta has its pluses, it remains ``a secondary
city'' for foreign business and leisure travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
