<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITIA LINKED TO ISRAEL QUITS AN ENCLAVE IN LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KFAR HOUNA, Lebanon _ Tanks and armored personnel carriers from
an Israeli-backed militia rumbled through this town in darkness
early Thursday to complete a retreat from the Jezzin enclave, a
mountainous, battle-scarred swath of southern Lebanon the militia
had held for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal from Jezzin was greeted with guarded relief by
many residents, who had found themselves caught in an increasingly
bloody crossfire as the militiamen of the South Lebanon army
battled Hezbollah guerrillas on Israel's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also signs of deep uneasiness among the
predominantly Christian population. Many regarded the Lebanese
militia as their protector from Hezbollah, a Shiite Muslim force,
which showed its military strength overnight by attacking the
departing convoy with roadside bombs, mortars and machine-gun fire
as it wound along a narrow mountain road.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, the burned-out, overturned remains of at least
three militia tanks destroyed on that road in the last two days
served as evidence of what was clearly a perilous retreat. Among
the several hundred members of the Israel-backed force that fled
Jezzin, at least two militiamen were killed during the move
southward to the relative safety of an Israeli occupation zone that
begins just south of this village.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents of Jezzin said Thursday that they wanted the
Lebanese army to be sent to the enclave to fill the void left by
the departing militiamen. But Lebanon's prime minister said he
would not take that step, because to insert Lebanese forces into
the area might crimp Hezbollah's efforts to oust Israeli forces
from the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to protect the Israeli occupiers from the
resistance action, and the army's presence might do so
unintentionally,'' the prime minister, Salim Hoss, said in an
interview in Beirut. Instead, he said, he would ``intensify'' the
presence in Jezzin of the Lebanese police.
</P>
<P>
   In another rebuff to residents of the enclave, Hoss said Lebanon
would not grant amnesty to some 200 militiamen who stayed behind
Thursday as their colleagues fled, and who have said they intend to
surrender to the government. All could be charged with treason.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the newly retired militiamen were waiting nervously in
Jezzin to see when and how they might be taken into custody, while
mothers like Odette Abu Zeid complained to reporters that their
sons did not deserve such a fate. In a town that was under South
Lebanon army control, Mrs. Abu Zeid said, her two sons, now 20 and
18, had had little choice but to accept an Israeli paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Jezzin, it was a matter of either the boys' carrying a gun
and putting food on the table or getting kicked out of town,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The militiamen who withdrew overnight from Jezzin, a 35-square
mile enclave that lies north of an Israeli occupation zone, had
positioned themselves Thursday morning on a hilltop just south of
Kfar Houna, within the relative safety of the heavily fortified
border strip.
</P>
<P>
   The militia commander, Gen. Antoine Lahd, had ordered the
pullout on grounds that the heavy toll imposed by Hezbollah attacks
had made the Jezzin enclave too dangerous. As his forces prepared
their pullout late Wednesday, they were assisted by Israeli
aircraft, which circled the skies above Jezzin.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal has been described by many as a possible test run
for a full-scale Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon, which
Israel's prime minister-elect, Ehud Barak, has promised will take
place within a year. But the fact that Lebanon has not responded to
the militia's retreat by sending its army to Jezzin is likely to be
interpreted as a cautionary sign by Israeli politicians, who have
said a withdrawal from southern Lebanon would need to be
accompanied by security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon, and Syria, its patron, have said any Israeli withdrawal
should be unilateral, without any such preconditions. Hoss refused
to say what steps Lebanon might take if Israeli forces did leave,
but he offered a staunch defense of Hezbollah's right to continue
its campaign to drive Israeli forces out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Israelis occupy Lebanese territory, they will be
exposed to resistance action,'' he said. Hoss said he regarded the
withdrawal of the South Lebanon army from Jezzin as ``very
positive,'' but he called the move ``an isolated case'' unlikely to
be followed by an Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
</TEXT>
