<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2116 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH04-COX     06-03 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crew was aware of storm, reports say
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Air traffic controllers warned the crew of
American Airlines Flight 1420 that a powerful thunderstorm was
spawning dangerous wind shears near the runway in the moments
before Tuesday's deadly crash, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the approach, there were two wind shear alarms that
were dispatched to the pilot,'' said National Transportation Safety
Board member George W. Black. ``About the time of the accident, the
most intense part of the storm was beginning to enter the
airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather reports showed sustained winds near 50 mph as the jet
approached Little Rock National Airport, while a gust of 87 mph
roared through minutes after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations renewed questions about why a veteran airline
pilot would choose to land his jet in such weather. Federal safety
officials refused to speculate about whether the pilot erred in
making the landing, although they admitted they may eventually
conclude that pilot error was a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be a conclusion after our investigation is
complete, but the process may take a year,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-80 aircraft, inbound from Dallas with 139 passengers and
six crew members on board, skidded off the runway, struck a light
tower, broke into pieces and burst into flames as it landed about
11:51 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people were killed and dozens were injured. More than 30
people were hospitalized, with five in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The dead included pilot Richard Buschmann, a 20-year American
Airlines veteran who lived in Chicago, and seven people from
Arkansas, five of them returning from a European tour to their home
in Russellville.
</P>
<P>
   The final victim was from San Jose, Calif., according to a
Little Rock television station.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were relieved to confirm that 13 passengers who
initially were unaccounted for after the crash had been located
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Safety investigators have not yet interviewed the first officer,
Michael Origel, who suffered a broken leg. They hope to talk to him
today to get a more thorough understanding of what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Weather is clearly the focus of the investigation, along with
the crew's decisions and their possible fatigue. Both pilots had
been on duty for more than 13 hours Tuesday, completing several
segments before their scheduled final run to Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   American's regulations require pilots to stop flying after 14
work hours in one day.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of thunderstorms and wind shears _ powerful bursts of
wind that can quickly change directions _ have long been known to
pilots, but took on new importance after a 1985 Delta crash in
Dallas that was blamed on the winds.
</P>
<P>
   Airports have installed sophisticated detectors that issue wind
shear alarms, and new, advanced Doppler radars enable ground
controllers to more precisely pinpoint the location and intensity
of storms.
</P>
<P>
   Little Rock's airport has Doppler radar, but not the most
powerful new version that has been installed at busier airports,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the conditions, the final decision on landing is always
left to the pilot, Black said. Control tower personnel simply relay
ground weather readings to help pilots make their decisions, but
cannot order aircraft not to land, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear Buschmann knew the weather near the Little Rock
airport was deteriorating, and that an intense storm was
approaching.
</P>
<P>
   According to several news reports, Buschmann asked to change
runways as he approached, moving to the only runway at Little Rock
that is equipped for instrument-only landings.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot initially tried to bring the jet down visually, but
lost sight of the runway as he approached and asked to switch to an
instruments-only landing, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, investigators backtracked the jet's skid marks from
its final resting spot near the Arkansas River back up the runway.
They found the jet initially hit the tarmac about 2,000 feet from
the approach end of the 7,200-foot runway, which is considered
normal.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are studying the runway's condition to determine
whether rain from the heavy downpour was draining too slowly. There
is a chance the jet hydroplaned on the wet surface, its wheels
unable to grip just like a car does on a wet road, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Once it touched the pavement, the jet veered to the right, then
veered to the left, then roared onto a grassy swale beside the
runway. It eventually ran off the runway's end, striking a lighting
tower that spun the craft around and broke it into three large
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dead appeared to have been seated on the left side
of the plane, as was pilot Buschmann. The first class cabin was
sheared away at the aisle, with passengers seated on the right side
surviving and those seated on the left simply disappearing out the
gaping hole created by the collision, survivors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a huge chunk of the plane taken away,'' said Jason
Klamm, who was sitting on the right in first class with his father
as they returned from a trip to Seattle to see his favorite
baseball player, Ken Griffey Jr. ``It seemed like it took the
passengers on the left side of the first class cabin with it.''
</P>
<P>
   While press reports cited Buschmann's sterling record as a
pilot, noting that he complied nearly 10,000 hours flying for
American, at least one safety official believes the evidence is
pointing toward pilot error.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is mounting evidence that the crew may have attempted to
beat the thunderstorm to the airport, which is a dangerous thing to
do,'' said Jim Burnett, former chairman of the NTSB. ``It's like
trying to beat a locomotive to a crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
