<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-03 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Koreas: North-South Talks to Resume
</P>
<P>
   North and South Korea agreed to resume talks at the deputy
minister level, beginning June 21 in Beijing. The discussion, which
was broken off 14 months ago, will include such issues as how to
arrange correspondence and meetings among family members who have
been separated since the 1950-53 Korean War. As part of the deal to
resume talks, South Korea also announced it was sending 200,000
tons of fertilizer to the North.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan: Indian Pilot Returned
</P>
<P>
   In a goodwill gesture, Pakistan released an Indian pilot whose
plane was shot down over the Pakistani side of Kashmir on May 27.
The pilot, Flight Lt. K. Nachiketa, crossed a cease-fire line while
taking part in raids against Islamic guerrillas holed up in the
rugged, high-altitude terrain on the Indian side of the territory.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Le Pen Convicted
</P>
<P>
   The far-right French leader Jean-Marie Le Pen was convicted in a
Munich court of inciting racial hatred and ordered to pay an
undisclosed amount in fines, prosecutors said. The charges against
the National Front leader stem from a 1997 Munich news conference
at which he referred to the Holocaust as a ``detail in the history
of World War II.'' Trivializing the Holocaust is a crime in
Germany, with a maximum penalty of five years in jail and a heavy
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Former Slave Laborers Sue
</P>
<P>
   Nazi-era slave laborers from Ukraine sued the Siemens
electronics company and BMW in the Munich Labor Court. The 134
Ukrainians are demanding between $13,000 and $21,000 each as back
wages and compensation. The court said it must first rule on
whether it has jurisdiction to hear the case, a process that could
take months.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Yeltsin Ends Executions
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin all but abolished capital punishment,
commuting to life in prison the sentence of the last Russian
prisoner on death row. Yeltsin, who permitted the execution of 163
prisoners during his terms in office, placed a moratorium on
executions in 1996 after Russia joined the Council of Europe, which
bans capital punishment in peacetime. Though Yeltsin has forsworn
executions, they remain legal, and parliament has been unwilling to
repeal the law.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Governor is Impeached
</P>
<P>
   The 30-member Morelos Legislature voted to strip Gov. Jorge
Carrillo Olea of immunity from criminal prosecution. As a result,
Carrillo, a member of Mexico's governing party who was forced to
take a leave in May 1998 after his attorney general was arrested in
a kidnapping scandal, will be tried by the state's supreme court on
charges that he failed to fulfill his constitutional duties. Until
recently, governors served at the pleasure of the president, and
Carrillo's impeachment is a first in modern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
