<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANC MAKES BROAD GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Voters in South Africa's peaceful second
democratic elections have redrawn the country's political landscape
and strengthened the African National Congress's lock on power.
</P>
<P>
   With 70 percent of the ballots counted, the ANC was on the
threshold of gaining its desired two-thirds majority in Parliament
and retained control of seven of nine provinces with resounding
majorities. The New National Party, a makeover of the one that
ruled the country for 48 years under apartheid and the official
opposition for the past five years, was badly trounced across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nats are hanging on by their fingernails,'' said Steven
Friedman, director of the Center for Policy Studies in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a victory celebration of thundering ANC stalwarts
Thursday in a ballroom near Johannesburg, Thabo Mbeki, the
president-in-waiting, vowed to continue outgoing President Nelson
Mandela's efforts to reconcile black and white South Africans. But
Mbeki said the ANC's top priority would be speeding up the pace of
social rebuilding for the impoverished masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have directed us to move forward faster with our
program of reconstruction and development so that the goal of a
better life for all is achieved sooner rather than later,'' he
said. ``The people have spoken. We have now arrived at the moment
where we go back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a notable lack of violence during the election, even
in areas that had been identified as potential flashpoints.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot process was monitored by 10,000 international and
local monitors, who Thursday identified some minor problems at
polling sites but declared the vote free and fair. Stations around
the country stayed open well past the official closing time to
accommodate long lines of voters.
</P>
<P>
   The first South African election since apartheid installed
Mandela as the first black president in 1994. This second election
shattered the historical political alignment, creating the
likelihood of improbable partnerships, changing the hue of some
parties, and sounding the death knell for others.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC outdrew the New National Party in the Western Cape but
did not secure an outright majority. It now appears the stage is
set there for a governing coalition between the erstwhile
liberation movement and its apartheid nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   A similar situation arose in KwaZulu-Natal, where the ANC nearly
caught the Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party. In this decade,
factional warfare between the two parties has killed more than
12,000 people. But budding rapprochement and strong ANC gains make
it likely that the two former foes will rule the province together.
</P>
<P>
   The Pan Africanist Congress, once the ANC's primary rival during
the liberation struggle, garnered so few votes that it lost all its
seats in Parliament. The Democratic Party, once the party of white
liberalism and an ally of the ANC, cut into the conservative white
vote and was poised to become the official opposition to the ANC.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign, opponents accused the ANC of seeking a
two-thirds majority in order to change the constitution. In fact,
the ANC was the only party whose election manifesto required no
changes to the nation's charter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the party emerges virtually unchallenged nationally,
increasing its control of Parliament from 62 percent to a likely 67
percent and gaining absolute or at least shared control in each
province.
</P>
<P>
   The party also has the freedom to form an all-ANC cabinet for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki tried to assuage concerns that the ANC would abuse its
rising strength. ``We are fully conscious of the fact that the
magnificent patience of our people was in part driven by their
knowledge that the ANC would approach the exercise of power without
any arrogance ... to build a South Africa which truly belongs to
all who live in it _ both black and white,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
