<HEADLINE>
RETAIL SALES CONTINUED TO GAIN STRONGLY IN MAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on rising retail sales, in dollar figures, is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. retailers posted robust sales in May as consumers continued
to show great confidence in the economy by snatching up everything
from wardrobes in summer white to pool furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in retail stores open at least a year, a key industry
measurement, rose 5.6 percent in May compared with results in the
month a year earlier, according to the Goldman Sachs retail
composite index. The figure was not a perfect comparison, however,
because some merchants did not include sales from the Memorial Day
weekend, traditionally a big spending weekend, which came a week
later than last year.
</P>
<P>
   The strong increase adds to an already brisk year for merchants.
In the first four months of 1999, sales in stores open at least a
year rose 6.7 percent compared with figures in the period a year
earlier. That was one of the biggest jumps in years, according to
the Goldman Sachs survey.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts see few signs that the consumption binge will abate.
``The depth and breadth of this economic expansion has been
unbelievable, and we continue to think the consumer is in good
shape,'' said Lehman Brothers managing director Jeff Feiner. ``The
really good news is that despite better-than-expected numbers,
retailers have budgeted very conservatively for the more important
second half of the year.'' Feiner has increased earnings estimates
for several large retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Discount chains continued to be at the center of the sales boom.
Wal-Mart Stores posted an increase of 7.7 percent, and Target, a
unit of Dayton Hudson Corp., was up 7.4 percent. Specialty apparel
stores _ buoyed by hot weather, which caused customers to snatch up
capri pants and brightly hued tank tops _ also sustained strong
increases. Ann Taylor was up 10.1 percent, and American Eagle
Outfitters was up 18.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even previously struggling brands showed solid gains. The
Limited Inc., which posted a 10 percent growth in sales, had star
performances from all its units, including Lane Bryant, which was
up 12 percent, and Express, up 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A notable exception in speciality apparel came from the normally
invincible Gap Inc. Though sales were up a solid 8 percent, almost
all the growth came from the rocket-charged performances of the
Banana Republic division, which gained 17 percent, and Old Navy, 19
percent. The Gap Stores and Gap Kids posted declines of 1 percent
to 4 percent. Analysts had been predicting that the Gap stores
would rise 1 percent to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to deliver a home run every time, especially
since we were up against very strong numbers from last year,'' said
Warren Hashagen, chief financial officer at Gap. Still, he added
that ``we have had a little bit of weakness in the merchandising
assortment, but we are getting new merchandise in this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Department stores, which have consistently lagged behind the
discounters in recent years, nevertheless had a strong showing.
Federated Department Stores, whose units include Bloomingdale's and
Macy's, had an increase of 4.1 percent, and Saks, the former
Profitt's, said sales increased 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even the moderate-price merchants, J.C. Penney Co. and Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co., which have struggled in recent years as they have
lost customers to hipper outlets like Target and Old Navy, posted
respectable gains. Sales were up 2.2 percent at Penney and 1.9
percent at Sears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2125 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      06-03 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCORD LEAVES MANY QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The brief Balkan war, squeezed into the final
months of the 20th century by ethnic tensions that have lasted a
millennium, may be ending with as many unanswered questions as were
raised when it began _ perplexing questions that still stare
remorselessly at Yugoslavia, Europe, NATO, the United States,
Russia and China.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative accord reached Thursday eventually could bring at
least a temporary end to the NATO bombing, to the Serbian cultural
crusade and to the new divide between West and East. But the
agreement brings no guarantees that the beginning of the next
century will be any more tranquil than the beginning of the last
one.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would it resolve critical questions about what role the
United States will play in a world without an overriding
ideological divide. Or where world opinion and global force might
be mobilized to resolve civil wars. Or how the Western allies might
win the trust and cooperation of the two giants of the old
Communist bloc, Russia and China, to prevent small disputes from
escalating into large ones.
</P>
<P>
   And, more important, the accord does not suggest how those
decisions should be made, and whether one doctrine will ever cover
all the complicated issues that prompt people to go to war.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton expressed caution Thursday about the
agreement, and the success of the accord will depend on how swiftly
and fully President Slobodan Milosevic complies. If the agreement
holds, it would bring short-term relief to a weary world. But it
would not address the important questions of diplomacy, strategy
and morality that still could bring long-term grief to the new
world order.
</P>
<P>
   Wars are fought to resolve difficult international questions,
and almost always raise even more vexing ones. World War I, for
example, was fought in part to resolve big-power tensions between
England and Germany, but the predominant question at its end was
how to assure collective security in Europe. World War II was
fought in part to resolve the tension between Europe's democracies
and its dictatorships, but the pressing question at war's end was
how to resolve the tension between capitalism and communism.
</P>
<P>
   This war is no different. Indeed, the questions raised near the
end are in many ways far more pressing than the ones prompted at
its beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for the return of hundreds of thousands of
refugees, but it will not erase the ethnic tensions that provided
the trigger for World War I, or that fueled what may turn out to be
the century's last bloody conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement provides a plausible rationale for NATO's months
of bombing. But it does not give the military alliance fashioned at
the end of World War II, and strengthened throughout the Cold War,
a discrete, defined role in a world where the Cold War has
disappeared and where World War II is increasingly a grandfather's
war.
</P>
<P>
   It buttresses the notion of European unity. But it does not
provide an example for how the continent, no longer the self-styled
seat of civilization, should arbitrate disputes and prevent civil
wars between the English Channel and the Urals from spiraling into
world conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   It reinforces the moral high ground that the United States seeks
to occupy, in an era when this nation is the world's only
superpower. But it provides no blueprint for how, when, why and
where the preeminent global power should get involved in faraway
disputes, project its power or influence the outcome of world
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   It salvages Russia's dignity at a time of political turmoil and
economic uncertainty. But it does not provide any hint of how a
continental power that spans 11 time zones should establish its
long-range stability, nor how a major power with strong local and
ethnic interests should prevent conflict before it occurs.
</P>
<P>
   It establishes China as a legitimate, prideful member of the
international community. But it does not guarantee that Beijing
will be a player in the next world conflict, nor does it provide
hints about what role China will play as its missile stocks and
influence grow.
</P>
<P>
   It redeems the prediction, dating to the days when Stanley
Baldwin was prime minister of Britain in the 1930s but never
realized until now, that wars could be won in the air. But it
offers few hints to help future decision-makers determine whether
relentless bombing will harden the resolve of opponents (as air
raids did in Britain in 1940 and North Vietnam in 1968) or weaken
their resistance (as an air assault apparently did in Yugoslavia in
1999).
</P>
<P>
   It establishes that the entire Western alliance, led by the
greatest power in civilization's history, can work its will on a
country with limited arms, almost no sense of national unity and
scant international support. But it does not provide Americans with
any assurance that its multibillion-dollar arsenal and its complex
set of alliances are suited to the challenges, military and
diplomatic, that will present themselves in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   It would bring an end to a conflict that made Clinton seem
alternately decisive (by entering the air battle so
enthusiastically) and ineffectual (by failing to bring the Serbian
force to its knees swiftly). But it underlines how little the
administration, in its seventh year, has thought through the
difficult questions of war, engagement, and peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   It raises the question, not fully answered by the Marshall Plan
at the end of World War II, whether a huge infusion of money like
the amounts expected to be directed at Yugoslavia in the next
several years, can salve wounds that have festered for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   It alleviates the worry of Vice President Al Gore that a
protracted air war or, worse still, a long ground war, could
undermine his presidential campaign. But it also raises questions
about what the vice president's views and role in the war were, and
about how he would handle a similar situation.
</P>
<P>
   It wipes away a contentious issue from the Republican table. But
it does not help resolve an important conflict within the party
about internationalism and isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   All these questions, though unanswered by the accord announced
Thursday, suddenly seem more difficult, more vexing, than they did
a year ago or at the beginning of the war. They are more urgent
than ever, and yet the solutions to them are more elusive than
ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
