<SLUG> BC-YUGO-NEIGHBORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBTS ON WHETHER MILOSEVIC WILL FOLLOW THROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ News of hope from Belgrade, in the form of a peace
accord, brought disdainful skepticism late Thursday in Hungary,
Yugoslavia's northern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe Milosevic at all,'' said one Hungarian, Zoltan
Karpati, a 33-year-old ticket-taker and trade union representative.
``I have spoken with a lot of Serbs, and they all agree that if
Milosevic makes a deal, he will be out of power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only a delaying tactic,'' Karpati said. ``Milosevic is
like Saddam Hussein _ you can't trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungary, which had a friendly relationship with Yugoslavia
before the war, found itself an adversary after it became a NATO
member. The Western alliance began bombing less than two weeks
after Hungary joined.
</P>
<P>
   That adversarial relationship was aggravated by Hungary's
agreement to host 24 F-18 fighter planes at its southern air base
in Taszar. Bombing in northern Serbia was heard by southern
Hungarian residents nervous about Hungary's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of peace, it seems, would be welcomed by
Hungarians. But almost no one here seems to believe that Milosevic
is on the level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply don't believe it. Only when there are changes in the
personalities will there be real change,'' said Laszlo Szekely, a
77-year-old retiree. ``I would like to believe it, but I was a
soldier, and I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Many here also expressed concern that if Milosevic stays in
power, he may make trouble in the northern Serbian province of
Vojvodina, where about 350,000 ethnic Hungarians live.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politicians must see the connection,'' said Tibor Tajti, a
37-year-old graduate student.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Milosevic, he added: ``If the question is not
settled now, it's going to move onto Vojvodina. They have to remove
him somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Aniko Villany, a shop cashier, said: ``This NATO bombing is of
no use. NATO should grab him somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hungarian government has been nervous about the Vojvodina
question as well. Rightists in the Hungarian parliament are
demanding that part of Vojvodina be annexed to Hungary as part of a
peace pact. The moderate government has rejected that idea as
absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary has acquiesced on the issue of sending Hungarian troops
to Kosovo. Previously, Budapest had opposed the NATO use of its
troops in Yugoslavia, because of the possibility that Hungarians
fighting against ethnic brothers might complicate the war, and the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, Hungary's foreign minister, Janos Martonyi, said
Hungary was ready to send at least 120 soldiers to participate in a
truce force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary ``is ready to make sacrifices and to take risks,''
Martonyi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
