<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-BEEF-SANCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE OVER HORMONE-TREATED BEEF GOES TO ARBITRATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A trans-Atlantic fight over hormone-treated beef
intensified Thursday when officials of the United States and
Canadian asked the World Trade Organization to approve $253 million
in retaliatory trade sanctions and the European Union countered by
demanding arbitration that it hoped would lower the overall amount.
</P>
<P>
   Like a recent dispute over bananas, the quarrel over beef
reflects American anger over the failure of the 15-nation European
Union to abide by decisions of the trade organization, which makes
the rules of international commerce. The trade arbiter has said
that the European preference for bananas grown in former colonies
was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the European Union's refusal to revise its
banana-import policy, the Clinton administration imposed $191.4
million in tariffs on European products. It is seeking a further
$202 million in 100 percent tariffs on a new range of European
goods because the European Union has refused to lift its ban on
beef produced in the United States, as it was supposed to do by May
13 under a previous trade organization ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians asked for $51 million in sanctions because their
beef is also blocked from the enormous European market.
</P>
<P>
   The trade organization first found the beef ban illegal in 1997
on the ground that food safety concerns cannot be used to restrict
trade without a specific finding of a health risk.
</P>
<P>
   As in the bananas case, European Union officials invoked the
right to a review by a trade organization arbitration panel and are
expected to argue that the U.S. beef trade is worth only half the
claimed yearly losses.
</P>
<P>
   The European Trade Commissioner, Sir Leon Brittan, said Thursday
that the trade bloc would seek a significant reduction, arguing
that the U.S. figure of $202 million was ``grossly excessive.'' He
said, ``They haven't suffered that amount of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   In declining to meet the May deadline, the European Union issued
preliminary findings from a new scientific study that said that one
growth-promoting hormone could cause cancer. Ian Wilkinson, deputy
head of the European Union's mission to the trade organization in
Geneva, said 17 studies were expected to be done by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the dispute goes to a three-member arbitration panel
that under the trade organization's rules must decide by July 12 on
the amount of trade sanctions. Only then will the trade
organization permit the United States and Canada to impose them.
</P>
<P>
   However, signaling a new area of dispute, the Europeans are
seeking a final list of products that will be penalized before the
sanctions are imposed, a request that Washington opposes.
</P>
<P>
   An initial list, which included pork, Roquefort cheese, truffles
and mineral water, was published on March 25 in the Federal
Register. But Rita Hayes, the U.S. envoy to the trade organization,
said Wednesday that ``the final list of sanctions would not be
drawn up until we have WTO authorization'' _ after arbitration is
completed.
</P>
<P>
   She said that although the U.S. cattle industry had reported
$500 million in lost business annually, Washington asked for a
lower amount because ``we felt this was a figure that would
represent the amount of damages we are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by the two sides to arrive at a compromise failed when
officials of the European Union would not commit to lifting the ban
eventually. Then, after the May 3 release of preliminary findings
that supported the United States position, the consumer affairs
director for the European Commission declared that it would never
lift the beef barrier. ``There has never been a comparable
statement from anyone in the EU contradicting this statement,'' Ms.
Hayes said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has offered to label its beef exports as
produced in this country, but that suggestion has foundered in part
because the whole area of altered or adulterated foods is highly
sensitive. One consequence of the ``mad cow'' disease outbreak in
Britain three years ago was that beef consumption in Europe
plummeted. More recently, a scandal over Belgian poultry and other
meat that could be laced with cancer-causing dioxin has reinforced
fears about the food trade.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the beef dispute have agreed to have scientists
look at the evidence in the European Union study that was released
last month. But U.S. officials say they have produced no new data
or findings that the six hormones at issue can cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no health risks from U.S. beef,'' Ms. Hayes said,
citing conclusions by World Health Organization experts last
February that three of the hormones, which occur naturally in
animals, do not pose health risks.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, 63 percent of all cattle and 90 percent of
feed cattle are fitted with hormone implants, which are placed
under the skin behind the animals' ears, to hasten growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
