<SLUG> BC-BEE-DeMAIORIBUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO STUDENT FALLS A LETTER SHORT IN SPELLING BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The word means a buzzing in the ear. The sound
Natalie DeMaioribus heard was the ringing of a bell, signalling
that she was no longer a contestant in Thursday's closing rounds of
the National Spelling Bee.
</P>
<P>
   When the judge read ``tinnitus,'' the 13-year-old hesitated for
the first time in the two-day competition.
</P>
<P>
   She asked the judge to repeat the word.
</P>
<P>
   Tinnitus.
</P>
<P>
   She asked what part of speech the word is.
</P>
<P>
   A noun.
</P>
<P>
   She asked for the judge to use the word in a sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman heard a tinnitus that sounded like a loud and
piercing voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Hesitantly, she repeated the word. T-I-N-I-T-U-S.
</P>
<P>
   Short one ``n,'' the bell sounded.
</P>
<P>
   With a surprised look on her face, DeMaioribus turned and walked
off the stage to the ``comfort room'' used by contestants in this
72nd gathering of top spellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel disappointed,'' said DeMaioribus, who recently
completed the seventh grade at Holy Spirit School in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Chris DeMaioribus, a vascular surgeon, later said
Natalie thought she had spelled the word correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was turning to go back to her seat when the bell rang,''
he said. ``I think she would have felt better missing a word she
didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But DeMaioribus added that while his daughter was upset, she
didn't take the competition too seriously. ``It's never been an
all-consuming thing for her or the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Natalie DeMaioribus tied for 104th place in the contest, and she
won $125 and a commemorative watch. The contest opened Wednesday
with 249 spellers.
</P>
<P>
   DeMaioribus, who was sponsored by the San Antonio Express-News,
plays the piano and violin, and rides horses.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the bee was Nupur Lala, 14, of Tampa, Fla. She won
after 11 rounds, the last of which pitted her against David
Lewandowski, 14, of Schererville, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Lewandowski was eliminated from the contest after misspelling
``opsimath,'' a person who begins to learn late in life. He spelled
it ``opsomath.''
</P>
<P>
   Lala then correctly spelled ``nocicepter,'' which refers to
something that causes harm or pain. She then sealed her victory by
spelling ``logorrhea,'' incoherent talkativeness.
</P>
<P>
   Lala, who was eliminated in the third round of last year's bee,
jumped in the air and screamed.
</P>
<P>
   She won a $10,000 cash prize, plus encyclopedias, two airline
tickets and computer software. The contestants, most sponsored by
their local newspapers, all won regional bees to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Scripps Howard, the newspaper group based in Cincinnati,
coordinates the national finals and produces the word lists and
study materials.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or e-mail
mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
