<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2141 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-SCENE-BOS &LR;      06-03 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE STREETS: RELIEF, YES. EUPHORIA, NO.
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BELGRADE _ For 72 days, the people of Serbia have endured air
raid sirens, gasoline rationing, crowded buses, bread shortages,
blackouts, water outages, cigarette lines, joblessness, black
market profiteers.
</P>
<P>
   And bombs, bombs, and more bombs.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, as word filtered out that their leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, had accepted a peace plan aimed at ending the bombing,
many ordinary people greeted the news with the same sleep-deprived
resignation with which they had come to regard the war.
</P>
<P>
   Relief, yes. Euphoria, no.
</P>
<P>
   People talked about life perhaps returning to normal, or at
least as normal as possible in an impoverished country that is led
by an indicted war criminal and is still subject to a host of
economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   People talked wistfully about not having to hoard cigarettes and
bread, about not going days without a shower or a shave, about
crossing the Sava River and not having to wonder whether this was
the night the bridge would be bombed.
</P>
<P>
   Most people interviewed on the streets of the Yugoslav capital
Thursday afternoon did not even know a deal had been struck, grim
testimony to the power of a state-controlled media that gives the
people only the news that the government deems they need.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a bench in a park in front of City Hall, 57-year-old
grandmother Ljerka Tatic seemed to capture the mood of most when
she said that she was ``glad for a deal,'' but dubious of what was
accomplished by subjecting people to more than two months of
bombing, hardship, and death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could have had that deal sooner,'' said Tatic. ``So
much destruction, for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The people of Belgrade had initially responded to NATO's
airstrikes by mounting defiant, jovial midday rock concerts
downtown. The daily concerts soldiered on, but gradually the crowds
melted away, as each day brought news of ``collateral damage,'' the
euphemism used by NATO to describe the deaths of civilians killed
by what NATO says were accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Dragan Mirac, 21, a student, voiced the realism that had come to
replace the bellicose rhetoric of hard-liners. Mirac dismissed
suggestions that Milosevic had capitulated, seeing instead a
courageous gesture meant to avert greater suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better that the war finish now than the possibility that
100,000 people get killed and then we get a signature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vladan Krstic, 42, a dentist, agreed that ``any peace deal is
better than war.''
</P>
<P>
   The bombing campaign had engendered great bitterness among
ordinary people, even those who long for a more open, democratic
society. Many considered it the height of cowardice that NATO was
only willing to bomb from the relative safety of 15,000 feet and
refused to send its ground forces to fight Serb troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is the site of Orthodox Christian monasteries that are
important to Serbs, and also the place where Serbs trace the birth
of their nationhood. Because of this, some Serbs consider the
deployment in Kosovo of an international force that could include
up to 7,000 Americans a humiliating concession.
</P>
<P>
   Ljiljana Kazic, 38, said the deployment of Americans in Kosovo
would amount to ``a defeat for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Svetozar Jovanovic, 66, is old enough to remember the Nazi
occupation of Serbia during World War II, and, as he put it, ``I'd
rather see Germans in Belgrade again than Americans in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   As he shopped for shoes in a mall, wearing the battle fatigues
that are so common here as tens of thousands of men have been
conscripted into the army, a Yugoslav soldier who would give only
his first name of Svonka said, ``Americans will not feel
comfortable in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone will hate them, even the Albanians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But just as many Serbs seem to accept that Americans and other
foreign troops in Kosovo is the price that has to be paid for an
end to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything against the Americans coming to Kosovo,
as long as they keep peace under the UN flag,'' said Krstic, the
dentist.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade is very much a cafe society, with tables and chairs set
up on sidewalks and any place where space permits. But there was no
celebrating Thursday night as dusk fell, and the prospect of a
second consecutive night without bombing loomed. There was no
bombing in the capital Wednesday night because the Russian envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin and the Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari were
in town presenting the peace deal to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But while there is no euphoria here, there is an unmistakable
sense of relief, a sense captured by a waitress who said, ``I used
to have a life. I used to go out at night. Maybe now I can do that
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many parents here, Alisa Dunic, 36, was not interested in
the political machinations behind Milosevic's acquiescence, or
whether history will regard this as one of the great capitulations
of all time. As someone who has hugged her children, trying to
comfort them over the deafening wail of air raid sirens and
reassure them after the bone-shaking explosions that have become a
fact of daily life here, she sought no political explanation for
what happened Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy because it means peaceful dreams for my kids,'' she
said. ``I don't care if it's capitulation or not. The most
important thing is that people are not killed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
