<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ACELA TRAIN IS A BIG DEPARTURE IN AMTRAK TRAVEL AND
ADVERTISING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's the midnight train to Georgia and the last
train to Clarksville, the A train and the soul train, not to
mention the Chattanooga Choo-Choo and the Atchison, Topeka &AMP; Santa
Fe. Now an unconventional campaign seeks to add another name to the
list of familiar rail monikers: Acela.
</P>
<P>
   Acela, pronounced ``a-CELL-a,'' is the brand to be introduced by
Amtrak later this year to designate service in the Northeast
corridor, its most heavily traveled route, replacing the Metroliner
and other trains. There is a lot riding on the fate of Acela,
because Amtrak is counting on the new service to help improve its
financial performance and end its dependence on federal operating
subsidies by 2002, as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, with an annual budget of $16 million, is
emblematic of the ambitious efforts being undertaken to make new
brands stand out in an extraordinarily cluttered advertising
environment. Complicating those attempts is the stampede to
introduce ``dot-com'' Internet and E-commerce brands.
</P>
<P>
   That may be why the campaign for Acela, which began Friday is so
unusual, selling with a life-style image approach rather than
promoting service features or disparaging alternative methods of
travel like flying and driving. The pitch, by the longtime Amtrak
agency, DDB Worldwide Communications Group in New York, is as sleek
and slick as Amtrak hopes Acela service will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about just a train ride,'' Barbara Richardson, the
executive vice president at Amtrak in Washington responsible for
marketing, said in a telephone interview, because ``Acela is a big
departure for us, representing a really new change in direction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign is meant to signal to people who have not
considered us previously that we offer a service they perhaps had
not expected from us previously,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   There will be three classes of Acela service: express, fast new
trains that are to reach speeds of 150 miles an hour; regional,
regular long-distance service linking Boston, New York and
Washington, and commuter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first step in the elevation of the Amtrak product
nationwide,'' said Joseph DiVincenzo, senior marketing director for
the Northeast corridor at Amtrak in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're saying is that there's a reason to travel on
Amtrak,'' he said, ``because Acela is a different product, a better
way to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   After conducting research among customers, the decision was made
to demonstrate that difference by proclaiming Acela to be a
significant improvement in one's quality of life _ a perk on rails,
as it were. ``Life on Acela'' is the campaign theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travelers for the most part said that travel by car or plane
interrupts their lives,'' said Abigail Kolodny, account planner at
DDB, a unit of Omnicom Group, who joined four agency colleagues
this week to provide a preview of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Acela lets you continue your life while traveling,'' she
added, ``working, eating, meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   So posters in the campaign, illustrated with surreal imagery,
carry such headlines as ``Transfer between left and right brain,''
``Find lost time,'' ``Arrive at a decision,'' ``Brainchild on
board'' and ``Return your mind to its upright position.'' One
poster even asserts in a Zen-like way: ``Be productive. Do
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Shuldman, group creative director at DDB, said: ``What we
intentionally tried to do was to create an Acela `language,' visual
and verbal, to interpret this new mind-set of traveling. It's very
optimistic, reflecting the feeling of what the train means to
Amtrak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the heart of the campaign is the human benefit of travel,''
he added. ``It's about not only arriving at the center of town, but
centered. You can walk into a meeting and say something intelligent
because the ride didn't dehumanize you.''
</P>
<P>
   The DDB team disputed a suggestion that the campaign may be too
ethereal or flaky to resonate with practical Northeast consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents such a bold departure,'' said Jose Banzon,
management supervisor at DDB, ``because Acela is such a different
experience from any train you've been on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Amtrak officials said the campaign ``speaks to sophisticated
travelers and is meant to grab their attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The kickoff Friday comes with commercials to run in movie
theaters showing ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.'' The
spots use quirky vignettes of urban travelers to call Acela ``a
place to recharge'' and ``a better place to unwind.'' They will
also run next month in theaters showing the Stanley Kubrick film
``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   The posters will appear as oversized wall hangings on busy sites
in Boston, Manhattan and Washington. There will be television
commercials in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media department and the creative department worked hand
in hand,'' said Jeroen Bours, group creative director at DDB.
``We'd see a wall on so-and-so street and ask, `Can you get us
there?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``They even got us into airports,'' Bours said of his media
counterparts. ``That was hard to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
