<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT SHRINKS FOR PRESIDENT'S VIEW ON CHINA'S TRADE STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton briefly acknowledged the 10th
anniversary of the Tiananmen Square killings Thursday and argued,
with logic that is meeting increasing skepticism on Capitol Hill,
that only by pushing ahead on expanding trade with Beijing can the
United States remain ``a force for social change in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Though members of Congress were not formally in Washington to
receive Clinton's annual notification that he was renewing ``normal
trade relations'' with China, they said they expected Clinton would
once again prevail. Though Congress has often threatened to revoke
China's trade status, it has never actually done so, even in the
months after Tiananmen.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, by the count of some legislators, the majority in
support of renewal is shrinking, on both the left and the right.
Since reports of Chinese of spying at national nuclear
laboratories, conservatives who once paid scant attention to human
rights issues in China have formed an alliance of convenience with
those who have long advocated linking China's trade status with its
behavior in other arenas.
</P>
<P>
   It is an alliance that clearly leaves some uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., and a harsh critic of
Clinton's policy, argued anew that Congress should deny China the
trade benefits _ mostly lower taxes on Chinese goods shipped to the
United States _ because Clinton's ``engagement'' policy ``has not
succeeded in making trade fairer, people freer or the world
safer.'' But she also went after some of the newest critics of
engagement: Republicans who were seizing on the spy scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, with a highly charged partisan atmosphere,'' she
said, ``the Republican leadership now wants to have it both ways.
They want to exploit politically the failures of the Clinton China
policy, while appeasing the business community'' by renewing
China's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many members of Congress appear of two minds.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic minority leader, Rep. Richard Gephardt, has
consistently voted against renewal of the trade rights, and in a
telephone interview Thursday said he would oppose it again this
year _ and expected ``somewhat more support.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also backs the administration's efforts to strike a deal
with China that would get it into the World Trade Organization.
Part of that bargain would require Congress to drop the annual
debate and grant China a permanent version of what was once called
``most favored nation'' status. (The pro-trade contingent in
Congress argued that the old phrase was misleading, since the
privileges are given to all but a few rogue states.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference,'' Gephardt said. ``If China's accession
to the WTO is done right, it can be a real force for change because
it would provide a real structure of rules and a way we could
enforce them.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has been pressing the White House to include some
commitments from China on human rights, something missing from the
current talks on China's membership.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, several members of Congress say they want to
preserve the right to vote each year on China's trade status
because it gives them an opportunity to vent their emotions on one
of the most emotionally charged issues in American foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they are under greater pressure from business
constituents, farmers and investors to take the deal that China has
offered, which calls for vast openings in China's market over the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have a difficult situation this year,'' said Rep.
David Drier, R-Calif., who has often led the fight to renew trading
rights. ``There's a great temptation to mix this issue with the
findings of the Cox Commission on spying, with campaign
contribution issues and with anger at China's response to the
accidental bombing of their embassy in Belgrade. But to me it still
doesn't make sense to withdraw the one positive thing we have going
with the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration makes a similar case, arguing that even if
China has gone backward on human rights issues (by the State
Department's annual assessment) and security relations are tainted
by the spying report, Washington should not waver from its trade
policies.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House's argument in favor of engagement is running
into increasing opposition precisely because the predicted results
have hardly materialized.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton switched sides on this debate in 1994 and decided
to separate the annual trade accord from China's human rights
record, he argued that deeper economic engagement would inevitably
open up the country to a more progressive view of rights. He made
that case again Thursday in a written statement, saying trade would
spread ``the tools, the contacts and ideas that promote freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree that is clearly the case: e-mail has changed the
way Chinese communicate with the outside world, and American
companies in China have pressed for clearer laws and insisted on
enforcement of international copyright rules and other conventions.
But China still imprisons dissidents and suppresses challenges to
the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there is growing pressure on the White House to
include at least some vague commitments on human rights in any
agreement to get China into the World Trade Organization. ``Members
will need some cover to retreat from their past positions,'' said
Mike Jendrzejczyk, the Washington director of Human Rights
Watch/Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But given its current mood, and the anti-American demonstrations
on the streets last month, China seems unlikely to let noneconomic
commitments into its WTO accord.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are badly split. Thursday the House Budget Committee
chairman, John Kasich, R-Ohio, said that at a time of espionage
charges, renewing China's trade status ``sends the wrong message at
the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was in sharp contrast to Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who
warned last week that this year's renewal ``could be in some
jeopardy'' if continued revelations about China ``poison the
environment.'' He has argued for a more tempered approach, one that
recognizes that `'we should not hold all of our other interests
hostage'' to China's behavior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
