<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH MORE TRUCKS ON THE ROAD, SHOULD SAFETY RULES CHANGE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rivers of cars may have the impression that there
are more big trucks competing with them for space on the highway,
and recent government statistics confirm that their perception is
correct. And although road fatalities are down over all, those
involving heavy trucks are fairly level, at more than 5,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   A booming economy combined with a shift to just-in-time
deliveries has meant a boom for the truck business. National
Transportation Safety Board Chairman James Hall pointed out in
recent testimony that the industry is producing about 220,000 heavy
trucks annually, up from 130,000 a decade ago. Transportation
Secretary Rodney Slater said the number of miles traveled by trucks
had increased 25 percent in the last four years, and the American
Trucking Associations said in May that mileage could rise 15
percent this year alone.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks are getting safer, but not fast enough to keep pace with
their increased use. Large trucks were involved in fatal crashes at
a rate of 2.5 for each 100 million miles traveled in 1997, the most
recent year for which full statistics are available. That is down
by more than half from 20 years earlier, when the rate was 5.4 for
each 100 million miles. (In comparison, the rate for cars in that
period fell to 1.9 from 3.5.)
</P>
<P>
   But truck miles traveled more than doubled in that period, to
191 billion miles from 95 billion miles, so the absolute number of
fatalities did not change much. The National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration, part of the Transportation Department, said in late
May that fatalities totaled 5,398 in 1997, of whom nearly all were
in a car, van, pickup or other light vehicle, not in the heavy
truck. The preliminary number for 1998 is 5,302. (The figures do
not measure whether the accident was the truck's fault.)
</P>
<P>
   Slater, speaking a day before a congressional hearing that
included testimony critical of his department's oversight, was
announcing a goal of reducing truck fatalities by 50 percent over
10 years. He had good reason to try to beat Congress to the punch:
A variety of critics, including his own department's inspector
general, trace safety shortcomings to his department's inspectors,
who these critics say seemed better suited to watching the large,
staid, regulated trucking companies of the past than to to keeping
an eye on the highly competitive, fast-moving swarms of small
operators that dominate the roads now.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is in such flux that the regulators have trouble
keeping track of it. Nearly 500,000 trucking companies are
registered with the department, but regulators say they think that
up to 30 percent have merged or gone out of business.
</P>
<P>
   A study released last week by former Rep. Norman Mineta, who was
chairman of the House Transportation Committee when he represented
a California district, said that companies less than three years
old had higher crash rates and more safety problems. Tens of
thousands of companies are less than three years old. The
Transportation Department had asked Mineta to do the study.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors spent many hours trying to educate companies on
safety procedures and Transportation Department regulations, said
Kenneth Mead, the inspector general. ``Partnership, collaboration
and education went too far,'' he said, with the department often
agreeing to forgo the collection of fines or other enforcement
measures in exchange for promises to do better. But he said a
significant minority of companies ``had no interest in being
educated.''
</P>
<P>
   One change announced by Slater is a limit on negotiated
settlements and ``wrist slaps,'' and an emphasis on bigger fines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that harsh penalties should replace
education and warnings. The American Trucking Associations,
reacting to a slight decline in deaths in 1998 from the year
before, said this showed the success of ``government partnership in
safety education and outreach programs.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government, though, is moving to get tougher. Slater said
another goal was to double the number of ``compliance reviews,'' or
in-depth examinations of trucking companies, done by each
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   The department is also trying to streamline the legal framework
for ordering bad carriers to shut down. Federal law used to require
that the department show a company was an ``imminent hazard''
before it could bar the company, but Mead said the department never
had a working definition of imminent hazard. A law that took effect
this spring changes the standard to ``unfit,'' and the department
is trying to establish a regulation that defines the term.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Claybrook, a former administrator of the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration who is now president of Public
Citizen, a nonprofit advocacy group, said the problem was that the
Transportation Department lacked the research and data base to make
good decisions, as well as ``a capacity to plan or meet deadlines
for issuance of safety standards.'' Many safety advocates outside
the department want truck regulation moved to the traffic safety
administration from its current home in the Office of Motor
Carriers, which they say shares the perspective of the trucking
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Slater has resisted the change and pointed to an improving level
of safety which, he said, can be made better yet. Safety experts
say that the biggest improvement in the last few years has been
requiring a commercial driver's license under a national system.
That prevents truckers from carrying licenses issued by several
states and accumulating violations on each.
</P>
<P>
   But Federal Highway Administrator Kenneth Wykle said regulators
had yet to use violations accrued on personal licenses, like
speeding or drunken driving, as a basis for revoking a commercial
license. Truckers involved in fatal accidents are often discovered
to have such violations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest unsolved question is hours-of-service regulations.
That, said Mead, is ``tied directly to fatigue.'' There are limits
on how many hours a trucker can drive and how many he can be on
duty, including loading time, but they are widely flouted, partly
because drivers are paid by the mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with firms that create an environment or a
culture where drivers are expected to drive to exhaustion,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that the problem varies by the size of the company.
Big companies with deep pockets may fear liability suits and follow
the rules more closely; small ones often don't. But the industry is
heavy with small companies. Mead said that 317,000 companies have
six or fewer tractors; only 2,800 have more than 100 tractors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
