<HEADER>
A2179 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-SENATE-BOS &LR;      06-03 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK OF A RUN BY FIRST LADY HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It looks like she's really going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, it seems, is really going to run for the
US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The only other New York Democrat who has expressed interest in
the seat, Representative Nita Lowey of Long Island, called her
Thursday to say she has dropped her Senate plans and will run for
reelection.
</P>
<P>
   Lowey had been saying for months that she would not mount a
campaign for the Senate seat if Clinton ran for it _ and Thursday,
the congresswoman said, it looked more and more clear that the
first lady is going to run.
</P>
<P>
   In reply, Clinton offered no encouragement to Lowey, nor did she
dispel the premise of her decision. Rather, in a written statement
issued through her press office, she said, ``I thank Nita for her
support. I look forward to working with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's chief political adviser, Harold Ickes, turned this
eyebrow-raising development into a tempest when he told the
Associated Press, later in the day, that the first lady ``has every
intention of setting up an exploratory committee'' for a Senate bid
``in early July.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's politics, that is practically the same thing as
tossing your hat in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this tantamount to declaring her candidacy for the
Senate?'' mused Hank Sheinkopf, a leading Democratic consultant
here. ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Ickes backpedaled Thursday evening and said in phone interview:
``If I said what I was quoted as saying, I overstated things. Mrs.
Clinton is going to continue to press forward, as she has in the
past. But no decision has been made about an exploratory
committee.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a source close to Clinton said, on condition of
anonymity, ``Mrs. Lowey's no longer in, Mrs. Clinton has said she
very much wants a Democrat to keep that Senate seat, and there's no
other candidate standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollster John Zogby made a point that follows that logic to the
next step: ``What if she doesn't run now? She will have shafted New
York Democrats in a big way. They had no other candidate.'' Zogby's
conclusion: ``She's running.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, people close to New York City Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani _ who has already formed an exploratory committee _ have
said in recent days that he will ``definitely'' run for the Senate
if Clinton is his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's chomping at the bit for her,'' one associate said.
</P>
<P>
   So, the race that every politician, bookie, and newspaper
columnist in the state has been pining for seems about to come
true.
</P>
<P>
   Forming an explorary committee is particularly crucial for
Clinton because it will allow her to raise campaign funds and,
therefore, pay for trips to New York out of her own budget. In her
increasingly frequent trips here lately, she has scheduled enough
appearances that could be deemed ``official White House business''
to justify flying on a government plane. However, as these trips
have become more obviously political, she has been criticized for
campaigning at taxpayers' expense.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts of both parties agree that Clinton comes into this race
with a long list of pluses and minuses, many of them stemming from
the same set of qualities.
</P>
<P>
   When politicos started buzzing about a possible
Hillary-for-Senate campaign late last year _ at first, as a lark,
with no authorization or even apparent interest from the first lady
herself _ polls showed her beating Giuliani, in a hypothetical
race, by over 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, every poll shows a very tight contest. Some show her
winning, some show her losing, but in every case, the margin of
victory or defeat is narrower than the poll's statistical margin of
error.
</P>
<P>
   They all show Clinton winning big in New York City, where the
population is overwhelmingly Democratic. They also show her
winning, generally, among blacks, Hispanics, union workers, and _
though not by much _ women.
</P>
<P>
   However, the polls show her losing in the suburbs, upstate, and
among white men.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone expects it to be one of the closest, most bitterly
fought, and most amply funded Senate races next year.
</P>
<P>
   The polls suggest one major issue will be the charge that
Hillary Rodham Clinton is a ``carpetbagger,'' someone who has never
lived in New York, rarely walked down any of its sidewalks, and who
is using the state for her own national ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that more than 40 percent of voters are concerned
about Clinton's nonresident status _ even though she has said she
will move to New York after leaving the White House, no matter
what. The issue has also become a guaranteed laugh-and-applause
line in Republican speeches across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats dismiss the concern, pointing out that Robert F.
Kennedy was elected senator here in 1964, despite his obvious
Boston accent.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sheinkopf, who hastened to note that he supports
Clinton, said the carpetbagger label could hurt her. ``People
forget RFK was the brother of the slain president,'' he said.
``They also forget Lyndon Johnson won New York state that year by
over 2 million votes. Al Gore isn't going to win New York state by
that much. Bobby also spent time in his youth in New York. And _
not least _ he was Irish Catholic. The Catholic vote determines
outcome in this state. And Catholics usually elect Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of recent Catholic officeholders in New York is
impressive: Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan (who is retiring from
the Senate seat in contention), Governor George Pataki, former
governors Mario Cuomo and Hugh Carey _ and Giuliani.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
