<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTEMPT-JEWEL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 reporters ordered jailed in Jewell suit
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two reporters for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
must go to jail until they reveal confidential sources for stories
about former Olympic bombing suspect Richard Jewell, the judge in
Jewell's defamation suit ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's attorneys immediately appealed to a higher
court, blocking enforcement of the contempt order by Fulton County
State Court Judge John Mather until the appeal is settled.
</P>
<P>
   That could take up to a year, said Lin Wood, Jewell's lead
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell, a security guard at Centennial Olympic Park when a bomb
exploded in July 1996, was initially lauded for spotting the
knapsack that held the explosive. An Albany woman died and 111
people were hurt in the blast.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal-Constitution was first to report that he was a
subject of the criminal investigation. Federal authorities cleared
him of any wrongdoing in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Jewell sued the newspaper in January 1997. His suit says
articles portrayed him as someone with a strange work history and
personality who probably was guilty. He is seeking tens of millions
of dollars in compensatory and punitive damages. He settled
lawsuits with CNN, NBC and a former employer, Piedmont College, for
undisclosed amounts.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute arose during pre-trial interviews when Jewell's
attorneys asked the reporters to identify law enforcement officials
who gave them information about Jewell. Mather ordered the
reporters to do so in April 1998. Georgia has a law that protects
reporters from naming sources in some instances, but Mather wrote
that the law does not apply when the reporters are parties to a
lawsuit or criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   Mather twice again ordered the reporters, Kathy Scruggs and Ron
Martz, to comply, writing in March that a recent state Supreme
Court decision supports ``what is apparent'' in the law.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper again refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's indulgence has now expired,'' Mather wrote
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He found the reporters ``in civil contempt'' and ``in willful
and continued disobedience of this court's directives.'' He wrote
that they have until 2 p.m. Saturday to report to the Fulton County
Jail, but added that an appeal would prevent their jailing while
the Georgia Court of Appeals considers the case.
</P>
<P>
   The state Supreme Court also might be asked to decide the issue
after the Court of Appeals, but it could decline.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for both sides said they expect to win on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge has ruled correctly, and, really, this was the only
thing he could do,'' Wood said. ``The newspaper and these reporters
never gave him any options.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper attorney Peter Canfield said Mather's order was
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that the appellate courts will find this order
unnecessary and that this whole case should have been thrown out a
long time ago because the Journal-Constitution's reporting was
accurate,'' Canfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, 17 reporters have been held for contempt of
court since 1984, some for just a few hours, said Jane Kirtley of
the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press in Washington.
Only one case, in 1984, involved libel. Currently, three other
reporters in the United States are fighting judges' efforts to jail
them for refusing court orders, all in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
