<HEADER>
A2181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE04-COX     06-03 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. gives Dole fund-raising boost in home state
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Four months after she announced her
presidential aspirations to shouts of ``Run, Liddy, run,''
Elizabeth Dole returned to North Carolina this week seeking a
down-home boost to her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In $1,000-a-person gatherings in Charlotte and Greensboro, the
former American Red Cross president who served in the Bush and
Reagan cabinets raised an estimated $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to speak at a Virginia high school graduation today
and resume campaigning Saturday in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bless your heart,'' Dole told nearly 200 supporters who lined
up Thursday to meet the undeclared presidential candidate at the
Greensboro City Club, a private facility atop the city's tallest
building.
</P>
<P>
   But the Salisbury native hasn't been able to quiet doubts that
she remains a longshot to become the first woman to win the
presidency. Also uncertain is whether ``North Carolina's favorite
daughter'' _ as her supporters affectionately call her _ can defeat
Texas Gov. George W. Bush Jr., even in her home state. She trails
Bush for the Republican presidential nomination in national
fund-raising and in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, the presidential primary will be held May 2,
two months after California, New York, Georgia and numerous other
states hold primaries that could give Bush a nearly insurmountable
lead, if his campaign doesn't falter.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina will send 62 delegates to the Republican National
Convention, a relatively small number that suggests Dole is
campaigning in the state more to raise money than to win votes.
</P>
<P>
   Dole needs to step up fund-raising dramatically the rest of the
year or risk being far behind Bush going into the big advertising
blitz preceding next May's primary, said Dan Gurley, political
director of the North Carolina Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Dole is in the midst of a two-month tour that has raised nearly
$1.2 million, on top of $686,000 she reported raising through
March. Bush, the son of former President George Bush, has raised
more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember that we've only been at this for four
months,'' Dole said, adding that recent overflow crowds at campaign
events suggest her campaign is gaining steam.
</P>
<P>
   So far, two of North Carolina's seven Republicans in the U.S.
House have endorsed Dole. Two have endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Coble (R-Greensboro), who endorsed Dole, said he is
puzzled by others' reluctance to do so. ``Not only is she
qualified, she is my neighbor down the road,'' Coble said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of everyday Republican politicians apparently see Bush
as a more likely presidential nominee than Dole,'' said Ferrel
Guillory, director of the Program on Southern Politics, Media and
Public Life at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   After her speech, Dole's supporters gathered round her. Some who
haven't yet decided to vote for her said they respected her
straight talk on controversial topics, such as gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ''Elizabeth Dole is a North Carolina girl,'' said former
Greensboro Mayor Jim Melvin. ''That is enough reason to support
her.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Elizabeth Dole is a great leader, and she will definitely make
a substantial mark,'' said Kathy Lubbers, daughter of former House
Speaker Newt Gingrich. She owns Carolina Coffee in Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   If Dole decides to seek the presidency, her official
announcement would likely come in September, said Ari Fleischer,
Dole's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Talk in Republican circles has swirled around prospects for a
Bush-Dole ticket, a combination that pundits say would appeal to
conservative Republicans as well as women of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Dole nor her Greensboro supporters were inclined to talk
about that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not doing this to be vice president,'' said Dole, who
drew rousing applause when she said she looked forward to riding in
Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   She walked into the crowd during a 40-minute speech, saying it
feels ''great to be back in my stomping grounds where I do not need
an interpreter.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of her toughest talk centered on gun control, an issue she
said might cost her Republican support.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can you think of any reason a family needs an AK-47 or an Uzi
to protect their family or go hunting?'' asked Dole, who favors
child safety locks on guns and instant background checks on people
trying to buy guns.
</P>
<P>
   While Dole did not mention Bush or Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic presidential front-runner, she criticized the Clinton
administration's foreign policy, particularly in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ''This country has no comprehensive foreign policy at this time
_ all of the stops and the starts and the threats that have not
been carried out,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
