<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Columbine students' visit helps heal Georgia counterparts
 &HT;    By Leon Stafford
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Heritage High School students have been offered
extensive counseling and support over the last two weeks, but a
concerned community couldn't really speak from experience about the
emotional aftermath of knowing that a classmate had chosen to open
fire on the student body.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, some of them met with five students from Littleton,
Colo., who had the misfortune to be uniquely qualified for the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a lot of people to tell us they understand what we
were going through, and they don't,'' said Heritage junior Zach
Moore, 16. Of his new friends from Colorado, he said, ``They
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Five students from the Littleton, Colo., school met with their
counterparts from Heritage at Smyrna Presbyterian Church's
campground in Conyers. They laughed, listened to music and talked
about grades, their plans for the summer and the future.
</P>
<P>
   They also talked about their painful past. Heritage sophomore
Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon opened fire on his classmates May 20,
exactly one month after the shooting at Columbine. Six students
were injured at Heritage, but none died. A teacher and 14 students,
including the two attackers, died at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're miles and miles apart, but we have so much in common
now,'' said Columbine student Michael Staver.
</P>
<P>
   That shared experience is what brought the Columbine students _
all rising seniors _ to Rockdale. While many people reached out to
help the Columbine students after the shootings took place,
conspicuously missing were representatives from schools where there
had been previous shootings, said Columbine student Barbara
Schnieder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have helped us an awful lot, if someone from one of
the other schools had come and talked to us,'' she said. ``It took
us a month to get over this. We are just hoping to speed things up
for the Heritage kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine students came up with the idea of visiting
Rockdale during an English class. They called the Rockdale school
system, which told them that an event for Heritage students was
being planned at Smyrna Presbyterian. The students then talked to
the Symrna organizers, who agreed to house them in the campground
cabins and to pay for meals. Delta Air Lines provided the
transportation. The students will fly home this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Two Columbine parents and a teacher from the school also
attended the gathering. They declined to speak to the media but met
with parents and faculty later in the evening. Security was tight
around the event, and reporters were kept away.
</P>
<P>
   While event organizers provided music and an opportunity for
Heritage students to sign each other's yearbooks, the Columbine
students became the focal point of much of the day, said Georgia
Conner, Christian Education Youth director for Conyers Presbyterian
Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times there would be one or two Columbine students
surrounded by a large number of Heritage students,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helped the healing process for us,'' said Heritage
student Kent Harris, 16. ``It is good. It's been fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine students also went bowling Wednesday and visited
Heritage to see what the school looked like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really surreal,'' Schnieder said. ``It was eerie
because it made me think that it really wasn't that different.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
