<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ETHICS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEFENSE OF THE SINGLE AND CHILDLESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine working for a company that bases compensation on family
status. If you have a spouse and children, you are paid more, even
though single, childless employees seem to work longer hours.
Singles hardly ever reach the highest levels of management. And the
company does just about everything it can to discourage single
employees from mating.
</P>
<P>
   Outrageous, no? You'd expect activists to be screaming about
such blatant discrimination, and lawyers to be filling the courts
with briefs.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, though, many American companies, hectored from almost
every side to make the workplace ``family friendly,'' are moving in
exactly that direction. Magazines heap laurels on the best
workplaces for working mothers, with their flexible hours, on-site
child care and so forth. But who extols companies that treat
everyone equally, regardless of family status?
</P>
<P>
   Many companies blithely discriminate against childless singles
by offering employee benefits that are worth most to people with
families: health and life insurance, subsidized child care,
pensions with survivors' benefits and so on. Those goodies add up
to a major workplace inequality that stands unchallenged despite
universal obeisance to the concept of equal pay for equal work.
</P>
<P>
   Workplace favoritism for ``family men'' over ``career girls''
has historically been a nemesis of equal-rights advocates. Remember
the episode of the ``Mary Tyler Moore Show'' in which Mary learned
that a man in her job was paid more? The reason should be obvious,
Lou Grant replied, as bosses have for decades: The guy's got a
family.
</P>
<P>
   If the equal-pay part of the equation is skewed, so is the idea
of equal work. Who stays behind, after all, when the mom-and-dad
exodus begins at 5:30 p.m.? Who shoulders the extra office burdens
when a co-worker stays home with a sick child?
</P>
<P>
   All of this buys singles no altitude on the corporate ladder.
Unmarried chief executives are a theoretical possibility, but
rarely found in nature.
</P>
<P>
   It's a miracle that most childless singles _ nearly one-third of
all workers _ don't stay that way. In recent years, frantic efforts
to desexualize the workplace may have had the unintended effect of
forestalling matrimony for singles who spend so much time on the
job they can't possibly meet people anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   For every harasser or adulterer deterred by the reintroduction
of taboos against office romance, dozens of potential healthy
relationships must be nipped in the bud. Talk about a hostile work
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Policies that hurt singles probably land hardest on gay people,
who cannot marry their partners, and, in most jobs, cannot even
obtain benefits for them. It's a rare company these days that will
acknowledge paying less or denying a promotion because an employee
is gay, even in states with no laws forbidding it. Yet companies
are proud of pro-family policies having the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   Workers almost never claim discrimination for being single and
childless. One reason is that they lack the protected status of
other groups. Another may be that single, childless people like the
environment at companies with family benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Levey, a management consultant with WFD Inc. in Boston,
cites a ``halo effect'' that makes everyone feel better about
companies that treat families well.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the work burden may not be as unequal as people
think. Mary B. Young of Boston University, who is writing a book
about work-life issues for singles, surveyed employees at two large
companies and found no difference in work time between childless
singles and others, though nearly all thought singles worked
longer.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that market forces are alleviating the problem.
Many companies, especially small ones, are shifting the costs of
employee benefits to workers or scrapping benefits entirely,
producing a kind of equity of misery.
</P>
<P>
   And for the growing legions of self-employed in the new
``free-agent economy,'' it's strictly fee for services regardless
of one's home life. So you may get the fairest shake when you work
on your own. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Akst is a novelist and financial journalist. His column
tilting at conventional business wisdom will appear the first
Sunday of each month. E-mail may be sent to
culmoney(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
