<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER REDUCES CAMPAIGN OPERATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with the difficulties of raising money in a
crowded Republican field, GOP presidential contender Lamar
Alexander scaled back his campaign operation, his aides said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The former Tennessee governor will be reducing staff and
concentrating limited resources on staging an upset victory in the
first caucuses in Iowa in February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign advisers acknowledge that Alexander has had a tough
time raising money because GOP front-runner George W. Bush has been
so successful in vacuuming up cash around the country. Bush aides
say the Texas governor is expected to have raised $15.2 million by
the end of this month, a record at this stage of a White House
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tough fund-raising environment right now,'' said Tom
Rath, a top Alexander adviser in New Hampshire. Rath said the
perception of Bush as the front-runner has ``impeded the cash flow
to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You got Bush and you got the rest of us,'' said Alexander's
political director Brian Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is expected to raise about $2.5 million by the end of
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the staff will be reduced from 38 to 34, with the
communications director and legal and research staffers among those
to be let go.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kennedy also said the campaign will be beefing up its
Iowa operation in the hopes of breaking through in that key primary
state.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any place that the Alexander operation has a chance
to shake up the conventional wisdom it is in Iowa, where the
candidate has built up an impressive grass-roots operation headed
by Republican former Gov. Terry Branstad.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign officials are hoping that if they can stage a
surprise upset, first in an Iowa straw poll in August, and later in
the Iowa caucuses next February they will improve their
fund-raising prospects and ability to compete in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign has always been about a strong showing in Iowa.
It is the ignition point,'' said Steve Schmidt, who will leave his
post as Alexander's communication director July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said he will continue as a consultant to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers say that Alexander has had more difficulty
making headway this time than during his first unsuccessful bid for
the White House in 1996. A centrist Republican, not only is he
competing with Bush for the establishment GOP vote, but also with
former Red Cross chief Elizabeth Dole and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz
_ both of whom are better known among voters.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has consistently trailed these candidates in national
and statewide polls.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Stuart Rothenberg said the Alexander campaign
is ``nowhere in the national polls and not where they should be in
the early primary polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg said that Bush, McCain and Dole would benefit if
Alexander were to drop out.
</P>
<P>
   McCain added celebrity luster to his campaign Thursday with the
announcement that cosmetic queen Georgette Mosbacher has been named
his national co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Mosbacher's decision to join the McCain campaign could be seen
as a snub of Bush, particularly since she was once married to
prominent Houstonian Robert Mosbacher, an old friend of the Bush
family and President Bush's former Commerce Secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Mosbacher is a Republican National committeewoman from New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
