<HEADLINE>
HARVARD AND YALE, PLUS HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. _ History. Tradition. Blood, sweat, and tears.
These are the ingredients that make up the Harvard-Yale regatta,
which will be held for the 135th time Saturday afternoon on the
Thames River.
</P>
<P>
   This matchup, the oldest intercollegiate competition in the
nation dating back to 1852, on New Hampshire's Lake Winnipesaukee,
is gut-wrenching. When the varsity shells square off for the 4-mile
downstream test every oarsman is ready to sacrifice his body for 22
minutes of nonstop rowing.
</P>
<P>
   The races start at 3:45 p.m. when Harvard's undefeated freshman
boat seeks to extend its record to 9-0 over a spunky 4-2 Yale boat.
The Harvard freshmen hope to remain undefeated for their trip to
the Henley Regatta in England later this month when they vie for
the Temple Cup, a trophy Yale's freshmen won in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the second varsity race, Yale's boat (no seniors) is 4-1.
Harvard's boat has a 4-2 record and has two seniors aboard.
</P>
<P>
   This is Harvard coach Harry Parker's 37th H-Y regatta. He has a
31-5 mark against the Eli and he's as eager for this race as his
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ultimate challenge for us,'' said Parker. ``This
is the only 4-miler and I love it. I do it for fun. I'm still
fascinated by this race. Every year you attempt to make your boat
go faster. If you get bored with a race like this then you have a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years the equipment has changed, but the athletes are
the same as 30 years ago. They work hard, they're dedicated, and
they work as a team. Really, very little has changed over the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard has won the varsity eights 13 of the last 14 years and
34 of the last 40. ``Forget the records,'' said Parker. ``You need
a solid performance every year from mostly different people. This
is a race you have to want badly and you go after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard captain Henry Nuzum has a 2-0 record against Yale's
heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   Nuzum of Chapel Hill, N.C., coxswain Jason Kastner of Naples,
Fla., and stroke Dan Dias of Ocala, Fla., are the only ones back
from last year's boat.
</P>
<P>
   While Harvard's varsity boats are the same as they were at the
Eastern Sprints, Yale coach Dave Vogel has made some changes. Alex
Reid moved from No. 6 to stroke; Mark McCusker from stroke to No.
7; James Donahue from No. 7 to No. 4; Robert Welhoelter from No. 5
to No. 3; captain James Needham from No. 4 to No. 6; sophomore
Scott Proper moved from second varsity stroke to No. 5, replacing
sophomore Robert Wesh, who joins the second varsity boat. Bowman
Lucas McLoughlin and No. 2 Hans von Trotha remain in their places.
</P>
<P>
   Needham rowed in all the varsity races a year ago and was moved
to the second varsity for the Harvard regatta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my last chance and I want to take advantage of it,''
he said. ``I worked extra hard last summer and got down from 215
pounds to 195 and I'm rowing better. We've been down here for
practice for three weeks and we had some great workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to beat Harvard badly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
