u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-03 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF HITS THE HIGH NOTES IN WIN OVER SELES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Did Richard Wagner, the old German tunesmith, have a
vision of Steffi Graf when he chose the legendary and indomitable
warrior Brunhilde as the bold heroine of one of his operas? Same
kind of ladies Brunhilde, the valkyrie, and Steffi, the valiant.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Brunhilde swung a battle ax _ but no more wickedly
than Steffi swung her tennis racket at Monica Seles Thursday to
bring down the house of 16,000 scrunched into Stade Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   Soap operas, horse operas, and Wagner's kind, lyric operas . . .
elements of all were on display as dust swirled and gusted across
the earthen battleground of the French Open, and Graf stormed
through the crimson haze, 6-7 (2-7), 6-3, 6-4, to yet another
height that had seemed beyond her in her supposedly declining days.
</P>
<P>
   Three years had passed and numerous disabling wounds incurred
since Graf last graced a major final, the US Open. Nevertheless,
here she is again, in the French title bout for a ninth time (tying
Chris Evert's record), yearning to beat up Saturday on a kiddie who
lifted her No. 1 rating and declared 29-year-old Steffi passe a
couple of years ago: Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, 18, arrived in the rarest of all French semis _ each of
the final four had held No. 1 _ feeling deprived. ``I'm the only
one who hasn't won here,'' she says, believing it's her turn now
after deposing Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, the 1998 champ, in a 6-3,
6-2 breeze. Graf, Seles, and Sanchez Vicario have won 11 of the
last dozen championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I have surprised even myself,'' Graf is saying, her
riveting blue eyes gleeful and flaxen hair let down and sweeping
across her face as she laughs. ``Monica beat me badly in Australia
and Serena (Williams) at The Lipton. My last tournament, Berlin, I
was a disaster (a loss to Julie Halard-Decugis). I just hoped to
get through a few matches here to get ready for Wimbledon, which I
thought was the only big one I could win anymore. But . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Those eyes were filled with red dirt at one point, and she had
to summon a trainer to wash them out. She might have been washed
out herself then, down a set. But she had resorted to a dainty,
seldom-used trick _ a drop shot _ to go ahead, 3-1, in the second
and life looked better, when she could see again.
</P>
<P>
   And those eyes dripped with tears as Steffi departed the court
where she has ruled France five times since winning her first of 21
majors 12 years ago. Quickly she mopped them aside before entering
a German TV studio to address her homeland. ``I don't like to be
seen crying. But there was a feeling of such joy. I couldn't help
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she thought about what she, Fraulein Forehand, and Monica
had done to each other once again to illumine the tournament. They
took us back to 1992 in the same arena _ their last collision in
Paris _ a final that was a tennis version of the horse operatic OK
Corral. Oh, how they'd plugged away at each other for 2 3/4 hours
before Seles was left standing, 6-2, 3-6, 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is one defeat that stays with me,'' Steffi says. ``No, I
wasn't thinking about it today. There was no revenge thing. But it
felt so good to be in the same kind of match on the same court, and
hang in to win like she did back then. It was fun to be part of it,
to know I could still play that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Since, they'd gone through so much genuine soap opera stuff:
Monica's stabbing and her father's death, Steffi's aberrant father
cheating on income tax and going to jail, as well as a slew of
injuries for both. Steffi had been hurt by the conventional wisdom
that she won five of her majors only because Monica was absent,
recovering. ``It bothered me for a while, but no more.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, OK Corral, the sequel, they used nearly 2 hours, and
used up each other _ ``my legs were heavy at the end, and I'm sure
Monica's were, too'' _ as the crowd urged them onward. When it
appeared Graf had broken ahead for good at 2-0 in the third, Seles
countered with a run of three games and would lead, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the end. ``I had to risk more, go for my shots,''
Steffi recalls. ``She got more aggressive, and won,'' says Monica.
Despite her gritty exertions and lusty double-barreled groundies,
Steffi was pouring on her own mammoth forehands. And she was
slicingly neutralizing Monica with a crosscourt backhand that
sizzled as low and dangerously as a rattlesnake in the grass.
</P>
<P>
   From 3-4, Steffi was an in-tune and merciless Brunhilde in a
mini and sneakers. She seemed to be wearing valkyrie armor, too,
because there was nothing Monica could do. She seized 12 of the
last 14 points, closing with a battle-axing 100 mile-per-hour
service winner.
</P>
<P>
   If Richard Wagner had been in the audience, he would have
declared, ``Steffi is my kind of Valkyrie. She had to zing for her
supper, and hit C above high C.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
