<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: BUSH SIGNS CONSUMER TAX CUTS INTO LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
and LISA DAVIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As a crowd of shoppers and sales clerks watched from
the men's underwear and women's hats sections, Gov. George W. Bush
signed into law a set of consumer tax cuts Thursday at Foley's
downtown department store.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sat in the boy's clothing corner while signing the bill,
emphasizing that it eliminates the sales tax on clothing and shoes
bought Aug. 6-8, just before the start of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rodney Ellis, a Houston Democrat who shepherded the
legislation and represents the downtown area, said he picked the
regional retail store for the occasion because it is a symbol of
the city's commerce and the rejuvenation of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The store's executives backed the tax-break bill during the
legislative session, which ended this week. The new law is expected
to trigger back-to-school price reductions and shopper swarms.
</P>
<P>
   The law also repeals sales taxes on over-the-counter medicines
year-round starting in spring 2000, reduces taxes on Internet
service starting in October, and provides tax breaks for small
businesses and for research and development. In Houston, state,
regional and local sales taxes total 8.25 percent on retail
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to touch a lot of lives,'' Bush said.
``Certainly that was the intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Flush with tax revenues in a booming economy, the Texas
Legislature produced a series of sales and property tax cuts that
tracked some _ but not all _ of Bush's campaign promises before his
re-election last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had called for elimination of the sales tax on diapers and
school supplies as well as clothing, but those items will not be
exempt. Nor will clothing and shoes manufactured for athletic use.
</P>
<P>
   But for anyone outside of Texas looking to see how the results
reflect on his status as a front-runner for the Republican
nomination for president, Bush saw only positives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are watching to determine whether I can set an
agenda, that I can work with people from both political parties and
achieve an agenda,'' he said. ``I think they are trying to
determine whether I am the kind of fellow who does (what) I say I
will do out on the campaign trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife, Laura, were to attend a reception for
campaign contributors late Thursday at a Houston hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Housemaid Ann Joshua, invited to the ceremony because she cleans
Ellis' house, poured on the praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will mean a lot to hundreds of grandparents and
parents like myself in purchasing clothing for our school children
so that they can look good as well as learn well,'' she
said.``Because when children look well they learn better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At suburban shopping centers Thursday, the law got a generally
positive reaction from shoppers _ with a few reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``All kids need athletic shoes and most people have to buy them
every year because kids wear them out in gym class,'' said Kim
Penrod, who was shopping for her nephew at Montgomery Ward in a
Houston-area mall. ``If they really wanted to help the parents they
would have included the athletic apparel You can always get shirts
and shorts cheap, but good deals on shoes are harder to find.''
</P>
<P>
   As a mother of four, however, Nautasha Randall said she would
take the help any way it comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pretty much already giving you a break, so it doesn't
have to be on everything,'' Randall said.
</P>
<P>
   Because buying clothes for so many children is so expensive,
Randall said she had already started purchasing items to spread out
the costs, but would be willing to hold off on her purchases and
save until Aug. 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, these malls are going to be crazy,'' Randall said.
``It'll be like shopping after Thanksgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed that the savings would be worth postponing
shopping trips until August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to get back-to-school shopping done ahead of time
because school starts in August, but I'll wait to do it in August
to save money,'' said Eulona Simon, who was shopping at Kid Spot.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Harter, the mother of a 13-year-old and self-described
member of the upper-middle class, said she felt that finding time
to shop was hard enough without trying to schedule it for a
specific weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like a nice idea that would have the greatest impact
on low-income families,'' Harter said at another shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers appear unfamiliar with the new law and have not
yet planned any promotions of the tax exemption period in
conjunction with back-to-school advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an option to consider, but we don't have any plans
right now for that weekend,'' said Christina Kerford, a spokeswoman
for Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
