<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCH-WOMEN-710&AMP;     06-03 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-WOMEN-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD GUARD AND YOUNG BLOOD TO MEET IN FRENCH OPEN WOMEN'S FINAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Anybody else would be in traction by now, or resting on
her grand collection of Grand Slam laurels. But Steffi Graf, with
her aching spine and 29-year-old legs banished to the background
while a 22nd career Grand Slam singles title comes ever closer, has
never been one to take a shortcut when there is a more treacherous
route available.
</P>
<P>
   And no Grand Slam tournament presents a greater test of nerve
and verve than Roland Garros, where every match has marathon
potential. Those who flinch when clay grit gets in their eyes and
under their skin, as happened to Graf on this windy day, should
battle elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, a five-time French Open champion who won this title in
1996 but didn't play here last year because of knee surgery,
stormed into the final with a 6-7 (2-7), 6-3, 6-4 comeback against
Monica Seles, the player who defeated her for the 1992 title. The
25-year-old Seles couldn't quite match Graf's gumption on the
critical points of their 1-hour-56-minute semifinal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to take the risks I needed to, especially in the
end of the third set,'' said Graf, whose backhand slices slithered
over the net so low that Seles needed to kneel like a supplicant to
field them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After match point, it was extreme joy,'' the German said about
the instant when Seles buried a backhand return in the net, a
mistake that delivered Graf to her first Grand Slam final since she
collected the 1996 U.S. Open. ``It's great after a few years to be
in a final; it's something I really did not believe that I'd be
able to do when I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's final, Graf will wield a 6-2 record against
top-ranked Martina Hingis, a player who never doubted she would
reach the final here, the only Grand Slam to elude her grasp so
far. The 18-year-old Hingis lit herself a candle at Sacre Coeur
before this event began, and Thursday, after humbling its defending
champion, Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, 6-3, 6-2, she said she would not
return to the cathedral again until this title belongs to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go after and say, `Thank God,' if I win,'' Hingis said
of her celebration plans. ``If I lose, no.''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't lose often when Grand Slam titles are at stake. In
1997, when she was just 16, Hingis won all three other Grand Slams
but fell one victory short of a sweep when she fell to Iva Majoli
in the final here.
</P>
<P>
   She traced that blunder to the dent in her fitness that occurred
when she fell off a friend's horse and injured her knee during a
springtime ride. The tumble required arthroscopic surgery just
three weeks before the 1997 French Open, and Hingis ran out of
adrenaline and stamina in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hingis' bid for a French Open title was thwarted in
the semifinals by Seles, who turned in a monumental performance
three weeks after the death of her father/coach, Karolj.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Hingis did no riding before this tournament but just
practiced on the red clay after winning her warm-up event at the
German Open. Through six rounds here, she hasn't dropped a set, and
Thursday she needed just 63 minutes to reach her third consecutive
Grand Slam finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a tough opponent because she plays really fast and takes
the ball really early,'' said Sanchez-Vicario, now 1-10 against
Hingis. Thursday, the Spaniard, a three-time Roland Garros
champion, found herself in a 5-0 hole before she had even had time
to get her backhand drives oiled. ``She controls the ball really
well. She plays my backhand, and she mixes it up really well. I
give my best, but she was better.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, 19-1 on clay this season, was in complete agreement with
the loser's assessment. ``I think we have the same type of game,''
Hingis said, ``just me better in a way, that I have better shots,
better technique. I like playing her.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis ended things on triple match point with one of her better
shots, an inside out forehand that Sanchez-Vicario didn't even
bother to chase. Hingis claimed to like her chances against her
next veteran opponent, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steffi, with the absence of the last two years, if she would
make it to the finals, I hope she'll be a little nervous,'' said
Hingis, who also implied that Graf, with her five French Open
titles, ought to cede the spotlight to her. ``This is about time
for me, at least one.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Graf, whose resolve to grab a 22nd Grand Slam title before
she adopts less physical challenges, wasn't buying into Hingis'
share-the-wealth philosophy. Nor did she expect to be nervous on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure I'll just go out there and play, not really
worry too much about anything,'' said Graf, mindful that that
tactic worked beautifully Thursday after she dropped a difficult
opening set to Seles in a 7-2 tie breaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I lost the first set, I didn't have the feeling
that the match was over at all,'' Graf said. ``I think that showed
in the way I started the second set, I got an early break, and I
started again the third set extremely well with getting the
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Graf used a backhand drop shot to provoke the forehand error
that put her up by 3-1 in the second set and broke Seles at love in
the first game of the third. Again, it was a forehand mistake by
Seles, who continually felt the sting of Graf's backhand slice,
that gave Graf the break.
</P>
<P>
   Seles appeared to be hampered by her oversized racquet, which
seemed to catch the wind like a butterfly net, as well as by Graf's
attack of her forehand side. Graf, by keeping her slices low and
lethal, took away Seles' option of crackling off any down-the-line
winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt my forehand was not really working today, not just
even attacking, but even my defensive forehand was nowhere,'' Seles
said. ``I struggled, maybe because of the wind. I think today was
such extreme wind.''
</P>
<P>
   And such extreme joy for Graf, whose ninth trip to a French Open
final ties her for the record with Chris Evert, a seven-time
champion. When this tournament began, Graf, whose back problems
flared in her tune-up at Berlin, thought her appearance here would
be short-lived and predicted her best chance of winning a Grand
Slam this year would come at Wimbledon. Now she has changed her
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's Paris,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
