<SLUG> BC-TRADE-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TRADE REQUEST DRAWS MIXED REACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's request Thursday to renew trade
relations with China drew a mixed response in Congress, after
reports that China stole US nuclear secrets and the NATO bombing of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The White House proposal also coincided with the 10th
anniversary of the military crackdown in Tiananmen Square. That
event, symbolic in many quarters of a flawed Chinese record on
rights, continues to haunt US-China relations.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is likely to turn the annual White House request to
extend privileges, formerly known as ``most favored nation status''
and now as ``normal trade relations,'' into a referendum on policy
toward China.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is expected to renew the trade relations. But the vote
is expected to galvanize a potent anti-China bloc on upcoming
issues, including national security concerns and a vote on China's
membership in the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Congress, Clinton argued that the United States
is best served by improving relations with Beijing. Increasing
trade is the only way to promote reform within China, he said. And
he renewed his pledge to press for closer economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``A policy of disengagement and confrontation would only
strengthen those in China who oppose greater openness and
freedom,'' he wrote. ``Trade ... remains a force for social change
in China, spreading the tools, contacts and ideas that promote
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has 90 days decide on Clinton's request. Since 1980,
every president and Congress has favored trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect the administration will have a fight on their hands
when it comes to renewing normal trade relations with China,'' said
Senator John F. Kerry, a member of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee. ``I personally support the renewal ... and believe our
policies cannot be dictated by knee-jerk reactions to recent
events.''
</P>
<P>
   But other members, especially in the House, are expected to vote
against normal trade relations for a variety of reasons, including
allegations that China stole US nuclear secrets and meddled in US
elections, as well as increased tensions between the countries
since the accidental US bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as the president's timing is sad, so too is his policy,''
Representative Nancy Pelosi, a California Democrat, said in a
written statement. ``The administration's China policy has not
succeeded in making trade fairer, people freer, or the world
safer.''
</P>
<P>
   John Czwartacki, a spokesman for the Senate majority leader,
Trent Lott, said, ``Election fraud, Chinese espionage, and
technology transfers are not likely to help the president make his
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have threatened to make China an election issue, and
the Republican National Committee chairman, Jim Nicholson, issued a
harsh comment. ``Clinton and Gore have pursued a policy of
kowtowing appeasement,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican presidential contenders, Patrick J. Buchanan and
Gary Bauer, also seized on the announcement. They criticized what
both referred to as the ``Clinton-Gore'' China policy, and urged
Congress to vote no on the trade status and the World Trade
Organization membership for China.
</P>
<P>
   But Governor George W. Bush of Texas, and Elizabeth Dole, the
former Red Cross president, backed Clinton's request.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the United States must ``constructively work with
China'' and supports Clinton on seeking to expand trade with
Beijing, said a spokesman, David Beckwith. `
</P>
<P>
   Dole, a former Cabinet secretary, ``supports allowing China to
maintain normal trade relations not pulling the rug out from
American companies trading with China,'' said her spokesman, Ari
Fleischer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
