u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      06-03 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAUGES MIXED IN ANTICIPATION OF JOBS DATA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices meandered to a mixed finish Thursday as
traders and investors awaited Friday's release of the government's
monthly report on the job market, which will provide the first
broad look at the economy's performance in May.
</P>
<P>
   An overly robust reading, analysts think, will make it more
likely that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates _ a
development already anticipated in the futures markets _ at its
two-day policy meeting later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were just trying to jockey for position before
tomorrow's big report,'' said Donald M. Selkin, chief market
strategist at Joseph Gunnar &AMP; Company. ``The key thing to watch is
the average hourly earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of a possible peace agreement in Yugoslavia made little
impression because weeks of bombing were regarded as having played
little role in the spring retreat from record highs. European
markets, however, were thought likely to benefit from an end to
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the Nasdaq composite index made the widest swing, but
in contrast to its performance on Wednesday, it weakened in the
afternoon and finished with a loss of 29.09 points, or 1.2 percent,
to 2,403.32, just above its low of the day. Internet stocks were
among the chief casualties, with conditions so soft that at least
two initial public offerings were postponed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, on the other hand, surged in
the final 15 minutes of trading and ended with a gain of 85.80
points, or eight-tenths of a percent, to 10,663.69. American
Express, the biggest contributor to the advance of the blue-chip
index, gained 3 3/16, to 121|.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, meanwhile, scarcely
budged, ending with a gain of 4.73 points, or four-tenths of a
percent, to 1,299.54, as 267 of its components rose and 212
declined.
</P>
<P>
   Strong reports of May sales lifted retail stocks, with Dollar
General up 3 1/16, to 30, Wal-Mart Stores up 1[, to 45{, and Best
Buy, whose president forecast better-than-expected first-quarter
earnings, up 7 7/16, to 55 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks, which have been out of favor recently, posted good
gains despite a report that President Clinton is close to a
decision involving Medicare overhaul that would allow the elderly
to pay less for prescription drugs. Pfizer climbed 2\, to 108{,
while Merck, Eli Lilly and Warner-Lambert each gained more than a
point.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of oil-service companies were mostly higher, with
Schlumberger, which was added to the recommended list at Goldman,
Sachs, rising 7/16, to 60 7/16, after trading as high as 62 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage stocks continued to reel from Merrill Lynch's decision
to offer low-cost online trading. Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
slumped 2\, to 57[, and Knight/Trimark fell 2|, to 50|, but Paine
Webber, which replaced Bankers Trust in the S.&AMP; P. 500 after the
close, advanced 15/16, to 42}.
</P>
<P>
   Zany Brainy, a retailer of toys, games and books, made its
market debut with the sale of 6.1 million shares at 10. The stock
traded as high as 13[ before closing at 11 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks resumed their slide. Yahoo fell 7[, to 135]; At
Home slumped 9 3/16, to 105\; Star Media dropped 8 11/16, to 40\;
Ebay slid 7{, to 161 5/16; Priceline.com fell 8 25/32, to 84[, and
Amazon.com declined 7 1/16, to 105 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was a moderate 733.3 million shares on the New York Stock
Exchange, up from Wednesday's 730.5 million, with advancing issues
surpassing declining ones by 1,624 to 1,325. There were 48 new
highs over the last 12 months and 45 new lows.
</P>
</TEXT>
