<SLUG> BC-TV-CHAMPIONSHIP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAKE OF `CHAMPIONSHIP SEASON' MISSES THE MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In updating ``That Championship Season,'' director Paul Sorvino
and playwright Jason Miller have made a dramatic statement that, in
the parlance of basketball, looks good when it leaves the shooter's
hands but ends up clanging off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   At least it's not an air ball. But you must remember this: A
miss is a just a miss, unless it's a remake of a remake, in which
case you should hit nothing but net.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Championship Season'' is Miller's Pulitzer Prize-winning
story about the reunion of a high school basketball team that won
the Pennsylvania state title. As a play, it made its debut in 1972
to wide acclaim. Ten years later, it became a film that was
whistled for several fouls, not the least of which was boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rousing individiual performances from a first-string
cast, the new version airing Sunday on Showtime premium cable
commits a similar violation. Over two long hours, the emotions of
five men are dragged over hot coals, stomped on, run through a meat
grinder and skewered. There's plenty of dramatics, but not much
drama, and the effect is enervating, not energizing.
</P>
<P>
   The blame has to rest with Sorvino, who obviously has a love
affair with Miller's story. In both the Broadway play and the
Miller-directed 1982 film, he played Phil Romano, one of the
ex-hoopsters celebrating the anniversary of the high school team's
state championship. This time, besides directing his first film and
moving the original story from the '70s to the '90s, Sorvino plays
Coach, at whose home four of the champions gather for a little
camaraderie, a little reminiscing and a lot of drinking. The fifth
member of the team _ the guy who made the winning basket _ stays
away, but we don't know why until almost the end of the film.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it isn't long before Coach's dream world is shattered
when his four disciples turn out to be unhappy, tormented souls
with enough excess baggage to shut down an airport.
</P>
<P>
   Romano, the big man on the team, is now a wealthy, ruthless
businessman who has been a key backer of his old teammate, George
Sitkowski, the
</P>
<P>
   town's corrupt mayor. Sitkowksi's campaign manager and
all-purpose sycophant is James Daley, underachieving principal of
the junior high. The fourth member of the group is Daley's brother,
Tom, an alcoholic writer and drifter.
</P>
<P>
   When Romano hints that he might back the mayor's foe in the next
election, the happy times turn sour. The film plumbs the
you-can-never-go-home-again theme to its core, opening wounds so
huge that plasma
</P>
<P>
   should get top billing. Fortunately, the guys have laid in
plenty of alcohol. Medicinal purposes, you know.
</P>
<P>
   As 20 years of jealousy, suspicion, fear, loathing and
insecurity come to a head, the most sympathetic character is the
cynical lush, Tom, played by Gary Sinise, who may be incapable of
giving a bad performance. Sedated much of the time, Tom is the
moral compass of the group who, despite his inebriation, ultimately
provides a sense of direction.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Kinney (as James Daley), Tony Shalhoub (as Sitkowski),
Vincent D'Onofrio (as Romano) and Sorvino are also fine, but
Sorvino the director fails to tie a series of raw, dramatic scenes
together into a believable whole.
</P>
<P>
   That Championship Season. Two-hour cable movie about a group of
men who get together 20 years after they won the state high school
basketball championship. Starring Paul Sorvino, Gary Sinise, Tony
Shalhoub, Vincent D'Onofrio and Terry Kinney. Sunday on Showtime.
Repeats June 16 and June 19. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
