</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MILOSEVIC SURVIVES WAR OF MISCALCULATION WITH HIS POWER
INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ From the start, this has been a war of
miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, led by the Clinton administration, assumed that a
relatively short period of bombing would be enough to cause
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to capitulate over
Kosovo. Drawing the wrong lessons from Bosnia, Western officials
underestimated the historical and cultural importance of Kosovo to
the Serbs. And NATO badly undervalued its political importance to
Milosevic, who rose to power on the promise to protect the Serbs of
Kosovo against the Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   But as he accepted on Thursday a deal not much better than he
was offered before the bombing began 10 weeks ago, Milosevic seemed
to have miscalculated as badly.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, for his part, expected the NATO alliance to split,
particularly as the number of civilian casualties grew. He is
unlikely to have thought Bill Clinton would ignore those casualties
and even intensify the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO's southern tier became frazzled as refugees ran into
Albania and Macedonia and then into Western Europe, the human tide
neither destroyed his impoverished southern neighbors nor sundered
the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was right in his calculations that NATO did not want
to risk a ground invasion of Serbia, whose citizens, no matter how
some may revile Milosevic, were willing to die for their country.
</P>
<P>
   While only a ground invasion could sweep him from power, he
ultimately came to believe that NATO could continue its
comparatively costless bombing campaign for many more months,
striking civilian targets as well as military ones and utterly
devastating the country's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   With his own losses mounting _ at least 1,200 civilians have
died in NATO ``accidents'' and NATO estimated Thursday that at
least 5,000 Yugoslav soldiers and policemen have died _ Milosevic
clearly decided that now was the moment to end an unequal war and
preserve his own power.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is evidently calculating again. At least for now, he
is surviving NATO's war against his country with his power intact.
</P>
<P>
   In a weak political field, he still looks like a titan, and for
many in Serbia _ especially the working classes, the old and the
poor _ he is likely to retain his aura of mastery. His party is
already claiming to have inspired this little nation to a noble
resistance against the combined forces of 19 of the world's most
advanced nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little nation that resisted for two months against
the greatest might that has ever existed in history, and there was
no demoralization, no panic, no mass desertions,'' said Aleksa
Djilas, a historian, exaggerating only a little. ``This has shown
that Western public opinion has proved less humane than we
believed. It was willing to tolerate far higher casualties in the
country being attacked than we had assumed, and it was prepared to
tolerate far fewer casualities on its own side than we had
assumed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's weak democratic opposition parties, largely muzzled
during the war due to censorship, have been eager to say that
Milosevic's problems will really begin after peace is established,
once the patriotic fever has passed and people awake to the
economic ruins around them.
</P>
<P>
   There is some truth to that, even Milosevic insiders agree, as
the country faces a hot summer and a cold winter with demolished
electrical power stations and heating plants.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's bombs have done enormous damage to Yugoslavia's economy,
already battered by eight years of international sanctions.
Billions of dollars of factories and equipment have been smashed,
along with thousands of jobs, and nearly every important highway or
railway bridge has been holed or destroyed, along with the
country's only two refineries.
</P>
<P>
   And so long as Milosevic and his top aides remain in power, many
of them recently indicted for war crimes, it remains to be seen
whether Yugoslavia will get any serious reconstruction aid or
investment from Western countries or the European Union. The West
is likely to tighten economic sanctions on Yugoslavia, increasing
the sense of isolation of its relatively cosmopolitan citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Western aid itself _ or the promise of it _ is already being
used as a sort of incentive to Serbs to depose Milosevic, by
electoral means or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   And it is possible that the Yugoslav army and police, having
withstood NATO's extensive bombing in Kosovo without cracking, will
find that Milosevic has made peace at too cheap a price, discarding
their own sacrifice and that of their dead comrades.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Already, the former general who leads a small democratic
opposition party, Vuk Obradovic, has called for Milosevic's
resignation and asked: ``What was the price of this war? And what
did it accomplish?'' Those questions have now been echoed by the
former mayor of Belgrade, Nebojsa Covic, who broke with Milosevic
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While military casualties have been a state secret in this war,
Yugoslav generals have said recently that they are relatively low,
estimating that 1,800 people have been killed or wounded badly
enough to leave their posts. But NATO officials Thursday, in
response, estimated that perhaps 5,000 Yugoslav military and police
have been killed and more than 10,000 wounded _ the first time they
have provided such figures.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   True or false, the report seems another effort by the West to
increase the political pressure on Milosevic from an angry
citizenry that might feel betrayed by the deal on Kosovo after so
many dead. The Serbs themselves like to speak of their small
families compared with large Albanian ones, and the loss of enough
conscript sons can set off spontaneous demonstrations, like the
ones recently repressed in Krusevac, Aleksandrovac and Cacak.
</P>
<P>
   While Yugoslav officials tried to minimize the importance of
those demonstrations, they also vowed to crush them, and this sort
of war weariness in the southern Serb heartland, where Milosevic
has always found his strength, is likely to have been another
important factor in his decision to end the war.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For all Milosevic's new vulnerabilities, he remains lucky in his
fractured, disputatious opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The ultranationalist leader of the Radical Party, Serbian Deputy
Prime Minister Vojislav Seselj, vowed Thursday to quit the
government once NATO troops enter Kosovo. He will no doubt try to
challenge Milosevic in elections, but most Serbs are not going to
find the prospect of even more tension with the world community a
politically attractive platform. Once out of power, Seselj will
also find the draconian press laws he favored put to use against
him.
</P>
<P>
   And the democrats are too busy either knifing each other or
competing for Milosevic's favors in coalition governments to do him
significant harm.
</P>
<P>
   Zoran Djindjic, the prominent leader of the Democratic Party,
has probably destroyed his political career in Serbia by fleeing to
its sister republic, Montenegro, while others remained in Belgrade
under the bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Draskovic, the leader of the Serbian Renewal Movement and a
former leader of the democratic opposition, still commands the
largest political following among them. He was prominent in pushing
for an early peace settlement, and he has his own television
station, since his party controls Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic is considered flighty, and as he praised the peace
Thursday, he also made it clear he would be more than willing to
rejoin Milosevic's government, especially if Seselj quits. If so,
he would be a useful interlocutor with the West for the indicted
Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
