<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN GO HOME AGAIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ariz., N.C., Fla., Kan.)   (af)  
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, Joseph and Joyce Ensminger moved from their home
state of Kansas to Green Valley, Ariz., a retirement community
about 20 miles south of Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   They went there because Ensminger, now 88, had been hospitalized
with pneumonia and they were seeking a warmer and drier climate.
</P>
<P>
   This month, they are moving back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Green Valley is a lovely place, but I miss my children and
family,'' Mrs. Ensminger, 73, said. ``After all, family is
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   She concedes that she wants to return more than her husband, and
that he is going along to please her. ``Joe recently had a serious
operation and he feels a little mortal,'' she said. ``He wants to
know that I am all settled before something happens to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ensmingers are not alone. Many retirees move to another part
of the country, then decide to return to where they had lived and
worked most of their lives. Usually, they long to be closer to
family members, often because of failing health or the death of a
spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they don't make new friends or otherwise decide that
they don't like their new environment as much as they thought.
Arizona or Florida can be wonderful in February; August is another
story.
</P>
<P>
   Such havens attract a surprisingly small percentage of all
retirees. Precise figures are difficult to come by, but Charles F.
Longino Jr., a gerontologist at Wake Forest University in
Winston-Salem, N.C., uses census data to estimate that only about 5
percent of retirees actually move to another state. Of that share,
about 1 in 10 eventually return, or reverse migrate. According to
the most recent available data, 104,000 people over 60 years old
moved from New York to Florida between 1985 and 1990, and 9,000
moved to New York from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 survey by AARP, 8 of 10 Americans 50 or over said they
wanted to stay in their own homes and never move.
</P>
<P>
   Some retirees, especially from the Northeast or West Coast, move
to cut their living costs. Others seek a better climate. But the
trade-off can be separation from familiar people and surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   For the Ensmingers and others like them, the trade-offs were not
worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Ensminger is a retired sports referee and sales manager for a
safety-glass manufacturer; Mrs. Ensminger is a retired public
school administrative assistant. The two have been married only 11
years, and it's the second time around for both.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, they have 6 children, 15 grandchildren and 3
great-grandchildren. They are selling their home in Arizona and
building a new one in Overland Park, Kan., a suburb of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   For Ensminger, his wife's social and personal considerations
outweighed the virtues of a Sun Belt climate. ``It bothers Joyce
that she doesn't have any close friends,'' he said. ``Also, people
out here don't entertain like we're used to. We're accustomed to
bridge parties and dinner parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in many ways it's ideal for me. I love to golf and swim
and go for walks. I love the atmosphere _ you wake up every morning
and the sun is shining. It's a great place to retire. My wife likes
a lot about it, but she wants to be near her grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 1,200 miles from Kansas City. One family member has been
out once and another twice. To see our family we have to travel
there. Now we'll be back with people we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Many retirees who are tempted to leave their new locales,
however, have decided to stay put. A second move can be stressful,
as well as expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Jean S. Beals, 77, moved to Naples, Fla., from
Mount Holly, N.J. A retired bank teller, she has been a widow since
1981. In April, while on a visit back to New Jersey, she seriously
considered returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got homesick,'' she said. ``I thought maybe I shouldn't have
moved. I missed my friends and my church.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Beals had something to draw her back to Florida that
many retirees there lack: a daughter in Naples and a son in
Sarasota. ``So I finally decided no,'' she said. ``I have a lovely
place in Florida, and I don't like cold weather anymore. Plus my
children are near me. It's too stressful for me to move now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
