<HEADLINE>
LUKAS NEEDS THIS CROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ D. Wayne Lukas doesn't know it, or won't admit
it, but he needs Charismatic to win this Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   He needs it to rescue the trainer's legacy from the cold
quicksand of statistics and dollar figures and all-time firsts.
</P>
<P>
   He needs it so when people think of the dominant horseman of his
era, they'll also think of a (ital)horse(end ital).
</P>
<P>
   Humble Charismatic, his rise the result of a late-winter change
in Lukas' conditioning tactics, will be that horse if he and jockey
Chris Antley win the Belmont Stakes on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, Lukas will no longer be the winner of the most purse
money (nearly $200 million) and the most consecutive Triple Crown
races (six, 1994-96), the trainer of the most national champions
(19) and the most Breeders' Cup winners (13).
</P>
<P>
   He'll be ``D. Wayne Lukas, trainer of Charismatic,'' the first
Triple Crown winner in 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't thought about that,'' Lukas said Thursday morning
beside his Belmont Park barn. ``Do you think this is going to be
the last time I get the opportunity to do this?''
</P>
<P>
   And it's possible he (ital)hasn't(end ital) thought about how
he'll be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   To Lukas, being ``that man with Charismatic'' might sound like
second billing.
</P>
<P>
   But it's flattering compared to the image he has allowed to be
created.
</P>
<P>
   This is the trainer who, at the Churchill Downs press conference
announcing his Hall of Fame election in May, thanked horse owners
living and dead and thanked his talented employees and even thanked
reporters _ but failed to acknowledge the contribution of a single
horse to his success.
</P>
<P>
   This is the trainer whose barn walls commemorate major victories
in such a way as to make the winning horses seem like bit players.
</P>
<P>
   ``1995 Kentucky Derby Winner,'' reads one sign on his Belmont
Park barn. ``Trainer: D. Wayne Lukas. Owner: Michael Tabor. Horse:
Thunder Gulch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``1994 Belmont Stakes winner,'' reads another that leaves out
the name of Tabasco Cat entirely. ``Trainer: D. Wayne Lukas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was asked Thursday which horses would be mentioned on the
Hall of Fame plaque that will be unveiled in Saratoga, N.Y., in
August. He responded by discussing how the plaque-making was being
delayed until his earnings officially reached $200 million. And he
again passed up a perfect opportunity to name the horses he's most
proud of.
</P>
<P>
   To Lukas' critics, examples like those are evidence of his
disregard for the flesh and blood that goes in one end of his
stables and out the other like so much ground beef.
</P>
<P>
   To his supporters, examples like those are evidence of
accomplishments so broad and awesome that singling out individual
horses is pointless.
</P>
<P>
   But not impossible. His Horses of the Year: Lady's Secret (1986)
and Criminal Type (1990). His first Kentucky Derby winner: the
filly Winning Colors. His slump-busting Preakness winner: Tabasco
Cat. His most versatile star: Farma Way. His sensational filly of
the '90s: Serena's Song.
</P>
<P>
   If Charismatic wins the Triple Crown, they'll all move to No. 2
on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas was asked Thursday if Charismatic would be an appropriate
horse with which to associate him. His answer would have puzzled
most listeners.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about how he probably ``blew my corporate image'' by
riding with Charismatic on the plane from Louisville, Ky., on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that hay and dust flying up and getting all over my Armani
suit,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas had bristled at the implication that Charismatic's
turnaround demonstrates his skill at horsemanship better than his
hundreds of other winners.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe he does get it.
</P>
<P>
   At 63, married for the fourth time to trainer Laura Pinelli,
Lukas has displayed a softer side this spring. Some reporters heard
his admission that he ``misjudged'' Charismatic, entering the colt
in a Santa Anita claiming race in February, and his
self-deprecating statement that many of his early champions ``won
in spite of me,'' and wrote Derby-week stories about the tough
guy's ``mellowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. This week Lukas had gone back to war with ``the
cockroaches,'' as he refers to selected members of the press.
</P>
<P>
   When a Daily Racing Form writer asked a sympathetic question
about how reporters would have reacted if Lukas, not rival trainer
Bob Baffert, had entered the filly Silverbulletday in the Belmont,
he erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys would have had a field day,'' Lukas was quoted
saying. ``How about me running Excellent Meeting in the Preakness
(as Baffert did with the filly who was pulled up early in the
race)? I wouldn't have even been able to show up here for two
weeks. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd say, `Well, he couldn't stand to be out of the
Preakness, and he ran the filly, and now he ruined her.' And I
would've been the butcher. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   That man with Charismatic can be touchy, huh?
</P>
<P>
   He needn't be. He can always point to two decades of winning
results. ``Tote board, baby!''
</P>
<P>
   But records alone don't make a horseman. Lukas needs to put a
face on his career, a face with big teeth and pointed ears and a
white stripe down the nose.
</P>
<P>
   He needs Charismatic to win the Triple Crown. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
