<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, June 4,
and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   MOLEST-PASTOR (TACOMA, Wash.) _ The youth pastor at one of
Tacoma's largest churches was charged with eight counts of rape and
child molestation Thursday for what police say was a 4-year-long
series of sexual assaults on a least 17 children _ most of them
members of his congregation. Police said Pastor Herman Glenn, 34,
of Bethel Christian Assembly Church conned the 13-to-15-year-old
boys into having sex with him by convincing them he had an alter
ego (named ``Alter'') he couldn't get rid of without sexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   By Jack Hopkins. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WENATCHEE (Seattle) _ State courts continue to order new trials
and freedom for people wrongly imprisoned during the Wenatchee
child sex abuse investigations. On Monday the state appeals court
in Spokane decreed that a rare investigative hearings be held for
Doris Green. Last month, the state Supreme Court ruled that an
identical hearing ordered last December for Manuel Hidalgo
Rodriguez be held over the objections of the state.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-AVERTED (AUBURN, Wash.) _ An attentive school security
officer is being credited with averting a tragedy at an alternative
high school in Auburn, when his tip led police to the home of a
drive-by shooting suspect whose bedroom walls were covered with
newspaper clippings from the Littleton massacre.
</P>
<P>
   By Kimberly A.C. Wilson. (Story will move in the ``a''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-HOUSING (Seattle) _ Catholic relief organization in
desperate search for housing after receiving word from the State
Department that with 48-hours notice, they are to receive two
Kosovo refugee families of eight people each. They have no place to
put them and keep them together.
</P>
<P>
   By Gordy Holt. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SHIP-MERCY (Seattle) _ Remember the famous old hospital ship,
Hope? The Caribbean Mercy, a floating hospital currently in Seattle
to load up on rice and medical supplies before sailing with doctors
and nurses urgently needed in North Korea, is part of its legacy.
The ship, fully equipped with things like a high-tech eye surgery
clinic, has been here since May 29, leaves June 6, and its stay
coincides with a diplomatic mission to N. Korea being led by former
U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Barber. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-TREATY (Seattle) _ The U.S. and Canadian governments
Thursday rejoiced at their deal to end the ``salmon war'' between
the two countries, and get on with conserving a fast-disappearing,
vital symbol of life in the Northwest. But hard questions and
controversies remain.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``i'' and ``a''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington, D.C.) _ President Clinton on Thursday
renewed normal trade relations with China, setting off an annual
debate in Congress complicated this year by allegations that China
has stolen U.S. nuclear weapons secrets. Few observers expect that
Congress will ultimately muster the votes to overturn Clinton's
action, but the debate is expected to be heated.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``w'' and ``i''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRBORNE-POSTAL SERVICE (Seattle) _ The Seattle-based
parcel-delivery company Airborne Freight Corp. said Thursday it was
joining with the U.S. Postal Service in a partnership that will
allow it to deliver packages to U.S. homes up to twice as fast as
its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SAYLES (Seattle) _ Steven Spielberg may be more financially
successful and Martin Scorsese may be more critically acclaimed,
but no director of the generation that has dominated American
filmmaking for the past 20 years is more universally admired than
John Sayles. With review of Sayles' new movie, ``Limbo.''
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
