<HEADLINE>
BOSTON LAWSUIT TARGETS GUN INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSON _ This city, known as a national leader for its
significant strides to reduce youth violence, filed suit against 31
gun manufacturers, distributors, and trade groups Thursday,
accusing the gun industry of creating a public nuisance with its
weapons and getting rich at taxpayers' expense.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, filed in Suffolk Superior Court, makes Boston the
20th city or county to sue gun makers in a campaign increasingly
mirroring the nation's fight against tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The filing of the suit Thursday drew loud cries of hypocrisy
from the gun industry, which cited Boston's successful recent
efforts to reduce gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the City of Boston knows what is needed to reduce gun
violence and I don't see how running to the civil courts trying to
sue the industry is going to save one life,'' said Robert Ricker,
executive director of the American Shooting Sports Council, a trade
group that is a defendant in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Ricker pointed to Boston's coordinated law enforcement effort,
which many credit for curbing youth violence when teen crime was
exploding around the country. For two years, not a single child
under 17 was killed with a gun in Boston. The city's homicide rate
has dipped to 1960s levels, with just 35 homicides last year, 25 of
them with a firearm. The number of guns used in the commission of
other crimes also has dropped off. Violent firearms offenses fell
from 2,026 in 1994 to 1,004 last year, according to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Mayor (Thomas M.) Menino is more concerned with
jumping on the bandwagon politically than he is with really looking
at solving violence problems in Boston,'' Ricker said.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Shultz, chief executive of Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp., a handgun
manufacturer, said he was ``not at all surprised'' by the suit.
``It seems to be the thing you need to do if you want to be a
big-city mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Menino said the issue has nothing to do with politics, but with
making the city safer. ``The gun industry has the money to make a
gun safer, but they'd rather use their resources to make guns
lighter, smaller, and easier for criminals to buy and conceal,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates assert that Boston's foray into gun
litigation signals the seriousness of the nation's continuing gun
problem, even in areas where political leadership has taken action
against it. It also shows frustration over the inability to
overcome the powerful gun lobby in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Henigan, legal director for the Center to Prevent Handgun
Violence in Washington, said Boston's progress through law
enforcement and creative strategies is ``consistently undercut by
the irresponsibility of the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a city that is basically sending a message that it is
not a choice between strong enforcement of the law and action to
hold the industry accountable _ that you need to do both,'' Henigan
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Boston's lawsuit, the Boston Public Health Commission
tracked all gun-related deaths and injuries between 1993 and 1998
to identify the manufacturer of each weapon, and then calculate the
public health costs for each company.
</P>
<P>
   The city is estimating damages from gun related deaths or
injuries at $100 million, including the loss of tax revenue from
neighborhoods where crime has quashed property values.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of four private law firms, led by Brown Rudnick
Freed &AMP; Gesmer, which shepherded the state's suit against tobacco
companies, the city is essentially aiming to place responsibility
for gun injuries, deaths, and public health costs in the hands of
gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   The suit argues that gun companies act with ``willfull
blindness,'' manufacturing and distributing thousands of firearms
in a manner that enables them to be purchased by juveniles and
criminals, thereby exploiting and maintaining an illegitimate
secondary market for guns.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also says guns are defective in design and could be
made more safely to prevent accidental deaths and injuries,
particularly those involving children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that some of our franchises and coffee
suppliers care more about our health than gun manufacturers,''
Menino said Thursday, referring to the printed warnings on the
several cups of coffee he was carrying. where
</P>
<P>
   Gun makers in turn have charged that the municipal lawsuits are
unfairly blaming them for the illegal actions of middle-men or the
negligent actions of gun users.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know guns by their very nature are dangerous. A cup of
coffee, you don't expect it to be 185 degrees,'' Ricker said. He
said firearms are ``the only product out there that's designed to
kill. By its very nature, people should understand that when
handling a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit targets gunmakers, including Springfield's Smith &AMP;
Wesson and Glock Corp., as well as distributors and trade groups
such as the American Shooting Sports Council Inc. and the Sporting
Arms and Ammunition Manufacturers Institute Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities that have sued the gun industry include Chicago,
New Orleans, Miami and Bridgeport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA controls Congress. The public controls the judiciary,
hopefully,'' said John Rosenthal, founder of Stop Handgun Violence,
based in Newton.
</P>
<P>
   But legislative efforts are already underway to thwart city
suits. On Thursday, Louisiana lawmakers passed a bill preventing
cities from suing gun makers in an effort to nullify the New
Orleans suit, which was the nation's first. A similar measure was
passed by Georgia's legislature in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
