<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Lighting to become Home Depot unit
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot Inc. has agreed to buy Atlanta-based
Georgia Lighting, signaling that the giant home improvement
retailer wants to expand its share of the lighting-fixture market.
</P>
<P>
   Closely held Georgia Lighting, a specialty retailer with six
showrooms in metro Atlanta, will retain its name and become a
wholly owned subsidiary of Atlanta-based Home Depot. The deal is
expected to close within 30 days. Terms weren't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Lighting President Harry Gilham started the company in
1960 with a showroom on Spring Street. That location moved to 14th
Street and became one of the country's largest lighting showrooms.
The company sells fixtures ranging from chandeliers to kitchen and
bath fixtures, lamps and outdoor systems. The stores' customers
include interior decorators and contractors, as well as consumers
in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Gilham, 69, said he's selling the company partly because there
are no family members interested in taking over the business.
``This presents an opportunity for me to secure the future of my
200 employees,'' he said. ``I've been in this business for 40
years, and I'm just happy I can spend the last part of my career
working for a company like Home Depot.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot is bringing the relatively small company on board
during a period when it is improving merchandising strategies in
several product categories. Gilham and Georgia Lighting General
Manager Ray Gardner are expected to enhance Home Depot's lighting
departments in its warehouse and Expo Design Center stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are regarded as preeminent experts in their field. The
primary benefit of this acquisition is in their expertise in
design, sourcing and distribution,'' said David Suliteanu, group
president of diversified businesses for Home Depot. Suliteanu
stressed that Home Depot is not planning to roll out a line of
specialty lighting stores, nor does it plan to close any Georgia
Lighting stores.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot did not disclose how much business it currently does
in lighting. Trade publication National Home Center News estimates
that lighting and electrical products represent 5 percent of Home
Depot's $30.2 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   The entire $9 billion market for lighting fixtures is expected
to grow by 5 percent annually over the next five years, according
to the American Lighting Association.
</P>
<P>
   The retail lighting industry is a fractured market of 3,000
lighting showrooms, comprised mostly of local and regional
operators.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
