<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    iXL gains nearly 50% in first day of trading
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of Atlanta-based iXL Enterprises, e-business
consultant for companies such as General Electric and Time-Warner,
rose nearly 50 percent in their first day of trading Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   iXL debuted in a much more temperate market than the one that
doubled the share price of Media Metrix, a web measurement company,
when it went public last month. Still, 13.8 million shares changed
hands, and the price rose to close at $17.87 1/2, a better than 48
percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   The offering had been priced at $12 Wednesday for big
institutional investors and company insiders. Individuals got their
shot Thursday when the stock opened at $15.12 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The stock rose as high as $24.50 in intraday trading.
</P>
<P>
   Since Atlanta businessman Bert Ellis, 45, founded iXL in 1996,
the firm has acquired more than 34 Web, video and interactive media
companies. His stake was worth $52.5 million at Thursday's close.
</P>
<P>
   iXL helps other companies figure out how to build Web sites,
advertise, market and conduct e-commerce on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   iXL also owns 77 percent of the locally based Consumer Financial
Network, which offers loans, life insurance and other benefits to
employees of major corporations via corporate intranets. GE Capital
owns the rest of CFN and has agreed to buy 2 million shares in iXL.
Affiliates of New York investment firm Kelso &AMP; Co. own about 25
percent of iXL; CB Capital Investors, nearly 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company raised $72 million from the offering of 6 million
shares at $12. iXL says it will use the money to pay off debt and
to fund growth.
</P>
<P>
   Web consulting firms such as iXL are in demand because many
companies are struggling to set up Web operations and need
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, Ellis gave Georgia Tech's DuPree School of
Management an initial endowment of $1 million to fund the iXL
Center for E-Commerce at Georgia Tech, aimed at becoming the
state-of-the-art e-commerce research facility.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the iXL offering to do well because of a
recent upward trend of all Internet-related stocks, even though
that market has cooled a bit. USWeb, iXL's closest competitor in
the interactive advertising marketplace, is currently trading at
about $25.25.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the company has yet to turn a profit. It lost $18.3
million for the quarter ended March 31 on revenue of $33 million,
compared with a loss of $5.9 million on revenue of $6.9 million the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
