A2239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-IMPACT04-COX     06-03 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-IMPACT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As rumors end, Lockheed Martin layoffs hit home
 &HT;    By Henry Farber and Steve Visser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now the worrying begins.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin Corp.'s announcement Thursday that its Marietta
aircraft plant will lose 2,000 jobs over the next year brought an
end to weeks of rumors.
</P>
<P>
   But for families, this was only the wobbling of the first
domino. The impact on mortgages, grocery bills and college tuition
will have to wait until the pink slips come.
</P>
<P>
   If there was good news, it's that the layoffs won't be the
hammer blow to Cobb County's economy they would have been 20 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get laid off, I gotta hit the road, find another job,''
said Aldora Grisson, 43, a $17-an-hour machinist who says she never
had children largely because of the volatility of the military
aircraft business. ``I've put off a lot of things because of the
way this industry is.'' But she did take a chance and make a down
payment on her Marietta home a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of the plant's 9,500 workers, about 4,300 are hourly employees _
most of them members of the Aeronautical Machinists Union. Years of
service will largely determine their fates. For the 5,200 salaried
workers, merit and the need for their position will determine their
future.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Miller was one of thousands of employees who came to work
Thursday and heard one of the speeches made by company President
Tom Burbage announcing the cutback.
</P>
<P>
   Miller had worked for Boeing in Seattle. Two months ago, he
moved to Marietta _ a decision he now regrets. An engineer on the
C-130J, Miller's salary supports his wife and 2-year-old. ``Just
like the aerospace industry. A couple of months ago they were
hiring, now they're getting rid of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed's economic impact, while proportionately smaller than
decades ago, is still sizable. Last year, Lockheed _ which has an
annual payroll of $532 million with 9,550 employees _ spent $137
million in goods and services with Georgia companies. It's still
the largest private employer in the county, and only the Cobb
school system now has more workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you had the layoffs in the 1970s, it really sent the
local economy into the tank,'' said Roger Tutterow, an economist
and co-director of the Econometric Center at Kennesaw State
University. ``These layoffs, while they are significant to the
families involved, they're really a bit minor for Cobb.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Donald Ratajczak, director of the Economic Forecasting
Center at Georgia State University, said while the county should
maintain its economic health, nobody should underestimate the
importance of the layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to notice it in the growth rate of Atlanta? Sure
we are, because you're taking away 2,000 high-wage incomes,'' he
said. ``You're probably talking about a total job impact of 5,000.
That's because those paychecks aren't being spent.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic impact on small businesses serving Lockheed Martin
Aeronautical Systems probably will be felt in the coming months as
the company cuts back on new contracts and orders, said Carlotta
Roberts, director of the Small Business Development Center at KSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some small businesses won't get repeat work they're counting
on getting,'' she said. ``It's a lesson about not putting all your
eggs in one basket. You can't rely on one big customer to provide
all your income.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
