<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKHEED-LAYOFFS04-CO     06-03 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-LAYOFFS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lockheed: Attrition will be 40% of cuts
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The latest wave of job cuts at Lockheed Martin's
Marietta plant will come from across the company, with about 40
percent achieved through attrition, retirements and transfers,
plant executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Plant spokesman Sam Grizzle said that cuts could begin by the
end of this month, with workers notified as soon as the targeted
jobs are identified. The job cuts will be combined with a broad
structural reorganization, details of which are still being
formulated.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 2,000 of the current 9,500 jobs at the plant will be axed
over the next year, plant executives said in a series of meetings
with employees Thursday. That number includes about 350 contract
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The cutback comes as the company faces a looming production
slowdown on the C-130J transport program, caused by slack
short-term demand for the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin is trying to persuade the Air Force to
accelerate long-term buying plans, in part by offering to cut the
price on each aircraft from about $58 million to $51 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is under pressure to meet congressional
spending caps on the F-22 fighter, still in the pre-production
phase. The program faces a major Pentagon review this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must continue to reduce our costs to make the C-130J more
affordable domestically and internationally and to meet the
commitment we've made to the Air Force to carry out F-22
development and production within the established budget,'' said
C.T. ``Tom'' Burbage, president of Lockheed Martin Aeronautical
Systems, the corporate division headquartered at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we need to streamline our operation and make our
organization more effective, so we're taking steps today to start
that process,'' Burbage said.
</P>
<P>
   Burbage, a former F-22 program chief promoted to his current
post in March, said long-term prospects for both the C-130J and
F-22 programs remain strong. He denied Lockheed Martin was
considering moving either program or shutting down the Marietta
plant. Burbage said he met Wednesday with Vance Coffman, chairman
of Bethesda, Md.-based Lockheed Martin, adding there is ``no
discussion at any level'' of such moves.
</P>
<P>
   While Lockheed Martin expects to sell hundreds of C-130Js and
F-22s over the next 10 to 20 years, both programs have been slow
starters.
</P>
<P>
   The C-130J debuted in 1995 _ two years behind schedule because
of development glitches that drove up the cost. The U.S. government
has ordered 35 of the planes, while foreign buyers have ordered 55.
Those orders will be filled by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force plans to order another 168 C-130Js to replace
older models, but doesn't want them until the middle of the next
decade. That's prompted concern that the Marietta plant might have
to be mothballed for two or three years, but Burbage insisted that
scenario is remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking at any production breaks,'' he said. The
company believes it can persuade the Air Force and Congress to add
enough orders during the lean years to sustain production.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lockheed Martin has previously warned in
congressional briefings that a production rate of 12 C-130Js a year
would only justify employment of 6,000 people. The plant is capable
of producing 36 planes a year. It will build 22 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Huge job fluctuations are nothing new at the plant, but the
trend has been down in recent years. The last major job cut came in
1994, when the company cut 2,000 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Plant employment was as high as 33,000 in the late 1960s, when
the facility produced three transport planes, the C-5A, the C-141
and early models of the C-130. It fell as low as 8,000 in 1976,
then jumped to 20,000 in the 1980s with production of the C-5B.
</P>
<P>
   The job count dropped to 11,000 after C-5B production ended in
1989 and has slowly shrunk since then to about 9,500 now, including
contract workers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent congressional briefing materials, Lockheed Martin
cited 8,205 as the ``historical low'' for Marietta plant
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Johnny Isakson (R-Ga.), whose suburban district includes
part of Cobb County, said he hopes displaced workers won't have
trouble finding new employment in Georgia's powerful economy. ``We
went through this once before when the (C-5B) contract ended, and
the market absorbed those jobs very easily, and that was a lot more
jobs,'' Isakson said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Mark Sherman contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
