</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plan would aid Madison firm's investors
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Investors in two companies with ties to a Madison
business might get some of their money back in a plan proposed by
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a federal judge froze $2.5 million in investor
money, saying it came from the sale of unregistered shares of
Citron and Electronic Transfer Associates through Glittergrove
Investments, an Irish firm. They were represented by Peter Lybrand,
a banned-for-life stockbroker who works out of a former
five-and-dime in Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mixter of the SEC's enforcement division, said he expects
the court to issue a default judgment in its case against
Glittergrove this month. When and if the court issues a default
judgment, Mixter said the SEC will file a plan with the court to
return the money to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
