<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring adding bookstore to its site
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring took a first step Thursday toward turning
its home page into a shopping and information destination by
signing a deal with Barnes &AMP; Noble to offer MindSpring members
their own version of the popular online bookseller.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring's Barnes &AMP; Noble site will be accessible to
subscribers and non-subscribers from the MindSpring home page at
www.mindspring.net. The affiliate marketing agreement will create a
book and music store, as well as an e-mail ``deals club'' for
MindSpring's 1.16 million members.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will also give MindSpring users access to
discounts on barnesandnoble.com's selection of books and access to
the soon-to-be-opened barnesandnoble.com music store.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things about this deal that are really
interesting,'' said Erika Jolly, MindSpring's vice president of
consumer products. ``It's a MindSpring-branded bookstore, really,
and it allows us to create our own bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, if we get reports from Barnes &AMP; Noble that
MindSpring customers like to buy books about France, we can
customize the content to coincide with what our subscribers are
most interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other aspects of the Barnes &AMP; Noble deal haven't been
integrated yet but are part of MindSpring's often-stated goal to
add more value to its home page.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnes &AMP; Noble deal will eventually complement additional
content the company hopes to add to the site, Jolly said.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring has built its reputation as an Internet service
provider with good customer service. Now, the company has turned
its attention to generating more revenue for itself and more value
for customers by adding branded content and commerce to its home
page.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we are so much larger and we have such a good
relationship with our subscribers, we can build on that
relationship by adding some depth to our site,'' Jolly said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
