<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-740     06-03 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON'S DEMOCRATIC COMPETITION FOR SENATE SEAT STEPS
ASIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saying she was convinced that Hillary Rodham Clinton
was running for senator from New York, Rep. Nita Lowey abandoned
her own bid for the position Thursday, announcing her decision in a
telephone call to Mrs. Clinton at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton made no attempt to dissuade her, and the first
lady's aides later said she is likely to form an exploratory
committee in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear she is running,'' Lowey, D-N.Y., said in an
interview shortly after her five-minute conversation with the first
lady. ``It's time for me to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The sequence of events _ starting with a 1:20 p.m. call by Lowey
to the White House that had been orchestrated by aides to the two
women the night before _ seemed to leave little doubt that the
first lady intends to seek the Democratic nomination to run in 2000
to succeed Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours after Lowey, who had presented herself as the
fallback Democratic candidate in the race, announced her decision,
Harold M. Ickes, Mrs. Clinton's senior political adviser, said that
the first lady was ``pressing forward'' with her candidacy. He said
she was likely to take the first formal step of creating an
exploratory committee when she returns from a trip to Europe and
the Mideast in July.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Mrs. Clinton issued a short statement that
praised Lowey's record as a member of Congress, and hinted at a
continued political alliance in the months ahead. ``I thank Nita
for her support, and I look forward to working with her,'' Mrs.
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   By design or not, the decision by Lowey effectively forced the
hand of the first lady, who has sought to put off giving any firm
sign of her intention until early summer. If Mrs. Clinton still had
serious doubts about making the race, several of her aides said
Thursday, she almost certainly would have have advised Lowey to
stay on the stage. Lowey said Mrs. Clinton said nothing of the
sort.
</P>
<P>
   In theory at least, Mrs. Clinton could still decide not to run,
and Lowey could reverse herself and get back in the race. But
associates of both women called the chances of that remote.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move by the first lady would be highly disruptive to the
state Democratic Party, leaving it in the lurch at a time when its
leaders are already concerned about of holding onto the seat if the
Republicans run mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Lowey's withdrawal ended one of the odder political
entanglements of recent years. Just last week, Mrs. Clinton came to
New York to help Lowey raise $1 million, money that would have
financed a Lowey campaign for Senate if Mrs. Clinton herself did
not make the race.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats had begun to suggest that Lowey's willingness to
stand back quietly awaiting Mrs. Clinton's decision, applauded at
first as a sign of loyalty, could begin to seem weak and even
farcical, particularly as Mrs. Clinton's candidacy seemed
increasingly inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there were no indications that Lowey felt any
resentment over how she has fared in the public spotlight these
last few months.
</P>
<P>
   As a political matter, she is today arguably in a much stronger
position than she was at the start of the year, by virtue of having
played even a secondary role in such a high profile contest. She
has gone from being a little-known representative from Westchester
to being a state-wide Democratic figure.
</P>
<P>
   She raised about $2 million during the last six months, her
spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said, probably more than she needs for a
re-election race. At the age of 61, she is unlikely to have an
opportunity to run again for Senate _ the next Senate race after
2000 is 2004, and that seat is already held by a Democrat, Charles
Schumer _ but she is certain to be viewed by Democrats as a
stronger contender for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Lowey had said she would run for the Senate only if Mrs. Clinton
did not. In an interview, she said that she decided to quit her
effort after a week in which Mrs. Clinton met with New York
political strategists in the White House, and flew to New York to
decry the state of the public school system in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past week or so, it was increasingly clear to me that
the first lady had decided to run,'' Lowey said. ``It didn't make
sense for me to stay in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law of diminishing returns had set in,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson called Ickes Thursday night to inform him of the
decision and arrange the telephone call, which Lowey placed from
her district office in White Plains. Lowey's aides said they had no
idea how the first lady would respond to the decision, and there
was a real sense of suspense in Lowey's camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to her that it was clear to me she was running, and
therefore I was going to continue working in the House for
re-election,'' Lowey said, recounting the conversation. ``She said,
`I look forward to working with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the timing of Lowey's announcement was less than
ideal for Mrs. Clinton. She has been enjoying the kind of benefits
that come from being a celebrity candidate who has not actually
announced for office, drawing tremendous and largely uncritical
coverage of her every move. That is likely to change the more she
is viewed as a real player on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's advisers said that as a formal matter, Lowey's
announcement would not accelerate their own political schedule.
``She's just going to push ahead and take this one step at a
time,'' said Mandy Grunwald, the political consultant who was
Moynihan's consultant and is expected to play a key role in Mrs.
Clinton's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In Mackinac Island, Mich., where Giuliani was addressing a
business group Thursday the mayor reacted to the news of Mrs.
Clinton's consideration of an exploratory committee with his
standard refrain in recent days _ noting that she was running for
Senate from a state where she should never lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she should explore New York a little more,'' he said.
Then, referring to his own political agenda, the mayor said, ``I
formed an exploratory committee about six weeks ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
