<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION OFFICIALS SAY DEAL IS A FIRST STEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinton administration officials warily embraced
news of the peace agreement with Yugoslavia Thursday, describing it
as merely a first step toward peace despite a far more enthusiastic
response from other NATO leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Serb officials agreed to such key NATO demands as the withdrawal
of Yugoslav troops and the entry of an international peacekeeping
force. Such moves, if carried out, would create the conditions for
an international rebuilding effort in Kosovo that the White House
has estimated would cost up to $3.5 billion, most of which, it
says, would be paid by Europe. The total US cost, including
Washington's share of the 11-week military offensive, refugee
resettlement and future peacekeeping efforts, would be about $6
billion, according to the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the apparent Yugoslav capitulation, US officials were
reluctant to declare victory. While several officials seemed
pleased by the development _ and several congressional sources said
administraton officials were hoping a pact would be sealed within
days _ the tone of public remarks remained skeptical. President
Clinton, speaking in the Rose Garde, said any diplomatic move by
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``is, of course, welcome. But
based on our past experience, we must also be cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``First,'' he added, ``we must have clarity that the Serbian
leadership has fully accepted these conditions and intends to fully
implement them. Until then, and until Serb forces begin a
verifiable withdrawal from Kosovo, we will continue to pursue
diplomacy, but we will also continue the military effort that has
brought us to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, NATO warplanes continued Thursday to pound
Yugoslavia, and Defense Secretary William S. Cohen said they would
not stop until ``Yugoslavia convincingly demonstrates that the
fighting is over.'' Cohen declined to specify how Milosevic would
have to prove his sincerity _ such as how many troops he would need
to pull out of Kosovo to convince NATO that he was actually
conforming to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, US military and diplomatic officials have said they
would know a Yugoslav peace concession when they saw one, insisting
that intelligence sources _ satellite photographs of troop
withdrawals, for example _ would prove more reliable than any
signed agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Some military and foreign relations analysts said they are are
skeptical of Milosevic's sudden willingness toward diplomacy,
saying they feared he was trying to divide the NATO alliance by
seeming conciliatory. In a worst-case scenario, the analysts said,
NATO would split over the issue that has threatened to divide them
before: whether to continue negotiations with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Interpretations differed among NATO leaders. After hearing
details of the negotiations from a European Union envoy, Martti
Ahtisaari, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder described Thursday's
events as ``a political breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace, in my opinion, is very close,'' said Schroeder, the
current president of the European Community. ``Politically, we have
to make sure it doesn't slip out of our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was much cooler in the United States, and Clinton
even called Schroeder to say ``that we are quite cautious here,''
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the developments sparked a frenzy of official activity
throughout Washington. Administration officials shuttled back and
forth across the city throughout the day for briefings on Kosovo,
and Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright canceled a trip to
Mexico, where she was supposed to lead a two-day commission on
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The message everywhere was caution. The Pentagon spokesman,
Kenneth H. Bacon, said, ``We have to see performance, not
promises.'' The State Department spokesman, James P. Rubin,
described it as a ``very sober time ... a very cautious time,'' and
warned, ``this is not a time for popping champagne corks.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the Serbian parliament vote to accept the deal,
there was political parrying inside and outside Capitol Hill.
Democratic congressional aides said they were relieved by the
developments.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Senator John McCain of Arizona, a Republican
presidential contender, issued a statement expressing ``concerns
about the timetable'' and ``serious questions about the details of
the provision.''
</P>
<P>
   Another GOP candidate, Elizabeth Dole, said the vague terms of
the settlement had left her ``worried that we are on the verge of a
sellout. I'm particularly concerned because this administration has
a long history of compromising and appeasing Milosevic and other
despotic leaders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
