<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2246 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEE-REAX-N     06-03 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEE-REAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES ARE ANXIOUS AND SKEPTICAL ABOUT PEACE AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER and DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STENKOVEC I CAMP, Macedonia _ When the loudspeakers at this
refugee camp broadcast the news on Thursday of a potential peace
agreement for Kosovo, Ahmet Sharifi burst out laughing. ``Milosevic
is lying again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't believe a word anyone says until we are actually on
the road to Kosovo, going back with the NATO troops,'' said
Sharifi, a 59-year-old refugee who has memorized all the broken
promises of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Such skepticism was echoed on the sidelines of the men's
round-robin volleyball game and in the long line of women filling
their plastic water jugs at an open spigot. No one here or in
Cegrane, the largest refugee camp holding some of the hundreds of
thousands of people displaced from Kosovo, put any faith on
Thursday in the agreement by Milosevic and the Serbian Parliament
to accept the NATO peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   One woman said she would ``faint with joy'' if it were true, but
she and other Kosovars said they refused to be taken in yet again
by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   There have been too many brutal disappointments over the last 10
years, they said, culminating with last October's agreement, which
was routinely cited by refugees here as the reason why they remain
incredulous. That settlement, brokered at the last minute by
Richard C. Holbrooke, the American special envoy, was supposed to
have led to a substantial withdrawal of Serbian forces from Kosovo
overseen by unarmed European monitors. Instead, Milosevic built up
his troops for the mass deportation that he unleashed in March as
NATO began its air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believed in the October agreement and all that happened was
four of my husband's cousins were murdered for renting their houses
to the European monitors,'' said Imrane Dema, a 37-year-old mother
of three children who has been living in this camp for five weeks.
``We've heard this so many times, and it makes me feel like I
couldn't live anymore if another settlement fails.''
</P>
<P>
   But slowly, as the word spread from tent to tent, refugees began
discussing the few details they knew about the agreement and
wondering if they could take the latest deal seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Would the involvement of Russia mean the division of Kosovo? Was
this another clever trick of Milosevic to stop the NATO bombing
until the alliance loses its stomach to resume it? How can Kosovo,
after so much strife, remain a part of Yugoslavia? Could they ever
live with their Serbian neighbors again, even with the
``substantial autonomy'' the agreement promises?
</P>
<P>
   Tentatively, they began imagining the only way they thought they
could return _ escorted by NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   Fear, they predicted, would consume them when they journey home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to be frightened when we get back,'' said
Elmaze Hajdari, a 47-year-old mother whose grown daughter remained
behind in Kosovo. ``We're afraid they put mines in our houses and
mines in our fields.'' Refugees expressed fears of Serbian revenge
against those Albanians still in Kosovo. Halit Ferizi, 49, said
four of his brothers were now in a Serbian jail there.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them will be beaten, and some of them will be killed,''
Ferizi predicted. ``I don't know what criteria they'll use to
decide who lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Apprehension also gripped those with missing relatives in
Kosovo, where grim or joyous answers about the fate of loved ones
awaited them.
</P>
<P>
   Still others talked of their own revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked me out of my house for two months,'' said Imer
Rexhepi, a 33-year-old barber who set up shop under a tarp here.
``I'd like to kick them out of theirs for 200 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the refugees said they could not imagine how they
would be able to live with the Serbs again. They predicted the
Serbian civilians who made up 10 percent of Kosovo's population
before the NATO bombing would flee. They all said Kosovo should be
given independence as part of a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we need to live with them if they tried to destroy
us?'' said Bexhet Myftari, a 22-year-old auto mechanic turned
refugee.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees also worried that the Kosovo they find may be
little more than a burnt shell. They said they would need help
rebuilding their homes, towns and cities. But beneath the
skepticism, worry and efforts to protect themselves by playing down
the importance of Thursday's events, hope and determination could
still be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the houses are burned,'' said Idriz Berisha, a
42-year-old technician, ``We would be happy to live in tents in our
back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of hope among the refugees was that the news on
Thursday apparently prompted some refugees to hold off on plans to
go abroad. U.N. officials said more than 100 refugees failed to
show up for their flights abroad on Thursday, a far higher number
than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Rabije Megjuami, 39, said she did not trust the Serbian peace
offer, but acknowledged that she was willing to make any sacrifice
for the chance to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd even go back and live with my mother-in-law,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
