<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0604-C     06-03 1732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0604-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ADVISES 'CAUTION' OVER SERB ACCEPTANCE OF KOSOVO PEACE
PLAN
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslavia agreed Thursday to withdraw its troops
and police from Kosovo and permit international peacekeepers into
the embattled province, opening the door to a possible end to 10
weeks of punishing NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   NATO military commanders were preparing to meet with Yugoslav
generals as early as Friday to hammer out specific arrangements for
Serb forces to pull out of Kosovo and transfer control of the
province to a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton welcomed the diplomatic advance, which could
lead to a
</P>
<P>
   bombing halt as early as this weekend, but he also voiced
skepticism and urged caution.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he does not trust Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
the president of Yugoslavia, and stressed that critical questions
remain concerning the composition of a Kosovo peacekeeping force
and the mechanics and pacing of a Serb retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed to press forward with NATO air strikes until Serb
forces begin a verifiable pullout from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some encouraging news on Kosovo, but we should be
cautious and we should see real results,'' Clinton told reporters
during brief remarks at the White House Rose Garden Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must have clarity that the Serbian leadership has fully
accepted these conditions and intends to fully implement them,''
Clinton said. ``Until then, and until Serb forces begin a
verifiable withdrawal from Kosovo, we will continue to pursue
</P>
<P>
   diplomacy, but we will also continue the military effort that
has brought us to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and allied warplanes pounded Serb positions through the
night and were under orders to continue their strikes into Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point not a single Serb soldier has withdrawn from
Kosovo,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters at the
Pentagon, immediately following a White House meeting between
Clinton and the Joint Chiefs of Staff. ``The bombing campaign will
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's government and the Serb-dominated Yugoslav
Parliament accepted the peace plan early Thursday, after it was
presented by Russia's envoy to the Balkans, Viktor Chernomyrdin and
the Finnish president, Martti Ahtisaari, in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The decision followed 2 1/2 months of NATO air strikes, during
which U.S. and allied pilots flew more than 32,000 sorties against
Serb military targets and fielded forces, destroying dozens of
bridges, scores of buildings, refineries and factories and roughly
700 military vehicles and aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimated that some 10,000 Serb soldiers have been killed
or wounded in the strikes, and Belgrade has placed civilian deaths
at 1,500. NATO has reported no allied fatalities, though two U.S.
warplanes were shot down and their pilots rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the brink of a major foreign policy triumph, Clinton
and his aides refrained from declaring victory against Milosevic, a
wily tactician whose past promises have often proven hollow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word of the day is 'cautious,''' said Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, a chief architect of Clinton's policy in
Kosovo. ``We'll have plenty of time to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Milosevic's record for reneging on pledges in Kosovo and
elsewhere across the Balkans, ``Verifiable deeds, not seductive
words, are the only currency that counts in this conflict,'' said
Albright's spokesman, James Rubin. ``This is the beginning of the
process; this is not the end of the diplomatic process.''
</P>
<P>
   During a press conference in Cologne, Germany, Ahtisaari said
Belgrade's decision marked a clear breakthrough but does not yet
guarantee peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear with me if I am not jumping here with enthusiasm, because
there is a lot of hard work that needs to be done,'' said
Ahtisaari, who was in Cologne to brief officials attending a summit
of European Union (EU) leaders. ``But I believe that, as I said,
that the first step in building peace has been made.''
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder voiced greater optimism,
however, and warned his NATO counterparts not to squander a genuine
chance for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a political breakthrough,'' said Schroeder, the
current EU president. ``The peace, in my opinion, is very close.
And, politically, we have to make sure that it doesn't slip out of
our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord approved in Belgrade, the Serb government
appeared to agree to the five key demands NATO has made since it
began bombing Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Those are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  an end to violence and repression targeting majority ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, the southern province of Serbia;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the withdrawal of all Serb military, police and paramilitary
forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the deployment of an armed security force with NATO
``participation;''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  guarantees that an estimated 1.5 million ethnic Albanians
forced to flee their homes may return in safety;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and political autonomy for ethnic Albanians, who made up 90
percent of Kosovo's population before hostilities prompted them to
flee in Europe's largest forced exodus since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb government also agreed to place Kosovo under United
Nations administration for an interim period of unspecified
duration.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, Serb forces would have seven days to vacate
Kosovo, beginning on the day they commence withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   After pulling out all forces, Serbs would be allowed to place
``a small agreed number,'' of troops and police back into Kosovo to
perform such duties as land-mine clearing, the monitoring of border
posts and liaison activities with international security and
civilian operations.
</P>
<P>
   The number of such personnel would be ``hundreds, not
thousands,'' according to a copy of the text that was translated
from Serbian into English by the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Critical questions remained, however, over the most contentious
point in the peace accord: the composition of a Kosovo peacekeeping
force, or KFOR.
</P>
<P>
   It is the position of the United States and its NATO allies that
such a force must be a heavily-armed contingent of some 50,000
troops led by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   There are 20,000 NATO troops pre-positioned near Kosovo's border
with Macedonia and Albania, and another 2,000 U.S. Marines afloat
near the Adriatic Sea. Cohen said additional forces could be
quickly mustered to form the vanguard of a peacekeeping force
capable of moving into Kosovo on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement endorsed by the Serb government, however, leaves
some room for interpretation. It describes a force to be deployed,
under the auspices of the United Nations, that would be
``effective,'' and contain ``essential NATO participation,'' as
well as ``unified control and command.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear whether that wording was part of a diplomatic
effort to finesse the issue of NATO control or whether in fact
Milosevic means to insist on a U.N.-led force with only token NATO
representation. Until Thursday, Milosevic had rejected a NATO-led
force.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, a key strategist
during the Kosovo crisis, told reporters at NATO headquarters in
Brussels that there was no ambiguity in his mind as to the intent
of the accord.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``effective,'' for instance, is diplomatic code for a
NATO force, Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to qualify as 'effective,' the Kosovo implementation
force needs to have NATO at its core,'' Talbott said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, the state department spokesman, said the next step
forward in the peace process would be to clarify precisely what it
is that Milosevic has agreed to, then to codify the deal in some
legally-binding set of accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could come in the form of military-to-military
codification, it could come in the form of a Security Council
resolution,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Serb military commanders were working late Thursday to
schedule a meeting in a neutral city to nail down the mechanics and
logistics of a Serb troop withdrawal from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our end, it would only take a few hours' notice,'' to
arrange such a meeting, said Mike Hammer, a spokesman for Clinton's
National Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said it wasn't decided whether such a meeting would be
attended by the NATO commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, or one
of his officers.
</P>
<P>
   If such a meeting produced agreement over the specifics of a
Serb troop withdrawal, Hammer said, it was conceivable that a
pullout could begin as early as this weekend, accompanied by a
suspension of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to move very quickly on this,'' Hammer said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Albright said she would travel to Europe in the
coming days to meet with her counterparts over how to proceed with
a U.N. Security Council resolution that would set forth a path for
the return of refugees and reconstruction efforts inside
war-devastated Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A year-and-a-half of Serb repression -- dramatically escalated
when NATO bombing began -- has driven an estimated 850,000 ethnic
Albanians out of Kosovo. Another 650,000 are believed to have fled
their homes and taken refuge in the rural mountains of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the State Department's belief that more than 5,000
ethnic Albanians have been executed inside Kosovo and untold
numbers of others injured, raped or otherwise brutalized, and the
proportions of the tragedy served to further temper relief within
the Clinton administration over the apparent capitulation of the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very sober time,'' Rubin said. ``This is not a time
for popping champagne corks. This is a time for getting the
refugees home and for getting the Serb forces out of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin stressed that Thursday's peace accord included no amnesty
for Milosevic, who has been indicted for war crimes by the U.N.
tribunal prosecuting such offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin instead called on Serbs to hand over Milosevic for trial
by the tribunal in the Hague, Netherlands, and said no U.N. member
state had the authority to immunize Milosevic against prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would not support any step by anybody to do that,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
