<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2252 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-US-REAX-(2TAKE     06-03 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-REAX-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE REACTS WITH CAUTIOUS RELIEF TO WORD OF PEACE ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER and JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton cautiously welcomed word of
Yugoslavia's apparent acceptance of international peace terms for
Kosovo as some members of the administration privately expressed
relief that a difficult military and diplomatic episode may be
coming to a close.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, if it holds up, would mark the beginning of the
end of a 10-week crisis that has brought devastation to the Balkans
and a bitter debate in Washington over Clinton's concept of a
limited, casualty-free war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movement by the Serbian leadership to accept these conditions,
established by NATO and the international community is, of course,
welcome,'' the president said in a brief Rose Garden appearance
Thursday afternoon. ``But based on our past experience, we must
also be cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and other senior administration officials still
expressed deep skepticism about Belgrade's intentions, saying that
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia has repeatedly broken
promises to abide by international accords. They insisted that the
bombing of Yugoslavia would continue until Milosevic has begun the
rapid withdrawal of his army and police forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until then, and until Serb forces begin a verifiable
withdrawal from Kosovo, we will continue to pursue diplomacy, but
we will also continue the military effort that has brought us to
this point,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met late in the afternoon with the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, to review the terms of the peace agreement and discuss the
steps leading to the deployment of a 50,000-troop peacekeeping
force in Kosovo. Military leaders told the president that they are
prepared to move allied soldiers into Kosovo swiftly, beginning as
soon as Yugoslavian forces start to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials at the White House, State Department and Pentagon
all hewed to the cautious line the president laid down. Behind the
administration's public reserve, however, was a deep sense of
relief, almost of vindication, after more than seven weeks of
relentless war-making in the Balkans and harsh criticism at home.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including members of Congress, charged that the
president engaged the nation in a distant war that did not threaten
U.S. interests. Others said Clinton pursued a military campaign of
half-measures that would never achieve its stated goals.
</P>
<P>
   But the calibrated war waged by the United States and its NATO
allies appeared to be on the brink of success in its limited aims _
the removal of Yugoslav troops from Kosovo, the return of refugees
to the province and the entry of a NATO-led peacekeeping force to
police the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore particularly welcomed the news, aides
said, not only because it meant the likely end of the latest Balkan
conflict, but because U.S. troops would not be fighting a European
war during his campaign for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it was too early to declare victory, because
countless details need to be resolved and nearly a million refugees
repatriated.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, one of the most ardent
advocates within the administration of the air war, expressed
guarded satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   She underlined the uncertainties about how Milosevic would
proceed in the coming days, a wariness brought on by the Yugoslav
leader's past failures to live up to accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to take this a step at a time,'' she told
reporters at the State Department Thursday afternoon. ``He has
accepted something but it has to be implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Her chief spokesman, James Rubin, added: ``This is not a time
for popping champagne corks. This is a time for getting the
refugees home and for getting the Serb forces out of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One senior administration official, speaking candidly only when
promised anonymity, said there would be plenty of time for
self-congratulation later if an end to the conflict on allied terms
has in fact been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared to declare victory when victory in fact is at
hand,'' the official said. ``We will be relieved when he has
withdrawn his forces. But right now we're viewing this with more
than a dash of skepticism. It's a long way from this to seeing the
last Serb soldier cross the border and walk north.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite this wariness, a top foreign policymaker said that the
allies are in a much stronger position today than they were 24
hours ago _ indeed, at any time since the bombardment of Yugoslavia
began on the night of March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either Milosevic complies, or his defiance vastly strengthens
our hand to do what we need to do,'' this aide said. ``It would
demonstrate his cynicism _when given the chance to choose peace he
chose war. It would alienate the Russians and make it easy to
resume the bombing until he complies.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Albright described Milosevic as accepting and understanding the
demands listed in a document delivered to him by the president of
Finland, Martti Ahtisaari, who was representing the European Union,
and the Russian envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   The two-page document, obtained by The New York Times, outlined
the basic five demands of NATO, most importantly the withdrawal of
all of Milosevic's forces from Kosovo under a ``rapid'' timetable
and the deployment of an international force under NATO command and
control to take back and protect the ethnic Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement said that once all the Serbian and Yugoslav forces
had left, an ``agreed number of Yugoslav and Serbian personnel''
would be allowed to return. They would serve as liaison with the
international military and civic missions in Kosovo, clear
minefields, and maintain a presence at Serb religious sites and at
border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   No specific number was mentioned in the document for the Serb
and Yugoslav officials who would be allowed to return, referring
only to ``hundreds, not thousands.'' Administration officials have
insisted in the last several weeks that these people would amount
to only a symbolic presence.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There was some confusion over whether the document given to
Milosevic _ and which was primarily drafted under the supervision
of the Deputy Secretary of State, Strobe Talbott _ was precisely
the same as that passed by the Serbian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The only difference, according to the State Department
spokesman, Rubin, was a footnote which was on the document given to
Milosevic but excluded in the document passed by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The footnote dealt with differences between NATO and Russia over
participation of Russia in the international security force.
Russia, according to the footnote, did not agree to its soldiers
participating in the international security force that was under
NATO command and control.
</P>
<P>
   The footnote states that the force would have a unified NATO
chain of command under the political direction of the NATO
countries.
</P>
<P>
   If Russian soldiers participated in the force, they would do so
under arrangements to be made in the future, the administration
said. The State Department said that Ahtisaari explained to
Milosevic the meaning of the footnote and told the Yugoslav leader
that the question of Russian participation was a matter between
NATO and Russia and had no bearing on Yugoslavia. Milosevic,
according to this account, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   For the State Department, the next few days promised to be
tense: a waiting game to see if Milosevic would agree to codify his
acceptance in a formal military-to-military agreement worked out
between NATO and the Yugoslav Army.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The British general, Michael Jackson, who heads the NATO troops
already deployed in Macedonia as a vanguard for the international
security force, was expected to head a NATO military delegation
that would negotiate with the Yugoslav military, an administration
official said. The meeting likely would take place not in Belgrade,
but along one of Serbia's borders, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The terms under which the NATO bombing would be suspended were
the most critical steps in the coming days, administration
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This was because once the bombing was suspended it would be
extremely difficult to resume the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   A number of alliance members would resist a resumption. Further,
an administration official said, once the bombing stopped, refugees
were likely to start returning home, making a resumption of bombing
problematic.
</P>
<P>
   While officials said the bombardment would continue until a
verifiable withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo begins, they
indicated that the pace and breadth of the bombing would diminish
over the next several days as the final diplomatic details are
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONALT TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Allied warplanes will not attack retreating Serb soldiers, one
official said. ``Everybody understands we would not do anything to
impede the withdrawal of their forces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the agreement ran from relief to scathing
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., lambasted the agreement as a ``so-called peace
deal'' which had been negotiated by the Russians, the European
Union and an indicted war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only acceptable deal with Slobodan Milosevic is one that
offers him safety in exile in exchange for his agreement to step
down and hand power to Serbian Democrats,'' Helms said in a
statement. ``Milosevic must be driven from power, vertically or
horizontally.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., has supported the air war but
has questioned whether air power alone would compel Milosevic to
capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he expressed satisfaction that Milosevic apparently
had given in to the core NATO conditions, relieving the United
States of the burden of planning and carrying out a ground
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that in fact we have achieved our objectives on the
ground from the air and achieved them at astonishingly low rate of
casualties. We did not lose a NATO soldier in combat,'' Lieberman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we have been victorious in turning back ethnic
aggression. It is very important for the stability and peace of
Europe, but also critically important for the credibility of NATO
and the United States as protectors of the rule of law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
