<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-HNS &LR;      06-03 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SHOULD NOT TRUST MILOSEVIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Filed in ``a'' and ``i'' categories) 
(Eds.: Notice dateline change) 
 
(Eds.: Analysis logo needed) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ As the USS Kearsarge sailed from the United
States for the Adriatic last month, one of the last things a sailor
told a reporter at the dock in Norfolk, Va., was: ``I don't trust
this guy.'' He was referring to Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, and he had the Balkan bully exactly right.
</P>
<P>
   Every international leader who lines up at a microphone to hail
the Yugoslav government's acceptance Thursday of the
Western-dictated peace proposal should first have to write 1,000
times: ``I don't trust this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with that political penance accomplished, the great and
good who allowed the Kosovo crisis, like the Bosnian imbroglio
before it, to turn from canker into cancer should not be allowed to
wax euphoric about the deal. They should point out how difficult it
will be to carry out and how it is a temporizing proposal that does
not come close to being a final chapter in the sad, bloody
Serb-Kosovar epic.
</P>
<P>
   Although the document agreed to by Milosevic and his puppet
parliament in Belgrade appears straightforward, the emphasis should
be on the ``ifs,`` ``buts'' and ``howevers'' that will fill what
could be a treacherous period of implementation.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, a new boy on the
international block but nonetheless in possession of the rotating
presidency of the European Union, verged on the triumphal as he
formally unveiled the deal at a summit of EU national leaders here
beside the Rhine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good day for Europe,'' Schroeder exulted. ``Peace
now is within reach.''
</P>
<P>
   But Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, a principal go-between
in the deal, refused to hurl himself into the victor's circle quite
yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``A first step,'' insisted Ahtisaari, who was seasoned
diplomatically by the decadelong wrangle over Namibia. The cautious
Finn said he reminded his EU colleagues:
</P>
<P>
   ``The English have a very good saying that the proof of the
pudding is in eating it. And the same goes for peace processes.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another fine saying in English: The devil is in the
details. And it applies amply in this case. Working out timing
issues, especially the withdrawal of Serb forces, will give new
meaning to the term ``fine tuning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, which has been burned repeatedly by
Milosevic, took the minimally prudent step of insisting that the
NATO air strikes continue until the Serb regime has agreed to a
verifiable schedule for pulling Serb armed forces _ military,
paramilitary and police _ from the province.
</P>
<P>
   This insistence came as President Clinton finally sat down with
U.S. military leaders to discuss what an invasion of Yugoslavia
might look like, arguably a step that should have come before the
first NATO bomb fell 10 weeks ago. That initial lack of resolve
encouraged Milosevic to delay making the deal he eventually had to
accept.
</P>
<P>
   The world now knows that a post-Cold War NATO can remain
resolute for at least two months, if the commitment is primarily
U.S. pilots dropping bombs. It has not been a stellar display by
the world's pre-eminent military alliance as an uncertain globe
spins closer to the 21st century, but it's marginally better than
the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Politics being the art of the possible, perhaps Belgrade had to
be allowed the face-saving device of yielding to a peace plan
presented by representatives of the European Union (Ahtisaari) and
Russia (former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin) rather than by
NATO brass with gold braid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the NATO leaders, however, got what they were
looking for as a political exit strategy in the second paragraph of
an Associated Press news bulletin announcing Milosevic's acceptance
of the peace proposal: ``The move came right after Serb lawmakers
in Belgrade capitulated on all major Western demands ... .''
</P>
<P>
   One of the best signs of the day was the more-Serbian-than-thou
defiance of one of Milosevic's erstwhile partner parties. ``We
shall not sit in the government and await the arrival of NATO
troops in Kosovo,'' Serb Radical Party member Vojislav Seseljl
declared after voting against the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   So much has been stage-managed in Belgrade (not to mention at
NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium) over the past few months
that it is tempting to write off these histrionics as more
theatrical decoration. But Milosevic was probably not in the mood
to have anyone appear more nationalistic than he on what cannot
have been one of his better days.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappily, the deal leaves Milosevic to fight again _ an
opportunity he almost certainly will take. The old Communist
bureaucrat has proven he does not know how to govern, only to
agitate.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari noted that dealing with whether Milosevic continues in
power was ``not part of my mandate.'' But the issue must be
addressed, and more than one leader in Washington and in Europe has
questioned how the troubled Balkans can move securely toward
democracy while Milosevic remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   As the EU heads of government met privately here by the Rhine
and began to discuss what will come next in southeastern Europe,
outgoing EU Parliament President Jose Maria Gil-Robles, a Spanish
centrist, expressed his deep concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem ... is Mr. Milosevic,'' Gil-Robles said of the
future southeastern Europe. ``I am not convinced Mr. Milosevic can
be changed. Nothing is impossible in this world , but it's not
probable.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer Milosevic stays, the longer U.S. troops will need to
remain as part of the international peacekeeping force. That much
is clear from the experience of the Dayton accords that brought
peace and U.S. troops to Bosnia and Herzegovina and has kept them
there four times as long as Clinton promised.
</P>
<P>
   To have continued meaning and effectiveness, the Bosnian accord
needs to be renegotiated with a view to a final peace settlement,
which will almost certainly be more difficult to reach than the
interim pact.
</P>
<P>
   And Bosnia, many analysts believe, was a less intractable issue
than Kosovo, which as every school child has learned over the last
two months, holds shrines that are at the core of Serb identity,
although Serbs have left the province over recent decades to ethnic
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   An ultimate resolution in Bosnia and Kosovo may lie in partition
along ethnic lines, a process that concedes defeat for the goal of
multiethnic societies and, equally disheartening, rarely guarantees
lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   As the second anniversary of the Dayton deal approached in 1997,
Brookings Institution analyst Susan Woodward told the Dayton (Ohio)
Daily News: ``The compromises that each side agreed to were
compromises that they could not deliver. It simply delayed the day
of reckoning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the deal agreed to Thursday, all sides can deliver if they
want to, but the final reckoning for Kosovo was not made any
clearer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
