u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANCOCK-OLYMPICS-BOS &LR;      06-03 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-OLYMPICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC WAR OF WORDS ESCALATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC Sports President Dick Ebersol on Thursday escalated his war
of words with David D'Alessandro, president of the John Hancock
Mutual Life Insurance Co., in an unusual clash between two of the
most powerful businessmen in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol charged that D'Alessandro's continuing calls for reform
of the International Olympic Committee are rooted in the Hancock
executive's disappointment over the return on the company's
marketing investment in the Olympics. Ebersol also reached back to
a lobbying scandal in the early 1990s to say that Hancock has
ethical problems of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, in more than three decades of this, I have never
criticized a sponsor before, especially publicly,'' Ebersol said.
``This was boiling up inside of me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the battle was largely one-sided Thursday. Officials at
Hancock said D'Alessandro would make no response.
</P>
<P>
   ``These continued personal attacks from Mr. Ebersol are
unbecoming of an exectuve from a major network,'' Hancock said in a
written statement. ``We are not going to trade personal insults
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers, meanwhile, expressed surprise that Ebersol had
mounted a second offensive against a major advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in advertising for 30 years and my father was at
CBS Sports, and I have to say during that entire time I don't
recall anything like this ever happening between a television
network and a major advertiser,'' said Walter Pile, president of
Pile and Co., a management consulting and marketing agency. ``And
it's not pretty to watch, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Both men are closely identified with the projects they are
seeking to protect. Ebersol is the driving force behind NBC's $3.5
billion investment for Olympic television rights. The scandals,
involving allegations of bribery of IOC officials, threaten to
diminish the willingness of corporations to purchase advertising
time during the lengthy broadcast schedule.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro is credited with modernizing Hancock's corporate
image through its sponsorship of sports events like the Boston
Marathon, the Olympics, figure skating events, gymnastics teams and
a college bowl game. He has threatened to withdraw Hancock's
sponsorship of the Olympic games and its television advertising if
substantive reforms are not adopted by the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen A. Greyser, who teaches corporate communications and the
business of sport at the Harvard Business School, said both men are
trying to speak to larger audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ebersol wants to speak to people who buy advertising at the
major companies who may consider whether to purchase time during
the Olympics,'' Greyser said. ``D'Alessandro's constituency is the
other companies who sponsor or who may sponsor the Olympics. He may
be perceived as the lightning rod for their discontent.''
</P>
<P>
   A marketing official with another major Olympic sponsor said
that both Ebersol and D'Alessandro are acting as surrogates in the
continuing debate over the pace and scope of reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some sponsors wish David would shut up and that someone would
come forward to defend the Olympics before they are really
damaged,'' the official said. ``Others wish the IOC would do
exactly what David has been advocating eloquently for months. Some
of the sponsors wish both things would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What also is playing out, observers said, is a struggle between
two powerful men used to getting their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are both known for not being entirely agreeable
characters,'' Pile said. ``There is an abrasiveness about both of
them that is well-documented.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol first went public Tuesday, bitterly criticizing
D'Alessandro's for his high-profile advocacy for Olympic reforms.
Then Thursday, after assembling several reporters from major news
outlets around the country for a conference telephone call from
Paris, Ebersol said D'Alessandro has long been disillusioned about
Hancock's Olympic sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many people involved with the Olympics have known for
some time that he is a dissatisfied sponsor,'' Ebersol said.
``Maybe he just found it was too rich for his blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock has paid $40 million for its current sponsorship of the
Olympic games, an amount that does not include television
advertising during the games. D'Alessandro has frequently said that
his criticism of the Olympic Games is motivated by dissatisfaction
with the terms of the company's sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol also said Hancock has its own ethical problems. He said
he was referring to a lawsuit, recently reinstated, based on
allegations that Hancock's lobbyists had improperly given gifts to
lawmakers in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not directly consulted with his superiors at
General Electric, which owns NBC, before making his criticisms
public. But he said he had made GE executives aware of his anger
and frustration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
