<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-BEIJING-NYT &LR;      06-03 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BEIJING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BEIJING, REMINDERS OF '89 PROTEST ARE FEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Next to a busy intersection Thursday night, about
eight miles west of Tiananmen Square, hundreds of retirees were
practicing a traditional flag-waving dance to the pounding of
drums.
</P>
<P>
   Happily pursuing a popular hobby, the dancers seemed unaware
that exactly 10 years ago Thursday night, this same intersection on
Changan Avenue was the scene of the first major bloodshed as troops
moved to crush student-led demonstrations in Tiananmen Square, the
giant plaza at the heart of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this intersection, called Wu Ke Song, that tanks and
troop-filled armored personnel carriers rolling in from the west
first encountered streets clogged with angry citizens who had
tipped buses and trolley cars to block the route to the square.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers opened fire with automatic weapons. In a three-hour
period that night, the nearby military hospital took in 83 gunshot
victims, 7 of whom died.
</P>
<P>
   Similar edgy crowds and barricades faced the army at many more
intersections along the way to the square, which troops finally
occupied early on June 4, at the cost of hundreds of lives. Street
confrontations and shootings continued in the city for days.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, there was little overt reminder in Beijing of the
intense emotions and violence of 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tiananmen Square itself is under construction and surrounded by
a blue metal fence, being newly resurfaced for a giant parade Oct.
1 to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from a surplus of police officers along Changan over the
last few days, the dense traffic and casual sidewalk life have
continued as normal. Thanks to heavy police pressure and strategic
detentions, any public demonstrations or memorials here have been
prevented.
</P>
<P>
   On the long stretch of Changan between the site of the first
deadly volleys and Tiananmen Square, there are many signs of how
things have changed over the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The military hospital that had received so many wounded has been
rebuilt. It now sports a red neon sign saying ``People's Liberation
Army General Hospital'' that recreates the calligraphy of Jiang
Zemin, whose signature appears in neon just below. Jiang was thrust
into leadership of the Communist Party and the country during the
1989 crisis, and has worked to bury that legacy with economic
progress ever since.
</P>
<P>
   At another intersection nearer the city center, a wall pocked
with bullets from the morning of June 4 _ where several soldiers
were said to have been killed by outraged crowds _ has long since
been torn down, replaced by a shopping complex that includes a
McDonald's restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country in the last few weeks, about 100 dissidents
have been picked up and warned not to engage in Tiananmen
memorials, and about 34 were being held Thursday, said a Hong Kong
human rights group.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern city of Hangzhou, a group wearing white flowers
of mourning tried to gather but were dispersed by police, with
three arrests, said the group, the Information Center of Human
Rights and Democratic Movement in China.
</P>
<P>
   At his regularly scheduled news conference, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao repeated the government's unwavering line:
``In the political turmoil of 1989, the government took timely and
resolute measures necessary for the stability and development of
China.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
