<HEADLINE>
THE DESKTOP FOLLIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, Conn., Calif., N.J.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Ah, the age of the computer. Remember the dream? The
computer would be a work saver, a herald of the paperless office, a
docile servant eager to lift burdens, solve problems, increase
productivity and leave time for creative thinking. But some dreams,
it appears, include comic nightmares.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Several years ago in my space agency office, we younger
engineers saw the need to develop an award system for the most
egregious computer malfunctions,'' writes Karen Bernstein of
Houston, who works for NASA at the Johnson Space Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We named the simple plaque award after one of the older guys
in the office, a gentleman who never really got the hang of the
electronic age,'' she says. ``The plaque was passed from desk to
desk by a kind of informal laugh meter that measured the level of
hysterical snickers following a computer disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, while Ms. Bernstein was trying to delete a few documents
from her computer, she was in the wrong directory when she typed in
a command. The move, she says, ``killed my hard drive forever.''
The award moved to her desk.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague received the prize ``for making smoke come out of
her CPU,'' she says. ``We still don't know how that happened,'' she
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Someone else in the office called the ``help'' desk because his
computer wouldn't stop beeping _ at least not until ``he took the
book off of his keyboard and released the pressure on the letter
`L.'''
</P>
<P>
   But her favorite award story, she says, was about a friend who
needed to print a sketch of some special space agency hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a plotter in our building.'' she writes. ``This is a
printer that uses a large roll of paper and can print graphic
images of any size.'' Her friend, she says, ``sent a print command
to the plotter to draw a picture of the International Space
Station. Full scale.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The laughter continues to this day,'' she adds, ``and the
award has been permanently retired.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Gerald Zuckier of New Haven, Conn., was
working for a health maintenance organization that was in the
middle of a drive to sign up some new service providers.
</P>
<P>
   In response to their applications, several of them received a
letter that said, ``Thank you for your application; we will be
contacting you just as soon as we complete processing.''
</P>
<P>
   There was just one hitch. The bottom of each letter displayed
the file name for the master copy. It read: ``C:/letters/rejection.
doc.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven E. de Souza of Santa Monica, Calif., a Hollywood
screenwriter and director whose writing credits include ``48
Hours'' and ``Die Hard,'' likes to remember what he calls ``the
infamously hectic writing'' for the 1994 film version of ``The
Flintstones.''
</P>
<P>
   In one version of the screenplay, the slick villain, to be
played by Kyle MacLachlan, was named Phil Lava.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before shooting, someone decided `Jerry Lava' was catchier,''
de Souza says. ``Simple global replace. No problem, except that the
Philadelphia joke in the script (there's always a Philadelphia joke
in a comedy) became Jerrydelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``P.S.: In the end, he was called Cliff Vandercave.''
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David J. Kaplan of Gillette, N.J., who works for CBS, spotted
something amiss on the stub of his computer-issued paycheck, so he
decided to dial the appropriate extension to help resolve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   When he did, he says, he learned just how testy computers can
be. He received this automated greeting:
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the CBS benefits office. Goodbye!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
