<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-03 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC ACCEPTS PEACE ACCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Under pressure from unrelenting airstrikes, a
war-weary public, and even his few remaining allies, Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic gave in Thursday and accepted a peace
plan that calls for the replacement of his troops in Kosovo with
international peacekeepers, including those from nations that have
bombed his country for 72 days.
</P>
<P>
   It was that very prospect _ foreign troops on Serbian soil _
that led a defiant Milosevic to pick a fight with NATO. But in a
stunning, sudden reversal greeted cautiously as a step toward peace
by Washington, Milosevic Thursday endorsed a settlement that gave
him less than he could have gotten 10 weeks ago, before much of his
nation's infrastructure was destroyed by NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's swift acceptance of the plan, without modifications
and less than 24 hours after it was handed to him by Russian envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari,
surprised even Ahtisaari and underscored how anxious Milosevic was
to end the bombing that has left much of his already impoverished
country in ruins. Such bombing continued Thursday night, as NATO
and Washington awaited proof that the Yugoslav leader would make
good on his latest promise.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is notorious for nitpicking over details and making
visiting envoys cool their heels for hours or even days. But with
even the Russians, Serbia's biggest traditional allies, pushing for
a deal, Milosevic apparently decided to cut his losses.
</P>
<P>
   Charging that hundreds of Yugoslav civilians and an unknown
number of soldiers died for nothing, opposition politicians seized
on what they called Milosevic's ``capitulation,'' the opening salvo
in what may be an attempt to drive him from office.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for the withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo, an
international peackeeping with ``essential NATO participation,''
demilitarization of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army that has been
fighting Serb forces for independence, and autonomy for Kosovo, all
of it overseen by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The plan makes no reference to the international war crimes
tribunal at The Hague, which last week indicted Milosevic for
orchestrating the forced explusion of some 800,000 ethnic Albanians
from Kosovo. War crimes prosecutors said they would not consider
dropping the indictment for Milosevic's acceptance of NATO's
demands.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari admitted he had mentally prepared for a long, drawn
out process and more trips to Belgrade, and was surprised that
Milosevic accepted the plan so readily. He said Milosevic had only
once suggested revising the text, but that the Serbian leader did
not argue when told it was ``the best offer the international
community was in a position to make.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton welcomed the news, but said that, given
Milosevic's history of broken pledges, the bombing would continue
until NATO could verify that Serb forces were withdrawing from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A military agreement for withdrawal of Serb forces would be
worked out in talks over the next several days between NATO and
Yugoslav military representatives, said Defense Secretary William
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a military-to-military relationship established,
at least for the purpose of going over the details and the
mechanics and logistics in the event that there is intent to fully
comply with this,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which was spelled out in less than three pages
of type, the Serbs have two days to pull their anti-aircraft
defense systems back from the Kosovo border, and seven days to pull
all of their estimated 40,000 troops from the war-torn province.
</P>
<P>
   It puts the postwar administration of Kosovo under the auspices
of the United Nations, which will oversee the peacekeeping force of
troops made up from NATO countries, Russia and possibly other
nonaligned countries. Ahtisaari said the details of troops, and who
will lead them under a unified command, still had to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari said NATO military leaders and officers of the
Yugoslav Army were in contact to coordinate troop withdrawals so
convoys of Serb troops would not be bombed by NATO pilots.
</P>
<P>
   While Ahtisaari cautioned against ``jumping with enthusiasm,''
he predicted the bombing would end ``within days,'' and that
preparations for getting refugees to return to their homes in
Kosovo could begin immediately.
</P>
<P>
   While Milosevic's acceptance of the peace plan brought
widespread relief here, it also led to immediate calls for his
resignation. His political enemies accused him of provoking a fight
with the world's most powerful military alliance and accepting a
settlement that was less advantageous to Yugoslavia than what was
on offer before NATO began bombing March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a capitulation,'' said Dragan Vselinov, a member of
the Serbian parliament. ``We asked for the resignation of this
government. This government... destroyed our country. Why was this
war needed if we sign a capitulation?''
</P>
<P>
   After a debate that lasted less than two hours, the Serbian
parliament endorsed the plan, 136 to 74, with only the extreme
nationalist Serbian Radical Party opposing it. In March, the same
parliament had rejected a similar plan, fashioned from peace talks
in France, that would have given Serb forces a bigger role in
Kosovo after an international peacekeeping force went in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never accept foreign, aggressor troops in Serbia,''
said Vojislav Seslj, whose Radical Party forms the coalition
government with Milosevic's Socialist Party of Serbia. He warned
darkly that NATO troops in Kosovo would be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   But others hailed the deal as an opportunity for Yugoslavia to
change its status as a pariah in the international community.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Draskovic, who was fired as deputy prime minister last month
when he called on Milosevic to accept a compromise similar to the
one accepted Thursday, called for reconciliation, going so far as
to suggest he would shake hands with American soldiers despite his
anger at the American-led NATO bombing campaign that killed
hundreds of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic criticized Seslj and others for ``creating conflict''
with the European Union and the United States. He also said, ``We
need all kinds of aid and support.''
</P>
<P>
   But speaking in Cologne, Germany, during a European Union
summit, European Parliament president Jose Maria Gil-Robles said
the EU would not help rebuild Yugoslavia as long as Milosevic is
its leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be able to negotiate with Serbia as long as Mr.
Milosevic is in power,'' Gil-Robles said. ``The difficulty is Mr.
Milosevic. The system in Serbia has to change to a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be Milosevic's allies that do him in before the
opposition gets a chance. Seslj vowed to pull out of the coalition
and bring down the government.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement carried by the state-controlled media,
Milosevic's government stressed that it had accepted an agreement
that would be overseen by the UN and that guaranteed that Kosovo
would remain part of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   But the western allies do not want an independent Kosovo and
respect for Serbia's ``territorial integrity'' had been assured
under the Rambouillet agreement which Yugoslav officials rejected
in March, precipitating the showdown with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rambouillet agreement would have allowed for thousands
of Serb forces in Kosovo, the peace plan accepted Thursday will
allow only ``hundreds'' to guard border crossings, clear mines and
protect Serb heritage sites, a reference to the Orthodox
monasteries and battle sites in Kosovo that Serbs hold dear.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's main concession, meanwhile, was to agree to have its
troops serve under the United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
