<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-4INSTINCT-COX     06-03 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-4INSTINCT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wild man's blues
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The most compelling scenes in the maudlin
psycho-thriller ``Instinct'' are a queer blend of the sublime and
the outrightly ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   They occur deep in the swallowing green of the Rwandan jungle,
sanctuary of the endangered mountain gorillas. There a
primatologist, played by Anthony Hopkins, is entranced by the
animals' simple existence and decides to trade his civilized life
for that among the great apes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked them. I even needed them,'' he recalls, without
snickering.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins and the gentle, eggplant-headed primates exchange
soulful looks _ seeds of mutual understanding _ and eventually
shake hands. You almost expect them to share a cigar and play
poker. Under Jon Turteltaub's commonplace direction, the images
move with gentle empathy and PBS lyricism. It's monkey poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Hopkins' flashback fades, the gorillas are gone, and the
real monkey business begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instinct'' swiftly devolves into ingratiating New Age schlock,
with aspirations to the psycho-thrills of ``Silence of the Lambs''
and tough epiphanies of ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.'' It's
not smart enough for either. Gerald DiPego's mawkish screenplay
(suggested by Austinite Daniel Quinn's philosophical novel
``Ishmael'') broadcasts this newsflash: ``We don't own the world.
We are not gods.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Ethan Powell's (Hopkins) message to civilization.
Scrambling but lost, modern humans are a species of ``takers,''
says Powell. We have lost the purity of existence enjoyed by men
10,000 years ago. Sure, but we've got cable.
</P>
<P>
   Powell has achieved Buddhalike enlightenment in the ungoverned
wilds. ``I had different teachers,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   In a brutal scene that will sting animal lovers, Powell kills
two Rwandan park rangers in a bid to protect the doomed gorillas.
He is locked up in an American prison for the criminally insane. He
won't speak and has a bad habit of flying into violent tantrums.
Hopkins, looking a tad ludicrous, snarls and wears his long, gray
hair in ``wild man'' mode, so that it sprays all over, crazylike.
He looks like one of the Allman Brothers during a real good jam.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Theo Caulder (Cuba Gooding Jr.), an ambitious young
psychiatrist desperate to make a name cracking what happened to
Powell, who was once a suburban family man employed at a zoo. The
men face-off, Caulder goading the ape-man prophet and Powell
sitting glazed with cryptic menace. It's Hannibal Lecter and
Clarice Starling all over again.
</P>
<P>
   What does Caulder learn? That man is a beast, and beast is a
saint.
</P>
<P>
   Instinct's'' pseudo-philosophizing is about as trite and
condescending as it comes. To make the point that the gorilla way
of life is superior, the filmmakers shamelessly anthropomorphize
the poor beasts, who I bet don't think there's anything very
special about eating branches, sitting in the rain and doing
without Gap khakis. And I'm sure they could live without Danny
Elfman's smothering angel choruses whenever we see the gorillas'
Edenic jungle home.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins and Gooding flex their considerable acting chops with
great seriousness. Gooding simmers with crisp intensity, but he
doesn't seem to be tapping anything very deep, and this dangerously
softens the portrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins is ... well, Hopkins. He spikes his stoic minimalism
with snaps of unlikely physical fury, but he's really not doing
anything we haven't seen before. He apes himself.
</P>
<P>
   `Instinct'
</P>
<P>
   2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Anthony Hopkins, Cuba Gooding Jr., Maura Tierney
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jon Turteltaub
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter: Gerald DiPego
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: R for intense violent behavior
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 2 hours, 4 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
