<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Desert Blue': Where life drifts along like tumbleweed
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the boring dustbowl of fictional Baxter,
Calif., pop. 89, diversion for the local teens comes in the form of
tourists getting gas or stopping to ogle with willed wonder the
giant plaster ice cream cone rising from the dirt into the big blue
sky.
</P>
<P>
   Escapism is at a premium in this forgotten outpost, where pop
culture, like precious water, is piped in in trickles, if at all.
So when a hot teen TV actress named Skye (Kate Hudson, as a Tori
Spelling archetype) arrives with her addled father (John Heard),
the Baxter teens are furnished a conspicuous outsider to sniff and
circle, with curiosity and contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Skye, to her huffy consternation, finds herself stuck in Baxter
after a truck filled with soda pop crashes and spills nearby. The
FBI, fearing a toxic spill, has quarantined the town. No one is
leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desert Blue,'' directed with quiet assurance by Morgan J.
Freeman (``Hurricane Streets''), traces the progressive minglings
of Skye and the local youths, a scruffy lot who conjure amusement
from the dust by setting off homemade bombs, riding motorbikes and
getting drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Extremely little happens in this miniaturist portrait of
alienation, a teen condition given metaphorical urgency by the
remote setting. The story's core has Blue (a zonked Brendan Sexton
III) and Skye inching into a tentative teen romance. Freeman
clutters the remaining empty space with quirks that reek of
precious symbolism. (Take the couple's overtly literary names _
Blue, Skye _ please.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Desert Blue'' is very much a young man's movie, a strained
attempt at real-time profundity that's finally undermined by its
own vacancy. The film is earnest, if quixotic, but doesn't say
anything larger than its navel-gazing self.
</P>
<P>
   `Desert Blue'
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Brendan Sexton III, Kate Hudson, Christina Ricci,
Casey Affleck
</P>
<P>
   Director: Morgan J. Freeman
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter: Morgan J. Freeman
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: R for language and teen drinking
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
