<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Return' shows courage and survival of POWs in VietnamBy Jody
Seaborn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Knocked out of the action, yet firmly in the
war, the 462 American pilots held prisoner for years by the North
Vietnamese during the Vietnam War fought uniquely personal battles.
A certain amount of luck may have been with these men when they
survived their initial shoot-down and capture, but it was pure
courage, discipline, willpower and a deep sense of honor that
enabled them to survive the beatings, torture and deprivation of
their long captivity. ``I knew if I lived, I was going to get
out,'' says one of the POWs, Air Force Lt. Tom McNish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return With Honor,'' a documentary by Oscar-winning filmmakers
Freida Lee Mock and Terry Sanders that played during this year's
South by Southwest Film Festival and returns today for a theatrical
run, tells these men's stories with sober reverence. The power and
emotion of the individual accounts engage our interest.
</P>
<P>
   Equally engaging _ indeed, fascinating _ is the archival footage
given Mock and Sanders by Vietnam's Ministry of Culture and
Information. As part of their propaganda machine, the North
Vietnamese shot reel after reel of 35 mm black-and-white film of
the POWs. Often forced to ``confess'' in front of the camera, many
of the POWs instead would transmit information to their commanders,
or defy their Vietnamese captors in other ways. Navy Cmdr. Jerry
Denton, for example, blinked out the word ``torture'' in Morse
code; Navy Lt. Cmdr. Richard Stratton pretended to be brainwashed.
``I played the Manchurian candidate,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Former POWs interviewed for ``Return With Honor'' include
Everett Alvarez, the first American pilot shot down over Vietnam
and a POW for 8 1/2 years; Arizona Sen. John McCain, held prisoner
5 1/2 years; James Stockdale, Ross Perot's 1992 running mate who
was a Navy commander held prisoner 7 1/2 years; Pete Peterson, held
captive 6 1/2 years and now the U.S. ambassador to Vietnam; Texas
Rep. Sam Johnson, held captive almost 7 years; Robinson Risner,
imprisoned 7 1/2 years; and Tom Madison, held captive 6 years.
Risner and Madison, who retired from the Air Force as a brigadier
general and a colonel, respectively, now live in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyingly, Mock and Sanders resort to strange zooms and
shifting, hallucinogenic focuses when showing the inside of Hanoi's
Hoa Lo Prison, the infamous ``Hanoi Hilton,'' briefly giving
``Return With Honor'' the cheesy look of tabloid television. And
despite the moving testimony from the POWs and their wives _ to
their credit, Mock and Sanders do not forget to pay tribute to the
home front _ ``Return With Honor'' often feels constrained by its
PBS-like box. It's pretty much standard-issue talking-heads stuff;
no one will mistake this for innovative documentary filmmaking. But
it'll do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
