<HEADER>
A2270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYSE-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      06-03 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYSE-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYSE POSTPONES AFTER-HOURS TRADING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After hearing concerns from big investment firms, the
New York Stock Exchange said Thursday it would delay extension of
its trading hours until at least the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes a week after the Nasdaq Stock Market said an
evening trading session could begin as soon as September. It raises
the possibility that, for the first time in history, significant
parts of the nation's leading financial markets will operate on
vastly different schedules.
</P>
<P>
   In reaching separate plans, the Nasdaq and the New York Stock
Exchange are characterizing themselves as serving different
customers: individual investors, who are said to want to trade
after hours in Nasdaq stocks, and big institutions, which dominate
the business of the Big Board.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Grasso, chairman of the New York Stock Exchange, said
Thursday that the board decided it first had to insure that the Big
Board and its members have prepared their computer systems to deal
with the Year 2000 problem and with the conversion of stock prices
to decimals from fractions, a change scheduled for the second
quarter of next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is consistent with the public interest to
introduce longer trading hours after these events have been
successfully reached,'' Grasso said. ``Whatever the competitive
arguments in favor of extending trading hours, the overriding
interest should be protection of the public interest and the
integrity of the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Grasso said that the exchange would probably
move up its planned introduction of late trading by a year, to this
summer.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Frank G. Zarb, chairman of the National Association
of Securities Dealers, which oversees the Nasdaq market, said that
his group, also with the public in mind, favored coordinating the
start of extended trading hours with the Big Board and with
alternative trading systems. Several of those private
electronic-trading networks intend to offer after-hours trading to
individuals this year.
</P>
<P>
   Zarb said, though, that if the alternative trading systems went
ahead with their plans, Nasdaq would try to extend its hours, with
or without the New York exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Approval by the Securities and Exchange Commission is needed to
change trading hours on either Nasdaq or the New York exchange.
Arthur Levitt, the SEC chairman, has said he would probably not
stand in the way. But Levitt has also said that the industry should
get past the start of the year 2000 and through the conversion to
decimals before extending hours.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt's and Zarb's offices had no comment about the New York
exchange's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Some market participants said they would like to see Levitt keep
everyone in lock step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if it's not appropriate to halt everybody at the
starting line until we've had a chance to work through the Y2K and
decimalization issues,'' said Andrew Brooks, head of equity trading
at T. Rowe Price, the Baltimore brokerage and mutual-fund firm. ``I
would expect Nasdaq and the NYSE to talk very carefully through
this and take the same approach to extending hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Grasso drew an analogy to Coca-Cola's disastrous decision in the
1980s to revamp its formula, saying that whenever a late session is
introduced, investors will have to be educated about the difference
between that session and the ``NYSE classic'' normal trading hours.
</P>
<P>
   The implication was that the exchange did not want to introduce
an after-hours session, which market research might indicate that
customers want, that would instead fall flat.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the conflict between Nasdaq and the New York
exchange pits the new world against the old: a technology-driven
market that exists only in the form of electronic links among
brokerage firms versus the 207-year-old institution, which sits at
the corner of Wall and Broad streets in lower Manhattan and
symbolizes the strength of the U.S. financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso repeatedly invoked that symbolism in announcing the
decision on extended-hours trading, which he said was unanimously
reached by the exchange's 26-member board.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the gilded hall where the exchange's board had met
an hour earlier, surrounded by somber portraits of eight former
exchange presidents, Grasso said that the Big Board had a
responsibility, as the world's largest securities exchange, to
protect the public's trust in the nation's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is the model the world aspires to,'' Grasso said. ``It is
clear that equities will become a global instrument that will one
day be traded in a semicontinuous fashion,'' virtually around the
clock, he said. ``But that has got to be coupled with the one key
ingredient that has defined U.S. equity markets: the public trust
and confidence that our product provides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are held to a higher standard'' than the alternative
trading systems, which aim to capture the fancy of new,
technology-driven investors, Grasso added.
</P>
<P>
   At issue again Thursday was whether sufficient demand exists
from investors who want to trade stocks for several hours in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to our customers,'' Grasso said. ``There does not
appear to be a demand, at least in our securities, for extended
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Lon Gorman, who is president of the capital markets and trading
unit of Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the largest online brokerage firm,
said that his company ``definitely does have customer demand for
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman is also a member of Nasdaq's committee on the quality of
markets, which proposed after-hours trading on that market. He said
he believed that if the SEC did not stop the alternative trading
systems from proceeding with extended-hours trading, Nasdaq would
likely go ahead as well.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone intending to extend trading hours this year, he said,
would have to reach that decision ``in the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the New York exchange comes with some conflicts
of its own. Some of the securities firms represented on the
exchange's board also hold stakes in alternative trading systems
that intend to go ahead with after-hours trading. That raises the
question of whether those firms are looking out more for their own
interests than those of the New York exchange, a not-for-profit
institution.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Deryck C. Maughan, vice chairman of Salmon Smith
Barney, is a director of the New York exchange. Yet on Monday,
Salomon Smith Barney, a unit of Citigroup, said it would invest in
Eclipse Trading Inc., a computerized trading system that plans to
begin offering evening trading to individuals this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Grasso said he was not concerned by the potential conflicts.
``These investments are all part of the evolution of the global
markets,'' he said. ``But when our directors come to the table,
they come as fiduciaries of the NYSE, and first and foremost in
their mind is the protection of the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Salomon Smith Barney declined to comment on its
potential conflict. But the firm has said it generally supported
the idea of after-hours trading if investor protections were in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sanderson, chief executive of Eclipse, said the company
would proceed with its late-hours trading plans. He was confident,
he added, that Eclipse would address the liquidity and volatility
concerns cited by Levitt and the chairmen of Nasdaq and the New
York exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
