800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-AGREEMENT-900&AMP;     06-03 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-AGREEMENT-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND CANADA AGREE TO SET SALMON QUOTAS ALONG PACIFIC COAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seeking to end a long-festering international dispute
that has imperiled salmon stocks and once provoked an angry
blockade by Canadian fishermen of Alaska-bound ferries, the United
States and Canada on Thursday announced a comprehensive plan to set
quotas on salmon catches along thousands of miles of the Pacific
coast and establish a conservation fund to help protect the fish.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to agree on such limits after the last salmon
treaty expired seven years ago, the two countries have engaged in
often heated disagreements over who was responsible for dwindling
runs of the region's signature fish. The salmon are, of course,
oblivious to international boundaries, spawning in the rivers of
one nation and migrating to the seas of the other, and forging any
kind of binational pact to protect them had proven a remarkably
contentious proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides sought to impose various limits, angering the other.
At one point, Canada seized several American fishing boats, and the
province of British Columbia once threatened to block the U.S. Navy
from access to a submarine test station in Canada. In the summer of
1997, embittered Canadian fishermen who blamed Alaskans for taking
too many fish formed a 180-boat flotilla around an Alaskan ferry
for three days near Prince Rupert, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with both nations having taken serious steps in recent
years to declare their salmon species threatened, and with the
leaders of both countries agreeing that a new pact was needed,
negotiators said on Thursday they had hammered out an agreement,
one that will cut catches of some particular salmon runs by up to
40 percent. Among the negotiators, who spoke at briefings here and
in Vancouver, was Lloyd Cutler, a former White House counsel, who
was appointed recently by President Clinton to head the American
bargaining team.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the fund money will be used to buy up fishing
licenses, essentially paying fishermen not to fish. But more
broadly, through a complex patchwork of guidelines covering dozens
of different rivers and salmon populations over the next dozen
years, the pact will for the first time set yearly harvest levels
based on scientific measurements of the salmon stocks. This
``abundance-based'' system will replace pre-set limits that both
countries had tried to impose in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement covers coastal areas and rivers in Oregon,
Washington, British Columbia and Alaska. Some elements will need
legislative approval in both countries, including authorization of
the conservation funds, but there are few signs that the process
will be contentious.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, the agreement will not necessarily revive the nine
different salmon runs declared threatened or endangered earlier
this year under this country's Endangered Species Act. But it will
be a major element of an overall plan to restore the salmon
populations, which in many cases are at only a fraction of their
peak populations earlier this century.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred years ago, a visiting biologist from the Smithsonian
Institution, Richard Rathbun, found the fish to be so prevalent in
the Northwest that he wrote, ``The quantities of salmon which
frequent these waters is beyond calculation, and seems to be so
great as to challenge human ingenuity to affect it in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   But development, logging, irrigation for farming, dam-building,
overfishing and countless other human activities have combined
since then to hammer the salmon population.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke of Washington, a Democrat, hailed Thursday's
announcement as a landmark in which both countries had agreed to
switch from a ``first-come'' fishing policy to a ``fish-first
conservation approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the salmon eaten in this country is raised in domestic
pens, and the availability and price of that fish is unlikely to be
affected by Thursday's agreement. But those who fancy the
higher-priced wild fish could well find that its price rises,
especially in years in which low measurements require significant
cutbacks in the harvest.
</P>
<P>
   As one example in the network of new rules, the ceiling on
catches of Chinook salmon from southeast Alaska, now set at about
263,000 yearly, would be lowered to about 150,000 in years of what
is defined as ``normal abundance,'' said Jeff Curtis, Western
conservation director for Trout Unlimited, a group that has been
lobbying strongly for a new treaty to protect salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   But that number could fall to as low as about 60,000 or could be
set even higher than current limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole issue is incredibly complex,'' Curtis said. ``But
what we have here is a pretty reasonable and innovative
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Other steps will clearly be needed to revive the salmon, and the
listing under the endangered-species act has prompted local
governments in the growing Seattle-Tacoma and Portland areas to
outline possible measures, from raising water rates and curbing
fertilizer and pesticide use to curbing new development. And
another debate looms over once-unthinkable proposals to remove some
dams in the West, which interfere with the salmon's ability to
return to their spawning grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly $150 million in the conservation fund, most of it
paid by the United States, will be used to buy licenses and to
undertake restoration efforts in rivers whose spawning areas have
been damaged.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a bid to give a political lift to Vice President Al Gore, the
White House had him issue an official statement about the treaty,
which is likely to help Gore's presidential campaign in the
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our agreement today with the government of Canada on Pacific
salmon is welcome news for the environment and for the economy in
both our countries,'' Gore said. ``Salmon are part of the very
fabric of the Pacific Northwest, and President Clinton and I are
absolutely committed to insuring that they not only survive but
thrive once again.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ottawa, Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy praised the agreement
in an announcement to Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does demonstrate that when two sides work together for a
mutual benefit, in this case the conservation of the fishing stock,
you can come up with a good deal,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
