<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN'S ISSUES RECEIVED FULL ATTENTION OF TEXAS LEGISLATORS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lawmakers called it the Year of the Child, and
after approving nearly $3 billion in new state spending for
children's health, safety and better schooling, it wasn't just one
more empty promise.
</P>
<P>
   Disadvantaged youngsters at risk for abuse, chronic illness,
school failure and crime stand to gain the most from programs to
ensure that they not be left behind any longer.
</P>
<P>
   All public school students, theoretically, will benefit from
across-the-board teacher pay raises and all between grades 3
through 11 will now annually take the Texas Assessment of Academic
Skills test. From preschoolers to college-bound high school
seniors, the education initiatives offer something for nearly
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all came about because of the surplus. We kept the pressure
on throughout the session,'' said Donna Haschke, vice president of
the Texas State Teachers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept saying, `If not now, when?' This year they had the
money and they had to put their money where their mouth was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it was a pretty good session for children's issues,''
said Rep. Patricia Gray, D-Galveston, who chairs the House Public
Health Committee and was a co-sponsor of a children's health
insurance bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   A new law, already signed by Gov. George W. Bush, seeks to
address Texas' embarrassment as the state with one of the largest
populations of uninsured children in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Health Insurance Program will make sure children
of lower-income working parents will get good health insurance,
including dental coverage. If the state succeeds in locating the
children who need the help, the program could insure half a million
of the 1.4 million children in Texas who lack any health coverage.
State health officials believe some of the remaining uninsured
children might qualify for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the tobacco settlement, the state also is going to
spend millions more for expanded immunizations and newborn hearing
screening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like they really did do a lot of things for the
children this year. The children are our future, and we felt so
strongly that you have to have healthy children to do well in
school and to have better students,'' said Texas PTA President
Sylvia Ostos.
</P>
<P>
   She also hailed more money for school-based health clinics, new
seat belt requirements for ages 4-15, funding for 300 more Child
Protective Services case workers to prevent child abuse and new
rules that parents be notified about class sizes and uncertified
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Grants for all-day kindergarten and pre-school kindergarten will
give preference to schools in economically disadvantaged areas
while other new programs will offer before- and after-school care
for children considered at risk. Companies that make contributions
to the school-based day care or to child care for their employees
will qualify for new tax exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   The PTA was joined by teachers in pushing for an end to the
practice of socially promoting children to the next grade level
even when they haven't mastered the grade they are leaving. The
practice, apparently encouraged by parents of failing children and
administrators trying to move them through the system, should be
greatly curtailed under a new policy that identifies weaknesses in
students and seeks to give them the help they need to meet school
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature and Governor Bush deserve credit for raising
academic standards dramatically and for putting necessary resources
into targeted programs for the students who need extra help to meet
those standards,'' said John Cole, president of the 31,000-member
Texas Federation of Teachers. ``The federation has fought long and
hard for an end to social promotion, and now we have a strong state
policy against social promotion, backed up by $170 million to help
those in danger of falling behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators say they are hoping a program offering remedial help
to failing ninth-graders will curb the dropout rate. Yet, it isn't
simply the failing students who drop out of school. Academically
gifted children placed in normal classrooms sometimes get so bored
they quit school as well, Ostos said. For that end of the spectrum,
the Legislature dramatically quintupled funding for advanced
placement courses for college credits from $4 million during the
last two years to $20 million for the next two.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while the Legislature is lauded by so many for helping
children succeed, some people are raising concerns about how it
wants to handle kids who make mistakes or are suspected of causing
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers heeded public opinion polls showing overwhelming
support for parental notification when girls aged 17 and
under &UR;  &LR; seek abortions, passing the first major limitation on the
procedure in Texas since the landmark Roe vs. Wade decision in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, who had offered a bill of her own on the issue, lamented
that the one that passed could place a girl seeking an abortion in
the uncomfortable position of facing a judge &UR;  &LR; as an alternative to
telling a parent. She had argued for other family members to fill
the role as well, noting that some of the girls might have
irresponsible or abusive parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a perfect world. Not all children live with their
parents. Not all parents are willing to be responsive in a
supportive way. I think we passed a very harsh bill,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters, however, said they believe pregnant teens will be
helped if a parent is informed. If a girl has been abused and turns
to a judge instead, state child protection officials would be
notified by the courts &UR;  &LR; to protect her. Also if a girl has medical
complications from an abortion, a parent could make sure she gets
immediate medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   An initiative creating a criminal street gang intelligence
database to be shared statewide also is stirring the concern of
civil libertarians. They ask what is to keep a juvenile from ending
up on a secret law enforcement list as the result of a personal
vendetta? Will minority children be singled out as most likely to
be in gangs? Will children get tagged as gang members even if they
aren't? Will parents know if their child ends up on the list?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious there are a lot of mistakes. It's not open to the
public; it's not open to inspection. The people who have access to
it are the people who have guns and badges and the power of the
state on their side. So you have the ability for the state to libel
and slander you without having any recourse,'' said Greg Gladden,
president of the American Civil Liberties Union in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Great pains were taken to toughen the criteria that law
enforcement officers must use in labeling anyone as a gang member
on a list, insisted Janna Burleson, an aide to the bill's sponsor,
Sen. Royce West, D-Dallas. Authorities could not place a person on
the list on the basis of dress alone, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   She also pointed to safeguards, allowing for reviews and appeals
if someone discovers his name has been erroneously listed. Parents,
however, would not have the right to see if their child's name is
in the database.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have a right to vote and they don't have anything
to say about what people in government do to them,'' Gladden said
of younger teens. ``It alienates them before they ever get a chance
to be part of the system. It's counterproductive and it's going to
drive people into antisocial behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
