<SLUG> BC-PLANES-WEATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER DATA WAS GIVEN TO PILOT IN LITTLE ROCK CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Air controllers gave detailed weather information
to the pilot of American Airlines jet before, and even while, it
crash-landed in high winds and rain in Little Rock, Ark., on
Tuesday, said federal safety officials Thursday. But they did not
say whether that information should have led the pilot to abort the
landing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nine people died and 80 were injured in the fiery crash of the
MD-80 at Little Rock National Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Two wind-shear alerts had been issued before the crash, but
officials have yet to determine how major a factor the weather was
in the crash, said George Black, a member of the National
Transportation Safety Board, in a briefing in Little Rock on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The flight touched down with plenty of room for a controlled
landing under normal conditions, but slid right and then left
before plowing off the end of the runway at high speed,
investigators said. Black praised the flow of information from the
control tower to the pilot about the wind conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they provided even more than they'd get at a busier
airport, because it appears they were getting periodic wind
vectors,'' he said of the descriptions of wind direction and speed.
``Actually, they continued to give wind vectors after the aircraft
had already crashed. They didn't know it had crashed.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service tracked a powerful thunderstorm
approaching the runway from the northwest as the plane, Flight
1420, came in from the southwest. But thunderstorms are localized
phenomena and Black took pains to note that the storm was still
outside the airport at the time of the crash, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators for the safety board are trying to reconstruct the
weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators here and in Arkansas examined evidence from the
plane, including the flight data recorder and cockpit voice
recorder, the Federal Aviation Administration began looking into
the characteristics of the runway. Diane Spitaliere, a spokeswoman,
said that since the late 1980s the agency has required 1,000-foot
overrun areas at the ends of new runways. The runway involved in
the crash does not have one, and the airport had evidently been
given a waiver, but officials were not immediately sure why.
</P>
<P>
   The airport authority, Ms. Spitaliere said, has been planning to
install an ``arrestor bed,'' a long pad of crushable concrete
designed to stop runaway planes, next year.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1420, with 145 people on board, was landing on runway 4
Right, which at 7,200 feet is typical for a runway than handles big
jets, but is 1,073 feet shorter than runway 4 Left.
</P>
<P>
   The two runways have the same equipment for handling instrument
landings, but only the one on the right has big steel light
standards at the end of the runway, which the American Airlines jet
struck after landing and losing control. The jet split open and
burst into flames after that impact.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were not certain which of the two men in the
cockpit was flying the plane, although they said they believe it
was the captain, Richard Buschmann, who was killed in the crash,
with communications being handled by the first officer, Michael
Origel. Origel was hospitalized and investigators hoped to talk to
him Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how the plane executed its approach is not yet known.
</P>
<P>
   In general, pilots approaching runways in bad weather usually
increase their speed, to counter the danger if the wind suddenly
shifts. A headwind that suddenly reduces in speed, or turns into a
tailwind, can cut a plane's speed through the air to the point
where the craft becomes uncontrollable. Increasing the air speed to
compensate for the wind conditions would also make the plane
somewhat harder to stop on a slick runway. Black said that
investigators would measure the traction of the runway where Flight
1420 landed, which is grooved for better water drainage.
</P>
<P>
   When flying in a crosswind, as the airplane was doing, normal
procedure is to approach in a ``crab'' position, with the nose
pointed into the wind, which in this case would have been somewhat
to the left of the plane's course over the ground. If the plane
were pointed straight ahead, the wind would blow it to the right.
</P>
<P>
   But to avoid landing sideways, according to pilots, just before
touchdown the crew would align the plane with the runway, dip the
left wing into a slight bank, and move the rudder slightly to the
right, to keep the plane moving straight over the ground. That
would make the left landing gear touch down first.
</P>
<P>
   A swept-wing jet like the one that crashed acts like a weather
vane, its nose seeking to point straight into the wind. The MD-80
is slightly longer than many other planes and shows that tendency
more strongly. A gust just before landing, or just after, could
twist the plane to one side, aviation experts said, although it is
too soon to say that happened in this case. If the plane were not
pointed straight down the runway at the point that the crew engaged
the thrust reversers, that, too, would tend to twist its course.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's crash was the airport's second weather-related crash
in recent years. A 21-seat Gulfstream II jet carrying executives of
Eastman Kodak crashed there in January, 1990, killing all seven
people aboard. The Safety Board attributed the crash to pilot
errors and a faulty weather instrument on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
