<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS AND FAMILY OF CRASH HERO GET SAD NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time James Harrison's friends saw him, he was standing
amid the chaos of a smoke- and flame-filled jet, guiding fellow
passengers to any available exit.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crash of American Airlines Flight 1420, his parents,
Lewis and Reba Harrison, of Paragould, Ark., and his classmates at
Ouachita Baptist University have prayed that the 21-year-old music
ministry major had escaped the wreckage and wandered off afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, coroner's officials told them that his body had
been found. No further information on his death was available
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Chuck DeVane, pastor of Harrison's church and the
family spokesman, said he was not surprised by Harrison's last act
of heroism and selflessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be very much in keeping with his character,'' said
DeVane, pastor of the Eastside Baptist Church in Paragould. ``He
was very, very devoted to Jesus Christ and a devoted son and
student and friend who apparently gave his life so others could go
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison was returning to Little Rock with 18 other members of a
university choral group, the Ouachita Singers, who had spent 10
days performing in Germany and Austria. Harrison sang bass with the
group and played saxophone in the school's jazz and concert bands,
DeVane said.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett Baber, a member of the singing group who also helped
passengers escape, said on Thursday that he didn't see Harrison
after the crash. But he said he remembered hearing him guide people
to the exits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quite a few rows ahead of me,'' Baber said. ``I heard
him shout out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a really godly guy, a real good Christian,'' he said.
``He was really a sweet, nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family members were confused and uncertain about
Harrison's fate after American Airlines issued a list at midday
Wednesday that listed Harrison as a survivor, DeVane said. A later
list from American did not include him.
</P>
<P>
   American spokesman Tim Doke apologized for the confusion
Wednesday, calling it the result of ``honest mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Harrison divided his time among Paragould, college
classes in Arkadelphia, and Royal, where he had worked three years
as a music minister for First Baptist Church of Royal.
</P>
<P>
   He conducted music for the worship services, led the choir and
organized special services, said the Rev. George Lynch, pastor of
the Royal church. He also helped launch the children's choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good-natured man, easy to get along with,'' Lynch
said. ``And he was always there to help, very caring, very
generous.''
</P>
<P>
   And gone too soon, Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't understand why the Lord would start somebody off in a
good direction and then call him home, but the Lord works as he
chooses. We have to learn to accept it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
