<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DRAFT BEHIND, USC LOOKS AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Thursday morning flight that took the USC
baseball team from Los Angeles to the Bay Area wasn't long enough
for a movie, but if it was, the selection would have been a
natural: ``Major League.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two Trojans _ catcher Eric Munson and pitcher Barry
Zito _ have realistic aspirations of playing in the majors by next
season after going high in Wednesday's Major League Baseball
amateur draft. Six others at least know they have the option
available to them.
</P>
<P>
   And, like the Cleveland Indians in that baseball movie from the
early 1990s, the Trojans got off to a slow start this season,
losing 11 of their first 15 games, and are rallying at the finish.
USC has won eight of its last 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the defending national champions and they're playing
very well,'' Stanford head coach Mark Marquess said.
</P>
<P>
   USC, which had seven players picked in the first 18 rounds of
the draft and eight taken overall, now focuses on the task at hand:
beating Stanford in a three-game series in an NCAA super regional
this weekend. The Trojans (36-24) are two wins away from making
their second consecutive College World Series appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The series begins tonight at 7 at Stanford's Sunken Diamond.
Saturday's game is at 1 p.m. and a third game, if necessary, is
Sunday at 1 p.m. Zito, a junior left-hander who was a first-round
choice (No.9 pick overall) of the Oakland A's on Wednesday, starts
the first game against the Cardinal's Jason Young.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford (46-13) is the national No.6 seed. The Cardinal won the
Pac-10 title, finishing two games ahead of second-place USC. The
teams split six games this season, with Stanford winning two of
three at USC and the Trojans winning two of three at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   After beating Pepperdine on Sunday to win a first-round regional
at home, USC knows it won't have as much fan support this weekend.
The games last weekend between the Waves and the Trojans drew
record crowds to Dedeaux Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll definitely be outnumbered,'' USC head coach Mike
Gillespie said, remembering a Sunken Diamond-record 8,126 in three
games in April.
</P>
<P>
   Not on the field, though. In addition to Munson, the third
overall pick to Detroit, and Zito, USC features three regulars who
were drafted: senior left fielder Jason Lane (sixth round,
Houston), senior center fielder Brad Ticehurst (10th round, New
York Yankees) and senior second baseman Dominic Correa (18th round,
Yankees).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good news day for us,'' Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   USC pitchers Justin Lehr (eighth round, Oakland) and Steve Smyth
(fourth round, Chicago Cubs) were also drafted. Lehr (7-2) starts
Saturday and Smyth is a long reliever who could pitch twice this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Marquess thinks the pressure of the draft is off the USC
players, especially Munson and Zito, who could be facing each other
in the big leagues in a year. Zito (12-2) was the Pac-10 pitcher of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably relieved and they can settle down,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
