<SLUG> BC-BBN-INTERLEAGUE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interleaguecould use change-up
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tom Glavine goes home to Fenway Park. The Yankees and
the Mets rumble for all of New York. The Oakland A's find their way
to Candlestick Point. The Dodgers fight freeway traffic to Edison
International Field and the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every conceivable angle will be played out this weekend
in the first dose of the season's 252 interleague games, and the
public interest in the AL-NL crossover remains undeniable. The
average interleague crowd last year was 8.2 percent bigger than
intraleague average.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Pedro Martinez, who leads the majors with 10 victories,
opposes National League Cy Young winner Glavine, from Billerica,
Mass., in tonight's top pitching showdown.
</P>
<P>
   The fanfare over interleague play has faded a bit, and the
reasons are the same in the clubhouses as they are in the stands.
There are still a whole lot of teams in the other league that fans
and players don't get to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they'd change it so that we would also play the NL
Central and NL East some years,'' Texas first baseman Lee Stevens
said. ``Because now, it's almost like it's just another game
playing the West teams again. I think the thrill of playing a new
team has worn off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Interleague is starting to get boring now,'' Pirates
outfielder Al Martin said. ``I thought it was a great idea when it
started in 1997. The fans got the chance to see some new teams.
Now, it's just five more teams on the schedule that everyone is
used to seeing every year.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be this way. As originally proposed after
the 1994 strike season, interleague play was supposed to rotate
yearly by division. Commissioner Bud Selig has made noise about
revamping the scheduling, but it is hardly the biggest issue on his
desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fans like it and it's good for baseball, I don't have a
problem with it,'' Philadelphia manager Terry Francona said. ``If
that's the case, it's up to the manager and the coaches and the
players to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0434 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-WILLIAMS04-COX     06-03 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WILLIAMS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Using zany style, former Braves coach Williams blossoms with
Boston
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Into the compressed atmosphere that seals New England
and the Boston Red Sox in a fretful vacuum, Jimy Williams stepped
to the microphones Nov. 11, 1996, and said he was prepared to serve
life's next course.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox managers are more scrutinized than almost any other in
the profession, and to Boston's hard-boiled media, this mix was all
wrong. Williams is a quirky man given to delightful double-talk. He
holds a college degree in agribusiness, animal science. His face
suggests that he is perpetually thinking about something else. He
had been holed up in Atlanta's third-base coach's box for six
years, ducking attention. He might read more than any other
manager.
</P>
<P>
   And he can be easily misread. Run out of Toronto in the early
1980s after taking the Blue Jays to consecutive second-place
finishes, a member of the Canadian press wondered, ``How can he
manage a team? He can't even keep track of the m's in his name!''
</P>
<P>
   So as Williams was ushered in as the 41st manager of the Sox
three winters ago, taking his place among the craggy likes of Joe
Cronin, John McNamara and Ralph Houk, the logical Bostonian
baseball question came from the back of the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you see yourself as the answer?''
</P>
<P>
   This is what Williams replied: ``The city wants something back.
And I know what it is. Everybody knows what it is. It's a world
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Something back? The Sox haven't been world champions since 1918.
Something back? This is the answer to new general manager Dan
Duquette's roster sabotage? The answer to this suffering
franchise's lost direction. The answer to Bambino's Curse?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I've got a wife and four kids,'' Williams went on. ``You
want turmoil?''
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing the new manager for a simpleton, Boston immediately
began its wait for manager No. 42, straining in the meanwhile to
translate the pretzel logic that came out of Williams' mouth.
Someone termed it ``Jimywocky.'' And they've been laughing ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves greet Williams tonight at Fenway Park, where
the best team in the AL East lives. Williams, runner-up for manager
of the year last season, is getting even more credit this year for
coaxing more from a hodgepodge roster than he should. Coming out of
a 20-8 month, the Sox just completed their best May since 1986,
blending rookies and sublime talents into an unexpected menace.
</P>
<P>
   They recently swept three from the league's front-running team
in Cleveland and are 3-3 thus far against the New York Yankees, who
just last year were toasted widely as the greatest team of all
time. Isn't this all something of a surprise?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about that, surprise, or all those other
adjectives, or what do you use? Adverbs? Prepositions?'' Williams
replied. ``I like gerunds. I went to high school with a guy named
Gerand Thornquist. His dad drove a bus for Greyhound. He was almost
the valedictorian. You'd have to be, with a name like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimywocky.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1996 season, the Red Sox have allowed to leave or
dealt away Roger Clemens, Mo Vaughn, Jose Canseco, Aaron Sele and
Jamie Moyer. Duquette, still viewed as a dark presence, compared
with Williams' unpretentiousness, did sign free agent Pedro
Martinez. The club has watched Georgia Tech shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra blossom into a true star.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams still scrambles to get more from less. Three-fifths
of the Class AAA Pawtucket Paws rotation has been shipped up, and
Brian Rose, Juan Pena (now on the disabled list) and John Wasdin
are a combined 10-0. The club skated through closer Tom Gordon's
and starter Bret Saberhagen's stints on the DL. Starter Mark
Portugal just left the team and might retire.
</P>
<P>
   Williams hasn't hesitated to play rookies Trot Nixon
(outfielder) and Brian Daubach (first baseman), who have eight
homers and 27 RBIs. When he saw it necessary to bench second
baseman Jeff Frye in favor of Jose Offerman _ Duquette had pledged
that Offerman would not play second when he signed him to a roundly
criticized $26 million, four-year deal last winter _ Williams made
the change and even Frye understood.
</P>
<P>
   What has emerged is something stronger than its individual
parts. And Boston is lapping it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really looking for a leader, maybe a so-called
leader,'' Williams said earlier. ``This is a baseball team.''
</P>
<P>
   And not one without flaws. Although the pitching leads the AL
with a 4.03 ERA, the Red Sox cannot boast the slugging lineup that
thrived for years at Fenway. Their 53 homers are the third-lowest
in the league, and with just 26 stolen bases, they also are the
AL's most inert. Yet they have a momentum that begins in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of the players up there, and they like Jimy,''
said Braves outfielder Otis Nixon, who played for Williams in
Atlanta in the early 1990s and against him last year when Nixon
played for Minnesota. ``They like playing for him. They want him to
do well. And when you have guys like that playing for you and
busting their butt for you, that means a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Transformed from the clueless intruder of three years ago,
Williams has become a reluctant celebrity. As if to satisfy the
public's thirst for Jimywocky, he already has uttered these items
this year:
</P>
<P>
   _ Called on league president Gene Budig's carpet after the
brawl-filled game on April 23 with Cleveland, Williams said, ``I
saw the good doctor. I don't know why he was smiling. I don't know
if it's because this is a good day or ... maybe his treasury's
gonna have more eagles in there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ While praising scouts as the ``unsung heroes'' for finding
tomorrow's talent, Williams was asked what scout found him in 1964
when he was playing in the semi-pro Basin League in Sturgis, S.D.
Response: ``God.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Asked if he felt helpless in the early going as the club
struggled at the plate, Williams replied, ``Helpless? Oh, no, I
don't have a chauffeur. I can still drive. I can make it through
two rotaries.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Prompted for suggestions on what should be kept from the old
Fenway and included in the new Fenway, still under design, Williams
said, ``I think I have the best shower in baseball. I'll take that
shower I got and put it in the new park. The rest of it, I'll leave
up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows where this is headed. At the start of the 1998
season, some people projected this team for fifth place. For now,
they play as if they deserve to win every game. Earlier in the
week, when the Sox rallied twice to beat Detroit on late home runs,
Tigers catcher Brad Ausmus said, ``Everything is going Boston's
way. When they need a player to fall on the basepaths, they have a
player fall on the basepaths.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the team has been transformed, then so has Williams, who
has become the answer to Boston's question after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a different town,'' Nixon said. ``They know their
baseball up there, and maybe they were waiting for the big name to
come in and sail the ship. And Jimy's got his own style of doing
things. It's a little different from the normal person. But it
works. And I don't think they're grumbling about anything now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimywocky: ``The only day you feel good is the first day of
spring training. After that it's all downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
