<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-MOORE-EWING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even Ewing finds that gain can't cover up the pain
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the world of sports, where heroes are expected to
ignore their aches and pains to stay immortal, courage often is
confused with stupidity. That brings us to Patrick Ewing, the
Knicks' center who will spend the rest of the NBA playoffs watching
instead of playing.
</P>
<P>
   Good. Only a cast around Ewing's partially torn Achilles' tendon
could bring a little sanity to this situation.
</P>
<P>
   A team physician diagnosed Ewing's injury between games of the
Knicks' ongoing battle with the Pacers for the Eastern Conference
championship. Otherwise, Ewing would still be out there, hobbling,
stumbling, looking much like a skyscraper ready to crash to Earth
at any second.
</P>
<P>
   It's as bad as it gets, when a guy doesn't know when it's time
to sit down.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Namath and Jim Otto are among the many NFL greats
maneuvering these days on artificial knees. They all stayed a
couple of hits too long. Willie McCovey's legs are so feeble from
his 22 years in baseball that he couldn't join other San Francisco
Giants stars of the 1960s during a recent celebration at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes will have a certain amount of pain after their
playing days, and I'm no exception,'' said Willis Reed, 57, who was
Ewing before Ewing. In fact, on May 8, 1970, Reed created a moment
for the ages by dragging his sore leg down the tunnel of Madison
Square Garden to inspire his Knicks to a world championship over
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Was that courage or stupidity? Reed chuckled Thursday over the
phone, before saying, ``I played the next year, and the leg wasn't
a problem. You really do get to the point where the wear and tear
on your body catches up with you, and, like all great players, I'm
sure Patrick knows right now in his career what he can take. What
is he, 40?''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing is 36. He just seems like he's older. When his knees
aren't covered with braces or pads, they are packed in ice. In
addition to his knees, he plays with a sore left shoulder, a
throbbing right quadriceps and a strained rib cage.
</P>
<P>
   I saw Ewing's physical woes up close and personal during the
Knicks' demolition of the Hawks in the second round. Once, at the
Garden, Ewing suffered so much that he staggered toward the Knicks'
bench in the middle of a play. His mind told him to leave, but his
heart told him to stay.
</P>
<P>
   That's when somebody has to bring common sense to the situation.
Somebody like the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Knicks' Jeff Van Gundy allowed Ewing to decide
whether to trust his mind or his heart, and you know what warriors
always pick. Ewing played, just as he did Tuesday night after he
felt a rip to his left Achilles' tendon in warmups.
</P>
<P>
   While ignoring the pain, Ewing nearly pushed the game into
overtime with a shot that just missed at the buzzer. Reed said,
``He's like Charles Barkley, Karl Malone, Reggie Miller and John
Stockton. They're all motivated to keep playing to get that world
championship ring.''
</P>
<P>
   They're also all motivated by the belief that they are
invincible, and many athletes live such a myth until their bodies
say otherwise. If not sooner, then definitely later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
