<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HUMMER-BELMONT04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Likable Lewises have horse sense
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ He wore green to the Belmont draw. She wore gold.
As in their racing colors, the colors borrowed from the University
of Oregon, where a platoon sergeant back from training recruits for
WWII first asked out a girl fresh off her tryouts for the pep
squad. All these years later, Bob and Beverly Lewis even dress as a
team.
</P>
<P>
   Hang in there, because the story gets even gooier.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewises are horse racing's favorite grandparents. Thrown
into the public glare with their second Triple Crown candidate in
three years, they have managed to come off as a rare breed _
likable rich folk.
</P>
<P>
   For these past nine years of a 52-year marriage, they have
forged a most profitable partnership. He buys the horses. She names
them.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'Charismatic' just came to me in the middle of the night,''
said Bev Lewis, citing the current Kentucky Derby and Preakness
champion that they bring to Saturday's Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the word. I couldn't even spell it,'' Bob Lewis
said. He has since learned that the name means a chance at racing
history. The same chance that his Silver Charm brought here in
1997, finishing three-quarters of a horse short.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to find a chink in the Charismatic story _
underappreciated horse, reborn jockey, trainer heading to the Hall
of Fame with only a Triple Crown missing from his resume _ don't
look to the owners. Bev, 72, and Bob, 75, are riding this wave of
good fortune with smiles permanently affixed.
</P>
<P>
   They're just so darn cute. ``They're always happy,'' said
Charismatic's jockey, Chris Antley. ``They're always
shoulder-length apart. If he turns to the left, she turns to the
left behind him. They're about as true a people as you would ever
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, they don't come off as equine Einsteins. The
sport has played a fundamentally important role in their lives. Bob
Lewis was 10 when his parents took him to the opening weekend at
Santa Anita. The couple honeymooned at Del Mar, and returned there
for their 50th anniversary. But that doesn't mean they invented
horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   There is the free admission that when Charismatic was risked on
a $62,500 claiming race in February, Bob Lewis was hoping someone
would take the nag off his hands. ``I was ready to take the money
and hit the road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four months later, that same horse attempts to become
the first Triple Crown winner in 21 years. ``You can't even fall
into that kind of luck,'' Bob Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   As horse owners, they have distinguished themselves as being
immensely successful without being overbearing. The ideal owners,
Charismatic trainer D. Wayne Lukas claims. ``They represent you
well,'' Lukas said. ``I've had to write plenty of notes to maitre
d's and valets apologizing for owners. Not them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lewis ``loves this sport so much,'' said Bob Baffert, who
trained Silver Charm for the Lewises and now goes against them with
the filly Silverbulletday. ``He has taken a lot out of the sport,
and put a lot back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   As humans, they haven't done too poorly, either. Bob Lewis made
a lot of money with his Southern California beer distributorship,
and has given a good chunk of it away. He helped build one
cancer-care facility and funded another one that cares for
developmentally disabled children. That's where Lukas' son
rehabilitated after being kicked in the head by a rambunctious
thoroughbred.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewises insist that, regardless of how Saturday shakes out,
it will be a day for celebration. They wouldn't dare brood over a
horse race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to be a loving husband, an adoring father (to
two sons and a daughter), win two Kentucky Derbies, two
Preaknesses, a Dubai World Cup,'' Bob Lewis says. ``Isn't that
lucky enough?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
