<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-US-HNS &LR;      06-03 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA AGREES TO WITHDRAW FORCES FROM KOSOVO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Battered by a 72-day NATO bombardment, Yugoslavia
agreed Thursday to withdraw its forces from Kosovo, stop ravaging
ethnic Albanians and end Europe's worst conflict since World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton and NATO leaders expressed wariness at
President Slobodan Milosevic's apparent capitulation and demanded
to see Serb forces begin their withdrawal from Kosovo before
calling a halt to the daily airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Movement by the Serbian leadership to accept these conditions,
established by NATO and the international community, is, of course,
welcome. But based on our past experience, we must also be
cautious,'' Clinton said in a Rose Garden address following a
meeting with his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we must have clarity that the Serbian leadership has
fully accepted these conditions and intends to fully implement
them. Until then, and until Serb forces begin a verifiable
withdrawal from Kosovo, we will continue to pursue diplomacy, but
we will also continue the military effort that has brought us to
this point,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav parliament, controlled by Milosevic, met behind
closed doors to accept the terms of a two-page peace agreement on a
136-74 vote. Opposition came from the Serbian Radical Party.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came after a series of diplomatic moves by Russian
envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari
who represented the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   The plan required the withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo, the
return of thousands of Kosovar Albanian refugees, the deployment of
an international security force ``with essential NATO
participation,'' and autonomy for Kosovar Albanians. Some Serb
forces will remain to protect Orthodox Christian religious sites in
Kosovo, and the ethnic Albanian rebel forces fighting for an
independent Kosovo must be disarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia accepts the documents for peace brought by the
highest representatives of the European Union and Russia,''
reported the state Tanjug news agency. The parliament action
followed a meeting between Milosevic, Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder called the agreement a
political breakthrough. ``The peace, in my opinion, is very close.
And politically we have to make sure that it doesn't slip out of
our hands,'' Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari, joining Schroeder in meeting reporters, said he and
Chernomyrdin presented Milosevic with the two-page document as
``the best offer that the international community was in a position
to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said, ``The acceptance by
Belgrade of these terms is a vital first step. But the
confrontation cannot end until these terms are complied with and
implemented. As a result, caution is the word of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav acceptance of the plan came at a critical time for
both the Balkan nation and the NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   Daily poundings by NATO bombs were destroying Yugoslavia's
infrastructure as well as its military equipment as the allies
sought to force Milosevic to halt his ``ethnic cleansing'' policy
against ethnic Albanians in the Serb province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But as the bombing campaign entered its 11th week, the United
States and other nations were coming under increasing pressure to
either launch a ground campaign to oust Serb forces from Kosovo or
seek a diplomatic solution short of their original demands.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was coming under increasing criticism from Congress as
U.S. support for the conflict waned.
</P>
<P>
   The pact is similar to one rejected by Milosevic earlier this
year. His rejection prompted the phased NATO bombing campaign. But
Milosevic's policy of ``ethnic cleansing'' continued as he sent
40,000 troops into Kosovo to oust nearly all the 1.7 million
Kosovar Albanians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces have killed an estimated 2,000 ethnic Albanians in
the past 13 months and reports of atrocities since the NATO air
raids began prompted the indictment last week of Milosevic for war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   If the peace agreement holds, it would pave the way for nearly
50,000 international troops to secure sites in Kosovo and ensure
the safety of the returning refugees. The troops would include
7,000 U.S. soldiers. Russia also will commit personnel but possibly
under its own command. The inclusion of NATO troops and its push
for a unified command had been a sticking point with Russia as the
plan was hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met in the afternoon with the Military Joint Chiefs of
Staff to discuss the deployment of U.S. forces. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said NATO military officials will meet with
Yugoslavia military officials to work out details on the withdrawal
of Serb forces and the deployment of NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no action taken that would in any way impede
their full withdrawal,'' Cohen said. ``Until such time as we're
satisfied that they intend to fully comply with the agreement, then
the air campaign will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin told reporters in Russia that NATO would halt its
bombing of Yugoslavia within two or three days of Milosevic
complying with the demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we have succeeded in doing at this stage is to
bring the situation into the legal field of the United Nations,''
Chernomyrdin said. NATO's military actions, taken without the
approval of the United Nations, sparked outrage from Russia and
China, both members of the permanent Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   At the EU Summit in Cologne, Germany, members issued a statement
emphasizing the ``urgent need'' for a UN Security Council
resolution authorizing the international security force and
establishing the provisional international civil administration for
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many details are yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to clarify the information that's been made available,
we need to figure out the details and the implementation,'' said
Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman. ``We're dealing with
someone who has made promises before and has not kept them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
