u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      06-03 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SAID TO HAVE PLAYED KEY ROLE IN ADVANCING NATO PLAN FOR
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Despite its outspoken criticism of allied bombing
raids, Russia played a vital role in advancing NATO's peace plan
for Kosovo, Western diplomats and Russian officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian envoy Victor Chernomyrdin supported the two-page list of
demands that Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari presented to
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia during talks in Belgrade
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's move appears to have persuaded Milosevic that he
was isolated diplomatically and that NATO was very unlikely to
soften its conditions.
</P>
<P>
   That has not only improved the prospects for concluding a peace
agreement, it has also helped President Boris Yeltsin defuse
domestic complaints that his government was powerless to end the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia diplomatic effort appears to have made a difference,''
said State Department spokesman James Rubin. ``We think they played
a crucial role in showing the Serbs that there was a united front
of Russia, Europe and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Chernomyrdin's diplomacy has been
universally applauded here. The Russian envoy returned Thursday
night to something less than a hero's welcome. Left-wing members of
parliament assailed him for going along with NATO. And some Russian
military officials were quick to register their dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our hearts, we soldiers are dissatisfied with many of the
points agreed upon in the negotiations,'' said Col. Gen. Leonid
Ivashov, the head of the Defense Ministry's department of
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO's bombs first began to fall on Yugoslavia 10 weeks
ago Yeltsin has found himself on the political defensive.
Nationalists complained that NATO's attacks demonstrated that
Russia had become weak and marginalized on Yeltsin's watch.
</P>
<P>
   Some even demanded that the Kremlin provide military assistance
to Belgrade, a step Yeltsin steadfastly opposed and one that would
have dealt a blow to his policy of maintaining a working
relationship with the West.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Kremlin a strong motivation to promote a
diplomatic settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking an end to the bombing, the Russians began by marketing
their own peace plans. One Russian proposal, which was promoted by
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, would have confined NATO's most
potent peacekeeping troops to the Albanian and Macedonia border
regions, while neutral nations and Russia forces maintained order
in central Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO let Moscow know that the plan was not going anywhere. That
left the Yeltsin government with some choices: pull out of the
peace talks, drag out the negotiating by proposing other
initiatives, or cooperate with the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin opted for the last. A former prime minister who was
also once the head of his country's natural gas monopoly,
Chernomyrdin may not be among Russia's foremost democratic
reformers. But he understands the value of cooperating with the
West.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of Russian politics, however, it was too much to expect
Chernomyrdin to negotiate on NATO's behalf. So he recommended that
a Western diplomat accompany him on negotiating trips to Belgrade,
relieving Russia of the unwelcome role of serving as NATO's
postman.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's proposal was made during a breakfast meeting he
held with Vice President Al Gore and Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright in Washington a few weeks ago. NATO tapped Ahtisaari for
the role.
</P>
<P>
   In his meetings this week in Belgrade, the Finnish president
warned that he had come to present NATO's demands, not to haggle
over them. Chernomyrdin backed him up.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian envoy got something for his support. NATO's plan
concedes that an international force should be stationed in Kosovo
with the authorization of the United Nations. Russia holds a veto
in the Security Council and has long sought to strengthen the U.N.
role.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the plan presented to Belgrade acknowledges that
Yugoslavia will maintain formal sovereignty over Kosovo. That is an
important principle for the Russians. With so many ethnic groups in
Russia, Moscow does not want to establish a precedent for using
Western power to create a homeland for separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin also insisted that Russian peacekeeping troops
would not serve under direct NATO command. Deciding how Russian
troops would work alongside NATO forces is still a major issue.
Chernomyrdin is likely to be deeply involved in that effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
