<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTON CLINCHES DEAL WITH AVONDALE SHIPBUILDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- In a deal that broadens its fleet of warship
products, Litton Industries Inc. on Thursday agreed to buy Avondale
Industries Inc. for $529 million in cash after a rival suitor
refused to submit a higher bid.
</P>
<P>
   Avondale, based in New Orleans, had agreed earlier to merge with
Newport News Shipbuilding Inc. in a deal valued at $470 million,
and the combination had won the government's endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   However, on May 6 the board at Litton hit the merger broadside
by making separate offers of $503.9 million for Avondale and $1.9
billion for Newport News.
</P>
<P>
   During negotiations, Litton increased its offer to Avondale, and
that company's board agreed this week to accept it but gave Newport
News, based in Newport, Va., 48 hours to come up with a higher bid.
</P>
<P>
   Newport News declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thoroughly reviewed the issues and determined that it was
not in the best business interests of our shareholders to raise our
offer for Avondale,'' William P. Fricks, the chairman of Newport
News, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Litton's purchase price for Avondale works out to $39.50 a
share. Avondale shares closed at $38.1875 on Thursday, down 18.5
cents. Litton shares closed at $69.0625, up $2.125.
</P>
<P>
   The combined companies would have revenues of approximately $5.5
billion, a backlog of orders totaling $8.8 billion, total market
capitalization of $4.7 billion and more than 40,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase is expected to have a positive impact on Litton's
earnings per share in the first year following the close of the
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Michael R. Brown, Litton's chairman and chief executive officer,
said the deal creates a world-class shipbuilding operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It significantly strengthens our lines of business and
provides substantial opportunities to increase revenues by
broadening our surface combatant and noncombatant government
business, both in new construction and support services,'' he said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, layoffs are expected, and Avondale's senior
management will keep their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Avondale's operations will continue to be managed by Albert L.
Bossier, that company's chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Litton spokesman Randy Belote said the merger would not
necessitate a major restructuring at the new company. And while a
new corporate identity has not been selected, both Litton and
Avondale probably would be part of the new name, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Newport News-Avondale merger probably was doomed May 28 when
the government indicated its intent to oppose Litton's combination
with Newport News on the grounds that the reduction in competition
from that merger would not offset cost savings in ships and other
kinds of military hardware.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Pentagon officials said there would not be any
objections to Litton merging with Avondale.
</P>
<P>
   But that deal still has to be approved by the Securities and
Exchange Commission and government antitrust regulators, a process
that could take up to four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a couple of hurdles to get through, but for the
most part the heavy lifting has been done,'' Belote said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
