u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-L.A.-TIMES-PUBLISHER-     06-03 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-TIMES-PUBLISHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLES RESIGNS AS PUBLISHER OF LOS ANGELES TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark H. Willes, chief executive of Times Mirror Co. and
publisher of its flagship newspaper, The Los Angeles Times, has for
the last 19 months used the publisher's job as a bully pulpit to
advance his argument that the newspaper business can thrive if only
it is willing to reinvent itself. Thursday, he suddenly resigned as
publisher, saying his corporate duties require his full attention.
</P>
<P>
   He turned the publisher's job over to Kathryn M. Downing, who
has served as the newspaper's president for the last 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   The move makes Ms. Downing the fifth person in the last 20 years
to serve at the helm of one of the country's leading newspapers _
an institution that had only four publishers, all members of the
Otis and Chandler families, in the preceding 98 years. Like Willes,
Ms. Downing, 46, comes to the job with significant executive
experience, and like him, she had little exposure to the newspaper
business before she joined The Times as its president last year.
She had been a top executive in the company's legal publishing
division before it was sold last year.
</P>
<P>
   Willes said Thursday that while he regretted leaving the
publisher's job he was convinced that Ms. Downing had built a
management team that could carry out the ambitious circulation and
revenue goals he has established for all Times Mirror newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In his early days with the company, Willes said he believed that
the newspaper's circulation could grow from just over a million to
1.5 million. Last year, Ms. Downing upped the ante, saying she
believed the paper could sell two million copies daily _ a
prediction she reiterated Thursday, without giving any firm time
frame by which the goal should be reached. The paper's daily
circulation now is 1.1 million; Sunday circulation is 1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ms. Downing was named president of The Times, a decision
that surprised observers who had expected the job to go to Mary E.
Junck, a Times Mirror executive with a long track record in
newspaper publishing, there has been extensive turnover in the top
ranks of business executives at the paper. One executive recruited
by Willes stayed at the paper just six weeks earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Willes said, ``Serving as publisher of
The Los Angeles Times, even with all of the criticism, even with
all of the breakage, even with all the difficulties involved, has
been intrinsically the most exciting and satisfying job that I have
ever had or expect to have.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added: ``When I appointed myself publisher, one of the
most difficult questions to answer was: how do you serve as
corporate CEO and publisher? The honest answer is, it's hard
because they are two very big jobs. My answer at the time was that
the most important thing that needed to be done within Times Mirror
was to be sure the L.A. Times was on the right track.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he believes he has done that, noting that the
newspaper's second-quarter earnings will reflect the first
year-to-year growth in five quarters. However, Ms. Downing said
circulation _ which has grown steadily over that same period _ was
``soft'' and would be down during the second quarter as the
circulation strategy shifted from an emphasis on direct marketing
to partnerships with Korean- and Spanish-language newspapers and
increased local coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Willes' dual roles as chief executive and publisher had already
caused some comment among the directors of Times Mirror. Last
summer, at a farewell dinner for three outgoing Times-Mirror
directors, one of the three, C. Michael Armstrong _ now chairman
and chief executive of AT&AMP;T _ noted in a farewell toast that he had
difficulty endorsing the concept that one person should hold both
jobs, according to two people at the dinner who insisted they not
be named.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Downing's appointment was announced to the newsroom by the
newspaper's executive editor, and vice president, Michael Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday what her journalistic goals were, Ms. Downing
praised Parks and singled out two areas of coverage for special
mention: an article about the paucity of textbooks available to Los
Angeles schoolchildren and the Kosovo coverage of Paul Watson, a
Times reporter who went back into the war-scarred province after
Western journalists had been ordered out in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
