<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0444 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CHINA-U.S.-EXILES-N     06-03 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CHINA-U.S.-EXILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXILED LEADERS OF TIANANMEN GATHER TO MULL ERRORS AND
ACCOMPLISHMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to remove photo note; no other changes.)  (rk) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass., _ For the first time since soldiers drove them
at gunpoint from Beijing's Tiananmen Square 10 years ago, the top
leaders of China's democracy movement gathered at Harvard
University Thursday, like alumni converging for a reunion on the
leafy New England campus.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering of the men and women the Chinese Communists had
denounced as instigators of a ``counterrevolutionary rebellion''
was itself significant, the leaders said, since some of them spent
years in prison and others have squabbled among themselves over
what went wrong and what they can do from exile to change China's
government.
</P>
<P>
   The former leaders, most of whom were university students at the
time, offered no new plan for political reform in China, but they
acknowledged mistakes they had made with unusual candor and
insisted that the movement they began has already changed China for
the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiananmen did not fail,'' said Li Lu, who was a physics
student at Nanjing University and a leader of the Tiananmen
demonstrators before the Communist leadership called in the troops
on the night of June 3-4, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Communists killed the messenger but had to take part of
the message,'' said Li, who is now managing partner of Himalaya
Capital Partners, a hedge fund in New York. ``The democracy
movement marked the end of the idea that one party dictatorship can
bring good to China, and so now the Communists are tolerating
things like village elections that they would never have accepted
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who attended the conference were Wang Dan, who
organized the student discussion groups at Beijing University in
the months before the spring 1989 protests; Wang Juntao, who ran an
independent think tank in Beijing that backed the students; and
Wu'er Kaixi, a student at Beijing Normal University who gained
prominence by daring to challenge Prime Minister Li Peng during a
nationally televised meeting. Both Wang Dan and Wang Juntao were
arrested after the crackdown and sent to prison. Wu'er escaped and
now works as a radio talk-show host in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined by Wei Jingsheng, perhaps China's best-known
dissident and the author of the most daring wall posters calling
for democracy during the short-lived Democracy Wall movement in
1979. For his temerity, Wei spent 18 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday Wu'er said, ``I'm optimistic, even in exile.'' The
Communists think they have made a ``deal'' with the Chinese people,
giving them economic development instead of political freedom, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Chinese government doesn't understand,'' he said,
``is that the people become greedy when they start to make money,
and when the government thinks it is satisfying them by giving them
economic freedom, the people will inevitably want more freedom to
protect their ability to make money, until this leads to
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Merle Goldman, a professor of Chinese history at Boston
University and an expert on Chinese dissidents, said the
participants at the conference now have ``a much better
understanding of what democracy means and what it takes to bring
about political change. The tragedy is, they can't use this
knowledge now from abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a group that is remarkably talented and intelligent
and cares about China,'' she said, pointing to the success of most
of the leaders since they were exiled. In addition to Li, who has
degrees from Columbia's law and business schools, she said, Wang
Dan is a graduate student in history at Harvard, Wang Juntao is
studying for his Ph.D. in political science at Columbia, and Chai
Ling, the best-known female student leader, runs her own Internet
company in Cambridge, having earned a degree from the Harvard
Business School.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, Wu'er pointed out, many of these highly
intelligent activists got their inspiration from Mao Zedong, when
he launched the Cultural Revolution in the late 1960s. ``We spent
our first 10 years in the Cultural Revolution, and we came to
believe that if all the people in the world united, we could create
utopia,'' Wu'er said. ``It was very idealistic and appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience also led these young Chinese to question
authority, as Mao preached that the youthful Red Guards should
track down and attack corrupt party officials, Wu'er said. Then,
when Mao died in 1976 and Deng Xiaoping replaced him as China's
paramount leader, Wu'er continued, he ``left us confused'' by
denouncing the Cultural Revolution and preaching that to ``get rich
is glorious.'' This created a ``vacuum in ideology'' that prompted
some students to begin studying democracy on their own.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also criticism Thursday of the students' tactics.
Chen Jun, a former Red Guard turned welder who published a magazine
during the Democracy Wall movement in 1979, said the student
protesters had a ``dream without a plan or leadership'' and led a
``romantic-tragic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The students in 1989, Chen said, were too elitist and mired in
China's imperial tradition of petitioning the government for change
rather than striking out on their own, and too afraid of the
government's reaction if they allied themselves with dissatisfied
factory workers who could have brought them greater numbers and
power.
</P>
<P>
   Li said the group, now formally organized as the Tiananmen
Generation Association, plans to meet again next year, in Taiwan,
to observe the presidential election there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
