<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-EXPLORER-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORER SPORT SEEMS TO HAVE WHAT THEY WANT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I entered the working world full-time in the late 1970s, I
couldn't wait until I'd saved enough from my meager paychecks to
buy my first brand-new car. I wanted something small, nimble, sleek
and sporty. And make it red.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was before trucks ruled the earth. Now a young
career woman's fancy frequently turns not to cute little sports
cars, but to rugged, assertive sport utilities. It seems women are
passing up Ralph Fiennes for a fling with Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the success of the Ford Explorer Sport. In 1998, sales
of these two-door models soared 72 percent, pushing total Explorer
sales to record levels. Women bought about half, a significant
percentage for any vehicle. These women were largely unmarried, and
more than a third fell into the 18-to-34 age group that
manufacturers covet.
</P>
<P>
   After a week with the Explorer Sport, I still cannot explain its
attraction to young women. I found its ride harsh, its steering
twitchy and its cabin uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Explorers have come in two-door versions since Ford introduced
the midsize sport utility in March 1990. But until last year, 90
percent of the Explorers sold _ and, as America's best-selling
sport utility, three million have hit the streets _ were of the
four-door variety. Many found homes with baby boomer couples that
had children.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a couple years ago, Ford and its dealers in California and
the Southeast, where four-wheel drive is not essential, began a
$19,995 price promotion to propel sales of the two-door,
two-wheel-drive Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the positive response, Ford gave all two-door
models the Explorer Sport name for 1998, and it gave them the same
$19,995 base price. Now the Sport accounts for one of every four
Explorers sold.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also came up with a ``premium package'' with more prominent
wheel well moldings and bumpers with a painted platinum surface.
Most buyers order this package, and Ford says the young women who
buy the Explorer Sport list styling as a main reason for their
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is the Ford's versatility in hauling people,
cargo and pets, which most of the female owners have. It can carry
five passengers, though I wouldn't want to ride cross-country in
the back; the rear backrest seemed particularly low and lacking in
upper-back support.
</P>
<P>
   Before you climb out, someone in front must release a front
seatback. There is some consolation for back seat passengers: In
the test vehicle they had their own air vents and audio jacks.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo bay is more than ample for groceries and sports
equipment _ there's also a roof rack _ and access through the
liftgate is convenient. A lever pull folds the bottom of the back
seat into the footwell, and the seatback folds to form a flat cargo
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, storage is stingy. There are a lot of nooks and
crannies, but they offer dainty bits of space. The door pockets
accommodate little more than a couple of cassettes. The armrest in
the test model covered a rectangular bin, but a compact disk
changer consumed most of the space, leaving room for only a
half-dozen CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Women buyers also say they bought the Explorer Sport for its
maneuverability and fun-to-drive character. It is maneuverable
enough for its size, but I found the test vehicle anything but fun
to drive.
</P>
<P>
   After a week at the wheel, I concluded that only a young person
could live with the Sport. My middle-age body and fragile lower
back felt battered by the harsh ride. The steering required
constant attention to keep the vehicle moving in a straight line.
</P>
<P>
   And the women who buy these vehicles had better have long legs.
I used the narrow running board for footing and clutched the grab
handles to hoist my short frame inside. As with any sport utility,
this is no ladylike maneuver in a skirt.
</P>
<P>
   The seats proved extremely uncomfortable for my short legs. The
bottom cushion was too deep, hitting me in the calves. I never felt
confident at the wheel because I couldn't find a good driving
position despite the multiple seat adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's standard engine is a pushrod V6 rated at 160
horsepower. The test vehicle had a 4-liter overhead-valve V6 that
puts out 210 horsepower; it is the better choice. A five-speed
manual transmission is standard; a four-speed automatic is
optional.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer Sport comes with two-or four-wheel drive. A knob
controls the four-wheel-drive system; positioned on ``auto,''
four-wheel drive kicks in when needed. There are high and low
settings.
</P>
<P>
   Women seem to like sport utilities in general because of the
safe, secure feeling they get from the high seating position. The
Explorer Sport is further equipped with dual front air bags,
anti-lock brakes and an anti-theft system. Side air bags are
optional for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features are power windows, mirrors and locks,
air-conditioning and an AM/FM radio with stereo/cassette. A new
option this year is a reverse sensing system that alerts drivers to
objects at the rear when backing up.
</P>
<P>
   Though the base price is $19,995 ($20,405 with destination
charges), four-wheel drive, the premium package and other equipment
can push the price above $30,000. The test car, which had the
$1,600 premium package as well as side air bags, reverse sensors,
power moon roof and upgraded stereo, came in at $31,230 _without
leather seats.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the base prices for both the two- and four-wheel drive
versions undercut the Chevrolet Blazer and Jeep Cherokee. The
Explorer is a little more expensive than the cute sport utilities
like the Toyota RAV4 and Honda CR-V, but it is a heavier, more
powerful, more substantial vehicle. To my taste, though, it's too
rough around the edges. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: More of a brute ute than a cute ute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
