</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RIVLIN-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVLIN, NO. 2 OFFICIAL TO GREENSPAN, QUITS AT FED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alice Rivlin resigned Thursday as vice chairwoman
of the Federal Reserve, leaving the No. 2 job empty at the central
bank as it confronts a tough call on whether to raise interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rivlin, 68, said she was stepping down to do research at the
Brookings Institution and to devote more time to her role as head
of the District of Columbia's Financial Assistance Authority, which
is trying to clean up Washington's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues said there was no hidden agenda in her decision,
which came a little less than four weeks before the Fed is to next
vote on whether the persistent strength of economic growth requires
an increase in interest rates to forestall the possibility of
resurgent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Although her resignation will not take effect until July 16, the
Fed said she would not take part in the monetary policy meeting
June 29 and 30.
</P>
<P>
   While unexpected, Ms. Rivlin's resignation is unlikely to have a
crucial effect on the debate within the Fed on the degree of danger
that inflation poses to the nation's long economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   She has been perhaps the most outspoken proponent at the central
bank of the view that the economy is more capable of
noninflationary growth than in the past, and more sympathetic than
most of her fellow policy makers to the idea that driving the
unemployment rate lower under those circumstances is worth the risk
of a slight uptick in prices.
</P>
<P>
   But her views were well within the economic mainstream, and
never once during her three-year tenure did she vote against the
Fed chairman, Alan Greenspan, whose influence inside and outside
the institution vastly overshadowed her own. Indeed, Ms. Rivlin was
the fourth deputy since Greenspan took office almost 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenspan has the bulk of the power, given both his position
as chairman and his successful stewardship of the Fed up until
now,'' said William Dudley, an economist at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
``This doesn't really change things very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rivlin accepted the Fed post somewhat reluctantly in 1996 at
President Clinton's behest, and although she was sometimes
mentioned as a possible successor to Greenspan, she never lost the
reputation of being more interested in fiscal policy _ her area of
expertise _ than in monetary policy. And Greenspan showed every
sign of wanting to stay on in the job even after his third term
ends next June.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rivlin declined interview requests Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Her departure leaves Clinton with two slots to fill on the Fed's
seven-member board of governors. The White House is close to
completing background checks on its choice for the seat left open
last year by the resignation of Susan M. Phillips _ Carol Parry, an
executive vice president of Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they had been aware of Ms.
Rivlin's intention to leave for several weeks, and that the search
for a successor was ``well under way.'' They gave no hint of who
was under consideration.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Rivlin announced her resignation after the close of the
stock market. The news had little effect on other financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed is a strong bulwark of U.S. economic policy, and I
believe we have contributed to keeping the American economy growing
and reducing strains in the international financial system,'' Ms.
Rivlin said in her resignation letter to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Greenspan said, ``Her wisdom influenced all our
deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for whom she served as White House budget director and
before that deputy director, said in a statement that she had been
``a steady and strong voice for fiscal discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed watchers have scrutinized the central bank particularly
closely the last several weeks, after its decision on May 18 to
tilt policy toward an increase in interest rates. The first
substantial clue could come on Friday, when the Labor Department
releases May unemployment data.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Fed's discussions in coming weeks will
crystallize a debate that has dominated policy making for the last
several years. To a substantial degree, that debate has revolved
around issues central to Ms. Rivlin's view of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   She has made the case that not just factors like higher
productivity are tamping down inflation, but that low unemployment
_ seen in traditional economic models as a trigger for inflation _
might itself be spurring higher productivity by forcing companies
to hold down wage costs through improved efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economists have had in their head the idea that tight labor
markets would lead to inflation and low productivity,'' she said in
an interview in April with The Financial Times. ``It may be that
under the present circumstances of fierce global competition, the
effect of tight labor markets is exactly the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rivlin has also been forthright in her belief that a low
unemployment rate _ especially during a period in which federal,
state and local governments are pushing many welfare recipients
into the work force for the first time _ is a benefit that should
not be given away through blind adherence to old rules about the
relationship between inflation, growth and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The models have been predicting higher inflation based on
tight labor markets,'' said Sung Won Sohn, an economist at Wells
Fargo &AMP; Co. in Minneapolis. ``Alice Rivlin tended to rely less on
models and more on her own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rivlin's long service as an economist and public official
included director of the Congressional Budget Office, which she
founded, from 1975 to 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
