<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROCTER&AMP;GAMBLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CHANGES SAID TO BE AFOOT AT PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. is expected to announce next week that it
will cut thousands of jobs worldwide, close several
under-performing plants and take a huge charge to become more
competitive and improve profits, according to analysts and
institutional investors who have met with management.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization will give investors the first detailed look
at where Durk Jager, P&AMP;G's new chief executive, is steering the
company, which makes Tide detergent, Pampers diapers and Crest
toothpaste among other things.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts, most of which are expected to take place outside the
United States, are intended to streamline P&AMP;G's top-heavy
management structure and allow the company to compete better in
fast-changing and highly competitive global markets.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G is expected to divide its businesses into seven units, which
will be run as global entities instead of as parts of regional
divisions. The units will focus on specific product segments,
including hair care, laundry and feminine protection, and are
expected to speed up the company's lethargic product development
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, part of what P&AMP;G is calling Organization 2005, are
part of a plan to focus on research and development instead of
geographical expansion. The strategy represents a new direction for
the company under Jager, who took over in January after 29 years
with P&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a bit of a change in mindset,'' said Mark
Godfrey, senior analyst with Investco Funds Group in Denver, which
holds 1.6 million P&AMP;G shares. ``Before they stuck to a pretty
conservative game plan. Durk has come in and shaken things up a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization is expected to be announced next Wednesday
when executives meet with investors and analysts in New York. The
company declined Thursday to comment on any planned job cuts or
shift in its business structure.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and analysts said that in addition to the job cuts and
plant closings, they expected the company, which has 110,000
employees worldwide, to announce charges of $2 billion to $3
billion related to the reorganization. It would be the first
significant revamping since 1993, when the company dismissed
thousands of workers, closed dozens of plants and also took huge
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said management would have to justify another round of
hefty charges. But the overall reorganization, if well executed,
should make the company more competitive and ultimately increase
profitability, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very strong hint we've been getting from P&AMP;G is that they
will end up being more nimble and getting product to market
faster,'' said Constance Maneaty, an analyst with Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Though still a dominant force in consumer products, P&AMP;G has long
been accused of having a cumbersome management structure, a slow
product development pipeline and a far too conservative global
growth plan. Such weaknesses have enabled rivals like Unilever to
grow more aggressively globally and smaller competitors like Clorox
Co. to respond faster to new product trends. In one high-profile
misstep, P&AMP;G was too slow to come out with new versions of Crest,
long the undisputed leader in toothpaste. As a result,
Colgate-Palmolive's new brand, Total, now outshines Crest.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, P&AMP;G has begun to show more spunk. It has
worked to push more forcefully into international markets. And last
year, it introduced Febreeze, a product that removes odors from
fabric and has quickly become a juggernaut. What is more, P&AMP;G is
rolling out two products that, while not revolutionary, analysts
said, represent innovation that has at times been lacking at the
company. They are Dryel, a dry-cleaning kit for home use, and
Swiffer, an electrostatic mop with with disposable cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by the potential of such new products as well as
innovation with its more traditional products, like new features on
diapers and new formulas for laundry detergent, P&AMP;G has said that
it expects to lift earnings 12 percent to 14 percent even without a
reorganization. Now, ``I'd expect that range to ratchet up,'' said
Sally Dessloch, an analyst with J.P. Morgan Securities. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
