<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Governor Davis Appoints 2 Interim Commissioners for PUC  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith and Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Governor Gray Davis yesterday appointed two members of his staff to
serve on the state Public Utilities Commission _ but only as
interim commissioners until permanent members are named.
<P>
   The surprise move, hastily arranged Wednesday night, appeared to
have been inspired by fear the commission, with three Republican
holdovers from the Wilson administration, was preparing to approve
measures the governor opposes.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC has been postponing decisions on important
telecommunications and energy issues since two of its five members
departed six months ago. The temporary appointments come amid
criticism that Davis has been taking too long to fill positions
throughout state government.
</P>
<P>
   The new appointees would not say what direction, if any, they've
received from Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't discuss my discussions with the governor,'' said
Loretta Lynch, 37, a former San Francisco litigation attorney who
headed the governor's Office of Planning and Research until she was
appointed to the PUC yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The other appointee, Tal Finney, 35, is known as an ``Energizer
bunny'' in Sacramento. He earned the nickname after Davis appointed
him on four previous occasions to temporarily head other agencies
or commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in February, Finney served two months as interim
director of the Department of Social Services. In January, he was
named to the Agriculture Labor Relations Board _ for a day. In
addition to the PUC, he has been representing the governor for no
pay on the Managed Risk Medical Board and the California Earthquake
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   His regular job has been the governor's director of policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I serve at the governor's pleasure wherever he wants me,''
Finney said after yesterday's PUC meeting in San Francisco. ``We'll
be representing his views here.''
</P>
<P>
   At yesterday's meeting, Finney and Lynch got the commission to
postpone scheduled votes on three issues:
</P>
<P>
   _One would affect the way phone companies compensate each other
for completing each other's calls. The issue is important because
it could affect how much consumers pay for Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, calls made to a local ISP number are considered
local. But Pac Bell has been arguing that calls made to an ISP are
long-distance, because the Internet is a global network.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which has ISPs fuming and threatening to raise
rates if it passes, apparently has the support of one or two
commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   _Rival proposals would let electric utilities like Pacific Gas &AMP;
Electric earn profits of as much as 11.6 percent on regulated
activities, such as power distribution. Consumer advocates have
suggested that the profits of PG&AMP;E, Southern California Edison and
San Diego Gas &AMP; Electric Co. be capped at something closer to 9
percent _ potentially saving ratepayers hundreds of millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   _The final issue would have established the PUC's position on a
bill that would reorganize its governance. The bill, SB 33, would
let the governor pick the PUC president _ rather than continuing to
use peer selection. It also would expand the president's powers and
allow the commissioners to hire more personal advisers from outside
the PUC staff.
</P>
<P>
   At yesterday's meeting, Commissioner Henry Duque attacked the
bill, saying it would ``politicize the agency'' and ``betray the
Commission's legacy as an independent agency and replace experts on
markets and law with experts on politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch and Finney said they will carefully study each issue
before casting votes as early as Thursday, at the PUC's next
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Onlookers expressed disappointment that Davis had not made &LR; 
 &LR; appointed permanent PUC commissioners. The job pays about $100,000
per year.
</P>
<P>
   One other important PUC position _ director of the Office of
Ratepayer Advocates _ is still vacant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like Mr. Toad's Wild Ride over there,'' said Nettie
Hoge, executive director of The Utility Reform Network, a consumer
advocacy group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Finney previously served as Davis' general counsel when he was
lieutenant governor. He earned his bachelor's degree in political
science from the University of California at Los Angeles, and has a
law degree from Loyola Law School.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch has been a partner in the San Francisco law firm Keker &AMP;
Van Nest since 1991. Previously, she was a lawyer for the Legal Aid
Foundation of Los Angeles, handling homelessness and welfare policy
cases and worked, briefly, for state Attorney General John Van de
Kamp.
</P>
<P>
   She graduated magna cum laude from the University of Southern
California and earned her law degree from Yale University Law
School.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
