<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2346 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEXT-NEXT_SFCHRON &LR;      06-03 1576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEXT-NEXT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Tech Millionaires Face the Rest of Their Lives  &HT;     By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
When Greg Gianforte sold the software company he founded to McAfee
Associates for $10 million five years ago, he faced an unsettling
question: Was he ready to retire at an age when most people have
barely gotten their careers on track?
<P>
   ``At 33 years old, I didn't have to work anymore,'' said
Gianforte, who was founder and chief executive of a New Jersey firm
called Brightwork &UR;  &LR; Development. ``I had to search through: What am
I going to do for the rest of my life? I wasn't ready to fly-fish
for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Reaping the riches of the Internet boom, a growing number of
30- to 50-year-old technology professionals today are facing
choices like Gianforte's.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They've helped turn living-room startups into billion-dollar
companies. They've amassed enough wealth to retire without a worry.
But they're rarely ready for golf-and-travel retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Many plunge right in to the next startup without a second
thought. Some move smoothly to new lives as private venture
investors, full-time parents or volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may be hard for other folks to work up much sympathy
for them, people who cash out early can face some deeply unsettling
questions: What do they really want out of life? Who are they if
they don't have a business card and a new venture in the works?
Will they ever be able to match their past success? How much money
is ``enough'' in today's turbo-charged tech economy?
</P>
<P>
   ``People find themselves with a set of issues that no one told
them about,'' said Rick Eigenbrod, who opened the Silicon Valley
office of Right Management Consultants and who has counseled a
number of newly wealthy tech professionals. ``There's no set of
instruction booklets saying what it means to `live happily ever
after.' And it's the undiscussable: It's considered unseemly or
ungrateful to talk about the problems that come with success.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, newly minted tech millionaires amount to only
a minuscule fraction of the American population.
</P>
<P>
   But the ranks of the super-rich are growing: The number of
households worth $10 million or more rose from 190,000 in 1995 to
275,000 in 1998, according to New York University economist Edward
Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   And a fair number of such households _ at least in Silicon
Valley _ are headed by people well under 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people who are 24 or 25 years old and are now
millionaires,'' said one woman who works at Yahoo. ``People are
seeing the four-year mark come (when their options are fully
vested) and scratching their heads and saying, ``What next?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; How Much is Enough? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just how much is enough to retire in Silicon Valley these days?
</P>
<P>
   There's no simple answer. As people's income rises, so does
their spending. So while most Americans would be happy with a nest
egg of $100,000, many Silicon Valley professionals can't imagine
retiring without $6 million, $10 million or even $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 21, I probably thought that $1.5 million was enough
to walk away,'' said Gene Raphaelian, 40, who recently left the
Gartner Group with several million dollars but plans to continue
working until he can amass about $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I had kids and a mortgage in Saratoga,'' Raphaelian
continued. ``The consensus among my friends, who are people making
$150,000 to $200,000, is that you need $6 or $7 million free and
clear to be at a point where you can weather any economic
downturn.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Opting Out &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once they've reached their own personal ``magic number,'' some
young tech professionals do in fact retire from the five-day work
week.
</P>
<P>
   Deepak Puri was the 68th employee at Netscape. Last winter, his
final stock options vested and he dramatically changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   Puri, 41, now spends two and a half days each week with his
4-year-old daughter, a day and a half working as a consultant and a
day volunteering for groups like Juma Ventures, a San Francisco
nonprofit that helps low-income teens get work experience.
</P>
<P>
   Puri's friends urge him to join another startup. He gets raised
eyebrows when people ask him what he's doing and he answers,
``Taking it easy.'' But he doesn't regret his change.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends say, `This is the golden age to make money
on the Internet,''' Puri said. ``Eighty percent of them joined
other startups. But I use the analogy of a buffet: All this food is
out there, but at some point you have to say, `My stomach's full.'
You don't continue to nibble.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Back in the Fray
</P>
<P>
   Other high-tech millionaires leave one venture to start another,
part of a group known as ``serial entrepreneurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kirsch amassed about $30 million as CEO of Frame
Technology. But after selling the firm in 1995, he jumped back in
the fray as founder and CEO of Infoseek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still working like a dog because I enjoy it and I can make
a difference,'' Kirsch said. ``It's not the money. It's what you're
doing and whether you're contributing in a positive way. I never
made a calculation, `Can I retire?' I'd just get bored if I quit my
day job.''
</P>
<P>
   On a similar but less grand scale, Kurt Brown sold one small
software startup and quickly founded a new one called Eletter,
which uses the Internet to speed up mass mailings.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 38, didn't need more money. But he craved the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a roller coaster,'' Brown said. ``The first time
through you get sick and say, `What am I doing?' Then you get off,
a little woozy, and you need some time to let your lunch settle.
But then you just want to get back on the roller coaster again _ a
bigger one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger`` is a key point. Brown and his co-founder Manish Mehta
refused to consider new ventures that didn't have the potential to
be bigger by a ``factor of 10'' than their previous one.
</P>
<P>
   Some Silicon Valley veterans think that too much financial
success, too fast, has inflated people's egos and career
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the newly rich are not entrepreneurs, but engineers or
managers of average talents who lucked into the right company at
the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their sense of personal value is inflated,'' said Valerie
Frederickson, an outplacement consultant who works with many tech
firms. ``I've had job candidates say to me, `I'm ready to become a
CEO.' When I mention that to their former company, people at the
company are appalled _ they don't view the person at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Angels
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of tech millionaires stop daily work but become
angel investors _ private venture capitalists who provide seed
money to new companies in return for an ownership stake.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Clark, the serial entrepreneur behind Silicon Graphics,
Netscape Communications, Healtheon and most recently MyCFO, is
skeptical of the talents of many young tech retirees, especially
those who were employees rather than founders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't entrepreneurs or people who drove the business,''
said Clark, who himself is worth well over $500 million. ``They
just came along and had some luck. Now they seem to think of
themselves as angel investors, but they don't have the drive or
skill set to be a venture capitalist. They hope to get lucky, so
they put $50,000 or $100,000 into these little schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   At its worst, sudden wealth may end up undermining the drive and
creativity of part of a generation in the valley.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Clark recalls describing plans for a new business
to a group that included both wealthy former Netscape employees as
well as younger people without money.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``The ones who made $10 million were a little cocky, almost
blase, saying, `I'm not sure that is worth my time,''' Clark said.
``While the younger guys were enthusiastic, eager, ready to jump
in. It was a really interesting, stark contrast.''
</P>
<P>
   At its best, however, sudden wealth may liberate people to do
work that is more creative, risky or meaningful than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get lured to do something quite interesting because
they don't need to take a `safe' job,'' said John Wilson, an
executive recruiter with Korn Ferry International.
</P>
<P>
   New wealth sometimes can give more meaning and focus to a
longtime job.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, the money made me a better employee,'' said one
woman who amassed $6 million from stock options while at 3Com.
``Because every day, I was there by choice. You can't be a victim;
you're there because you want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In Greg Gianforte's case, he decided to start a new company
after he sold his old one to McAfee, which since has become Network
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   But this time he had the financial ability to write his own
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Gianforte moved to Montana, fulfilling a longtime dream he
shared with his wife. He no longer does much business travel, and
he's home with his kids by 5:30 or 6 p.m. And his focus now isn't
so much on making money as as on creating jobs _ both through his
own small firm, Right Now Technologies, and by helping bring
business to Bozeman.
</P>
<P>
   That, for him, is much closer to the good life than
seven-day-a-week fly-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are given certain skills, and if you don't use them
effectively, you are being irresponsible,'' Gianforte said. ``I
concluded that I know how to start and grow software companies. The
worthwhile thing I could do was create livelihoods for people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
