<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2347 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-AMERICAN-HNS &LR;      06-03 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-AMERICAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWER REPORTEDLY RELAYED UPDATED WEATHER CONDITIONS TO AMERICAN
AIRLINES CREW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ American Airlines Flight 1420 was radioed
frequent weather updates before it crashed on landing but was
unaware that an intense storm was approaching the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew would not have known there was a level six, (the most
powerful of rain storms) we know that now because we analyzed the
data. They would have known there was a thunderstorm or an intense
storm, but not necessarily a level six,'' said George Black Jr., a
member of the National Transportation Safety Board investigating
the aircraft's crash.
</P>
<P>
   The Super MD-80, carrying 145 people from Dallas attempted to
land at Little Rock National Airport late Tuesday. It shot past the
end of the runway in gusting winds and heavy rain, hit a light
standard and caught fire, killing eight passengers and the pilot
and injuring 83.
</P>
<P>
   Black declined to speculate whether the crew should have
attempted the landing in heavy weather. He said wind gusts up to 39
mph per hour were reported when the accident occurred, but that the
brunt of the intense storm did not hit the runway until five or six
minutes after the accident, when wind gusts reportedly reached 87
mph.
</P>
<P>
   Now little used by weather officials, the 1-6 scale of
categorizing thunderstorms referred to by Black was a general
designation of a storm's potential power and ability to generate
rain.
</P>
<P>
   The weather updates to the pilots came from the airport control
tower, sometimes as frequently as every 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole purpose of conveying this information, by all means,
is for the flight crew to make the decision on whether they want to
try to shoot the approach or not and that is purely their
discretion,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the flight crew makes that decision
based on the information that they get from the ground plus what
they see on their own radar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. Richard Buschmann, was an experienced flier
with American Airlines who served as a pilot chief, flying only
about two months of the year on regular routes to maintain
proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The flight, originating from Dallas/Fort Worth International
Airport, was delayed by more than two hours by inclement weather
and became the last commercial aircraft of the evening to approach
Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   The accident, the first fatal crash of a domestic flight in the
United States in 1 1/2 years, has raised questions about the
decision to land in intense weather and about the condition of the
flight crew, which had been on duty 13 1/2 hours, a half hour short
of the maximum a crew is expected to work in a day.
</P>
<P>
   James Burnett, a former NTSB chairman, said the crew was bound
to follow thunderstorm avoidance procedures, which stipulate
landing attempts should be avoided whenever a severe thunderstorm
is within three miles of the runway after the aircraft has
descended under 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know whether the three-mile guideline was violated or
not because we do not know yet how close the thunderstorm was at
the time the initial decision to land was made,'' said Burnett, a
Little Rock native.
</P>
<P>
   He said any attempts to land as a major storm moves into an
airport can be catastrophic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a pilot attempts to race a thunderstorm to the airport,
that's like attempting to race a locomotive to a crossing,'' he
said. ``You're fine if you beat it, but if you tie, you're in
trouble and in this case they tied.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have heard a portion of the radio traffic between
the flight crew and the tower taken from the cockpit voice recorder
and hope to interview Buschmann's co-pilot, Michael Origel, on
Friday. Origel, who suffered a broken leg, was questioned briefly
Wednesday, but he was still under medication.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Feith, NTSB accident investigator-in-charge at the scene,
said investigators also were trying to determine which pilot
attempted the landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now one of the first priorities of the (cockpit voice
recorder) group is to actually confirm who was flying the aircraft
and who was not flying, who was radioing communications. The
presumption right now is that it was the first officer doing the
two-way communications with the tower. At this point right now we
can't confirm that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But whoever was handling the radio traffic, he said, he was
receiving updates as frequently as every 20 seconds to 30 seconds
on changing wind direction and velocity.
</P>
<P>
   Black said the tower continued transmitting updates, even after
the accident, apparently unaware the aircraft had crashed.
</P>
<P>
   He said a doppler radar site located about seven miles northwest
of the airport showed the level six storm approaching the airport.
Though the radar site was not state-of-the-art, he said it
sufficiently diagrammed the storm. He said those diagrams will be
enhanced for further analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The thunderstorm was traveling from the northwest to the
southeast and remained away from the runway during the aircraft's
approach from the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The flight crew) was given a regular interval sequence of
weather updates namely winds and wind directions by the controller
and these were available to the crew to help in their
decisionmaking about their flight and their approach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What the crew did not know, however, was the storm's level of
intensity.
</P>
<P>
   During his 10-year tenure as NTSB board member and chairman,
Burnett said, guidelines were developed to offset the problems of
aircrafts taking off and landing in thunderstorms From 1970 to
1985, the NTSB was investigating wind shear incidents every year
involving pilots flying in thunderstorm conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the 1985 Delta accident, guidelines were developed on
wind shear avoidance because there were people in the aviation
industry who thought that if you flew in the southeastern United
States you had to take off and land into thunderstorms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Black said families and survivors will be allowed to return to
the crash site today to retrieve personal items and luggage. Crews
will begin removing the wreckage today to a storage area for
further analysis.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 investigators working in various groups in Washington
and Little Rock have begun the tedious process of documenting data
from the crash site and survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, investigators have determined that skid marks show the
aircraft landed about 2,000 feet from the approach end of the
7,200-foot runway, indicating a normal touchdown. Commercial
airplanes normally land about a third of the way down a runway.
</P>
<P>
   He said skid marks show the airplane drifted gradually to the
right and then turned to the left before running off the runway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
