<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2350 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS_SFC     06-03 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 WORKWAYS/ILANA DEBARE  &HT;     Hiring Is A Hairy Situation 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: Can a company reject someone for an executive-level position
because they have a beard and the company feels beards are ``not
appropriate for our image''?
<P>
   A: Let's assume you're talking about a neat and trim beard, not
the Charles Manson model. And let's assume the job in question
isn't CEO of a company that sells razors.
</P>
<P>
   Then this kind of hiring criterion falls in the ``legal but
dumb'' category of corporate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Why legal? Because companies have the right to hire whomever
they want for whatever reason they want, as long as they're not
discriminating on the basis of one of the categories protected by
civil rights law. Those categories include gender, race, religion,
national origin, age, disability, and in some states like
California, sexual orientation _ but they don't include appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time that a company couldn't require employees to be
clean-shaven would be if they had a beard for religious reasons or
because of a skin condition that prevented shaving,'' said Denise
DeRose, an employment lawyer with Crosby Heafey Roach &AMP; May in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Why is the policy you're describing dumb? If it's not obvious,
let me drop a few names.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle CEO Larry Ellison. Men's Wearhouse CEO George Zimmer.
Adobe Systems executives Chuck Geschke and John Warnock. Wells
Fargo Chief Financial Officer Rodney Jacobs. Former Symantec &UR;  &LR; CEO
Gordon Eubanks. National Semiconductor CEO Brian Halla. Some dude
named George Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   They all run world-class companies. They've all sported beards
during their executive tenure. And while their firms may have had
ups and downs, you'd be hard-pressed to find anyone who would
suggest it was because of their facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm a 54-year-old Denver resident and a wife, mother of five
children, and grandmother of eight. I'd like to find work doing
exactly what I have been doing over the years _ lifestyle
orchestration for a mature individual. This job would involve
managing his or her residences, directing the household staff, and
assisting in this person's social responsibilities. I have formerly
been an administrative assistant to a U.S. senator as well as a
flight attendant, tour director, model, Realtor and concierge. I
have been a wife/partner to two professional husbands who have
required business entertainment in our homes, so I know how to do
it. What is your suggestion on to connect with the appropriate
person? The type of person I hope to assist is not the type, I
believe, that would hire me from a classified ad.
</P>
<P>
   A: There are definitely people out there doing what you want to
do, which typically goes by the title of personal assistant,
household manager or personal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to find such folks in big financial centers like New
York and Los Angeles. Some cities have firms that place such
people, like Private Secretaries Agency Inc. in San Francisco. In
L.A., they've even organized themselves in a group called the
Association of Celebrity Personal Assistants at (310) 322-4495.
</P>
<P>
   There's an institute in your own backyard that trains and places
household managers all over the country _ the Starkey International
Institute in Denver. Starkey offers two-month courses for $6,300
that cover topics like how to behave in a wealthy household and how
to set boundaries between yourself and your client. It then helps
its grads find jobs, which typically pay $35,000 to $50,000 plus
housing.
</P>
<P>
   With your extensive experience you may feel like you don't need
to spend that much money on formal training. But you wouldn't
necessarily feel out of place in their program: More than 80
percent of its students have college degrees, and their average age
is 44.
</P>
<P>
   Can't stomach the idea of returning to school for something
you've been doing for the past 20 years? It couldn't hurt to place
ads in small neighborhood newspapers that cater to well-heeled
communities.
</P>
<P>
   But basically, you'll need to network, network and network. Get
to know local corporate leaders through your Chamber of Commerce.
Meet the top human resource folks at big local companies: Their
executives may be looking for someone like you.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like you already know a fair number of wealthy people.
Ask all of them if they know someone who could use your services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I'd phrase it is that you're about to enter a new
phase in your life,'' said Oakland career counselor Marty Nemko.
``Tell them you've been the (famed Washington hostess) Perle (CQ) &LR; 
 &LR; Mesta of your own domicile and it seems a shame to toss out 30
years of experience. Tell them you're looking to offer your talents
to someone else who needs a director of operations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
