<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GTE-GTE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Judge Nixes GTE's Plan to Grab 4 Parking Spots at SFO 
 &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In a case that pits for-profit utilities against local governments,
a Superior Court judge has shot down GTE Wireless' attempt to take
control of four parking spots at the San Francisco International
Airport.
<P>
   In a ruling yesterday, San Mateo County Superior Court Judge
Phrasel Shelton rejected GTE's claim that it could assume control
of the parking spots under a 1930s state law.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling could have a wide-ranging effect because it may
prevent other wireless carriers from annexing public property for
private use.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco City Attorney Louise Renne called the ruling a
``crucial decision'' for local governments.
</P>
<P>
   The cellular phone company wanted the parking spots _ which are
public property _ to house equipment that GTE needs to offer
wireless phone service near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   GTE argued it could take the spots using a 1930s state law,
which gave utilities, including phone companies, the ``power of
eminent domain.'' That power allowed utilities to assume control of
public or private land in order to lay infrastructure needed for
telephone or electric service.
</P>
<P>
   But San Francisco argued that the law was never intended to be
used by competitive wireless carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the law was written at a time when there was just one
phone company, which was highly regulated, and getting telephone
service to people was viewed as a public necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eminent domain statute was intended to allow the old Ma
Bell to provide a public service, not to allow a potentially
unlimited number of companies to take whatever public property they
think they need in order to compete with each other,'' said Deputy
City Attorney Andrew Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   While the judge's ruling doesn't set a legal precedent for any
company other than GTE, Schwartz said other carriers may be less
likely to try to use eminent domain given yesterday's order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's victory here is not going to go unnoticed in the
industry,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   GTE officials said they were disappointed with the ruling and
said the company might appeal the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had a very well-established eminent domain law that
we applied to this,'' said Annette Jacobs, GTE area president of
California. ``There were several facts that the city presented that
we dispute and we are going to consider all the options that are
available to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said the ruling will not disrupt the carrier's wireless
service at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
