<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENENTECH-GENENTECH_S     06-03 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-GENENTECH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Roche Swallows Genentech  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Relief and hope were in the air at Genentech Inc. yesterday as
employees mulled the news that their biotech firm will be acquired
then partially spun off by the Swiss pharmaceutical giant Roche.
<P>
   Roche, which already owns two-thirds of Genentech, said late
Wednesday that it would exercise its option under a 1995 agreement
to buy the rest of Genentech for $4 below Wednesday's closing price
of $86.50 a share, or about $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 Genentech employees crowded into a warehouse at the
company's South San Francisco headquarters yesterday as chief
executive Art Levinson explained Roche's promise to resell up to 19
percent of Genentech in an IPO _ letting the biotech firm keep its
name, some independence and its stock option incentive plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have been subsumed, but now we can all rest much
easier,'' Levinson said, promising no layoffs or management
changes. ``We are going to chart our own course for future
success.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Joining Levinson on a stage festooned with balloons was Herb
Boyer, the silver-haired scientist who launched the entire biotech
industry when he co-founded Genentech in 1976. The warehouse
cheered when Boyer, who has been on Genentech's board for 23 years,
said Roche had asked him to serve on the new, six-person board that
will run Genentech after the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Boyer alluded to the tough negotiations that led up to the
current plan, which lies somewhere between what Genentech had
wanted _ which was for Roche to let its option lapse and do nothing
_ and a full acquisition as a Roche subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our board pounded into their heads how valuable it would be to
maintain the independence of Genentech,'' Boyer said, adding, ``I
will try to maintain the culture of Genentech, of which I am so
proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Levinson said he could understand if outside observers took a
wait-and-see attitude about how much independence Genentech really
would maintain once Roche completes its acquisition and replaces
the current board with new directors. Roche has named two
representatives to the new board. Levin and Boyer hold two other
seats, with two yet to be filled.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said this quasi-independent status is the best that
Genentech could have hoped for given the two agreements, negotiated
in 1990 and 1995, that gave Roche until June 30, 1999, to buy
Genentech at a set price no higher than $82.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the other end of the spectrum, you had the very possible
scenario of Roche buying the rest of Genentech and assimilating
them,'' said Joel Sendek, with Gerard Klauer Mattison in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Meirav Chovav, with Salomon Smith Barney in New York, said Roche
and Genentech both win something from the compromise. Roche gets
Genentech at a below-market price, with the option of making a
profit on the sale of IPO shares. And Genentech presumably keeps
enough identity and control to keep its top talent from walking to
startups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roche gets to eat its cake and have it, too,'' Chovav said.
``And the likelihood is if they manage it the right way, Genentech
will generally remain intact.''
</P>
<P>
   The big losers, Chovav said, clearly are the current
shareholders, who had bid Genentech shares above the $82.50 call
price on the bet that Roche would let the June 30 deadline lapse
without exercising its below-market option. Chovav said in addition
to losing the $4 per share, institutional investors would get stung
with huge capital-gains taxes because many had held Genentech
shares for years and bought the company in the $30s or $40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Current holders are not happy,'' Chovav said. ``The first
several clients I spoke with in the morning were angry. By
afternoon, they were more resigned to their fate.''
</P>
<P>
   The fates of Roche and Genentech have been intertwined since
February 1990, when the Swiss pharmaceutical-maker bought a 60
percent stake in the biotech firm for $2.1 billion. At the time,
Genentech shares hovered under $30. During the years, Roche
gradually increased its stake and negotiated a larger say in
Genentech's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Genentech ousted former chief executive Kirk Raab and
replaced him with Levinson, after Raab asked Roche to guarantee a
$2 million personal loan. Under Levinson's leadership, Genentech
steadily has increased its products and revenues. Levinson won
approvals for key cancer-fighting drugs and doubled the company's
share price, which was in the $40 range when he took over.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Genentech's strong performance gave it extra
bargaining clout. Levinson said the deal was ironed out in
transatlantic phone calls in the 36 hours leading up to the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Roland Haefeli, a Roche spokesman, said one of the reasons his
firm will put 19 percent of Genentech on the stock market is so
Genentech employees can keep the stock options that they've come to
expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think their culture is driving their success, and an
integral part of that is their incentive program,'' Haefeli said.
</P>
<P>
   Roche and Genentech said it was only a coincidence that their
deal was announced just hours after a San Francisco federal jury
deadlocked on a patent trial against the biotech giant brought by
the University of California. UC had sought as much as $1.2 billion
in damages, alleging that Genentech infringed on a UC patent for
human growth hormone.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Charles Engelberg, with AmeriCal Securities in San
Francisco, thinks Roche deliberately waited until after Genentech
had won this round in the case. He noted that the U.S. Justice
Department recently fined Roche $500 million _ a record punitive
damage _ for price-fixing in the vitamin market, and European
regulators have opened their own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would Roche buy a potential $1.2 billion liability?''
Engelberg asked.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts could only speculate on the possible price of a
Genentech IPO. A $100-per-share figure has been kicked around, but
Chovav, at Smith Barney, observes that a price that high would only
permit Roche to issue some 13 million shares _ too small a float to
interest institutional investors who like to see 30 million shares
of an issue so they can move in and out of a stock without causing
ripples.
</P>
<P>
   At Genentech headquarters, some employees expressed a
willingness to roll their current options over to the new IPO. Paul
Boles, James Owens and Martin Gaffney, maintenance men on
Genentech's drug assembly line, sipped champagne after Levinson's
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to let it roll,'' Boles said, adding, ``I believe in
Art (Levinson).''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
