<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO RENEW CHINA'S `MOST FAVORED' TRADE STATUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton notified Congress on Thursday
that he intends to renew China's ``most favored nation'' trade
status, despite suspicions that China stole top-secret nuclear
weapons data and satellite information from U.S. research
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to congressional leaders, Clinton sought to separate
economic and trade issues from the continuing debate on Capitol
Hill over Beijing's human rights abuses and a congressional report
released last week accusing China of pilfering information that can
be used to enhance its missile and weapons development programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that keeping the trade relationship strong would
not only help promote the economic well-being of both nation's
peoples, but also would make it easier for the United States to
register its strong objections and concerns about the other issues
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pursue engagement with our eyes wide open, without
illusions,'' Clinton said. ``A policy of disengagement and
confrontation would only strengthen those in China who oppose
greater openness and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that trade would ``remain a force for social change
in China'' and could lead to the creation of a democratic
government there over time.
</P>
<P>
   The president's letter was sent to congressional leaders on the
eve of the 10th anniversary of the violent Tiananmen Square
crackdown on student protesters by the Chinese military. Clinton
referred to the demonstration as a courageous show of determination
by the Chinese people to change their government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to speak and work strongly for human rights in
China. A continued policy of principled, purposeful engagement
reinforces these efforts to move China toward greater openness and
broader freedom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will have 90 days to consider Clinton's recommendation
that China's MFN status be renewed for another year before it takes
effect automatically. But lawmakers are expected _ after an intense
debate that's expected to be more angry and contentious than in
past years _ to go along with the annual renewal, which last year
accounted for $14.3 billion in U.S. exports to China and nearly $72
billion in imports from the Asian giant.
</P>
<P>
   The special trade status would continue to give China the same
kind of low-tariff access to American markets that most countries
already have. The MFN designation must be renewed each year by law,
however, because China is not governed by freely elected leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans and Democrats are expected to raise serious
objections to renewing MFN, but congressional leaders in both
parties plan to support Clinton's call for another one-year
extension, including Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., one of the
authors of the report essentially charging China with stealing U.S.
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Cox and other Republicans believe that to deny China the normal
trade status held by nearly every other country with the United
States will further strain relations already hurt by charges of
spying and the accidental bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Yugoslavia by NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we treat China like an enemy she surely will become one,''
Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., told Reuters News Service. ``There are
a number of my colleagues who realize what a mistake that would
be.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Dreier said, ``that doesn't mean we shouldn't be as
vigilant as we could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will have the support of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
Republican presidential front-runner, who came out Thursday in
favor of renewing China's MFN status. Bush spokesman David Beckwith
said the governor agrees with Clinton that the United States must
work constructively with China by expanding trade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
