<SLUG> BC-NETSTOCKS-NETSTOCKS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Rate Jitters Keep Slamming Net Stocks  &HT;     By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The threat of higher interest rates has taken a huge toll on
Internet stocks, which continued their slide yesterday. Many,
including Amazon.com and Yahoo, are trading at half their recent
highs.
<P>
   The Dow Jones Internet index has fallen by one-third since April
13, as air continued to leak from the online balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Growth stocks have always been especially sensitive to interest
rate fluctuations, because they trade at high multiples to
earnings. If higher rates hurt corporate earnings, these stocks
have farther to fall than low-P/E stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks, being the most growth-oriented of all, have
been especially hard hit by rate jitters. The recent drops may
deepen if today's unemployment report nudges the Federal Reserve to
raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stock charts ``are beginning to look like the
Washington Monument _ thin triangles,'' said David Simons, managing
director at Digital Video Investments, a New York research company.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Jim Marks, an Internet analyst at Deutsche Bank in New York,
said Internet stocks were suffering from oversupply of shares as
more companies went public, seeking to take advantage of Wall
Street's euphoria about the sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're nearing a point of some saturation,'' said Internet
analyst Jill Frankle, of International Data Corp. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Some Net companies are postponing their IPOs until the market
settles down and some recent new issues regain their footing.
</P>
<P>
   Companies including TheStreet.com, a financial news service in
New York, and Santa Monica's EToys Inc., an online retailer, have
fallen at least a third from their first day of trading last month.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, high-tech experts had said it would be a
catastrophic event _ such as a huge market drop, a jump in interest
rates or a financial collapse in Japan _ to temper the wide-scale
Internet stock shopping spree.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Internet stocks have been falling since mid-April,
there was no single event that sparked the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all greed going up and all fear coming down,'' said
William H. Davidow, a partner at Mohr Davidow Ventures in Menlo
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Simons called the mad dash to invest in online stocks a
``perfect blend of video arcade and gambling casino, but where few
lose.'' Until recently, in fact, everyone seemed to be making a
killing in the cyber Gold Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Motro, chief executive of Web portal Infoseek, is taking
the long view. ``It's a volatile sector. It goes up and down and
will probably go back up again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not for the weak of heart. But it's premature to say
the game is over. The market is sorting through a number of new
online IPOs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
