<HEADER>
A2359 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-TIMELINE-TEX     06-03 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-TIMELINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM WEATHER WOES TO A DESCENT INTO TERROR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN and BETSY BLANEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least four hours before the crash of Flight 1420, the leg to
Little Rock wasn't going as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The American Airlines plane that skidded off the runway late
Tuesday night wasn't supposed to be headed to Arkansas. Plane
``N215AA,'' now crumpled beside the Arkansas River, was pressed
into duty after mechanical problems surfaced on another MD-80
aircraft, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The substitution was routine, but it followed a bad-weather
delay that had already set back air travel out of North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday flight from Dallas/Fort Worth Airport to Little
Rock, Ark., was scheduled to depart at 8:28 p.m. A full plane, with
139 passengers and six crew members, didn't leave until 10:40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't worry a lot about it,'' said Wayne McDaniel, who was
returning from a family reunion in New Mexico and had sat through a
two-hour delay in Albuquerque. ``I just went outside and smoked
cigarettes and drank a good cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been through that before.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon, he and dozens of others would be in unfamiliar and
frightening territory. They would be scrambling through cracks in
the fuselage of the wrecked aircraft, ducking to avoid fire and
smoke, and tramping through a violent thunderstorm, battered by
gale-force winds, heavy rain and hail.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers said they had no inkling of the terror to come. They
recall that the pilot, about 25 minutes before Little Rock, turned
off the seat belt sign but warned that some turbulence might be
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the plane was buffeted by the storm and the
seat belt sign was on again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit it a little sooner than expected,'' the pilot said on
the public address system, according to McDaniel.
</P>
<P>
   The storm had been forming for many hours, and meteorologists
had been tracking it most of the day. George Wilken of the National
Weather Service in Little Rock said a ``typical squall line,''
common in Arkansas during May and June, was spawning thunderstorms
just ahead of a cold front that stretched from Missouri through
Arkansas and into Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The same line probably produced the storms that delayed the D/FW
departure of Flight 1420, he said. But the Little Rock storm was
created by a separate cell along that line, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 9:30 p.m., the weather service issued a severe
thunderstorm watch for the area around Little Rock, and a local TV
weatherman began warning about the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The storm line was moving from the northwest toward the
southeast and gaining momentum, Wilken said. At 10:15, a 60-mph
wind gust hit Hot Springs, 45 miles southwest of Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:18, Wilken said, the service issued a severe thunderstorm
warning for Pulaski County, which includes Little Rock. The warning
indicated that residents could expect hail up to 3/4-inch in
diameter and wind gusts of at least 58 mph.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines prohibits its MD-80 pilots from landing when
cross-winds top 30 knots, or about 35 mph.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, wind conditions at the Little Rock airport were
mild, Wilken said, but the storm was moving toward it and
intensifying.
</P>
<P>
   About 11:30, wind gusts hit 65 mph at the NWS office 7 miles
northwest of the airport, Wilken said. By 11:45, spotters near the
airport area clocked 75-mph winds.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1420 was approaching its destination, and the crew and
passengers appeared to be aware of the growing storm.
</P>
<P>
   Paul MacIntosh, traveling on business from Glendale, Ariz., said
the plane began flying through heavy rain about five minutes
outside of the airport. A few moments later, the rain became
stronger and the drops larger, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the lightning picked up, illuminating the standing water on
the soggy ground and giving the area a surreal look.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite an electrical show,'' MacIntosh said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots were in constant discussions with air traffic
controllers, assessing the weather conditions, crash investigators
said yesterday. As the plane approached the runway, it was headed
from the north. But the pilots decided to take another tack,
passing the airport and returning in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane began landing at 11:50, wind speeds at the
airport were about 34 mph, near the permitted limit, Wilken said.
The surging wind drove the rain even harder, producing about .30 of
an inch of rain in a minute, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the aircraft was approaching from the south, the storms
were approaching at the same time from the northwest,'' Wilken
said. ``They collided at about the worst moment.''
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel is a truck driver, and he said he knows the
destabilizing effects of wind and water. As soon as the plane
touched down, he thought it was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was out of control,'' he said, adding that he ducked his
head in preparation for a crash.
</P>
<P>
   MacIntosh said the plane bounced and then turned nearly 180
degrees as it slid across the ground and crashed into light banks
used for the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hear the wheels scraping on the ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Klamm, who was sitting in first class with his son,
Jason, said he was just hoping the plane would stop sliding.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I put my head down and just held on for life,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane hit the light banks, the pilot was killed, the
co-pilot broke his leg, and part of the fuselage was sheared off
behind the cockpit. The plane broke into several pieces, and fire
and thick smoke began to build.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the craft, the storm was surging, and survivors who
climbed from the wreckage were pelted by hail and rain.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes after the crash, wind gusts hit 87 mph at the
airport, the peak recorded during the storm, Wilken said.
</P>
<P>
   MacIntosh climbed out of a hole near the front of the plane and
darted for the marshy ground. He was hospitalized for a deep gash
in his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was getting out of that plane because I was thinking there'd
be an explosion,'' he said. ``I made a dash for the swamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Klamm said he was briefly knocked unconscious, and had to be
roused and led from the plane by his son.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel was smashed in the right shoulder, breaking the bone,
and had to wiggle free from an object that was pinning him to his
seat. As the lightning continued, it illuminated a crack in the
fuselage a few rows away, and he moved in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   He and several people squeezed through the opening and dropped
to the ground. They huddled near bales of hay, seeking shelter from
the pelting hail and rain.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the shock settled in: ``I started getting the shakes
real bad,'' McDaniel said.
</P>
<P>
   A nearby passenger used his cell phone to call 911, and McDaniel
described their location. It is his voice, he said, that is on the
911 tapes being played on newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few minutes, the rescue mission was under way.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 ambulances arrived on the scene, along with 85
rescue and medical workers. They marked the injured with colored
tags, and in 90 minutes had transported more than 80 people to six
area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel said he didn't stay at the hospital long.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't let me smoke there,'' he said, ``and I needed a
smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Yvette Craig and Renee C. Lee contributed to this
report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
