<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2360 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-TEX     06-03 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF DOPPLER RADAR LIMITED WEATHER INFORMATION BEFORE CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ The pilots of doomed American Airlines
Flight 1420 had been alerted to wind shears but had no way of
knowing the severity of the thunderstorm pounding National Airport
with high winds, blinding rain and hail, a federal investigator
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Without the state-of-the-art Terminal Doppler Weather Radar that
is installed at major airports, not even the air traffic
controllers guiding the pilots knew that the thunderstorm packed
the severe rating of Level 6, said George W. Black Jr., the
National Transportation Safety Board member in charge of the crash
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew could not have known it was a Level 6 storm,'' Black
said. ``We only know that from our analysis of the Doppler weather
radar data after the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather is suspected as a primary factor in Tuesday night's
fiery crash, which killed the captain and eight passengers on the
McDonnell Douglas Super 80 jetliner. At least 82 others were
injured, some critically, but 136 people survived.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, which had aborted one landing to make its ill-fated
approach from the opposite direction, slid off the runway, hit a
large steel stanchion supporting runway lights, broke apart and
burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Black said the pilots had been given regular updates on the
deteriorating weather conditions, consisting primarily of wind
speed and direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was changing rapidly,'' Black said. ``There's even
indications the tower controller was providing sort of a
play-by-play wind direction and velocity sequence of radio
transmissions during the approach.''
</P>
<P>
   NTSB chief investigator Greg Feith described the stormy
conditions as .MDSD/.MDNM/''a very dynamic situation with wind
conditions changing every 20 to 30 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Feith and Black emphasized, however, that the plane's captain,
not the controllers, decided whether to land or divert to another
airport.
</P>
<P>
   The controllers initially cleared the aircraft to land from the
north on Runway 22-Left. Informed of the shifting wind, the pilots
then requested permission to land on the same runway, but from the
south.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft touched down about 2,000 feet down the 7,200-foot
runway but then veered off the concrete, went over an embankment at
the end of the runway, hit a steel support for runway lights and
broke in two, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they have not determined how fast the plane
was going when it touched down, whether it was blown off the runway
by a strong wind gust or whether the tires hydroplaned on the wet
pavement, causing the plane to go out of control, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed at 11:51 p.m., when airport winds were clocked
as high as 35 mph. Within five minutes, the NTSB said, a gust of
more than 80 mph was recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Burnett, a former NTSB chairman, said the pilots had enough
information about the tumultuous storm that they never should have
tried to land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to race a thunderstorm to the airport is like trying to
race a locomotive to the railroad crossing,'' said Burnett, who
served as NTSB chairman from 1982 to 1988. He is now a lawyer and
transportation safety consultant in Clinton, Ark. ``Even if you
tie, you're in bad shape. And this airplane tied.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Baker, American's executive vice president of operations,
cautioned against speculation blaming the pilot for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, he said, must learn ``exactly what the facts are
regarding the wind velocity and direction ... exactly when that
airplane was making the approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to want to try to figure out exactly what the
(cockpit) crew knew. What did the tower tell them? What did the en
route (air traffic control) center tell them? Did the crew have the
information to make an intelligent decision? And then what were the
actual wind conditions?''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett said pilot fatigue could have figured in the decision to
land rather than divert to another airport.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Richard Buschmann, the pilot who was killed, and Michael
Origel,the co-pilot who survived with a broken leg, had been on
duty 13 hours, 20 minutes at the time of the crash. The limit for
American pilots is 14 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked longer than 14 hours yesterday, but nothing I did
affected the lives and safety of anyone,'' Burnett said. ``With
pilots, the last thing they do at the end of a 14-hour shift is
land an airplane, which is the most difficult part of any flight.
They were called upon to make value judgments as well as to use
their flying skills to bring that airplane down safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 14 hours is just too long for pilots to work.
Eventually something will go wrong, like it did here.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett also said the accident might have been averted if the
airport had the Federal Aviation Administration's Terminal Doppler
Weather Radar, which could have given controllers better
information about the position and intensity of the thunderstorm
approaching the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated radar system has been installed at such major
U.S. airports as Dallas/Fort Worth, Dallas' Love Field and
Houston's George Bush Intercontinental, but smaller airports such
as Little Rock's were not budgeted to get the multimillion-dollar
system.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett, who left the NTSB in 1991 while the Terminal Doppler
Weather Radar program was being developed, said he was pressured by
the federal Office of Management and Budget ``not to advocate a lot
of these radar systems'' because of their cost.
</P>
<P>
   The Doppler radar was developed in direct response to the deadly
1985 crash of Delta Air Lines Flight 191 at D/FW Airport, which was
attributed to a microburst of wind from a thunderstorm over the
airport as the Lockheed L-1011 tried to land.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House Committee on
Transportation and Infrastructure, questioned why the Little Rock
airport does not have the Terminal Doppler Weather Radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike the system at Little Rock now, this radar could warn
the pilot in advance that dangerous winds were developing,'' he
said. ``There is no reason that airports like Little Rock should be
lacking the latest in weather prediction technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Rock has a regional Doppler weather radar facility about
seven miles northeast of the airport, but it does not provide the
detailed information about wind shear and microbursts _ highly
localized, high-speed downward blasts of wind _ that an airport
Doppler system is designed to detect, NTSB officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The airport does have a less-sophisticated, low-level wind-shear
alert system with sensors that measure wind speed and direction. A
computer links the sensors and compares their information to give
controllers information about wind shear _ rapid changes in wind
speed and direction that can be deadly to a low-flying aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   That system alerted controllers to wind shear as Flight 1420
approached the airport, and that information was relayed to the
pilots, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   ( Staff Writer Maria Recio contributed to this report, which
contains material from The Associated Press. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2361 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-PILOT-TEX     06-03 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-PILOT-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM FUQUAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year, U.S. airlines are expected to fill more than 14,000
cockpit seats with new pilots, and one is Michael Origel, the first
officer aboard Flight 1420, which crashed Tuesday night in Little
Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Origel and his peers are hardly fledglings, having already spent
hundreds if not thousands of hours steering tons of aluminum
through the sky. They train in multimillion-dollar flight
simulators, use weather data that didn't exist a decade earlier,
and rely on cockpit technology incorporating the best of today's
computer wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   But their prospective employers also look for something else: Do
they make good decisions?
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash of Flight 1420, which occurred in nasty
weather, remains unknown. But in addition to weather, investigators
are examining many factors, including decisions made by the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines did not return phone calls on thursday seeking
comment on pilot training, and other airlines, along with flight
simulation companies, also declined to comment, citing the Arkansas
crash.
</P>
<P>
   But two pilot training experts say that during the past 20 years
the industry has invested as much on improving pilot judgment and
behavior as it has on improving technology. The issue is
particularly important today, as airlines hire record numbers of
new pilots to replace retirees and staff growing fleets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines interview the most qualified pilots, but they hire
the people they like, who do a good job solving problems,'' said
Kit Darby, a United Air Lines pilot and a principal at Aviation
Information Resources in Atlanta. AIR, as the company is known,
advises military and private pilots who want to work for the
nation's largest airlines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 U.S. carriers hired 14,123 pilots, a record for the
fourth consecutive year, and are expected to top that in 1999,
Darby said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 years, those airlines have adopted pilot training
systems that increase collaboration between crew members, the air
traffic control system and any other source of information that
could help pilots make good decisions. The systems go by names such
as human factors and crew resource management.
</P>
<P>
   An example is line-oriented flight training, or LOFT. Using a
flight simulator, a flight crew must deal with equipment failures,
unexpected weather and other crises.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose is to teach the entire crew, including flight
attendants, ``to hone those skills they have been taught dealing
with judgment and decision-making,'' said Tim Forte, flight safety
officer for Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Daytona Beach,
Fla. The school bills itself as the world's largest aviation
training institution, with about 12,000 students worldwide, about
half of them pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The captain who once flew solo through emergencies, relying on
technical skills, is an outdated concept, Forte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a wealth of information out there,'' he said, and the
plane's captain _ who still has the responsibility of the final
decision about what to do _ is expected to use all the resources at
hand to achieve the best result.
</P>
<P>
   Said Darby: ``The fighter pilot, the lone individual that
doesn't work so well when all these other people and resources are
available,'' isn't an airline's first choice.
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, some of his clients complain that they were passed
over for someone with lesser technical skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It mystifies pilots who spend years getting their tickets
punched along the way, getting experience that gets them in the
door,'' Darby said. ``But those things don't get them selected _
and they shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Darby and Forte suggested that the ultimate example of
cooperative crew work is the 1989 crash-landing of a crippled DC-10
in Iowa. With one of three engines out and the plane's hydraulic
controls disabled, a fourth pilot _ who was a passenger on the
flight _ jumped in to help maneuver the plane using the plane's two
remaining engines. The crew also used information from the plane's
builder and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot was receptive, and that saved many lives,'' Darby
said.
</P>
<P>
   That assumes there is time to explore options, Darby said. And
usually there is, he and Forte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's usually a chain of events that lead to an accident,''
Darby said. ``Crew resource management gives you many opportunities
to break that chain.''
</P>
<P>
   An example of the failure to break the chain of error is the
1995 crash of an American Airlines jet near Cali, Colombia. That
accident, which killed 159 of the 163 people aboard, was traced to
a discrepancy between the crew's navigational charts and the
plane's autopilot system that distracted the crew as the plane flew
too low in a mountainous region.
</P>
<P>
   In response, American altered its training to blend the teamwork
approach with renewed emphasis on pilots actively controlling their
aircraft, rather than relying too much on cockpit automation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the federal government also required that pilots be
trained in recovering from unusual events, such as a buildup of ice
on the wings.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
