A2362 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODGUYS-GOODGUYS_SFC     06-03 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODGUYS-GOOD </SLUG>
 GUYS _ SF CHRON  
 Good Guys' Founder Back To Rescue Firm  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The Good Guys is bringing back its founder, Ron Unkefer, in a bid
to reverse its flagging fortunes.
<P>
   Battling competition from Best Buy and Circuit City,
Brisbane-based Good Guys has posted three years of losses amid
stagnant sales in its consumer electronics stores. Shares dropped
to a low of $3 last month, but shot up $1.38 on yesterday's news to
close at $5.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is arguably one of the best moves the board could have
made,'' said David Childe of Morgan Keegan, one of the few
securities analysts who still follows the company.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced, though. ``I'm not betting on him, but
I'm not betting against him,'' said Douglas Gordon, an analyst with
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. ``He's got a big job ahead of
him and there are a number of things that are outside of his
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer founded Good Guys in 1973 as a store in the Marina
District and ran the company for 20 years, taking it public in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   He ceded the chief executive position in 1993 to Bob Gunst, who
has announced his resignation and is now handing the title back to
Unkefer. In 1996 Unkefer resigned the chairman's post, which Gunst
never held. Unkefer will resume the chairmanship upon his return
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a search under way and we had some good candidates, but
Ron very aggressively wanted to come back,'' said Good Guys board
member Howard Lester, who is also chairman of Williams-Sonoma Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the judgment was that there was a big benefit in
bringing in someone who knew the company, who knew the vendor
community and could hit the ground running, versus someone who was
unproven for us,'' Lester said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This turnaround will be the biggest business challenge I've
ever had,'' said Unkefer. ``I didn't want the company to drift for
another couple or three years and wind up in Chapter 11. I also saw
a great business opportunity'' because the stock price is so low.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with his return, Unkefer bought 10 percent of
Good Guys' shares outstanding, or 1.45 million shares, for $4.7
million, and acquired warrants to buy 1.43 million more shares over
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer returns to a competitive consumer electronics
environment dominated by two low-cost national retailers, Circuit
City and Best Buy.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting Best Buy, which is opening stores aggressively on the
West Coast, is one of Good Guys' biggest challenges, said Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   But Childe said there is plenty of room for a more upscale
player like Good Guys. A turnaround ``requires a different
merchandising vision, not a Herculean effort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Good Guys' heyday in the late '80s, it had ``the highest
operating margins, the highest sales per square foot and the
highest return on assets in consumer electronics sector,'' said
Childe. ``It was competitive then, there were just different
players. So there's no reason why Good Guys can't get to those kind
of levels again, in my opinion.``
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer expects to move back to the Bay Area from Dallas, where
he is chairman of First Broadcasting, a company he founded to
develop and resell radio stations. In the early- and mid-1990s, he
owned KYA and KSFO in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years he has funded and run First Ventures, a
venture capital firm that invests in early-stage Silicon Valley
startups.
</P>
<P>
