<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2366 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-PILOT-TEX     06-03 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-PILOT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES EXPECTED TO HIRE MORE THAN 14,000 NEW PILOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (Resending to include summary line) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JIM FUQUAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year, U.S. airlines are expected to fill more than 14,000
cockpit seats with new pilots, and one is Michael Origel, the first
officer aboard Flight 1420, which crashed Tuesday night in Little
Rock, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Origel and his peers are hardly fledglings, having already spent
hundreds if not thousands of hours steering tons of aluminum
through the sky. They train in multimillion-dollar flight
simulators, use weather data that didn't exist a decade earlier,
and rely on cockpit technology incorporating the best of today's
computer wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   But their prospective employers also look for something else: Do
they make good decisions?
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash of Flight 1420, which occurred in nasty
weather, remains unknown. But in addition to weather, investigators
are examining many factors, including decisions made by the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines did not return phone calls on thursday seeking
comment on pilot training, and other airlines, along with flight
simulation companies, also declined to comment, citing the Arkansas
crash.
</P>
<P>
   But two pilot training experts say that during the past 20 years
the industry has invested as much on improving pilot judgment and
behavior as it has on improving technology. The issue is
particularly important today, as airlines hire record numbers of
new pilots to replace retirees and staff growing fleets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines interview the most qualified pilots, but they hire
the people they like, who do a good job solving problems,'' said
Kit Darby, a United Air Lines pilot and a principal at Aviation
Information Resources in Atlanta. AIR, as the company is known,
advises military and private pilots who want to work for the
nation's largest airlines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 U.S. carriers hired 14,123 pilots, a record for the
fourth consecutive year, and are expected to top that in 1999,
Darby said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 years, those airlines have adopted pilot training
systems that increase collaboration between crew members, the air
traffic control system and any other source of information that
could help pilots make good decisions. The systems go by names such
as human factors and crew resource management.
</P>
<P>
   An example is line-oriented flight training, or LOFT. Using a
flight simulator, a flight crew must deal with equipment failures,
unexpected weather and other crises.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose is to teach the entire crew, including flight
attendants, ``to hone those skills they have been taught dealing
with judgment and decision-making,'' said Tim Forte, flight safety
officer for Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Daytona Beach,
Fla. The school bills itself as the world's largest aviation
training institution, with about 12,000 students worldwide, about
half of them pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The captain who once flew solo through emergencies, relying on
technical skills, is an outdated concept, Forte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a wealth of information out there,'' he said, and the
plane's captain _ who still has the responsibility of the final
decision about what to do _ is expected to use all the resources at
hand to achieve the best result.
</P>
<P>
   Said Darby: ``The fighter pilot, the lone individual that
doesn't work so well when all these other people and resources are
available,'' isn't an airline's first choice.
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, some of his clients complain that they were passed
over for someone with lesser technical skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It mystifies pilots who spend years getting their tickets
punched along the way, getting experience that gets them in the
door,'' Darby said. ``But those things don't get them selected _
and they shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Darby and Forte suggested that the ultimate example of
cooperative crew work is the 1989 crash-landing of a crippled DC-10
in Iowa. With one of three engines out and the plane's hydraulic
controls disabled, a fourth pilot _ who was a passenger on the
flight _ jumped in to help maneuver the plane using the plane's two
remaining engines. The crew also used information from the plane's
builder and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot was receptive, and that saved many lives,'' Darby
said.
</P>
<P>
   That assumes there is time to explore options, Darby said. And
usually there is, he and Forte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's usually a chain of events that lead to an accident,''
Darby said. ``Crew resource management gives you many opportunities
to break that chain.''
</P>
<P>
   An example of the failure to break the chain of error is the
1995 crash of an American Airlines jet near Cali, Colombia. That
accident, which killed 159 of the 163 people aboard, was traced to
a discrepancy between the crew's navigational charts and the
plane's autopilot system that distracted the crew as the plane flew
too low in a mountainous region.
</P>
<P>
   In response, American altered its training to blend the teamwork
approach with renewed emphasis on pilots actively controlling their
aircraft, rather than relying too much on cockpit automation.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the federal government also required that pilots be
trained in recovering from unusual events, such as a buildup of ice
on the wings.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
