<HEADLINE>
WEARY AND WARY, THE SERBS ARE SKEPTICAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ It was hard to find anyone in Belgrade
Thursday who expressed support for President Slobodan Milosevic,
but with the news of a peace deal, the recriminations came
unusually swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Ivica Tasic, 33, a bookseller on the main shopping street, asked
the most common question: ``Who will ask him why so many people had
to die and all of us have had to go through this? He will never
have to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   And Katarina Ivanovic, 32, asked, ``Why did all those people
die?''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Belgrade expressed relief at the news of a deal
that could end the war, but their relief was tinged with bitterness
that they had been put through 10 weeks of bombing for little
apparent gain.
</P>
<P>
   Most politicians welcomed Belgrade's acceptance of NATO's terms
as a chance for peace and prosperity, but people on the street did
not seem so sure. Few said they would be celebrating. Many were
uncertain, even skeptical that this really meant an end to the war.
Some warned that NATO had more in store for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a trick,'' said one flamboyantly dressed student with
ragged dreadlocks. ``They will send nuclear bombs next.''
</P>
<P>
   Jelena, an economist who has found herself unemployed since the
beginning of the war, said: ``People will not be celebrating. They
are relieved but weary. This is a wise decision, but it should have
been accepted at the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Visnja, a retired teacher, said, ``It is great, because it means
a stop to the killing of people and to the ruin of our country.''
She acknowledged that the agreement seemed like a defeat for
Serbia, but added, ``We do not have any other choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic had to agree because he faced ``a destroyed country
and destroyed people,'' said Visnja's friend Mila, an architect.
Both women chatted freely in an outdoor cafe, but they did not want
their full names in a foreign newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that he was even thinking of going on to fight a
ground war,'' Mila said of Milosevic, ``but there are some
intelligent people around who warned that we should on no account
embark on a ground war.''
</P>
<P>
   For such ``intelligent people,'' the women said, the loss of
electricity and water was the last straw. Added to that, Mila had
four missiles land just 300 yards from her home on Monday. ``I did
not realize the bombing would be so drastic, that civilians would
be killed,'' she said. ``I thought it would just be in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Serbs expressed anger at their government for the long
bombing campaign. ``That was a mistake of our government,'' said
Damir, 22, a waiter in a hotel restaurant. ``A lot of people died
for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend Nenat, 23, chimed in, ``We did not want foreign
troops on our land, but now so many people have died, it's not
worth it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Some tried to put a good face on things. ``Well, everything is
OK if you have your head on your shoulders,'' said Sloba, a worker
drinking beer with a friend selling popcorn. ``Things will get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Others took some solace in branding NATO a loser, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least Kosovo is clean of a lot of Albanians and not all of
them will come back,'' said Nenat, a supporter of the extreme
nationalist Serbian Radical Party.
</P>
<P>
   As Mila put it: ``You could not say NATO is the winner when they
had such a large force and they had to bomb for nearly three
months.'' Her friend Visnja added, ``NATO is the moral loser _ such
a large force attacking such a small country.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many Serbs remain suspicious of NATO's intentions, saying they
expect that the alliance would not be satisfied with occupying
Kosovo and would later move to take over the whole of Serbia in
their pursuit of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Few think that Serbia will be free of war for long: some foresee
civil war, and some think NATO will be behind it. Nenat said that
``with 50,000 troops'' in Kosovo to resettle refugees, the alliance
``could start a war in 15 minutes,''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everyone predicts that Serbian civilians will flee
Kosovo as their troops and police forces leave, swamping Serbia
with a new wave of refugees. They also predict an exodus from
Serbia as people try to go abroad. ``What is there for us here?''
Nenat asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
