<SLUG> BC-QUEEN-NOOR-MINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEEN NOOR URGES   BAN ON LAND MINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jordan's Queen Noor, a leader in the global campaign
against land mines, warned Thursday that long after fighting ends
in Kosovo, hidden anti-personnel weapons will be killing and
maiming returning refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kosovo, land mines have been used in barbaric and
terrifyingly inhumane ways to promote ethnic cleansing,'' said
Noor, who was in Boston as part of a series of events sponsored by
UNICEF of New England aimed at outlawing the use of land mines.
</P>
<P>
   If ethnic Albanian refugees are allowed to return to Kosovo as
part of the peace agreement that Belgrade accepted Thursday, she
said, their return will have to be carefully managed to avoid a
``humanitarian catastrophe'' because of the large number of mines
and booby-trapped houses left by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The routes in are heavily mined,'' said Noor, who is patron of
the Landmine Survivors Network, an organization that helps people
injured by land mines.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of a ban on land mines call them ``a slow motion
weapon of mass destruction'' that kill at least 800 people a month
around the globe and injure another 1,200. Most of the victims are
civilians; many are small children.
</P>
<P>
   Mines wait silently long after wars end. It will take many years
to clear mines in Kosovo and neighboring Bosnia, Noor said. Though
the military has new techniques for demining, the primary means of
disarming them remains a soldier inching along the ground on his
stomach, probing with a bayonet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That epitomizes the great evil and inhumanity of
anti-personnel mines,'' she said. ``They have an impact 50 or 100
years after they are laid.''
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF New England has launched a program in Mozambique to raise
awareness of the danger of land mines, which were sown throughout
that country during years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of Jordan's King Hussein took up the anti-mine cause
early last year, filling a role the late Princess Diana once held.
She said she is especially concerned about mines in the Middle
East, many of which are from World War II and continue to cause
civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Noor said she has personally lobbied President Clinton and
members of Congress to join 135 other nations in signing the 1996
Ottawa Convention banning land mines. The vast majority of land
mines in the world are manufactured in the United States or contain
US-made components.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have opposed the treaty, arguing that mines
are an important military tool that have enabled US forces, for
instance, to defend South Korea from a possible attack from North
Korea. But many former US military commanders, including retired
General Norman Schwartzkopf, have endorsed the treaty, saying
humanitarian concerns far outweigh military utility.
</P>
<P>
   US officials have also been worried that wording in the treaty
could mean a ban on cluster bombs, such as those dropped by NATO in
Yugoslavia. Cluster bombs, which are used against tanks and mobile
artillery, scatter dozens of hand-size bomblets around an area.
These devices can kill or injure civilians long after they are
deployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are figures in Congress who understand,'' said Noor, who
was born and raised in the United States. ``But many have only been
given a perspective from the Pentagon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
