<SLUG> BC-CRASH-FRIENDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRUE TEXANS' AMONG THE DEAD ON AMERICAN AIRLINES FLIGHT 1420 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Kathey is cq) 
 
By LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Gordon and Linda Joyce McClaren moved to
Arkansas more than 10 years ago, but according to their friends
they remained ``true Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved Texas. He loved the coast. He loved to fish in the
Gulf,'' Arnold Bowden said Thursday from his home in Russellville,
Ark. Bowden and his wife, Kathey, developed a close relationship
with the McClarens after they retired to the small town about 50
miles northwest of Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, originally from Corpus Christi, were among nine
killed aboard American Airlines Flight 1420 when it crash-landed
Tuesday night at Little Rock National Airport. The McClarens and
Bowdens had been traveling with eight friends, returning from a
tour of the British Isles.
</P>
<P>
   Half of those on the tour group, which planned yearly jaunts
around the world, did not survive the crash. Along with the
McClarens, those who died included Judy Thacker, 54, Betty Evelyn
Ingram, 69, and Sara Renee Gray, 88, all of Russellville, and Mary
Elizabeth Couch, 68, of Havana, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``All six had been in Rome last year together,'' Bowden said.
``It's very personal for me. All those people we had with us are
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Also killed were the pilot Capt. Richard Buschmann,48, and
passengers Debra Ann Sattari, 38, of San Jose, Calif., and James
Harrison, 21, of Paragould, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden and his wife escaped with minor injuries but the pain of
losing their friends will haunt them forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my best fishing buddy,'' Bowden said. ``My wife and I
developed a close relationship with them. They were the type of
friends you didn't mind sharing everything with because you knew it
would be held in confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The McClarens bought a lot in the community that rests in the
shadow of the Ozark Mountains near the Ouachita River and in 1988
they built a home _ to be closer to their eldest son who works for
Entergy in Arkansas. They are survived by two other adult children
and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Linda McClaren, whom friends called Joyce, often volunteered her
clerical skills to local charity organizations in Russellville
while Gordon, a retired chemist for the Texas Health Department in
Corpus Christi, served as president of his new hometown's art
council.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said Gordon McClaren never forgot where he came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``His allegiance to Texas was to the point that it was awfully
hard to make a hog out of him,'' Bowden said. ``He must have had
more than 350 Aggie jokes, and he very rarely told the same one
twice. He had a tremendous sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the trip that began May 19, Bowden said, both
McClarens were interested in seeing the Scottish Highlands because
both were of Scottish descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove up there and he saw the home of his ancestors,''
Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more memorable moments of the trip to the Highlands
was when they got to a village where the Campbell clan on the
orders of Queen Mary killed part of the MacDonald clan in 1692, an
event that has taken on legendary status in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joyce was a Campbell,'' Bowden said. ``And when we got there
Gordon said ``You know I don't think we'll tell them we've got
Campbell blood.'
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the kind of man he was. He was quick with a joke, but
he was very intelligent. He spoke three languages, English, Spanish
and German. He was also an amateur astronomer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he, Gordon McClaren and two other friends usually
planned an extensive fishing trip each year. This year they were
scheduled to cast into the Buffalo River in northern Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a bigger Texan than Gordon,'' Bowden said. ``He
would always tell me ``A Texan never lies,' and I'd say back ``When
his lips are closed tight.' That's the kind of relationship we
had.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
