<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2377 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-     06-03 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS' `DAY OF RAGE' IS PUNCTUATED BY CALM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEIR QADDIS, West Bank _ Hundreds of Palestinians marched down a
hilltop here Thursday, trampling though rocks and bramble toward a
neighboring, and expanding, Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Adults waved protest banners and youths swung slingshots loaded
with rocks. They hiked determinedly toward a line of Israeli
soldiers waiting with guns beside a rough road newly plowed by the
settlers through the Palestinians' olive fields.
</P>
<P>
   Khandumi Moustafa, an elderly woman wearing a traditional
Palestinian embroidered dress, went running toward the marchers,
shaking her head. ``Go back, young people, I beg you,'' she said.
``Go back. It is my olive trees that were uprooted, but I'm 80
years old. I don't want to see any more blood spilled, not on my
land.''
</P>
<P>
   This town and others throughout the West Bank and Gaza
experienced an unexpectedly feeble day of protest Thursday.
Palestinian officials had summoned their people into the streets
for a ``Day of Rage,'' only to turn around and order them to be
peaceful in their rage.
</P>
<P>
   Confused by the mixed signals, many Palestinians stayed home.
Others, especially young men, pushed to the brink of violent
confrontation with Israeli troops, but most of those
confrontations, at poorly attended demonstrations, fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   The Day of Rage was meant as a warning to Israeli Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak that the Palestinians will not tolerate
the continuing expansion of Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
But it served mostly as an exercise in security cooperation between
Israeli and Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers, in most cases, acted with restraint, and
Palestinian protest leaders used bullhorns to tamp overheating
emotions. As in this village, there were patches of stone-throwing
and firing of rubber-coated bullets, but in relative terms there
were few injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to an uncertain future, many Palestinians are as
frustrated and wary as ever. But five years after the end of the
protracted uprising known as the intifada, many have tired of
violent street fights with the Israelis. And many have grown
equally weary _ and suspicious _ of their leaders' calls for
protests that bear little fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Amar Barghouti, for instance, who spent months in an Israeli
prison for rock-throwing during the 1987 to 1994 intifada, stood on
the sidelines here Thursday, swinging his cellular phone. Shading
his eyes under a fierce midday sun, he scanned the crowd for the
faces of the Palestinian officials who had convened the protest,
sponsoring buses from Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is Abu Ala?'' he asked, referring to Ahmed Qurei,
speaker of the Palestinian Legislative Council. ``Home eating
watermelon? The Legislature called us here and none of them
appeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Thursday's protests were directed at Barak, who for
the last two weeks has been working to form a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, the Labor Party leader, has made no known overtures to
the Palestinians since he was elected May 17. He has also voiced no
reaction to settlement activity that seems to have increased in the
final days of the government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   And he is negotiating with the conservative Likud Party, which
Netanyahu has quit as leader, as well as with the settlers'
National Religious Party to join his government.
</P>
<P>
   All this concerns the Palestinians, who fear that Barak is cut
from the same cloth as Netanyahu, whom they loathed. They are also
anxious that Barak will give priority to negotiations with Syria on
the withdrawal of Israeli troops from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Although Barak has not even been sworn in yet, ``it's never too
soon'' to protest, said Yusef Farsakh, 73, a Palestinian-American
from Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's protest day was specifically intended to alert Barak
that the Palestinians felt very strongly about the settlement
expansion and would not re-enter peace negotiations until he froze
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to continue to talk about peace when they
continue to build settlements on our ground,'' said Marwan
Barghouti, a leader of the Fatah Party of Palestinian Authority
President Yasser Arafat. Barghouti has called settlement building a
``terrorist act.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Palestinians said they did not believe their leaders
had any intention to break off relations with a new Israeli prime
minister. Their relative apathy Thursday _ not even 2,000
demonstrated throughout the West Bank and Gaza _ fit into a general
wariness, a concern that they are being manipulated by Palestinian
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, Palestinian merchants held a general strike. In
Bethlehem, Palestinian police helped disperse a demonstration near
Rachel's Tomb. In Gaza, Palestinians blocked the main thoroughfare
near a junction with a Jewish settlement. In Hebron, Israeli
soldiers, under order from their commander, permitted Palestinians
to march farther than they ever have into the Jewish section of
town _ right to the door of the Bet Hadassah housing complex on
Martyrs Street.
</P>
<P>
   Near Hebron, in an incident separate from the demonstrations, a
Palestinian man, Ala Abu Sharkh, was shot to death by Israeli
troops at a roadblock. Israeli and Palestinian officials gave
different accounts of what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   In Deir Qaddis, an Arab village of 500 families, protesters
gathered on the playground of the high school and then trekked to
the border with the Jewish settlement of Kiryat Sefer, an expanse
of concrete apartment buildings, ringed by new structures under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Mahmoud Abdel Rahim, an elderly man wearing a caftan, walked
with a cane. He said he owns many acres of land that the Israelis
are trying to confiscate, and he is enmeshed in court proceedings
to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This land is our precious blood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The town's zoning is controlled by the Israelis, and the
Palestinians say they cannot obtain building permits to expand.
``We live on top of each other like in a refugee camp,'' said Tareq
Nasser, 30, a truck driver. ``I'm married with four children and we
are all in one room. We have land, but we cannot build on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen-age boys pushed by, whistling, rowdy and ready for action.
Middle-age women yelled after them, imploring them to calm down. At
the same site, in a confrontation with the Israelis two years ago,
one Palestinian man was killed and 17 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd clambered up a hilltop, chanting, ``We are the sons of
this land and we will resist.'' Wrapped in Palestinian flags, they
thundered down, slingshots in tow. Behind them, organizers shouted
over bullhorns for them to keep back from the soldiers. ``Your
security and safety is more important,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   The youths began unearthing large rocks. A few were lobbed. The
soldiers, on a signal from their commander, exploded tear gas
canisters. Palestinians fumbled in their pockets for the onions
they bring to demonstrations; inhaling a sliced onion counteracts
the effect of the gas.
</P>
<P>
   These confrontations are almost choreographed. They were a
routine part of many days during the intifada. But this time, the
adults on both sides held the younger men back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thank you very much for your solidarity,'' the organizers
shouted. ``Please retreat. We've conveyed our message and the other
side has received it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the youths had been summoned to rage. They left and
returned. Six collapsed from the tear gas. Others hurled more
rocks. The soldiers let loose a few rubber bullets. And then it was
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that was nonsense,'' Amar Barghouti said as he began the
walk back to the village. ``That accomplished nothing fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
