<SLUG> BC-INSIDER-TRADING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 CHARGED WITH INSIDER TRADING ON TAKEOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn.)   (af)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For two years, a junior investment banker at Salomon
Smith Barney and his former boss at the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi
Trust Co. thought they had devised a foolproof plan to make
millions through insider trading. But Thursday they were charged
with criminal securities fraud and conspiracy by the U.S. attorney
and civil insider-trading violations by the Securities and Exchange
Commission in connection with 13 potential and announced takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kirkbride, an associate at Salomon, would take note of
what he overheard and saw on desks, copiers and printers about
takeovers in the works, federal authorities said. Then he passed
the information along to Richard Ference, his old boss and a vice
president at the Bank of Tokyo, who would trade on the information
and split the profits with him.
</P>
<P>
   By using pay phones and prepaid calling cards, exchanging
cash-stuffed envelopes and never making bank deposits, authorities
contend the pair figured they were in the clear _ even after
amassing $750,000 in profits from deals including Tyco
International Ltd.'s takeover of Keystone International and the
Hughes Electronic Corp.'s acquisition of United States Satellite
Broadcasting Co.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their carefully laid plans to avoid detection, the
pair broke their own rules and traded without each others'
knowledge, ultimately unraveling their scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkbride's lawyer, Frank Wright, did not return a telephone
call, and a message left at Kirkbride's Manhattan residence was not
answered. Calls to Ference's home in Greenwich, Conn., were not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   According to people close to the investigation, the scheme began
to unravel after Salomon Smith Barney was informed that Kirkbride,
30, was making stock trades at another brokerage firm, York
Securities, in strict violation of Salomon's rules.
</P>
<P>
   Kirkbride was immediately suspended in March and Salomon Smith
Barney officials informed the SEC of what they had learned. He left
the firm soon after.
</P>
<P>
   William Baker, an associate director in the SEC's enforcement
division, declined to comment on how the case was broken. But he
said, ``They broke their own rules. I think there's an old adage:
No honor among thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount at issue here is by anybody's standards a
significant amount,'' Baker added. ``This was egregious
misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirkbride was arraigned in U.S. Magistrates Court in Manhattan
Thursday morning, where he pleaded not guilty and was released on a
$10,000 personal recognizance bond. If convicted, he could face 10
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney, a unit of Citigroup, said in a statement:
``This former employee violated our stringent rules on employee
trading, upon discovery of which he was promptly suspended and the
appropriate authorities notified.''
</P>
<P>
   Ference, who is 51 and could also face 10 years in prison if
convicted, is expected to be arraigned Friday morning. Bank of
Tokyo officials declined to comment about him, citing company
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the two men made $750,000 illegally, which they
agreed to split three ways: Ference would keep one third for
himself, keep one third to cover taxes, and pass the remainder to
Kirkbride. Ference still holds $1.2 million in stock purchased
based on illegal insider information, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Ference traded on the information Kirkbride supplied about
takeovers involving Salomon Smith Barney clients, and then to avoid
detection, he paid Kirkbride in envelopes that he instructed the
younger man to throw away immediately, adding that he should not
deposit it anywhere or report it on tax filings but only spend it
on ``luxury'' items, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Ference also instructed his former subordinate to act like he
did not keep in touch with his old boss if the matter ever came up
in conversation, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But while all this was going on, Kirkbride traded in his own
name at his account at York Securities, including a fateful trade
that was brought to the attention of his employer. According to the
SEC, the trades were made ``despite Ference's warning that
Kirkbride not trade in his own name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
