u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNALISTS-JAILED-NY     06-03 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNALISTS-JAILED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 REPORTERS JAILED FOR PROTECTING SOURCES IN OLYMPIC-BOMBING
STORY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in Atlanta Thursday ordered two reporters for
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution to be jailed for failing to reveal
who told them that Richard Jewell, a part-time security guard, was
a leading suspect in the bombing at the 1996 Summer Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper immediately filed an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The two reporters, Kathy Scruggs and Ron Martz, based their
reporting in July 1996 on confidential sources. The
Journal-Constitution identified Jewell as the focus of a Federal
investigation into the bombing and wrote that he ``fits the profile
of a lone bomber.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion on July 27, 1996, injured 111 people and killed
two. Jewell, who was never charged with a crime, is suing the
newspaper, its owners and the reporters for libel.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998 and again in March of this year, the two
reporters were directed by Judge John R. Mather of U.S. District
Court to reveal their sources. Both times they refused.
</P>
<P>
   An order to imprison reporters in a libel case is rare, said
Jane Kirtley, the executive director of the Reporters Committee for
Freedom of the Press. Ms. Kirtley said there are three other cases
in the United States that involve reporters who have failed to
comply with a court order to reveal sources and whom the court has
subsequently ordered imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   None of these reporters are in prison and none are involved in
libel suits.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how long it will take for the appeal by The
Journal-Constitution to be processed.
</P>
<P>
   Peter C. Canfield, the lawyer for Cox Communications, the
company that owns The Journal-Constitution, said Thursday, ``We are
confident that the Court of Appeals will find any disclosure of
confidential sources unnecessary. When your reporting has been
accurate, who your sources were is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No court as yet has looked at the issue of whether The
Journal-Constitution's reporting was accurate,'' Canfield added.
``We're confident that when a court does, it will conclude that it
was accurate, that Jewell was the focus of the investigation, and
that we accurately reported why he was the focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the case involves libel, Jewell's lawyer, L. Lin Wood,
is required to prove that the newspaper knowingly printed false
stories about Jewell that were negligent or malicious.
</P>
<P>
   Wood has argued that because he cannot identify the reporters'
sources, his case is unfairly hampered. He said he was confident
that the reporters would eventually serve a jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere down the road,'' Wood said, ``the newspaper and
these reporters face some tough decisions. They have to decide
whether they are going to jail, or whether they will do what they
have been ordered to do, and that is to tell the truth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2384 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-TOUR-TEX     06-03 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-TOUR-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By YVETTE CRAIG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Bank lending officer Judy Thacker shared her
passion for travel by sending postcards home to co-workers and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Her final greeting, which arrived just hours before American
Airlines Flight 1420 cracked open upon landing, will haunt tiny
Russellville, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wales is more spectacular than I ever imagined &AMP; tomorrow we
head for Scotland. ... I may see you before this arrives!''
</P>
<P>
   Thacker, 53, was among five Russellville residents killed in the
crash late Tuesday. Three other passengers also died, as did the
pilot, Richard Buschmann.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our small town is in utter shock,'' said Betty LaGrone,
president of the Russellville Chamber of Commerce. ``It's hard to
keep going on with the day-to-day work. ... The loss has left an
opened wound in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Thacker organized a 12-member group of widows and older couples
who left Russellville on May 19 for a trip to London, Scotland and
Wales. Among them were Thacker and her husband, Jack; 88-year-old
Sue Gray; Betty Ingram, 69; and Gordon McLerran, 64, and his wife,
Joyce, 65. Mary Couch, 68, was from neighboring Havana.
</P>
<P>
   All six perished when the McDonnell Douglas Super 80 that was
bringing them home crashed upon landing in a severe thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrone said the dead were wound into the fabric of
Russellville, a city of 25,000 about 75 miles northwest of Little
Rock. The devastation is easily felt in the tight-knit community,
where children play in the streets and old-timers fish and picnic
along Lake Dardanelle.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, a widow, taught Sunday school and embroidered altar linens
at All Saints Episcopal Church, said church member Beverly Lanier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sue took care of our church's memorial garden,'' Lanier said.
``She kept the most beautiful flowers there. Her love was pink
roses and they circled the whole garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were waiting for her to come home so she could bring more
flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Lawton, executive vice president at River Valley Bank, said
Judy Thacker lived at full speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a ball of energy ... '' Lawton said. ``She was a
friend to the young and the old and was so warm. It's strange to
think she died doing what she loves to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Thacker was in critical condition at Baptist Memorial
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Bowden, 63, and his wife, Katherine, who survived the
crash, said the travelers were drained when they boarded Flight
1420 at Dallas/Fort Worth Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Most rested during the flight. The McLerrans were exhausted
because they had caught a late-night performance of Shakespeare's
Othello in Stratford-on-Avon. The couple had used the British tour
to research their Scottish roots.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden described Gordon McLerran, a retired state chemist from
Corpus Christi, as a fishing buddy and ``true Texan'' who had ``no
fewer than 150 Aggie jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   After the crash, Bowden lost contact with the McLerrans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't see anything but fire and smoke in front of me,''
he told The Associated Press. ``There's no time to consider your
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden grabbed his wife's hand and fled, following the smell of
fresh air. While heading toward a wing exit, he helped a 2-year-old
girl whose mother was struggling with her other child.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden's son, Jeff, learned of the crash when his father woke
him with a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder why these things happen,'' said Jeff Bowden, a
Marine Corps major. ``I don't know what it would be like to be a
relatives of those who perished. We've determined that the Lord
took six angels home and left the other angels here on earth to
finish what needs to be accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Renee Lee contributed to this report. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
