<SLUG> BC-CARS-WOMEN-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY BLAZING A COAST-TO-COAST TRAIL, SHE HELPED PUT A NATION ON
WHEELS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.J.)   (af)  
 By CHERYL JENSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a soggy bon voyage. Alice Huyler Ramsey stood in the rain
outside the Maxwell auto company's New York showroom on the Upper
West Side in Manhattan, holding a bouquet of carnations and posing
for photographers as she waited impatiently to climb into her car
for a cross-country drive.
</P>
<P>
   The trip would not merit attention today, but Ramsey, who left
for San Francisco 90 years ago this week, was intent on becoming
the first woman to drive across America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Damp but not discouraged, the 22-year-old Vassar graduate set
out on June 9, 1909, in her 30-horsepower Maxwell for the
3,800-mile trip. Her adventure would take 41 days, but its success
would help convince America that automobiles were safe and
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   If Ramsey had doubts, she did not make them public. A newspaper
quoted her as saying: ``I see no reason why any woman who can drive
a car cannot take one across the continent. All that is needed is a
good car such as I have, and careful driving in the bad spots, and
the trip can be, I think, consummated without trouble.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One challenge was navigation. She made her drive before there
were guidebooks or road maps from the Mississippi west. The first
transcontinental road trip had come six years earlier, when Dr. H.
Nelson Jackson of Burlington, Vt., and his chauffeur, Sewall K.
Crocker, drove a Winton from San Francisco to New York in 63 days.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey left her husband and year-old son at home in New Jersey
and took along her husband's two sisters and a woman friend. The
right-hand-drive Maxwell was started with a hand crank _ in those
days, a crank's kickback sometimes resulted in a broken arm. The
fuel tank was under the front seat.
</P>
<P>
   The women's daily mileage over dirt tracks ranged from 4 to 198
miles. When it rained, the dirt turned to muck, making travel
impossible or dangerous. It took the women 13 days to get across
Iowa's 360 miles of ``gumbo.''
</P>
<P>
   They had to be towed out of two holes within a mile of each
other in Nebraska. She wrote in her book, ``Veil, Duster and Tire
Iron'': ``The farmer's son caught one of their horses in pasture
and pulled us out _ for a fee _ then walked on to the next hole,
repeated his towing, but doubled his fee!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, they thought they were being attacked when they saw
Indians on horseback heading at them and heard what they thought
were war whoops. ``I could almost feel the color drain from my
face,'' she wrote. ``I had read _ not too long ago _ about Indians
having attacked people in the Western United States.'' Then a jack
rabbit leaped across their path trying to escape its pursuers, who
paid no attention to Ramsey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey continued to make at least one coast-to-coast trip every
year for much of the rest of her life. In 1961, she expressed
amazement at the improvements that had shortened her 41-day trip to
a week: ``As evening approaches one can be sure of Beautyrest
mattresses and other luxuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey, who lived in Hacksensack, died in Covina, Calif., in
1983. She was 97. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2215EDT &QL; 
