A2391 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV06     06-03 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALMING THE BUTTERFLIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., N.J.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Help! I've just been promoted to a position that
will require me to give presentations to clients, trade
organizations and even our board of directors. Unfortunately, I'm
one of those people who freezes in front of a group. I've tried
picturing the audience in its underwear and a half-dozen other
tricks, but the moment the spotlight falls on me, I start babbling.
I'm thinking of signing up for public-speaking lessons, but I've
got a big speech to get through in a couple of weeks. Any survival
tips?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Scrunch your toes together several times. Seriously. ``It's
an isometric exercise that diverts a bit of the adrenaline edge,''
said Frank Carillo, president of the Executive Communications
Group, a consulting firm in Englewood, N.J. ``When a person starts
freaking out, it's because their adrenaline response is getting the
best of them. You don't want to shut off that response, but you
need to get the edge off.''
</P>
<P>
   Other ways to reduce stress include warming up your voice for a
few minutes before a presentation and, during your speech, talking
a bit louder than usual, Carillo added. ``This gets you breathing
more vigorously,'' he said, and the pumping of breath eases the
tension.
</P>
<P>
   As for the presentation, make sure the key points are clear in
your mind and stick to them, said Pam Keyzer, district governor of
the New York and New Jersey branch of Toastmasters International,
an organization that helps members sharpen their public-speaking
skills. ``Say what you have to say and then stop talking,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Keep it focused and succinct, Carillo agreed. At high-level
meetings in particular, he advised, ``don't go in planning to make
an hour presentation with 75 slides.'' Your listeners will become
impatient and start interrupting you with questions to get the
information they want. ``And you will feel victimized,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid babbling, learn the value of strategic repetition. Many
speakers start rambling because they've lost their train of thought
and want to cover their lapse, Carillo said. Instead, pause and
reiterate a snippet of what you just finished saying. ``Most people
are such bad listeners they won't notice,'' he said, ``and it will
give you a second running start at the thinking process.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, if someone asks you a tough question, repeat it
aloud. That not only insures that you (and the rest of the
audience) are clear on the question, but it also buys you valuable
thinking time, Ms. Keyzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to take a few seconds to formulate an answer. ``You
don't have to hit the button like you're on `Jeopardy,''' Carillo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, because many speakers feel overwhelmed by a sea of
faces in front of them, try focusing on just one person at a time.
``Don't ever try to talk to `the audience,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And forget about that picturing-people-in-their-underwear trick.
``That's not a pretty sight,'' he joked, ``with most senior
management groups.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by E-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
