A2394 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RESPONSE-TEX     06-03 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RESPONSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCY RESPONSE TIME COMES UNDER SCRUTINY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene was ``surreal'' when emergency crews reached the site
where American Flight 1420 crashed, one fire official said
Thursday. Passengers who had escaped the burning wreckage were
scattered in a boggy field. Some were ``walking wounded;'' others
seemed dazed and disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   For some, help came too late. Some may have perished in the
flames that erupted when the plane careened off the runway.
Authorities requested dental records from families to identify
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The crash has raised questions about how long it took emergency
crews to get the call alerting them to the crash in Little Rock,
Ark., and how long they took to reach the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities did not release the exact times that emergency crews
arrived. ``Some things we're not at liberty to say,'' said Al
Davis, Little Rock's fire chief, citing the National Transportation
Safety Board investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But some officials estimated response time at seven minutes.
Others, including passengers, put the response time at 25 minutes
or more.
</P>
<P>
   That would be far longer than the three minutes required by the
Federal Aviation Administration. All commercial airports _
regardless of their acreage or passenger load _ are required to
have at least one fire engine at the center of any runway within
three minutes and a second one there a minute later.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the emphasis on time is that, when an aircraft is
on fire, the interior quickly can reach temperatures of 400 to 600
degrees Fahrenheit, Dallas/Fort Worth Airport firefighters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first five or six minutes of a fire is critical,'' said
John Broyles, a systems engineer for Environmental Tectronics
Corp., a Florida company that sells aviation disaster-simulation
products. ``That's the time you need to break that fire down.''
</P>
<P>
   Help may have been delayed in Little Rock because for some time
after the crash, air traffic controllers were apparently unaware of
what had happened and continued to radio the crew with weather
updates, NTSB officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed about 11:50 p.m. Tuesday. Little Rock fire
officials said Thursday that they headed to the scene ``around
midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   A 911 call from a passenger at the scene was received about
12:07 a.m. Wednesday, officials said. It was unclear if that call
was the first time any emergency crews learned of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Many passengers said the wait added to their terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I circled three or four times around the airplane to help
people,'' Paul MacIntosh said, describing the scene before rescuers
arrived. ``A lot of things were occurring around the aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Another passenger, Brian Boyce, added: ``It seemed like forever.
It was just surreal, with all these people hurt like this, no
lights, no sirens, the plane burning. That was to me the worst
feeling about this whole thing. It was a very helpless feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very curious why after the first three or four minutes,
the tower couldn't know they had a problem and roll their own
trucks to look,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   After several minutes of helping others, Boyce said he spotted
firefighters walking up a rock embankment and over a 15-foot
section of fence the plane barrelled through. Soon after, other
fire department units arrived on the rain-soaked and mushy
perimeter road and put out the fire using chemicals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Three fire engines stationed at the airport went to find the
crash scene after possibly getting word from the tower that a jet
was missing from Runway 4R, Davis said, although he was unsure how
they learned of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Before medical personnel arrived, firefighters worked to put out
flames and to get people off the plane, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their main function is to extinguish the fire, open the
aircraft and get the people out,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as many as 85 emergency rescue and medical personnel and
more than 30 ambulances from Little Rock and surrounding areas
worked to help the injured and transport them to six area
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Wilkerson, a driver of a Little Rock fire engine, said
it took three minutes for him to get to the airport after he
learned of the crash and five more minutes to get to the crash
site. He did not know what time he started toward the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, he said, the worst wounds he saw were burns, some
over as much as 50 percent of some passengers' bodies. Some
supplies at the scene got depleted quickly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have had more blankets,'' Wilkerson said.
``Everybody was freezing to death.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday at D/FW Airport's fire training center, officials
declined to discuss details of the Little Rock incident, but they
put on a emergency preparedness demonstration to show how emergency
crews learn to cope with such disasters. Firefighters from across
the nation come to the facility to practice putting out fires at
two simulated aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who trained at the facility last year were six
firefighters from Little Rock, said Capt. Bill Wekenborg, training
director for D/FW's Department of Public Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Wekenborg said he did not know if any of those six firefighters
took part in the rescue effort after the American Airlines crash.
</P>
<P>
   Wekenborg stood outside the husk of a simulated aircraft
Thursday and pointed into the smoke that hid the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of fire that can usually happen on a plane,''
Wekenborg said. ``There is thick black smoke, and you can't even
see the fire. A lot of times everything is done by touch.''
</P>
<P>
   FAA standards require that small airports and large airports
have the same type of firefighting equipment, Broyles and Wekenborg
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the airport fire department, that's one
budget that doesn't get cut,'' Broyles said. ``Those people
generally get whatever they need.'' (Star-Telegram writers Mitch
Mitchell, Gordon Dickson, Betsy Blaney, Deanna Boyd and Renee C.
Lee contributed to this report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
