u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCHE-GENENTECH-NYT &LR;      06-03 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCHE-GENENTECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCHE EXERCISES ITS OPTION FOR ALL SHARES OF GENENTECH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Roche Holding AG, the European drug maker, said
Thursday that it would exercise its right to buy the 33 percent of
Genentech Inc. it does not already own.
</P>
<P>
   Roche will then issue new shares equivalent to as much as 19
percent of Genentech, the pioneering biotechnology company, so it
can continue to be publicly traded.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the option, Roche, based in Basel,
Switzerland, will pay $82.50 a share, or $4.2 billion, for the
remaining shares and options of Genentech, which is based in South
San Francisco. Terms of the new stock offering have not been
disclosed, but the sale should help Genentech maintain its
entrepreneurial culture and lets it offer stock options to attract
and retain key employees.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Genentech dropped on the news, closing at $82, down
$4.50, in NASDAQ trading on Thursday. Genentech shares have been as
high as $90 over the last year as investors bet that Roche would
let its option to buy the rest of the company expire. Roche had
until June 30 to exercise its option, which it has held since
buying its original stake in Genentech in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the transaction was good for Roche, which should
realize a gain when it sells shares, and good for Genentech, which
retains its quasi-independent status. But it is not so good for
shareholders, particularly if they bought shares within the last
few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Roche's point of view, it's a brilliant and creative
solution to a dilemma they faced,'' said Viren Mehta, an analyst
with Mehta Partners. ``From Genentech's point of view, we must
await precise terms of the additional rights Roche has obtained.
The current shareholders face a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Roche now has so-called opt-in rights, which let it obtain
marketing rights to new Genentech drugs when they have completed
the second of the three phases of clinical trials typically
required for approval by the Food and Drug Administration. Under
the new arrangement, Roche is expected to be able to extend those
rights to the completion of the third phase of trials, thus
virtually eliminating any risk that the drug might fail. Roche
might also add to its two seats on Genentech's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roche, in the end, I believe, concluded that they would not be
able to exercise their call option, exert 100 percent ownership and
control and still retain the growth prospects of the company,''
said Genentech president and chief executive Arthur Levinson in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson acknowledged that the deal did little for current
shareholders. ``Existing shareholders, particularly those that came
in recently, understandably will be disappointed, but it's hard for
me to imagine any remotely sophisticated investor not being aware
that Roche could take them out at $82.50,'' he said. ``To some
extent we were an arbitrage play between those that believed Roche
would exercise its call and those that believed Roche would not.''
</P>
<P>
   Roche's arrangement with Genentech is in contrast to its 1994
acquisition of Syntex, whose identity was rapidly submerged within
the parent company. ``We believe in the value and unique culture of
Genentech,'' said Roche chief executive Franz Humer in a statement.
By selling a portion of shares, Genentech ``will maintain its
independent operations as it continues to pursue its mission to
provide important products for patients and an opportunity for
financial growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when Genentech was struggling, Roche passed on a
previous option to buy the remaining stake for $60 a share. But
under the management of Levinson, who took over as chief executive
in 1995, Genentech has delivered a string of breakthrough drugs,
including Herceptin, the first gene-based therapy for breast
cancer, and steady growth in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Levinson's strategy has been to increase earnings per
share to a level where a reasonable price-earnings multiple would
put the share price above Roche's option, thus prompting Roche to
keep the company semi-independent. Toward this end, he spent
heavily on research and development in the early 1990s to build the
company's pipeline of drugs and has cut back in recent years to
lift the bottom line. But the strategy may have worked too well.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really rather sad because Art Levinson and his team have
really done a fantastic job of returning Genentech to its former
glory,'' said Richard van den Broek, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genentech is the most powerful drug development engine in all
of pharmaceuticals'' he said, noting that of 18 drugs in the late
stage of development at Roche, 8 came from Genentech. ``That is
exactly why Roche exercised its option. They couldn't afford to let
it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Genentech's founding scientist, Herbert Boyer, pioneered the
process of splicing together DNA to produce therapeutic proteins.
Genentech's performance has been consistent in recent years, but
there have been some setbacks this year, including the clinical
failures of a drug to promote nerve growth in diabetes patients and
a protein-based drug to stimulate the growth of blood vessels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
