<HEADER>
A2396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-720&AMP;ADD     06-03 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EUROPE-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS IMPRESSED BY THEIR UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Gerhard Schroeder, the German chancellor and current
president of the European Union, opened Thursday night's news
conference in Cologne, Germany, with the words, ``This is a good
day for Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the bombing campaign 10 weeks ago, European
leaders have emphasized that the Kosovo conflict was being fought
on the fringe of Europe to protest activity condemned under
European values by a Yugoslav regime led by Slobodan Milosevic who
by his actions had given up any claim to being accepted as a
European.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain, the most combative
proponent of the war, heads of governments appealed for popular
support by recalling the particular responsibilities borne by a
continent where some 50 million people have died in wars during
this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Europe, the war is about more than the singular wickedness
of Milosevic,'' said Philip Stephens in a column for The Financial
Times. ``The rape of Kosovo is an affront to the Continent's
self-image. It awakens the demons of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   All 19 NATO members, some like Greece, Italy and Germany with
considerable levels of internal dissent, maintained support for the
air campaign to a degree that apparently surprised Milosevic,
pleased senior NATO diplomats and even impressed the Europeans
themselves, who have had ample reason to be skeptical about the
Continent's ability to live up to its own claims of togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people I talk to have been surprised that the coalition
held together the way it did,'' said David Hine, a fellow of Christ
Church College, Oxford, whose speciality is the politics of
European integration. ``Two or three years ago, the Italian
moderate left or the Greens would have never held on for this.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some sense of shame in European capitals four years
ago when the conflict in Bosnia, a crisis that many European
leaders said would be a test of the Continent's ability to build a
common political will and to act with the force of unity, ended up
being settled in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put simply, we failed then,'' Hine said. ``The question is,
have we passed the test this time? The answer, I suppose, is yes,
but the cynical answer is yes, with the help of American command
and control.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the realization that the Europeans had finally
succeeded in coming together for a common purpose and beating back
individual national pressures, the war brought clear evidence that
they cannot mount military campaigns without the dominant
assistance of the United States. Most of the air power deployed in
the Kosovo operation has been American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite years of grumbling about the need to enhance the
defense capacity of Europe, the reality is that Europeans are even
more dependent on the U.S. than during the Cold War,'' said Gerald
Segal, director of studies at the International Institute for
Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Blair enjoyed support in Britain for his aggressive push for a
no-compromise solution and the possible commitment of combat troops
to Kosovo, and President Jacques Chirac held a firm line in France
and Thursday night praised the ``solidarity of the entire nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But other European leaders had to stand back from hard-line
positions to keep followers from withdrawing support for NATO.
Schroeder, whose coalition depends upon the cooperation of Green
Party members eager to see a halt in the bombing and a negotiated
end to the war, had to separate himself from Blair's pugnacious
statements, declaring the discussions over ground troops a
``specifically British debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Germany came up with the first peace plan in mid-April, when
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer produced a proposal, notably
including the Russians, that would have rewarded the beginning of a
Yugoslav pullout from Kosovo with a bombing pause.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema supported NATO, sent
Italian troops to Macedonia, dispatched aid for refugees and
allowed bombing raids from Italian soil but did so in the teeth of
deep opposition from the leftist groups that form the base of his
government's political survival.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's seeming breakthrough was greeted with particular
fervor and relief in Rome and in Athens, where the Greek government
was also cooperating in the NATO effort while holding off
overwhelming public opposition to the aerial war.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It has been a trying year for European institutions, with the
entire European Commission in Brussels, Belgium, forced to resign
after allegations of cronyism and mismanagement and the European
single currency going into an unanticipated swoon after its festive
launching.
</P>
<P>
   The euro made its debut on Jan. 1 with 11 countries signed up
and hopes high that it would challenge the dollar. Instead it has
fallen 12 percent from its opening value of $1.17 to Thursday's
level of $1.03.
</P>
<P>
   If it dips below the dollar, its credibility as an alternative
to the U.S. currency will be severely dented.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Gretschmann, an adviser to Schroeder, said Thursday that
moves toward peace in the Balkans would reverse the euro's falling
fortunes. ``If we get more news from Yugoslavia, then I am sure
that it will strengthen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence in European budget discipline was undermined last
week by a deal allowing Italy to escape tough European rules on
deficits. On the other hand, the deal displayed a new flexibility
on the part of Europe since the favorable treatment was extended to
Italy in the knowledge that D'Alema was facing difficulties at home
shoring up support for the NATO campaign and needed evidence that
there was something for Italy in holding to European unity.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the European Commission president-designate, Romano
Prodi, set out plans in Cologne to overhaul the disgraced executive
body, saying he would merge portfolios to put an end to past
favoritism and duplication.
</P>
<P>
   There are elections June 13 for the members of the 626-seat
European Parliament in Strasbourg. The Legislature has grown in
stature this year since it was its members who successfully
challenged the continuation in office of the members of the
commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
