<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING LIGHTS A FIRE UNDER HIS UNDERMANNED TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The Knicks had just finished stretching on the
practice floor when they drifted toward Patrick Ewing and huddled
in front of him as if they were at a bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   They took a peek at the plastic boot protecting his torn
Achilles' tendon, stared up at his square jaw and weary eyes, and
listened to a superstar who, in a very Ewing-esque way, inspired
them as he demanded a favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them before practice started that I believe in them,
and for them to go out there and get me my ring,'' Ewing said
Thursday with a smile. ``They're ready. They're ready to get it for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   And so a defiant mood was struck for a team that tends to hook
itself up to adversity as if it were an intravenous dripping
adrenaline into its bloodstream. After the stunning diagnosis of
Ewing's season-ending injury was made on Wednesday _ when a partial
tear of his Achilles' tendon was discovered _ his teammates moved
past their dismay, embraced their aging superstar after his brief
message Thursday and proceeded to have one of their most intense
practices of the shason.
</P>
<P>
   There was a definite edge to the Knicks that extended from the
10 healthy players left on the roster _ all of whom seem undaunted
by the task of facing the Indiana Pacers for Game 3 of their
Eastern Conference final on Saturday _ to the prickly demeanor of
Coach Jeff Van Gundy. Instead of striking a somber tone of a coach
who had just lost his center, he struck back at the Pacers for
their vocal attempts to change the tone of officiating between
Games 1 and 2. In Game 1, the Knicks won and were called for 27
personal fouls. In Game 2, the Knicks lost on their way to
absorbing 40 foul calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the NBA has come to a point where the way you
try to win in the playoffs is by whining,'' Van Gundy said. ``And
they whined about everything. They're a great team, and I know
they're trying to take over for Chicago, but they didn't have to do
it in the whining category.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to grouse, of course, but Van Gundy did discuss the matter
on Wednesday with Rod Thorn, the league's vice president of
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to him, but it's not about him,'' Van Gundy said.
``It's about what's going to be called in the heat of battle.''
</P>
<P>
   By complaining, Van Gundy was returning a volley Coach Larry
Bird began when he noted the Knicks' physical play in Game 1. And
now, without Ewing, each whistle is going to carry more weight.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Dudley, Kurt Thomas and Marcus Camby have all found
themselves in foul trouble at one time or another in this series.
Although Van Gundy did not name a starter at center _ which has
usually been Dudley when Ewing has been out in the past _ all three
big men will be critical to the Knicks' success. Without Ewing as a
post presence, there is less opportunity to lure Rik Smits into
foul trouble. Without Ewing, there is a hole in the Knicks'
defensive rebounding and a vacuum in their offense.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks have managed great stretches against Indiana
without Ewing, such as the 17-4 run they went on during the second
half of Game 2. During that game, the Knicks made up for their
deficiencies with speed in transition and lively play on defense.
Now, everyone will see if the uptempo style run by Latrell
Sprewell, Childs and Camby _ a look that has grown in popularity
with some Knicks critics _ has the legs to carry them through the
playoffs in Ewing's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Just two days ago, Ewing seemed prepared for the push to the end
on his sore Achilles' tendon. He was told by doctors months ago
that he couldn't damage it any further, but as he explained today,
he knew something was wrong when he felt a tearing sensation as he
jogged through the layup line before Tuesday's Game 2. He played
on, in visible pain, but late that night, as the injury showed
signs of swelling, a decision was made to have a magnetic resonance
imaging test on Wednesday morning as a precaution. Or so he
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked and disappointed,'' said Ewing, who fought back
from wrist surgery and a four-month absence last season. ``It was
rough. After going through what I did last year with my wrist, to
have to go through this now is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   It is especially difficult for a player two months shy of his
37th birthday, a player who has been through an often-jinxed
14-year journey to achieve the one thing he has never accomplished:
winning a title. If that championship occurs this season, Ewing
will let the confetti fall on him as he stands on the court in
street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still part of this team,'' Ewing said. ``I'm still going
to be on the sideline cheering them on, patting them on the back
and cursing them out. Whatever I have to do to help the team win.''
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
