<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS IN FAMILY FEUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- As talks between the Angels and Terry Collins about a
contract extension for the club's manager proceed, general manager
Bill Bavasi has found himself in the middle of a family feud.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi met with a small group of Angels players Wednesday
afternoon to discuss Collins' status with the team. The group of
players, who initiated the meeting, is apparently unhappy with
Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi is unhappy that word of the meeting got out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a huge bite taken out of the trust that existed
between the organization and the players,'' he said. ``A player, or
players, in the meeting or who knew of the meeting, within a
half-hour chose to talk to a writer. That's a bitter pill to
swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some players who are so unhappy with Collins,
according to a source close to the team, they have implied they
would strongly consider leaving if Collins returns. Of course, only
players eligible for free agency would have that option.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the group of players eligible for free agency at
season's end are pitcher Chuck Finley and second baseman Randy
Velarde.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi, who refused to identify any of the players involved, was
asked what Angels management thought of the job Collins was doing
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're asking for is a vote of confidence, and that is
absolute garbage,'' he said. ``The club has shown a lot of heart
and I'll leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi also said he is doing everything he can to difuse the
situation, which he says is not so unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are employers, like any other company,'' he said. ``When
employees have complaints, concerns or questions, it's our
responsibility to listen. We take it seriously. We evaluate it
seriously. To the extent any employee is dissatisfied with what I'm
doing, or what Terry is doing, we'll look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Collins said he's not concerned about
having everyone like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never going to be a manager in the game that can
please 25 guys, it's impossible,'' he said. ``You make decisions,
and any decision you make, somebody's not going to like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
