<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO BACK AT FIRST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Mo Vaughn will be back at first base tonight against
the Dodgers, because he has no choice. In the National League
ballparks -- the Angels play three at Dodger Stadium and three in
San Francisco in the next six days -- there is no DH spot for
Vaughn and his sore left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn hasn't played first base since May 9 at Boston, when it
was obvious that his ankle would not allow him to play in the
field. The decision has been a good one as Vaughn has hit well in
the DH spot and struggled at the plate when playing first base.
</P>
<P>
   He's hitting .328 with 12 homers and 37 RBIs as a DH, and only
.095 (2 for 21) with one homer and two RBIs as a first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited, Vaughn said about playing first again. ``To tell
you the truth, I'm surprised about the success I've had DH-ing.
It's not my style. I like to get a sweat going. My last couple of
at-bats the last couple of nights, I've been freezing cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn also said he's looking forward to playing at Dodger
Stadium for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of history there, and I'm into that,'' he said.
``You talk about rivalries, I was a part of one between Boston and
New York. If you can't be excited about that, something's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Charlie O'Brien heard a pop in the bottom of his right
foot and he ran toward first base in the second inning Wednesday
night and had to leave the game. He was scheduled to have an MRI
exam performed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The last time through the starting rotation, the five Angels
starters have combined to give up 10 earned runs in 40 innings,
going 4-0 (one no-decision) with an ERA of 2.25. All five pitched
at least seven innings, four of the five pitched at least eight
innings and two pitched into the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a horrendous May at the plate (.130, 12 for 92), third
baseman Troy Glaus is on a pace to break the Angels record for
doubles in a season. With 17 doubles, he's on a pace for 52. The
team record is 42, held by Jim Edmonds (1998), Johnny Ray (1988)
and Doug DeCinces (1982).
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and Angels have played eight regular season games
since interleague play begin in 1997, the Dodgers holding a 5-3
lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
