<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT TIMES FOR NHRA COMPETITORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summertime? When the living is easy?
</P>
<P>
   Not for National Hot Rod Association competitors, who start the
dreaded summer season when opening-round qualifying begins today
for this weekend's Route 66 Nationals in Joliet, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Summertime in the NHRA usually means competing in hot weather
conditions on very slippery race tracks. That sometimes spells
trouble for Top Fuel and Funny Car crew chiefs who must find a way
to control their 6,000-horsepower machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summer is always the key (to the championship),'' said
Tony Pedregon, who along with teammate John Force, is one of only
two Funny Car drivers to win a national event this season. ``I said
that even after the first couple of races that we won. Once we get
on these tracks (in the summer), like Chicago (Joliet), Columbus
(Ohio), and (Indianapolis) to an extent, it gets a little hot and a
little tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like some of the lesser power cars get down tracks
like that. They've proved that time after time, and that's going to
be the true test. Whoever can make that swing in the summer, is
definitley going to make the difference in the championship. It's
going to be very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   One who might have an advantage in Top Fuel is two-time
defending champion Gary Scelzi, whose most recent win was on
Atlanta Dragway's slick and hot asphalt. ``Now that we are in the
heat of the summer and on the slicker race tracks, there are only a
few guys who have a handle on it,'' Scelzi said. ``I feel that
after Atlanta, (crew chief Alan Johnson) has real good tuneup for
slick tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan is really good at controlling tire spin from halftrack
on. We did very well at all the slippery race tracks last year, so
I think (the summer) kind of plays into our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   It also might work well for five-time champion Kenny Bernstein,
who completed the three-race stretch at Chicago, Columbus and St.
Louis with two wins and a runner-up finish.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Skuza, who has finished in the top 10 in the Funny Car
points standings in each of the past three seasons, announced this
week that he and long-time crew chief Ronnie Swearingen have parted
company.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Lance Larsen, who was co-crew chief with Swearingen of
Skuza's Dodge, will assume all crew chief duties.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the second such change in the Funny Car division.
Joe Gibbs Racing dismissed veteran driver Cruz Pedregon in a mutual
agreement last week.
</P>
<P>
   Covina native Randy Anderson will drive the Gibbs Pontiac Funny
Car this weekend before Tommy Johnson Jr. takes over the seat on a
permanent basis next week.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR driver Dale Jarrett said he wouldn't mind going winless
in a season if he could trade it for the Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Top Fueler Bernstein isn't sure if he agrees with that,
but that doesn't mean he is disappointed about his peformance after
nine races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy I guess because the consistency is there,'' said the
five-time NHRA champion, who is third in points, 108 behind leader
Mike Dunn. ``We're certainly in the points chase. But on the other
side, I'm a little disappointed that we haven't won a race yet.
It's a strange deal, a bit different from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine. I happy with (the start), we just need to win a
race or two to make things a little better.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
