r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BCS-LADN     06-03 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE RANKINGS FOR BCS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commissioners of the six conferences tied into the Bowl
Championship Series will meet later this month to decide which --
if any -- computer rankings should be added to the survey that
determines the nation's top college football team, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, featuring the Pac-10, Big Ten, Atlantic Coast, Big
East, Southeastern and Big 12 conferences, and Notre Dame, will be
held in Newport, R.I. from June 20-23.
</P>
<P>
   It has attracted the attention of a different breed of college
football fan -- university mathematicians who have developed
programs that rank NCAA Division I teams.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these mathematicians and hobbyists post their findings
in the Internet newsgroup rec.sport.football.college. Most would
love to see the inclusion of more computer polls in the BCS formula
and several hope that they will be chosen to take part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a really good idea to add more computers,'' said
Ross Baker, an Indiana University computer science grad student who
has his own ranking system.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS promises college football fans that the top two teams in
the country will play for the national championship during New
Year's week. In its current configuration, the championship game
rotates among the Sugar, Orange, Fiesta and Rose bowls.
</P>
<P>
   This year the championship was played at the Fiesta Bowl. The
Sugar Bowl will serve as host for the game on Jan. 4, 2000. The
Rose Bowl will be the host in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Last year BCS standings were determined by a combination of
national polls, won-loss records, strength of competition and
computer rankings. Those rankings come from the New York Times, the
Seattle Times and college sports guru Jeff Sagarin of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Still the system can't get a consensus. Many believe more
computers will help smooth out irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good because the polls (of sportswriters and coaches)
don't take into account a team's strength of schedule enough,''
Baker said. ``(Last year) it seemed that the BCS was more about
picking the hottest team.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be pitfalls. If the college football Internet
newsgroup is any indication, many of the computer gurus are more
likely to know the names -- and correct spellings -- of Star Wars
characters than the name of their university's second-string middle
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   David Wilson, a University of Wisconsin mathematician whose
ranking system is being considered for inclusion by the BCS,
readily admits he's never been to a college football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in the mathematics of it,'' said Wilson, who
also maintains a web site devoted to the various computer rankings.
``The problem is that there is no official champion. On the other
hand, nobody would be interested in this if there was a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, in math terms, the problem becomes, how does one think
that the champion should be picked?,'' Wilson said. ``It's an
interesting math problem that has no one right answer.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Pac-10 is concerned, the more computers the
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine with us,'' said Jim Muldoon, assistant
commissioner in charge of public relations. ``One the reason
there's more than one computer (used by the BCS) to start with, is
that it makes this more legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more computer rankings you have out there, the less
important any one is,'' he said. ``It makes it so that one computer
doesn't have undue influence. It's a good idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
