<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAIL-DEATH04-COX     06-03 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-DEATH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Authorities release report on jailed Mexican who died
 &HT;    By Leah Quin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Juan Campos was arrested at his Austin home this
spring on a 2-year-old misdemeanor charge, booked into the Travis
County Jail and died after 18 days in custody from a mysterious
blow to the head.
</P>
<P>
   That much is certain from a 50-page report on Campos' May 12
death the sheriff's department provided Thursday. But the report,
which suggests Campos injured himself by banging his head, says no
one saw or heard Campos hurt himself. It also raises questions
about whether he was adequately cared for and supervised.
</P>
<P>
   Campos is among 21 inmates who have died in the sheriff's
department's custody in the last 10 years. Virtually all deaths
were from suicide or illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Campos, 35, was first found lying on the floor of his cell about
3:45 a.m. on May 11, but jailers didn't realize he was in danger
until more than six hours later. He was taken to Brackenridge
Hospital at 11:30 a.m. where doctors said he was already brain
dead. He died the next morning in the intensive care unit.
</P>
<P>
   A week before he died, Campos was moved from a closely
supervised medical unit where inmates are checked every 15 minutes
to a second-floor ``psych'' block where he was isolated but checked
only hourly.
</P>
<P>
   The jail's medical staff said Campos was suffering from extreme
withdrawal from alcohol _ hallucinating, talking gibberish and
walking into walls _ up to the day he was found comatose. A
psychiatrist who evaluated him May 8 found him incompetent to stand
trial, but Campos died before a hearing that probably would have
sent him to the Austin State Hospital, said Dr. Richard Coons.
</P>
<P>
   Det. Stan Roper of the sheriff's department, who investigated
the death for potential criminal wrongdoing, said he found nothing
to indicate that anyone intentionally hurt or neglected Campos. But
he questioned the hours Campos was left on the floor of his cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say who's at fault there,'' Roper said. ``Was
something wrong and they just didn't see it?''
</P>
<P>
   Roper's report also quotes corrections officers who disagreed
with a nurse's decision to transfer Campos to the less-supervised
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The death will be further investigated by the Travis County
district attorney's office, which may refer the matter to a grand
jury, and by the sheriff's internal affairs division, which will
send the case to the state attorney general's office. Those
procedures are routine for inmate deaths, said Sheriff Margo
Frasier.
</P>
<P>
   Campos, a Mexican citizen who lived in Travis County for nearly
20 years, was unmarried and had many relatives in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief conversation Wednesday, Felipe Nun(tilde)ez said he's
angry about his brother's death, which is also being investigated
by the Mexican consulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know exactly what happened and how it happened,'' he
said in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Cortez of the consulate said the family had requested
help, but she declined to define the scope of the consulate's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Campos' autopsy report lists the cause of death as a subdural
hematoma, or bleeding in the brain, ``probably sustained by
striking his head against a wall in his jail cell,'' wrote Travis
County Medical Examiner Roberto Bayardo.
</P>
<P>
   Bayardo said Thursday the injury ocurred no more than a few
hours before Campos was found lying unconscious on floor. Bayardo
said he was told by sheriff's deputies that Campos hit his head
against the wall at various times.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Roper's report says that Campos banged his head
against the wall, though several are quoted saying he couldn't get
up without help and frequently fell. Roper said no one heard any
noise from Campos' cell the hours before he died.
</P>
<P>
   The report gives this chronology:
</P>
<P>
   At 12:30 a.m. on May 11, a jailer saw Campos trying to open a
cell window. He told the guard, ``The taco lady is trying to shut
the garage door and I want to get some tacos.'' The jailer notified
a nurse of the behavior, and she said she would evaluate him during
her rounds, three hours later.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:35 a.m., the nurse saw Campos standing in his cell. When
she went in a few minutes later, he was lying on the floor on his
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The nurse checked him and noticed his hair was wet. She looked
for cuts and bruises but saw none. Campos swallowed two pills and
she left, giving instructions that he be monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Guards reported that he stayed in the same position, snoring,
with his eyes open and unblinking. One guard told others Campos
appeared dead but wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   After Campos missed two meals, a guard called another nurse at
10:30 a.m. She and other staff tried to revive him. An ambulance
came at 11:15 a.m. One guard who rode with him to Brackenridge said
Campos was bleeding from the nose and mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Campos' 18 days in jail started April 24 when Austin police
arrested him on an outstanding warrant stemming from a criminal
trespass charge in 1997. A videotape of Campos being booked at the
jail shows him acting normally, the report says. However, the
booking form indicated he might be suicidal, so he was referred to
the medical unit.
</P>
<P>
   During the next few days, Campos was restrained five times,
either by handcuffs or soft leather straps, to prevent him from
falling and hurting himself. He spoke incoherently but didn't
communicate with anyone, including his court-appointed attorney,
Wade Russell of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
