<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBORNE-POSTAL-SERVICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBORNE MAKES E-COMMERCE DEAL WITH POSTAL SERVICE FOR FASTER
DELIVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Airborne Express plans to enter the booming electronic
commerce market in July by joining forces with the U.S. Postal
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Airborne, exclusively a business-to-business delivery service
until now, has missed out on much of the growth of e-commerce.
Internet retailers have relied mostly on United Parcel Service or
Federal Express because those companies ship directly to customers'
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Seattle-based Airborne promises to move a package to
one of the Postal Service's 24,000 hubs within two days. Then, the
Post Office will deliver the order to the customer the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Airborne &LR; Home, as the new service is known, involves only a
handful of clients in its initial test. But Airborne executives
have little doubt they will expand the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge potential opportunity because the market is
enormous,'' said Kent Freudenberger, executive vice president of
marketing at Airborne Express. ``It's millions and millions of
dollars'' of potential business.
</P>
<P>
   Freudenberger, however, said it is too early to estimate how
much revenue the company could eventually earn from its new
venture.
</P>
<P>
   The Post Office opened the door for Airborne and others in
January when it offered discounts to shippers for the first time.
The discounts made it cost effective for Airborne, according to the
company's executives. In the past, Airborne, along with other
shippers, avoided the residential market because of its high costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly it made economic sense for us,'' Airborne's
Freudenberger said. Now, Airborne, the third-largest U.S.
express-freight carrier, will compete with the No. 1 carrier,
Federal Express Corp., owned by FDX Corp., and United Parcel
Service of America Inc. for a piece of the residential shipping
pie. All three firms are particularly interested in tapping the
burgeoning e-commerce market.
</P>
<P>
   That's because retail sales on the Internet are expected to
explode in the next three years, with sales estimated to rise by as
much as 75 percent to $75 billion by 2002, from $8 billion in 1998,
according to a report from Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them a platform in the new medium which is
e-commerce,'' said Jeffrey Pittsburg, a partner at Goldis-Pittsburg
Institutional Services. ``It will boost the bottom line
significantly'' over the long term.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, RPS Inc., a subsidiary of Federal Express, launched its
own plan to test the residential market last week. If the test goes
well, the firm could begin a full-fledged service as early as 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While Airborne is following Federal Express's lead, it is
launching a more ambitious program, according to financial
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bought the infrastructure (from the Post Office)
basically,'' said Alex Brand, a research analyst for Richmond,
Virginia-based Scott &AMP; Stringfellow Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Airborne is already promising consumers it will be able to
deliver products up to 60 percent faster than competing services.
</P>
<P>
   Most investors welcomed the deal, pushing the stock of Airborne
Express's parent, Airborne Freight Corp., up 3 7/8, or 16 percent,
to 28 9/16 in trading Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, however, is completely sold on the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the jury is still out over whether the
Seattle-based carrier can balance the need to offer low prices to
attract clients with the drive to generate profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's all predicated on their ability to
generate large volumes from shippers,'' said Scott &AMP; Stringfellow's
Brand.
</P>
<P>
   Shippers will also lose their ability to track packages once the
Post Office picks them up under the Airborne system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
