<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RENEWS CHINA TRADE STATUS AMID ROCKY RELATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday renewed normal trade
relations with China, setting off an annual congressional debate
complicated this year by allegations that China has stolen U.S.
nuclear weapons secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Few observers expect Congress to muster enough votes to overturn
Clinton's action, but the debate is expected to be heated. And
hopes are fading that Clinton can win congressional approval for
Chinese membership in the World Trade Organization before the next
round of international trade talks in Seattle in November.
</P>
<P>
   As one indication of the trouble now facing U.S.-China
relations, Rep. Jack Metcalf, R-Wash., who has supported normal
trade relations with China throughout his four years in Congress,
said Thursday he is now ``undecided and gravely concerned.'' The
other 10 members of the state's congressional delegation, although
expressing a variety of concerns about China's behavior, continue
to support normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insisted Thursday that maintaining normal trade
relations with China is in U.S. interests because of a rapid
increase in U.S. exports to China. But in a statement issued just a
day before Friday's 10th anniversary of the Chinese massacre of
protesters at Tiananmen Square, Clinton acknowledged widespread
concerns about China's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pursue engagement with our eyes wide open, without
illusions,'' he said. ``We continue to speak frankly about our
differences and to firmly protect our national interests. A policy
of disengagement and confrontation would only strengthen those in
China who oppose greater openness and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, U.S.-China relations seemed to be on an
upswing. China offered to lift a 27-year ban on the importation of
Northwest wheat as part of a broad package of trade concessions,
and the two countries appeared to be on track to negotiate China's
accession to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But on May 7, NATO forces accidently bombed the Chinese Embassy
in Belgrade, killing three people. That was followed by several
days of anti-Western demonstrations in China.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a House committee headed by Reps. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif., and Norm Dicks, D-Wash., reported that China had
succeeded in stealing design information about all seven nuclear
warheads currently deployed on American missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we had lousy counterintelligence at our national
labs is something we should be embarrassed about, but we should not
change our basic relationship with China,'' Dicks said. ``We're
cleaning up our mess, but I don't think we should create another
one by trying to go to a Cold War setting with China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly anybody would say that this is a very difficult time
to pass legislation giving normal trade relations to China,'' said
Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash. ``I think it will pass ... but what I'm
worried about is that there will be so much Red Scare-ing ... that
we will lose sight of the larger goal, which is to involve the
Chinese in the community of countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's Republican members of Congress are more
inclined to blame Clinton than China for the spying episode, and,
with the exception of Metcalf, they do not believe the spying
debate should be tied to trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't be surprised that there are people spying on
us,'' said Rep. Doc Hastings, R-Wash. ``Our surprise should be when
we discover that we don't act on it.''
</P>
<P>
   China is the fourth largest trading partner of the United
States, which last year exported $14.3 billion of goods to China
and imported $71.2 billion worth.
</P>
<P>
   For Washington state, where two-way trade with China ranks third
largest among Asia-Pacific nations at nearly $10 billion in 1997,
there are a variety of economic issues at stake. Rep. George
Nethercutt, R-Wash., said he supports normal trade relations with
China because of the importance of winning better access to Chinese
markets for eastern Washington agricultural products. Rep. Jay
Inslee, D-Wash., said normal relations would allow a tougher
crackdown on software piracy in China that would help companies
like Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, the state's largest employer, will be leading the charge
in favor of normal relations through its chairman, Philip Condit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade with China is a cornerstone of a stable U.S.-China
relationship, and presents Americans with unprecedented
opportunities with the world's most populous country,'' Condit
said. ``Normal trade relations with China not only sustains
hundreds of thousands of export and import-related jobs, but it
also supports U.S. companies operating in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said that ``In the long run, when
individual members of Congress are looking at the 5,000 concessions
China has made, they're going to think of their own districts, and
when they see the benefits for the high-tech community, for the
beef producers, for the wheat farmers, then we will move away from
the current contentious atmosphere and look at reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., in the past a skeptical voice on
U.S.-China relations, this year said that he would support
permanent normal trade relations with China based on a series of
concessions agreed to this spring. Gorton is now worried that the
deal with China may have fallen apart, but if Clinton reconstructs
it, Gorton has pledged to help him win permanent normal relations
in the Senate, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The three other members of the state's congressional delegation,
Republican Jennifer Dunn and Democrats Brian Baird and Adam Smith,
support normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has normal trade relations with most
countries. The status, formerly known as most favored nation,
allows countries low tariffs when exporting to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The president must decide each year whether to renew normal
trade relations with countries like China that do not grant their
residents freedom of emigration.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has 60 days to overturn a president's action on trade
relations, but has done so only once, in 1989, shortly after
Tiananmen Square. President Bush vetoed that action, and Congress
failed to override his veto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
