<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLES-LATIMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES MIRROR CEO STEPPING DOWN AS L.A. TIMES PUBLISHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Times Mirror Co. chief executive Mark H. Willes
stepped down Thursday as publisher of the Los Angeles Times after
20 controversy-filled months and named second-in-command Kathryn M.
Downing to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Willes was an executive at cereal maker General Mills when he
joined Times Mirror in 1995 and pledged to reinvent the newspaper
business. In naming Downing as publisher, he said the foundation
has been laid for significant gains in profits and revenues. ``The
time is right for me to step back and allow Kathryn to continue to
lead the revitalization of the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Willes, 57, remains Times Mirror chairman, chief executive
officer and president.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper world was surprised when Willes took the reins of
one of the nation's largest newspaper publishing companies in
mid-1995. Among his first moves was slashing 800 jobs at the Times.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was delighted and Times Mirror's long-depressed
stock price rocketed upward. But Willes' promise to boost
circulation by 500,000 has been unfulfilled, and recently the
company's stock performance has been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call with reporters Thursday, Willes
acknowledged that many executives have departed during his reign
because of other opportunities and disagreements over strategy. But
he emphasized that he has become ``increasingly comfortable and
confident'' with the senior management team.
</P>
<P>
   Downing, 46, was named president and chief executive officer of
the Times 15 months ago. She joined Times Mirror as head of its
legal publishing arm in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
