<SLUG> BC-LAMAR-CAMPAIGN-FUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMAR ALEXANDER CUTS BACK AS CAMPAIGN FUNDS FLOW TO TEXAS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After months of watching Republican dollars bypass
Tennessee in a mighty rush toward Texas, Lamar Alexander moved to
hoard his disappointing campaign treasury Thursday, laying off four
top staff members and curtailing his travels.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee, is making his
second run for the Republican presidential nomination, and has
found the all-important task of raising money far more difficult
than it was in 1996. He has now raised about $1.7 million, and
aides said he would report from $2 million to $2.5 million at the
end of the month, about a third of his original target.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has raised about $10
million, much of which has come from donors whom Alexander and the
other Republican contenders had hoped to reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of Bush's fund-raising has been phenomenal,
unprecedented, just amazing to watch,'' said Steve Schmidt,
Alexander's communications director, one of the staff members who
is leaving the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he's sucked all the oxygen out of the news
environment, and everyone else's fund-raising is off from their
projections,'' Schmidt continued. ``So the campaign had to make a
decision to take some painful moves now.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials insisted that this was only a minor bump in
Alexander's carefully plotted road to the Republican nomination.
Only five of 35 staff members were being let go, they said _
including Schmidt's deputy, the campaign's legal director, and its
research director _ allowing Alexander to save money to achieve his
primary goal, a strong showing in the early stages of the campaign
in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is still planning to add several lesser-paid staff
members based in Iowa, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision, first reported Thursday by The Associated
Press, comes as Alexander is struggling to buck up his supporters
concerned about his low standing in national polls. Wherever he
goes, the candidate tells voters that the early polls mean nothing
until the caucus-goers of Iowa have their say next February. Now
his aides must say the same thing about his fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does well in Iowa, the money will turn around on a
dime,'' said Ted Welch, Alexander's finance chairman and one of the
Republican Party's most able fund-raisers. ``After he came in third
in Iowa last time, we started to get $100,000 a day. So the idea of
this move is to get to the first of the year with enough money to
prevail in those early primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is by no means out of the political picture. He has
what is generally regarded as the strongest campaign organization
in Iowa, with two-thirds of the county leaders behind him, along
with a popular former governor, Terry Branstad.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is a crisp speaker with a wholesome personal life who
is certain he can capitalize on a national longing for strength of
character in high office. If he does well in the Iowa caucuses or
in a straw vote that takes place in Ames, Iowa, in August, his poll
ratings and his treasury are likely to climb rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's cutbacks make it clear how much of Alexander's
campaign is based on the hope that Bush will stumble, or that
damaging disclosures will emerge about the Texas governor's private
life. With $10 million in hand and many months before Iowa, Bush is
capable of a withering media assault that none of his competitors
can match, much as Bob Dole effectively turned his cannons on
Alexander in the 1996 New Hampshire primary. The party's rush to
embrace a governor with a famous last name has been infuriating to
the Alexander camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just hard to figure out this Bush phenomenon,'' Welch
said, adding: ``There's no justification for him being at these
lofty levels. And yes, it probably has made it harder to raise
money this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, who will stay on temporarily as a consultant to the
campaign, said he suspected that other Republican campaigns were in
the same financial straits as Alexander's, but were not announcing
similar moves because they feared the momentum-slowing impact of
bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later, the other campaigns are going to have to face
reality like Lamar has,'' Schmidt said. ``If they don't, they'll
never make it to Iowa.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
