<HEADLINE>
POISED AGASSI IS TALK OF PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ His recent divorce from Brooke Shields may be the talk
of Hollywood, but here in Paris, it is Andre Agassi's solo act at
Roland Garros that has become the talk of the town. The fans
perform the wave for him, he responds with air-blown kisses, and
now he is in his first French Open semifinal since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Twice he has been a runner-up at the French, the only Grand Slam
event he has not won. But this year, the 13th-seeded Agassi seems
primed, poised and pared-down for his first Grand Slam title in a
roller-coaster four-year span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to go out there and win because I deserve it,'' said
Agassi, who knocked out the defending champion, Carlos Moya, in the
fourth round and faces 30th-ranked Dominik Hrbaty of Slovakia in
the semifinals on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The only cloud on Agassi's Paris horizon is his 0-1 record
against Hrbaty, the 21-year-old powerball player who defeated him
this year at Lipton. Hrbaty got to the semifinal by defeating the
top-ranked Yevgeny Kafelnikov in the second round and outgunning
ninth-seeded Marcelo Rios in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   In the other semifinal, 100th-ranked Andrei Medvedev of Ukraine,
who reached this round six years ago, takes on 54th-ranked Fernando
Meligeni of Brazil. Meligeni, 28, derailed third-seeded Patrick
Rafter, sixth-seeded Alex Corretja, and 14th-seeded Felix
Mantilla. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
