<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVIN MAKES POINT TO FILL NEEDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Servic clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Each spring seems to bring a twist to UCLA's
recruiting efforts. Two years ago, the Bruins landed Baron Davis
and Schea Cotton after prolonged, surreal pursuits. Last spring,
they battled maddening NCAA logistics to sign the giant Europeans,
Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric.
</P>
<P>
   While the current group can't match its predecessors for
melodrama or reputation, it didn't exactly follow a conventional
path to Westwood: When the April signing period began, the Bruins
didn't expect to sign either Artesia High School's Jason Kapono or
Santa Margarita's Spencer Gloger. Yet today, they form coach Steve
Lavin's third straight successful recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past UCLA recruits like Mitchell Butler, Toby Bailey,
Jelani McCoy, Charles O'Bannon, JaRon Rush, Ray Young, Moiso and
Gadzuric _ exquisite athletes with raw talent _ both Gloger and
Kapono are highly skilled. They can pass, shoot, read defenses, use
screens and handle the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both bring high basketball IQs, and they're both
tremendous shooters,'' Lavin said. ``When you look at our team last
season, we were (ninth) in the Pac-10 in 3-point shooting and last
in free-throw shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of filling our needs, we've definitely addressed two
glaring deficiencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloger, who picked UCLA over Princeton, is a 6-foot-6 shooting
guard with long arms, good quickness and live legs. He probably
won't challenge for a starting spot next season, but in two or
three years the Bruins expect him to contribute consistently. And
he's a better player than the big-name shooting guard UCLA did not
sign, Kareem Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono, meanwhile, is a 6-8 McDonald's All-American who chose
UCLA over Missouri and Arizona. Capable of playing any position
except center, Kapono will be UCLA's best passer and 3-point
shooter the instant he enrolls. No doubt, his presence will create
intense competition _ with Young, Rush, Moiso, Rico Hines, Billy
Knight and Matt Barnes _ for playing time at shooting guard and
both forward spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we don't have a true power forward, there are minutes
to share,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Early returns: No player has made more offseason progress than
Young, a 6-4 sophomore whose workouts emphasize shooting and
ballhandling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are talking him up,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Gadzuric is rapidly recovering from the
arthroscopic knee surgery that forced him to miss the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running on the track and playing once or twice a week,''
Lavin said. ``He's ahead of schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and Ends: Both Gadzuric and Moiso are expected to
participate in Hall of Fame coach Pete Newell's highly regarded
summer camp for big men.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin said he has received no indication that either Rush or
Barnes plans to transfer following Kapono's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if forward Travis Reed reverses his decision
to transfer and winds up at UCLA next season. Asked about Reed's
future, Lavin declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
