<SLUG> BC-MEGAPLEX-DECLINE-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER OPERATORS LOSE FASCINATION WITH GIANT-SIZE VENUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Say goodbye to the 30-plex movie theater and put
the 24-screen megaplex on the endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   That's the clear message from the nation's theater operators,
who are tapping the brakes after four wild years of
bigger-is-better expansion. It's a stunning reversal following an
explosion of shiny new palaces with a seemingly infinite number of
auditoriums.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been some degree of insanity to build as large as
30 screens,'' said theater design veteran Francisco Behr, head of
Behr Browers in Westlake Village, Calif. ``There's only so much
product to show. I think people have started to realize that
there's not much advantage beyond 24 screens.''
</P>
<P>
   Retail consultant Mark Kissel of Rockville, Md., agreed. ``For a
while, it seemed we were heading toward the infinity-plex,'' he
said. ``Maybe we've realized there is a limit to what you can place
on one site.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the nation's biggest chains _ AMC, Regal and Loews
Cineplex _ have indicated recently that 20 rather than 30 has
become the top-end number at new theaters. ``There's no ideal
single size for a theater, but the biggest ones have become subject
to more scrutiny,'' Behr said.
</P>
<P>
   During the expansion, the biggest theater to come to the San
Fernando Valley has been the Winnetka 20, which includes two
715-seat auditoriums. Neal Haltrecht, director of real estate for
Los Angeles-based Pacific, said the Winnetka is as big as his chain
will go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may build another 20, but we're most likely to build
theaters in the 10- to 18-screen range,'' Haltrecht said. ``We
never believed in 24- to 30-screen theaters and thought they were a
mistake. What we like is a complex with several large auditoriums
rather than 30 small auditoriums.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one is proclaiming the death of the megaplex, the
major motor in the modernization of the American movie house.
Between 1995 and the end of last year, the number of U.S. screens
grew an astounding 23percent to 34,168 even though the number of
sites slid 4.2percent to 7,418.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call this the abandonment of the megaplex, but
building 30-screen theaters was never a part of our plans,'' the
megaplex,'' said Marc Pascucci, Loews executive vice president.
``You lose operating efficiencies when you're too big.''
</P>
<P>
   Loews plans to spend $1billion over the next five years to add
12 or 13 new theaters annually. During that time, it will install
700 new screens, an average of a dozen per site, and close down 500
older auditoriums.
</P>
<P>
   AMC launched the megaplex era in 1995 with the Grand 24 in
Dallas, offering staggered start times, huge snack bars, stadium
seating with unobstructed sight lines and state-of-the-art sound
and projection. It raised the ante in December 1996 by opening the
Ontario Mills 30, 50 miles east of downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, the Edwards chain stunned the business by
rolling out a 22-screen theater across the street from Ontario
Mills. Rival executives doubted either would make much money; one
even proclaimed at that year's ShoWest convention, ``Thou shalt not
Ontario each other.''
</P>
<P>
   AMC wound up building eight other 30-screen complexes, including
sites in Covina and Orange, but recently closed down six
auditoriums at its 30-plex in Kansas City in favor of restaurant
space. Its most recent announcement of a new theater called for 20
auditoriums with 4,000 seats in a Dallas suburb.
</P>
<P>
   As for Edwards, it also opened 22-screen plants in Brea and
Irvine and a 26-screen complex in Long Beach. But its most recent
expansion efforts have included much smaller properties such as the
six-screen Grand Palace Cinemas in Calabasas, which opened late
last year and occupies a mere 60 feet of frontage at the Tuscan
village-like Commons shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Caruso, chief of the firm that designed the Grand Palace
exterior, said communities prefer smaller theaters to megaplexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of Calabasas, the theater's size was driven by the
community not wanting a large project,'' he said. ``Operators want
more than six screens to make it more efficient, but I believe the
Grand Palace has become popular partly because of the small scale.
Our goal was to bring back the romance of going to the movies
instead of going to a large box and fighting crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   (Second take to come)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
