A2432 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEGAPLEX-DECLINE-2ndt     06-03 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEGAPLEX-DECLINE-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: fighting crowds.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Megaplexes _ defined as any theater with at least 16 auditoriums
_ will live on because of compelling economics. They are more
profitable at the snack bars and customers will often drive past
conventional theaters to get to a state-of-the-art one.
</P>
<P>
   But chains have taken on big debt loads to open hundreds of
megaplexes as they plowed profits into building programs that cost
$1million per screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall view in the exhibition business is that Act 1 is
now over and the period of aggressive building has come to a
close,'' said Kevin Skislock of Laguna Research Partners. ``The
question during Act 1 was when was saturation going to be reached
with all the good sites taken. There are only so many markets that
can support a 25- or 30-screen theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideal theater size may be somewhere between 14 and 20, Behr
asserts. ``When you drop below 14, you're vulnerable to someone
coming in and undermining you but when you get over 20, you don't
have that much advantage,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Behr points out, all the obvious places for
megaplexes have been filled in, leading to a focus on smaller
theaters. ``Secondary markets are going to be next, where you have
smaller populations and it doesn't warrant putting in Death
Star-type theaters,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude marks a huge change from a few years ago when
megaplexes were booming. Doug Brown, managing partner at Los
Angeles-based Regent Properties, recalls finding little enthusiasm
in 1996 when he first tried selling the idea of an ``urban
village'' center with an eight-to-10 screen theater at the run-down
area at Sunset and Vine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, we were calling possible tenants and they
were laughing at us,'' Brown said of the Hollywood Marketplace
development, due to break ground this summer. ``But what we're
finding now is when you do a large theater, it scares potential
retail tenants because they're concerned that customers won't be
able to find parking. So it makes sense to build something more
manageable.''
</P>
<P>
   What's replaced the megaplex as the industry's hot development
ticket? Developers now swoon over what's termed the entertainment
destination.
</P>
<P>
   Loews Cineplex, for example, is opening 15 theaters in mid-June
in San Francisco at Sony's massive Metreon, a cross between a theme
park, shopping mall and Sony marketing vehicle. Metreon includes
such offbeat attractions as The Way Things Work _ In Mammoth 3D. If
successful, Sony plans to roll out other Metreons around the world.
</P>
<P>
   New theaters are now often integrated into business districts
with powerful retailers. At the Marketplace in Glendale, a Mann
fourplex is surrounded by such draws as Gap, Borders, Tower and Old
Navy. ``What we were trying for is a fun village environment where
parents can bring their kids and spend four hours,'' said Brown,
who helped develop the project.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, developers are taking similar approaches at the
legendary Mann's Chinese Theatre and Pacific's Cinerama Dome, along
with the Hollywood Marketplace and the first theaters at Farmer's
Market. ``Downtowns got blighted because of the power of malls so
what those areas are now looking for are powerful retail tenants
and theaters that still have a village feel,'' Brown said. ``The
newer projects are the best of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Caruso, who is developing the Farmer's Market expansion, said
theater operators originally wanted up to 20 screens but the
project will likely contain 10 to 12. ``We don't want the theater
to overwhelm the rest of the project,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In short, moviegoers want more than a megaplex. ``Customers are
still looking for alternatives to driving out to the big box and
walking through a 20-acre parking lot,'' Behr said. ``That's not a
very rich experience.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
