<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE ENDING NO ATHLETE COULD WANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ If the Knicks can take a most improbable run to
a championship climax, at least Patrick Ewing will have his ring,
even if he is on the sidelines for most of the last two legs. At
least he will have been part of a team that would be long gone from
the playoffs if it weren't for him.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing won't have to die a thousand athlete's deaths, as Don
Mattingly did when the Yankees won the 1996 World Series the season
after he'd quit. Mattingly watched the Yankees take down the Braves
in his Evansville, Ind., home until there were two out in the ninth
inning of Game 6. Then he walked out of the room, leaving behind
his wife and children, not wanting them to see his ashen face.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Mattingly, the retired first baseman's wife, described this
moment to me a couple of winters ago, tears filling her somber blue
eyes. That, I remember thinking, had to be among the saddest of
sporting happenstances. This latest Ewing development has some of
that but may eventually be remembered more as another contentious
chapter in a continuing allegory that was carried too far.
</P>
<P>
   Along the journey from out of the playoffs into title
contention, Ewing the warrior became Ewing the martyr. Is it
coincidence that he sustained a partial tear of his Achilles'
tendon after 40 grueling and unrealistic minutes last Sunday
against Indiana in Game 1? The team physician, Norman Scott, said
it was exactly that _ a coincidence _ but under the circumstances,
what else could he say?
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird limits Rik Smits and his nerve-damaged feet to 32
minutes a night, when Smits doesn't foul out first. After Game 1 of
the conference final, Bird drawled that if Smits played 40 minutes,
we wouldn't see him for another two years.
</P>
<P>
   Bird is no doctor, and neither am I, but the timing of Ewing's
injury brings us back to when the Achilles' problem surfaced, after
an out-of-shape Ewing labored through major minutes of several
early-season games, including 43 one typically heated night in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, Jeff Van Gundy, was already feeling the fiery breath
of the general manager, Ernie Grunfeld, on his neck and was
overusing the player he trusted most. Van Gundy held a news
conference one night and played a little doctor himself, mocking
the notion that there was a bodily difference between playing 32
minutes and 40-plus. Days later, Ewing limped out of a game at
Madison Square Garden, and here we are, Ewing telling his teammates
Thursday that he believes in them and to go ahead and ``get me my
ring.'' The Knicks proceeded to promise an inspired, up-tempo
assault Saturday night at the Garden in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   With all the intramural shouting this season about the new
running game versus the old half-court game, you kept wishing that
Red Holzman were still around to clear his throat and remind
everyone that championship teams, in the end, have usually been
capable of executing both ways, as the Knicks demonstrated in Game
1.
</P>
<P>
   If that road victory turns out to be the difference in this
series, then Bird will be Indiana's goat for not removing Smits in
two late-game dead ball situations with the Pacers ahead by 5, then
3. On the first of those two Knick possessions, Bird compounded his
mistake by not double-teaming Ewing as he drove against Smits to
rescue the Knicks from the edge of the cliff. Smits had no mobility
and five fouls. On one leg, Ewing blew by him to the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that Patrick does is go at Smits and get him in foul
trouble,'' Van Gundy said, correctly worried that Smits won't have
to guard anyone the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Ewing's injuries gave him no choice, but he seemed to be
relishing his reduced part on this evolving team. He was no longer
the franchise but he had an important role, and it was better than
the role Mattingly chose in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's and Mattingly's careers ran similar courses,
statistically brilliant players whose teams lacked essential
championship components until their bodies were breaking down. In
his last season, Mattingly was stung by criticism that the Yankees
were better off without him. When they signed Tino Martinez, he
took his glove home, rather than refocus, become a spare part in
pursuit of a ring. He was never as hard-headed as Ewing and, as it
turned out, not as resolved. Ewing turned a deaf ear to it all,
fought off the pain, limped past Miami, kept going, right around
Smits near the end of Game 1, his last crucial basket in what could
still be that championship season.
</P>
<P>
   The ring will fit Ewing fine if the Knicks somehow win.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
