<HEADER>
A2437 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-US-REAX-ART-1S     06-03 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-REAX-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: symbolic presence.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was some confusion over whether the document given to
Milosevic _ and which was primarily drafted under the supervision
of the Deputy Secretary of State, Strobe Talbott _ was precisely
the same as that passed by the Serbian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The only difference, according to the State Department
spokesman, Rubin, was a footnote which was on the document given to
Milosevic but excluded in the document passed by the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The footnote dealt with differences between NATO and Russia over
participation of Russia in the international security force.
Russia, according to the footnote, did not agree to its soldiers
participating in the international security force that was under
NATO command and control.
</P>
<P>
   The footnote states that the force would have a unified NATO
chain of command under the political direction of the NATO
countries.
</P>
<P>
   If Russian soldiers participated in the force, they would do so
under arrangements to be made in the future, the administration
said. The State Department said that Ahtisaari explained to
Milosevic the meaning of the footnote and told the Yugoslav leader
that the question of Russian participation was a matter between
NATO and Russia and had no bearing on Yugoslavia. Milosevic,
according to this account, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   For the State Department, the next few days promised to be
tense: a waiting game to see if Milosevic would agree to codify his
acceptance in a formal military-to-military agreement worked out
between NATO and the Yugoslav Army.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The British general, Michael Jackson, who heads the NATO troops
already deployed in Macedonia as a vanguard for the international
security force, was expected to head a NATO military delegation
that would negotiate with the Yugoslav military, an administration
official said. The meeting likely would take place not in Belgrade,
but along one of Serbia's borders, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The terms under which the NATO bombing would be suspended were
the most critical steps in the coming days, administration
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This was because once the bombing was suspended it would be
extremely difficult to resume the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   A number of alliance members would resist a resumption. Further,
an administration official said, once the bombing stopped, refugees
were likely to start returning home, making a resumption of bombing
problematic.
</P>
<P>
   While officials said the bombardment would continue until a
verifiable withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo begins, they
indicated that the pace and breadth of the bombing would diminish
over the next several days as the final diplomatic details are
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONALT TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Allied warplanes will not attack retreating Serb soldiers, one
official said. ``Everybody understands we would not do anything to
impede the withdrawal of their forces,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the agreement ran from relief to scathing
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Sen.
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., lambasted the agreement as a ``so-called peace
deal'' which had been negotiated by the Russians, the European
Union and an indicted war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only acceptable deal with Slobodan Milosevic is one that
offers him safety in exile in exchange for his agreement to step
down and hand power to Serbian Democrats,'' Helms said in a
statement. ``Milosevic must be driven from power, vertically or
horizontally.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., has supported the air war but
has questioned whether air power alone would compel Milosevic to
capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he expressed satisfaction that Milosevic apparently
had given in to the core NATO conditions, relieving the United
States of the burden of planning and carrying out a ground
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that in fact we have achieved our objectives on the
ground from the air and achieved them at astonishingly low rate of
casualties. We did not lose a NATO soldier in combat,'' Lieberman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we have been victorious in turning back ethnic
aggression. It is very important for the stability and peace of
Europe, but also critically important for the credibility of NATO
and the United States as protectors of the rule of law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
