<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DON'T TRY NEW YORK'S TRIPLE CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Don't do it. Make believe Ed Koch is still the mayor
and repeat after me: ``Don't even think of trying it,'' with heavy
Kochian emphasis on the ``think.''
</P>
<P>
   What you should not attempt Saturday is attending all three
events in New York's own Triple Crown, one of the epic sporting
days in the region:
</P>
<P>
   At 1:15 p.m., the Mets and the Yankees will continue their
interleague series for the fans' right to say nyah-nyah for another
24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 p.m., the Knicks will play the Pacers in a vital playoff
game, without their injured captain, Patrick Ewing, as they
continue to embarrass top management, which was caught dickering
with another coach for next season.
</P>
<P>
   And in between, Secretariat's great grandson, Charismatic, will
try to win the Triple Crown of horse racing out at the Belmont on
the Queens-Nassau border.
</P>
<P>
   No horse has won racing's Triple Crown since 1978, but New
York's own Triple Crown would be even more demanding. Performing it
would be such a gross stunt that only somebody with absolutely no
taste, like a builder who puts his own name on all his projects,
would even attempt it.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you were into conspicuous consumption and wanted to pay
three-figure street prices for a baseball ticket and maybe even
four-figure street prices for a basketball ticket from the friendly
gents working the sidewalks of New York, you cannot get there from
here. Make that your mantra. It would be folly to try to watch even
the first six or seven innings of the Met-Yankee game and then
drive to Belmont. George Steinbrenner makes things up, but he is
not making it up about the traffic jams at the antiquated ball yard
in the Bronx. Sometimes it takes an hour just to get away from
161st Street.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you managed to get within striking distance of the
Belmont before post-time, the parking lots will already be jammed
from a potential crowd of 80,000, and latecomers will be forced to
park farther away than the mile-and-a-half distance of the Belmont
itself. Then it would be impossible to drive to the Garden remotely
close to 6:30 p.m., a starting time so ludicrous that only a
network could have come up with it. Nah. Fuhgeddaboutit.
</P>
<P>
   Mass transit? Nice idea, taking the IND or the IRT from the
Bronx to Penn Station and then the Long Island Rail Road out to the
Belmont, but, alas, the last special racing train from Penn Station
leaves at 12:55 p.m. (they want the bettors out early to do their
duty.)
</P>
<P>
   Anybody at the Belmont could catch a 6:09 p.m. train back to the
city right after the big race, arriving in the dismal basement
below the Garden at 6:41 p.m., just in time to catch Latrell
Sprewell take off his warm-ups and glare at Jeff Van Gundy for not
starting him.
</P>
<P>
   However, we are talking about catching all three events, which
probably involves a helicopter (does Trump have landing rights at
the Garden?) A limousine has already been done, for a Grand Slam of
New York sports dabbling.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1982, this very newspaper dispatched John Leonard into
the hinterlands to observe snippets of the Giants football game in
New Jersey, the Yankee game in what Leonard called ``East Berlin''
(the Cold War was still on), the Jets game in their old playground
at Shea, and then Jimmy Connors playing cock-of-the-walk at the
United States Open tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard managed the stunt with the help of a rented limousine,
and then concluded with the lament: ``At $30 an hour, couldn't I
have rented a brain? I didn't deserve a limousine. Nobody does.''
The Cold War is over, but Leonard's words are definitive. It's time
to make sane choices.
</P>
<P>
   Go Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   For $4 you can get into the clubhouse section and for $2 you can
mingle with the real people in the general admission. Come early.
Bring something electronic to follow the intramural ball game up in
the Bronx: a Cuban named Hernandez versus a Japanese named Yoshii.
Only in America.
</P>
<P>
   Go Belmont. There are real trees and real grass and you can
watch the horses being saddled in the paddock. Here's a dirty
little secret of racing: you don't have to bet. They cannot make
you. Also, bring a pair of binoculars to see if an imported filly
named Silverbulletday or one of the colts can keep Charismatic from
winning the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, let everybody else scurry to their cars for a
traffic jam worthy of Yankee Stadium. The people who run Belmont
Park have promised to put the Knicks game on the television sets
all over the stands. During those interminable television timeouts,
you can do a bit of honest stooping for discarded tickets. You
never know. By avoiding most of the traffic from New York's own
Triple Crown, you just might get lucky.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
