<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-FILLY-NYT     06-03 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-FILLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S IGNORING A MIGHTY TABOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a sweltering July afternoon and Bob Baffert
thought he was done buying horses. Before he climbed in his car,
however, he caught sight of a bay filly ready to enter the sales
ring. She wasn't on his shopping list. When he took a closer look,
he noticed her knees were off center. But the California trainer
was bowled over by her athletic look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we missed one,'' Baffert told his blood stock agents,
Kevin and J.B. McKathan, who have helped him find future racing
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes and $155,000 later, Baffert had bought
Silverbulletday for the owner Mike Pegram at the Fasig-Tipton sale
in Lexington, Ky. Now, two years and $2.2 million in winnings
later, Silverbulletday will try to become just the third filly _
the first since 1905 _ to win the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   She is a formidable challenger to Charismatic, the Kentucky
Derby and Preakness winner, who will be bidding to become the 12th
Triple Crown winner in history tomorrow. But by running
Silverbulletday in a one-and-a-half-mile test of endurance, Baffert
and Pegram are taking on one of horse racing's most fundamental
tenets: that fillies don't belong with the colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been taboo,'' Baffert said. ``The wisdom has been, why
take the chance when there are plenty of races for fillies. There's
the thought that colts are more developed at this time of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, there's no reason,'' said Baffert, sounding like an
iconoclast, before adding, ``If it wasn't a $1 million race, I
wouldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The battles between the sexes in horse racing have been around
from the beginning of the sport. In fact, the very first Belmont in
1867 was won by the filly Ruthless. But the debate about it has
gotten louder in more modern times, especially in the spring when
the rich Triple Crown races showcase the maturing 3-year-old
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Fillies rarely run against the colts. Even more rarely do they
win. Thirty-seven have run in the 125-year-old Kentucky Derby and
only three have won, the last being Winning Colors in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 927 Belmont starters in the 130-year history of the race,
Silverbulletday will be only the 21st filly to run. Baffert and
Pegram hope she joins Ruthless and the 1905 winner, Tanya, in the
record books. Those two fillies won the Belmont at different
distances _ Ruthless at the longer distance of 1| miles and Tanya
at a shorter distance of 1\ miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are physical differences,'' said John Nerud, the
86-year-old Hall of Fame trainer and breeder. ``Why don't women
play baseball against men? Because they aren't good enough. Why
don't they play football? They aren't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure why a filly can match a colt's time on a
stopwatch, but needs extraordinary talent to beat the opposite sex
in head-to-head competition. Dr. Ted Hill, a veterinarian, said
most of the evidence is anecdotal and encompasses a variety of
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, males are bigger and stronger,'' said Dr. Hill,
who is the Jockey Club steward at New York tracks. ``But there also
is a question of intimidation, especially when the filly is eye to
eye with a colt. There's an awful lot of energy and proximity when
the horses load in the gate. They are social and herd animals and
the male dominance may be intimidating.''
</P>
<P>
   In Silverbulletday, Baffert and Pegram have a champion filly who
has overwhelmed her own sex. She has won 11 of 12 races at five
different tracks _ including eight in a row _ each time as the
odds-on favorite. Her speed figures are higher than those of any
colt in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   In any given race, horses must overcome a variety of factors _
including post position, track bias, pace and racing luck. For
fillies, there's one more factor that doesn't affect colts _ during
spring and summer they come in heat every 20 days. Baffert said the
only time he noticed the affect of the cycle on Silverbulletday was
in March at the Fairgrounds in New Orleans. She ran a sluggish
race, he said, but still won by three lengths.
</P>
<P>
   In track parlance, Silverbulletday has earned the reputation as
a ``monster'' or ``freak'' because of how effortlessly she seems to
run. And win. In her last race, the Black Eyed Susan at Pimlico,
Silverbulletday came within three-fifths of a second of breaking
the track record for a mile and an eighth despite the fact her
jockey, Gary Stevens, never used his whip and just galloped her
home to a two-lengths victory. ``This is the only horse I've ever
seen who is cooled down by the time she gets to the winner's
circle,'' Baffert said. ``She is a push button horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and his rival, D.Wayne Lukas, who trains Charismatic,
both came from quarter-horse racing where colts against fillies is
more common. Lukas marshaled Winning Colors from her Derby victory
to a third-place finish at the Preakness and a last-place finish at
the Belmont. He respects Silverbulletday and Baffert's attempt to
capture the race, but said that Winning Colors was tested against
the colts before her Derby triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's had a cupcake schedule,'' Lukas said of Silverbulletday.
``We'll see what happens when she is tested.''
</P>
<P>
   The filly, however, has her backers. Cynthia McGinnes, an owner
and breeder in Maryland, applauds Baffert and Pegram for entering
Silverbulletday in the Belmont when there is little reward. She
watched the filly roll at Pimlico and believes she is the best
3-year-old regardless of sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sporting because it's back to the essence of the sport,''
she said. ``Who has the fastest horse. She is a Secretariat type of
filly and I don't think the colts are that outstanding of a
group.''
</P>
<P>
   If Silverbulletday wins, there is no guarantee that it will
increase her value beyond the $600,000 first-place money. While big
victories enhance the value of stud fees for colts, it does little
for potential broodmares.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Baffert nor Pegram are thinking beyond tomorrow.
They believe they have a fast horse who can get the distance and
gun down the competition. Period.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert can even envision a duel down the stretch between
Silverbulletday and Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see him pulling eye to eye with her,'' Baffert said.
``Then he falls in love and doesn't pass her.''
</P>
<P>
   Much like Baffert did two years ago in a sales ring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
