<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY GAMES, WITH A DASH OF MUSTARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There will be pressure on the Mets to emerge from
their deepest slump of the season against a superior team in enemy
territory. There will be pressure on the Yankees to show they are
the best team in the five boroughs and to satisfy George
Steinbrenner. There will be pressure for three hectic days at
Yankee Stadium because it is New York against New York in baseball
and there is really nothing else that compares.
</P>
<P>
   Leave work early, make sure the babysitter is prompt and take
mass transit. Be prepared. Wear Derek Jeter's jersey and boo
Armando Benitez if you are a Yankee fan. Wear Mike Piazza's jersey
and, since Hideki Irabu is not likely to pitch, pick another Yankee
to chastise if you are a Mets fan. Laugh at the bleacher denizens
if you love Paul O'Neill. Stay away from them if you have a Benny
Agbayani cheer lurking in your lungs.
</P>
<P>
   The series features a second-place club that is slowly surging
and a third-place club that is quickly crumbling and it could be
considered a blip on the 162-game regular-season schedule, but it
is an event that has been and will be talked about for weeks. The
majority of the 170,000 tickets for the three games sold out
swiftly, more than 250 news media credentials have been issued and
both teams have had their advance scouts studying each other's
pitches, swings and signs for close to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost as if the city commands you to stop and make this
a big series,'' David Cone said. ``Everyone's into it. The city is
excited. I don't think the fans can get enough of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who will oppose the Mets' Rick Reed in the opener Friday
night, understands the rivalry between the Yankees and the Mets and
between their fans as much as anyone since he has pitched for both
teams and is one of the handful of players who has lived in
Manhattan. More than any other player, he knows both organizations,
knows what both teams' fans are like and knows why these three
games and three more at Shea Stadium in July, though draining for
players who are more concerned with the Red Sox or the Braves
respectively, are important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know after playing three games at Shea last year, our
players were glad to see it was over,'' Cone said. ``There was
intense scrutiny, high stress and high drama at a time of the
season when you're trying to play it day by day. But it's for the
fans and I'm sure they will see six games as a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Joe Torre acknowledged the importance of the matchup
for fans, the first thing the manager said when asked about playing
the Mets was, ``I hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how Bobby Valentine and the Mets feel. They have to face
the Yankees' three best starters in Cone, Orlando Hernandez and
Roger Clemens, they have to do it in a hostile environment and they
have to do it while they are searching for their first victory in a
week. Obviously, the Yankees are not invincible, as they seemed to
be last year, and are not as crisp as they would like to be,
despite winning 8 of their last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   But the defending World Series champions have the advantage in
all the pitching matchups, especially since the Mets' five primary
starters have a 17-19 record and a 5.67 earned run average. Still,
the Mets, who might be helped by using a designated hitter like
Bobby Bonilla in the American League park, hope that the spotlight
jostles them out of their six-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I think we'll need,'' Mike Piazza said. ``There
will definitely be a little bit of a shot of adrenaline, a little
shot of electricity. Hopefully it will be like another opening day
for us. We can turn the page and get going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will try to turn the page Friday night. The Yankees
will try to stop them. It will be a fight between two teams who are
not competitors in their own divisions, but who are fierce
competitors everywhere else. There will be dueling fans and feuding
fans as two teams who usually catch only glimpses of each other on
television play amidst the pressure and skirmish for the pride of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play the Mets, that's the media World Series,''
O'Neill said. ``It just kind of goes on and on. I don't think we've
played our best baseball. Maybe we need something like this to get
us going. There are a lot bigger games down the road with us,
especially in September and October. Some of the attention and
stuff gets to you with this, but this is a fun atmosphere. Just put
it that way. It's a fun atmosphere to play in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
