<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING'S ABSENCE MAKES THE PACERS THINK AGAIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Reggie Miller said winning the Eastern Conference
finals may be more difficult for the Indiana Pacers now that
Patrick Ewing is out for the year. Antonio Davis chimed in that the
Knicks may be more motivated after losing the cornerstone of their
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   As the Indiana Pacers resumed preparation Friday for Game 3 on
Saturday at Madison Square Garden, the prevailing sentiment on
Ewing's season-ending injury was offered by Mark Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not a better team without Patrick Ewing; let's get
that out of the way,'' Jackson, the Pacers' point guard, said.
``They can still win without him but they're certainly not better.
They're missing a Hall of Fame center, a guy who requires your
undivided attention when he's in the game and catches it on the
post. They'll miss that. They'll miss his presence. But they still
have capable, quality guys that can hurt you. They can still win.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after Ewing was diagnosed with a partial tear in his
left Achilles' tendon, Coach Larry Bird began preparing the Pacers
for a sleeker, revved-up version of a Knicks team that could
present problems for Indiana in transition.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Pacers is Rik Smits. The 7-foot-4-inch
center fouled out of the first two games trying to stop Ewing and
now he may spend more energy concentrating on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to stay in the game to help us,'' Bird said.
``Hopefully we'll be able to keep him in the game a little longer
because he's been playing great defense for us. He's been giving a
lot of help so we want to keep him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird befriended Ewing when they were teammates at the 1992
Olympic Games in Barcelona, Spain. Much the same way he wanted
Michael Jordan to be the measuring stick for his team this season,
Bird regretted that Ewing would not be on the floor to help decide
the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for Patrick,'' Bird said. ``His career is winding
down and he had a legitimate shot to win the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird added: ``I don't know if they're better but obviously
they'll come out and they'll play well. They've been playing
without Patrick a little bit this year, so they'll know what to
expect. They'll be running a little bit more and be driving and
kicking and trying to hit the open shooters. But our defense has to
toughen up.''
</P>
<P>
   The sideline chess match is altered significantly by Ewing's
injury. While the 6-11 Chris Dudley is expected to start in Ewing's
place, the Knicks will try to counter the Pacers' size advantage by
trying to seize an advantage on the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they go small, we go big,'' Bird said. ``Let them stay
small. We're going to try to establish inside position because it
opens up the outside for other players. They've been doubling
Reggie off every pick and roll, which we like. So we're just going
to punch it down low and keep driving it at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said, ``They'll run more, so it's up to us to get back
faster and not let them get out on the break.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are 7-5 without Ewing this season and 28-28 last
season while he was rehabilitating a broken wrist. Liberated from a
low-post game, many of his more-athletic teammates often flourish
early on in Ewing's absence before discovering how much they miss
an offensive-minded center.
</P>
<P>
   Against a more physical and taller Pacers team, Ewing's loss may
be even more compounded. Asked if, in fact, the Knicks were a
better team without Ewing, Bird said: ``No, not at all. I think
with Patrick Ewing in there they're a lot better. You've seen at
the end of games here in our series, every time they needed a
basket down the stretch they went to Patrick.''
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose, the Pacers' sixth man, said: ``A lot of people were
talking during the season about them being a better team without
Patrick. Now we'll have a chance to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
