<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2453 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-03 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS' DEFENSE: TORTURER ACTED ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the final day of arguments in the Abner Louima
police brutality case, the lawyer for a police officer charged with
holding Louima down while Justin A. Volpe tortured him declared
Thursday that his client was the victim of an unjustified attempt
to widen the case beyond ``one sick, depraved'' officer.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the officer, Charles Schwarz, sought to convince
the jurors in Federal District Court in Brooklyn that Schwarz had
not joined in the attack with Volpe, who has admitted that he
jammed a stick into Louima's rectum in a restroom at a Brooklyn
police station two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe said as he entered his guilty plea last week that another
officer, whom he did not identify, had been in the restroom with
him. He described the other officer only as someone who ``saw what
was going on'' and ``did nothing to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in responding to the prosecution charge that the other
officer was Schwarz, his lawyer, Stephen C. Worth, said that
Schwarz was not in the restroom at all, and argued that the
prosecution had sought to expand the case to show that police
brutality went beyond ``a few bad apples'' like Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has been tried to be made into this culture of
police brutality, and it never was,'' Worth said, holding that the
case involved a form of ``rape'' that a single officer had
committed against a prisoner in ``some kind of sick rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth's closing arguments reflected statements on Wednesday in
which defense lawyers for two of the other three officers on trial
and the prosecution invoked Volpe's name to their own ends. Neither
side called Volpe as a witness, saying they believed he had no
credibility, but the prosecution used its closing arguments to
portray Volpe as the ``driving force'' behind the crimes against
Louima, while defense lawyers used theirs to suggest to the jury
that the only guilty officer had come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Worth continued that argument Thursday. He said that Louima
``has been vindicated'' by Volpe's plea and that the jury should
now vindicate Schwarz by acquitting him.
</P>
<P>
   The jury is expected to begin deliberations in the case Friday.
The others on trial include Officers Thomas Wiese and Thomas
Bruder, who prosecutors say joined Volpe and Schwarz in beating
Louima in a police car after he was arrested in a street brawl in
Flatbush, Brooklyn, in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Michael Bellomo is charged with trying to cover up the
alleged beating in the police car and Volpe's assault of a second
man, Patrick Antoine, in the area of the melee.
</P>
<P>
   The case has had bitter racial overtones from the time that
Louima, who is black, first accused the officers, who are white, of
brutalizing him.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in giving the final prosecution argument, Loretta E.
Lynch, chief assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, contended that
Wiese had ``tried to hide behind the color of his girlfriend's
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a response to a defense argument Wednesday, and earlier
in the trial, that Wiese's fiancee, a black woman, would not ``have
had a child with him and moved in with him and become his fiancee''
if he had been the kind of man who used racial slurs, as Louima had
earlier testified to a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Lynch criticized the argument Thursday, a woman sitting
with relatives and friends of Wiese in the packed courtroom gallery
said, ``Oh, come on!'' Later, members of the group complained to
Ms. Lynch's boss, Zachary W. Carter, the United States attorney,
who was also sitting in the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese's lawyers asked Judge Eugene H. Nickerson to declare a
mistrial, arguing that Ms. Lynch's comment could create prejudice
against the officer.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said they considered it proper for them to refer to
the officer's fiancee in the context of refuting Louima's
accusation.
</P>
<P>
   In his summation, Worth also assailed Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn M.
Kornberg, for his suggestion in his opening argument in the case a
month ago that Louima's severe internal injuries _ a torn rectum
and bladder _ had been caused not by Volpe's attack with the stick
but by a consensual sex act with another man.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion, Worth said, was ``despicable and, frankly,
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was insulting to you and it was insulting to us and it was
insulting and offensive to Abner Louima,'' he told the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg, who has not been in the courtroom since Volpe pleaded
guilty last week and was jailed, said later, ``Every lawyer has to
say and do what's best for his client's interests, and that
certainly goes for Steve Worth during his summation, although he
did not take that position at the beginning of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo's lawyer, John Patten, said in his closing argument
Thursday that rather than trying to cover anything up, the sergeant
had made ``honest mistakes'' in his reports about what had happened
in the chaotic street melee in which Louima and Antoine were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's here because the prosecution needed to have a boss in the
case,'' he said, referring to Bellomo's rank as a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lynch responded that Bellomo was being tried not ``because
of his rank,'' but because of his efforts to cover up illegal
assaults by his officers and then hide his original cover-up
attempt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
