<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHE TO PAY $4.2 BILLION FOR THE REST OF GENENTECH
</P>
<P>
   Roche Holding, the European drug maker, said that it would
exercise its right to buy the 33 percent of Genentech it does not
already own for $82.50 a share, or $4.2 billion. Roche will then
issue new shares equivalent to as much as 19 percent of Genentech,
the pioneering biotechnology company, so the company can continue
to be publicly traded. Analysts said the transaction was good for
Roche, which should realize a gain when it sells shares, and good
for Genentech, which retains its quasi-independent status. But it
is not so good for stockholders because shares have been as high as
$90 over the last year. They fell $4.50, to $82, on the news.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES INCREASED 5.6 PERCENT IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Sales in retail stores open at least a year rose 5.6 percent in
May as consumers continued to show great confidence in the economy
by snatching up everything from wardrobes in summer white to pool
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS MIXED AHEAD OF JOBS REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices were mixed as traders and investors awaited
Friday's release of the government's monthly report on the job
market for May. The Nasdaq composite index finished with a loss of
29.09 points, or 1.2 percent, to 2,403.32. The Dow Jones industrial
average surged in the final 15 minutes of trading and ended with a
gain of 85.80 points, or 0.8 percent, to 10,663.69. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index ended with a gain of 4.73 points, or 0.4
percent, to 1,299.54.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT SCRUTINIZES TESTIMONY
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Microsoft questioned the credibility of James
Barksdale, the chief executive of Netscape, in the rebuttal phase
of the software giant's antitrust trial. The apparent
inconsistencies between Barksdale's testimony last fall and
statements out of court caught the attention of Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson _ so much so that the judge urged a government
lawyer to take account of them in court.
</P>
<P>
   NEW PUBLISHER AT LOS ANGELES TIMES
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Downing was named publisher of The Los Angeles Times,
taking over from Mark Willes, who remains chairman and chief
executive of the paper's parent, Times Mirror. Ms. Downing, the
paper's president for the last 14 months, was hand-picked by Willes
as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   SANCTIONS SOUGHT IN BEEF DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   A trans-Atlantic fight over hormone-treated beef intensified
when U. S. and Canadian officials asked the World Trade
Organization to approve $253 million in retaliatory trade sanctions
and the European Union countered by demanding arbitration that it
hopes will lower the overall amount.
</P>
<P>
   FACTORY ORDERS ROSE 0.5 PERCENT IN APRIL
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders rose 0.5 percent in April, excluding demand at
aircraft makers, the fifth increase in the last six months,
Commerce Department figures showed. Overall orders fell 1.2 percent
during the month after declining 0.6 percent in March. In a
separate report, initial jobless claims rose 4,000, to 305,000,
last week.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA TIGHTENS CONTROL OF CURRENCY
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese authorities announced that they were tightening
control over international transfers of the yuan, the nation's
currency. The news rekindled fear about a devaluation, but the
People's Bank of China denied any such plans.
</P>
<P>
   NEW GLOBAL BANKING RULES PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   The top global banking regulator introduced proposals that would
strengthen protections against bad loans and subject the
risk-assessment operations of big international banks to greater
supervision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
