<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: METS SINK INTO MIRE OF UNMET EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About those plans to watch the Subway Series in
October, better plan instead to watch the Mets and the Yankees this
weekend and July 9-11 and save October for watching the leaves
change colors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tarnish on the legendary status they gained last
season, the Yankees will play in October. Even if the Boston Red
Sox should somehow continue playing well over their heads and gain
revenge for 1978, the Yankees are virtually guaranteed a spot in
the playoffs. No one in their own division or either of the other
divisions would beat them out of the wild-card entry.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets are another matter. The Mets once again have
promised more than they can deliver. They have fooled their fans
and themselves before, and here they have gone and done it again.
</P>
<P>
   The team that was going to challenge the perennial champions of
their division or, at the least, snatch the wild-card spot is
stumbling all over itself. A third of the way through the season,
the Mets are 27-26 and have established only that the race they are
running in is the one with the Los Angeles Dodgers to see which can
be the league's most disappointing and underachieving team.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets await Friday night's start of their first three-game
interleague series with the Yankees, five National League teams
that aren't in first place, four in the supposedly weaker Central
Division alone, have better records. That's a lot of company for a
wild-card race even if the season has four months to run.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Mets put together a team they thought worthy
of post-season play, the manager, Jeff Torborg, paid for their
miscalculation. He wasn't fired that season, 1992, but that was his
first with the Mets. He was, however, gone after 38 games of the
1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   No one has suggested that a repeat of that act is being
contemplated this season, but Bobby Valentine is in the classic
dismissal position. The Mets have a $63.5 million payroll, eighth
highest in the major leagues; they made moves during the winter
designed to improve the team and they are playing poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow we have to shake it up to get it back on track,''
general manager Steve Phillips said on the telephone Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He had not been asked about Valentine's status, and he
presumably was not alluding to Valentine's status, but teams have
been known to fire their manager to shake things up and get the
team back on track, especially when they feel they should be on the
track headed for first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The likelihood,'' Phillips added, ``is the solutions are from
within because there aren't any solutions from without.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager, it is well known, does not hit for the hitters and
he does not pitch for the pitchers. Injuries generally are beyond
his control. Nevertheless, managers are fired all the time when a
team underachieves, especially an expensive team.
</P>
<P>
   With the Atlanta Braves suddenly looking vulnerable under the
weight of the uncharacteristically ineffective pitching of Greg
Maddux and Tom Glavine, the Mets had a wonderful opportunity to
establish their credentials as replacement champions.
</P>
<P>
   But they failed to take advantage of Atlanta's problems,
spiraled into a skid of their own and plummeted five games behind
the Braves. Rather than resemble a challenger for the Braves'
perennial division championship, the Mets have more readily evoked
memories of 1962, the year of the 40-120 record.
</P>
<P>
   With the sweeps by Arizona and Cincinnati, the Mets lost
successive three-game series at home for the first time since 1962.
In May, the pitchers compiled a 5.71 earned run average. Only once
before, according to the Elias Sports Bureau, had the Mets' staff
produced a higher ERA in a calendar month. The ERA was 6.32; the
month was the first of their existence, April 1962.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, the Mets did not have a $63.5 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   If Valentine survives the team he has been unable to spark and
the Mets don't supplant the Braves, he will solidify his rank among
managers who have never finished first. With 65 more games _
concluding Aug. 14 in San Francisco, barring rainouts _ Valentine
will supplant Jimmy McAleer (1901-11) as No. 3 on that list.
Valentine will have managed 1,659 games without a winner and will
have only Paul Richards (1,837) and Jimmy Dykes (2,962) ahead of
him.
</P>
<P>
   As if the team's shortcomings haven't created enough problems,
Valentine has more people in baseball pulling against him than any
other individual. Brian McRae, the Mets' center fielder, raised
that issue after a late-season loss last year, and others have
brought attention to it this season.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Arizona Diamondbacks said that one of their
pitchers wanted ``to go after'' Valentine last Saturday when the
manager questioned the glove of the team's 20-year-old relief
pitcher, Byung Hyun Kim. Then Cincinnati manager Jack McKeon
questioned Jason Isringhausen's glove as he was about to pitch
against the Reds on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips prefers to focus on the races, division and wild-card.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're five behind the Braves and three behind the Cubs,'' he
said. ``It's not like we've buried ourselves. This is a test to see
how strong we are. We have our work cut out for us. We're going
into Yankeetown and that's not an easy task for us.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets emerge having been swept for a third successive
series, October won't come soon enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
