<HEADLINE>
CROMBIE TAYLOR, ARCHITECT WHO HELPED CHAMPION BAUHAUS, DIES AT 85  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J., Ill., Calif.)   By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crombie Taylor, an architect and teacher who helped spread the
influence of the Bauhaus to American architecture during the 1940s,
died on May 24. He was 85 and lived in Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Oakmont, Pa., Taylor was educated at Penn State and
Princeton University. In 1944 he joined the Institute of Design, a
Chicago school founded by a former Bauhaus instructor, Laszlo
Moholy-Nagy. The school was a successor to the New Bauhaus, so
called because its faculty included prominent refugees from Nazi
Germany. After Moholy-Nagy's death in 1946 Taylor became assistant
director to the designer Serge Chermayeff.
</P>
<P>
   While in Chicago, Taylor became a passionate enthusiast of the
work of Louis Sullivan, a pioneer of modern skyscraper design and
the mentor of Frank Lloyd Wright. Taylor was instrumental in the
restoration of interior spaces at Sullivan's Auditorium Building at
Roosevelt University in Chicago. The Chicago architect John Vinci,
Taylor's student at the time, said his restoration of the
building's banquet hall in 1967 was ``a revelation that introduced
a new way of thinking about Sullivan.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's work included unearthing Sullivan's long-neglected
polychromatic stencils for the auditorium's ceilings and walls.
Taylor had recently completed a book on Sullivan's work, written in
collaboration with Jeffrey Plank. It is to be published next year
by Harry N. Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's own architectural work was spare, in the manner of Mies
van der Rohe, but distinguished by interiors furnished with 18th-
and 19th-century antiques. In 1973 Taylor was elected a fellow of
the American Institute of Architects.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Hope; three children, Victoria
Taylor of Los Angeles, Beth Fergon of Monterey, Calif., and John
Taylor of Santa Barbara, and two grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
