<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TV-SPORTS-SANDOMIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CHARISMATIC SEEKS THE TRIPLE CROWN, ABC IS SMILING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silver Charm proved it. So did Real Quiet. If you're a horse,
and you've won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes, you can
boost ABC's Belmont Stakes ratings by showing up and looking
competitive. You don't even have to win, although the Triple Crown
means nice cash and plenty of gourmet oats.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Real Quiet's loss by a nose to Victory Gallop
elevated the Belmont's Nielsen rating to a 5.9 from a 5.3 for
Silver Charm's loss in 1997 by three-quarters of length. The year
before, when the Kentucky Derby winner, Grindstone, skipped the
Preakness because of a knee injury, the Belmont rated a 2.9.
</P>
<P>
   Two consecutive near-Triple Crown winners emboldened Al Michaels
of ABC Sports to say, ``I don't know how we'd handle the Belmont if
this were not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to get giddy when an equine nears Visa's $5 million
bonus. If Charismatic runs away from the pack, might ESPN amend its
list of the century's 100 greatest North American athletes?
Secretariat's place is secure at No. 35.
</P>
<P>
   ABC will focus on Charismatic's gallop to glory/disappointment
with 37 cameras, including two isolated on him, and some others on
his owners, trainer and chiropodist. The vehicle-borne ``Ben-Hur''
camera will follow the race from an access road inside the track.
Whether a victory by Charismatic can solve all of thoroughbred
racing's ills is uncertain. Newly created fans will probably not
follow him around the country and jam tracks. He's only one horse!
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to get too far ahead,'' said Tim Smith, commissioner
of the National Thoroughbred Racing Association, ``but if he wins
the Triple Crown, he could run several more times this year and
there'd be a lot of celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic could star in the Breeders' Cup, shoot a layout for
Cigar Aficionado and ink licensing deals. Actually, his handlers
have cut a licensing deal with the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association, which is selling his T-shirts and caps. But if he wins
Saturday, Charismatic will not wear the officially licensed locker
room cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Cigar's victory tour, he traveled the country and
people wanted to see him,'' said Smith. ``It was a little like
McGwire and Sosa.''
</P>
<P>
   As he ages, Charismatic could take advantage of the thoroughbred
association's plans. ``We're trying to harness the great public
relations of the Triple Crown by setting up a series for older
horses,'' said Smith. May I suggest the AARP Handicap?
</P>
<P>
   The experience of two potential Triple Crown winners has caused
the Belmont to expand its marketing. ``The last couple of years, we
decided to spend a couple of hundred thousand dollars on ads only
after the Preakness,'' said Terence Meyocks, president of the New
York Racing Association. ``This year, we decided no matter what,
we'd spend it, Triple Crown or not.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is unworried about competition coming from the
Mets-Yankees and the Pacers-Knicks games. ``I've gotten hundreds of
requests from people who never would have thought of coming but are
coming Saturday,'' he said. ``People sense there is something
special here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
