<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUEHNE'S LEADS BY 1 IN U.S. WOMEN'S OPEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ It was 90 degrees in the shade, but Kelli
Kuehne's performance was even hotter.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with poise and precision, and displaying the talent that
carried her to U.S. Amateur championships in 1995 and 1996, Kuehne
stole the first-round spotlight Thursday at the U.S. Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting the second-best round in Open history, and setting a
course record at Old Waverly Golf Club, Kuehne finished with an
8-under par 64. That was one stroke better than Juli Inkster and
three strokes better than Moira Dunn, who was at 67.
</P>
<P>
   Se Ri Pak, the defending champion, was tied for fourth place
(68) with Dottie Pepper and Sherri Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Kelli Kuehne many expected to see last year, when
she joined the LPGA Tour at age 21, backed by a lucrative contract
from Nike and carrying great expectations after a splendid amateur
career. But Kuehne struggled as a rookie, earning just $39,831 and
finishing 124th on the money list.
</P>
<P>
   She returned this year with a fresh attitude, a better game and
an insulin pump she wears on her waist while playing, which has
enabled her to cope better with the diabetes condition she has had
since age 10.
</P>
<P>
   After winning her first professional tournament on Sunday, the
LPGA Corning Classic, Kuehne entered this week with momentum. Is
Kuehne ready to win a U.S. Open at age 22? Didn't Pak win last year
at age 20?
</P>
<P>
   ``My driving was solid, my irons were sharp, and my putting was
true,'' said Kuehne, who needed only 25 putts during her round.
``I've been playing really well and I came here this week with a
lot of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this course is in unbelievable shape. If you pick the
right line, you can make a lot of putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne fell one stroke short of the Open record 63 shot by Helen
Alfredsson in 1994 during the first round at Indianwood Golf and
Country Club in Lake Orion, Mich. But that was a par-71 course, so
Kuehne's 8-under Thursday matched Alfredsson's 8-under.
</P>
<P>
   Making eight birdies during a bogey-free round, Kuehne's putting
stroke was the key. She set the tone at No. 1 by making a 30-footer
for birdie, and later she made another 30-footer at the 12th hole,
and an 18-footer at the 15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   When Kuehne made four consecutive birdies at the sixth through
ninth holes and made the turn at 5-under par, the leader board was
filled with red numbers. The Open is not usually a birdie-fest, but
with the greens softened by heavy rains Wednesday, and with the
rough at Old Waverly lower than most Opens, players kept firing at
pins and making putts.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest obstacle was the heat, as 90-degree afternoon
temperatures, coupled with 60-degree humidity, led to a heat index
of 99. However, no player looked cooler than Kuehne, who at 5 feet
2 inches averages about 245 yards off the tee, and held her own on
one of the longer-playing Open courses.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne was virtually raised on a course, part of a remarkable
golfing family from Dallas. Her oldest brother, Trip, finished
second to Tiger Woods at the 1995 U.S. Amateur. Her 23-year-old
brother, Hank, is the reigning U.S. Amateur champion, and he will
turn professional when he leaves SMU this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne's parents, Ernie and Pam, followed their daughter with
pride Thursday, and smiled with every birdie. ``She put a lot of
pressure on herself last year,'' her father said. ``It was tough
for her. But she's really coming on now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelli admitted as much earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know I still have the same instinct I had during
my amateur days because that's been missing for a while,'' Kuehne
said. ``I've struggled as a pro. The most frustrating thing is that
I have not played to my potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came out here, it was great that I had a great amateur
record, but it didn't do anything for me. I needed to earn the
respect of my peers. It's something I had to reestablish this year
by playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuehne continued to earn that respect Thursday, but with proved
winners like Inkster, Pepper, and Pak lurking in contention, the
tournament was just beginning. Yet Kuehne's round was one to savor.
And she hoped the best was yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I wanted to show everyone I belonged out here and
that I could play,'' Kuehne said. ``That dug me into a hole. Then
you realize that you have nothing to prove except to yourself. Last
year wasn't much fun. It was growing pains. But now, I feel great
about my game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
