r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COL-KAN &LR;      06-03 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES IN CREDIT CARD ABUSE GAME NEED BETTER CONTROLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there are two groups that deserve each other, it's those who
abuse credit cards and the companies that market them
irresponsibly.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Consumer Federation of America survey showed three of
four respondents saying credit card issuers bear at least part of
the blame for the surge of bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
   The respondents are right, and so was the federation's executive
director when he called the credit card industry ``shameless'' for
pushing tighter bankruptcy restrictions ``while they aggressively
market and extend credit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aggressively'' is too mild a characterization, though, given
the flood of credit card applications that daily choke most
mailboxes. Hardly a week goes by at Chez Heaster without at least a
half-dozen or so pitches arriving, most with teaser rates of under
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It's strictly a numbers game. Send out X jillion applications,
get Y percent acceptances, figure Z respondents will be deadbeats,
and set charges on outstanding balances high enough to recoup the
anticipated breakage. A prominent Kansas City banker likes to call
it ``lending to the telephone book,'' and, as far as can be
determined, his bank has never had much luck with this approach to
marketing credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting, however, that deadbeat credit card users are
just as culpable in this game as the cynical mass merchandisers of
credit cards. While issuers rig the game to ensure that responsible
borrowers often pay outrageous carrying costs to subsidize
deadbeats, equally cynical card users live far beyond their means
with no intention of ever fully paying their debts.
</P>
<P>
   What's really crazy about this arrangement is that the more
lenders complain about the need for tighter bankruptcy strictures,
the more intensely they pursue customers, heedless of credit risks.
This has been the trend since a broad liberalization of bankruptcy
law in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, if lawmakers sincerely want to balance everyone's
interests, including those of responsible credit card users, they
need to go beyond traditional remedies.
</P>
<P>
   What's needed is a law mitigating against the moral hazard
problem as it relates to irresponsible lenders and debtors alike.
This means structuring the relationship to create a canceling-out
effect for reckless behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say Don Deadbeat files for bankruptcy as a result of
overwhelming credit card abuse. The legal factor determining how
much relief the lender should be allowed would depend on the
prudence used by the lender during the approval process.
</P>
<P>
   Did the lender use due diligence checking the applicant's
character and capacity to pay? If not, the lender shouldn't be
allowed any relief. If the lender did use adequate due diligence,
was the borrower honest and truthful on the card application? If
not, any relief accorded the bankrupt in any judgment should be
minimal. Moreover, criminal charges should be an option for
particularly egregious cases of dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   The current approach won't solve the problem, because it's a
blame game involving two equally irresponsible parties. Thus, the
real losers are those who get stuck with interest rates higher than
otherwise would be the case in the absence of such
irresponsibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990603.0539 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
