<HEADER>
A2594 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUKE-KAN &LR;      06-03 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC HOSPITAL AGREES TO LET DOCTORS GROUP OPERATE HEART INSTITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _  &LR; by2:The Kansas City Star  &LR; tx:Cardiovascular
Consultants, a doctors group, will operate St. Luke's Hospital's
Mid-America Heart Institute under a management contract that is
expected to be signed around July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physician collaboration is both a basic and historic tenet of
the St. Luke's-Shawnee Mission Health System,'' said G. Richard
Hastings, president and chief executive officer of the system. ``We
believe it is the most effective way of providing quality health
care at an affordable cost.''
</P>
<P>
   No assets will change hands, and the heart institute will
continue to be owned by St. Luke's. David Steinhaus, a cardiologist
and president of Cardiovascular Consultants, said the group would
receive a management fee to operate the institute. Steinhaus will
become the institute's medical director for cardiovascular
services.
</P>
<P>
   Financial details of the transaction were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes amid rising demand for specialty medical
care. In response to that demand and other market factors,
hospitals around the country have been forging management
agreements with specialty physician groups.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, at St. Luke's midtown campus, opened in 1982. A
record 112 open-heart surgeries were performed there in April, and
the institute expects to perform its 200th heart transplant soon.
</P>
<P>
   Cardiovascular Consultants is a group of 22 cardiologists who
primarily practice at the institute.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhaus said the agreement, which has been under discussion
for about 18 months, would not impede those cardiologists at the
institute who are not part of Cardiovascular Consultants. Patients
who see those doctors should expect to continue seeing them, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, our hope is that their practice will be enhanced,''
Steinhaus said.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhaus said about 10 key staff members of the institute would
become employees of the doctors group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to concentrate on quality of care, cost
efficiencies and program development,'' he said. ``We hope to make
it more consumer-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinhaus said he hoped cost efficiencies realized from the new
arrangement would lead to more agreements with managed-care
companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
