<HEADER>
A2599 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KC-WATER-TAKEOVER-KAN     06-03 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-WATER-TAKEOVER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS, MINISTERS QUESTION KC MAYOR ABOUT REPORT ON WATER
DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GROMER JEFFERS JR.  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Angry city workers and area ministers
confronted Mayor Kay Barnes on Thursday, demanding that she explain
her relationship and that of her top campaign consultant with a
company that wanted to buy or manage the Water Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded at City Hall by about 100 workers and other
protesters, state Rep. Terry Riley of Kansas City also asked for a
federal investigation and for Barnes to step down as mayor, a
request that Barnes later called ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Barnes campaigned on honesty and integrity,'' Riley
said. ``But after only a few weeks in office she has shown us that
she is not trustworthy. She is not for the poor people of this
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters _ some holding signs that read ``KC's Watergate'' and
``City Hall for Sale'' _ included several black ministers and
activists who supported Barnes during her mayoral campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said she had done ``absolutely nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I resent deeply any implication by the press or by anyone else
that I have done something wrong,'' Barnes said in an interview
after Thursday's council meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said she has never supported selling or privatizing the
Water Services Department. She said she has only supported an
exploration of options for a public//private partnership, which
might extend to the department's management or marketing or other
duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water department may be fine just the way it is,'' Barnes
said. ``I have not had any discussions publicly or privately about
selling the water department. If it came up at this point, I would
be opposed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   /{The Kansas City Star/} reported last week that political
consultant Pat Gray, while working on Barnes' mayoral campaign, was
working for a St. Louis company to develop a plan to buy or manage
the Water Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   A document outlining a plan for taking over the operations of
the Water Services Department was obtained by /{The Star/}. It
included a strategy to elect a mayor and council that favored
privatization of city services and a plan to discredit the
department's reputation so the public would support a private
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The document obtained by /{The Star/} anonymously through the
mail called for the Water Services Department to be sold or leased
by Nov. 1, 1999, to EA2//Systems, a consortium of three companies
that includes Environmental Management Inc. of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Gray has said the document could have been stolen from his
office or altered, and he declined comment on it. He could not be
reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes acknowledged Thursday that she had a 45-minute meeting
with Gray and officials from EA2//Systems. She said she did not
remember whether Gray set up the meeting, held before she assumed
office on April 10, but maintained that she never discussed the
sale of Water Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no expectation on my part at all,'' Barnes said.
``If such a plan would have come before me, I would have rebuffed
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Whitley, spokesman for U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr.,
said Thursday that his office would examine any information it
received.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always receptive to a citizen or a group of citizens
who want to bring information to our attention,'' Whitley said.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers calling for an investigation _ all of whom lead
churches in the black community _ said they were worried that the
Barnes administration was focusing on a mostly black city
department for takeover. The Water Services Department has about
1,000 employees, about 600 of whom are minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we supposed to do? Are we supposed to simply
internalize this?'' said the Rev. Wallace Hartsfield. ``We are the
ones who supported you for mayor, and these revelations affect our
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said it would have been more appropriate for leaders of
the protest to bring concerns directly to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one approached me,'' she said. ``That's not the way I
would've handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Williams, a 14-year veteran of Water Services and former
union steward, said he was angered mostly by revelations of a
campaign to discredit the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a plot against city workers,'' Williams said. ``The
workers are doing the best job they can. Something is wrong with
this picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Kelvin Simmons said he supported the call for an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community has raised some serious issues,'' Simmons said.
``We need to continue to look at this issue. We also need to make
sure that there are no targets and that no departments are singled
out for privatization.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Barnes and the council have directed City
Manager Bob Collins to study the feasibility of privatizing city
facilities, including Kansas City International Airport and Kemper
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Collins also has been asked to analyze the operations of the
Water Services Department and the Public Works Department in an
effort to cut costs and improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes said Thursday that those two departments were
selected by Collins for study and not by her.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he chose those two departments because they are
among the largest in the city, they affect every citizen in the
city and ``because they both do their jobs very well.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also wanted a contrast between an enterprise fund and
a department funded by the general fund. The water department is an
enterprise fund, meaning it functions like a business: It makes
money and can only spend that money within its own department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
