<SLUG> BC-FUEL-SUMMIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL SUMMIT ENDS WITHOUT CLEAR DIRECTION FOR CLEANER AIR IN KC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ No consensus has emerged from this week's
``fuel summit'' on what to do about Kansas City's air pollution
problem.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of debate and testimony, a panel of experts on
fuel and pollution _ from state and federal agencies, private
industry and think tanks _ could not agree on any single
recommendation for Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan and Kansas Gov. Bill
Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Smith, who facilitated the summit at the Jack Reardon Civic
Center in downtown Kansas City, Kan., said nobody really expected a
single plan to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the primary goal of the summit was to exchange ideas
and concerns, and make it possible for Kansas and Missouri
officials to report back to their governors on the full range of
options on how to lower air pollution in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governors are going to have some hard calls to make,'' he
said. ``Everyone here agrees that the goal, first and foremost, is
clean air. But how to get there, at least in the short term,
there's no single answer, no clear-cut, silver-bullet solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit was a response to a federal ruling that Kansas City's
transportation plan had failed to conform to its clean-air plan. As
a result, if the governors don't act within about a month to bring
the transportation plan into compliance, millions of dollars in
highway expansions _ such as the new Chouteau Bridge _ may be
placed on hold, perhaps for years.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Randolph, chief air pollution regulator for the Missouri
Department of Natural Resources, said it appeared to him that
reformulated gasoline _ a fuel designed to decrease the production
of harmful ozone _ was the most popular solution to Kansas City's
air quality problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel this summit kind of lost sight of cleaning up the air
and protecting the public health,'' he said. ``And the basic issue
here is that Kansas City air is too dirty to protect the public
health. We need to take definitive action that will drive the point
home and put this issue to rest. And the community's best answer
looks to be reformulated gas.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fuel also had detractors, including those who cited a
federal lawsuit by the oil industry that claims it is illegal for
Kansas City to receive such fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Matson, Kansas Gov. Graves' spokesman, said his office was
eager to hear full reports on what came out of the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Gov. Graves won't rush into a decision,'' he said. ``The
whole idea of the summit was to sift through the available options,
and he'll take a good look at what came out of there. But I'm sure
he'll also be looking into other options as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's spokesman said his office was waiting to review a
summary of the summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
