<HEADLINE>
UNION VOTE LOOMS ON TWA CONTRACT OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Most area union employees of Trans World
Airlines will vote Tuesday on whether to accept the company's
contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A morning meeting and an evening meeting will be held Tuesday at
Bartle Hall to accommodate 2,300 employees who work three shifts at
TWA's overhaul base at Kansas City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Also at that time, the workers will vote on whether to authorize
a strike, should it become necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Nelson, president of Machinists Local 1650, said the
company's 73-page proposal to the mechanics group was being copied
this week. The union hopes to distribute it to all its members by
today.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators for the union, Machinists District 142, have
strongly recommended that its 16,000 TWA members reject the
contract and force the company to return to the bargaining table
with a better offer.
</P>
<P>
   TWA repeatedly has said this is a ``best and final'' offer.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also sent information about the company's contract
proposals to the three worker groups represented by the Machinists:
mechanics, flight attendants and passenger-service workers.
</P>
<P>
   TWA has about 40 area union workers in the passenger-service
group. The union also plans to distribute the contract proposal for
them, with a vote at Machinists Local 1650's union hall in
Riverside. A date for that meeting has not been scheduled, Nelson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants will vote by mail because of their work
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials have said the voting process will not be
completed until late June or early July.
</P>
<P>
   Meetings to vote on the new contract in St. Louis, TWA's
headquarters, will take place Wednesday. Employees voting there
include mechanics, ramp workers, ticket agents and reservations
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said all three employee groups must ratify their
contracts to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the terms of the proposals for the work groups:
</P>
<P>
   {Mechanics:} Raises of 6 percent this year, 4 percent next year
and 7 percent in 2001. Bonuses of $2,200 this year, $1,700 next
year and $700 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   {Ramp workers:} Raises of 3 percent this year, 2 percent next
year and 4.3 percent in 2001. Bonuses of $1,700 this year, $700
next year and $1,700 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   {Passenger-service employees:} Raises of 5 percent this year,
2.75 percent next year and 5.75 percent in 2001. Bonuses of $700
this year, next year and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding benefits, all employees except the flight attendants
would get an increased pension contribution of 50 cents an hour.
All workers would receive $10,000 more in life insurance and a new
dental plan.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said all employees will reach 90 percent of the
industry standard by July 2001 under this proposal. The union has
remained adamant in its position that after more than a decade of
concessionary contracts, TWA employees must be paid the industry
standard.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City meetings to vote on the contract and to
authorize a strike will be held at 10 a.m. and 7 p.m. Tuesday at
Room 1203 of Bartle Hall. Nelson said representatives from
Machinists District 142 would be in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Updated union cards will be needed to attend the meeting and
vote, Nelson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
