<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELMONT IS ALL ABUZZ FOR MAIN EVENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Belmont Park is ready _ from the eight busloads
of extra security people and mutuel clerks shipping in from
Saratoga, to the steeplechase horses jumping and the fillies
running, to the strolling bands and the street festival, to the $2
million in purses, to the parking valets decked out in tuxedos to
greet the customers as they arrive Saturday to see, for the third
consecutive year, if a horse can sweep the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The main event is the 131st running of the Belmont Stakes, and
it will draw New York's biggest sports crowd of the day and the
year, probably between 80,000 and 85,000, to watch 11 colts and 1
filly race in the $1 million Belmont Stakes with a bonus of $5
million if Charismatic completes his sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know it's a chance to see history in the making,'' said
Terry Meyocks, president of the New York Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if they'll set a record for attendance or
betting or not. We do know it has captured people's minds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the history of thoroughbred racing, only 11 horses have swept
the Triple Crown by winning the Kentucky Derby, the Preakness and
the Belmont Stakes within five weeks in the springtime of their
3-year-old seasons. Fourteen who attempted to complete a sweep have
failed, including the last six who tried, and most dramatically the
last two.
</P>
<P>
   So, Charismatic will try where Silver Charm failed by
three-quarters of a length in 1997 and where Real Quiet missed by a
nose in 1998. He will be the centerpiece of months of planning,
marketing and strategy aimed at endowing the Belmont with something
like the impact of the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have momentum in our corner,'' said Bill Nader, the
director of promotions for Belmont Park. ``People left here the
last two years and realized that Belmont Park is more beautiful
than they knew, and the Belmont Stakes more exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we turn it into something like the Derby, which draws
100,000 people for the Kentucky Oaks the day before and 150,000 on
Derby Day? One step at a time. We're starting with the day before
the Belmont, the Friday, when we're running the Acorn Stakes to
open the Triple Tiara series for fillies. And we'll go from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has so many more options than, say, Louisville. But
if we can get people to Belmont Park, and they leave with the idea
that it's a lovely way to spend an afternoon, with steeplechase
racing on Thursday and the Acorn on Friday and the Triple Crown on
Saturday, we'll have something going.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest crowd to see a Belmont Stakes was 82,694 in 1971,
when Canonero II shot for the Triple Crown (and missed), and
hundreds of fans climbed the fences to watch him. Since then, the
race has drawn about half as many, something like the 40,787 who
watched Editor's Note win in 1996. But the next year, with the
Triple Crown on the line for Silver Charm, the crowd took a quantum
leap upward to 70,682. Last year, 80,162 watched Real Quiet lose in
the final stride to Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors might influence Saturday's crowd: the weather, which
is supposed to be mostly sunny with temperatures in the 80s, and
the other options that New York offers. By chance, there are two
huge options this year: the Mets at the Yankees in the afternoon,
and the Indiana Pacers at the Knicks in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spirit of things,'' Meyocks said, ``we'll stay open
after the races for the Knicks-Pacers game so that our fans can
watch it on TV. That will also help dissipate the traffic leaving
the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been planning for Belmont Day for months. We went to the
high schools and colleges five months ago to recruit workers, and
we'll have eight or nine busloads of security people and mutuel
clerks coming from Saratoga. We'll use a total of 800 mutuel clerks
to man the windows, and that's more than 100 over the maximum we've
ever had. But after the last two years, people got a taste of the
Triple Crown.''
</P>
<P>
   Belmont Park got a running start on Belmont Day when it ran the
$100,000 Meadow Brook steeplechase race Thursday, and it gathers
momentum Saturday with the $200,000 Acorn. In the evening, a
festival will be held in in Garden City to provide what Nader calls
``a Saratoga feel'' on the Hempstead Plains where the first
organized racing on Long Island was held in 1665.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, gates open at 8:30 in the morning, 11 races starting
at 12:30, the main event at 5:27 surrounded by four stakes with
Broadway casts supplying songs between races. The rest is up to
Charismatic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
