<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-BANKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INTERNATIONAL BANKING PANEL PROPOSES WAYS TO LIMIT RISK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The top global banking regulator introduced proposals
Thursday that would strengthen protections against bad loans and
subject the risk-assessment operations of big international banks
to greater supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals, announced in London by a panel of the Bank of
International Settlements of Basel, Switzerland, were not a direct
result of the financial crises in Asia and Russia or of the
near-collapse of Long-Term Capital Management, banking officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposals by the regulator, wich draws its membership
from central banks, represented an acknowledgment that since the
rules were last agreed to in Basel in 1988, international banking
operations had become far more complex and, as the events of
1997-98 showed, prone to instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last decade,'' said Howard Davies, chairman of
Britain's Financial Services Authority, a supervisory body,
``banks' operations have become increasingly sophisticated and,
particularly in the last few years, we have witnessed considerable
turbulence. The new accord should result in a more efficient use of
capital, better risk management by banks and improved disclosure,
leading to a safer, more efficient financial system.''
</P>
<P>
   William J. McDonough, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank
of New York and chairman of the panel, told a news conference here
that the new proposals rested on three pillars _ an overhaul of the
rules requiring banks to set aside capital against default, closer
supervisory scrutiny of the way banks assess risks and greater
transparency in banking operations. Such improvements, he said,
would encourage ``safe and sound banking practices.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules foresee the use of credit-rating agencies to
assess the creditworthiness of governments and corporations seeking
loans. That would mean that borrowing costs for large corporations
rated triple-A by Moody's or Standard &AMP; Poor's could fall, while
the cost of borrowing would increase for corporations with less
solid ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Banks would offset the cost of the capital they set aside by the
interest rates charged on loans. Thus, a high-risk loan would mean
a higher capital commitment and consequently higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   McDonough said that banks and other financial institutions had
until March 31 of next year to respond to the new proposals, and
banking officials said they were unlikely to take effect before
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1988 agreements, banks must set aside 8 percent of
assets _ or part of that depending on the risks associated with a
particular loan _ to cover the possibility of default. But bankers
have complained that the system makes little distinction between,
say, overnight loans to a blue-chip corporation and medium-term
loans to some governments.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposals would allow banks to use their own methods to
calibrate risk, but only in conjunction with supervisory
authorities. ``The new proposals put much greater emphasis on the
bank supervisory process and consequently a much heavier burden on
the capabilities of bank supervisors,'' McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals could intensify a long-running disagreement
between banking supervisors and bankers, and some bankers
immediately criticized the proposals. ``We are trying to figure out
whether this is a Trojan horse because it outlines a program of
broader and more intrusive oversight and more stringent
supervision,'' an American banker in New York said.
</P>
<P>
   Against that, a governor of the U.S. Federal Reserve, Laurence
H. Meyer, said Thursday that large banks that engaged in complex
activities needed far more careful supervision and different
capital requirements than the rest of the industry. And Claes
Norgren, a member of the special panel, said the proposals are
intended to make the regulatory requirements proportional to the
risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
