<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NYC-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CITY BUDGET SHOWDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 4:
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and the New York City Council have
reluctantly scaled down an array of proposed tax cuts that seemed
certain to be approved earlier this year. Their action was forced
by the loss of revenues when the state Legislature repealed the
commuter tax last month. Now the mayor and council need to reach
agreement on other issues in the $35 billion budget. They should
first restore Giuliani's proposed cuts in libraries, after-school
programs, cultural institutions and legal services for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast with Albany, where the budget is two months overdue,
Giuliani and Council Speaker Peter Vallone are engaged in a
constructive give-and-take on fiscal matters. There is no reason
they should not agree on a budget by the statutory deadline
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   In April Giuliani proposed a reasonably sensible financial plan
using most of the $2 billion surplus this year for expenses in the
next two years. He did propose cuts, knowing that the council would
reject them. Vallone is right to press for full funding of programs
that serve important educational needs and keep the quality of life
at a decent level for New Yorkers of modest means.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone is also right to challenge two broad mayoral
initiatives, one setting aside money for sports stadiums and the
other providing vouchers for families with children in private and
parochial schools. No matter how they are structured and
administered, vouchers are not a sound approach to meeting the
educational needs of a majority of students. They also pose
constitutional problems. As for setting aside revenues to help pay
for new stadiums for the Yankees, Mets and perhaps a new football
team, it is premature to put money in the budget for projects that
have not yet been presented to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent ease with which the budget for the next fiscal year
is being adopted belies serious problems ahead. The city is
projecting deficits in the next few years, and Giuliani has laid no
groundwork for demanding changes in labor practices to save money.
Times are good now, but it is not too soon to start thinking of
ways to squeeze more savings from budgets down the road. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-03-99 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
