<HEADER>
A2633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-     06-03 0254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN INSULT TO CAMPAIGN REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 4:
</P>
<P>
   The latest indication of the GOP congressional leadership's
indifference to cleaning up a corrupt campaign financing system is
its attitude toward an upcoming vacancy on the Federal Election
Commission. Instead of scouring the country for a distinguished
individual with a passion for reform, Senate Republicans are said
to be considering an Ohio law professor whose writings make plain
his hostility to the agency he would be joining and the campaign
finance laws it is supposed to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, Bradley Smith of Capital University Law School in
Columbus, has called for repeal of the Federal Election Campaign
Act, which he describes as ``profoundly undemocratic and profoundly
at odds with the First Amendment.'' He also questions the
proposition that money corrupts politics. These views have made him
the first choice of Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, campaign
finance reform's main nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   Three reform-minded groups _ Common Cause, Democracy 21 and the
Brennan Center at New York University Law School _ have urged
President Clinton to reject Smith should Trent Lott, the Senate
majority leader, submit his name for nomination. Such a show of
backbone would be a departure for Clinton, who has repeatedly
passed up opportunities to transform the Election Commission into a
serious enforcement agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
