<HEADER>
A2636 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LAD     06-03 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY'S INJURY NOT SERIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ X-rays on Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley's sprained
left wrist were negative Thursday, which is astonishing given how
badly things have gone for the Dodgers of late.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley will probably miss the next three to five days, making
it unlikely he'll play in the three-game series that begins tonight
against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Angel Pena figures to be the only healthy catcher for the
Dodgers over the next few days. Pinch-hitting specialist Dave
Hansen and outfielder Trenidad Hubbard are the Dodgers' emergency
catchers, but general manager Kevin Malone said Hundley may be able
to catch in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did an X-ray and further tests just to make sure since
it's the one he broke (twice before),'' Malone said. ``We think, as
tough as Todd is, we're not going to want to use him for a few
days.''
</P>
<P>
   The news is welcome to the Dodgers, who averted a potential
catching disaster. If Hundley's injury was long-term, another
catcher would be needed. But likely call-up candidate Paul LoDuca
broke his right hand Wednesday in a game for Triple-A Albuquerque
when it was hit by a foul tip. LoDuca began the season as Hundley's
backup but was demoted after getting two hits in 36 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley hurt his left wrist in the third inning of Wednesday's
8-4 loss in Pittsburgh during a collision at home plate with the
Pirates' Ed Sprague. He left the game after batting in the top of
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   If Hundley's health doesn't progress as expected, the Dodgers
may look to place him on the disabled list and recall catcher Rick
Wilkins from Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek X-rays: Hundley's health is no longer an issue, but
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek's hand swelled up after he punched a
wall in frustration after grounding into a double play Tuesday
against Pittsburgh. Malone said Grudzielanek will have X-rays
taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting him checked out just to make sure there's
nothing there,'' Malone said. ``It's precautionary measures. We
don't think anything's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek is hitting .284 but has grounded into a team-high
nine double plays.
</P>
<P>
   Players' agent confident: Gus Dominguez, the agent for a pair of
Cuban minor-leaguers in the Dodgers system, said he's confident the
commissioner's office will rule in favor of the players and declare
them free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Carlos Diaz, a first baseman at Double-A San Antonio, and
Josue Perez, an outfielder at Single-A Vero Beach, petitioned Major
League Baseball to become free agents. They claim the Dodgers
signed them illegally and alleged Dodgers officials helped both of
them defect from Cuba on different occasions and forced them to
sign contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the decision will be in our favor,'' Dominguez said.
``When (the commissioner's office) interviewed the guys and spoke
to the guys separately, the kids told the truth. Their stories are
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez said he based his belief ``just by the way (the
commissioner's office) spoke to me.'' Dominguez said he's hoping
the players will become free agents immediately after the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers remained tight-lipped about accusations that Ralph
Avila, vice president of the Dodgers' facility in the Dominican
Republic, Campo Las Palmas, and the complex's general manager Pablo
Peguero, helped orchestrate the defections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working with the commissioner's office on the
issue,'' Dodgers president and CEO Bob Graziano said. ``I can't
speculate at this point as to what will happen. We'll work with
them on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball rules prohibit teams from scouting in Cuba, and the
United States has a trade embargo against communist nations. If the
Dodgers are found in violation of the rule, there could be fines up
to $500,000, suspensions and the loss of picks in the amateur
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Walks, balks and chalk: Malone said the Dodgers will activate
utility infielder Jose Vizcaino from the disabled list and place
outfielder Todd Hollandsworth on the disabled list with a torn
muscle in his side before today's game. . . . If those white mesh
practice caps the Dodgers wear aren't appealing to you, wait until
this six-game homestand when the Dodgers break out their blue
jerseys for Think Blue Week. The Dodgers will wear the uniforms
during the three-game series with Anaheim and the three games with
Texas. The game-worn jerseys will be signed by the player and
donated to a charity auction. The proceeds go to the Dodgers Dream
Foundation. . . . Dodgers right field Raul Mondesi has 18 home runs
in 52 games. He needs two tonight to tie Gil Hodges for the
quickest to 20 homers in Dodgers history. Hodges hit 20 in 53 games
in 1951 when the club was in Brooklyn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
