A2640 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RIVALRY-LADN     06-03 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RIVALRY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEWAY RIVALRY SLOW TO DEVELOP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It would be great to say fans this morning are
painting their faces bright blue or periwinkle in wild anticipation
of tonight's opening game of the Freeway Series.
</P>
<P>
   Or that Dodgers pitchers are snarling into the bathroom mirror
saying, ``If Mo Vaughn digs in on me, he's going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Or that there is some neighborhood between L.A. and Anaheim that
has been designated as a no-man's land in this long, bitter
struggle between the Dodgers and Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is there is no border war, no rivalry to press in the
pages of an old scrap book.
</P>
<P>
   As the teams begin the third year of interleague play, they have
played too much bad baseball to wonder who owns Southern
California. You can't throw out the stats on this one, they are not
good enough on either side.
</P>
<P>
   But it is more than the fact that the Angels are in last place
in the American League West and the Dodgers are nothing more than a
.500 team after getting swept by the Pirates in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike New York and Chicago, where in-season series between the
Yankees and Mets and Cubs and White Sox quickly have become the
talk of the town, there is little water-cooler debate about the
Dodgers and Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proximity does not create a rivalry,'' Dodgers first baseman
Eric Karros said. ``History creates it. A lot of (the lack of a
rivalry) has to do a lot with the tradition. The fans create it.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York, Chicago _ the cities are different than L.A. They've
been around longer. They're not as transient. Just because you're
playing one another doesn't make it a rivalry. You have to
establish something. You can't just create it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even in corporate America where Fox _ the Dodgers owners _
and Disney, which runs the Angels, are mega media rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Fox did create some anger in the Angels camp this winter when it
canceled the final two games of the preseason Freeway Series in
favor of a two-game set against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were left with two open dates, forced to play a club
from the Mexican League and a team from Cal State Fullerton, led by
alum Kevin Costner.
</P>
<P>
   In a cross-section of opinion from players and coaches on both
teams, the underlying theme to the nonrivalry is this: The Angels
have never been taken seriously because they haven't been to the
World Series in their 39-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Dodgers have not won a playoff game since 1988,
the franchise has six Series titles. The Angels have played in
three league championship series (1979, '82, '86) and lost them
all. They blew leads in the final two and haven't been back since,
helping to stamp their reputation for futility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always a feeling on our team when we played the
Dodgers that they were the major leagues and we were the minor
leagues,'' said Hall of Famer Rod Carew, now the Angels hitting
instructor. ``I didn't get caught up in it too much, but it
bothered a lot of guys. Winning a World Series brings a
respectability you can't get any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The two teams really have never gotten close to playing each
other in the World Series. They rarely have been competitive in the
same season.
</P>
<P>
   After winning pennants in 1977-78, the Dodgers faltered in 1979,
the year the Angels won their first division title.
</P>
<P>
   The best chance might have been in 1985, when the Dodgers won
the West _ but the Angels finished one game behind Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Others included 1982, when the Angels won the West and the
Dodgers lost on the final day on a home run by the Giants' Joe
Morgan. In 1983, the Dodgers won the West and the Angels lost 92
games. In 1986, the Angels won the West and the Dodgers finished
under .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were just never lined up right,'' said Hubie Brooks,
who played for both clubs in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think winning a championship would certainly go a long way
toward curing a lot of ill will and wiping away a lot of
shortcomings of the past,'' said Tim Belcher, who broke in with the
Dodgers at the end of 1987 and is now an Angels starter. ``It would
all be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Any bump in enthusiasm has come from Angels fans. The preseason
Freeway Series, which began in 1962, always drew its best crowds at
Anaheim Stadium, including five over 61,000.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds at Dodger Stadium will be good this weekend,
including possible sellouts tonight and Sunday. But fan interest
might be misleading because both are linked to popular promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kahn, who does pre- and post-game shows for the Angels
flagship station KLAC-AM (570), was the Dodgers radio reporter
several years ago when KMPC-AM (710) was an all-sports station.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn says there is a real sense of urgency from Angels callers
that this series is an important statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers haven't really had a rivalry since the Cincinnati
Reds in the late 1970s,'' he said. ``They were the Big Red Machine
and the Dodgers were always looking up at them. Those games sparked
quite an interest. That's the position I see the Angels in right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have not become popular despite using the Dodgers
method of building the club through the farm system. In Los
Angeles, it enabled Steve Garvey, Ron Cey and Davey Lopes to become
long-time fixtures in fans' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Angels' 10 projected opening-day starters (including
designated hitter), eight came through their minor-league clubs.
The first baseman, Mo Vaughn, signed an $80 million free agent
contract last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the home-grown products were upset when the Dodgers
pulled out of the Freeway Series in April, including closer Troy
Percival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they realize we might be stealing some of their
thunder,'' he said. ``I think they know there is another good team
in town. They have the tradition and they've earned it, but we're
starting to step on their toes a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   First they have to get out of last place in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, these are big games with the Dodgers,'' said
Angels manager Terry Collins, who played and managed in the Dodgers
farm system. ``All of a sudden it's not early in the season. We're
into June and these are games we have to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
