<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CASINO-UPROAR-ART-     06-03 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CASINO-UPROAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.D.) 
MAN'S PLAN TO GIVE LAND TO INDIAN TRIBE AROUSES CASINO VISIONS, AND
FEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAMSONVILLE, N.Y. _ For years, longtime residents and weekenders
from Manhattan treasured this woodsy hamlet as the closest thing to
rustic paradise, a place where the streams made more noise than the
residents, where slender country roads rolled past old stone walls,
where the number of general stores (1) dwarfed the number of
traffic lights (0).
</P>
<P>
   One could sigh, and sigh again, when contemplating the crisp
air, the clear-day vistas of Connecticut and, perhaps most precious
of all, the leisurely and utterly predictable cadence of life.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before the rumors about an American Indian casino
turned life upside down, triggering fears that this pastoral
incarnation of ``Ah, Wilderness'' would suddenly turn into
``Paradise Lost.''
</P>
<P>
   It all began late last year, when word got out that a wealthy
landowner here named Harry C. Fotopoulos planned to donate about
one-sixth of his more than 300 acres to the Oglala Sioux of South
Dakota. The goal, Fotopoulos said, was to create a historic theme
park and campground, complemented by a motel and some restaurants,
that would help the impoverished tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 70 years old,'' said Fotopoulos, who during a recent
interview at his cabin here tucked a gun and hunting knife into his
belt. ``Whatever time I have left, whatever good I can do for some
people, that'll be my legacy. This can turn out to be such a
beautiful, beautiful thing for the Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is no one here believes him. After all, the Sioux
live about 1,500 miles away and have never had a historic
connection to New York state, much less the Catskills or this
Ulster County hamlet, which is part of the town of Olive. So
instead, many residents say they are convinced that Fotopoulos, a
Manhattan real estate developer, really wants to pave the way for a
casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's insane; never ever has there been anything done to this
pristine land,'' said Harriet Black, who, with her husband, Bob,
splits her time between their sign business in Manhattan and their
weekend house on Haver Road, next to Fotopoulos' property. ``This
is a crime in the deepest sense. It's not man-made crime; it's God
and nature crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the chances for a casino are remote, federal officials
say. Even establishing a sovereign Indian nation on Fotopoulos'
property would not be easy. But the fact that Fotopoulos has
widened roads on his property, submitted a subdivision plan and
declared that he is this close to clinching the transfer has
persuaded many residents that some kind of radical change _ casino,
theme park, commercial enterprise, whatever _ is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the story has evolved into much more than just the
biggest development skirmish in this part of the Catskills since _
well, since never. The fight has been so unexpected, so out of
character, that for the first time, residents are now feeling
vulnerable, and somewhat powerless, about an idyllic world that
they never dreamed would change.
</P>
<P>
   Fotopoulos, in turn, says he has been surprised, and
disappointed, by the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``How dare anybody not want to help the Indians?'' said
Fotopoulos, who bought his property about 40 years ago. ``This is
an absolute disgrace that people are trying to force me to do with
my land what they want to do with the land. Now, I don't want a
casino up there. But if they stop me, then I may transfer the whole
300 acres. And I'll say, `Now let's put a casino.'''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Fotopoulos, who has dabbled in politics in
Manhattan and was once branded (unfairly, he says) by The New York
Post as one of the city's worst landlords, had never evinced any
interest in American Indian affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, a group called the Five Feathers Heritage Group
that Fotopoulos said was affiliated with the Oglala Sioux
approached him about donating some land. How and why they picked
Fotopoulos is not clear. But when he learned about the Sioux _ who
have an unemployment rate higher than 80 percent _ he said that,
yes, he would donate a 54-acre parcel.
</P>
<P>
   With the transaction now almost final, work on a five-acre
parking lot could begin this summer, Fotopoulos said. Eventually,
he hopes to invite some Oglala Sioux to live on the land, start a
bottled water business, stage mock battles, dig a new lake, build a
fort with vending booths. Among other ventures.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Fotopoulos said he wanted to reap about 45 percent of
the profits. But now, he says he wants only the ability to manage
the project and, perhaps, a small plaque to commemorate his
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no money for me,'' he said. ``It's money for the
Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Fotopoulos' intentions, a casino is probably unlikely
because of stringent federal criteria, said Rex Hackler, director
of communications for the Interior Department's Bureau of Indian
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there is plenty of fear and loathing to go around here
over whatever the final product will be, because of concerns over
traffic and the environment in a watershed area abutting the
Ashokan Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   The subject has inspired so much concern that longtime residents
and weekenders from the city have shoved aside traditional tensions
over development, forming a rare united front to oppose the
project.
</P>
<P>
   They have planted signs that say, ``No Camp _ No Theme Park _ No
Casino.'' A citizens' group, Preservation of Olive New York ,
published its first newsletter in early May. Some residents even
rented an airplane last winter to fly over Fotopoulos' property to
take photographs of what they suspected was illegal logging
activity. But the pictures were not very good, said Vincent
Barringer, the Olive Town Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unglued a lot of us,'' said Ellen Iwanowski, who
runs the Dream House Bed and Breakfast, just down the road from
Fotopoulos' cabin. ``If he goes and gives this piece of property to
this Indian nation, and they're a sovereign nation, Harry has
nothing to say and neither does anyone else. We're all afraid, I
tell you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
